    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Carita Mula-Mula</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Carita Mula-Mula<bt>Story of the Beginning</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Mulai dari Tuhan Allah bekin langit deng bumi<bt>Beginning from *Lord God making the sky/heaven and earth/world</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah bekin langit, bumi deng dia pung isi dong<bt>Lord God makes the sky/heaven, earth/world and its contents</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Mula-mula Tuhan Allah bekin langit deng bumi.<bt>At the beginning *Lord God made the sky/heaven and earth/world. [EXEG: Issue #1: Be aware that there is extensive discussion over translation of Hebrew text as “In the beginning God created...” vs. “When God began to create...” ISSUE #2: Be aware that there is extensive discussion over the meanings and interrelationship between Heb /baraʔ/ ‘create (something new)’, /asa/ ‘make’, /yasar/ ‘form’. /baraʔ/ is used here in 1:1, 21, 27; 2:4; 5:1-2; 6:7. TH “The primary meaning (of bara) is to create something new, something of a kind that never existed before”. Also cf NET Bible fn “in this context (bara) always describes the divine activity of fashioning something new, fresh, and perfect.” But TH also notes “Created is replaced by the verb ‘make’ in verses 7, 16, 25, and 26, but the sense is the same as ‘create’. The Septuagint translates the Hebrew for ‘created’ by the verb ‘to make.’”] [NOTE to daughter translations: This is a kind of generic-specific relationship between ‘make’ (generic) and ‘create’ (specific). Kupang (and many languages) do not have a way to keep this distinction without forcing it or skewing the focus. But one or two lgs in the NTT region do seem to have a /pe-jadi/ “cause to become (=create)” type of word that seems to work without being artificial. Be sure to discuss this with the team.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins Seder (major division for reading"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">Begins Seder (major division for reading on a three-year cycle) reʾshit: starting point in time, first (with a sense of also the best). Parallels John 1:1.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>baraʾ: create (something new), bring into existence, cause to be; used only with God as subject shamayim: heavens, sky, air around us; the atmosphere below the "firmament"<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Itu waktu, bumi balóm jadi, deng samua masi harba-biruk. Yang ada, aer. Deng galáp gulita tutu ame sang dia. Tuhan pung Roh ada bajalan di atas itu aer.<bt>At that time, the earth had not yet been made/come into being, and everything was still chaotic/without organisation. There was water. And pitch dark covered it. God's *Spirit was going on/over that water.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haytah: become, happen, exist, copula tohu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">haytah: become, happen, exist, copula tohu: wasteland, emptiness, formlessness, chaos. Change order, sounds better.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bohu: void, waste choshekh: night, darkness<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>tehom: primeval ocean, deep sea. An emotionally charged word used a lot in poetry, not just "deep" as a measurement. ruaH ʾəlohiym: could be "the Spirit of God" or "a wind from God" or "a mighty wind" (pagan Nineveh is "a city of God" in Jonah, meaning it's a huge city, not that it's a godly city or a sacred city).<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>mrachefet: hovering tremblingly</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani di sini, dia pung arti bisa macam-macam ke &lt;Tuhan pung Roh&gt;, ko, &lt;angin dari Tuhan&gt;, ko, &lt;kuasa dari Tuhan&gt;.<bt>The Hebrew language here, can have several meanings like &lt;God's Spirit&gt;, or &lt;wind from God&gt;, or &lt;power from God&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="3" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Musti ada taráng.&gt;&gt; Omong abis bagitu ju, taráng ada.<bt>Then the Lord God spoke saying, &lt;&lt;There must be light.&gt;&gt; When [He] finished speaking in that way, light was there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾor: light of day, brightness, appearing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾor: light of day, brightness, appearing in the spatial setting defined in verse 2.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Lia itu taráng, ju Dia pung hati sanáng, tagal apa yang Dia su bekin tu, memang bae. Ais Dia kasi pisa itu taráng dari galáp, ko satu-satu ada pung waktu sandiri.<bt>Seeing that light, He was happy/pleased, because what He had made was really good. Then He separated the light from dark, so each had its own time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyraʾ ... ki: saw the light,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayyraʾ ... ki: saw the light, that it was good = saw how good the light is. "look someting" is not the same as "look at someting." "Stay" with "good" might be taken that it isn't an inherently good thing in itself (which is what the Hebrew implies and theology emphasizes), but that it was okay for the present and might change. "Saw how good it was" is a positive affirmation, not a last minute check to make sure nothing had gone wrong. yavdel (bdl hif): distinguish between ("put someting" + locative noun is standard; "put on" may be overkill.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Dia kasi nama taráng tu, &lt;siang&gt;, deng galáp tu, &lt;malam&gt;. Itu hari partama.<bt>He named that light, &lt;daytime&gt;, and that dark, &lt;night&gt;. That was the first day. [EXEG: This Gen 1:1-2:4 passage is perhaps one of the most scrutinised and debated in the whole of the Hebrew and Christian scriptures. Commentators from as early as Augustine (4th cent.) to Hamilton (“Problems in Interpretation: the ‘days’ of Genesis 1”) and more recent commentators as well, have noted the obvious literary structure of the passage. One of the markers delineating the subsections of this passage is this highly literary phrase “And there was evening and there was morning, the … day.” (vs. 5, 8, 13, 19, 23, 31). They have also noted other things, e.g. structural parallels between days 1-3 being mirrored in 4-6, etc. Many scholars are also familiar with the heavy redundancy and repetition that is good Hebrew style (that's part of why we get the term “Hebraism”), but which would be heavy and unnatural in so many other languages. In most of the AN lgs of NTT and Maluku, when one is narrating a multi-day event or happening (such as a special wedding, a special celebration, building a church, building an airstrip, a hunt [group or individual], a long trip, a particularly difficult sickness, etc.) it is not uncommon for the narrator to break up the narration by saying, “That was the …(e.g. first) day.” Etc. By that s/he means “That's the end of everything that happened during that night-day cycle.” That's the point that a narrator can take a pee break, smoke break, or drink break, before resuming. In these lgs also, I know of no occurrences in natural texts (from leading 2 discourse workshops in two provinces, plus my own first-hand ressearch) where either morning or evening would be mentioned as part of one of these episode closures. So literal would skew the focus. Also in these languages, doublets like “daytime-nighttime” (more often “nighttime-daytime”) are used to signal something that is on-going continuously around the clock. But most commentators favour creation events in response to God's utterances, than a round-the-clock durative process. So trying something like that either skews the focus or conveys wrong meaning. Hamilton and others point out some of the problems with pushing a literal rendering of the phrase, including: 1) it appears that one would see a yom-day as beginning in the evening and ending in the morning--skipping the daylight hours, whereas the narrowest sense of Heb /yom/ is “daylight hours” (the most common sense being “day, 24-hour cycle”-with other broader senses as well); and 2) it appears that the seventh day had no evening or morning (perhaps that's what makes it special :-)).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqraʾ: give a name yom: daylight"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiqraʾ: give a name yom: daylight hours; also 24-hour period, time for something, long period during which certain things happen<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>laylah: at night ʿerev: evening, sunset<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>boker: light of daybreak, morning</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="6-7" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Musti ada tampa kosong ko kasi pisa aer. Andia ko ada aer di bagian atas, deng ada aer di bagian bawa.&gt;&gt; Omong abis bagitu ju, itu aer tabagi dua.<bt>Then Lord God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;There must be an empty place to separate the water. That is so there is water in the upper part and and water in the lower part.&gt;&gt; When [He] finished speaking in that way, the water was divided in two.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raqiyaʿ: beaten metal plate; vault of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">raqiyaʿ: beaten metal plate; vault of heaven, solid dome (not implied by the Hebrew, but used in LXX, possibly under the influence of Alexandrian philosophy (TWOT: also In the OT, however, Isaiah insists that God "stretches out the heavens [lit.] like gauze (do4q, Isa 40:22); and even Ezekiel's limited canopy (ra4q|&lt;a() is "as the [lit.] eye of awesome ice" (Ezk 1:22), i.e. transparent, "shining like crystal" (RSV), though so dazzling as to be terrifying (KD; cf. Dan 12:3 "brightness").) tok: middle, throughout<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>mavdil: participle, a distinction, segregated yaʾash: manufacture, create (when God does it), produce<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>mitchat: that is underneath ʿal: over<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vayhi ken: that's how it came out</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ais Dia kasi nama tampa kosong di bagian atas tu, &lt;langit&gt;. Itu hari kadua.<bt>Then He named the empty place in the upper part, &lt;sky/heaven&gt;. That was the second day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ais Dia kasi nama aer di"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Ais Dia kasi nama aer di bagian atas tu, &lt;langit&gt;.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="9" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Aer di bagian bawa tu musti takumpul di satu tampa, ko biar ada tana karíng.&gt;&gt; Omong abis bagitu ju, tana karíng ada.<bt>Then Lord God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;The water in the lower part must be gathered in one place, so that there can be dry ground.&gt;&gt; When [He] finished speaking in that way, there was dry ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqawu (qwh nif): come together, be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiqqawu (qwh nif): come together, be collected (intransitive) ʾel-maqom echad: one place (doesn't say where), area<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>vteraʾah: become visible hayyabbashah: dry land, opposite of ‘sea’<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>miqveh: accumulation (what you get when qwh happens)</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ais tana karíng tu, Dia kasi nama &lt;darat&gt;; deng aer yang takumpul tu, Dia kasi nama &lt;laut&gt;. Lia itu samua, ju Dia pung hati sanáng, tagal apa yang Dia su bekin tu, memang bae.<bt>Then that dry ground, He named &lt;land&gt;; and the water that was gathered, He named &lt;sea/ocean&gt;. Seeing all that, He was happy/pleased, because what He had made was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yammim: seas, like the Mediterranean, that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yammim: seas, like the Mediterranean, that were more familiar than the mysterious tehom; all the different bodies of water</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Darat musti kasi kaluar tanaman. Musti ada tanaman yang babua, yang babiji, deng yang badaon ijo. Biar ko satu-satu tanaman kasi kaluar dia pung hasil iko dia pung macam.&gt;&gt; Omong abis bagitu ju, samua tanaman jadi.<bt>Then Lord God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;The land must put out plants. There must be plants that have fruit, that have seeds, and that have green leaves. [local major categories] Let each plant put out produce according to its type.&gt;&gt; When [He] finished speaking in that way, all plants were there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tadsheʾ: be green with grass, sprout"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tadsheʾ: be green with grass, sprout desheʾ: new fresh grass like what comes up after it rains<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʿesev mazriaʿ zeraʿ: technical term for the green plants of the rainy season, seed-producing plants rather than perennials ʿets: trees in general<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>peri: fruit bearing kind ʿosheh: manufacturing, producing<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>minu, minehu: species zarʿu: form seed, zarʿu-vu seed in it<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Di darat, tanaman dong kasi kaluar dong pung hasil iko satu-satu pung macam. Lia itu samua, ju Dia pung hati sanáng, tagal apa yang Dia su bekin tu, memang bae.<bt>On land, the plants put out their produce according to each of their types. Seeing all that, He was happy/pleased, because what He had made was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="totseʾ (= yatsaʾ): bring forth, produce,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">totseʾ (= yatsaʾ): bring forth, produce, what the ground does minehu, minu: species, type<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Itu hari katiga.<bt>That was the third day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="14-15" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Di bagian atas tu, musti ada macam-macam barang taráng ko bekin taráng ini bumi. Musti ada yang kasi taráng waktu siang, deng musti ada laen yang kasi taráng waktu malam. Dong samua jadi tanda ko biar bisa itong hari, taon, deng musim.&gt;&gt; Omong abis bagitu ju, samua barang taráng ada.<bt>Then Lord God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;In that upper part, there must be various sorts of light things to give light to this earth. There must be [something] to give light when it's daytime, and there must be [something] to give light when it's night. All of them are signs so that days, years, and seasons can be counted.&gt;&gt; When [He] finished speaking in that way, all the light things were there. [DISCOURSE: It might be simpler to say ‘in the sky’ than, ‘in the top part’, but it wouldn't be 1) as beautiful, nor 2) track the referents through the discourse nearly as effectively. After a gap this resumes a reference and framework from vs. 8-9 and earlier. That's a discourse tracking reason. But culturally I can give 50+ anthropology references on dualism and parallelism in the cosmologies of eastern Indonesia over the past 80 years. That's how they make sense of their world. E.g. upper-lower, male-female, older-younger…]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mʾorot: luminaries, things that give out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mʾorot: luminaries, things that give out light birqiyaʿ: in the vault = v. 6<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>l-: for the purpose of. In the context of "let there be X," the infinitives give the functions of X. Pidgin grammar can subordinate these with "fo," but it gets dull fast that way. Telling what they are supposed to do sounds better. havdil (bdl hif inf): the distinguishing or separating of something - also used of the "firmament"<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʾotot: marks, signs, banners; omens announcing things to come moʿədim: appointed time, fixed day, time of feast, religious festivals, special days to worship God, or possibly parts of the year<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yamim: day-long periods shanim: years<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>birqiyaʿ: in the vault = v. 6 haʾiyr (ʾwr hif inf): to illuminate<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʾarets: world, land, ground</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Dia bekin dua macam barang taráng yang bésar. Yang lebe bésar, kasi taráng waktu siang; yang lebe kici, kasi taráng waktu malam. Dia ju bekin bintang dong.<bt>He made two types of large light things. The larger one gives light when it's daytime; the smaller one gives light when it's night. He also made the stars.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyaʿas (ʿsh narrative): the next thing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayyaʿas (ʿsh narrative): the next thing that happened was that he made. Ross's suggestion "had made" would fit better if it were ʿasah. shni: years (construct)<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>haggadolim: great (in importance) memshelet: ruling power<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>hayyom ... hallaylah: in the daytime ... in the nighttime qatan: be small, trifling<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>kokhavim: stars</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Dia ator itu barang dong di langit, ko dong senter kasi taráng bumi.<bt>He arranged those things in the sky, so they shone (=torched) giving light to the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitten: put, provide ʾotam: them|i(17) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yitten: put, provide ʾotam: them<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ais dong kasi taráng waktu siang, deng kasi taráng waktu malam. Deng bagitu, dong kasi pisa taráng dari galáp. Lia itu samua, ju Dia pung hati sanáng, tagal apa yang Dia su bekin tu, memang bae.<bt>So they give light when it is daytime, and give light when it is night. In that way, separate light from dark. Seeing all that, He was happy/pleased, because what He had made was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bayyom ... ballaylah: during the day"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">bayyom ... ballaylah: during the day ... during the night Here the infinitives should be translated as complementizers ("fo") to play down the information, since it has already been given once.<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ki-tov: as in v. 4</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Itu hari ka'ampa.<bt>That was the fourth day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00600c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="20" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Musti ada macam-macam binatang yang idop dalam aer. Deng musti ada macam-macam burung yang tarbáng di atas bumi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Lord God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;There must be various sorts of animals which live in the water. And there must be various sorts of birds which fly on/over/above the earth.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: The current KM phrasing carries variety and plurality, but not abundance “swarming, teeming”. Our attempts so far have all been heavy overtranslation, or forced/stilted. If you find a good solution, let us know.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishrtsu: a place swarms with or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yishrtsu: a place swarms with or teems with something alive sherets: tiny animals occurring in large numbers somewhere<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Hayyah: animals ʿof: flying creatures = bugs and birds<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>ʿal: two complementary human perspectives: above the ground, across the sky</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ais Dia bekin samua macam ikan deng binatang bésar yang idop di aer. Dia ju bekin samua macam burung yang tarbáng di langit. Lia itu samua, ju Dia pung hati sanáng, tagal apa yang Dia su bekin tu, memang bae.<bt>So then He made all the kinds of fish and large animals which live in the water. He also made all the kinds of birds that fly in the sky. Seeing all that, He was happy/pleased, because what He had made was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taninim: sea-monsters, sea-dragons haromeshet: swarming creatures,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">taninim: sea-monsters, sea-dragons haromeshet: swarming creatures, teeming creatures<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>minehem: species, kind kol-ʿof kanaf<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ais Dia omong kasi berkat sang itu binatang dong samua bilang, &lt;&lt;Ikan dong musti tamba banya, ko bekin ponu aer di mana-mana. Deng burung dong ju musti tamba banya.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke giving *blessing to all those animals saying, &lt;&lt;The fish must add more (=increase in number), to they fill the water everywhere. And the birds also must add more.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yvarekh: make someone able to fulfill"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yvarekh: make someone able to fulfill his or her destiny, do what they were designed to do, bestow power for success (English "bless" in its most basic sense; other senses have to do with verbal actions intended to bring this about or showing appreciation for it) pru: be fruitful<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>rvu: become numerous milʾu: fill up<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yammim: in the seas</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Itu hari kalima.<bt>That was the fifth day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24-25" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Musti ada macam-macam binatang yang idop di darat. Andia binatang piara, binatang liar, deng binatang marayap di tana, satu-satu deng dia pung macam.&gt;&gt; Omong abis bagitu ju, samua binatang ada. Lia itu samua, ju Dia pung hati sanáng, tagal apa yang Dia su bekin tu, memang bae.<bt>Then Lord God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;There must be various sorts of animals which live on the land. Such as domestic animals, wild animals, and animals that crawl on the ground, each one with (according to) its type.&gt;&gt; When [He] finished speaking in that way, all the animals were there. Seeing all that, He was happy/pleased, because what He had made was really good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="totseʾ (ytsʾ hif imperf): produce v.12"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">totseʾ (ytsʾ hif imperf): produce v.12 chayyah: living things<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>bəhemah: animals in general, here probably domestic animals in contrast with Hayto remes: collective of small animals including reptiles -- everything except large animals and birds. It would include mice and rats and mongoose, as well as lizards and snakes.<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>chayto: living beings, animals, especially untamed land animals ʾadamah: soil producing plants<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ais Tuhan Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Mari ko Kotong bekin manusia iko Kotong pung model. Biar dong urus deng ator samua ikan di laut, samua burung di langit, samua binatang piara, deng samua binatang laen dong yang idop di bumi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Lord God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;Let's (1p-inc) make humans following our-inc model. Let them manage and organise (see Hamilton) all the fish in the sea, all the birds in the sky, all the domestic animals, and all other animals that live on the earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="urus = mengelolah, manage (lebe luas);"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">urus = mengelolah, manage (lebe luas); ator = mengorganisir, menata, organise</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʿəseh: we make (first time this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">naʿəseh: we make (first time this verb is used, I think). The plural may be one of deliberation as in Isaiah 6:8 "who will go for us?" talking over alternatives. Early Christian writers saw this as a reference to the Trinity, but that is a conclusion that the wording permits, not a teaching that it imparts. It could be a plural of majesty. tsalmenu, tselem: model, statue, drawing, image (of us). UBS suggests not using "picture" because that is too specific a kind of resemblance<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>dmutnu: pattern, shape, form, something like us; image of God yirdu: subdue, rule, govern, be over<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>dgat: fishes bhemah: animals in general<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="1:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kolose 1:16</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00604c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ju Dia bekin manusia iko Dia pung model. Dia bekin sang dong, laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>Then He made humans following His model. He made them, male and female.</bt><v n="28" />Ju Dia omong kasi berkat sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong musti barana tamba bam-banya, ko bekin ponu deng ator ini dunya. Beta ju kasi hak sang bosong ko urus ikan-ikan, burung-burung, deng samua binatang di darat.<bt>Then He spoke giving blessing to them saying, &lt;&lt;You-PL must give birth adding many, to fill this world, and organise it. I also give you-PL the *right/authority to manage the fish, the birds, and all the animals on the land. [EXEG: Note Heb term is also for shepherd - sheep, not just for king - subjects; traditional is non-sensical and collocational clash. This rendering is more faithful to both the Hebrew and the context. Max J. also pointed out it lays the groundwork for a theology of environmental responsibility, rather than just hell-bent exploitation.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pru: be fruitful, bear fruit rvu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">pru: be fruitful, bear fruit rvu: become many<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>kivshuah (kbsh imperv): make subservient, subdue rdu (rdh imperv): rule<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>Hayyah: beasts, living things romeset (partcpl fem sg): creeping, crawling<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Dengar bae-bae! Beta kasi sang bosong makanan macam-macam di ini dunya. Andia: tanaman yang babua, yang babiji, deng yang badaon ijo.<bt>Listen well! I'm giving you various sorts of food here on this world. Such as: plants which have fruit, those which have seeds, and those which have green leaves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿesev: every plant zoreaʿ: producing seeds|i(29)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿesev: every plant zoreaʿ: producing seeds<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>hinneh: emphasizes the following clause, something unexpected. I doesn't mean to look at something; it has more to do with the fact that what he is about to say is significant</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Beta ju kasi samua macam tanaman, ko jadi samua macam binatang pung makanan. Ada makanan buat binatang piara, binatang liar, binatang marayap, deng burung-burung dong.&gt;&gt; Omong abis bagitu ju, samua macam makanan ada.<bt>I'm also giving all types of plants to be food for all the kinds of animals. There is food for the domestic animals, wild animals, crawling animals, and the birds.&gt;&gt; When [He] finished speaking in that way, all the types of food were there. [EXEG: TH notes that 11-12 are focusing on plants in general, and 29-30 are focusing specifically on plants for food. Theologically, Hamilton points out that God provides for what He creates. So 29-30 are seen as additional acts of creation, not just arranging or organising what He had previously created on day 4. To change the last sentence would also break up the lexical cohesion of the clear literary structure of the passage.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yereq: green plant, verdure"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yereq: green plant, verdure</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Lia itu samua, ju Dia pung hati sanáng, tagal apa yang Dia su bekin tu, memang talalu bae. Itu hari ka'anam.<bt>Seeing all that, He was happy/pleased, because what He had made was exceedingly good. That was the sixth day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Deng bagitu, Tuhan Allah bekin ame langit deng bumi, deng dia pung isi dong samua.<bt>In that way, Lord God made [+accomplished] the sky and the earth, and all its contents.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikhullu (klh puʿal): were completed, finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yikhullu (klh puʿal): were completed, finished tsvaʾam: the host of them; host of heaven: heavenly objects, i.e. sun, moon, stars<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="2" />Dia karjá abis samua, ju dia pung beso, pas deng hari katuju, Dia barenti.<bt>When He had finished all that work, on the following day, exactly on the seventh day, He stopped [=stop work/rest].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hela nafas OR barenti cape carry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">hela nafas OR barenti cape carry undesired baggage</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ykhal (klh piʿel narr): he finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ykhal (klh piʿel narr): he finished mlaʾaktu: his job, the work he was doing, his task<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yishbot: stop working, come to a standstill</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Deng bagitu, Dia bekin hari katuju jadi hari bésar dari hari-hari laen dong. Dia ator bagitu, tagal Dia su bekin abis Dia pung karjá, ais di hari katuju Dia istirahat.<bt>In that way, He made the seventh day to be a big day (=special) from the other days. He arranged it that way, because He had finished His work, and then on the seventh day He rested.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yvarekh (brk piʿel narr): he blessed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yvarekh (brk piʿel narr): he blessed yqaddesh (qdsh piʿel narr): he set it apart for himself<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>shavat: more like taking the day off because he was finished, not because he was tired. baraʾ: created (used only of God)<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4a" />Tuhan Allah bekin langit deng bumi pung carita, andia bagitu.<bt>Lord God made the sky and the earth's story, it's like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tolədot: life and times; the other"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tolədot: life and times; the other ten times this word is used in Genesis in refers to a group of generations defined by a genealogy. Here there's no generation yet, but the idea of what went on during a significant period remains. UBS and several modern translations relate it to Chapter 1, though it could be read as introducing the rest of Chapter 2. In Chapter 10 it is also used to point backwards, so the UBS idea makes sense. The style changes in the next sentence. hibarʾam (brʾ nif inf pl): being created, acts of creation<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah bekin laki-laki deng parampuan<bt>Lord God makes man and woman</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 19:4-6; Markus 10:4-9; 1 Korintus 6:16; 15:45,47; Efesus 5:31-33)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4b" />Waktu TUHAN Allah baru mulai bekin langit deng bumi tu,<bt>When the LORD God had just begun to make the sky and the world, [EXEG: “Just begun” is necessary to signal the flashback in 4-5 to the earlier state of creation before there were plants or rain, or humans (e.g. before the third day). Otherwise, it is taken as a confusing continuation of the preceding verses. Commentators are in full agreement that this takes up a second pass at the story filling in more details (like adding a second OHP acetate laid over the first one). This is a well described strategy of Hebrew narrative discourse. This second pass begins by setting the stage prior to the creation of humans.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="There are cases where it's clear"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">There are cases where it's clear that God wants people to know that he has a name, Yahweh. We're departing from the Jewish tradition (although the New Testament regularly follows LXX in rendering YHWH as Kyrios) whenever it seems important, but we usually associate it with "Boss#" to give terminological uniformity. Begins new Seder.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yhwh: the name of God was so respected that to this day most Jewish people hesitate to pronounce it. [2005 The Messianic rabbi Barbara is studying Hebrew with has no problem about reading "Yahweh," though his prayer book and his congregation read "ʾAdonay" in the rituals.] Instead they say "adonai" ‘Master’ when they come across it in the Bible, and now they mostly read "hasshem" ‘the Name’. Most modern translations, but not all, use the regular term for master, but spell it with small capitals to show it is really the name of God. People later on didn't realize why the Jews were doing it. So the Gentiles (one suspects they were Roman) took the consonants of the Name and the vowels of "ədonay" which were written under the consonants as a reminder not to read the consonants, and made up the mixed spelling "Iehovah", which represents a misunderstanding of the Jewish writing. That morphed into a "J" spelling in German. Let's try writing "Boss" with a "#" added at the end, which the computer will turn into small capital letters automatically. HCE: We've changed "Boss#" to "Yahweh" in different ways in different contexts for several books in a matter of minutes. Once we agree that Yahweh intends that he be known by that name, the Pharasaic tradition, dating from Ezra's time or a little later, of "putting a hedge around the Torah" falls apart, and one could argue that following it violates several princples of good translation. Not the least is the reaction of some of the translators to "boss," as used both on the plantations and in current usage, as carrying along a lot of negatives. One translator prefers Good Boss. But Yahweh doesn't mean "boss" anyway, and just using the Name solves the problem of people preaching sermons down the line on the Lordship of Christ, and taking verses that mention Yahweh as their text, rather than the numerous texts that do assert that he is the Boss.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʿasot: make, infinitive</Message></Annotation><v n="5-6" />balóm ada tanaman apa-apa, tagal Dia balóm kasi turun ujan. Itu waktu, yang ada cuma kabut yang nae dari tana ko bekin basa bumi. Deng balóm ada manusia yang bekin kabón.<bt>there were not yet any plants, because He had not yet sent down the rain. At that time, what there was was only fog which came up from the ground to wet the earth. And there were not yet humans to make gardens/fields.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="siyach: shrub, bush sadeh: open country,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">siyach: shrub, bush sadeh: open country, open field; also fields aroun a city<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>Terem: not yet (only on the last situation) ʿesev: grass<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>yitsmach: spring up, sprout himəTir (mTr hif): make the rain come, send rain<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>ʾayin: wasnʾt any ʿavod (inf): work the soil, till<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>ʾed: exhalation, vapour (of the ground) hishqah (shqh hif): caused to drink<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais ju TUHAN Allah ame tana sadiki, ko bekin ame jadi manusia. Ais Dia fuu kasi maso napas pi dalam dia pung lobang idong, ju itu manusia idop memang.<bt>Then the LORD God took a little gound/soil, and made it become a human. Then He blew breath entering into his nostril, and so that human immediately came to life.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bekin ame jadi pot ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">bekin ame jadi pot ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitsar: form, shape as a potter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yitsar: form, shape as a potter shapes a bowl, fashion ʿafar: loose soil like clay, not small and dry like dust<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʾadam, ʾadamah: "man" and "groun" sound very similar in Hebrew yipaH (npH narr): blew on his breath on him<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʾapayw: his nose, the center part of his face nishmat: breath<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>hayyim: lifetime, duration of life, being alive, life nefesh hayyah: a living soul<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais itu, TUHAN Allah buka ame satu kabón di tana Eden, di sablá matahari nae. Ju Dia kasi itu manusia ko tenga di itu kabón.<bt>After that, the LORD God made a garden in the land of Eden, on/to the east side. And He made [without force] the human live in that garden.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiTTaʿ (nTʿ qal narrative): plant a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiTTaʿ (nTʿ qal narrative): plant a garden or vineyard. The narrative tenses yiTTaʿ ... yasem make it sound like God (1) created man, (2) planted a park somewhere else, (3) transported the man to the new park and placed him there. If the park were already in place, I would expect niTaʿ. gan: garden, oasis; not a vegetable garden [Stanley had already run into this in a Bible study with Lucky], but more like Foster Gardens or Maluhia or Liliʿuʿokalani, like a park with trees.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>miqqedem: in front = on the east side, in an eastern region yasem (sym narr): he put<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Dalam itu kabón, Dia su kasi idop macam-macam pohon yang bagus, deng pohon yang orang bisa makan deng enak. Dia ju kasi idop dua macam pohon di itu kabón pung teng-tenga. Kalo orang makan dari pohon yang satu pung bua, dia dapa idop tarús. Ma kalo orang makan dari pohon yang satu lai pung bua, dia bisa tau mana yang bae deng mana yang jahat.<bt>Inside that garden, He had brought to life various sorts of nice trees, and ones which people could eat deliciously. He also brought to life to kinds of trees in the middle of that garden. If someone ate the fruit from one of the trees, s/he could live continually. But if someone ate the fruit from the other tree, s/he could know which is good and which is evil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bekin idop = direct, implies died"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">bekin idop = direct, implies died ; kasi idop = indirect, cause</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatsmaH (hif): make plants grow or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yatsmaH (hif): make plants grow or sprout; cause to sprout neHmad: desirable to look at, pleasing, beautiful: "pleasant to the sight"<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>lmarʾeh: to the sight, vision maʾakal: eating, food<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>eating the fruit of the Tree of Life and the Tree of the Knowledge of Good and Evil would make them have their effect daʿat: general knowledge, technical knowledge or ability, knowledge about something, acquaintance with (as here)<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>raʿ: bad quality, inferior, ugly, disagreeable, bad, no value, evil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ada kali satu di situ, yang malele kaluar dari itu kabón. Itu kali bacabang ampa.<bt>In that place there was a river which flowed out from that garden. That river had four branches.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nahar: river like in Waimea Valley,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nahar: river like in Waimea Valley, flowing all the time. From it came the water that made the trees in the park grow. It went on outside the park, and there it split and went four different ways yotseʾ (partcpl): rising, coming forth<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>hashqot: = v. 6, supply water for plants (also for providing things to drink for people) yippared (prd nif): was divided; branched off, like a river delta or a family tree where parts separate from each other<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>raʾshim: head, beginning, head of family group, branch of a river, highest part</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Dia pung cabang partama, nama Pison. Itu cabang bataputar kuliling tana Hawila, yang ada banya mas.<bt>Its first branch, was named Pison. That river twisted around through the land of Hawila, where there was a lot of gold.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʾechad: number one, the first, not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">haʾechad: number one, the first, not in importance, but just the first one mentioned Sovev: going aroun, flow aroun the outside (or wind through the middle)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>Hawilah: nobody knows where this is, but the idea is that the river that came out of Eden was the source of watta for the whole ancient world zahav: gold<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Di situ ada mas barisi, ada pohon yang dia pung dara wangi, deng ada batu mangkilat.<bt>In that place there was pure gold, there were trees with fragrant sap (&gt;blood), and there were shiny rocks/gems. [EXEG: Heb /shoham/: “lapis lazuli or onyx or carnelian, a precious stone”. I.e. what is clear is that it is some sort of precious stone (as CEV). What is not clear from current knowledge of the Hebrew is what kind (although many translations follow the traditional English translation of “onyx”. Indonesian /krisopras/ consistently carries zero meaning to both translators and UNS's in both Maluku and NTT. Even if it were onyx, nobody would know what to call it with any certainty that readers would understand. Specific-generic.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mas barisi = pure gold ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">mas barisi = pure gold ; mangkilat = something inherently shiny ; bakilat = reflects s.t.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tov: good quality (gold) bədolach: bdellium,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tov: good quality (gold) bədolach: bdellium, fragrant, transparent, yellowish gum-resin from a South Arabian tree, used in perfume<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʾeven: stone shoham: lapis lazuli or onyx or carnelian, a precious stone<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Itu kali pung cabang kadua, nama Gihon. Itu cabang bataputar kuliling tana Kus.<bt>The river's second branch was named Gihon. That branch twisted throughout the land of Kus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sheni: number two, another river Kush:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">sheni: number two, another river Kush: may refer to Nubia, or southern Sudan, or around the Red Sea, or an area in Mesopotamia where the Kassites lived<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dolu ini tana pung nama &lt;Kus&gt;. Sakarang dia bagian dari negara Etiopia deng negara Sudan, yang ada di Afrika pung sablá matahari nae.<bt>Formerly the land was named &lt;Kus&gt;., Now it is part of the country of Etiopia, and the country of Sudan on the eastern side of Afrika.</bt></note><v n="14" />Dia pung cabang katiga, nama Tigris. Ini cabang ni jadi batas di tana Asyur<bt>Its third branch was named Tigris. This branch boundaries the eastern side of the land of Asyur.</bt><note reference="2:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Asyur tu, negara yang sakarang nama &lt;Irak&gt;.<bt>That Asyur, is in the country which is now named &lt;Irak&gt;.</bt></note>pung sablá matahari nae. Dia pung cabang ka'ampa, nama Efrat.<bt>Its fourth branch is named Efrat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiddeqel: the Tigris river in Iraq,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hiddeqel: the Tigris river in Iraq, now flows north of Baghdad holekh: water flowing<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>qidmat: in front = on the east side ʾashshur: Assyria<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>frat: the Euphrates river, now flows through Baghdad</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />TUHAN Allah kasi itu manusia tenga di Eden, ko dia urus bae-bae itu kabón.<bt>The LORD God made that human live in Eden, so he could properly manage that garden/field.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqach: take, laqach, modern Hebrew qach"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiqqach: take, laqach, modern Hebrew qach yannichehu (nwch hif): settled him, caused him to rest, live in that place<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʿavdah: till soil, cultivate plants, work (= v. 5) shamrah: watch, guard something, but without saying what the danger might have been, take responsibility to make sure it is okay<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ju Dia parenta sang itu manusia bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu bole makan bua apa sa dari samua pohon di ini kabón.<bt>And He commanded that human saying, &lt;&lt;You-sg may eat any fruit from all the trees in this garden.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ytsav: order, direct somebody to do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ytsav: order, direct somebody to do something, command, give an order leʾmor: with these words, like quotation marks<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʾakhol toʾkhel (ʾkl inf): permission to eat freely</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ma ada satu yang lu sonde bole makan. Andia, itu pohon yang kasi tau mana yang bae deng mana yang jahat. Kalo lu makan, lu pasti mati.&gt;&gt;<bt>But there is one which you may not eat. That is the tree which makes one know which is good and which is evil. If you eat [it], you will certainly die.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="EXEG: see HCE to combine “physical"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">EXEG: see HCE to combine “physical death” with “spiritual death”</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ais TUHAN Allah omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde bae kalo ini manusia idop sandiri. Jadi Beta mau bekin kasi dia, satu tamán yang pas deng dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the LORD God spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;It is not good for this manusia to live alone. So I want to make for him, a friend/companion who is a good-match with him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoʾmer: God was not talking to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yoʾmer: God was not talking to anybody else, just thinking out loud heyot: be, stay, live (infinitive)<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>lvado: in his solitude, alone ʾeʿesah-lo: I will make for him<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ʿezer: helper, supporter, one who comes to somebody's aid negdo: counterpart, corresponding to him, his opposite<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-20" />Itu waktu, TUHAN Allah ame tana, ko bekin ame macam-macam binatang deng burung. Ais Dia antar bawa itu binatang deng burung dong pi di itu orang, ko biar dia kasi nama sang dong. Tarús, itu orang kasi nama itu binatang deng burung dong, satu-satu deng dia pung nama. Ma dia sandiri balóm dapa satu tamán yang pas deng dia.<bt>At that time, the LORD God took soil, and made various sorts of animals and birds. Then He escorted those animals and birds to that person so he could name them. Then2, that person named those animals and birds, each one with its own name. But only he himself didn't yet get a friend/companion that was a good-match with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitser: formed, shaped, create flashback to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yitser: formed, shaped, create flashback to an earlier scene; not a second creation after the man is created<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>chayyat: animals sadeh: open country, fields (wild animals)<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>yaveʾ: brought = caused the animals to go, not carried them lirʾot: to see. God expected the man to decide the names, and God accepted them<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>matsaʾ: come across, happen to meet, find what you are looking for negdo: his counterpart<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00603c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais itu, TUHAN Allah bekin itu orang ko tidor sonu. Waktu dia ada tidor, Tuhan ame dia pung tulang rebis satu, ais tutu kambali itu luka.<bt>After that, the LORD God cause that person to sleep soundly. When he was asleep, God took one of his rib bones, and then covered/closed back that wound.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kuuk = ribcage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">kuuk = ribcage</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yappel (npl hif): cause to fall"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yappel (npl hif): cause to fall down, cause to lie down tardemah: snoring, deep sleep, stupefied, supernatural stupor, out like a light, deep, sound sleep<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>yiyshan (yshn imperf): he went to sleep achat: one thing<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>mitsalotayw: from his ribs, one of his ribs, from his side where the ribs are yisgor: close, shut<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>basar: skin, living flesh tachtennah: closed what was underneath with flesh<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Dari itu tulang tu, Dia bekin jadi parampuan. Ais Dia sarakan itu parampuan pi itu orang.<bt>From that bone, He made it become a woman. Then He turned-over that woman to that person.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiven: make something out of material."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiven: make something out of material. Start with a rib and end up with a woman. The rib was the material from which the woman was made. Not as if he turned the rib into a woman by magic, but he built the woman out of the rib laqah: took<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>lʾishshah: made the rib (as material) into a woman yviʾeah: made her go, like the animals -- not forcing her to go<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Lia itu parampuan, ju itu orang bilang,<bt>Seeing that woman, that person said,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Naaa! Ini dolo! Ini baru pas deng beta!<bt>&lt;&lt;Naaa! Here it is [finally now]! Only with this one is there a good-match with me!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dia pung tulang sama deng beta pung tulang.<bt>Her bones are the same as my bones.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Deng dia pung daging ju sama deng beta pung daging.<bt>And her meat/flesh is also the same as my flesh.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tagal dia jadi dari laki-laki, andia ko beta kasi nama sang dia &lt;parampuan&gt;.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because she was made from a male, that is why I will name her &lt;female&gt;.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paʿam: time, occurrence, once = this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">paʿam: time, occurrence, once = this time, at last, after checking out all the animals ʿetsem: bone, bones, seat of perceptions, total being, complete identity<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>ishshah, ish: the Hebrew words for "woman" and "man" sound similar luqəchah (lqch passive): she was taken<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, laki-laki bilang <span class="Italic">&lt;ish&gt;.</span> Deng parampuan bilang &lt;<span class="Italic">isha</span>&gt;. Jadi di sini dong ada maen kata bilang, &lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">isha</span> (parampuan) jadi dari <span class="Italic">ish</span> (laki-laki).&gt;&gt;<bt>In the Ibrani language 'male' is &lt;<span class="Italic">ish</span>&gt;. And 'female' is <span class="Italic">&lt;isha&gt;.</span> So here they (non-referential) are playing with words saying, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;isha</span> (female) came into being from <span class="Italic">ish</span> (male).&gt;&gt;</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Tagal itu, laki-laki musti kasi tenga dia pung papa deng dia pung mama,<bt>Because of that, a man must leave behind his father and his mother, [NOTE to daughter translations: here the Kupang /musti/ with third person generic is expressing an ideal action that results in ideal state of affairs. It is not a second person command. Check carefully that the rendering in your language is taken in a weaker, rather than a stronger obligatory sense. Omit the modal if you can't find a workable rendering with it.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko pi idop satu hati deng dia pung bini,<bt>to go live in one accord (&lt;one liver) with his wife,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="not just satu atap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">not just satu atap</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te dong dua su ta'ika jadi satu.<bt>so the two of the are bound/united as one.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʿazav: leaves behind, abandons, leaving not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yaʿazav: leaves behind, abandons, leaving not in the sense that the man rejects his parents, but that he doesn't live with them any more; he lives with his wife instead vədavaq: clings, sticks to, hold on to (deveq ʾsoldering, weldingʾ), be united with. It includes sex, but it also includes the new family unit<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>basar ʾechad: one body, one relationship (our very own brother = brother of our basar). Composite oneness (as in the Shemaʿ, ʾəloheynuw ʾechad).</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Itu waktu, dong dua ada talanjang bulat, ma dong sonde ada rasa malu sadiki ju.<bt>At that time, the two of them were stark naked, but they felt no shame/embarrassment.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shnehem: the two of them ʿarummim:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">shnehem: the two of them ʿarummim: naked, unclothed, genital areas exposed<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>yitboshashu (bwsh hitpaʿel): did not feel shame, did not appear being ashamed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Manusia sonde mau dengar sang Tuhan Allah<bt>Humans don't want to listen to/obey Lord God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Dari samua binatang yang TUHAN Allah su bekin di ini dunya, ular yang paling pintar putar-balek. Satu kali, ada ular yang tanya sang itu parampuan bilang, &lt;&lt;Batúl, ko? Tuhan Allah ada larang bilang, &lt;Bosong sonde bole makan bua dari pohon-pohon di ini kabón, aa?&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Among all the animals which the LORD God had made in this world, the snake was the most clever at deceit. One time, there was a snake which asked that woman, &lt;&lt;Is it true? Did Lord God forbid saying, &lt;You-pl may not eat the fruit from the trees that are in this garden, right?&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bamengge = putar-putar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">bamengge = putar-putar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿarum: subtle, shrewd, clever; crafty, sly,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿarum: subtle, shrewd, clever; crafty, sly, wise -- wise, but with an evil agenda. In Hebrew the word sounds like ʿarummim "naked" in 2:25 ʾaf: really? even; agreeing but not agreeing<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00606c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Itu parampuan balas bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde! Botong bole makan! Ma ada satu pohon di tenga kabón sa, yang Tuhan Allah larang botong makan. Dia bilang botong sonde bole makan, deng sonde bole sonto dia pung bua, te nanti botong mati.&gt;&gt;<bt>The woman responded saying, &lt;&lt;No! We-exc are allowed to eat [them]! But there is only just one tree in the middle of the garden, which Lord God fordade. He said we are not allowed to eat, and not allowed to touch its fruit, cuz (elaboration) then we will die.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pen: lest, so that ... not,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">pen: lest, so that ... not, prevent an otherwise predictable event tmutun: for you to die<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ma itu ular manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;We, itu sonde batúl! Bosong sonde mati!<bt>But that snake answered saying, &lt;&lt;We, that's not true! You-pl won't die!</bt><v n="5" />Tuhan Allah memang larang bagitu, tagal Dia su tau kalo bosong makan itu bua, bosong jadi pintar sama ke Dia. Andia, tau mana yang bae, deng mana yang jahat.&gt;&gt;<bt>Lord God really forbade in that way, because He already knows, if you-pl eat that fruit, you will become clever/knowledgeable just like Him. That is, knowing which is good, and which is evil.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nifqəhu: passive, be opened (eyes, not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nifqəhu: passive, be opened (eyes, not other things) -- metaphor for coming to understand (see) things after not knowing, which is like wandering around in the dark ʿeyneychem: your eyes<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>yodʿey (partcpl pl): those who know</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ais, itu parampuan lia te itu pohon pung bagus lai, deng dia pung bua tingka ke enak sakali. Ju dia pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo beta makan ini bua, tantu beta jadi pintar.&gt;&gt; Ais dia ketu itu bua, ju dia makan. Ais dia bawa kasi dia pung laki, ju dia pung laki iko makan.<bt>Then that woman saw how attractive that tree was, and its fruit it seemed that it would be delicious. She also thought saying, &lt;&lt;If I eat this fruit, certainly I will become clever.&gt;&gt; So she picked (=broke off with hand) that fruit, and she ate. Then she took and gave it to her husband/man, and her husband also ate [along with/following her].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʾəwah-huʾ: longing, desire; it was a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">taʾəwah-huʾ: longing, desire; it was a delight to the eyes nechmad: desirable<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>lhaskil (skl hif inf): make you understand, make you be keen and clever mipiryo: some of its fruit<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>gam: associating, adding, too</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Makan abis ju, baru dong tau bilang, dong dua ada talanjang bulat. Andia ko dong natok daon ko tutu dong pung talanjang.<bt>After eating, they suddenly realised that the two of them were stark naked. That is why they poked-joining leaves to cover their nakedness.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mala'e = anyam (but can't do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">mala'e = anyam (but can't do it with fig leaves); natok = tusuk deng lidi utk sambung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tipaqachnah (nif): were opened, the eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tipaqachnah (nif): were opened, the eyes of the two of them ʿeyrummim (adj): naked<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yitpəru (tpr): sew things together (fasten?) ʿaleh: leaves, foliage. SK "would have been cheaper"<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>tʾenah: fig, Ficus Carica has fairly big leaves, bigger than your hand but smaller than a taro leaf; FF 118,119 chgorot: loincloths, belts, sashes, something around the middle; a band (made out of leather or cloth) or a piece of cloth worn around the waist<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Dia pung sore, dong dengar TUHAN Allah ada bajalan di itu kabón. Ais dong pi sambunyi di balakang pohon, ko biar TUHAN sonde dapa lia sang dong.<bt>That afternoon, they heard the LORD God walking in that garden. So they went and hid behind [a] tree, so the LORD would not be able to see them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mithallekh (hlk hitp partcpl): walking vayyishimiʿu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mithallekh (hlk hitp partcpl): walking vayyishimiʿu: they heard<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>qol: voice, sound vayyitchabeʾ (chbʾ hitp sg with pl NP): be in a place where one can not be readily seen, often used in contexts implying danger<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ma TUHAN Allah pange itu laki-laki bilang, &lt;&lt;We, Adam! Lu ada di mana?&gt;&gt;<bt>But the LORD God called the man saying, &lt;&lt;We! Adam, where are you?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqraʾ: call out to somebody lo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiqraʾ: call out to somebody lo ʾayyekah: ?<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Itu laki-laki manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ada dengar Tuhan pung suara di sini. Ma beta malu, te beta ada talanjang. Andia ko beta lari sambunyi.&gt;&gt;<bt>The man answered saying, &lt;&lt;I heard the Lord's voice here. But I was ashamed/embarrassed, cuz (elaboration) I am naked. So that is why I ran and hid.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾiyraʾ: I was afraid"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾiyraʾ: I was afraid</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ais Tuhan bilang, &lt;&lt;Sapa yang kasi tau kalo lu ada talanjang? Karmana? Tantu lu su makan itu bua yang beta larang, aa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the Lord said, &lt;&lt;Who told you that you are naked? How is it? You have surely eaten that fruit that I forbade, right?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mi: who? higgid (ngd hif): announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mi: who? higgid (ngd hif): announced to you (sg)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʿeyrom: naked ha-: is it ...? isn't it ...?<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tsiwwiyticha: I ordered you, I forbade you lbtilti: non-existence, not to do something<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʾəkhal (inf): to eat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini parampuan yang Tuhan kasi ko batamán deng beta tu, dia yang kasi itu bua ko beta makan!&gt;&gt;<bt>He answered saying, &lt;&lt;This woman that the Lord gave as my companion, she is the one who gave me that fruit to eat!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="natattah: you gave, put here ʿimmadi:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">natattah: you gave, put here ʿimmadi: my company, with me to help me [SK laugh]<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʾokhel (narrative): I ate [it]</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ais ju TUHAN Allah omong deng itu parampuan bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko lu bekin bagitu?&gt;&gt;<bt>So then the LORD God spoke to the woman saying, &lt;&lt;Why did you do that?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju itu parampuan manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ko ular tipu ame sang beta na! Andia ko beta makan itu bua, suda ma.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the woman answered saying, &lt;&lt;The snake tricked me! [+emphatic; defensive] That's why I ate that fruit, [+modal of protest].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="June says you can have su"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">June says you can have su + ma; Lu yang pancuri be pung doi su, ma.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mah-zzot: what is this? why? This"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mah-zzot: what is this? why? This is an accusing question, accuses the person addressed of doing something wrong ʿasit: do, make, bring about<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>hishshiʾani (nshʾ hif): duped, tricked, deceived</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah kasi kutuk sang dong<bt>Lord God curses them</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais itu, ju TUHAN Allah kasi kutuk itu ular bilang,<bt>After that, then the LORD God cursed the snake saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Tagal lu pung bekin ni, Beta kasi hukum sang lu. Dari samua binatang yang laen, cuma lu sandiri yang kaná kutuk bagini. Mulai sakarang sampe lu mati, lu cuma tau marayap deng dada sa, deng lu tau makan di tana sa.<bt>&lt;&lt;Because of what you have done, I am punishing you. From (among) all the other animals, only you alone are cursed like this. Beginning now until you die, you will only be able to just crawl on your chest, and you will only be able to just eat on the ground. [EXEG: HCE, MC “No speakers of languages I've checked believe that snakes ‘eat’ dirt.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾarur (ʾrr partcpl passive): inflicted with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾarur (ʾrr partcpl passive): inflicted with a curse (by God) miqol habehemah: away from all the animals, in a way that the animals are not (also 4:11), domestic or wild<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ghon: belly of a reptile telek (halak): go, characteristic was of getting around. For snakes, crawl or creep<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʿafar: dry, fine particles of dirt, dust, loose soil, rubble from something that has been destroyed. Carries with it the idea of something perishable and transitory toʾchal: eat, probably metaphorically rather than physically. The two lines mean about the same thing. Should they be collapsed?<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Beta bekin lu deng ini parampuan bamusu tarús. Deng bosong dua pung turunan dong, ju bagitu. Lu pung turunan nanti gigi ame orang pung tumit. Ma dia pung turunan satu, nanti titi bekin ancor lu pung kapala.&gt;&gt;<bt>I make you and this woman to be enemies continually. And the descendents of both of you will also be like that. Your descendent will bite at the heal of a person. But one of her descendents will smash (&lt;bop causing destruction) you on the head.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadeluk ; titi ; habok ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">kadeluk ; titi ; habok ; hamok</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeyvah: hostile intention, enmity, enemy ʾashit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾeyvah: hostile intention, enmity, enemy ʾashit (shayat): I order, put, appoint, direct, make something into something<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>zeraʿ: seed, offspring. Can be plural, all humans. Can be singular, one particular descendent, a prophecy of Christ yshufcha (shwp): he will crush you [SK picha!]<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>roʾsh: head tshufennu (shwp): you will snap at, snatch at him, Holladay lists as different - why?<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʿaqev: heel End of S section<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais itu, Tuhan Allah kasi tau itu parampuan bilang,<bt>Then Lord God told the woman saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Nanti Beta tamba lu pung susa waktu dudu parú, deng tamba saki waktu lu barana. Biar bagitu, ma lu ju masi rindu tarús sang lu pung laki. Deng dia yang ator sang lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;I will increase your difficulty when you are pregnant, and increase your pain when you give birth. Even that being the case, nevertheless you will still continue to yearn for your man/husband. And he will organise/manage you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="harbah ʾarbeh: I will definitely make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">harbah ʾarbeh: I will definitely make greater ʿitstsəvonech: your hardship, pain, distress<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>heronech: your pregnancy ʿetsev: pain, hardship<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>teldi (yalad): you will bear children tshuqatech (shuq): your urge, craving, impulse, also in 4:7 and SS 7:10 (4:7 suggests it could be an urge to dominate that will be frustrated, but SS 7:10 is sexual desire). UBS suggests it covers any kind of strong urge.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>Exchange between MC &amp; JEG: [MC] "4:7 is an extended metaphor. I think this refers just to sexual desire, in spite of painful childbirth, as youʾve translated it." [JEG] "The relationship between the parts seems to be that even though pregnancy and childbirth will be more painful than they would have been, it will be worth it to you [and he will reciprocate? and he will be in a dominant position over you? be your leader?]" yimshal (qal): rule, govern, dominate, control; but also "repeat, be like," hif "compare with" (rare, not in Qal except here, if this is that verb). "Be like" never occurs in the qal unless this is the one instance. It is the stem behind mashal ʾproverb, analogyʾ, so it would fit one meaning of the passage. But the "control" meaning occurs 80 times in the qal.<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais Tuhan kasi tau itu laki-laki bilang,<bt>Then the Lord told the man saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Lu sonde iko Beta pung parenta, ma iko lu pung bini pung mau, sampe lu makan itu bua yang Beta su larang tu. Andia ko lu ju kaná hukum. Deng tana kaná hukum ju. Mulai sakarang sampe lu mati, lu musti karjá banting tulang bale tana, ko lu bisa dapa makan. Deng karjá bagitu, baru lu dapa idop.<bt>&lt;&lt;You didn't follow my command, but followed your wife's desire, to-point-that you ate that fruit which I had forbidden. That is why you also get punished. And the ground will also be punished. Beginning now until you die, you must work incredibly hard turning the soil, so you can get food. Working that way, only-then will you be able to live.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsivitiach: I ordered you leʾmor: infinitive,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tsivitiach: I ordered you leʾmor: infinitive, to say<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʾarurah: passive participle, cursed. A curse will be placed on the ground, God will make something bad happen to the ground, and probably by saying so, God made it happen right then and there baʿavureach: on account of you<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʿitsavon: pain, hardship, distress [= v. 16]</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Biar lu tanam macam-macam, ma tana cuma kasi kaluar duri deng onak sa.<bt>Even though you plant various sorts, but nevertheless the ground will only just put out thorns and brier patches.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="onak = brier patch (?), like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">onak = brier patch (?), like blackberry patch (BI = onak)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qots: thorn bush dardar: whorl, a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">qots: thorn bush dardar: whorl, a kind of thistle, Centaurea pallescens or iberica, very thorny and prickly<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>tatsmiach: make plants grow ʿesev: broad term that includes weeds, grass, vegetables, cereals, grains, wild and cultivated both. Up to this time they had been eating the things God planted for them inside the park<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>[JEG] Syntacticians distinguish "benefactive" from "malefactive"; but in many languages the actual semantics is "applicative," affecting you in some way, good or bad. That's how SK take "fo you." But we put in "too" because some of the seed does actually come up.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ais lu musti karjá banting tulang, baru tana kasi lu makan. Lu musti karjá parés karingat bagitu sampe mati. Beta bekin ame sang lu dari tana. Jadi kalo lu mati, lu kambali pi jadi tana lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>So you must work to the bone, and only-then with the ground give you food. You must work squeezing sweat like that until you die. I made you from the ground. So when you die, you will return to become soil again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zeʿat: sweat ʿad: up to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">zeʿat: sweat ʿad: up to the time, during<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>shuvach: your return ʾadamah: soil<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>luqqkchta: you are one who has been taken ʿafar: dust, crumbled dry dirt<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ais itu, Adam kasi nama dia pung bini &lt;Hawa&gt; (yang dia pung arti &lt;yang idop&gt;), te dia tu, samua orang yang idop pung mama.<bt>After that, Adam named his wife &lt;Hawa&gt;, cuz (elaboration) she is the mother of all who live.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ftn on Hawa changed into text"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Ftn on Hawa changed into text from Dhao check Sept 2004 ***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chawwah: &quot;Eve&quot; in Hebrew reminds people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">chawwah: "Eve" in Hebrew reminds people of chay "alive"</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, &lt;<span class="Italic">adam</span>&gt; pung arti &lt;manusia&gt;.<bt>In the Hebrew language, &lt;<span class="Italic">adam</span>&gt; means 'human'.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00605c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais TUHAN Allah bekin pakean dari binatang pung kulit, ko kasi dong dua pake.<bt>Then the LORD God made clothes from the skin of animals, and gave to the two of them to wear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi pake dong dua = God"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">kasi pake dong dua = God puts it on them; kasi dong dua pake = God gives it and they put it on themselves</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katnot: long shirt-like undergarments, like a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">katnot: long shirt-like undergarments, like a long t-shirt, but made out of animal hides ʿor: skin, hide<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>yalvishem: cause somebody to put on a garment, clothe somebody [no need "fo wear" SK] End of S section.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah usir kasi kaluar Adam deng Hawa<bt>Lord God evicts out Adam and Hawa</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais TUHAN Allah omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang, ini orang dong su tau mana yang bae, deng mana yang jahat, sama ke Kotong. Jang sampe dong ju makan bua dari itu pohon yang kasi dong idop tarús.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the LORD God spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Now these people know what is good and what is evil, just like Us-inc. It should not be that they also eat the fruit of the tree that makes them live continually.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins new Seder. vayyoʾmer: said (to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">Begins new Seder. vayyoʾmer: said (to himself, in this case)<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>kʾachad mimmennu: like one of us viʿattah: so now, in the present situation, introducing a new thought<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>pen-yishlach: in order to keep him from putting out his hand yado: his hand<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>gam: in addition to the other ʿolam: long time, all the coming time, forever<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ais ju Dia usir kasi kaluar sang dong dari itu kabón di Eden, ko dong pi tampa laen, idop deng bale tana, ko dong idop dari tana pung hasil.<bt>So then He evicted them out from that garden in Eden, so they went to live in another place, living by turning the soil, so they can live from the produce of the ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***clause deleted, plus last clause changed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">***clause deleted, plus last clause changed from Amarasi check Oct 2005</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yshallechehu: he drove them out, sent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yshallechehu: he drove them out, sent them away laʿavod<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>luqqach: was taken from</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ais ju Dia usir kasi kaluar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Ais ju Dia usir kasi kaluar sang dong dari itu kabón di Eden, ko dong pi di tampa laen, idop deng bale tana. Te manusia asal dari tana, jadi dong ju musti idop dari tana.</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Usir abis, ju Tuhan suru Dia pung ana bua basayap dari sorga dong,<bt>After evicting, then the Lord ordered his *winged underlings from heaven,</bt><note reference="3:24" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, Tuhan pung ana bua basayap dari sorga tu, &lt;<span class="Italic">kerubim</span>&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language, the Lord's winged underlings from heaven are called, &lt;<span class="Italic">kerubim</span>&gt;.</bt></note>ko pi jaga di itu kabón pung sablá matahari nae. Dong pegang kalewang yang ta'ayun pi-datang, yang manyala sama ke api. Tuhan suru dong tutu jalan maso, te Dia sonde mau orang dong ketu ame itu bua yang kasi dong idop tarús.<bt>to go guard that garden on the east side. They held [a] fighting-sword which swivelled back-and-forth and flashed like fire. The Lord ordered them to close the entrance path, cuz (elaboration) He didn't want the people to pick the fruit which make them live continually.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta'ayun ~ ba'ayun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">ta'ayun ~ ba'ayun</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ygaresh: banish, drive out yashken: settle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ygaresh: banish, drive out yashken: settle somebody in a place, make them live there<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>miqqedem: in front = on the east side hakkruvim: fierce living beings with wings, the body of a lion or a bull, and the face of a man. In Ezekiel they are spoken of only as "living beings" in Chapter 1 and "cherubim" in Chapter 10. They guard holy places. In the Bible they are never classified as angels (messengers who serve God and do his bidding), because that is not their job, though they seem to be a similar kind of being.<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>Exchange between MC &amp; JEG: [MC] Isnʾt Ezekiel in the Bible? (note is confusing); [JEG] Most mentions of them are as artistic objects; only here and in Ezekiel 1 and 10 are they referred to in their living form. lahat hacherev: flaming blade of a sword (dagger or short sword)<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>hammit happechet: ? turning every which way lishmor: to guard [=2:15]<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kaen deng Habel pung carita<bt>Kaen and Habel's story</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Ais Adam pi tidor deng dia pung bini Hawa. Ju itu parampuan dudu parú. Ais ju dia barana satu ana laki-laki. Ju dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su barana kasi kaluar satu ana laki-laki, tagal TUHAN su tolong sang beta.&gt;&gt; Ais dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Kaen</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;kasi kaluar&gt;).<bt>Then/later (vague) Adam went and slept with his wife Hawa. Then the woman became pregnant. Then she gave birth to a son. And she said, &lt;&lt;I have given birth bringing out a son, because the LORD has helped me.&gt;&gt; So she named the child, Kaen (which means &lt;bring-out&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yadaʿ: knew, a euphemism for sex"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yadaʿ: knew, a euphemism for sex tahar (harah): she got pregnant<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>teled (yalad): she had a baby qayn, qaniti (qanah): "Cain" sounds like "get" in Hebrew. Acquire, buy<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʾet: with the help of, together with, in the presence of (not ʾet accusative)</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ais Hawa barana lai satu ana laki-laki. Ju dia kasi nama <span class="Italic">Habel</span>.<bt>Then Hawa gave birth to another son. And she named him Habel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu dong dua bésar datang, Habel gambala binatang, deng Kaen karjá kabón.<bt>When the two of them were grown, Habel became a shepherd, and Kaen worked the fields/gardens.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) su bésar - bésar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">*** (2009) su bésar - bésar datang (naturalness)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatosef (yasaf): she went on to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vatosef (yasaf): she went on to do, continued doing, did it again laledet: to have a child<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>achiv: his brother roʿeh: shepherd<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>tsoʾn: small livestock (sheep and goats) ʿoved ʾədamah (ʿavad): cultivator, tiller of the soil, dirt farmer<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Satu kali, Kaen bawa ame dia pung kabón pung hasil saparu, ko kasi sang TUHAN.<bt>One time, Kaen brought part of the produce of his garden, to give to the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bawa ame = take purposely ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">bawa ame = take purposely ; Ya, beta ame bawa Om Sam pung CD = take unintentionally @@</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qets: limit, boundary, miqqets yamim some"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">qets: limit, boundary, miqqets yamim some time later, at the end of a period yaveʾ (boʾ hif.): cause to come, bring in<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>pəriy: some of the fruit. May be more generic. minchah: present, gift to show respect; sacrifice of homage or allegiance<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Habel ju bawa ame dia pung domba mai dong pung ana partama. Dia horo itu domba dong, ais dia bawa daging yang paling bae kasi sang Tuhan. Lia bagitu, TUHAN pung hati sanáng sang Habel deng dia pung korban tu.<bt>Habel also brought his female sheep's first offspring. He butchered those sheep, and then brought the best meat to give to the Lord. Seeing that, the LORD was please with Habel and his *offering/sacrifice [korban].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bchorot: firstborn mehelvehen (chelev): fat in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">bchorot: firstborn mehelvehen (chelev): fat in the body, choicest part of the meat for offering<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yishaʿ (shaʿah): look with favor. In Gen 4:4-5, it means to look at with approval, to approve of.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ma Dia sonde suka sang Kaen deng dia pung korban tu. Ju Kaen mara mau mati, sampe dia pung muka asaráng.<bt>But He didn't like Kaen and his sacrifice. So Kaen was very angry, to-point-that his face was vicious.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar (charah apocopated): became angry, anger"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yichar (charah apocopated): became angry, anger broke out in Cain yipplu (nafal fall): face fell, he was downcast.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju TUHAN omong deng Kaen bilang, &lt;&lt;He, Kaen! Akurang ko lu mara bagitu? Karmana ko lu pung muka asaráng bagitu?<bt>So the LORD spoke to Kaen saying, &lt;&lt;He, Kaen! Why are you so angry? How come your face is vicious like that?</bt><v n="7" />Kalo lu bekin bae, tantu Beta ju tarima bae sang lu. Ma ati-ati! Kalo lu bekin jahat, nanti itu jahat makan bale sang lu, sama ke kucing mau kobo tikus. Jadi, kalo lu ada kapingin bekin jahat, lebe bae lu tola buang memang!&gt;&gt;<bt>If you do good, I will certainly accept/receive you well. But watch out! If you do evil, that evil will eat you up in return, like a cat about to pounce on a mouse. So (consequently), if you have a desire to do evil, it's best if you reject it immediately!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: last sentence is explication of NRSV: "but you must master it."; NLT "and you must subdue it."; CEV "but don't let it!"]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kobo = pounce and cover ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">kobo = pounce and cover ; kapingin = cenderung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾim-tetiv (ytv hif): if you behave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾim-tetiv (ytv hif): if you behave well, make things go well sʾet: exaltation, raising oneself up; lift up, smile, opposite of hang face. Can mean receiving the sacrifice, or feeling good about it<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>petach: entrance, doorway, opening of a tent, a city hattaʾt: sin (miss a goal, displeasing, offend, blameworthy or guilty, needs confessing and clearing up)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>rovets (rvts pt): lie down with chest to the ground like an animal. Some commentators take this as the name of a demon, but others take it as a metaphor teshuqato: craving, impulse (to take over, same word as in 3:16)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>timshal-bo: are to rule, govern, gain dominion over it, get control</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00617c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Kaen mau bunu sang Habel<bt>Kaen is about to kill Habel</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Satu kali, Kaen buju sang Habel bilang, &lt;&lt;Adi! Mari ko kotong jalan-jalan pi kabón.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Kaen persuaded Habel saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-brother! Let's go for a walk in the fields.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ada barapa tulisan tua yang pake Kaen pung omong tu, ma itu kata dong sonde ada dalam tulisan bahasa Ibrani yang paling tua.<bt>Several old writings have what Kaen says, but these words are not in the oldest Hebrew writings.</bt></note>Waktu dong sampe di sana, takuju sa Kaen papoko bekin mati sang dia pung adi.<bt>When they got there, suddenly Kaen beat to death his younger-brother.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The main Hebrew manuscripts donʾt have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">The main Hebrew manuscripts donʾt have the words Cain used, but the Aramaic ones do. bihyotam (hyh inf 3pl m obj): when they were there<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yaqam: stood up; he went and did something, he up and killed him yahargehu: he killed him, murdered (also used of executions and war, slaughtering an animal -- deliberate)<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais TUHAN tanya sang Kaen bilang, &lt;&lt;He, Kaen! Lu pung adi ada di mana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the LORD asked Kaen saying, &lt;&lt;He, Kaen! Where's your younger-brother?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Kaen manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta sonde tau dia ada di mana! Kira beta ni, tukang pegang dia pung kaki, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>Kaen answered saying, &lt;&lt;I don't know where he is! You think that I am a habitual hanger on his leg! (=Idiom: hang around him all the time).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="alibi = alibi ; tukang koko"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">alibi = alibi ; tukang koko = baby sitter, nanny, penjaga, pengawal ; pegang dia pung kaki = (Idiom) hang around him/her</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾey: where? hashomer: the one who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾey: where? hashomer: the one who looks after him, his protector, guard, custodian<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ju Tuhan omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko lu bekin jahat bagitu? Jang kira ko lu bisa sambunyi lu pung adi pung dara di tana, te Beta su lia samua!<bt>So the Lord said, &lt;&lt;Why did you do evil like that? Don't think that you can hide you younger-brother's blood in the ground, cuz (elaboration) I have seen everything! [EXEG: on “his blood cries out to me”. A lot of work and widespread cultural research has gone into this. Perkara's involving blood put them into a whole different category of cultural baggage (see B.D. Grimes, Fox-various, &amp; other anthro writings around eastern Indonesia). KM avoids the personification (=good translation) and goes for the purpose/result (i.e. the message got across to the one who can/should do something about it). This is clearly the intent from vs.11.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meh ʿasita: what have you done?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">meh ʿasita: what have you done? assumes it was bad. In Pidgin it needs the "hah" [actually nasalized] to make it an accusation; with just the verb it would be an information question, which is not what God needs. dmey: (plural) blood shed in violence, for which a relative (or in this case, God) is supposed to take vengeance<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>tsoʿaqim (participle, plural agreeing with "blood"): raise a cry, wail, call for help (mostly to God). BDB This root means to call out for help under great distress or to utter an exclamation in great excitement. ʾelay: toward me<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>Consultant exchange: [MC] was he/it calling for help or for vengeance? ; [JEG] The Hebrew is specifically a call for help. So calling for vengeance would be reading something into it that's weakly founded, though if it were me I'd probably call for vengeance. One could argue that the only way God could help Abel now is by avenging him -- still, that doesn't sound like Abel.</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Sakarang kutuk su nae kaná sang lu. Te waktu lu bunu lu pung adi, tana isap ame dia pung dara. Jadi sakarang itu tana su sonde bisa kasi idop sang lu lai.<bt>Now a curse is rising upon you. Cuz (elaboration) when you killed your younger-brother, the ground sucked up his blood. So (consequently) now that ground is not going to give life to you anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="weʿattah: introducing a new thought, and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">weʿattah: introducing a new thought, and now ʾarur: cursed so that you canʾt work the soil, or cursed even more than the soil was (in 3:17)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>min-haʾadamah: away from the ground, in a different way than the ground was cursed? more than the ground was cursed? patstah (fem): it has opened wide<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>piyah (peh): mouth, metaphor laqachat: to receive, accept<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>miyyadecha: from your hand</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Kalo lu bekin kabón, tana su sonde mau kasi lu hasil apa-apa lai. Mulai sakarang, lu maen tapaleuk pi-datang sama ke orang kasian yang cari idop di ini dunya.&gt;&gt;<bt>When you make a garden, the ground will not give you any sort of produce anymore. Beginning now, you will be busy wandering back-and-forth like a pitiful person trying to find a way to live/livlihood in this world.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʿavod: you are going to try"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">taʿavod: you are going to try to work the ground tosef (yasaf): it (the ground) will not go on doing<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>kochah: strength (of a field = its yield) naʿ: roaming around withut shelter or home, homeless<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>nod: swaying, being aimless, homeless</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ma Kaen protes sang TUHAN bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Tuhan, é! Karmana ko Tuhan kasi beta kutuk barát talalu, sampe beta su tar bisa pikol lai ni?<bt>But Kaen protested to the LORD saying, &lt;&lt;Awii! Lord, é! How could the Lord give me such a heavy curse, to-point-that I cannot shoulder-carry it any more.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="awii = for s.t. good ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">awii = for s.t. good ; awe' for s.t. bad</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿavoni: my activity that is crooked"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿavoni: my activity that is crooked or wrong, offence, sin, also guilt or punishment. Here it's the punishment he is complaining about; he never addresses the guilt of what he did. nsoʾ (nsʾ inf): more than I can be made to lift, more than I can show my face to<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Tagal Tuhan su usir sang beta dari ini tampa, beta nanti jao dari Tuhan. Beta maen tapaleuk pi mana-mana. Ais sapa sa yang nanti katumu sang beta, tantu dong bunu bekin mati sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Lord has evicted me from this place, so now I will be far from the Lord. I wander from place to place. So just anybody who meets me now will certainly kill me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: demonstrative interjection and conjunction gerashta:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hen: demonstrative interjection and conjunction gerashta: drive out, banish<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʾoti: me meʿal: from over, from upon, down from<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>mippaneycha: from your presence ʾessater: I will hide<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>motsʾi (mtsʾ partcpl): who happens to meet me by chance</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ma TUHAN manyao bale bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde bagitu! Sapa yang bunu sang lu, Beta nanti hukum sang dia tuju kali lebe barát!&gt;&gt; Ais TUHAN bekin tanda di Kaen, ko biar orang dapa tau kalo dong sonde bole bunu sang dia.<bt>But the LORD told him in response, &lt;&lt;It's not like that! Whoever kill you, I will punish him seven times heavier!&gt;&gt; So the LORD made a sign on Kaen, so that people would know, they were not allowed to kill him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lachen: therefore, indeed horeg (partcpl): killing|i(15)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">lachen: therefore, indeed horeg (partcpl): killing<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>shivʾatayim: sevenfold yuqqam (naqam): be avenged (stative passive)<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yasem (sym): put in a place, make be there ʾot: sign, like a mark of kapu<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>lbilti: non-existence, so that nobody would hakot-oto (nkh inf.): make him be hit, beat, kill<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ais Kaen jalan kasi tenga itu tampa, ko pi jao-jao dari TUHAN. Dia jalan sampe di satu tampa di kabón Eden pung sablá matahari nae. Itu tampa pung nama <span class="Italic">Nod</span>, yang pung arti bilang &lt;Tapaleuk&gt;. Ais ju dia tenga di situ.<bt>Then Kaen left behind that place, and went far from the LORD. He went until he came to a place on the eastern side of the garden of Eden. That place was named Nod, which means &lt;Wander-aimlessly&gt;. And then he stayed there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyetseʾ: go out, go forth nod:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayyetseʾ: go out, go forth nod: become aimless, homeless<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>qidmat-ʿeden: east of Eden</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kaen pung turunan dong<bt>Kaen's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais itu, Kaen kawin, ju dia pung bini dudu parú. Ju dia barana satu ana laki-laki, yang dong kasi nama, Henok. Deng Kaen kasi bangun satu kampong. Ais dia kasi nama itu kampong, Henok, iko dia pung ana pung nama.<bt>After that, Kaen married, and his wife became pregnant. Then she gave birth to a son, who they named Henok. And Kaen built a village [following CEV and TH]. Then he named the village, Henok, following the name of his child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatahar: get pregnant, conceive a baby"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vatahar: get pregnant, conceive a baby vateled (yld): bear a child<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>boneh: build ʿiyr: city = town with walls<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>vayyiqraʾ hashem: called its name, named it</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ais Henok pung ana, andia Irad. Irad pung ana, Mehuyael. Mehuyael pung ana, Metusael. Deng Metusael pung ana, Lamek.<bt>Then Henok had a child, Irad. Irad had a child, Mehuyael. Mehuyael had a child, Metusael. And Metusael had a child, Lamek.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwaled: be born to, either directly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiwwaled: be born to, either directly as father or skipping generations as ancestor</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00613c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Lamek pung bini dua. Satu nama Ada, deng satu nama Sila.<bt>Lamek had two wives. One was named Ada, and the other was named Sila.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqqach-lo (lqh): took for himself (as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayyiqqach-lo (lqh): took for himself (as wives), married nashim (ʾisshah): women<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ada pung ana, nama Yabal. Dia pung turunan dong, jadi gambala. Dong idop bapinda-pinda deng tenga di tenda.<bt>Ada had a child, named Yabal. His descendants were herders. They lived nomadically, and lived in tents (loan).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾohel: tent miqneh: livestock|i(20) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾohel: tent miqneh: livestock<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Dia pung adi, nama Yubal. Yubal pung turunan dong jadi tukang maen musik, pake suling deng alat musik kuti pake tali sanár.<bt>He had a younger-sibling, named Yubal. Yubal's descendants were musicians, using flutes and strummed musical instruments that used strings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tali sanár = fishline, music strings;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">tali sanár = fishline, music strings; kuti = strum</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tofes: handle, have to do with,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tofes: handle, have to do with, deal with kinor: lyre, a stringed instrument with a sounding-board or sound box<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʿugav: vertical flute</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00188c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Alat musik<bt>Musical instruments</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Lamek pung bini Sila barana sang Tubal Kaen. Dia pung turunan jadi tukang besi, ko dong bekin barang macam-macam dari besi deng tambaga. Tubal Kaen pung adi parampuan, nama Na'ama.<bt>Lamek's wife Sila gave birth to Tubal Kaen. His descendants were ironworkers, and they made all sorts of things from iron and bronze. Tubal Kaen's younger sister was named Na'ama.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lotesh: sharpening, working as a smith"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">lotesh: sharpening, working as a smith or metalworker choresh: craftsman, plower, engraver, cutter<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>nchoshet: copper, bronze (= copper + tin) barzel: iron<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Satu kali, Lamek angka-angka diri di muka dia pung bini dua-dua bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong dengar, é! Tadi ada satu nyong yang hantam sang beta, ma beta habok bekin mati sang dia.<bt>Once, Lamek was boasting (&lt;lifting himself up) in front of both his wives saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl listen, é! Earlier there was a young-man who attacked me, but I beat him to death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʾəzennah (ʾzn hif): lissen to someting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">haʾəzennah (ʾzn hif): lissen to someting ʾimrati: my word, opinion (poetic)<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>haragti: I killed someone, I would kill anyone who wounded me lfitsʿi: to my wounding; inflict bruises, crush<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>chabburati: my wounding, striping, even a boy who bruised me</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Orang yang bunu sang Kaen, dapa hukuman tuju kali. Ma kalo ada yang mau balas dendam sang beta, dong dapa hukuman 77 kali.&gt;&gt;<bt>A person who kill Kaen, gets a punishment seven times. But if anyone wants to take revenge on me, they will get a punishment 77 times [heavier].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shivʿatayim: sevenfold, seven times as much"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">shivʿatayim: sevenfold, seven times as much (Sounds like good old Middle East invective, like Saddam Hussein in the first gulf war, "mother of all battles.") yuqqam (nqm qal passive): be avenged, stative passive = v. 15<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>shivʿim vshivʿah: 77 times</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Adam pung ana laen, andia Set<bt>Adam's other child, that is, Set</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Adam pung bini Hawa barana satu ana laki-laki lai. Ju dong kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Set</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;sorong kasi&gt;), tagal Hawa bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su sorong kasi beta ini ana ko ganti sang Habel, yang Kaen su bunu bekin mati tu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Adam's wife Hawa gave birth to another son. So they named that child, Set, because Hawa said, &lt;&lt;Lord God has given me this child to replace Habel, who Kaen killed.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿod: again shet: Seth|i(25) (25) |rshat-li:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿod: again shet: Seth<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>shat-li: put for me, "give, establish" sounds like "Seth" in Hebrew zeraʿ: seed, offspring, descendants<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʾacher: another one in a series, following one, next tachat: instead of, for the sake of<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Lama-lama Set dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Enos.<bt>Eventually Set had a son, named Enos.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Itu waktu, orang dong mulai sémba sang TUHAN Allah.<bt>At that time, people began to *worship the LORD God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yullad: passive, was born to Seth"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yullad: passive, was born to Seth az: then<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>huchal (chll hof): was begun liqraʾ: invoke, appeal to for help<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>bshem: name, reputation, renown End of P section.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>“worship the name of the Lord”: HCE = “Dat was da time wen da peopo firs start fo aks Yahweh fo help um cuz dey know wat kine God him.” [JEG] We worked this out for the New Testament, and it works even better than "name" in many passages in the Old. The exceptions are things like "taking the Lord's name in vain", which is "use my name an ack like dat give you da right fo do wase time kine stuff", and places where Yahweh wants his people to know what his name is.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Adam pung turunan sampe Noh<bt>Adam's descendants until Noh</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1-2" />Waktu Allah bekin manusia, Dia bekin dong pung model, sama ke Dia pung diri sandiri. Dia bekin sang dong, laki-laki deng parampuan. Ais Dia pange sang dong &lt;&lt;manusia&gt;&gt;, deng Dia kasi berkat sang dong.<bt>When Allah made humans, He made their model the same as He himself. He made them male and female. And He called them &lt;&lt;human&gt;&gt;, and He gave blessings to them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Manusia partama pung nama, Adam. Ini ni, Adam pung turunan dong pung nama:<bt>The first human was named Adam. These here, are the names of Adam's descendants:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins new Seder. Sefer: writing, book;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">Begins new Seder. Sefer: writing, book; list, record<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>tolədot: life and times ʾadam: Adam the individual, but the same word means "mankind"<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>bəroʾ (inf): creation (used of God) bidmut (dmh ʾbe likeʾ, dmut ʾpattern, form, shapeʾ): as something like, a form or shape, an image<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>zakhar: male (opposite to female) nqevah: female<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayvarek otam: he bestowed power for success, prosperity, fertility. Also declared them endowed with power for success or prosperity or fertility. One person can express a wish that another will have the power for the same, and can declare that God is the origin of that power for success or prosperity or fertility in people hibarʾam (brʾ nif inf): the day of his creating them<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="3" />Waktu Adam su umur 130 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, dia pung model sama ke dia pung bapa. Ju dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Set.</span><bt>When Adam was already 130 year old, he had a son, whose model was like his father. And he named that child, Set.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dapa satu ana = have a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">dapa satu ana = have a child; ; angka satu ana = adopt</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoled (yld hif narrl): he caused"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yoled (yld hif narrl): he caused him to be born ktsalmo (tselem): as the spitting image of him<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ais itu, Adam masi idop lai 800 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Adam still lived another 800 years, and he had additional sons and daughters. [See June's alternate rendering.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="holiydo (yld hif): he caused him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">holiydo (yld hif): he caused him to be born</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 930 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 930 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="6" />Waktu Set umur 105 taon, ju dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Enos.<bt>When Set was 105 years old, he had a son, named Enos.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoled (yld hif narr): caused to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yoled (yld hif narr): caused to be born</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais Set masi idop lai 807 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>Then Set still lived another 807 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><v n="8" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 912 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 912 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="9" />Waktu Enos umur 90 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Kenan.<bt>When Enos was 90 years old, he had a son, named Kenan.</bt><v n="10" />Ais itu, Enos masi idop lai 815 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Enos still lived another 815 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><v n="11" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 905 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 905 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="12" />Waktu Kenan umur 70 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Mahalalel.<bt>When Kenan was 70 years old, he had a son, named Mahalalel.</bt><v n="13" />Ais itu, Kenan masi idop lai 840 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Kenan still lived another 840 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><v n="14" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 910 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 910 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="15" />Waktu Mahalalel umur 65 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Yared.<bt>When Mahalalel was 65 years old, he had a son, named Yared.</bt><v n="16" />Ais itu, Mahalalel masi idop lai 830 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Mahalalel still lived another 830 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><v n="17" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 895 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 895 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="18" />Waktu Yared umur 162 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Henok.<bt>When Yared was 162 years old, he had a son, named Henok.</bt><v n="19" />Ais itu, Yared masi idop lai 800 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Yared still lived another 800 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><v n="20" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 962 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 962 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="21" />Waktu Henok umur 65 taon, dia dapa ana laki-laki satu, nama Metusalak.<bt>When Henok was 65 years old, he had a son, named Metusalak.</bt><v n="22" />Ais itu, Henok idop satu hati deng Tuhan Allah sampe 300 taon lai. Ju dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Henok lived intimately (=one liver) with Lord God for another 300 years. And he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayithalek (hitp): he walked back and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayithalek (hitp): he walked back and forth, around, walk constantly</Message></Annotation><v n="23-24" />Dia idop satu hati tarús deng Tuhan Allah. Ais waktu dia pung umur 365 taon, ju dia ilang, tagal Tuhan Allah su angka nae sang dia.<bt>He continued to live intimately with Lord God. Then when he was 365 years old, he disappeared, because Lord God had taken him up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeynennu: there was no more of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾeynennu: there was no more of him End of P section.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25" />Waktu Metusalak pung umur 187 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Lamek.<bt>When Metusalak was 187 years old, he had a son, named Lamek.</bt><v n="26" />Ais itu, Metusalak masi idop lai 782 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Metusalak still lived another 782 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><v n="27" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 969 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 969 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="28" />Waktu Lamek umur 182 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki.<bt>When Lamek was 182 years old, he had a son.</bt><v n="29" />Lamek kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Noh</span> (yang mirip satu kata yang dia pung arti &lt;kasi hibur&gt;), tagal dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini ana nanti hibur bekin sanáng kotong pung hati dari kotong pung karjá satenga mati di ini tana yang Tuhan Allah su kutuk ame sang dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>Lamek named that son, Noh, because he said, &lt;&lt;This child will comfort bringing happiness to our hearts from our hard work on this ground which Lord God has cursed (it).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hibur ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">hibur =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ynakhmenu (nkhm piel): reassure, comfort mimaʿsenu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ynakhmenu (nkhm piel): reassure, comfort mimaʿsenu (maʿseh): what happens to someone, work activity<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʿitsvon: distress, hardship, pain ʾerərah (ʾrr piel): inflicted with a curse<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ais itu, Lamek masi idop lai 595 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Lamek still lived another 595 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><v n="31" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 777 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 777 years old.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Waktu Noh pung umur su 500 taon, ju dia dapa tiga ana laki-laki, andia Sem, Yafet deng Ham.<bt>When Noh was already 500 years old, he had three sons, that is, Sem, Yafet and Ham. [NOTE to daughter translations: check to make sure this is not seen as triplets. :)]</bt><note reference="5:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ham tu, ana bungsu. Lia <span class="Italic">Carita Mula-mula</span> 9:24-25.<bt>Ham was the youngest child. See Gen. 9:24-25.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Manusia pung jahat<bt>Human's evil</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Itu waktu, manusia su tamba banya. Ais dong su idop batasiram di mana-mana di ini dunya. Dong ju barana ame ana-ana parampuan.<bt>At that time, humans had already increased in number. And they were living scattered all over the place in the world. They also gave birth to daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barana ame = melahirkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">barana ame = melahirkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hechel (chll &quot;profane&quot; hif + l-"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hechel (chll "profane" hif + l- + inf): began, from "untie" meaning yullədu (yld passive): were born to them<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Tuhan pung ana laki-laki dong<bt>The Lord's sons</bt><note reference="6:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;Tuhan pung ana laki-laki dong&gt; tu, sonde jalás. Ada orang yang pintar saparu bilang dong tu, raja dong pung ana-ana. Ada saparu yang bilang dong tu, orang dari makluk yang bukan manusia. Ada saparu yang pikir dong tu, Tuhan pung ana bua dari sorga. Ma sonde ada yang tau batúl.<bt>That 'sons of God2' is not clear. There are some knowledgeable people who say that they are nobility. There are some who say they are creatures who are not human. There are some tho think they are angels. But there is nobody who knows with certainty.</bt></note>dapa lia manusia pung ana nona dong manis-manis. Ju dong pi kawin ame deng nona-nona yang dong suka.<bt>saw the the daughters of humans were pretty (&lt;sweet-sweet). So they went and married the young women that they liked.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ftn added from Dhao check Sept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Ftn added from Dhao check Sept 2004 ***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bney haʾelohim: literally &quot;sons of God&quot;,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">bney haʾelohim: literally "sons of God", possibly supernatural beings that people would think of as gods. Other suggestions: angels Job 1.6; 2.1; Psa 29.1; 89.6; Dan 3.25? descendants of Seth? heavenly beings? people from aristocratic families (used as a royal title in 2 Sam 7.14; 1 Chr 22.10; 28.6; Psa 2.7; 89.26-27)? Nearly all translations are agreed that the reference is to some kind of heavenly beings, and many versions call them “angels.” But it could mean "people so impressive you would call them godlike," following the widely used Hebrew idiom "son of X" meaning "person with the qualities of X." yiqchu (lqch narr): they took as wives<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bacharu: they pick</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ais ju TUHAN bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su cape deng manusia pung idop yang harba-biruk. Beta pung Roh yang kasi idop sang dong tu, su sonde mau kasi tenga dong idop tarús lai.<bt>Then the LORD said, &lt;&lt;I am tired of the chaotic lives of these humans. My Spirit which gave them life, already doesn't was to allow them to continue to live.</bt><note reference="6:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani di sini sonde talalu jalás.<bt>The meaning of the Hebrew language here is not clear.</bt></note>Dong musti mati. Jadi nanti dong cuma idop sampe 120 taon sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>They must die. [From TH re: 'mortal'] So (consequently) in the future they will only live to just 120 years.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ruchi: my spirit, the breath from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ruchi: my spirit, the breath from me, my life-giving spirit yadon (dyn? dwn ʾruleʾ?): judging? taking responsibility? staying with? Used only here. BDB As far as the small number of occurrences allows a test, the range of meanings is exactly the same [as shpT]: to govern, in the whole range of activities of government: legislative, executive, judicial or otherwise. UBS adds that "ʾabideʾ and ʾremainʾ have been used traditionally and seem to fit the context well." Holladay for DWN says "unexplained, context suggests ʾremain,ʾ see commentaries. DYN is "bring justice, redress a wrong, pass sentence", but its imperfect is yadiyn, not yadown. Not clear where "strive" comes from. NIV acknowledges two problems in the text.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>bshagam: neither ... nor basar: flesh<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Itu jaman, deng jaman ba'iko-ba'iko dong, su ada orang-orang raksasa di dunya.<bt>In that era, and in following eras, there were giant people in the world.</bt><note reference="6:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang &lt;orang Nefil dong&gt;. Ma dia pung maksud sonde jalás.<bt>The Hebrew language says 'people of Nefil'. But the meaning is not clear.</bt></note>Waktu Tuhan pung ana laki-laki dong kawin ame manusia pung ana parampuan dong, ju dong barana ame orang-orang hebat, andia, kapala-kapala paráng, yang takanál dalam carita dolu-dolu.<bt>When the Lord's sons married the daughters of humans, they gave birth to some noteworthy people, such as, war champions, who are known in the stories from long ago.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nfilim: miscarriage [nefel]? giants produced by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nfilim: miscarriage [nefel]? giants produced by miscarriages? physically powerful men? giants? freaks? consultant exchange: [MC] That sounds a bit far-fetched to me! ; [JEG] Holladay again: Exo 21:22 possibly ʾmiscarriageʾ. Here, ʾgiantsʾ produced by miscarriage or thrown out of heaven (Nephilim comes from NPL ʾfallʾ); gigantic early population of Palestine Num 13, of mythological origin Gen 6:4, see commentaries. UBS: The fact that the term nefilim was known and used in Mosesʾ time does not necessarily mean that these kinds of men survived the flood. It can mean that just the name and the concept survived. There is no doubt that Middle Eastern mythology knew about giants, and that belief in the existence of such men was common at the time of the writing of Genesis. There have been many guesses made to explain the history of the word Nephilim, but none has any real likelihood of being true. Those who understand the sons of God in verse 2 as human beings and not supernatural beings, reject any reference to the Nephilim as offspring of human and heavenly unions, and so the Nephilim are taken to be powerful and violent men who existed along with those men who carried the title of "sons of God.ʾʾ Martin Luther for instance interpreted the Nephilim not as giants but as tyrants who fell upon the people and treated them violently.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>gibboriym: strong, mighty ones meʿolam: from antiquity<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʾanshey hashem: men of renown, famous men, big names End of P section<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Itu waktu, TUHAN lia manusia di dunya pung jahat su talalu. Dong pung hati cuma tau pikir jahat tarús sa.<bt>At that time, the LORD saw that humans on the earth had evil that was already excessive. Their livers were just only able to think evil continually.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rabah: was getting to be more"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">rabah: was getting to be more and more raʿat: evil, harm to somebody, evil intent, perverseness, trouble, crime<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>yetser: thought, impulse, tendency machshəvot: thought, idea, intention, plan, design<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>raq only</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ju TUHAN manyasal su bekin ame sang dong ko tenga di ini dunya. Itu bekin Dia pung hati saki mau mati.<bt>So the LORD regretted that [He] had made them to live in the world. It made Him very sad.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yinachem (nchm): regretted, allowed himself to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yinachem (nchm): regretted, allowed himself to be sorry yitʿatstsev (ʿtsv hitp impf): felt outraged, grieved; grieved himself<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Andia ko Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Deng bagitu, nanti Beta bekin ancor manusia, yang Beta su bekin ame di ini dunya. Burung-burung deng binatang laen dong, ju Beta bekin ancor samua. Te Beta manyasal su bekin sang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;In that way, I will destroy human, who I have made in this world. The birds and other animals, I will also destroy all of them. Cuz (elaboration) I regret that I have made them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾemcheh: I will wipe out baraʾtiy:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾemcheh: I will wipe out baraʾtiy: I created<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>remes: creeping animals nichamti (nchm nif): I regret having made them<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ma cuma Noh sa, yang bekin sanáng TUHAN pung hati.<bt>But there was only just Noh, who pleased the LORD's liver.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chen: agreeableness, approval; find pleasure, satisfaction"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">chen: agreeableness, approval; find pleasure, satisfaction in someone else's eyes End of P section<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Noh pung carita<bt>Noh's story</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9-10" />Noh pung carita bagini: dia pung ana laki-laki ada tiga orang, andia Sem, Yafet deng Ham. Noh tu, idop lurus deng sonde bekin jahat. Itu waktu cuma dia sandiri sa yang bae. Dia idop deka deng Tuhan Allah.<bt>Noh's story is like this. He had three sons, that is Sem, Yafet and Ham. Noh lived straight (=righteous) and didn't do evil. At that time it was only he himself who was good. He live close to Lord God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="idop deka contrasts with idop jao"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">idop deka contrasts with idop jao dari Tuhan.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins new Seder. toldot: genealogy plus,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">Begins new Seder. toldot: genealogy plus, something like "the life and times of Noah"<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>tsadiq: something examined and found to be in order, right, innocent, guiltless, morally upright, righteous, godly tamim: whole, entire, intact, unobjectionable, blameless<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>dorotav: all his adult contemporaries, a time with its noteworthy events &amp; people hithhalek-noach: walk back and forth, walk around, walk constantly (with God) as in 5:22<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yoled (hif): he had three boys</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11-12" />Ma Tuhan Allah lia kalo samua orang laen dong jahat abis. Di mana-mana sa, orang pung jalan idop dong su rusak mau mati. Tuhan Allah lia manusia di dunya tu, cuma ada jahat sa.<bt>But Lord God saw that everyone else was thoroughly evil. Everywhere, people's way of life was really rotten. Lord God saw that of the humans in the world, there were only evil ones.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tishshachet (shcht nif): became corrupt, spoiled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tishshachet (shcht nif): became corrupt, spoiled timmaleʾ (mlʾ nif): was full, was filled<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>chamas: violence, wrong, violent treatment hinneh: with reference to that time<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>nishchatah ki hishchit (shcht nif, hif): it became corrupt, spoiled because its ways have become corrupt, because they made their ways corrupt End of Seder section.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ais Tuhan Allah kasi tau sang Noh bilang, &lt;&lt;Di mana-mana, Beta cuma dapa lia manusia pung jahat sa. Jadi Beta su putus bilang, Beta mau bekin ancor abis ini dunya deng dia pung isi samua.<bt>So Lord God told Noh saying, &lt;&lt;Everywhere I only see the evil of humans. So (consequently) I have decided that I will completely destroy this world and everything in it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qets: the end, limit hinəni: here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">qets: the end, limit hinəni: here I am (introduces an unexpected new development)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>khamas mipneyhem: violence in front of them (in mind constantly) mashchitam: their destroyer (same lexeme as in 11 and 12, but the play on words - poho - doesn't seem to work in Pidgin)<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Jadi bagini, Noh! Sakarang lu bekin ame satu kapal bésar dari kayu yang kuat. Di itu kapal pung dalam, lu bekin kamar-kamar. Ais lapis itu kapal deng ter.<bt>So this is what to do, Noh! Now you will make a large ship from strong wood. Inside that ship you will make rooms. And you will cover of the ship with tar. [EXEG: inside and out = explicit &gt; implicit; inside violates local logic]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lapis = add onto the outside,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">lapis = add onto the outside, dompul, ; ter = tar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tevat: chest, ark, box, ship gofer:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tevat: chest, ark, box, ship gofer: Nobody is sure what kind of wood this is, but its similarity to the Greek word for cypress suggests that it may be the evergreen cypress Cupresus sempervirens, or possibly the Cilician fir Abies cilicica. The Phoenicians used the cypress in building ships.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>qinim: compartments kafarta: spread pitch over it, cover it with pitch<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>bayit: inside chuts: outside<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>kofer (same stem as kafarta): pitch, bitumen that seeps out of the ground</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Itu kapal, lu bekin dia pung panjang 133 meter; dia pung lebar 22 meter; deng dia pung tinggi 13 meter.<bt>That ship, you will make its length 133 meters; its width 22 meters; and its height 13 meters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾammah: (ordinary) cubit: linear measure of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾammah: (ordinary) cubit: linear measure of 44.5 cm (17.5 inches; elbow to fingertips, 24 fingers, 6 palms, 2 spans); (royal) cubit: linear measure of 51.81 cm (7 palms); roughly 18 inches, 2 cubits = about 1 yard. 300 cubits long, 50 cubits wide, 30 cubits high. A fathom of rope is about 2 cubits, measured with the arms stretch out to both sides. ʾorekh: length<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>rachbah: its breadth qomatah: its height<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Pasang atap di itu kapal. Ma kasi farei itu atap kira-kira satenga meter dari atas dinding. Lu bagi itu kapal jadi tiga tingkat. Ais bekin satu pintu di itu kapal pung rebis.<bt>Put a roof on the ship. But leave free the roof about half a meter from the top of the wall. Divide the ship into three levels. Then make a door in the ship's side/rib.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="farei = open, free ; rebis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">farei = open, free ; rebis</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsohar: roof (only here) tkhalennah (piʿel):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tsohar: roof (only here) tkhalennah (piʿel): you are to finish<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>milmaʿlah: down from above petach: door<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tsiddah (tsad): its side tasim: you are to put<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tachtiyim shniyim ushlishim: underneath things (=decks) second and third</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Inga bae-bae! Beta nanti kasi turun banjer bésar ko bekin mati samua yang idop di ini dunya, sampe sonde ada sisa satu apa ju.<bt>Pay attention! I will send down a large flood to kill everything that lives on this world, to-point-that there is nothing left at all.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mebiʾ (bwʾ hif partcpl): bringing in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mebiʾ (bwʾ hif partcpl): bringing in mabul: heavenly ocean, deluge<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>lshachet (piʿel): to destroy ruach chayyim: spirit of life, breath of life<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yigwaʿ: die (unusual poetic word, used 12 times in Genesis for "perish")</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ma Beta mau ika Beta pung janji deng lu. Nanti lu maso pi dalam itu kapal sama-sama deng lu pung bini, lu pung ana-ana, deng lu pung ana mantu dong.<bt>But I want to bind My promise with you. You will enter into that ship together with your wife, your children, and your daughters-in-law.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haqimoti (qwm hif): I will set"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">haqimoti (qwm hif): I will set up, carry out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-20" />Dari samua binatang dong, lu musti pi ame satu-satu pasang, ko bawa maso pi dalam itu kapal, ko biar dong idop sama-sama deng lu. Sama ke binatang piara, burung-burung, deng binatang marayap dong, ko biar dong samua idop.<bt>From all the animals, you must go get a pair of each, to bring them into the ship, so they can live together with you. Like domestic animals, birds, and crawling animals, so they can all live.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taviyʾ (hif imperf): you are to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">taviyʾ (hif imperf): you are to bring lhachəyot (hif inf): to preserve alive<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ʾitakh: along with you zakhar: male<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nəqevah: female lmiynehu, lmiynah: in its kind, species<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>yavoʾu: they will come</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Lu musti bawa maso pi dalam itu kapal samua macam makanan kasi sang bosong, deng kasi itu binatang-binatang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>You must bring into the ship all types of food, for you-pl, and for the various sorts of animals.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʾəkhal: food yiʾakhel (ʾkl nif): that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">maʾəkhal: food yiʾakhel (ʾkl nif): that is eaten<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʾaSafta (ʾSp perf): gather, collect</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00625c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom">Noh mulai bekin kapal bésar<bt>Noh begins to make a big ship</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais ju Noh bekin iko sama deng Tuhan Allah pung parenta samua.<bt>Then Noh did according to everything that Lord God had commanded.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiwwah: order, direct, command, put in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tsiwwah: order, direct, command, put in charge of doing End of Seder section.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Banjer bésar<bt>Big flood</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, ju TUHAN omong deng Noh bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta lia pi mana-mana, ma cuma lu sa yang pung hati lurus. Tagal itu, lu deng lu pung bini-ana dong maso pi dalam kapal su.<bt>After that, the LORD spoke with Noh saying, &lt;&lt;I look everywhere, but only just you have a straight heart. Because of that, you and your wife-children should enter the ship now.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dor: generation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">dor: generation</Message></Annotation><v n="2-3" />Dari samua macam binatang yang bosong bole makan, deng yang bole bawa kasi sang Beta, na, lu bawa tuju-tuju pasang pi dalam itu kapal. Dari samua macam burung ju bawa tuju-tuju pasang. Ma dari binatang laen dong, bawa cuma satu-satu pasang sa. Deng bagitu, itu binatang deng burung dong jadi bibit, ko dong ada tarús.<bt>From all the kinds of animals which you-pl are allowed to eat, and which you are allowed to bring to Me, na, you are to bring seven pairs each into the ship. From every type of bird also bring seven pairs each. But from the other animals, just bring one pair each. In that way, those animals and birds, are seed (lexically implying for planting or stud), so they can continue to be.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Təhorah: approved for sacrifice, cultically clean,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">Təhorah: approved for sacrifice, cultically clean, ritually all right to eat zakhar: male<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>nəqevah: female lchayyot (chyh piʿel inf): to preserve alive (CHYH in the piʿel can have the meaning "bring back to life.")<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>zeraʿ: seed, offspring</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Inga bae-bae, ó! Te tuju hari lai, Beta kasi turun ujan tar pake barenti sampe ampa pulu siang ampa pulu malam. Deng bagitu, Beta kasi mati abis samua yang idop di darat yang Beta su bekin.&gt;&gt;<bt>Pay attention, ó! Cuz (elaboration) in seven more days, I will make descend continuous rain for 40 days 40 nights. In that way, I will kill off everything that lives on land, that I have made.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿod: still shivʿah: seven days from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿod: still shivʿah: seven days from now, in one week, seven days after today<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>mamtir (mtr hif): make torrential rain come down, enough to cause severe flooding ʾarbaʿim yom vʾarbaʿim laylah: forty days and forty nites, for forty days, nite and day<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>umachiti (mchh): I will wipe out, destroy yəqum: what subsists, what is living<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ais ju Noh bekin iko sama deng TUHAN pung parenta samua.<bt>So then Noh did following like all the LORD's comands.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiwwahu: he commanded him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tsiwwahu: he commanded him</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Waktu banjer datang tu, Noh pung umur 600 taon.<bt>When that flood came, Noh was 600 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mabul: heavenly ocean, deluge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mabul: heavenly ocean, deluge</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais Noh deng dia pung bini, deng dia pung ana-ana, deng dia pung ana mantu dong, maso pi dalam itu kapal, ko salamat dari itu banjer bésar.<bt>Noh and his wife, and his children, and his daughters-in-law, went into the ship, to be safe/saved from that big flood.</bt><v n="8-9" />Iko TUHAN pung parenta tu, ju Noh bawa maso pi dalam kapal samua macam burung deng binatang laen dong, satu-satu deng dia pung pasang, bae dari yang orang bole makan, deng dari yang orang sonde bole makan.<bt>Following the LORD's commands, Noh also brought into the ship all types of birds and other animals, each one with its pair/mate, both from the ones people are allowed to eat, and from those they aren't allowed to eat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeynennah: there was none"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾeynennah: there was none</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Abis tuju hari, ju banjer tapo'a datang ko mulai tutu ame ini dunya.<bt>After seven days, the flood dumped down to begin covering/closing this world.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00626c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Pas waktu Noh umur 600 taon, lewat dua bulan deng 17 hari, ju banjer pung datang! Itu waktu, tingka ke pintu langit tabuka, ko dia pung aer tapo'a turun. Deng samua mata aer di bawa tana dong tapica ko aer maspurak kaluar.<bt>Exactly when Noh was 600 years old, after 2 months and 17 days, the flood began to come! At that time, it was like the door of the sky was opened, so that its water dumped/spilled down. And all the spring under the ground broke so the water burst out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maspurak = burst up from undergound"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">maspurak = burst up from undergound like a broken water pipe, fountain, volcano; same root as Oe Pura</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nivqʿu (bqʿ nif): split open, burst"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nivqʿu (bqʿ nif): split open, burst open maʿəynot: springs of water, powerful sources of water<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tehom: primeval ocean, deepest parts of the sea, subterranean waters ʾərubot: windows<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>niftachu: they were opened</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ju ujan turun tar pake barenti siang-malam, sampe ampa pulu hari.<bt>And it rained without stopping day-and-night, for 40 days.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="geshem: torrential rain, as in v."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">geshem: torrential rain, as in v. 11</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ma itu hari ju, Noh, dia pung bini, dia pung ana tiga-tiga andia Sem, Yafet, deng Ham, deng dia pung ana mantu dong samua maso pi dalam kapal.<bt>But that day, Noh, his wife, his three sons, that is, Sem Yafet, and Ham, and his three daughters-in-law all went into the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿetsem: bone, body, self, the very"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿetsem: bone, body, self, the very same day</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Dong maso sama-sama deng binatang dong, andia binatang piara, binatang liar, binatang marayap, burung-burung, deng binatang laen yang ada sayap dong.<bt>They went in together with the animals, that is, the domestic animals, the wild animals, the crawling animals, the birds, and other animals that have wings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chayyah: animal, being miynah: its species|i(14)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">chayyah: animal, being miynah: its species<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>tsippor: bird (generic) kanaf: wing<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15-16" />Satu-satu pasang dari samua yang idop maso pi dalam kapal sama-sama deng Noh, sama ke Tuhan Allah pung parenta sang dia.<bt>A pair of everything that lived, entered into the ship together with Noh, just as Lord God's command to him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu dong samua su maso abis, ju TUHAN konci itu kapal pung pintu.<bt>When they had all finished entering, then the LORD closed/locked the door of the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəsher-bo ruach chayyim: which had the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾəsher-bo ruach chayyim: which had the breath of life in it yiSgor: shut<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>baʿədo: for him (for it)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-19" />Ujan bésar turun tarús sampe ampa pulu hari, ju banjer nae tamba tinggi sampe kapal ta'apung. Aer nae tarús sampe tutu ame gunung-gunung yang tinggi.<bt>The big rain came down constantly, for 40 days, and the flood kept getting higher until the ship floated. The water continued to rise until it covered the high mountains.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayirbu (rvh qal): became great vayisʾu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayirbu (rvh qal): became great vayisʾu (nsʾ): lifted, raised high. Is this what rising water does to boats?<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>vataram (rwm hif): raise, lift, pick up, lift up vayigbəru: swelled, rose, became strong<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yirbu (rbh): became much vatelek (hlk): went here and there, floated around, drifted<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yəkhussu (ksh pual): were covered with water gvohiym: high mountains<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Itu aer nae sonde pake barenti, sampe dia pung tinggi ada tuju meter di atas gunung.<bt>The water rose without stopping, until it was seven meters above the mountain.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʿəlah: above gavru: became strong|i(20) (20)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">maʿəlah: above gavru: became strong<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>yəkhussu: they were covered</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21-23" />Deng bagitu, samua yang idop di darat dong mati abis. Andia: manusia, binatang piara, binatang liar, binatang marayap, deng burung-burung dong. Cuma Noh deng samua yang ada dalam itu kapal yang salamat.<bt>In that way, everything that lived on land died off. That is: humans, domestic animals, wild animals, crawling animals, and the birds. Only Noh and everything/everyone which was in the ship was safe/saved.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayigvaʿ: breathed its last, died (poetic)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayigvaʿ: breathed its last, died (poetic) basherets: swarming things, tiny animals occurring in large numbers<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nishmat (cs nishmah): the blowing of the breath of life, breath; blast (of wind); breath; breath of life; breathing beings; breath (of God) bʾafayw: in its nostrils, nose<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>charavah: dry ground vayimach (mchh): (God) wiped out<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>yəqum: substance, being yimmachu (mchh nif): they were wiped out<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>vayishshaʾer (shʾr nif): was left over, remained ʾakh: only<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Itu aer sonde tau turun-turun sampe saratus lima pulu hari.<bt>The water didn't begin to go down for 150 days. [NOTE to daughter translations: can also say “for five months”; for Kupang, using 150 days emphasizes the momentous occasion and the accuracy of the narrator.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tana mulai karíng<bt>The land begins to dry out</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Ma Tuhan Allah sonde lupa sang Noh dong deng samua binatang di itu kapal. Ju Dia kasi angin ko fuu bekin turun itu aer banjer.<bt>But Lord God didn't forget Noh (collective) and all the animals in the ship. So he gave a wind to blow the flood waters to go down.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tevah: chest, ark, big boat (in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tevah: chest, ark, big boat (in this context) vayaʿaver (ʿvr hif): made a wind sweep across, cause to pass<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayashoku (shkk): they went down, abated, drained off</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Dia tutu samua mata aer di bumi, deng kasi barenti ujan dari langit.<bt>He closed all the springs in the earth, and made the rain in the sky to stop.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiSSakru (skr nif): the cosmic springs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayiSSakru (skr nif): the cosmic springs were stopped up. In Kealakekua and Kalapana, Hawaii, and Lahaina, Maui, there are fresh water springs that come out under the ocean; Starlight remembers the ones in Kalapana. maʿəynot: springs of water<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>təhom: primeval ocean, deep ʾarubot: windows<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vayikkaleʾ (klʾ nif): were kept back (of water) The opposite of 7:11<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ju aer kurang tarús. Abis 150 hari, ju aer sonde bagitu tinggi lai.<bt>And the waters diminished continually. After 150 days, the water wasn't so high anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aer tinggi = high"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">aer tinggi = high</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayashuvu (shwv): go back where they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayashuvu (shwv): go back where they came from halokh (inf): walk<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vayachSru: diminished, became less miqtseh: from the edge, from one end, the far edge; at the end of 150 days<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Pas deng bulan tuju lewat 17 hari, ju itu kapal tadudu di atas satu gunung yang tinggi, nama Ararat.<bt>Exactly in the seventh month and 17 days, the ship sat on a high mountain, which was named Ararat. [DISCOURSE: in the lgs of eastern Indonesia (probably all of, since it's also common in Indonesian and classical Malay), for momentous events of historical significance, this more formal way is how they signal that and historical precision. More informal NLT rendering doesn't convey that.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatanach (nwch): settled gently into position."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vatanach (nwch): settled gently into position. Like happens with a small boat when the tide goes out and the boat is left resting on the reef or the bottom, stuck but not damaged, or like locusts floating down on land chodesh: lunar month<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʿal: down onto</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Aer turun tarús sampe hari partama bulan sapulu, ju gunung-gunung pung ujung dong mulai kantara.<bt>The water descended continually until the first day of the tenth month, and the peaks of the mountains began to appear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chaSor (inf): go down, diminish ʿad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">chaSor (inf): go down, diminish ʿad: clear up to, until, indicates the distance from<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>raʾshey: heads of</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00631c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Noh kasi lapás burung pompa<bt>Noh releases a dove</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Lewat ampa pulu hari, ju Noh buka kapal pung jandela satu.<bt>After 40 days, Noh open a window on the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiftach: he opened chalon: hole in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiftach: he opened chalon: hole in the wall for air and light, window opening. It was probably covered with a wooden cover to keep the rain out, not with glass like a modern window.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais dia kasi lapás satu burung gagak. Itu burung tarbáng tarús pi-datang sampe aer banjer su turun batúl. Dia sonde kambali lai pi kapal.<bt>Then he released a crow/raven. The bird kept flying back-and-forth until the flood waters had really gone down. It didn't return to the ship again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayshalakh (shlkh piel): he stretched out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayshalakh (shlkh piel): he stretched out his hand and let it go free. He probably held the bird outside the door, then gave him a little push to make him fly away. ʿorev: raven, genus Corvus. Looks like the ʿalala, but eats dead meat<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayetseʾ yatsoʾ: went out, went away shov: came back. The idea of a raven flying around (Holladay) and not coming back for more than seven days, and maybe for a lot longer time, then finally coming back is traditional, but it depends upon the notion that the raven found dead animals still floating on the water to eat ten months or more after the flood started is questionable because of decomposition. But having a raven fly in and out at will without bringing back any useful evidence of what was going on outside is perfectly plausible.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʿad-ybosheth (ybsh inf): up to the time of the water drying up</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ju Noh kasi lapás lai satu burung pompa, ko mau cari tau itu aer su turun batúl, ko balóm.<bt>Then Noh released a dove, to see if the water had really gone down or not yet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yonah: dove. Doves donʾt eat dead"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yonah: dove. Doves donʾt eat dead meat as ravens do, so it needed to find freshly grown plants haqalu (qll): if the waters were lighter, if the waters were growing less<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ma tagal aer masi tutu dunya samua, andia ko itu burung sonde dapa tampa hinggap. Ju dia kambali pi kapal. Noh sorong dia pung tangan, ko tarima ame itu burung maso dalam kapal.<bt>But because the water still covered the whole earth, that is why the bird didn't find a place to alight. So it returned to the ship. Noh stretched out his hand and received the bird into the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manoach: resting place lkaf-raglah: for the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">manoach: resting place lkaf-raglah: for the sole of the foot<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>tashav ʾelayw (masc): she (Hebrew gender) returned to him (Noah, masc) to the boat (fem) yiqqacheha (lqch): took it<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Noh tunggu tuju hari lai, ju dia kasi lapás ulang lai itu burung.<bt>Noh waited seven more days, and he released that bird once again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayakhel: waited ʾəcheriym: other|i(10) (10) |rvayosef:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayakhel: waited ʾəcheriym: other<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>vayosef: he additionally ..., he went on to ...</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Dia pung sore, itu burung datang kambali sang Noh, deng dia ada bawa daon saitun satu yang dia baru pata ame. Ais ju Noh dapa tau kalo aer su turun batúl.<bt>In the afternoon, the bird came back to Noh, and it brought a saitun (loan) leaf that it had just broken off. Then Noh knew that the water had really gone down.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿəleh-zayit: foliage, leaves of an olive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿəleh-zayit: foliage, leaves of an olive tree taraf: freshly plucked<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>bfiyah: in its beak, mouth qallu: the waters were light, not much (= v. 8)<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Dia tunggu tuju hari lai, ju dia kasi lapás ulang itu burung pompa. Ma ini kali, itu burung su sonde kambali lai.<bt>He waited seven more days, and then he released the dove again. But this time, the bird didn't return again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="one nodda week? one week moa?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">one nodda week? one week moa? yiyyachel (ychl nif): he waited?<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yaSfah (ySp): continue, repeat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Waktu Noh pung umur 601 taon, kaná hari partama bulan satu, aer su turun batúl-batúl. Ju Noh buka itu kapal pung jandela, ais dia lia kuliling, te tana dong su karíng.<bt>When Noh was 601 years old, on the first day of the first month, the water had truly gone down. So Noh opened the window of the ship, and he looked around, and the ground was [beginning to] dry. [EXEG: Problem: the Heb here is neither the normal word for “window” nor the normal word for “roof”. And the word for “removed” is also not what is done to either a window or a roof. Note CEV says “made an opening in the roof of the boat” and adds a note “One possible meaning for the difficult Hebrew text.” Both TH and TN discuss some of the issues. Possible BT noise for consultant and daughter translations as KM “window” can also serve for hatch, opening, etc. as (according to TN) in NJB, NEB, REB, NLT. The KM solution results in an opening from which he can look out. My intuitions are that “remove roof's covering” would be both forced and non-sensical in the worldview and the languages here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="riʾshon: first kharvu: drain off (the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">riʾshon: first kharvu: drain off (the water), dry up (the land) - redundant<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yaSar (Swr): turn aside. Stepped out of his usual routine? mikhSeh: covering, like the covering of a tent - sort of like a tarpaulin<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Sampe bulan dua, hari 27, te tana su karíng batúl-batúl.<bt>To-point-that on the second month, the 27th day, the ground was really dry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais ju Tuhan Allah omong deng Noh bilang,<bt>Then Lord God spoke with Noh saying,</bt><v n="16" />&lt;&lt;Noh! Sakarang bosong samua turun suda dari ini kapal.<bt>Noh! Now all of you should disembark from this ship.</bt><v n="17" />Kasi kaluar itu binatang dong samua! Andia: binatang piara, binatang liar, binatang marayap, deng burung-burung dong. Kasi tenga ko dong samua tamba banya, deng bekin ponu ini dunya.&gt;&gt;<bt>Let all the animals out! That is: the domestic animals, the wild animals, the crawling animals, and the birds. Let them all increase in number, and fill this world.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="basar: flesh, species? remes: the creeping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">basar: flesh, species? remes: the creeping mass<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>hwtsʾ (ytsʾ hif imperv): make them go out vshartsu: let them swarm, teem, be innumerable<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>faru (prh): let them be fruitful</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18-19" />Ais ju Noh deng dia pung bini, dia pung ana-ana, deng dia pung ana mantu dong samua kaluar dari itu kapal. Itu binatang dong samua ju kaluar, satu-satu deng dia pung golongan.<bt>So then, Noh and his wife, his children, and his daughters-in-law all left the ship. All those animals also went out, each one with its category.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="golongan ; gerombolan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">golongan ; gerombolan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lmishpəchotehem: in all their extended families"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">lmishpəchotehem: in all their extended families (species)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Noh kasi korban sukur sang Tuhan<bt>Noh give a thank offering to the Lord</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\Hk00252c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Dong susun batu bekin meja korban<bt>They arrange stones to make an *offering table</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ais Noh susun batu ko bekin meja korban kasi sang TUHAN. Dari binatang-binatang yang bole pake jadi binatang korban, Noh ame satu-satu ekor. Ais dia horo ko bakar sang dong di atas itu meja korban, ko jadi tanda sukur sang TUHAN.<bt>Then Noh piled-arranged stones to make an *offering table to the LORD. From the animals which are permitted to use for animal sacrifice, Noh took one each, and cut them to burn them on the offering table, as a sign of thanks to the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mizbeakh: altar for God Təhorah: acceptable,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mizbeakh: altar for God Təhorah: acceptable, ritually "clean"<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>vayaʿal (ylh hif): he took the animals up ʿolot: offerings completely burned on an altar<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Waktu TUHAN dapa ciom itu korban pung baboo wangi, ju Dia pung hati sanáng. Ju Dia pikir bilang,<bt>When the LORD smelled the fragrant smell of the sacrifice, He was pleased. And He thought saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">&lt;&lt;Mulai sakarang, Beta sonde akan kutuk lai ini dunya tagal manusia pung jahat. Biar dong cuma tau pikir jahat dari kici sa, ma Beta sonde akan kasi ancor abis lai samua yang idop, sama ke yang Beta su bekin tu.<bt>&lt;&lt;Beginning now, I will not curse again this world because of the evil of humans. Even though they can only think evil from the time they are small, but I will not again destroy everything that lives, in the way that I have done.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarach (rwch hif): enjoy the smell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yarach (rwch hif): enjoy the smell of something; metaphor for looking favorably on the sacrifice reach: odor, scent<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nichoach: soothing ʾoSif (ySp hif): I will not continue<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>lqallel (piel): declare something cursed ʾadamah: ground, soil<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>baʿavur: on account of yetser: thought<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nəʿurayw: his youth (stage of life) lhakot (nkh): strike, batter, destroy<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Salama ini dunya masi ada, ini musim dong samua jalan tarús, iko dia pung atoran. Andia: musim tanam deng musim koru, musim dingin deng musim panas, musim karíng deng musim ujan, siang deng malam.&gt;&gt;<bt>As long as this world still exists, the seasons will continue on, according to their pattern/regulation. Such as: planting season and harvest season, cold season and hot season, dry season and rainy season, day and night.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zeraʿ: seed, offspring qatsiyr: yield of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">zeraʿ: seed, offspring qatsiyr: yield of the harvest<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>qor: cold chom: heat<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>qayits: summer, summer fruit choref: autumn, winter<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yishbotu: they will [not] cease</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah ba'ika janji deng Noh<bt>Lord God mutually binds a promise with Noh</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Tuhan Allah kasi berkat sang Noh deng dia pung ana-ana dong, deng omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong barana bam-banya, ko bekin ponu ini dunya lai.<bt>Lord God gave blessing to Noh and his children, and spoke saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl should have lots of children, to fill this world up again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəbarek (piel): bestow power for success,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yəbarek (piel): bestow power for success, prosperity, fertility. God did it for people, animals, a field, the seventh day. Also God or another person declares somebody to be endowed with power of that kind, or wishes them success. A person can declare God to be the source of power for success, prosperity, or fertility; a form of praise pəru (prh command): bear fruit, be fruitful (and multiply)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>umilʾu: and fill up something (ergative-absolute?)</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Nanti samua binatang liar, burung deng ikan dong taku sang bosong. Bosong yang musti ator sang dong.<bt>Later all the wild animals, birds and fish will fear you. You-pl must manage them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moraʾkhem: the fear of you chitkhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">moraʾkhem: the fear of you chitkhem: the terror of you<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>byedkem: in your hand nitanu bayad (nif): they are given into your power, turned over to you<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Bosong bole makan itu binatang samua pung daging, sama ke bosong ju bole makan tanaman dong pung hasil. Samua ni, Beta kasi sang bosong.<bt>You may eat the meat from all animals, just like you may eat the produce of all plants. All this, I give to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="remesh: all the animals, except large"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">remesh: all the animals, except large animals and birds yerek: greens, vegetables, green plants<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʿesev: non-perennial plants that grow during the rainy season, including weeds, grass, vegetables, and cereals</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Cuma bosong sonde bole makan daging yang masi ada pung dara, tagal binatang pung nyawa ada di dia pung dara.<bt>Only you may not eat meat that still has its blood, because the animal's life-soul (nyawa) is in its blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akh: particle of assurance or emphasis,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">akh: particle of assurance or emphasis, restrictive</Message></Annotation><v n="5-6" />Beta bekin manusia iko Beta pung model. Tagal itu, sonde bole bunu manusia. Kalo ada orang ko binatang, yang bunu bekin mati manusia, musti bunu bekin mati sang dong ju. Ini hukum datang dari Beta.<bt>I made humans following my model. Because of that, it is not allowed to kill humans. If a person, or an animal kills dead a human, they must also be killed dead. This law/punishment comes from Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾedrosh, ʾedrəshenu (with et-): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾedrosh, ʾedrəshenu (with et-): I will demand someone's blood (of them), call them to account, inquire about the matter miyad ʾish ʾakhiw: from the hand (responsibility) of a man, his brother<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>shofek (shfk): shed blood, pour out a liquid, spill tselem: model, image, drawing, statue<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Bosong musti barana bam-banya, ko bekin ponu ulang lai ini dunya.&gt;&gt;<bt>You-pl must have lots of children, to refill this world again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shirtsu: swarm, be innumerable End of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">shirtsu: swarm, be innumerable End of S section<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Tuhan Allah sambung lai Dia pung omong bilang,<bt>Lord God continued speaking saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾitto: &lt;object&gt; 3s, sounds awkward in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾitto: &lt;object&gt; 3s, sounds awkward in Pidgin</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />&lt;&lt;Sakarang Beta mau ika Beta pung janji deng bosong, sampe deng bosong pung turunan ju.<bt>&lt;&lt;Now I want to bind my promise with you-pl, and also with your descendants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meqim (qwm hif participle): setting up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">meqim (qwm hif participle): setting up, carrying out, performing, keeping one's word, establishing zarʿəkhem: your seed = your descendants<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ini janji ju kaná deng samua yang idop, andia binatang piara, binatang liar, deng burung-burung. Pokonya, samua yang kaluar sama-sama deng bosong dari itu kapal.<bt>This promise also affects everything that lives, such as domestic animals, wild animals, and birds. The important this is, everything that came out of the ship with you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotsʾey (ytsʾ partcpl pl): the ones"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yotsʾey (ytsʾ partcpl pl): the ones coming out</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Beta pung janji tu, bagini: Beta sonde akan kirim banjer bésar lai, ko bekin mati samua yang idop, deng bekin ancor abis ini dunya.<bt>My promise is like this: I will never again send a big flood, to kill everything that lives, and to thoroughly destroy this world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həqimoti (qwm hif): I am setting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">həqimoti (qwm hif): I am setting up vloʾ-yikkaret (krt nif imperfect): will not be eliminated, rooted out, extinguished, cut off<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mimmey: from the waters of mabul: flood<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>lshachet (piel): wipe out, ruin, spoil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-13" />Beta taro Beta pung palangi di langit ko jadi tanda yang kasi inga Beta pung janji yang sonde putus-putus deng bosong, deng samua yang idop, deng ini dunya.<bt>I put my rainbow in the sky as a sign to cause remembrance of My promise which is never broken with you-pl, and with everything that lives, and with this world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾot: sign, distinguishing mark, sign to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾot: sign, distinguishing mark, sign to bring to mind a covenant obligation beni ubenekhem: between me and you<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ldorot: for generation after generation qashti: my bow (for shooting), metaphor for a rainbow<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʿanan: mass of clouds</Message></Annotation><v n="14-17" />Kalo ada awan di langit, ais palangi kaluar, nanti dia kasi inga sang Beta itu janji bilang: nanti banjer bésar sonde akan bekin ancor abis lai samua yang idop. Deng bagitu, Beta pung janji yang sonde tau abis tu, su ta'ika deng bosong, deng samua yang idop.&gt;&gt;<bt>If there is a cloud in the sky, and then a rainbow appears, it will remind Me of that promise, that: a big flood will never again thoroughly destroy everything that lives. In that way, My promise which is never ending, applies to you-pl, and everything that lives.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿanəni (piel inf): cause something to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿanəni (piel inf): cause something to make an appearance nirʾətah (nif): be seen, appear<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vzakharti: I will remember, I will be thinking about End of P section.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Noh mabo<bt>Noh gets drunk</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Noh pung ana-ana yang kaluar dari itu kapal, andia Sem, Yafet deng Ham. (Ham tu, Kana'an pung papa).<bt>Noh's children that came out of the ship were Sem, Yafet and Ham. (That Ham, was Kanaan's father).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hayotsʾim (partcpl): the ones who came"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hayotsʾim (partcpl): the ones who came out vayihyu: there were, starts a new section of the story<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Samua orang di dunya pung turunan datang dari Noh pung tiga ana dong.<bt>Everyone on earth is descended coming from Noh's three sons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naftsah: scattered, spread out, were dispersed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">naftsah: scattered, spread out, were dispersed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\Hk00112c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Pohon anggor<bt>Grape vine</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Noh tu, orang tani. Dia yang partama kali bekin kabón anggor.<bt>Noh was a farmer. He was the first person to make a grape field.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachel (chll hif): let something be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yachel (chll hif): let something be profaned. From the meaning "untie" associated with this, comes the idea of "begin" vayiTTaʿ (nTʿ): plant (a garden, a vineyard, a tree, desolation)<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>karem: vineyard</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Satu kali, dia minum anggor sampe mabok barát. Ju dia buka buang dia pung pakean, abis tidor laloli talanjang bulat di dalam dia pung tenda.<bt>One time, he drank wine to-point-that he was heavy drunk. Then he took off his clothes, and then slept sprawled unconscious stark naked inside his tent.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mabok barát = mabok sonde jadi-jadi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">mabok barát = mabok sonde jadi-jadi = mabok son jadi doi (tidak ada harga diri lai); tidor laloli = tidor talepo = sprawled out unconscious</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayishkar: he got drunk vayitgal (glh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayishkar: he got drunk vayitgal (glh hitp): exposed himself<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>btok: in the middle of ʾahəlah: the tent place<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Waktu Ham dapa lia dia pung bapa pung talanjang tu, ju dia lari kaluar, ko pi kasi tau dia pung kaka Sem deng Yafet.<bt>When Ham saw his father's nakedness, he ran outside to go tell his older-brothers Sem and Yafet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿerwat: genital area of either sex,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿerwat: genital area of either sex, nakedness. This reflects Middle East cultural values, but seems strange in Hawaii (UNS). It doesn't block understanding, as people in Hawaii are highly aware that not everybody holds to the same cultural values. vayaged (ngd hif): put something up conspicuously in front of someone, tell, inform, denounce. Not just giving them information, but disrespectfully tattling on his own father.<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>bachuts: on the outside</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ais dong dua ame satu salimut, ju dong buka kasi tagantong di dong pung bahu. Ais itu, dong jalan mondor maso pi dalam itu tenda, ko tutu ame dong pung bapa. Deng bagitu, dong sonde lia dong pung bapa pung talanjang tu. Ais dong kaluar.<bt>So the two of them took a blanket, and they opened it so it hung from their shoulders. Then, they walked backwards into the tent, to cover their father. In that way they didn't see their father's nakedness. Then they went out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jalan mondor (people) = antrék (Belanda)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">jalan mondor (people) = antrék (Belanda) for cars</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="simlah: mantle, wrapper (both garment and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">simlah: mantle, wrapper (both garment and under-blanket) shkem: both shoulders, the neck and upper part of the back<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>shneyhem: the two of them ʾachoranit: (walk) backwards<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>yəkaSSu (kSh) (piʿel): cover with something, with accusative for what was covered but the covering unexpressed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Waktu Noh pung mabok mulai ilang, ju dia dapa tau dia pung ana bungsu pung bekin.<bt>When Noh's drunk began to disappear, he found out what his youngest son had done.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="falai = high, drunk (drink or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">falai = high, drunk (drink or drugs)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiyqets: wake up (intransitive) from sleep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiyqets: wake up (intransitive) from sleep or from being drunk qatan: younger or youngest? Ham is always mentioned second, but most English translations translate "qatan" as ʾyoungestʾ anyway.<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ais dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Heh! Kana'an pung bapa! Beta kutuk sang lu! Lu nanti jadi lu pung kaka dong pung budak!<bt>So he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;He! Kanaan's father! I curse you! You will become the slave of your older-brothers! [EXEG: The consensus from the context is that Ham's actions have offended Noah. Why the curse then brings Canaan's name in, is still a matter of debate. Some views include: 1) teknonym: “Kanaan's father”; 2) metonymy: Kanaan is the flag that refers to that branch of the family; 3) eponymous: referring symbolically to the Canaanite people at the time of the Exodus that the Jews are supposed to exterminate and justifying their going after those people rather than others; 4) social distancing: refuse to use the person's name directly to emphasise the degree of displeasure, 5) etc. Numbers 1, 2, and 4 are extremely common in the societies of NTT and Maluku. And we have gotten 1 &amp; 4 back as UNS explanations. Some of the solutions taken by translations such as NLT (from #3, which is going way outside the text) unravel in things like clashing with the grammar in the following clauses (singular/plural, etc.). Ours is no worse, and may be better than some of the other solutions. If nothing else, the current rendering is a solution the readers can make sense of, which they couldn't without “father”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqets: qatan: small, youngest|i(25) (25) |rʿeved"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiqets: qatan: small, youngest<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʿeved ʿəvadim: a slave of slaves, forced to do work that even ordinary slaves would not do. ʾachiyw: his (Canaan's) brothers; it probably means all of Noah's descendants, but it is phrased in such a way that it could be taken as cousins, the children of Shem and Japheth, plus possibly Ham's other children. But "ach" evidently can refer to uncles too. What the commentaries don't make clear is why the curse is directed to Canaan (unless it is simply eponymous, referring symbolically to the Canaanite people at the time of the Exodus that the Jews are supposed to exterminate and justifying their going after those people rather than others), not on Ham.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="26" />Puji TUHAN! Biar ko Dia kasi berkat sang Sem!<bt>Praise the LORD! May He give blessing to Sem! [NOTE to daughter translations: If this feels like it's left hanging, consider adding “because of what he has done.” to tie it into the context.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baruk (qal cs): filled with power,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">baruk (qal cs): filled with power, God be praised</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Puji TUHAN, tagal Sem!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Puji TUHAN, tagal Sem!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ma biar ko Kana'an jadi Sem pung jongos.<bt>But just let Kanaan become Sem's low-servant.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="27" />Biar Tuhan Allah bekin tamba luas Yafet pung tana;<bt>Let Lord God increase the size of Yafet's land;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng dia pung turunan idop dame deng Sem pung turunan.<bt>And his descendants live in peace with Sem's descendants.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Ma biar Kana'an jadi Yafet pung kuli.&gt;&gt;<bt>But let Kanaan be Yafet's labourer.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="idop dame = live in peaceful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">idop dame = live in peaceful coexistence; idop badame = implies were formerly bamusu, and now badame.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaft (yph hif impf): provide ample"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yaft (yph hif impf): provide ample space (sounds like Jafet's name), may he make spacious vyishkon: and may he settle down to live<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>bʾahaley-shem: in the tents of Shem lo: it isn't clear grammatically from the Hebrew whether the Canaan line is to be slaves to the Jafet line or the Shem line. The line is word for word the same as the last line of 26, but that doesn't mean it has the same referent for its pronoun.<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Mulai dari itu banjer abis, Noh masi idop lai 350 taon.<bt>Beginning from the end of the flood, Noh still lived another 350 years.</bt><v n="29" />Dia mati waktu dia pung umur su 950 taon.<bt>He died when he was already 950 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Noh deng Yafet pung turunan<bt>Noh and Yafet's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Abis banjer, ju Noh pung ana-ana dong dapa turunan. Andia turunan dari Sem, Yafet deng Ham.<bt>After the flood, Noh's children also had descendants. That is, descendants from Sem, Yafet and Ham.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwaldu (yld nif): were born"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiwwaldu (yld nif): were born</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="2-5" />Yafet pung turunan, andia, Gomer, Magog, Madai, Yawan, Tubal, Mesek deng Tiras. Satu-satu deng dong pung bahasa, dong pung suku, deng dong pung tana sandiri.<bt>Yafet's descendants were, Gomer, Magog, Madai, Yawan, Tubal, Mesek and Tiras. Each with their own language, their own tribe/clan, and their own land.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Gomer pung turunan, andia, Askenas, Rifat deng Togarma.<bt>Gomer's descendants, were, Askenas, Rifat and Togarma.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Yawan pung turunan, andia, Elisa, Tarsis, orang-orang Kitim, deng Dodanim<bt>Yawan's descendants were, Elisa, Tarsis, the people of Kitim, and Dodanim who live at the edge of the shore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kittiym: Cyprus dodaniym: Rhodes|i(2) (2) |rmeʾelleh:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">kittiym: Cyprus dodaniym: Rhodes<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>meʾelleh: from these? some of these? nifrədu (frd nif): branch off<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʾiyey: islands of, coastlands of; coast, island, shore, region ʾartsotam: their lands<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>lilshono: according to their own language lmishpachotam: according to their own ethnic and national subdivisions, felt blood relationships. BDB: a subdivision of a larger group such as a tribe or nation. Thus in Num 11:10 Moses hears the people weeping "by families." In Josh 7:16-18, in which the search is carried out to find the man guilty of causing God's displeasure on Israel, first the tribe of Judah is isolated, then the "family" (mishpa4h[a=) of the Zerahites, then the next smaller unit, the "household" (be=t) of Zabdi. Do Pidgin speakers make all these distinctions? Holladay: plural, races, subdivisions of ethnic and national groups.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bəgowyehem: by their peoples - their own presumed ethnicity? It seems to be talking social groupings here, not genetics.</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ada tulisan tua saparu bilang &lt;Rodanim&gt;.<bt>Several old writings say 'Rodanim'.</bt></note>yang tenga di pinggir-pinggir pante.</p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ham pung turunan<bt>Ham's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ham pung turunan, andia, Kus, Misraim, Put, deng Kana'an.<bt>Ham's descendants were, Kus, Misraim, Put, and Kanaan.</bt><note reference="10:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kus tu, andia &lt;Etiopia&gt;. Misraim, andia &lt;Masir&gt;.<bt>That Kus, that is 'Etiopia'. Misraim is 'Mesir' [Egypt].</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="7" />Kus pung turunan, andia, Seba, Hawila, Sabta, Raema deng Sabteka.<bt>Kus's descendants were, Seba, Hawila, Sabta, Raema and Sabteka.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Raema pung turunan, andia, Syeba deng Dedan.<bt>Raema's descendants were, Syeba and Dedan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Kus pung ana laki-laki sang Nimrod. Dia tu, panglima paráng partama yang hebat.<bt>Kus had a son, Nimrod. It is he who was the first noteworthy war commander.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hekhel (khll hif): he began gibor:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hekhel (khll hif): he began gibor: manly, vigorous, heroic; macho man, also a pushy despot<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Dia pung hebat datang dari TUHAN, sampe dia ju jadi tukang buru binatang yang paling jago. Andia ko orang biasa omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar ko lu jadi tukang buru binatang yang jago sama ke Nimrod, yang dapa dia pung hebat dari TUHAN.&gt;&gt;<bt>His exceptional-qualities came from the LORD, to-point-that he also was a champion hunter. That is why people often spoke saying, &lt;&lt;May you become a champion hunter like Nimrod, who got his exceptional-qualities from the LORD.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsayid: hunting, game killed while hunting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tsayid: hunting, game killed while hunting yeʾamar (nif): be talked about as, be called<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Mula-mula dia pung da'era mulai dari Babel, Erek Akad, deng Kalne. Dong samua ada di Sinear.<bt>In the beginning his region began from Babel, Erek Akad, and Kalne, all of them in Sinear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reʾshit: beginning, first, best, main sources"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">reʾshit: beginning, first, best, main sources of power mamlakhto: his rulership<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="10:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sinear tu, Babel pung nama laen. Sakarang, itu tampa tu, ada di Iran deng Irak.<bt>That Sinear, is another name for Babel. These days, it is in the land of Iraq and Iran.</bt></note><v n="11" />Dari situ, dia kuasa tamba Asyur. Ais ju dia kasi bangun kota Niniwe, Rehobot-Ir, Kala,<bt>From there, he over-powered (gained/extended authority over Asyur. Then he built the cities of Niniwe, Rehobot-Ir, Kala,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatsaʾ: went out. It implies that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yatsaʾ: went out. It implies that he took over Assyria</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />deng Resen, yang ada di Niniwe deng Kala pung teng-tenga. Samua tu, kota-kota bésar.<bt>and Resen which is in between Niniwe and Kala. All of those were large cities.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="13" />Misraim pung turunan, andia, orang-orang Ludim, Anamim, Lehabim, Naftuhim,<bt>Misraim's descendants were, the people of Ludim, Anamim, Lehabim, Naftuhim,</bt><v n="14" />Patrusim, Kasluhim, deng Kaftorim. Orang Kasluhim tu, andia orang Filistin dong pung nene-moyang.<bt>Patrusim, Kasluhim, and Kaftorim. The people of Kasluhim, were the filistin people's ancestors.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="15" />Kana'an pung ana sulung, andia, Sidon. Kana'an ju jadi nene-moyang dari orang-orang Het,<bt>Kanaan's oldest child was, Sidon. Kanaan was also the ancestor of the people of Het,</bt><v n="16" />Yebusi, Amori, Girgasi,<bt>Yebusi, Amori, Girgasi,</bt><v n="17" />Hiwi, Arki, Sini,<bt>Hiwi, Arki, Sini,</bt><v n="18" />Arwadi, Semari, deng Hamati.<bt>Arwadi, Semari, and Hamati.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Kana'an pung turunan dong tasiram jao-jao<bt>Kanaan's descendants spread out far-far,</bt><v n="19" />sampe dong pung batas-batas tana mulai dari Sidon tarús pi Gerar, sampe di Gasa. Dari situ pi Sodom, Gomora, Adma, deng Seboim, sampe di Lasa.<bt>until their land boundaries began from Sidon going on to Gerar, arriving at Gasa. From there, going on to Sodom, gomora, Adma, and Seboim, until coming out at Lasa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nafotsu (pwts nif): they were scattered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nafotsu (pwts nif): they were scattered gəvul: boundary, territory<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>boʾəkhah (bwʾ partcpl): when you are going</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Dong samua tu, Ham pung turunan. Satu-satu deng dong pung bahasa, dong pung suku, deng dong pung tana sandiri.<bt>All of them were Ham's descendants. Each with their own language, their own tribe/clan, and their own land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sem pung turunan<bt>Sem's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Yafet pung kaka Sem, jadi orang Eber dong pung nene-moyang.<bt>Yafet's older-brother Sem, became the ancestor of the Eber people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yullad (qal passive): was born to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yullad (qal passive): was born to him (here as elsewhere, the person named can be either the father or a more remote ancestor, with generations skipped in between)</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ada orang yang pintar saparu bilang Eber tu, andia &lt;Ibrani&gt;.<bt>Some knowledgable people say this Eber, is 'Ibrani' [Hebrew].</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="22" />Sem pung turunan, andia, Elam, Asyur, Arpaksad, Lud deng Aram.<bt>Sem's descendants were Elam, Asyur, Arpaksad, Lud and Aram.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="23" />Aram pung turunan, andia, orang-orang Us, Hul, Geter deng Mas.<bt>Aram's descendants were, the people of Us, Hul, Geter and Mas.</bt><note reference="10:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Mas pung nama laen, &lt;Mesek&gt;.<bt>Mas's other name is 'Mesek'.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24" />Arpaksad pung ana, Sela. Sela pung ana, Eber.<bt>Arpaksad's child was Sela. Sela's child was Eber.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25" />Eber dapa dua ana laki-laki. Yang sulung, dapa nama <span class="Italic">Pelek</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;tabagi-bagi&gt;), tagal itu waktu, orang dong tabagi-bagi di dunya. Dia pung adi, nama <span class="Italic">Yoktan.</span><bt>Eber had two sons. The oldest, was named Pelek, because at that time, people were split up on the world. His younger-brother's name was Yoktan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;Peleg&quot; is the regular word for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">"Peleg" is the regular word for an artificial irrigation channel. PLG in the nifʿal is used only of this occasion (also 1 Chronicles 1:19), so there's no evidence that any other kind of division is involved, like political division or even geological separation. It's reasonable to take it as a reference to the development of irrigation-based societies, where water rights became prominent in law and encouraged the codification of law, and irrigation agriculture made it possible for a lot of people to live in a small area, which went along with the need for consistent laws. It points plausibly to the introduction of irrigation, which brought about a lot of political changes because now somebody could control who got how much water. Similar social changes took place in the eastern part of the Valley of Mexico when started digging irrigation ditches. Hawaiʿi is still arguing about the allocation of irrigation water in 19th century ditches even though the sugar cane and pineapple fields are no longer under cultivation. [JEG] nifləgah (plg nif fem sg): the earth/land was divided, cut open, split with channels (the noun is used for an artificial water-channel, like a water ditch, in Isaiah 30:25 and elsewhere). Job 29:6 has ditches full of olive oil. Job 38:25 has the piʿel form "open a channel, split with channels." Psalm 55:10 has pallag, which Holladay says has to be read as peleg. Modern Hebrew pilleg ʾsplitʾ, pullag ʾbe splitʾ.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="26" />Yoktan pung turunan, andia, Almodad, Selef, Hasar-Mawet, Yera,<bt>Yoktan's descendants were, Almodad, Selef, Hasar-Mawet, Yera,</bt><v n="27" />Hadoram, Usal, Dikla,<bt>Hadoram, Usal, Dikla,</bt><v n="28" />Obal, Abimael, Syeba,<bt>Obal, Abimael, Syeba,</bt><v n="29" />Ofir, Hawila, deng Yobab. Dong samua ni, Yoktan pung turunan.<bt>Ofir, Hawila, and Yobab. All of these were the descendants of Yoktan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Dong pung tampa tenga tu, mulai dari Mesa, tarús sampe di Sefar, andia tampa bagunung-bagunung di sablá matahari nae.<bt>Their dwelling place began from Mesa, continued on to Sefar, that is the mountain region in the east.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tampa bagunung-bagunung ~ tampa-tampa bagunung ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">tampa bagunung-bagunung ~ tampa-tampa bagunung = mountains, mountainous region</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moshavam: their area of residence Har"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">moshavam: their area of residence Har Haqedem: the Eastern Mountains = the northern border of Sinai?<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Dong samua tu, Sem pung turunan. Satu-satu deng dong pung bahasa, dong pung suku, deng dong pung tana sandiri.<bt>All of them were Sem's descendants. Each with their own language, their own tribe/clan, and their own land.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Itu samua tu, Noh pung turunan, satu-satu deng dia pung suku sandiri-sandiri. Waktu banjer bésar abis, dong ni yang tasiram bekin ponu dunya.<bt>All of those were Noh's descendants, each with his own tribe. When the big flood ended, these are the people who spread out to fill the world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nifrədu: divided into family groups, branched"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nifrədu: divided into family groups, branched off (v. 5) End of P section.<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Manara Babel<bt>The tower of Babel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Dolu-dolu, samua orang di dunya ba'omong pake satu bahasa sa.<bt>Long ago, everyone in the world spoke using just one language.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="safah: lip; manner of speaking. Doublet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">safah: lip; manner of speaking. Doublet doesn't transfer gracefully into Pidgin in this case. dvariym: words<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Waktu dong saparu mulai bapinda pi sablá matahari nae, dong sampe di satu tana rata di Sinear,<bt>When some of them began to move to the east, they arrived at a flat land in Sinear, and they stayed there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bnaSʿam (nSʿ inf): in their pulling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">bnaSʿam (nSʿ inf): in their pulling up tent stakes and moving, going on from one place to another, living in each place for a while. Used of nomads like today's Bedouin graups. yimtsʾu: they reached a place, found what they were looking for, ran into it by chance<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>biqʿah: valley-plain, broad with shallow walls (like between Dallas and Ft. Worth, or around Sacramento). In this case, it is the broad valleys of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers in modern Iraq and the fairly level ground in between.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;Pi sablá matahari nae&gt; dalam bahasa Ibrani, dia pung arti ju bisa bilang &lt;dari sablá matahari nae&gt;. Sinear pung nama laen &lt;Babel&gt;.<bt>'Go to the east', in the Hebrew language can also mean 'from the east'. Sinear's other name, 'Babel'.</bt></note>ju dong tenga di situ.</p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00638c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3-4" />Dong samua ba'akór bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Sodara-sodara dong! Mari ko kotong bangun satu kota bésar. Kotong musti bekin batu bata, ais kotong bakar sampe karás. Deng kotong susun itu batu bata dong pake ter. Ais kotong kasi badiri satu manara tinggi, yang dia pung ujung sampe di langit, ko biar kotong dapa nama. Biar ko kotong jadi satu bangsa bésar yang sonde usa tabagi-bagi.&gt;&gt;<bt>They were all of one accord saying, &lt;&lt;We! Brothers and sisters! Let's (inc) build a large city. We need to make bricks, and bake them until they are hard. Then let's pile-arrange the bricks with tar. We'll make stand a high tower, whose tip reaches the sky, so we can get a name (=be famous). It's fine if we are one large race that doesn't need to be divided up.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mal = cetak, put in a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">mal = cetak, put in a form</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reʿehu (reaʿ): their friends, compatriots, people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">reʿehu (reaʿ): their friends, compatriots, people like them havah (yhb cohortative plural): come on = "let's do something"<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>nilbənah (nlb cohortative plural): let's mold bricks (mix mud and chopped up straw and put it into rectangular molds and let it dry in the sun. Then they stack them up along with a lot of firewood inside a big brick building with a rounded roof and a hole in the top, and light the firewood. The heat makes the bricks hard enough to last hundreds of years, so they can be used for large scale building just like stone blocks.) ləveniym: bricks<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vnisrəfah: let's burn them thoroughly (fire them inside a kiln, not just bake them in the sun -- the kind of hard brick that sugar mill smokestacks are made of) sərefah: place of burning, brick kiln<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>chemar: bitumen, a natural derivation of crude petroleum that leaked out of the ground (that's where the Iraq oil fields are today) chomer: mortar for buildings<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>migdal: tower; watch tower, temple tower, fortress tower pen-nafuts: in order not to scatter (could be from pressure by enemies, or from not having a home base)<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>nafuts (pwts qal 1pl): we be scattered</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ju TUHAN turun ko maloi coba itu kota deng dia pung manara yang dong bangun.<bt>Then the LORD descended to have a look at the city and its tower that they were building.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bney haʾadam: the sons of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">bney haʾadam: the sons of the earth, the sons of Adam; humans, the people doing the building as distinct from God</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ais Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini manusia dong samua, satu bangsa, deng pake satu bahasa. Apa yang dong bekin sakarang ni, baru mulai langka partama sa. Beso-lusa, kalo dong samua ta'ika jadi satu sama ke sakarang ni, nanti dong bisa bekin apa sa.<bt>Then He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;All these people are one race, and they use one language. What they are doing here now, is just the beginning of the first step. Later on (lit. tomorrow-next day), if they are all united (&lt;bound as one) as they are now, then they will be able to do whatever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lkhullam: for all of them chillam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">lkhullam: for all of them chillam (chll hif inf): their beginning<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>yibtsar: will be impossible yazmu (zmm impf): they plan to do<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Lebe bae Kotong turun bekin dong pung bahasa jadi laen-laen, ko biar dong sonde bisa mangarti satu deng satu lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>It would be best if We-inc descend and make their languages into many different ones, so they won't be able to understand each other.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nirdah (yrd cohortative): let's go down."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nirdah (yrd cohortative): let's go down. Plural of majesty, as in 1:6? nivlah (bll impf): moisten with oil, pour oil, we will mix up, confuse, shake up<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais ju Tuhan turun ko bekin kaco dong pung bahasa. Deng bagitu, Dia bekin itu manusia dong tasiram pi samua tampa di dunya. Ju dong su sonde bangun tarús itu kota lai.<bt>So the Lord descended to make chaotic their language. In that way, He made the humans scatter over all places in the world. And they didn't continue to build that city anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayafets (pwts hif): he made them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayafets (pwts hif): he made them scatter, disperse (the very thing they did not want to do) vayachdəlu (chdl event + inf): they stopped building (should this be said first? They gave up on the town and moved out all over the world.)<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Andia ko dong kasi nama itu kota, <span class="Italic">Babel</span>, (yang amper sama ke satu kata yang dia pung arti &lt;babingung&gt;), tagal TUHAN bekin kaco dong pung bahasa deng kasi tasiram sang dong pi mana-mana di dunya.<bt>That is why they named that city, Babel (which is almost like a word meaning &lt;confused&gt;), because the LORD made their language chaotic, and he scattered them everywhere in the world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həfiytsam (pwts hif0: he scattered them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">həfiytsam (pwts hif0: he scattered them End of P section.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] He did a good job, didnʾt He? [JEG] Job security for linguists.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dari Sem sampe Abram<bt>From Sem to Abram</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ini Sem pung turunan. Waktu banjer bésar su barenti dua taon, pas deng Sem umur 100 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Arpaksad.<bt>These are Sem's descendants. When the big flood had stopped for two years, exactly when Sem was 100 years old, he had a son, named Arpaksad.</bt><v n="11" />Ais itu, dia masi idop lai 500 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, he still lived another 500 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Waktu Arpaksad umur 35 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Sela.<bt>When Arpaksad was 35 years old, he had a son, named Sela.</bt><v n="13" />Ais itu, Arpaksad masi idop lai 403 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Arpaksad still lived another 403 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Waktu Sela umur 30 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Eber.<bt>When Sela was 30 years old, he had a son, named Eber.</bt><v n="15" />Ais itu, Sela masi idop lai 403 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Sela still lived another 403 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Waktu Eber umur 34 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Pelek.<bt>When Eber was 34 years old, he had a son, named Pelek.</bt><v n="17" />Ais itu, Eber masi idop lai 430 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Eber still lived another 430 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Waktu Pelek umur 30 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Rehu.<bt>When Pelek was 30 years old, he had a son, named Rehu.</bt><v n="19" />Ais itu, Pelek masi idop lai 209 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Pelek still lived another 209 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Waktu Rehu umur 32 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Seruk.<bt>When Rehu was 32 years old, he had a son, named Seruk.</bt><v n="21" />Ais itu, Rehu masi idop lai 207 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Rehu still lived another 207 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Waktu Seruk umur 30 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Nahor.<bt>When Seruk was 30 years old, he had a son, named Nahor.</bt><v n="23" />Ais itu, Seruk masi idop lai 200 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Seruk still lived another 200 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Waktu Nahor umur 29 taon, dia dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Tera.<bt>When Nahor was 29 years old, he had a son, named Tera.</bt><v n="25" />Ais itu, Nahor masi idop lai 119 taon, deng dia dapa tamba lai ana laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>After that, Nahor still lived another 119 years, and he had additional sons and daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Waktu Tera umur 70 taon lebe, ju dia dapa tiga ana laki-laki, andia, Abram, Nahor, deng Haran.<bt>When Tera was over 70 years old, he had three sons, that is, Abram, Nahor, and Haran.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tera pung turunan<bt>Tera's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Tera pung turunan dong, bagini: Tera pung ana dong, andia Abram, Nahor, deng Haran. Haran dapa satu ana laki-laki, nama Lot.<bt>These are tera's descendants. Tera's children were Abram, Nahor, and Haran. Haran had a son, named Lot.</bt><v n="28" />Haran mati di dia pung kampong asal, nama Ur, di orang Kasdim pung tana. Waktu dia mati tu, dia pung bapa Tera masi idop.<bt>Haran died in the village of his origins, named Ur in the land of the Kasdim people. When he died, his father Tera was still alive.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="restructured at Dhao check, Sept 2004"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">restructured at Dhao check, Sept 2004 ***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yamat: he died moladto: his family|i(28)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yamat: he died moladto: his family<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʾur: Usually taken as the city of Ur in southern Mesopotamia, a cultural center. But because Abram was a nomad and lived in tents, some scholars feel there must be another Ur in northern Mesopotamia, probably not too far from Haran. Nobody is sure. kasdiym: Chaldeans<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Abram kawin deng Sarai. Nahor kawin deng Haran pung ana parampuan, nama Milka. Haran ju dapa ana laki-laki, nama Yiska.<bt>Abram married Sarai. Nahor married Haran's daughter, named Milka. Haran also had a son, named Yiska.</bt><v n="30" />Ma Sarai mandul, sonde bisa barana.<bt>But Sarai was barren, [and] couldn't give birth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿəqarah: sterile, barren"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿəqarah: sterile, barren</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Satu kali, Tera bawa dia pung ana Abram, dia pung ana mantu Sarai, deng cucu Lot, ko dong kaluar kasi tenga kampong Ur. Itu waktu dong mau pi tana Kana'an. Ma sampe di negrí Haran, ju dong tenga di situ sa.<bt>One time, Tera brought his son Abram, his daughter-in-law Sarai, and his grandson Lot, and they left behind the village of Ur. At that time they wanted to go to the land of Kanaan. But arriving at the town/state of Haran, they just stayed there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalato: his daughter in law: a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">kalato: his daughter in law: a woman who is first under control of her father, then of her husband and her father-in-law (as her father's representative) yetsʾu (ntsʾ): they went out<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Di situ, Tera mati waktu dia pung umur 205 taon.<bt>In that place, tera died when he was 205 years old.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah pange sang Abram<bt>Lord God calls Abram</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />Itu waktu, TUHAN su omong deng Abram bilang, &lt;&lt;Abram! Lu kaluar kasi tenga lu pung kelu, lu pung bapa pung ruma, deng lu pung kampong. Lu pi satu tampa yang nanti Beta kasi tunju sang lu.<bt>At that time, the LORD had spoken with Abram saying, &lt;&lt;Abram! You [must] go leaving behind your family, your father's house, and your village. Go to a place, which I will later point-out to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="leave behind 1 2 3 reordered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">leave behind 1 2 3 reordered to 2 3 1 at Dhao check Sept 2004 ***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meʾartskha: from your land (probably your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">meʾartskha: from your land (probably your native land, not your piece of property) moladtkha: your relatives<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>beyt avikha: your father's household ʾarʾekha (rʾh hif): I will show you<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Nanti Beta kasi berkat sang lu.<bt>I will give blessing to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng lu pung turunan nanti tamba banya,<bt>And your descendants will increase in number,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">deng jadi bangsa yang hebat sampe orang dong kanál lu pung nama.<bt>and become an impressive race to-point-that people know your name.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ais lu nanti jadi berkat kasi sang orang laen.<bt>Then you will be/become a blessing to other-people [can also mean 'other tribes, clans, races, not your own'].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəvarkhah: and I will bestow on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾəvarkhah: and I will bestow on you the power for success, prosperity, fertility (= I will bless you) həyeh: you are to be<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bərakhah: blessing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Nanti Beta kasi berkat sang orang yang kasi berkat sang lu.<bt>I will give blessing to people who give blessing to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ma Beta kasi kutuk sang orang yang kasi kutuk sang lu.<bt>But I will give curses to people who give curses to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dengar bae-bae!<bt>Listen well! [NOTE: Why this transition? See Hamilton "The grand finale in this catalogue of blessings and promises is: (so that) by you all the earth's clans shall be blessed. Again, the syntax of this passage helps isolate this climactic phrase. This unit began with an imperative, continued with a number of first singular imperfects (punctuated with an imperative that has imperfective force), and now climaxes with a perfect (niþrƒ±û)....&gt;&gt;]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te nanti samua suku-bangsa di ini dunya dapa berkat, tagal lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>All peoples/races in the world will get blessing because of you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəvarəkhah (brk piʿel): I will bless"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾəvarəkhah (brk piʿel): I will bless məvarkheykha (brk piʿel partcpl): the one who blesses you<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>mqallelkha (qll piʿel partcpl): the one who curses you ʾaʾor (ʾrr piel): I will inflict with a curse<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>nivrəkhu bəkha (brk nif passive): they will be blessed in their relationship to you, through you. (The nifʿal inflection here has also been taken as equivalent to a hitpaʿel "they will bless themselves, consider themselves fortunate") mishpəchot: clans, lineages<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-5" />Itu waktu, Abram pung umur 75 taon. Dia bawa dia pung bini Sarai, dia pung adi pung ana Lot, dia pung barang pusaka samua, deng samua orang karjá yang dia dapa di kota Haran. Ju Abram dong jalan kasi tenga Haran, ko pi di tampa yang TUHAN su kasi tau sang dia. Jadi dong jalan tarús, sampe di satu tampa, nama Kana'an.<bt>At that time, Abram was 75 years old. He took his wife Sarai, and his younger-sibling's child Lot, and all his possessions, and all the workers that he had obtained in the city of Haran. And Abram (collective) went leaving behind Haran, to go to the place which the LORD had told him. So [+consequently] they continued on until they came to a place, named Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tseʾto (ntsʾ inf): at his departure"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">tseʾto (ntsʾ inf): at his departure rəkhusham: their property<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>rakhashu: they had accumulated, gathered nefesh: company of people<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Sampe di sana, ju Abram jalan kuliling itu tana, sampe deka deng satu kampong, nama Sikem. Ais dong tenga tahan deka satu pohon bésar di More. Itu waktu, orang Kana'an dong masi tenga di situ.<bt>Arriving there, Abram went around that land, until [he was] near a village, named Sikem. Then they stayed there temporarily near the big tree at More. At that time, the Kanaan people still lived there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məqom: place, spot ʾelon: oak tree"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">məqom: place, spot ʾelon: oak tree FF 154, 155, 183, Quercus coccifera or Quercus aegilops, or perhaps terebinth (turpentine tree), Pistacia terebinthus. The main point is that it was a prominent tree used for worship.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʾaz: then, earlier. The Canaan people were already living around Shekem when Abram showed up. Moreh: may come from "teacher" or "oracle," related also to Torah ʾinstructionʾ; so possibly it's a site where people would come to consult the gods, like Delphi in Greece.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>HCE “Da Canaan peopo dat live ova dea awready stay go Moreh, fo find out wat dea gods like dem fo do.” [MC] Do you think there will be "static" at having this spelled out? I notice "The Message" here has only "the Oak of Moreh", whereas later on, Peterson renders "sex-and-religion places". [JEG] Here neither sex nor sacrifice is in focus, but divination. And it's the place where Abraham is given the kind of information that others would pay a diviner big bucks for. This all depends on how descriptive the term "Moreh" is, which nobody knows for sure.</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Di situ, TUHAN kasi tunju diri sang Abram. Dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Nanti Beta kasi ini da'era sang lu pung turunan.&gt;&gt; Ais ju Abram susun kasi badiri satu meja batu ko pake jadi meja korban kasi sang TUHAN yang su kasi tunju Dia pung diri di situ.<bt>In that place, the LORD revealed Himself to Abram. He said, &lt;&lt;I will later give this region to your descendants.&gt;&gt; So then Abram pile-arranged standing up a stone table to use as a talbe for sacrifice to the LORD, who had revealed Himself there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeraʾ (rʾh nif): allowed Abram to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yeraʾ (rʾh nif): allowed Abram to see him nirʾeh (rʾh nif partcpl): who allowed Abram to see him.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] How does "let Abram see him" fit with "no man has seen God at any time"? [JEG] This isn't a textual or a translation problem; it's a theologiansʾ problem. There are numerous places where Yahweh "appears" to somebody, using the same type of verb: the elders of Israel, for example, or Isaiah. But none of the passages where the verb is used in this way actually say what God looked like. They tell what they saw in his vicinity: a colored pavement, his train filled the Temple. The theologians have concluded that God let them see that it was him there, but no details. Others, like Abram and Gideon, saw a stranger and deduced from what the stranger said and did that it was God in disguise.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00640c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Abram sémba sang Allah di meja bakar korban<bt>Abram worships Allah at the table for burning sacrifice</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais itu, Abram dong pinda pi gunung di salatan, ais tenga tahan di kampong Betel deng kampong Ai pung teng-tenga. Di situ dia kasi badiri satu meja korban, deng dia sémba sang TUHAN.<bt>After that, Abram (collective) moved to a mountain to he south, and then stayed temporarily in between the village of Betel and the village of Ai. There he erected (&lt;made stand) a table for sacrifice, and he worshipped the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beyt-ʾel: House of God, named that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">beyt-ʾel: House of God, named that later by Jacob yaʿteq: (ʿtq hif): moved on<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yeT (nTh imperf): spread out, pitched a tent ʾhlh (ktiv) ʾohelah (qereʾ): tent<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yiqraʾ bəshem yʾ: invoked the name of Yahweh, summoned Yahweh shem: name as standing, reputation, renown (make a name for oneself), fame<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ais itu, dia bapinda-bapinda tampa, sampe di tana Negeb di Kana'an pung sablá salatan.<bt>After that, he kept moving location, until he came to the land of Negeb on the southern side of Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSSaʿ (nSʿ qal): depart halok: continuation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yiSSaʿ (nSʿ qal): depart halok: continuation and progress of the action, journeyed further and further south, bit by bit<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>naSoaʿ: making his way negbah: to the Negev, the desert in the south of Israel<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abram pi negrí Masir<bt>Abram go to the country of Masir [Egypt]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Satu waktu, ada musim lapar yang hebat di tana Kana'an. Andia ko Abram dong jalan lebe jao lai pi sablá salatan, sampe di negrí Masir. Dong tenga tahan di sana.<bt>One time, there was an exceptional hunger season (=famine) in the land of Kanaan. That is why Abram (collective) went even further to the south, until [they arrived] at the country of Masir. They stayed there temporarily.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʿav: famine lagur (gwr): live for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">raʿav: famine lagur (gwr): live for a limited time as an alien<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>khaved: heavy</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Waktu dong mau maso pi negrí Masir, dia kasi tau dia pung bini Sarai bilang, &lt;&lt;Sarai. Lu ni, talalu manis.<bt>When they were about to enter the country of Masir, he told his wife Sarai saying, &lt;&lt;Sarai. You are really pretty.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tagila-gila = mau jato cinta"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">tagila-gila = mau jato cinta</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiqriyv (qrb hif): he drew near"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hiqriyv (qrb hif): he drew near yəfat marʾeh: beautiful to look at<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ma nanti kalo orang Masir lia sang lu manis bagini, tantu dong mau bunu sang beta, tagal beta ni lu pung laki. Deng bagitu, dong bisa ame sang lu.<bt>But later if/when the Masir people see your beauty, they will certainly want to kill me, because I am your man/husband. In that way, they can take you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəchayyu (chyh piʿel): they will let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yəchayyu (chyh piʿel): they will let you stay alive, keep you alive</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Jadi ada lebe bae, lu kasi tau sang dong bilang, beta ni, lu pung kaka. Deng bagitu, dong sonde bunu sang beta, ma nanti dong babae deng beta, tagal lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be better, that you tell them that I am your older-brother. In that way, they won't kill me, but they will be good to me, because of you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾimriy: tell lmaʿan: in order that,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾimriy: tell lmaʿan: in order that, so that<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yiyTav-liy: it will turn out well for me ʿəvurek: for the sake of you<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>chaytah nafshiy: my soul will live, I will stay alive biglalek: on account of you<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00646c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Sarai di raja Masir pung ruma jabatan<bt>Sarai in the raja Masir's official residence</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Tarús, waktu Abram dong su sampe di Masir, orang dong dapa lia itu parampuan manis talalu.<bt>So later, when Abram (collective) arrived in Masir, people saw that the woman was very pretty.</bt><v n="15" />Waktu raja Masir pung pagawe dong dapa lia sang dia, ju dong puji-puji itu parampuan pung manis di muka raja. Ais dong bawa itu parampuan pi raja pung ruma.<bt>When the raja Masir's employees/officials saw her, they kept praising the woman's beauty in front of the raja. Then they brought that woman to the raja's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarey: officers of yəhaləlu: they praised|i(15)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">sarey: officers of yəhaləlu: they praised<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>tuqakh: she got taken as a wife</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Jadi raja babae deng Abram, tagal Sarai. Ju raja parsén binatang kasi sang Abram, andia: kambing, domba, sapi, keledai, deng onta. Dia ju kasi parsén hamba laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>So (consequently) the raja was good to Abram, because of Sarai. And the raja gave gifts to Abram. Such as: animals like sheep, goats, cows, donkeys, and camels (loan). He also gave gifts of male and female servants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parsén = hadia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">parsén = hadia</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heyTiyv (yTb hif): do well, treat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">heyTiyv (yTb hif): do well, treat well baʿəvurah: on account of her<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>chəmoriym: donkeys ʾətonot: female donkeys<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>gmalim: one-humped camel, Camelus Dromedarius (FF 13, 14). Some scholars thought there were no camels in Egypt in Abraham's time, but later research by Free showed camel figurines and pictures from before Abraham's time. Camels originated east of Palestine, but they got around because they were important for carrying things to sell. shfachot: female servants or slaves<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ma tagal raja su ame orang pung bini pi dalam dia pung ruma, andia ko TUHAN hukum macam-macam sang dia deng dia pung isi ruma dong.<bt>But because he had taken a(nother) person's wife into his house, that is why the LORD punished the raja and his household in various ways. [EXEG: 1) “diseases” is actually too specific for this Heb word, and is had by implication or association. 2) the Heb phrase includes both a verb form and a noun form of the same root, commonly glossed as “touch” or “struck”; so 3) something like “touched with various/heavy touches” “struck with various strikings” or “afflicted with various/severe afflictions” and “plagued with various plagues” are in the literal ball-park, albeit not elegant ones. But the words plague and affliction in the OT are used much more broadly than just “sicknesses, diseases”. So the Kupang captures it quite well, and is mirrored in the vernaculars. UNS responses always include “disease”, and often some of the other things that should come up under “plagues &amp; afflictions” that are not strictly diseases.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaynagaʿ (piʿel) ngaʿim gdolim: afflicted them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vaynagaʿ (piʿel) ngaʿim gdolim: afflicted them with severe sicknesses (ngʿ touch)</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ais raja pange sang Abram ko tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Abram! Lu su bekin karmana sang beta? Akurang ko lu sonde kasi tau bilang, itu parampuan tu, lu pung bini?<bt>So the raja summoned Abram to ask him saying, &lt;&lt;Abram! What have you done to me here? Why didn't you tell me that the woman was your wife?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higdəta (ngd hif): you did not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">higdəta (ngd hif): you did not put forward the information, speak out</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ma lu bilang dia ni, lu pung adi! Amper sadiki beta ame sang dia jadi beta pung bini! Ini dia, lu pung bini. Sakarang, ame bawa sang dia, deng iskarobis suda dari beta pung muka!&gt;&gt;<bt>But you said she was your younger-sister! It nearly came to me taking her as my wife! Here she is, your wife. Now, take her away, and get-away from my face!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾamarta: you have been saying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾamarta: you have been saying</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ais raja parenta dia pung pagawe dong, ko usir kasi kaluar Abram, dia pung bini, deng dong pung barang samua dari itu da'era.<bt>Then the raja commanded his employees to evict Abram, his wife, and all their belongings from that region.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yətsaw (tswh piʿel): order someone to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yətsaw (tswh piʿel): order someone to do something yəshalkhu: they escorted them out, went with them to the border, sent them away<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abram deng Lot bapisa<bt>Abram and Lot separate</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, Abram jalan kasi tenga Masir, ko kambali pi tana Negeb. Dia bawa dia pung bini deng dia pung harta pusaka samua. Dia pung adi pung ana Lot ju ada iko sang dong.<bt>After that, Abram left Masir, to return to the land of Negeb. He went with his wife, and all his possessions. His younger-brother's child Lot also went with them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʿal (ʿlh): went up (always used"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yaʿal (ʿlh): went up (always used for going from Egypt to Palestine; the reverse route is always ʾwent downʾ) kaved: rich<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>miqneh: possessions, especially livestock</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Abram tu, kaya mau mati. Dia pung binatang piara deng mas-perak, talalu banya.<bt>Abram was very wealthy. He had a lot of domestic animals, and silver-gold.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Dari Negeb dia jalan bapinda-bapinda ko pi kambali di kampong Betel deng kampong Ai pung teng-tenga. Dolu dia parná tenga di situ.<bt>From Negeb he travelled nomadically (&lt;moving-moving) to return to the place in between the village of Betel and the village of Ai. He had stayed there before.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yelekh (hlk): he went here and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yelekh (hlk): he went here and there lmaSSaʿayw: in his daily breaking of camp, by a series of daytime marches<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>təchillah: the beginning</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Deng dia ju su kasi badiri meja korban. Ais dia sémba sang TUHAN di situ.<bt>And he had also erected a offering table. And he worshipped the LORD there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Lot, yang iko sama-sama deng Abram tu, ju ada pung binatang piara banya, deng dia pung orang karjá dong ju banya.<bt>Lot, who went together with Abram, also had many domestic animals, and his working people were also many.</bt><v n="6-7" />Ma itu tampa sonde cukup luas kasi Abram deng Lot, deng dong pung harta-benda samua, ko idop sama-sama di situ. Ais Abram deng Lot pung gambala dong mulai bakanjar, tagal rumput di itu tampa sonde cukup kasi dong pung binatang. (Itu waktu, orang Kana'an deng orang Feris masi tenga di situ ju.)<bt>But that place wasn't wide enough for Abram and Lot, and all their possessions, to live together there. So Abram and Lot's herders began to argue/dispute, because grass in that place wasn't enough for their animals. (At that time, the Kanaan people and the Feris people were still living there also.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nasaʾ: fit, get enough room lashevet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">nasaʾ: fit, get enough room lashevet (yshb inf): to live<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>yachdaw: together rəkhusham: their property<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vayhi riv ben roʿe miqneh-Avram uben roʿe miqneh-LoT: a dispute arose between the herders of the herds of Abram and the herders of the herds of Lot riyv: quarrel, dispute, with lots of words<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>haknaʿəni: the Cannanite haprizzi: the Perizzite<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʾaz: then yoshev: living<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00647c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Abram deng Lot pili tampa<bt>Abram and Lot choose places</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais ju Abram kasi tau sang dia pung ana bilang, &lt;&lt;Lot, é! Kotong ni bakelu. Jang sampe kotong dua batar-enak satu deng satu, ais kotong pung orang karjá dong maen babakalai tarús.<bt>So then Abram told his child (~nephew) saying, &lt;&lt;Lot, é! We are RECIP-family. It should not come to-point-that we two are mutually-yucky with each other, and our workers should not fighting with each other continually.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təhiy (hyh): for there to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">təhiy (hyh): for there to be məriyvah: quarrel<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Naa, lebe bae kotong dua bapisa sa. Ini tampa luas. Jadi, kalo lu pili ame tana di bagian kiri, na, beta ame di bagian kanan. Ma kalo lu pili ame tana di bagian kanan, na, beta ame di bagian kiri.&gt;&gt;<bt>Naa, [+shift] it would be better if the two of us just separate. This is a wide area. So (consequently), if you choose the land on the left side, na, I'll take it on the right side. But if you choose the land on the right side, na, I'll take it on the left side.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həloʾ: isn't it true that ...?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">həloʾ: isn't it true that ...? hippared (prd hif): let's split up<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>smoʾl: the left side ʾeyminah (ymn cohortative): let me go to the right<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yamiyn: right side, south ʾasməʾiylah: let me go to the left<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais Lot lia-lia kuliling. Ju dia dapa lia kali Yarden pung lemba yang limpa deng aer, sampe di kampong Soar. Itu tampa pung subur sama ke TUHAN pung kabón, deng sama ke tana Masir. (Itu waktu, TUHAN balóm kasi ancor kota Sodom deng Gomora. Jadi itu tana masi bae.)<bt>So Lot looked around. And he saw the valley of the Yarden river was aplenty with water, to the village of Soar. The place was as fertile as the garden of the LORD, and the same as Masir. (At that time, the LORD had not yet destroyed the cities of Sodom and Gomora. So (consequently) that land was still good.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʾ (nsʾ): lift up his eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yissaʾ (nsʾ): lift up his eyes kikkar: disk-shaped pita bread, lead disk, talent (75-lb disk of gold or silver used for money), circuit, the environs (on all sides)<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>mashqeh: well irrigated shachet (shcht piʿel): destroy<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>boʾəkhah (bwʾ inf): as you go</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Jadi Lot pili ame samua tana di kali Yarden pung lemba. Ais dong dua bapisa. Ju Lot pi sablá matahari nae.<bt>So Lot chose all the land in the valley of the Yarden river. So then the two of them separated. And Lot went to the east side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yivchar l-: he chose yiSSaʿ (nSʿ):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yivchar l-: he chose yiSSaʿ (nSʿ): pull out, depart, pull up stakes<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>miqqedem: eastward (min from, but here a general adverbial; Lot was on the west bank of the Jordan at the time) yippardu (prd nif): they separated, they were separated<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʾachiyw: his brother</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ma Abram tenga tarús di tana Kana'an. Ais Lot pi tenga di kampong-kampong deka kota Sodom di lemba Yarden.<bt>But Abram continued to live in the land of Kanaan. And Lot went to live in the villages near the city of Sodom in the Yarden valley.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kikkar: district yeʾəhal: he pitched his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">kikkar: district yeʾəhal: he pitched his tent<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʿad: off in the direction of</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ma orang Sodom jahat mau mati. Deng dong sonde mau dengar sang TUHAN.<bt>But those people of Sodom, were incredibly evil people. And they didn't want to listen to/obey the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʿim: bad quality, disagreeable, unwholesome, of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">raʿim: bad quality, disagreeable, unwholesome, of no value, contemptible, evil, morally depraved, vicious, harmful chaTTaʾim: inclined to sin, fallible, sinners, with faults<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Waktu Lot deng Abram su bapisa, ju TUHAN bilang sang Abram, &lt;&lt;Abram! Coba lu buang mata kuliling ko lia samua tampa dari tampa yang lu badiri tu. Lia bae-bae muka-balakang kiri-kanan.<bt>When Lot and Abram had separated, then the LORD said to Abram, &lt;&lt;Abram! Take a look around to see all the places from where you are standing there. Have a good look front-back left-right.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saʾ naʾ ʿeyneykha (nsʾ imperv): lift"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">saʾ naʾ ʿeyneykha (nsʾ imperv): lift up your eyes, look around tsafonah: to the north<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yammah: to the west, toward the sea (makai)</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Samua tana yang lu lia tu, nanti Beta kasi sang lu deng lu pung turunan dong, ko jadi bosong pung pusaka tarús sampe salamanya.<bt>All that land that you see, I will give it to you, and your descendants, to be their inheritance/possession until forever.</bt><v n="16" />Nanti Beta kasi lu pung turunan dong jadi banya sama ke pasir di pante. Sampe orang dong sonde bisa itong lu pung turunan pung banya.<bt>I will make your descendants become many just like the sand on the beach. to-point-that people will not be able to count your descendants in number.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samti: I will put kaʿəfar haʾarets:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">samti: I will put kaʿəfar haʾarets: like the dry, fine particles of dirt, dust<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>limnot (mnh inf): count yimmaneh (mnh nif): be counted, be open to counting<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Sakarang lu jalan kuliling iko ini tana pung panjang deng lebar. Te samua tu, nanti Beta kasi sang lu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Now you go around following this land's length and width. Cuz (elaboration) all of that, I will give to you!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qum (imperv): stand up, get going"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">qum (imperv): stand up, get going hithallekh (hlk hitp): go around here and there<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʾarkah: the length of it rachbah: the breadth of it<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ais ju Abram dong pinda, deng pi tenga ulang lai di itu tampa deka pohon-pohon bésar di Mamre, deka kampong Hebron. Ais dia susun meja korban, ko sémba sang TUHAN di situ.<bt>After that, Abram (collective) moved, and went to stay once again at the place near the big trees at Mamre, near the village of Hebron. And he pile-arranged a table for sacrifice, to worship the LORD there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeloney: oaks of mamreʾ: name of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾeloney: oaks of mamreʾ: name of an Amorite, in 14:13<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abram pi ame kambali sang Lot dari paráng<bt>Abram goes to retrieve Lot from war</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Title changed at Dhao check Sept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Title changed at Dhao check Sept 2004 ***</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Itu waktu, ada ampa raja bakumpul. Andia: Amrafel, raja negrí Sinear. Ariok, raja negrí Elasar. Kedarlaomer, raja negrí Elam. Deng Tideal, raja negrí Goyim.<bt>At that time, there were four rajas who gathered (=formed an alliance). They were: Amrafel, raja of Sinear state (=political unit ranging from village up to country). Ariok, raja of Elasar state. Kedarlaomar, raja of Elam state. And Tideal, raja of Goyim state.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goyim: nations, nonspecific. Later it came"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">goyim: nations, nonspecific. Later it came to mean "Gentile nations," not Jews, but in Genesis 12:2 God tells Abram "I will make you become a great nation (goy)," showing that it has a general meaning. "Goyim," which is simply transliterated in some translations, is not a place name or a people name as far as we know. But to render it as nonspecific "King over some nations whose names I canʾt remember but it doesn't matter" makes good sense. UBS says "Tidal is the name of several Hittite kings, but the narrator does not associate the name with the Hittites. King of Goyim means ʿʿking of nationsʾʾ and may be an honorific title," which is another possibility, but to push it would result in a more complex rendering for a very minor identification.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Itu waktu, ju ada lima raja laen yang bakumpul. Andia: Bera, raja negrí Sodom. Birsa, raja negrí Gomora. Sinab, raja negrí Adema. Semeber, raja negrí Seboim. Deng raja negrí Bela (andia negrí Soar). Ais, itu ampa raja dong baparáng lawan itu lima raja laen dong.<bt>At that time, there were also five other rajas who gathered. They were: Bera, raja of Sodom state. Birsa, raja of Gomora state. Sinab, raja of Adema state. Semeber, raja of Seboim state. And the raja of Bela state, (that is Soar state). Then the four rajas went to war against the other five rajas. [EXEG: Hamilton notes variant readings with the Masoretic Text “Bela king of Zoar” (ov) and “king of Bela, that is, Zoar.” But the significantly stronger reading is Zoar as a later place name for an earlier Bela.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="milkhamah: crowding, shoving; scuffle, combat, war"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">milkhamah: crowding, shoving; scuffle, combat, war</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Deng Bela, raja negrí Soar."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Deng Bela, raja negrí Soar.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Itu lima raja dong bakumpul deng dong pung tantara di lemba Sidim, (yang sakarang dong bilang Laut Mati).<bt>The five rajas gathered with their armies/soldiers in the valley of Sidim, (which now they call the Dead Sea).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Itu paráng pung akar bagini: dolu itu lima raja tondo sang raja Kedarlaomer sampe 12 taon. Ma taon ka-13, ju dong bangun malawan sang dia.<bt>That war, its root is like this: formerly the five rajas bowed-to (=paid homage to, were under) Raja Kedarlaomer for 12 years. But in the 13-th year, they rose up in opposition to him (=rebelled).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chavru: join forces ʿemeq: valley|i(4) (4)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">chavru: join forces ʿemeq: valley<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yam hammelach: the Salty Lake, known now as the Dead Sea, but it has land all around it, and you can see from one side to the other. maradu: they revolted politically, rebelled<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Waktu maso pi taon ka-14, ju raja Kedarlaomer deng dia pung tamán tiga raja tu, datang deng dong pung tantara. Ju dong baparáng bekin kala barapa negrí. Andia: orang Refaim di negrí Asterot-Karnaim, orang Susim di negrí Ham, orang Emim di negrí Sawe-Kiryataim,<bt>Upon entering into the 14-th year, Raja Kedarlaomer and his three raja friends, came with their armies. And they warred causing several states to lose. They were: the Refaim people of Asterot-Karnaim state, the Susim people of Ham state, the Emim people of Sawe-Kiryataim state,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaku (nkh hif): strike"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yaku (nkh hif): strike</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />deng orang Hori yang di gunung Seir sampe di tampa kosong El Paran pung pinggir.<bt>and the Hori people who [place] goes from the Seir mountain to the edge of the empty place/wilderness of El Paran.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="harəram: their mountains hammidbar: area not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">harəram: their mountains hammidbar: area not cultivated, wilderness, range pasture<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais dong bale kambali pi En Mispat (yang sakarang nama Kades). Ais itu, dong bekin ancor orang Amalek pung negrí, deng orang Amori yang tenga di negrí Haseson-Tamar.<bt>Afterwards, they returned again to En Mispat (which now is named Kades). After that, they destroyed the Amalek people's state, and the Amori people who live in Haseson-Tamar state.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayashuvu (shwv): motion back in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayashuvu (shwv): motion back in the direction of their point of departure</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8-9" />Ais, itu lima raja ator dong pung tantara di lemba Sidim, ju dong baparáng lawan itu ampa raja dong.<bt>So then, the five rajas organised their soldiers in the valley of Sidim, and they warred against those four rajas.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetseʾ (ntsʾ imperf): go out vayaʿarkhu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yetseʾ (ntsʾ imperf): go out vayaʿarkhu: set in rows, draw up in battle order, form up<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>milchamah: battle</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Di itu lemba, ada banya kolam ter. Waktu dong baparáng tu, raja Sodom, raja Gomora deng dong pung tantara, bangun lari. Dong saparu jato maso dalam kolam ter. Deng saparu lari pi gunung.<bt>In that valley, there were many tar pits/pools. When they were fighting, the raja sodom and raja Gomora and their soldiers fled. Some of them fell into the tar pits. And some of them fled to the mountains.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beʾərot: holes, wells, openings chemar: bitumen,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">beʾərot: holes, wells, openings chemar: bitumen, tar, like asphalt<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>yanuSu (nwS): they fled, escaped, slipped away yiplu: they fell (could also mean ʾcast themselvesʾ, like to hide, but they could have slipped or tripped just as well)<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>shammah: into there (the tar pits). The implication is that they died. nishʾariym (shʾr nif partcpl pl): the ones that remained. It's possible to read the text in such a way that the two kings of Sodom and Gomorrah are the only ones that fall into the tar pits, and everybody else runs for the mountains, but it can also be taken that some of the soldiers fell in and some got away.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Jadi itu ampa raja yang manáng tu, pi rampas ame samua barang deng makanan dari Sodom deng Gomora. Ais ju dong mulai pulang.<bt>So those four rajas who won, went and looted (&lt;snatched taking) all the belongings and food from Sodom and Gomora. And then they began to go home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rəkhush: property yelekhu (hlk): they continued"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">rəkhush: property yelekhu (hlk): they continued on their way<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ma Abram pung ana Lot ada tenga di Sodom. Ais, itu ampa raja dong ju tangkap bawa Lot dong, deng rampas bawa dong pung barang samua.<bt>But Abram's offspring (nephew = minus-1 generation, classificatory 'offspring') Lot was living in Sodom. Then those four rajas captured taking Lot (collective), and looted all their stuff.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ma ada satu orang yang talapás. Ju dia lari pi lapor sang Abram, orang Ibrani. Itu waktu, ada satu orang Amori, nama Mamre. Abram ada tenga deka-deka Mamre pung pohon-pohon bésar. Mamre pung sodara sang Eskol deng Aner. Dong tu, jadi Abram pung partei.<bt>But there was one person who got free. So he ran and reported to Abram, the Ibrani person. At that time, there was an Amori person named Mamre. Abram was living near Mamre's big trees. Mamre's siblings (brother?, cousin?) were Eskol and Aner. They were Abram's good-friends (slang).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palit: fugitive who had escaped from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">palit: fugitive who had escaped from the invading army shokhen (partcpl): had settled, was living<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʾəchiy: brother of, kinsman of baʿle bərit: partners in an agreement<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] Is this the first occurrence of the word "Hebrew" in the Bible? Do you want a footnote re. it means the same as Jewish people? ; [JEG] "Jew" doesn't figure until after the split kingdom or even the Exile. Most references are to "Israel." Abraham isn't referred to as a Jew in the Torah. ʿivriy means from an ethnic group whose story involves crossing a piece of land or a river (ʿbr), like "Abraham the Transient." Weʾre in the mental world of 2000 BC.</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Waktu Abram dapa dengar bilang, orang su tangkap bawa dia pung adi pung ana, ju dia kumpul dia pung orang karjá yang pintar baparáng. Dong samua ada 318 orang. Ais ju dong pi buru itu ampa raja sampe di kampong Dan yang jao di sablá utara.<bt>When Abram heard that people had kidnapped (&lt;catch-carry) his younger-brother's child, he gathered hism workers who were skilled at warring. There were 318 of them in all. So they went chasing/ hunting the four rajas until they came to the village of Dan which is far on the north side. [EXEG: Leaving out “born of his household” is deliberate undertranslation, since the loyalty relationship is carried by the possessive in KM and his ability to call them to battle. We get the right range of responses when asking UNS's “who might these people be?” To force the “born in his household” would minimally skew the focus, but more likely convey wrong meaning, since Heb “household” includes the entire social network of his large &amp; complex camp/group.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishmaʿ: he heard, he learned, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yishmaʿ: he heard, he learned, he found out nishbah (nif): had been captured<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yareq (ryq hif): he led out, emptied out; called out all of them chnikhav (singular): his followers, vassals. May be related to chnk "train" as in Prov 22:8, which also means "dedicate a house or an altar"<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ylidey: born (singular) shmonah: eight<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beyto: as part of his household, in his camp; homeborn slaves, children of his servants vayirdof (rdf): set off after them to catch up with them, hostile; set out in pursuit<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Di sana, Abram bagi dia pung orang-orang dong jadi barapa kalompok. Dia pung malam, ju dong pi saráng itu orang dong. Ma ada yang lari. Ais Abram dong buru tarús sang dong, sampe di kampong Hoba, di kota Damsik pung sablá utara.<bt>There, Abram divided his people into several groups. That night, they went and attacked those people. But there were some who fled. Then Abram continued chasing them, until the village of Hoba, on the north side of the city of Damsik.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yechaleq (nif): they split up, divided"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yechaleq (nif): they split up, divided themselves (singular) yakem: they struck them<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>smoʾl: left side - north?</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ais Abram dapa ame kambali sang Lot, dia pung orang dong, dong pung barang samua, deng orang-orang laen ju.<bt>So Abram was able to get Lot back, with his people and all their belongings, and other people as well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeshev (shwb hif imperf): brought back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yeshev (shwb hif imperf): brought back heshiyv (shwb hif): bring back people and things as booty<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Melkisedek bakatumu deng Abram. Dia jadi raja, deng kapala agama dari Tuhan Allah ju<bt>Melkisedek meets with Abram. He is a raja, and the head of religion for Lord God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Waktu Abram pulang dari kasi kala itu ampa raja dong, ju raja Sodom datang sambut sang Abram di lemba Sawe (yang orang biasa subu bilang, Lemba Raja).<bt>When Abram returned home from causing those four rajas to lose, the raja of Sodom came to greet-respectfully Abram in the valley of Sawe (which people commonly refer to as the Valley of Rajas).</bt><v n="18" />Itu waktu, Melkisedek jadi kota Salem pung raja.<bt>At that time, Melkisedek was the raja of the city of Salem.</bt><note reference="14:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ada orang yang pintar saparu bilang, kota Salem deng kota Yerusalem tu, sama sa.<bt>There are some knowledgeable people who think that the city of Salem and the city of Yerusalem are the same.</bt></note>Deng dia ju kapala agama dari Tuhan Allah yang Paling Tinggi. Dia datang ko bawa kasi sang Abram roti deng aer bua anggor.<bt>And he was also the *priest (head of religion) of Lord God who is Most High. He came to give Abram, bread and wine (&lt;juice of anggur fruit).</bt><v n="19-20" />Ais ju dia omong kasi berkat sang Abram bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar Tuhan Allah yang Paling Tinggi, yang bekin ame langit deng bumi, kasi berkat sang lu. Puji sang Tuhan Allah, yang su bekin lu manáng dari lu pung musu dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke giving blessing to Abram saying, &lt;&lt;May Lord God who is Most High, who made heaven and earth, give blessing to you. Prasie Lord God, who has made you win over your enemies.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəvarkhehu: he blessed qoneh (partcpl): creator,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yəvarkhehu: he blessed qoneh (partcpl): creator, or possibly purchaser<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais itu ju Abram bagi kasi Melkisedek satu per sapulu bagian dari samua yang dia su rampas kambali tu.<bt>So then also Abram divided giving Melkisedek one out of ten parts from everything he had re-looted back.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miggen (piʿel): delivered tsareykha: your oppressor,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">miggen (piʿel): delivered tsareykha: your oppressor, adversary, enemy (tsar narrow, distress, dread)<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais ju raja Sodom soya sang Abram, deng bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa Abram. Barang-barang yang bapa su rampas ame dari beta pung musu dong, biar bapa soa samua. Ma beta cuma minta kambali beta pung orang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the king of Sodom bowed to Abram, and said, &lt;&lt;Father Abram. The belongings that father has already snatched from my enemies, it's fine if you keep them all. But I only ask that you return my people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ma Abram manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta sumpa di muka Tuhan Allah yang Paling Tinggi, yang bekin ame langit deng bumi,<bt>But Abram answered saying, &lt;&lt;I swear before Lord God who is Most High, who made heaven and earth,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hərimoti yadi (rwm hif pf): I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hərimoti yadi (rwm hif pf): I have lifted up my hand (= sworn)? I hereby swear? UBS likes the immediate form, but the perfective aspect of the verb makes it sound more like he had already made up his mind and sworn his oath. NIV, RSV, and NLT translate it as perfective; the discussion in UBS makes it sound like a defense of the TEV. Waltke and OʾConnor, however, give four other examples of what they call the "instantaneous perfective" for a situation occurring at the very instant of speaking or making a gesture associated with speaking, in Deut 26:3, 2 Sam 17:11, 2 Sam 19:30, and Psalms 143:6.</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />bilang, beta sonde akan ame barang satu apa ju dari lu pung barang. Biar banáng sapo'ong ju, beta sonde akan ame. Deng bagitu, lu sonde bisa omong bilang, &lt;Abram jadi kaya, gara-gara beta.&gt;<bt>that I will not take even one tiny bit of your belongings. Even a length of thread, I will not take. In that way, you will not be able to say, &lt;Abram's wealth is because of me.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="michuT: thread, cord, thin rope heʿəsharti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">michuT: thread, cord, thin rope heʿəsharti (hif): I made him rich<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Beta sonde parlú apa-apa. Cuma mana yang beta pung orang dong su pake, anggap sa su abis. Deng biar beta pung tamán tiga orang ni, Aner, Eskol deng Mamre, ame bawa dong pung bagian.&gt;&gt;<bt>I don't need anything. Only whatever my people have already used, consider it gone. And allow these three friends of mine, Aner, Eskol and Mamre, take away their portions.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bilʿaday: without me, not involving me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">bilʿaday: without me, not involving me raq: only<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>cheleq: part, portion End of S section<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah bajanji deng Abram<bt>Lord God mutual-promise with Abram</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, TUHAN kasi tunju diri sang Abram. Ju Dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Abram! Lu sonde usa taku. Te Beta yang tangkis ko pele sang lu dari musu. Deng Beta kasi ontong bésar sang lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the LORD revealed Himself to Abram. And He said, &lt;&lt;Abram! You needn't be afraid. Cuz (elaboration) I am the one who shields you from enemies. And I give you great advantage/reward.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hadvarim haʾeleh: these things (chapter 14)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hadvarim haʾeleh: these things (chapter 14) bamakhzeh: in the vision (seeing as a seer sees, not a regular dream)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>magen: shield, metaphor for protection or refuge skarkha: your wages, your reward; also expenses, maintenance, fare for Jonah's boat trip<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>harbeh (rbh hif inf): to make you great</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Ma Abram bilang, &lt;&lt;Eee, Tuhan Allah. Biar Tuhan mau kasi sang beta bagitu banya ju, sonde ada guna apa-apa. Te beta sonde ada ana ko kasi beta turunan. Jadi mau dapa pusaka bam-banya bekin apa? Paling-paling beta pung hamba, Eliasar dari Damsik yang dapa samua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Abram said, &lt;&lt;Eee, Lord God. Even though the Lord wants to give me so many things, there is no use. Cuz (elaboration) I don't have a child to give me descendants. So (consequently) what's the point of me getting/having lots of inheritance/wealth? At the very least, my servant Eliasar from Damsik will get everything.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mah titten liy: ʾwhat are you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">mah titten liy: ʾwhat are you going to give me?ʾ is not a question about how much Abraham will inherit, but a rhetorical question ʾwhat of significance could you possibly give me? I am already rich but I donʾt have any heirs to pass it on to.ʾ holek: I will go my way = die<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʾəriyriy: alone, in solitude (no children) ben mesheq beyti: unexplained. Son of the possessions of my house = my sole heir? Pun on Dammeseq "Damascus"? Servant born in my household?<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ben-beyti: son of my house, servant born to my retinue? yoresh (partcpl): stands to inherit, be the heir<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-old\Hk059a.jpg" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ma TUHAN manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bukan bagitu! Te lu pung ana sandiri yang nanti dapa itu pusaka, ma bukan itu hamba.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the LORD answered saying, &lt;&lt;It's not like that! Cuz (elaboration) your very own child will get those possessions, not that servant.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hineh: stresses the following word yiyrashkha:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">hineh: stresses the following word yiyrashkha: will be your heir<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>meʿeykha: inside your body, as seat of the origin of man</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ju Dia bawa sang Abram kaluar, ais Dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang lu lia pi langit. Coba lu lia itu bintang. Lu bisa itong sang dong, ko? Lu pung turunan nanti jadi sama banya deng itu bintang dong!&gt;&gt;<bt>And He took Abram outside, and He said, &lt;&lt;Now look at the sky. Have a look at those stars. Can you count them? Your descendants will later become just as many as those stars!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="night time; the sacrifice was next"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">night time; the sacrifice was next afternoon. habeT-naʾ (nbT hif imperv): look!<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju Abram tarima TUHAN pung omong. Ais TUHAN cap sang dia orang hati lurus, tagal Abram parcaya sang Dia.<bt>So Abram accepted what the LORD said. And the LORD stamped/branded him as a straight/righteous person, because Abram *believed Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="fixed undertranslation from CEV in Dhao"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">fixed undertranslation from CEV in Dhao check, Sept 2004 ***</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vheʾmin (hif ʾmn): trust someone, rely"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vheʾmin (hif ʾmn): trust someone, rely upon, treat someone as reliable vayakhshəveah: valued that (feminine) for him, reckoned; have an opinion with regard to someone or something: consider, count as<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>tsdaqah: in this case, Abram has a good relationship with God; also can refer the behavior which God expects man to show to God, blameless behavior, honesty, justice "do da right ting"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ju TUHAN sambung lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, Tuhan Allah. Beta yang su bawa kaluar sang lu dari kampong Ur di orang Kasdim dong pung tana. Deng Beta yang kasi ini tana jadi lu pung pusaka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the LORD continued [speaking] saying, &lt;&lt;I am Lord God. I am the one who brought you out of the village of Ur in the land of the Kasdim people. And I and the one who gives you this land as your belonging/inheritance.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasdiym: Chaldean people lərishtah: to inherit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">kasdiym: Chaldean people lərishtah: to inherit it, possess it<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ma Abram tanya lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Ma karmana TUHAN? Karmana ko beta bisa tau bilang, nanti ini tana jadi beta pung pusaka?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Abram asked saying, &lt;&lt;But how it LORD? How can I know that this land will become my inheritance?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾadonai yahweh: to be read as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʾadonai yahweh: to be read as ʾadonai ʾelohim, rather than as ʾadonai ʾadonai, because of the pointing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ju Dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Mari kotong bekin satu acara, ko ika apa yang Beta omong tadi. Sakarang lu pi ame binatang kasi sang Beta: sapi mai satu, kambing mai satu, deng domba laki satu. Dong samua musti umur tiga taon. Ais lu ame bawa lai burung takukur satu ekor deng burung pompa satu ekor.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He answered saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! Let's make a ceremony, to bind what I have said just-now. Now you go get animals for Me: one female cow, one female goat, and one male sheep. They must all be three years old. And you also get one turtledove, and one dove.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿeglah: young cow məshulleshet (puʿal particpl):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿeglah: young cow məshulleshet (puʿal particpl): three years old<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>ʿez: female goat ʾayil: male sheep<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>tor: dove, Columba livia or Turtur communis, Streptopelia turtur gozal: baby bird (turtledove, eagle)<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>Habərit ben habaturim: the covenant between the pieces (Hebrew title)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Hebrew has a title here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">Hebrew has a title here</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ju Abram pi ame itu binatang samua. Ais dia balá bagi dua itu sapi, kambing, deng domba. Ju dia ator itu daging dong bagi dua di tana, satu bamangada deng satu, jadi dua baris. Ma dia sonde balá itu burung dong.<bt>So Abram went and got all those animals. Then he split in two the cow, goat and sheep. And he arranged that meat in two halves on the ground facing each other, in two lines. But he didn't split the birds.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəvatter (piʿel): cut in pieces. Jeremiah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yəvatter (piʿel): cut in pieces. Jeremiah 34:17ff describes a similar ceremony to finalize an agreement. He cut them down the spine, not with the head in one piece and the tail in the other. ʾish bitro: each one of them (animate) put his part. Sounds like God put his pieces in one row, Abram in another; but it's probably Abram putting each half animal opposite the other half of the same animal, like two rows.<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>liqraʾt: opposing sides reʿehu: their counterparts<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ais ju burung-burung tukang makan bangke dong datang ko mau makan itu daging dong. Ma Abram usir buang sang dong.<bt>The vultures (&lt;corpse-eating birds) came to eat that meat. But Abram shooed them away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayered: whenever they came down NJB"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">vayered: whenever they came down NJB ʿayiT: birds of prey (SK mentioned crows, then vultures)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>hapgarim: carcasses yashshev (nshb hif): drive away<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Waktu matahari tanggalám, ju Abram tidor sonu. Dia mimpi bilang, galáp gulita ada tutu ame sang dia sampe dia taku mau mati.<bt>When the sun set, Abram slept soundly. He dreamt that pitch dark covered him until he was terrified.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tidor kucing = sleep fitfully"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">tidor kucing = sleep fitfully</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Late afternoon, toward the end of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">Late afternoon, toward the end of the full day after the nite time remark about the stars laboʾ (inf): going (down)<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>tardemah: not regular sleep, but a deep sleep or a trance. Same word used when God anesthetized Adam to make Eve. Groggy, couldnʾt make out what was happening. ʾeymah: terror, dread<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>chəshekhah: absence of daylight ʾeymah chəshekah gədolah: N N A, horror of great darkness (does gdolah go with ʾemah too, or just with chshekah? One Jewish commentator thinks chshekah is a gloss on ʾeymah, but with no textual or exegetical basis. great dark dread, dark fear<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-15" />Ais Tuhan Allah kasi tau sang dia bilang,<bt>Then Lord God told him saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Abram! Nanti lu idop sampe tua sakali, deng mati deng tanáng, baru dong kubur bae-bae sang lu.<bt>&lt;&lt;Abram! You will live until you are very old, and die in peace, and then they will bury you properly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ma lu pung turunan dong nanti pi jadi orang manumpang di orang laen pung negrí.<bt>But your descendants will become immigrants in other people's country.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nanti bangsa dari itu negrí bekin sang dong jadi kuli, abis tendes bekin sangsara satenga mati, sampe ampa ratus taon.<bt>And the race from that country will make them become slaves, then oppress them with great-difficulty, for four hundred years.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ma nanti Beta hukum itu bangsa.<bt>But later I will punish that race.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ais Beta bawa kaluar lu pung turunan dari situ, deng dong bawa harta pusaka bam-banya.<bt>And I will bring your descendants out of there, and they will bring lots of belongings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yadoaʿ (inf abs): know certainly ger:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">yadoaʿ (inf abs): know certainly ger: man who, either alone or with his family, leaves his village and tribe bacause of war, famine, pestilence, blood-guilt, or some other reason, and seeks shelter and sojourn elsewhere, where his right to own land, marry, participate in the administration of justice, worship, and war is curtailed; an alien<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʿəvadum: and they will (have to) work for them; have to switch valence to match the valence of the next verb in order to keep Pidgin discourse continuity ʿinu (ʿnh piel): make them feel dependent, humiliated<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yaʿəvodu (qal): the people that they (your descendants) serve dan (din pf): pass sentence, execute justice, call them to account<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>rəkhush: possessions, property tovoʾ ʾel-ʾəvoteykha: you will go to your ancestors<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>bəshalowm: with everything okay, in peace tiqqaver (qbr nif): you will be buried<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>seyvah: gray-headedness Tovah: good old age = extremely old? or quality of life?<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="15:13-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Utusan dong pung Carita 7:6-7</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Nanti Beta ator ko lu pung turunan kalima dong pulang datang di sini lai.<bt>I will arrange it so your fifth descendants will return home to this place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sakarang, orang Amori dong ada tenga di atas ini tana. Ini orang dong jahat, ma balóm talalu barát.<bt>Now, the Amori people are living on this land. These people are evil, but not yet too heavy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nanti kalo lu pung ana-cucu dong su pulang datang di sini, Beta mau pake sang dong, ko hukum bekin ancor orang Amori dong. Te itu waktu, dong pung jahat su kalewat batas.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later when your children-grandchildren return home here, I'm going to use them to punish and destroy the Amori people. Cuz (elaboration) by that time, their evil will already have passed the threshold.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: In many English translations, this verse is so cryptic as to be non-sensical. The Kupang rendering (refined through several languages with several consultants), makes sense of it by making explicit the logical link between the first part and the second part, and also linking it to high-level themes. Why else would the verse link the return with punishment, if the return has nothing to do with the punishment? Merely a coincidence or marker of time? I don't think so. Note that TH says “this [second] clause suggests a reason for God’s action against the Amorites that is not explained in detail but must be stated explicitly in translation to make it clear.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalewat = spill over"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">kalewat = spill over</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dowr: generation, span of time. Some"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">dowr: generation, span of time. Some commentators suggest "century," which would fit the context. rəviyʿiy: fourth<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>hennah: they, fem (dowr is masculine - why?) shalem: complete, finished up, rounded out<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʿəwon: transgression, sin; guilt (caused by sin); punishment (for guilt) ʾəmoriy: can be generic for any inhabitant of Canaan<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Waktu su malam, takuju te ada satu ra'o tana liat ba'asap deng satu obor manyala bagarák lewat itu daging dua baris pung teng-tenga.<bt>When it was dark, suddenly, there was a smoking clay pot, and a flaming torch, moving by in between the two lines of meat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ra'o = tungku ; pareuk ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z">ra'o = tungku ; pareuk = periuk</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿəlaTah: darkness tanur: fire-pot, furnace, oven;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:34Z" status="Information">ʿəlaTah: darkness tanur: fire-pot, furnace, oven; portable brazier or pan full of coals<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʿashan: ascending smoke lapiyd: torch<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>gəzarim: the two rows of pieces of animals that were sacrificed. Custom for ratifying a covenant</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Itu waktu, ju TUHAN ika janji deng Abram. Dia kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta janji, nanti Beta kasi ini da'era sang lu pung turunan, mulai dari kali Masir,<bt>At that time, the LORD bound promise with Abram. He told him saying, &lt;&lt;I promise, I will give this region to your descendants, beginning from the Masir river,</bt><note reference="15:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kali Masir tu, mungkin kali Misraim di Sinai, mungkin ju kali Nil pung cabang sablá matahari nae.<bt>That Masir river, could be the Misraim river/stream in Sinai, or it could also be the eastern branch of the Nil river.</bt></note>sampe ke kali Efrat,<bt>to the Efrat river,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karat brit: make a covenant by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">karat brit: make a covenant by cutting up a sacrificial animal nahar: watercourse that always has water in it<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>nahar mitsrayim: "river of Egypt," referred to also in Numbers 34:5 and Joshua 15:4 and 47, is probably the Wadi ʾArish in the eastern Sinai, which is a "nahal" ʾbrookʾ, not a "nahar" like the Euphrates because it doesn't have water in it all the time. pərat: Euphrates<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />deng tana orang-orang Keni, Kenas, Kadmon,<bt>with the land of the peoples of Keni, Kenas, Kadmon,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾet X ʾet Y ... are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾet X ʾet Y ... are objects of "give" in 18.</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Het, Feris, Refaim,<bt>Het, Feris, Refaim,</bt><v n="21" />Amori, Kana'an, Girgasi, deng Yebus.&gt;&gt;<bt>Amori, Kanaan, Girgasi, and Yebus.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Hagar deng dia pung ana Ismael<bt>Hagar and her child Ismael</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1-3" />Itu waktu, Abram su kambali dari Masir, ko su tenga sapulu taon di Kana'an. Dia pung bini, Sarai, balóm dapa ana. Sarai ada pung hamba parampuan orang Masir, nama Hagar.<bt>At that time, Abram had returned from Masir, and had lived ten years in Kanaan. His wife Sarai, di not yet have [any] children. Sarai had a female Masir servant/slave, named Hagar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="noun phrase beginning the chapter: new"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">noun phrase beginning the chapter: new scene lo: children for Abram, not children in general<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>shifchah: female slave, maidservant. How important is the fact that Hagar had no say in what went on?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Satu kali, Sarai ba'omong deng Abram bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! TUHAN su pele beta pung tampa ana. Ada lebe bae bapa pi tidor deng beta pung hamba Hagar, ko biar dia barana kasi beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Sarai was talking with Abram, and said, &lt;&lt;Father! The LORD has blocked my womb (&lt;child place). So it would be good if father goes and sleeps with my servant Hagar here, so she can give birth for me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿətsarani miledet: he has held me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿətsarani miledet: he has held me back from giving birth ʾulai: perhaps, in the sense of hope, entreaty, or fear<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʾibbaneh (nif): I will be built = I will live on in a child from here. Pun on "ben"? miminah (min + 3sgf): from Hagar<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>Calvin, "the deadliness of interpretation." They didnʾt just trust God; they figured they needed to do something that he wasnʾt doing.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Abram iko dia pung bini pung omong. Ais Sarai kasi Hagar ko jadi Abram pung bini muda.<bt>Then Abram followed what his wife had said. So Sarai gave Hagar to become Abram's younger wife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqets: at the end of ten"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miqets: at the end of ten years of Avram living ... ləshevet (yshb inf): of living<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>titen: Sarai give Hagar to Abram. That makes sure Hagar's status stays low. If Abram had married Hagar as a regular wife, Sarai would have had no more leverage. ʾishshah: wife, not pilgash "concubine." Gen 25:6.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ais ju Abram pi tidor deng Hagar, ju itu parampuan dudu parú. Ma waktu Hagar tau dia su dudu parú, dia jadi sombong, ju dia pandang enteng sang Sarai.<bt>So then Abram went and slept with Hagar, and that woman became pregnant. But when Hagar knew she was pregnant, she became arrogant, and belittled/scorned Sarai.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant vateqal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant vateqal (qll): she came to esteem her lightly. Probably not outright contempt, more like putting on airs. QLL covers quite a range.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00644c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ais Sarai omong deng Abram bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta yang kasi itu hamba ko jadi lu pung bini muda. Ma waktu itu parampuan tau dia bunting, ju dia pandang enteng sang beta. Itu lu pung sala samua! Kasi tenga ko TUHAN putus kotong dua pung parkara. Baru lu tau!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Sarai spoke to Abram saying, &lt;&lt;I'm the one who gave that slave to be your younger wife. But as soon as the woman knows that she's pregnant (derogatory, for animals), she belittles me. This is all your fault! Let the LORD decide this dispute between the two of us-inc. Then you'll know! [lang of threat]&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəmaSi ʿalekha: this evil action on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chəmaSi ʿalekha: this evil action on me is upon you, your fault becheyqekha: in your embrace, the area where two people touch when they are hugging sexually<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>tereʾ: she sees ʾeqal (qll qal): I am lightly esteemed in her eyes<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>yishpoT: will judge, will decide</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ais ju Abram manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Lu ni, bini tua. Ma dia tu, cuma bini muda sa. Jadi lu yang ada pung kuasa sang dia. Lu mau bekin apa sang dia, dari lu sa!&gt;&gt; Ais ju Sarai bekin kasar-kasar sang Hagar sampe dia bangun lari.<bt>So then Abram answered saying, &lt;&lt;It like this! You are the one who is the older wife. She's merely the younger wife. So you have rights/authority over her. So whatever you want to do to her, that's just up to you!&gt;&gt; So Sarai treated Hagar coursely, to-point-that she ran away. [EXEG: Note vs. 3: Heb /ʔishshah/: “wife”, not /pilgash/ “concubine” as in Gen 25:6. /titen/: Sarai gives Hagar to Abram. That makes sure Hagar's status stays low. If Abram had initiated marrying Hagar as a regular wife, Sarai would have had no more leverage. Secondly, the KM and daughter translations that follow it, build on the normal vocabulary and kakak-adik authority relationship that is normal among multiple wives (or between wives and concubines if they operate in the same hamlet). The anthropological literature on this in eastern Indonesia is overwhelming. To go to boss-servant vocabulary would not be good translation.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Abram is not taking sides. He"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Abram is not taking sides. He cops out. ʿəsiy (ʿsh imperv)<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>təʿaneah (piʿel): she humiliated her, made her feel dependent, oppressed. The mistreatment is psychological, not physically beating her up tov bəʿenekah: no norm. Used in Judges for every person doing whatever "was right in their own eyes." Not "use your best judgment."<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Dia lari sampe di padang pasir. Ju TUHAN pung ana bua satu dari sorga dapa sang dia deka deng mata aer di jalan pi Sur.<bt>She ran to the desert (loan). And an *angel (&lt;one of the LORD's underlings from heaven) encountered her near a spring on the road to Sur.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayimtsaʾah: find, doesn't imply that she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayimtsaʾah: find, doesn't imply that she was lost, only that he met her there. It can imply that he went looking for her. angel of the Lord: angel who was the Lord (in theophanies)?<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʿal: facing, over against, off from, down from. The spring wasnʾt right on the trail, but you could see the trail from there exchange w/consultant: [MC] Now this parenthesis IS important! ; [JEG] Some contain major content as here, some are merely helpful. Very few are really irrelevant. The true identity of the angel comes out only in 10 and 13, and saying "one angel messenja guy from the Boss#" (a possible reading of the Hebrew) guarantees that most readers will miss the identity, because the person who sends a message is not often the messenger and "from" confirms it, so Verse 10 will seem out of kilter.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ais dia bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Hagar, Sarai pung hamba! Akurang ko lu ada di sini? Lu dari mana, deng mau pi mana?&gt;&gt;<bt>And s/he said, &lt;&lt;We! Hagar, Sarai's slave/servant! Why are you here? Where are you coming from, and where are you going?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***made more natural vocative, from Amarasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">***made more natural vocative, from Amarasi check Oct 2005</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Hagar manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta lari kasi tenga beta pung nyonya.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Hagar answered saying, &lt;&lt;I ran away from my mistress.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾey-mizzeh: where from this? ʾanah: where|i(8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾey-mizzeh: where from this? ʾanah: where<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>telekhiy: are you going (what's the -iy?) mifne: from the presence of Sarai, not just "from Sarai"<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>borachat (partcpl fem): running away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ju TUHAN pung ana bua kokoe sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Lebe bae lu pulang pi lu pung nyonya. Dia bekin karmana sang lu, na, tarima sa.<bt>So the LORD's underling coaxed her saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! It's best if you go home to your mistress. Whatever (+however) she does to you, just accept it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitʿani (ʿnh hitp): humble yourself under"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hitʿani (ʿnh hitp): humble yourself under her hand/domination. This verse was cited by slaveholders in the U.S. around 1850 as proof that slavery was ordained by God.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Lu jang taku. Nanti beta bekin lu pung turunan bam-banya, sampe orang sonde bisa itong ontong sang dong.<bt>Don't be afraid. I will make your descendants many, to-point-that people will not be able to count them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="harbah ʾarbeh (rbh hif inf abs):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">harbah ʾarbeh (rbh hif inf abs): I will make you many vloʾ yiSSafer (nif): be counted<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>merov: innumerable malʾakh yhwh: the angel turns out to be the Lord; note first person. So it's more "an angel who was the Lord" than it is "an angel of the Lord." Ambiguous reading.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Sakarang lu ada dudu parú. Sonde lama lai, lu barana satu ana laki-laki. Lu musti kasi nama sang dia, <span class="Italic">Ismael</span> (yang amper sama ke satu kata laen yang pung arti bilang, &lt;Tuhan dengar&gt;), tagal TUHAN su dengar lu pung manangis.<bt>You are now pregnant. In a little while, you will give birth to a son. You must give him the name, <span class="Italic">Ismael</span> (which is almost the same as another word which means &lt;Lord hears&gt;), because the LORD has heard your crying.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿanyekh (ʿani, ʿnh): your miserable situation,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿanyekh (ʿani, ʿnh): your miserable situation, be bowed down (pun on "humble yourself" v. 9?), pitiful, dependent, humiliated, overwhelmed by want, poor, wretched</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ma itu ana bésar datang, dia idop jao dari dia pung sodara dong. Tagal dia sama ke kuda liar yang sonde tau dengar parenta. Sapa sa, dia lawan. Deng samua orang lawan bale sang dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>But when the child grows up, he will live far from his siblings (=bad relationships). Because he is/will be like a wild horse, which doesn't know how to hear/obey commands. No matter who, he will oppose [them]. And everyone will oppose him in return.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana besar datang = when he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ana besar datang = when he grows up</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pereʾ: zebra, wild ass, onager. Syrian"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pereʾ: zebra, wild ass, onager. Syrian onager, now extinct. Not a symbol of stubbornness, but a free spirit, unrestricted, untrammeled, because they live outside the normal human realm of domesticated animals [and people]: Psalm 104:11 the wild donkeys quench their thirst ... He promises Hagar that Ishmael will be independent and free, not a slave like her. Lines 2 and 3 probably an expository apposition (in what way is he going to be like a wild donkey?) [JEG] "Wild donkey" is the ground of comparison, not "donkey." Donkeys (Equus asinus) are the antithesis of outsiders; wild donkeys (Equus hemionus), as in Psalm 104:11, the epitome of animals that could adapt to human shelter and fodder but arenʾt about to buy into it. Changing the punctuation helps slightly. Pereʾ doesn't apply to domestic donkeys; all three of the species the word covers are a different species from the donkey. In Hawaiʿi we got cowboys before the Wild West had them because some cattle given as a gift to King Kamehameha I in the 1790s went wild in the Kamuela area and became a danger to everybody; but I donʾt think weʾve ever had Equus asinus go wild. (Kamehameha asked the Mexican government in California for vaqueros to train his guys, who started a subculture called Paniolo, from español, still going, that produced some world class cowboys.)<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yishkon: he will settle down, live ʿal-pny: at odds, not "to the east of" as in some contexts<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yishkon: will dwell, stay</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Dengar abis bagitu, ju Hagar omong dalam hati bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su lia TUHAN, yang ada lia deng jaga sang beta.&gt;&gt; Ais dia mulai pange sang Tuhan pake nama &lt;&lt;Tuhan yang paduli sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>After hearing that, Hagar spoke in her heart (liver) saying, &lt;&lt;I have seen the LORD, who sees and watches-over/guards me.&gt;&gt; So she began to call the Lord, using the name &lt;&lt;the Lord who cares for me.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: “named the Lord” here is taken as NLT “thereafter...referred to the Lord...as”; and CEV “So from then on she called him,...”; EXEG: Regarding the meaning of the name, the Heb is most honestly characterised by the NRSV ftn “Meaning of Heb uncertain”, reinforced by the fact that most English translations have a ftn here as well. TH says the TEV &amp; RSV rendering is “a conjecture or probable interpretation”. Part of the issue is that Heb /roʔi/: may mean both “I see God” and “he sees me”. KM “the Lord who cares for me” has made explicit the implications for Hagar of the encounter from the context of vs. 4-12, which gives her the courage to return to her mistress in the following verses. High level.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾatah: &quot;you&quot; is actually part of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾatah: "you" is actually part of the name she gives him. roʾi: may mean both I see God and he sees me.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Andia ko orang kasi nama itu mata aer, <span class="Italic">Beer Lahai Roi,</span> yang dia pung arti, &lt;&lt;Mata aer dari Dia yang idop, yang paduli sang beta.&gt;&gt; Dia pung tampa di kampong Kades deng kampong Beret pung teng-tenga. Itu mata aer masi ada sampe sakarang.<bt>That is why people named that spring, <span class="Italic">Beer Lahai Roi,</span> which means, &lt;&lt;spring from Him who lives, who cares for me.&gt;&gt; It is located in between the village of Kades and the village of Beret. That spring is still there to this day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʾi: again, nonspecific as to subject"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">roʾi: again, nonspecific as to subject "Well of the Living One [?] Seeing"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais itu, Hagar pulang. Ju dia barana ame satu ana laki-laki. Abram kasi nama sang dia <span class="Italic">Ismael.</span><bt>After that, Hagar went back home. And she gave birth to a son. Abram named him &lt;Ismael&gt;.</bt><v n="16" />Waktu Hagar barana sang Ismael, Abram pung umur su 86 taon.<bt>When Hagar gave birth to Ismael, Abram was 86 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan ika janji deng Abram pake tanda sunat<bt>The Lord binds a promise with Abram using the sign of *circumcision</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="17" />
      <v n="1" />Waktu Abram pung umur 99 taon, TUHAN datang kasi tunju Dia pung diri sang Abram. Ju Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, Tuhan Allah yang Paling Kuasa. Lu musti iko tarús Beta pung mau, deng idop lurus-lurus.<bt>When Abram was 99 years old, the LORD came and revealed Himself to Abram. And He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;I am Lord God Most Powerful. You must follow my will continually, and live straight-straight (=pure, righteous).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="13 years have passed since the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">13 years have passed since the Hagar incident. vayeraʾ ʾel-(nif): was seen, appeared to<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>shadai (shdd? devastate) hithallekh lfanay (hitp): go about in my presence; walk back and forth, move, walk constantly. Purposive holoholo. 1 Sam 2:21 has ʿim, but lifnay is a respectable variant.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>hyeh (imperv): be tamim: without blemish, blameless 5:22, 24; 6:9; 24:40; 48:15.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Beta mau ika janji deng lu, deng bekin lu pung turunan dong balipa-ganda.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will bind my promise with you, and make your descendants multiply (idiom).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="balipa-ganda ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">balipa-ganda =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾetnah (ntn cohortative): I confirm, apply"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾetnah (ntn cohortative): I confirm, apply (not "make") ʾarbeh (rbh): I will make you (your line) many people<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>biməʾod məʾod: really a lot</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ju Abram tikam lutut ko tondo kapala sampe di tana. Ais Tuhan Allah omong tarús bilang,<bt>And Abram kneeled and bowed his head to the ground. Then Lord God continued speaking saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayipol (qal): fall, bow down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayipol (qal): fall, bow down</Message></Annotation><v n="4-5" />&lt;&lt;Beta bekin janji deng lu, bagini: nanti lu jadi banya bangsa pung nene-moyang. Tagal itu, lu pung nama bukan <span class="Italic">Abram</span> lai (yang dia pung arti &lt;bapa yang nama takanál&gt;), ma <span class="Italic">Abraham</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;banya bangsa pung nene-moyang&gt;).<bt>&lt;&lt;I make promise with you, in this way: you will become the ancestor of many races/peoples. Because of that, your name is no longer <span class="Italic">Abram</span> (which means &lt;father with a famous/praised name&gt;, but <span class="Italic">Abraham</span> (which means founding-ancestor of many races/peoples).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾani hineh ... vʾatah (v. 9):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾani hineh ... vʾatah (v. 9): correlative and causal (Wenham); since my covenant is with you, I will do ... You, for your part, will do ... vhayita lʾav: you will become the father<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>həmon: crowd, big stack goyim: ethnic groups<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yiqqareʾ (nif): your name will not be called Abram ʿowd: still, continuation<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʾavraham etymology? ʾAV-RAV-HMON? ʾAV-RAM-HMON from former name?</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Beta nanti bekin lu pung turunan dong balipa-ganda. Deng nanti Beta ju kasi bangun banya bangsa dari dong, deng angka banya raja dari itu turunan dong.<bt>I will make your ancestors multiply. And I will also found many races/peoples from them, and elevate/appoint many rajas from those descendants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifreti (prh hif): I will make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hifreti (prh hif): I will make fruitful yetseʾu (qal): will come out<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>Ishmael : Isaac :: Saul : David. The first one was not God's choice, but God allowed people to try their own ideas and made things come out his way anyway.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Beta pegang tarús Beta pung janji deng lu, deng lu pung turunan dong. Ini janji sonde tau putus-putus, te Beta ni, lu deng lu pung turunan dong pung Tuhan Allah.<bt>I will hold firm/continually My promise with you, and with your descendants. This promise will not be broken/cease, cuz (elaboration) I am you and your descendants' Lord God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lev 26 blessings &amp; curses. V."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Lev 26 blessings &amp; curses. V. 44, even with the curses, one thing remains: I am still their God. həqimoti (qwm hif): I am setting up<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>beni uvenekha uven zarʿəkha ʾachrekha: between me and you and your progeny after you. Removed the repetition of zrʿ. lədorotam (dor pl): in [each of] their generations, for generation after generation<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>librit ʿolam: as my perpetual contract with you</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ini tana Kana'an samua, nanti Beta kasi sang lu deng lu pung turunan dong. Sakarang lu cuma tenga manumpang sa di sini. Ma nanti lu pung turunan dong soa ini tana Kana'an sampe salamanya. Deng nanti Beta ju jadi dong pung Tuhan Allah.<bt>This entire land of Kanaan, I will give you and your descendants. Now you are only living here as an immigrant. But later, your descendants will possess this land of Kanaan until forever. And I will be their Lord God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾet ... ʾet: piling up accusatives."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾet ... ʾet: piling up accusatives. ʾerets məgurekha: the land where you have protected status as an alien<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>laʾchuzzat: as your property, your possession (not you and the Canaanites)</Message></Annotation><v n="9-10" />Ma lu deng lu pung turunan dong ju musti pegang tarús ini janji deng satia. Samua laki-laki musti sunat.<bt>But you, and your descendants must continue to hold this promise faithfully. All males must be circumcised.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lədorotam: generation by generation himmol (mwl"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lədorotam: generation by generation himmol (mwl nif inf abs): be circumcised<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11-13" />Mulai sakarang, samua laki-laki mulai dari umur dalapan hari, musti sunat. Lu pung kelu, lu pung orang karjá samua, deng budak yang lu su béli ame dari negrí laen, samua musti sunat. Sunat tu, jadi kotong dua pung tanda janji yang makaditi di bosong pung badan.<bt>Now, all males beginning from eight days old, must be circumcised. Your family, and your workers, and your slaves which you have purchased from other countries, all must be circumcised. That circumcision, is a sign of the promise between the two of us-inc which adheres to /on your bodies.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nmaltem (nif): and you will be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nmaltem (nif): and you will be circumcised lʾot: as a distinguishing mark<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʿarlatkhem: the foreskin of their penis yimmol (mwl nif): be circumcised<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>lakhem: where does it connect? yəliyd: son, one born in the household<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>miqnat-kesef: a purchase involving money, purchased for money ben nekhar: from any foreigner who is not from your ohana<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Laki-laki mana yang sonde sunat, sonde dapa bagian dalam Beta pung janji, deng sonde maso jadi Beta pung orang.&gt;&gt;<bt>Whatever male does not get circumcised, is not have a part/right in My promise, and doesn't enter to become [one of] My people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿarel: foreskin, metonymy for an uncircumcised"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿarel: foreskin, metonymy for an uncircumcised person nikhrətah (krt nif): he is to be excluded from the community, rooted out, cut off<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʿammeyha: from its (fem) community hefar (prr hif): invalidate, put an end to, break, destroy<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>End of S section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais itu, Tuhan Allah omong tarús lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Mulai sakarang ni, lu jang pange lu pung bini, deng nama <span class="Italic">Sarai </span>lai, ma pange <span class="Italic">Sara</span> sa.<bt>After that, Lord God continued to speak saying, &lt;&lt;Beginning from now, you should no longer call your wife, Sarai, but just call her Sara.</bt><v n="16" />Nanti Beta kasi berkat bam-banya sang Sara, ko dia barana kasi lu satu ana laki-laki. Batúl! Nanti Sara jadi banya bangsa pung nene-moyang. Deng nanti Beta angka banya raja dari dia pung turunan.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will give many blessings to sara, so she will give birth to a son for you. That's right! Sara will become the ancestor of many races/peoples. And I will elevate many rajas from her descendants.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ju Abraham lipa lutut ko tondo sampe di tana. Ma dalam hati dia ada katawa. Dia pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;Laki-laki kakaluk umur 100 taon ke beta ni, masi dapa ana lai? Deng Sara yang su tua ganggók, umur 90 taon, mana masi bisa barana lai?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham kneeled2 (&lt;folded knees) to bow to the ground. But in his liver he was laughing. He thought saying, &lt;&lt;A 100 year withered old man like me is still going to have a child? And Sara who is already old and feeble, at 90 years old, how can she still be able to give birth?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakaluk = tua kariput (wrinkled up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kakaluk = tua kariput (wrinkled up skin), kurus tua ; tua ngganggók ~ ganggók = tua rentah, amat tua</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitschaq: he laughed blibo: in his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yitschaq: he laughed blibo: in his heart<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>halven: interrogative, to a son meʾah-shanah: 100 years<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>yiwwaled (nif imperf): will be born teled: she will have a baby<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ju dia kasi tau sang Tuhan bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan. Biar Ismael sa yang dapa beta pung pusaka ju, sonde apa-apa.&gt;&gt;<bt>So he told the Lord saying, &lt;&lt;Lord. [Why don't you] just let Ismael be the one to get my inheritance/belongings, [I have] no problem whatsoever with that.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lu: O that, I wish yichyeh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lu: O that, I wish yichyeh lfanekha: he will live in your sight, your presence<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ma Tuhan Allah manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde! Te nanti lu pung bini Sara barana satu ana laki-laki. Lu kasi nama sang dia, <span class="Italic">Isak.</span> Beta pung janji nanti turun pi sang dia deng dia pung turunan, sampe salamanya.<bt>But Lord God answered saying, &lt;&lt;No! Cuz (elaboration) you and your wife Sara will give birth to a son. You are to name him, Isak. My promise will descend to him, and his descendants, until forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəval: an interjection that introduces something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾəval: an interjection that introduces something that will not please the hearer həqimotiy (qwm hif): I will set up<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Beta ju su dengar apa yang lu minta kasi Ismael. Tagal itu, Beta ju kasi berkat sang dia, deng Beta bekin tamba banya dia pung turunan. Nanti ada 12 kapala suku dari dia pung turunan. Deng dia pung turunan nanti jadi satu bangsa yang hebat.<bt>I have also heard what you have asked for Ismael. Because of that, I will also give blessing to him, and I will increase greatly his descendants. There will be 12 tribal heads from his descendants. And his descendants will become an noteworthy race/people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifreytiy (prh hif): I will make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hifreytiy (prh hif): I will make him fruitful hirbeytiy (rbh hif): I will increase the number<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>nəsiʾim: minor kings, chiefs, leaders of lineages ntatiw lgoy gadol: and I will grant to him to be a great people<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Biar bagitu, ma Beta pung janji ni ta'ika deng lu pung ana Isak sa. Nanti taon muka, kira-kira waktu bagini, Sara barana sang dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>Nevertheless (&lt;even letting it be like that), but this promise of Mine is just bound with your child Isak. Later in the front year, approximately at a time like this, Sara will give birth to him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾaqiym (qwm hif): I will set"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾaqiym (qwm hif): I will set up</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Omong abis bagitu, ju Tuhan Allah kasi tenga Abraham sandiri sa di situ.<bt>After [He] finished speaking, Lord God left Abraham by himself there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəkhal (klh piʿel): finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yəkhal (klh piʿel): finished</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23-27" />Itu hari ju, Abraham iko memang Tuhan Allah pung parenta. Ju dia sunat. Ais dia sunat sang Ismael deng samua laki-laki dalam dia pung ruma. Dia ju sunat budak laki-laki dong samua. Itu waktu, Abraham su umur 99 taon, deng Ismael umur 13 taon.<bt>That day, Abraham followed right away Lord God's command. He got circumcised. Then he circumcised Ismael, and all the males in his house. He also circumcised all the male slaves. At that time, Abraham was already 99 years old, and Ismael was 13 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yamal (mwl narr): he circumcised bʿetsem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yamal (mwl narr): he circumcised bʿetsem: in bone; complete identity, that very day<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>meʾet ben nekhar: bought from a foreigner End of P section.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tiga orang datang katumu deng Abraham<bt>Three people come and meet with Abraham</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="18" />
      <v n="1" />Satu waktu, Abraham ada tenga deka pohon-pohon bésar di Mamre. TUHAN datang kasi tunju diri sang dia di situ. Dia pung carita bagini: itu hari panas mau mati, jadi Abraham dudu cari angin di muka tenda.<bt>One time, Abraham was living near the big trees at Mamre. The LORD had come and revealed Himself to him there. The story goes like this: That day was very hot, so Abraham was sitting relaxing (&lt;looking for wind) in front of the tent.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Begins a new Seder (major division"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Begins a new Seder (major division to give a three-year reading cycle, S section) ʾelon: big tree, species not specified, usually taken as oak or terebinth<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>kəchom: at the hottest part of the day [JEG] Pagan worship here is superfluous. Still, the worship was for real. A place for divination, if not sacrifice. 13:18 identifies them as "sacred"; So Abram moved his camp and settled near the sacred trees of Mamre at Hebron, and there he built an altar to the LORD. BDB: Terebinth, oak. (ASV and RSV usually translate "oak" with a marginal note "terebinth." The KJV erroneously translates as "plain.") It is generally conceded to be the same as )e4la=. The tree figures often in Abraham's travels (Gen 12:6; 13:18; 14:13; 18:1). A noted one is mentioned near Ebal and Gerizim (Deut 11:30). The RSV translates the term on one occasion "divining Oak" (Jud 9:37), while ASV follows KJV in translating "the oak of Meonenim." Apparently certain such trees became so famous as landmarks that they were generally recognized by all as suitable for specifying rendezvous. But all that doesn't enter into the story at this point.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Waktu Abraham angka muka, ju dia dapa lia ada tiga orang badiri di sana. Ju dia lari pi sambut sang dong capát-capát. Dia tikam lutut,<bt>When Abraham lifted his face [not a Hebraism], he saw three people standing there. So he ran quickly to greet/welcome them. He bowed1 (&lt;pierce knees),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitstsavim ʿalaw (nif ptcpl): who had"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nitstsavim ʿalaw (nif ptcpl): who had taken their stand. If they had walked up, he probably would have seen them coming from miles away. Sounds like they appeared out of nowhere. yarats: he ran<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vayishtakhu (khwh hishtafal): bown down deeply ʾartsah: to the ground? toward the earth?<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />ais bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa-bapa dong! Kalo bisa, na, bapa dong singga tahan di beta pung tenda dolo. Biar cuma minum aer kosong sa, ju bae.<bt>and said, &lt;&lt;Fathers (coll.)! If you can, na, father (collective) stop in temporarily at my tent now. Even if [you] just drink plain water (&lt;empty water = whatever is available, phrase of hospitality), that's fine.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aer kosong = whatever is available"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">aer kosong = whatever is available</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾadonai: Lord, Master, polite vocative. With"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾadonai: Lord, Master, polite vocative. With qamets on the last syllable rather than petach, could be "my lords"; but bʿenekha later in the verse is singular chen: favorable attitude<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʾal-naʾ taʿvor: lest you go on past (Middle East courtesy with a flourish). Josephus comments on the misoxenia of the people of Sodom, unwilling to share and eager to exploit; this is a great example of philoxenia, willingness to share. Jacques Ellul, The Meaning of the City, uses Babylon as a symbol of people making their own creation without reference to God.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Bapa dong barenti cape di bawa sombar. Nanti ana-ana dong ame aer ko datang cuci bapa dong pung kaki.<bt>Father (collective) rest under the shade. The underlings will fetch water to come and wash father (collective)'s feet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yuqach-naʾ (lqch qal impv impf): please"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yuqach-naʾ (lqch qal impv impf): please take mʾat: a little bit<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>rachətsu: wash hishshaʿənu (nif impv): stretch out and rest<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Nanti beta pi sadia makan kasi bapa dong, ko dapa kuat sadiki, baru bapa dong jalan tarús. Te beta sanáng bisa layani sang bapa dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will go prepare food for father (collective), so [you] can get a little strength, only-then father (collective) continue going. Cuz (elaboration) I'm happy to be able to serve father (collective).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais ju dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu. Makasi bam-banya. Botong singga.&gt;&gt;<bt>So they answered saying, &lt;&lt;That's fine. Thank you. We'll(exc) stop in.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="fat: little bit Saʿədu libkhem (imperv):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">fat: little bit Saʿədu libkhem (imperv): strengthen yourselves, support<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>ʾachar taʾvoru: later you will go on</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ais Abraham lari pi tenda, deng kasi tau sang Sara bilang, &lt;&lt;Capát! Ame tarigu yang paling bae satu sak, ko bekin roti.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Abraham ran to the tent, and told Sara saying, &lt;&lt;Quick! Get the best flour, one sack, to make bread.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shlosh Səʾim: three seahs = 21"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shlosh Səʾim: three seahs = 21 liters = about five gallons = capacity of an oversize bucket, more than three or four people could possibly eat qemach Solet loshi: knead up some wheat flour ground fine from the inner kernels of the wheat. Same quality as God prescribed later for the Bread of the Presence.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʿugot: several circular, flat bread like modern pita bread, baked in ashes or on top of hot stones; pita bread, thick flour tortillas</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;ame tarigu tiga <span class="Italic">seah</span>&gt;. Tiga seah tu, sama deng satu sak tarigu (20-25 kilogram).<bt>The Hebrew language says &lt;get three <span class="Italic">seah</span> of flour&gt;. Those three saehs is like a single sack of flour (20-25 kilograms).</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais dia lari pi dia pung sapi dong, ko dia pili ame sapi ana satu yang gumuk. Ais dia suru dia pung hamba ko horo itu sapi, deng masa dia pung daging.<bt>Then he hurried to his cattle, to select a fat cow offspring. Then he ordered his servant/slave to cut that cow, and cook its meat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sapi montok (BI) = gumuk (gumuk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sapi montok (BI) = gumuk (gumuk preferred by UNS);</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baqar: herd rakh: tender, delicate. A"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">baqar: herd rakh: tender, delicate. A full-grown cow would have to hang a while after butchering before they could eat the meat; the meat of a calf could be fixed right away because it's still tender.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Tarús Abraham pi ame susu, keju, deng daging yang baru masa tu, ais dia bawa kasi itu tamu dong. Waktu dong makan, dia badiri di bawa pohon ko layani sang dong.<bt>Straightaway Abraham went and fetched mild, cheese, and meat that had just been cookded, and he brought it to those guests. When they ate, he stood under [a/the] tree to serve them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chemʾah: curdled milk, almost like yogurt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chemʾah: curdled milk, almost like yogurt (like Isaiah's curds and honey) ʿalehem: like he's hovering over them, waiting on them like a waiter.<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais dong tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Lu pung bini Sara, di mana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they asked him saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Your wife, Sara, is where?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Di dalam tenda.&gt;&gt;<bt>He answered saying, &lt;&lt;Inside the tent.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾelayw: to him. This is one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾelayw: to him. This is one of 15 instances of the word marked with four diamonds. Whether the Masoretes thought it should be deleted, or posed a doctrinal problem, nobody is sure. ʾayyeh: where?<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00655c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Sara dengar dari balakang pintu<bt>Sara listens from behind the door</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ju satu dari dong tiga omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kira-kira taon datang, Beta kambali. Itu waktu, lu pung bini Sara su barana ame satu ana laki-laki.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then one of the three spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Approximately in the coming year, I will return. At that time, your wife Sara will already have given birth to a son.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taon datang ~ taon muka ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">taon datang ~ taon muka ; su bobot tana = tua sakali (Idiom)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu dong omong bagitu, Sara ada dengar dari balakang pintu.<bt>When he spoke like that, Sara was listening from behind the door.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿet: time, same time; OK for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿet: time, same time; OK for the yearly cycle, or only the daily cycle? chayyah: alive, but ʿet chayyah "the same time next year"<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>huʾ ʾacharaw (read as hiʾ): she was behind him -- Abraham canʾt see Sarah.</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Itu waktu, Abraham deng Sara memang su talalu tua, deng Sara ju su barenti datang bulan.<bt>At the time, Abraham and Sara were really already very old, and Sara had already had menopause (&lt;stopped coming month).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="datang bulan = period, haid ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">datang bulan = period, haid ; barenti datang bulan = menopause</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʾim bayamim: who were getting along"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">baʾim bayamim: who were getting along in years chadal: it had ceased, gone<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʾorakh kanashim: the manner of women; past the menopause kanashim: archaic genitive (Frank Anderson)<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Dengar dong omong bagitu, ju Sara katawa dalam hati. Ju dia pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;Awe'! Beta su tua kakaluk bagini, deng beta pung laki su mamalek. Mana ko botong masi kapingin jadi panganten baru, ko cari ana lai?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing them talk like that, Sara laughed in her liver. And she thought, &lt;&lt;Awe! I'm already old and wrinkled, and my man/husband is already withered. How is it that we-exc could still desire to be like newlyweds, to try again for children?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bqirbah: the inward part of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bqirbah: the inward part of the body, considered the seat of laughter. Probably positive; it's so neat that now it's really going to happen! But other commentators think she is laughing in disbelief, at how preposterous the idea is, which may fit better with taking V. 13 as a reprimand. bloti: I am all used up, worn out, exhausted<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʿednah: pleasure, including sexual, but can be the joy of having a baby</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ais TUHAN tanya sang Abraham bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko Sara katawa? Dia pikir apa yang Beta omong ni, sonde bisa jadi, tagal dia su tua, ko?<bt>Then the LORD asked Abraham saying, &lt;&lt;Why did Sara laugh? Is it that she thinks what I am saying can't happen, because she is already old, or what?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʾaf (intrj): even ʾumnam: really?|i(13) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haʾaf (intrj): even ʾumnam: really?<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Beta ni, TUHAN! Sonde ada yang Beta sonde bisa bekin! Inga bae-bae, é! Nanti kalo Beta kambali di sini taon datang, Sara su barana ame satu ana laki-laki.&gt;&gt;<bt>I am the LORD! There is nothing that I cannot do! Pay attention, é! Later when I return here in the coming year, Sara will have already given birth to a son.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həyippaleʾ (nif imperf): is it difficult,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">həyippaleʾ (nif imperf): is it difficult, too hard lmoʿed: on the fixed day<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Dengar bagitu, ju Sara taku. Ais dia manyangkal bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta sonde katawa, ma!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, Sara was afraid. So she denied it saying, &lt;&lt;I didn't laugh, [+protest]&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Tuhan manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu tadi memang katawa, ma.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the Lord answered saying, &lt;&lt;You did laugh just now, [+protest]&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tkhachesh (piʿel): she denied it yareʾah:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tkhachesh (piʿel): she denied it yareʾah: she was afraid<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham kokoe ame sang Tuhan ko jang hukum orang Sodom<bt>Abraham coaxes (process, not result) the Lord to not punish the Sodom people</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="grasi = grace (like Tommy Suharto"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">grasi = grace (like Tommy Suharto seeking reprieve from jail sentence) (seen as BI)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais, itu tiga tamu dong barangkat mau pi kota Sodom. Ju Abraham antar sang dong sampe di tenga jalan. Dari situ, dong bisa dapa lia kota Sodom.<bt>Then, the three guests departed wanting to go to the city of Sodom. And Abraham escorted them until halfway (=not precise). From there, they could see the city of Sodom.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaqumu (narr construct): they stood up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaqumu (narr construct): they stood up vayashqifu ʿal-pney (hif narr): they looked out over the edge of the hill and down toward Sodom. ʿal-pney: taking in the whole scene, which was not very far away<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>lshalləcham (piʿel inf): to see them on their way -- politeness. Next morning he goes back to the same spot.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ais TUHAN omong dalam hati bilang, &lt;&lt;Lebe bae, Beta carita kasi Abraham, kalo Beta mau kasi ancor kota Sodom.<bt>Then the LORD spoke to himself (in his liver) saying, &lt;&lt;It would be good if I tell Abraham that I am going to destroy the city of Sodom. [EXEG: Heb /ʕoseh/ (ptcpl): “the thing I am about to be doing”. I think we had something vague and literal like that in early versions, but UNS's linked their answers to verses 18-19 which are actually just background explanation for why Abraham should even be considered worthy of God's counsel at all. Technically, in vs. 20-21 God is only talking about a plan to check it out, but if you continue on to vs.23ff. it is unambiguously clear to Abraham from what he heard in vs.20-21 that God is going to destroy the cities. To avoid the confusion we were getting with the UNS's we've linked it to the higher level context explicitly.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** deleted mangkali, from Amarasi check"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** deleted mangkali, from Amarasi check Oct 2005</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yhwh: yhwah with double dot over"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yhwh: yhwah with double dot over w in 18:1 different from vayhwah here with single dot over w and circle over h. The circle (Massora parva) indexes the Massora magna, a type of concordance listing for this word. The double dot in 18:1 is the cholem (o) plus the single dot. say to himself, think to himself - not out loud. "Yahweh had wondered." Some Jewish authors think this is an informal meeting of the heavenly council.<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʿoseh (ptcpl): not eventive - the thing I am about to be doing hamkhaSSeh (piʿel ptcpl): keep something secret from somebody. Amos says that prophets are told the secrets of God, so this scene validates Abraham as a prophet. (rabbinical view)<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te dia pung turunan nanti tamba banya, deng jadi bangsa yang hebat. Dia nanti jadi berkat kasi sang samua suku-bangsa di ini dunya ju.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) his descendants will increase, and become many noteworthy races/people. And he will later be/become a blessing to all the peoples of the world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hayo (hyh inf): being ʿatsum: mighty,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hayo (hyh inf): being ʿatsum: mighty, powerful. Tanakh "populous, mighty in numbers"<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>nivrkhu (nif): they will wish for themselves blessing like Abraham's (= Gen 12:3) bo: Abraham takes on an iconic stature<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Beta su pili ame sang dia, ko ajar dia pung ana-ana deng orang laen dong, iko tarús TUHAN pung jalan, ko dong idop lurus deng jujur. Kalo dong bekin bagitu, Beta bekin jadi Beta pung janji deng Abraham.&gt;&gt;<bt>I have chosen him, to teach/instruct his children and other people, to follow the LORD's way continually, so they will live straight and honestly. If they do that, I will fulfill (&lt;make be) My promise with Abraham.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ydaʿtiw: select, choose, take up his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ydaʿtiw: select, choose, take up his cause; singled him out, entered into a special relationship lmaʿan ʾasher: in order that<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>beto: children and household both ytsawweh (tswh piʿel): appoint, order<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>shamru derekh yhwh: they will keep the way of the Lord. Derekh Yʾ -- how much does Abraham know of it at this point? The Sodom people know general moral things. The Way of the Lord is introduced here, in Psalm 1, and elsewhere in the Torah. umishpat: legal decisions<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>habiʾ (hif): bring diber (piʿel): he told him. The angel of the Lord speaks like Yahweh, and speaks about him -- if this is not a theophany. Or there may be seams in the redaction.<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ais TUHAN kasi tau sang Abraham bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Beta su dengar orang banya dong mangomek so'al orang dari kota Sodom deng Gomora. Dong pung jahat, su talalu kalewat.<bt>Then the LORD told Abraham saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! (=I have s.t. to tell you) I have heard many people complaining about the people from the cities of Sodom and Gomora. There evil, is already too past-limit.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zaʿqat: cry for help chaTTaʾtam: their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">zaʿqat: cry for help chaTTaʾtam: their sin<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>khavdah: heavy, grievous, weighty</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Andia ko Beta turun, ko mau pareksa sandiri, samua yang Beta su dengar tu, batúl ko sonde. Kalo sonde, nanti Beta musti dapa tau.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why I have come down, to investigate for myself, everything that I have heard, [whether] true or not. If not, I must know it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾerədah-naʾ: I am going down naʾ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾerədah-naʾ: I am going down naʾ: urgency, politeness<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>hakətsaʿəqatah: the fact that they are calling for help. Who is calling for help? Probably visitors to Sodom who are being treated like Lot and the angels, wronged victims of the Sodom people. In Sodom they may have had a policy of denying hospitality vigorously so as not to attract strangers, whom they despised. kalah: completion (fo real), destruction<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Waktu TUHAN masi ba'omong deng Abraham, itu dua tamu dong jalan tarús pi kota Sodom.<bt>When the LORD was still speaking with Abraham, those two guests continued walking on to the city of Sodom.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayifnu: they turned, went on ʿodenu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayifnu: they turned, went on ʿodenu (ʿod 3sg): still<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Abraham pi deka-deka sang Tuhan, ais kokoe bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana? Bapa mau kasi ancor orang bae deng orang jahat sama-sama, ko?<bt>Abraham approache close to the Lord, and coaxed saying, &lt;&lt;How about it? Will father destroy the good people and the evil people together?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayigash (ngsh): he stepped up to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayigash (ngsh): he stepped up to make a case, like a plaintiff before a judge haʾaf: even<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>tispeh: you will sweep away, snatch</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Kalo ada 50 orang bae dalam itu kota, Bapa masi mau kasi ancor sang dong samua ju, ko? Ko, Bapa sonde kasi ancor itu kota tagal dong.<bt>If there are 50 good people in that city, will Father still destroy all of them as well? Or Father will not destroy the city, because of them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear; perhaps? haʾaf: also, even: addition, emphasis, ascending importance, contrast ʾand yetʾ, implied question<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>tispeh: wipe them out, sweep away the place vloʾtisaʾ (nsʾ): lift up [someone's head = pardon them]; and will not pardon them<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Bapa jang kasi ancor sang dong bagitu! Jang sampe itu orang bae dong ju iko mati, tagal Bapa mau kasi ancor orang jahat dong. Bapa yang jadi Hakim di ini langit deng bumi. Deng Bapa sandiri su tau kalo itu sonde adil.&gt;&gt;<bt>Father should not destroy them like that! It should not be that the good people are also killed, because Father wants to destroy the evil people. Father is the one who is Judge in heaven and earth. And Father himself already knows that that is not just/fair.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: I think we were forced to go to this “heaven-earth” rendering because literal skews the focus. The well-documented dualism in the cultures of eastern Indonesia, and corresponding parallelisms in the lgs, automatically evokes the pair “heaven-earth”. So saying only “earth” raised questions and implications that He is not judge in “heaven”, somebody else is. This rendering better deals with the immediate context, the higher-level context (supernatural judgment), and local worldview.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chalilah: with min + infinitive, far"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chalilah: with min + infinitive, far be it from you to do such a thing. From chll ‘profane’. Always adversive (Holladay). ləhamiyt (mwt hif inf cs): for you to kill. Waltke &amp; OʾConnor [536] "The wəqatalti construction [wəhayah] after an infinitive construct [ləhamiyt] functions in ways similar to those we have observed in connection with other leading verbs. The line between an apodosis and a consequent situation is often fuzzy in the construction. The examples can be taken as conditional sentences ..." The translation is "to kill the righteous with the wicked AND SO the righteous BECOME as the wicked." For k- ʾasʾ [642], "The particle k- can be used with two compared things, the effect being that the situation of one of them is likened to that of the other" and they translate "And the state of the righteous would be like the state of the wicked."<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>shofet: the one judging, the judge mishpaT: judgment, sentence, decision. Your job is to uphold the distinction between good and bad people. Same stem as shofet; being a judge means maintaining the difference between right and wrong.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />TUHAN manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo Beta dapa 50 orang bae di kota Sodom, Beta sonde hukum itu kota, tagal dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>The LORD answered saying, &lt;&lt;If I get/find 50 good people in the city of Sodom, I will not punish that city, because of them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʿvuram: on account of them, for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">baʿvuram: on account of them, for the sake of them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ju Abraham omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa, minta ampon, kalo beta bisa omong sadiki lai. Beta ni, cuma manusia bodo yang sonde tau apa-apa.<bt>Straightaway Abraham spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;Father, forgive me, if I could just speak a little more. I here, am only a dumb/stupid/uneducated human, who doesn't know anything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʿan (ʿnh): came back at him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaʿan (ʿnh): came back at him, replied, responded, picked up on what God said. He's sticking his neck out hoʾalti (yʾl hif): make a beginning, said politely and modestly, go on to do something else<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʿafar vaʾefer: dirt particles on the ground and loose soil crumbling to dust (put on the head as a sign of mourning)</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Andekata sonde sampe 50 orang bae, ma cuma dapa 45 sa, karmana? Kalo kurang lima orang sa, Bapa masi mau bekin ancor itu kota, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>If-perchance they don't reach 50 good people, but only find just 45, how about it? If there is only lacking just five people, will father still destroy the city, or what?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tuhan manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo Beta dapa 45 orang bae di situ, na, Beta sonde bekin ancor itu kota.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Lord answered saying, &lt;&lt;If I find 45 good people there, na, I won't destroy that city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachsrun: they wonʾt make it, there"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yachsrun: they wonʾt make it, there will be a lack of five of the good people htashchit: will you ruin, spoil<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʾashchit: will destroy, needs explicit object or will be taken as destroying the good people</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ais Abraham kokoe lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo cuma dapa 40 orang sa, karmana, Bapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham coaxed again saying, &lt;&lt;If you only find just 40 people, how about it, Father?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo Beta dapa 40, Beta sonde hukum sang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He answered saying, &lt;&lt;If I find 40, I will not punish them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayosef ʿod: and he went on,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayosef ʿod: and he went on, added, continued d yimatsʾun (nif): are found<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Abraham kokoe tarús lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa jang mara, ma andekata cuma 30 orang bae sa, karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Abraham continued to coax again saying, &lt;&lt;Father don't be angry (=apologies), but if-perchance only just 30 good people, how about it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo Beta dapa 30 orang, Beta sonde jadi hukum sang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>He answered saying, &lt;&lt;If I find 30, I will not punish them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar (chrh): become hot, become angry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yichar (chrh): become hot, become angry</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ais Abraham tawar lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa jang mara kalo beta tanya lai sadiki. Kalo cuma dapa 20 orang sa, karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham bargained again saying, Father don't be angry if I ask a bit more. If only find just 20 people, how about it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Dia manyao lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo dapa 20 orang, Beta sonde akan kasi ancor itu kota.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He answered again saying, &lt;&lt;If I find 20, I will not destroy that city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hineh-naʾ: look, again ... hoʾalti ldaber:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hineh-naʾ: look, again ... hoʾalti ldaber: take up the matter, push ahead, go on<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ju Abraham konci dia pung omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! Beta omong satu kali lai, ma jang mara sang beta, ó! Karmana kalo cuma dapa 10 orang bae sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>The Abraham closed (&lt;locked) what he had to say saying, &lt;&lt;Father! I will speak one more time, but don't be angry with me, ó! How about if only find just 10 good people?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo Beta dapa 10 orang bae di situ, Beta sonde kasi ancor itu kota.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He answered saying, &lt;&lt;If I find 10 good people there, I will not destroy that city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾakh: only, surely, nevertheless ʾakh happaʿam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾakh: only, surely, nevertheless ʾakh happaʿam: only this one time<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ba'omong abis bagitu, TUHAN jalan tarús, ais Abraham pulang.<bt>After RECIP-speaking in that way, the LORD continued on, and Abraham went home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="killah (klh piʿel): he finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">killah (klh piʿel): he finished</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Orang Sodom dong pung jahat<bt>The evil of the Sodom people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />Waktu Tuhan masi ba'omong deng Abraham, Dia pung ana bua dua pi tarús di kota Sodom. Dong sampe di sana, ju matahari su mau tanggalám. Itu waktu, Lot masi dudu di kota pung pintu maso.<bt>When the Lord was still speaking with Abraham, His two underlings went on to the city of Sodom. [When] they arrived there, the sun was going down. At that time, Lot was still sitting at the gate of the city.</bt><note reference="19:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dolu-dolu, kota pung pintu maso, jadi tampa orang tua-tua dong dudu ko putus parkara, ju dong ba'omong di situ.<bt>Long ago, at the city gate, the respected elders sat to decide disputes and to chat there.</bt></note>Dapa lia itu dua orang, ju dia pi sambut sang dong. Tarús dia tikam lutut deng tondo di dong pung muka.<bt>When He saw those two people, he went to greet/welcome them. Then he kneeld and bowed in front of them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vlot: first in sentence, marked, possibly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vlot: first in sentence, marked, possibly emphasizing "at just the time when the angels came, Lot was there." shaʿar: city gate, the place where the prominent people talked over and decided all the affairs of the city. Possibly Lot was there so he could rescue strangers from the Sodom welcoming committee. (Canʾt prove it, and it doesn't affect the translation; but it does fit in with 2 Peter 2:7, "God rescued Lot out of Sodom because he was a good man who was sick of all the immorality around him.")<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayakam (qal qwm): got up, stood up vayishtakhu (khwh hisht) he bowed down deeply, all the way to the ground<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʾafayim (ʾaf dual): his nose, nostrils, the area around his nose, his face</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ais dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa dong! Mari ko singga tahan di beta pung ruma dolo. Biar ko bapa dong cuci kaki, ais tidor di sana. Nanti beso papagi, baru bapa dong jalan tarús.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers! Come stop in a bit at my house. You can wash your feet, and sleep there. Then later early tomorrow morning, only-then should fathers continue on.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Tarima kasi. Ma sonde usa repot! Biar botong tidor di kota pung tana lapang sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But they answered saying, &lt;&lt;Thank you. But don't trouble yourself. Let us-exc just sleep in the city's open-space [town field used for ball games, parades, ceremonies and public gatherings].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾadonai (pl): my lords (to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾadonai (pl): my lords (to the two) suru (swr imperv pl): turn aside from your road<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>linu (lwn imperv): spend the night, remain over. Washing the feet is mentioned after staying the night, possibly as a detail of what "staying the night" entails. Raki thinks the order is iconic with time, so that Lot can say "they have just arrived and havenʾt even had time to wash their feet yet." But in Pidgin the washing needs to come before the sleeping or it doesn't make sense. rachətsu (imperv): wash<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vhishkamtem (shkm hif): you get up early, load up for travel rkhov: in the open public square or plaza, just inside the gate (not "in the street"). This was part of God's test of Sodom's people.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ma Lot kokoe tarús sang dong, sampe dong mau manumpang di dia pung ruma. Ais Lot dong bakar roti deng ator meja, ju dong makan rame-rame.<bt>But Lot continued to coax them, until they agreed to overnight at his house. So then Lot baked bread and prepare the table, and they ate festively/together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiftsar-bam: urged them strongly vayasuru: they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiftsar-bam: urged them strongly vayasuru: they turned aside, stopped off at his house<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>mishteh: drinks for a feast, prepare a feast with wine matsot: unleavened bread, no yeast. It could be prepared quite fast, whereas regular bread with sourdough or yeast would take a long time to rise before it could be baked. At the time of the Exodus, five centuries later, unleavened bread took on religious symbolism, and yeast became a symbol for sin; but in Abraham's time there is no evidence of either -- Lot was in a hurry, that's all. Sarah the day before had had a lot more time for her breadmaking.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʾafah: he baked. Not enough time to raise dought with yeast. Raki thinks it was a Passover type of celebration, but there too the reason for unleavened bread was the urgency of the situation, not the symbolism of purification from sin that was attached to it at Sinai.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Itu tamu dong balóm pi tidor, te laki-laki Sodom dong, kici-bésar samua, datang kuliling Lot pung ruma.<bt>Those guests had not yet gone to sleep, and the males of Sodom, both young and old (&lt;small-large), came surrounding Lot's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ron = round, surround (not known"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ron = round, surround (not known by all, but by Max)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Terem + imperfect = before they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Terem + imperfect = before they Xed Terem yishkavu: before they lay down<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>vʾanshey haʿiyr ʾanshey Sədom: why the doubling? Actually four references to the subject. Too much for Pidgin. naSabu (Sbb nif): surrounded<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>miqqatseh: to the end = every last man in town, or all the people clear out to the outskirts of town</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Dong batarea kasar-kasar sang Lot bilang, &lt;&lt;He, Lot! Itu laki-laki dua tadi di mana? Kasi kaluar sang dong datang, te botong mau nae sang dong!&gt;&gt;<bt>They shouted coursely to Lot saying, &lt;&lt;He, Lot! Where are those two men earlier? Send them outside here, cuz (elaboration) we want to mount them!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="makaroroak = loudly ; baku nae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">makaroroak = loudly ; baku nae = mount sexually ; maen seks has connotations of professional sex worker ; Mus objects to this rendering ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾayyeh: where? with nouns, not verbs;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾayyeh: where? with nouns, not verbs; where is ...? hotsiʾem (ytsʾ hif): make them come out, bring them out<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>nedʿah (ydʿ 1pl cohortative): let us know them = euphemism for sodomy, have homosexual sex with them. The antithesis of hospitality; gang rape would not have been tolerated anywhere, though homosexuality was known. Suggested by some Jewish scholars that the cities were wealthy, and did this kind of thing to keep strangers away (misoxena), so as not to spend their money on them. NIV and NLT use "make sex."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00651c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:right">Lot omong deng orang Sodom dong<bt>Lot speaks to the people of Sodom</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Tarús Lot kaluar, ais tutu pintu.<bt>Right away, Lot went out, and closed the door.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="petchah: entrance, location to go in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">petchah: entrance, location to go in through delet: door, piece that moves<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>sagar: shut something (doesn't need et-)</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Sodara dong! Bosong jang bekin jahat bagitu deng beta pung tamu.<bt>He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Siblings! You-PL shouldn't do evil like that to my guests.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾachai: my kinsmen (which they werenʾt)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾachai: my kinsmen (which they werenʾt) tareʿu (rʿʿ imperf 2pl): do something bad. "Do no harm" has been suggested, but their reaction shows that they take loʾ tareʿu as fighting words.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Bosong coba dengar, é? Beta pung ana nona dua orang. Dong masi parawan. Biar beta kasi dong dua sang bosong. Bosong mau bekin apa sang dong, tarsará sa. Ma bosong jang bekin apa-apa deng beta pung tamu. Te iko kotong pung adat, beta musti jaga babae sang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>You-PL listen up, é? I have two daughters. They are still *virgins. You may do whatever, it's up to you. But you should not do anything to my guests. Cuz (elaboration) according to our-inc customs, I must protect them well.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾotsiʾa naʾ (ytsʾ cohortative): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾotsiʾa naʾ (ytsʾ cohortative): I will make them come out, let me bring them out katov bʿenekhem: usually means that anything goes, not that they are to consider the moral consequences<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>raq: only baʾu: implicit cultural obligation to make sure one's guests are safe when they are with him, needs to be made explicit for Local culture. He's trying to protect the men.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>btsel: to the shade qorati: the beams of my house = my house; under the shadow of my roof beam<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ma itu orang Sodom dong batarea bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu jang iko campor! Te lu ni, cuma orang manumpang sa di sini! Lu orang luar, jadi lu sonde ada hak ator sang botong. Lebe bae lu iskarobis dari sini. Kalo sonde, botong bekin sang lu lebe barát dari itu dua orang!&gt;&gt; Ais dong tola buang sang Lot, ju dong rame-rame pi tabrak, ko mau bekin ancor itu pintu.<bt>But the people of Sodom shouted saying, &lt;&lt;You should not mix (=butt in to this matter). Cuz (elaboration) you here, are only just an immigrant here! You are an outsider, so you have no right to organise us-exc. It would be better if you scram from here. If not, we'll do you worse (&lt;heavier) than those two people.&gt;&gt; So they shoved Lot back, and they rushed forward to smash into and destroy the door.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dobrak = BI or Kupang?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">dobrak = BI or Kupang?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gesh halʾah: stand back, get out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gesh halʾah: stand back, get out of the way ngsh: step forward, step away?<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>halʾah: to there, farther haʾechad: the one, this guy, this character<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yishpoT: he is acting as judge naraʿ (rʿʿ hif 1pl): we will do evil to you<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>mehem: more evil to you than to them vayiftsru: they urged him strongly<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>baʾiysh bəloT: why the duplication? lishbor: to break down the door, smash it (the door, not Lot)<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ma itu dua tamu sorong tangan ko hela kasi maso sang Lot pi dalam ruma, ju dong konci pintu.<bt>But those two guests reached out their hands to pull Lot into the house, and then they locked the door.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaviyʾu (bwʾ hif): they brought him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaviyʾu (bwʾ hif): they brought him into the house sagaru: shut<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ais dong dua bekin buta itu orang Sodom dong pung mata, sampe dong raba-raba cari pintu, ma sonde dapa.<bt>Then the two of them made blind the Sodom people's eyes, to-point-that they were groping for the door, but they couldn't find it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="petach: at the doorway hikku (nkh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">petach: at the doorway hikku (nkh hif): strike someone with a disability<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>baSSanwerim: in dazzling light miqqaton: from the insiginificant ones to the great ones<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>vayilʾu (lʾh): they gave up, got tired of doing it (the men from the town)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan kasi kaluar Lot dong dari Sodom<bt>God2 brings Lot (collective) out from Sodom</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** Sep 2004, Dhao check"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** Sep 2004, Dhao check</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-13" />Ais ju itu dua tamu omong deng Lot bilang, &lt;&lt;Lot! TUHAN su tau ini kota pung jahat. Jadi Dia kirim sang botong datang ko mau kasi ancor bekin abis ini kota. Jadi lu masi ada pung kelu laen di ini kota, ko sonde? Kalo ada ana laki-laki, ko parampuan, ko ana mantu, ko sapa sa, na, pi ame bawa sang dong kaluar dari ini kota su!&gt;&gt;<bt>And then, those two guests spoke with Lot saying, &lt;&lt;Lot! The LORD already knows the evil of this city. [check personification]. So (consequently) He sent us here to destroy this city. So (consequently) do you have any more kin in this city, or not? If there is a son, or daughter, or child-in-law, or whoever, na, go get them [and] bring them out of this city now!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿod mi-lkha: is there still anybody"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿod mi-lkha: is there still anybody else with you poh: here<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>chatan: related by marriage (a son-in-law, bridegroom) baneykha: your sons<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>banoteykha: your daughters mashchatim (shcht hif partcpl): ones who are going to destroy. Participles for things about to take place, but the events havenʾt actually occurred yet<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>tsaʿəqatam: their cries for help (the victims of Sodom) lshachtah: to ruin it, spoil it, wipe it out. The final -h with dagesh is marked as a feminine suffix (for haʿir). With a locative -h, the accent would never be on the last syllable.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Tarús Lot pi katumu dia pung calon ana mantu dua orang, ais dia kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Dengar bae-bae! Sakarang bosong kaluar capát-capát dari ini kota suda, te TUHAN su mau bekin ancor sang dia!&gt;&gt; Ma dong kira Lot cuma omong maen gila sa.<bt>Right away, Lot went [and] met with his two candidate sons-in-law, and he told them, syaing, &lt;&lt;Listen up! Now you need to quickly leave this city, cuz (elaboration) the LORD already is about to destroy it!&gt;&gt; But they thought that Lot was just kidding.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loqche bnotaw: in the process of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">loqche bnotaw: in the process of taking his daughters soon. Unusual expression. Were these engaged to become his sons-in-law, or were they married to two other daughters who did not live with him? Probably the first. mashchit (shcht hif partcpl): imminent destruction<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ki-mtsacheq (tschq piʿel partcpl): he was joking, mocking at them. REB "they did not take him seriously"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Dia pung beso papagi, ju Tuhan pung ana bua dua orang tu, paksa sang Lot ko dong kaluar capát-capát suda. Dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Lot! Bangun suda! Hela bawa lu pung bini, deng itu ana parampuan dua-dua, ko bosong lari suda. Kasi tenga ini kota. Jang sampe bosong mati bodo-bodo, deng ancor sama-sama deng ini kota.&gt;&gt;<bt>Early the next morning, the two undelrings of the Lord, forced/pressed Lot to leave immediately. They said, &lt;&lt;Lot! Get up! Drag away your wife, and both your daughters, to flee now. Leave this city behind. May you not (&lt;don't to-point-that) you-pl die from stupidity/pointlessly, and get destroyed along with this city.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mati bodo-bodo = mati parcuma"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">mati bodo-bodo = mati parcuma</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khmo: k- proclitic participle of comparison,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">khmo: k- proclitic participle of comparison, as hashshakhor: the reddish light before dawn, very early<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʿalah: was going up vayaʾitsu (ʾwts hif): they urged, tried to hurry<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>hanimtsaʾot (mtsʾ nif partcpl fem pl): the ones who happen to be, who are found here - the two daughters and the wife (does this mean that the sons-in-law lived elsewhere with two other daughters?) pen-tiSSəfeh (Sph nif): lest you get snatched away<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʿəwon: activity that is wrong, sin, guilt, punishment</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ma Lot masi ba'eok. Padahal TUHAN mau kasi salamat sang dia. Andia ko itu tamu dua-dua pegang dong pung tangan ko hela sang Lot, dia pung bini, deng dia pung ana parampuan dua, ko bawa kaluar sang dong dari itu kota.<bt>But Lot kept delaying. Whereas the LORD wanted to save him. That is why both the guests held their hands and pulled Lot, his wife, and his two daughters, outside away from that city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ba'eok = delay, baputar, sibuk dgn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ba'eok = delay, baputar, sibuk dgn urusan yg tidak penting.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitmahmah (mhh hitpalpel): delayed, lingered, fiddled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yitmahmah (mhh hitpalpel): delayed, lingered, fiddled around, dawdled, dithered yachziqu (chzq hif): take hold, seize, grab, strong-arm somebody<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>bchemlat: by the compassion, forbearance yotsiʾuhu (ytsʾ hif): they caused him to go out<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>nichuhu (nwch hif): they caused him to settle down, give rest</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Tarús satu dari itu dua tamu parenta bilang, &lt;&lt;Lari capát-capát, ko cari salamat suda! Jang lia pi balakang! Jang barenti di lemba! Lari nae tarús pi gunung sana, ko biar bosong jang mati!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then one of the two guests commanded saying, &lt;&lt;Run quickly, to try and get safe now! Don't look backwards! Don't stop in the valley! Keep running up that mountain over there, so you won't get killed!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hotsiʾam (ytsʾ hif inf): as they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hotsiʾam (ytsʾ hif inf): as they got them out hachutsah: to the outside [of town]<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>himmaleT (mlT nif imperv): get yourself to safety for your life, escape, run for your life ʾal-tabbit (nbt hif): donʾt look in a specific direction, behind you<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʾal-taʿmod: donʾt stand still, stop, stay bkhol hakikar: in any of the environs<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ma Lot balas bilang, &lt;&lt;Aduu, pak! Jang bagitu!<bt>But Lot responded saying, &lt;&lt;Aduu, mister! Don't let it be like that!</bt><v n="19" />Pak memang su tolong kasi salamat sang botong. Ma itu gunung talalu jao! Jang-jangan botong balóm sampe di sana, te bahaya su buru dapa sang botong di tenga jalan.<bt>Mister has realy helped make us-exc safe. But that mountain is too far! May it not be that we have not yet arrived there, and the danger has overchased us along the way.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsaʾ ʿavdəkha chen bʿeyneykha: has found"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">matsaʾ ʿavdəkha chen bʿeyneykha: has found favor in your eyes, treated me with favor chasdəkha: loyalty, solidarity, faithfulness<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ləhachəyot (hyh hif inf): to preserve me alive pen-tidbaqani: so it wonʾt fasten itself on me, cling to me, stick<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>matiy: I die</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Pak lia dolo. Ada satu kampong kici sonde jao dari sini. Itu kampong sonde ada pung arti apa-apa. Jadi kalo pak mau, na, biar botong pi cari salamat di situ sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Mister have a look. There is a small village not far from here. That village has no significance. So if it's OK with mister, na, just let us seek safety there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lanuS (nws inf): escape, slip away,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lanuS (nws inf): escape, slip away, flee mitsʿar: modest, few<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Repetitious. Lot is pleading for his life, but he's so stressed out he is bumbling and stumbling. Hebrews 11 must use Lot as the example of minimal faith, barely squeaking through but making it somehow. At least he did it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ju dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu! Pi suda! Nanti beta sonde kasi ancor itu kampong.<bt>And he answered saying, &lt;&lt;OK! Go on, now! I will not destroy that village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nasaʾti panekha: I will allow that,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nasaʾti panekha: I will allow that, pay attention to you; I will show favor, have regard gam: in addition to all the other slack they already cut him<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>lbilti hafkiy (inf cs): for the nonexistence of the destruction, not to destroy. This courtly language, like a king to a subject, shows the angel's reaction to Lot's panic. hafki: (I will not) overthrow; turn upside down or on its side<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Jadi sakarang bosong lari capát suda pi sana! Te beta sonde bisa bekin apa-apa, kalo bosong balóm sampe di sana.&gt;&gt; Mulai dari itu waktu, orang kasi nama itu kampong <span class="Italic">Soar,</span> yang dia pung arti &lt;kici&gt;.<bt>So (consequently) now you must run quickly there! Cuz (elaboration) I can't do anything, if you have not yet arrived there.&gt;&gt; Beginning from that time, people named that village &lt;soar&gt;, which means &lt;small&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="himmaleT (mlT nif imperv): escape ʿad-boʾəkha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">himmaleT (mlT nif imperv): escape ʿad-boʾəkha (bwʾ inf): until your arrival<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>Initial NPs may identify a bunch of near simultaneous things, not in sequence tsoʿarah (tsʿr): trifling, insignificant. The name was given on this occasion, but also used to identify its king earlier in the light of the name the town came to be known by.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kota Sodom deng Gomora tabakar ancor-ancor<bt>The cities of Sodom and Gomora get burned to destruction</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00656c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Waktu matahari mulai nae, Lot dong sampe di Soar.<bt>When the sun began to rise, Lot (collective) arrived in Soar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rashi suggests that God made the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Rashi suggests that God made the fire come at the transition from night to day in order to hit both the sun worshippers and the moon worshippers. Jude holds that Sodom and Gomorrha and the three other cities left their first estate (rather than the angels?) tsoʿərah: to Zoar. Accent is on the first syllable, as the last is a locative that never takes the accent. The -h may be a mater lectionis to identify the "a" vowel.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Takuju sa, TUHAN po'a api deng balerang tabakar dari langit turun pi Sodom deng Gomora.<bt>Suddenly, the LORD poured-out fire and burning sulpher from the sky descending down on Sodom and Gomora.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="balerang = bahan kuning di dinding"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">balerang = bahan kuning di dinding gunung api; balerang tamba salpeter tamba arang, jadi mesiu/obat sanapan (gunpowder), Orang Rote (Dengka) pintar bekin sanapan deng mesiu.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="himTiyr (hif): make rain come down,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">himTiyr (hif): make rain come down, make sulfur come down like rain gafrit: sulphur<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>vʾet: hendiadys, burning sulphur</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />TUHAN bekin ancor abis samua kota deng kampong di itu da'era, deng samua yang idop di situ, andia: manusia, binatang, deng tanaman dong.<bt>The LORD totally destroyed all the cities and villages in that region, and everything that lived there, that is: humans, animals, and plants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yahafokh (hpk): destroy. He wiped out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yahafokh (hpk): destroy. He wiped out everything that was attractive to Lot. The valley had been "like the garden of the Lord" haʾel: God (old term)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>tsemach: growth, what sprouts</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Waktu dong lari, Lot pung bini lia pi balakang. Takuju sa, dia jadi tiang garam memang.<bt>When they ran, Lot's wife looked back. Immediately she became a post/pillar of salt.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Not clear if this is in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Not clear if this is in sequence, or just one of the many things that was going on. tabet (nbt hif): look, gaze, have a look in a specific direction, glance<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>meʾacharaw (masc) or meʾacharay (fem): looked behind Lot to the destruction? if she was going first; as she was following along behind Lot she looked back? natsiv: pillar, post, military garrison or outpost<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>melach: salt, but hard rock, not like Hawaiian salt crystallized from sea water or the salt you buy in the supermarket. More like the salt rock in the caves near Bogota.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Dia pung beso papagi, Abraham pi ulang lai di tampa yang kamaren dia badiri ko kokoe sang TUHAN.<bt>Early the next morning, Abraham went again to the place where yesterday he had stood to coax the LORD. [EXEG: See discussion in TH of two interpretations on the timing. (I can see reasonable arguments for both, although we're following the second here.) The KM is correct for Kupang. “Yesterday” is commonly used in a loose sense in KM (and other regional varieties of Malay) to refer to an event that happened any previous day (spanning from 1 day to 1 month or more, but most commonly within the past week). Indonesian distinguishes between “yesterday” and “day before yesterday”. KM does not normally do that.] [NOTE to daughter translations: match it to the correct terminology of your language's system of talking about time.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkem (hif): got up early, eagerly."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yashkem (hif): got up early, eagerly. Usually goes with hlk (vayelekh) ʿal-panay: In 18:22, the Massoretes guessed that it originally said that Yahweh stood in front of Abraham. This verse suggests they were wrong.<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Ju dia lia turun pi Sodom deng Gomora, deng itu lemba samua. Dia lia, te di mana-mana asap kabuak-kabuak nae pi langit. Deng api makan bekin abis samua.<bt>And he looked down on Sodom and Gomora, and that whole valley. He looked, and all over the place smoke was billowing up into the sky. And fire was eating up everything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="forom = archaic ; ofen ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">forom = archaic ; ofen ; tungku bakar kapur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayashqef: looked down, usually from the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayashqef: looked down, usually from the point of view of someone below, but probably not here. Same thing in v. 18. Anyway, Abraham is in the up country, and the towns are in a flat area at the foot of some rather steep hills qiTor hakivshan: thick smoke like the smoke that comes from a furnace for smelting metal or a forge. Rashi says it can also be a pit where stones are burned to make plaster. Same thick, oily look as the clouds that obscure Sinai in Exodus.<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Tuhan Allah tolong sang Lot kaluar dari itu tampa yang kaná hukum, waktu Dia bekin ancor itu kota-kota dong, tagal Dia inga Dia pung janji sang Abraham.<bt>God helped get Lot out from that place that was punished, when He destroyed those cities, because He remembered His promise to Abraham.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Jadi, waktu Tuhan Allah bekin ancor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Jadi, waktu Tuhan Allah bekin ancor itu kota-kota dong, Dia inga Dia pung janji sang Abraham. Andia ko Tuhan tolong kasi kaluar sang Lot dari itu tampa yang kaná hukum tu.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bshachet (inf): on the occasion of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bshachet (inf): on the occasion of destroying (not ʾas he destroyedʾ) zqr: remember in the sense of activating his covenant relationship<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>vayshallakh (piʿel): let Lot go free mitokh: from in the middle<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>hfekhah: destruction</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lot deng dia pung ana parampuan dong<bt>Lot and his daughters</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Itu waktu, Lot taku tenga tarús di kampong Soar. Andia ko dia deng dia pung ana parampuan dua orang pinda pi gunung. Ais dong tenga dalam goa satu.<bt>At that time, Lot was afraid to continue living in the village of soar. That is why he and his two daughters moved to the mountain. Then they stayed in a cave.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bamʿarah: in the cave (was it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bamʿarah: in the cave (was it pointed out in later years as a sort of tourist attraction? Did the Moabites and the Ammonites venerate it?)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Satu kali, ana parampuan yang kaka omong deng dia pung adi bilang, &lt;&lt;Kuliling di sini, sonde ada satu laki-laki yang bisa datang kawin deng kotong. Deng sonde lama lai, bapa tamba tua, deng su sonde bisa dapa ana lai.<bt>One time, the older daughter spoke to her younger-sibling saying, &lt;&lt;Around here, there is not one male who can come and marry us. And in the near future (&lt;not long again), father will grow older, and won't be able to have children anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsəʿiyrah: young, little laboʾ ʿalehu: to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsəʿiyrah: young, little laboʾ ʿalehu: to come to us (for sex)<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>kderekh: in the way of all the world. Theyʾre so thoroughly indoctrinated by the life they have lived that they react like Sodom people.</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Jadi lebe bae, kotong kasi minum mabo sang bapa. Ais kotong tidor deng dia, ko biar kotong bisa sambung bapa pung turunan.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be good if we-inc get father drunk. Then we sleep with him, so we can continue his descendants.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lkhah (hlk): come on! not necessarily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lkhah (hlk): come on! not necessarily feminine. Samaritan text makes it masculine. nashqeh (shqh hif): give something to drink<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>nishkəvah: we will have sexual intercourse with him. Wenham says it's a coarse expression, like the F word. nəchayyeh (Hyh piʿel): we will preserve life<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ju itu malam, dong kasi minum bekin mabo dong pung bapa deng anggor. Ais ju ana yang kaka pi tidor deng dia pung bapa. Ma bapatua talalu mabo, sampe dia sonde tau dia su bekin apa deng dia pung ana parampuan.<bt>So that night, they got their father drunk with wine. Then the older-sibling went and slept with her father. But the old-man was too drunk, to-point-that he didn't know what he had done with his daughter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tashqeyna (shqh hif): they gave him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tashqeyna (shqh hif): they gave him to drink tishkav: she lay down (standard expression for having sex)<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Dia pung beso, ju kaka kasi tau dia pung adi bilang, &lt;&lt;Adi! Tadi malam beta su tidor deng bapa. Ini malam, lu pung bagian. Nanti kotong bekin mabo sang bapa lai, ais adi maso pi tidor deng dia. Deng bagitu, kotong dua sama-sama bisa dapa ana, ko sambung bapa pung turunan.&gt;&gt;<bt>The next day, the older-sibling told the younger-sibling saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sibling! Last night I slept with father. Tonight, it's your turn (&lt;part). Let's get father drunk again, then younger-sibling go in and sleep with him. In that way, both of us can have children together, to continue father's descendants.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chen: particle, focuses on the next"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chen: particle, focuses on the next thing No attempt to convince with naʾ or the other usual particles. Just "do this, do that."<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>ʾemesh: yesterday evening boʾiy (imperv): you go<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Itu malam ju, dong bekin mabo lai dong pung bapa. Ais ana bungsu maso pi tidor deng dia pung bapa. Ma bapatua su talalu mabo, sampe dia sonde tau dia su bekin apa deng dia pung ana parampuan.<bt>That night, they got their father drunk again. Then the youngest child entered and slept with her father. But the old-man was too drunk, to-point-that he didn't know what he had done with his daughter.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Deng bagitu, dong dua dudu parú dari dong pung bapa barana sandiri.<bt>In that way, the two of them became pregnant from their own birth father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tahareyna (hrh): they got pregnant"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tahareyna (hrh): they got pregnant</Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Ais ju ana yang kaka, barana ame satu ana laki-laki. Ju dia kasi nama, <span class="Italic">Moab</span> (yang dia pung bunyi amper sama ke satu kata laen, yang dia pung arti &lt;datang dari bapa&gt;). Dia yang jadi orang Moab yang ada sakarang, pung nene-moyang.<bt>Then the older daughter gave birth to a son. She named him, Moab (which is almost like another word which means &lt;comes from father&gt;). He is the one who became those who are the Moab people's ancestor.</bt><v n="38" />Ais ana yang adi, ju barana ame satu ana laki-laki. Dia kasi nama, <span class="Italic">Ben Ami</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;ana dari beta pung orang&gt;). Dia tu, jadi orang Amon yang ada sakarang, pung nene-moyang.<bt>Then the younger daughter also gave birth to a son. She named him, <span class="Italic">Ben Ami</span> (which means &lt;offspring of my people&gt;). It is he who became those who are the Amon people's ancestor.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** ftn added from Dhao check,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** ftn added from Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:37-38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Di balakang hari, orang Moab deng orang Amon dong bekin susa sang orang Isra'el dong tarús-tarús.<bt>Later on, the Moab people and the Amon people continually caused trouble for the Isra'el people.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham putar-balek sang raja Abimelek<bt>Abraham deceives raja Abimelek</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** Dhao check, Sept 2004"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="20" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, Abraham pinda dari Mamre, pi tana Negeb yang di sablá salatan, deng dia tenga di kampong Kades deng kampong Syur pung teng-tenga. Ma sonde lama, ju dia pinda lai pi kampong Gerar.<bt>After that, Abraham moved from Mamre, to the land of Negeb on the south side, and he stayed in between the village of Kades and the village of Syur. But it wasn't long, and he moved again to the village of Gerar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSSaʿ (nSʿ): depart, pull out yagar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiSSaʿ (nSʿ): depart, pull out yagar (gwr): live as an alien, for a limited time<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ju dia kasi tau orang-orang di sana bilang, Sara tu, dia pung adi. Andia ko Abimelek, raja Gerar, suru dia pung orang-orang dong pi minta sang Sara, ais bawa sang dia pi raja pung ruma jabatan.<bt>And he told people there that, Sara was his younger sibling. That is why Abimelek, the raja of Gerar, ordered his people to go request Sara, and then bring her to the raja's official residence. [DISCOURSE: consider putting v.18 here--background-foreground + chronology; see Amarasi for model.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** added note from Amarasi check"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** added note from Amarasi check</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Satu malam, Tuhan Allah kasi tunju diri sang raja dalam mimpi. Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu su mau mati, andia ni! Te lu ada ame orang pung bini na.&gt;&gt;<bt>One night, Lord God revealed Himself to the raja in a dream. He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;You are already dead, and that's the way it is! Cuz (elaboration) you have taken someone's wife.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bʿulat baʿal (qal pass partcpl): one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bʿulat baʿal (qal pass partcpl): one who belongs to a man as engaged or married to him</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-5" />Ma Abimelek manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan! Beta balóm sonto itu parampuan. Deng beta ju sonde sala. Abraham sandiri yang bilang, itu parampuan, dia pung adi! Deng itu parampuan ju mangaku bagitu. Andia ko beta suru pi ame sang dia deng hati barisi. Jadi Tuhan jang kasi sala sang beta!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Abimelek answered saying, &lt;&lt;Lord! I haven't yet touched that woman [sounds like Clinton :)] And I have done no wrong. Abraham himself was the one who said that woman was his younger sister! And that woman also acknowledged/confessed [check collocation] like that. So (consequently) Lord shouldn't put the blame on me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsaddiq: innocent, in the right in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsaddiq: innocent, in the right in this context. This is the same argument as Abraham used with God in 18:25. btom lvavi: in the integrity of my heart; guilelessness, good faith<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>bniqyon kapai: in cleanness of hand, innocence</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju Tuhan manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Memang Beta tau lu pung hati barisi. Deng Beta yang tahan, ko lu jang sonto itu parampuan. Deng bagitu, lu ju sonde bekin sala sang Beta.<bt>And the Lord answered saying, &lt;&lt;I know that your heart is clean/pure. And I am the one who restrained, so that you did not touch that woman. In that way, you also didn't do wrong to Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾechsokh (chskh): I restrained you, held"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾechsokh (chskh): I restrained you, held you back; to keep something or someone under control: to restrain, hold back, keep from, prevent, withhold, spare chəTo (chTʾ inf): to sin against me<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>lnagoaʿ (inf): to touch</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Sakarang lu kirim pulang itu parampuan pi dia pung laki. Dia tu, Beta pung jubir. Jadi minta sang dia ko sambayang kasi sang lu, ko biar lu jang mati. Ma kalo lu sonde kasi kambali itu parampuan, lu inga bae-bae! Te lu deng lu pung orang samua nanti mati, andia tu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Now send that woman home to her man/husband. He is My spokesman. So (consequently) ask him to pray for you, so you won't die. But if you don't return the woman, you remember this! Cuz (elaboration) you and all your people will die, and that's certain.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hashev (shwb hif imperv): give back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hashev (shwb hif imperv): give back yitpallel (pll hitp): he will pray<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>baʿadkha: for you chəyeh (chyh imperv): live<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>meshiyv (shwb hif partcpl): giving her back daʿ (ydʿ imperv): know this<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Beso papagi, ju raja pange dia pung pagawe samua, ais carita dia pung mimpi. Ju dong samua jadi taku.<bt>Early the next morning, the raja summoned all his officials/employees, and told them his dream. Then they were all afraid.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkem (shkm hif imperf): he got"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yashkem (shkm hif imperf): he got up early bʾaznehem: in their ears<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ais raja pange sang Abraham, ju dia tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ada bekin sala apa sang lu, sampe lu bekin calaka sang beta deng beta pung rakyat dong bagini? Lu sonde bole bekin hal yang tar bae bagini.<bt>Then the raja summoned Abraham, and he asked saying, &lt;&lt;What wrong have I done to you, to-point-that you have done this disaster to me, and to my people in this way? You shouldn't do things that aren't good like this.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heveʾta ʿali: you caused this to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">heveʾta ʿali: you caused this to come upon me, brought it on me, got me into this bad situation mamlakhti: my dominion, what I rule over<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>chəTaʾah: morally and/or ethically wrong act (not necessarily committed on purpose) or the state of guilt which is its consequence: sin, guilt maʿsim: things done, behavior toward someone<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yeʿasu (nif): they were done</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Lu pikir apa, sampe lu bekin bagini?&gt;&gt;<bt>What were you thinking, to-point-that you did this?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mah raʾita: what did you perceive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mah raʾita: what did you perceive</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ju Abraham manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja! Beta pikir bosong samua orang yang sonde kanál sang Tuhan Allah. Jadi tantu ada yang mau bunu sang beta, ko biar bisa ame beta pung bini.<bt>Then Abraham answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father raja! I thought that all of you were people who didn't know/acknowledge Lord God. So (consequently) certainly there would be someone who would want to kill me, so they could take my wife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jintiu = not known by all"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">jintiu = not known by all UNS's;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirʾat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yirʾat</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Beta memang omong batúl bilang, beta pung adi sang dia. Te botong dua satu bapa, ma laen mama. Andia ko botong ba'ame jadi laki-bini.<bt>I spoke the truth, that my younger-sister is her. Cuz (elaboration) the two of us have the same father, but different mothers. That is why we can marry each other as husband and wife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾamnah: in reality ʾakh: certainly, only|i(12)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾamnah: in reality ʾakh: certainly, only<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Jadi waktu Tuhan Allah suru botong pi maranto, beta kasi tau beta pung bini bilang, &lt;Kalo kotong pi mana-mana, ais ada orang tanya kotong dua pung hubungan, deng kalo lu sayang sang beta, na, manyao bilang, botong dua bakaka-adi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) when Lord God ordered us to seek-living-away-from-homeland, I told my wife saying, &lt;If we-inc go anyplace, and then people ask the relationship between the two of us, and if you love me, na, answer saying the two of us are RECIP-elder-younger-siblings.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitʿu (tʿh hif): made me wander"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hitʿu (tʿh hif): made me wander off, caused me to stagger ʾomar: I said<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>chaSdekha: (loving)kindness, solidarity, joint liability, grace ʾimriy (ʾmr imperv fem): say "he is my brother"<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14-16" />Ais ju raja Abimelek kasi pulang sang Sara. Ju dia omong deng Sara bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang beta bayar kasi lu pung kaka saribu doi perak, ko jadi bukti bilang, beta sonde bekin sala apa-apa deng lu. Biar samua orang tau bagitu!&gt;&gt;<bt>So then raja Abimelek returned Sara. And he spoke to Sara saying, &lt;&lt;Now I'm paying to your older-sibling one thousand pieces of silver money, as proof that I didn't do anything wrong with you. Let everyone know that!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais raja omong deng Abraham bilang, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Beta pung negrí ni, tabuka buat lu. Lu mau pi tenga di mana sa, bole.&gt;&gt; Ais dia ju kasi sang Abraham, sapi deng kambing-domba. Dia ju kasi hamba laki-laki deng parampuan.<bt>Then the raja spoke to Abraham saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham! My country here is open to you. You want to stay wherever, you may.&gt;&gt; Then he gave Abraham cows and goat-sheep. He also gave male and female servants/slaves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shev (yshb imperv): settle, live kəSut"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shev (yshb imperv): settle, live kəSut ʿeynayim: covering for the eyes = public declaration of unbesmirched honor of a woman<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>nokhachat: ahead of you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-18" />Dolu TUHAN su tutu tampa ana dari samua parampuan yang tenga di Abimelek pung da'era, tagal dia su rampas ame Abraham pung bini. Ma waktu raja kasi pulang Sara pi dia pung laki, ju Abraham sambayang, ko Tuhan buka ulang lai itu parampuan dong pung tampa ana. Ju dong bisa barana lai.<bt>At the beginning the LORD had closed the wombs of all the women who lived in Abimelek's regions, because he had taken Abraham's wife. But when the raja returned Sara to her husband, Abraham prayed that the Lord would reopen the women's wombs. And then they were able to give birth again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirpaʾ: he healed ʾamhotayw: his female"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yirpaʾ: he healed ʾamhotayw: his female slaves<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʿatsar: he held them back baʿad: for<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>rechem: every womb End of S section.<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sara barana ame Isak kasi Abraham<bt>Sara gives birth to Isak for Abraham</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** VS 1-7 restructured at Dhao"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** VS 1-7 restructured at Dhao check to get background-foreground and chronology uncluttered, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="21" />
      <v n="1-7" />Ais itu, ju TUHAN kasi berkat sang Sara, iko Dia pung janji. Abraham su tua, deng Sara su dudu parú. Waktu dia mau barana tu, Abraham pung umur su 100 taon. Ais pas dia pung waktu, ju dia barana ana laki-laki satu. Ju Abraham kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Isak</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;dia katawa&gt;).<bt>After that, the LORD gave blessing to Sara, following His promise. Abraham was already old, and Sara was pregnant. When she was going to give birth, Abraham was 100 years old. Exactly at the appointed-time, she gave birth to a son. And Abraham named the child, <span class="Italic">Isak</span> (which means &lt;s/he laughs&gt;).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Sara ju omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah bekin beta katawa, tagal sakarang beta sanáng. Orang dong pikir, sonde mungkin beta dapa ana di hari tua bagini. Padahal, biar beta pung laki su tua kakaluk, ma beta masi barana kasi sang dia. Jadi sakarang, sapa sa yang dengar ini hal, dong ju iko katawa sama-sama deng beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>Sara also spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Lord God has made me laugh, because now I am happy. People thought thee was no possibility that I could have a child in my old age like this. However, even with my husband already old and wrinkled, I nevertheless still gave birth for him. So (consequently) now, whoever hears this matter/event, they will also laugh with me.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu Isak umur dalapan hari, Abraham sunat sang dia, iko Tuhan Allah pung parenta.<bt>When Isak was eight days old, Abraham circumcised him, following Lord God's command.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paqad: took up the cause of,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">paqad: took up the cause of, take care of. Also used of Hannah. The word appears in many different contexts and is translated in a corresponding variety of ways: generally "do something about something"? yaʿas: he did. The verse is pleonastic, but not poetic, so the two halves need to be partly collapsed for Pidgin.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ben lizqunayw (pl): son of his old age lamoʿed: at the fixed time, at the time appointed. 25 years after Genesis 12; that sheds light on what Hebrews calls "not wavering in faith"<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʾoto (masc): him (Abraham) ʾelohim: does switching between yahweh and ʾelohim complicate things?<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>The convoluted syntax builds up to the name as punch line. The promise means nothing without the boy. Also of interest to Moses in legitimating Israel as a nation. yamal (mwl): circumcised<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>tsiwwah (piʿel): ordered. Parallel to dibber ʾoto ʾəlohiym in verse 2. bəhiwwaled (yld nif inf): at the time Abraham fathered him. Ishmael is 14 to 16, naʿar. "lo" ʾfor himʾ is redundant here in Pidgin.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>tschoq (noun? infinitive construct?): because there can be bitter laughter and sneering laughter as well as happy laughter and funny laughter, or as Kafka pointed out, laughter at the absurdity of it all, "feel good" ʾbe happyʾ is needed to eliminate the negative senses. The laughter that gave Isaac his name in Chapter 17 is embarrassed laughter; this is the laughter of pure delight. Tschoq sometimes goes with laʿag l- ʾscornʾ in poetry. So even "laugh at" is possible. hashomeaʿ: whoever hears.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>millel (piʿel pf): say, speak. Odd collocation: Alter calls it poetic, and several translations treat it as poetry. It's a birth announcement. heyniqah (ynq hif pf): nurse a baby<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>baniym: sons (Pidgin uses a generic noun, because in reality there was just the one)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Hagar deng Ismael dapa usir<bt>Hagar and Ismael are evicted</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais ju Isak tamba bésar. Waktu mau sole sang dia, Abraham bekin pesta bésar.<bt>After that, the child grew. When they were going to wean him, Abraham made a big celebration.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sole = wean, lepas susu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sole = wean, lepas susu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiggamal (gml nif): he got weaned,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiggamal (gml nif): he got weaned, finished being nursed. In Pidgin, "nurse" is what a mother does to a baby; the same expression doesn't say what the baby does. Probably around the age of 3, to celebrate a triumph over high infant mortality. The long time to weaning may also have had a contraceptive function. mishteh: drinking bout, drinks for a feast, banquet with wine; kind of like a one-year birthday luʿau, but later in honor of his weaning. All the detail about the luʿau is there because it is the setting for the blowup between Sarah and Hagar.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>higgamel (gml nif inf): his weaning</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9-10" />Satu kali, Sara lia Abraham pung bini muda, Hagar pung ana Ismael, ada maen baganggu deng Isak. Lia bagitu, ju Sara ba'omong deng dia pung laki bilang, &lt;&lt;Usir itu budak dari Masir deng dia pung ana suda! Te beta sonde mau itu ana budak tarima pusaka apa-apa. Cuma beta pung ana Isak sa, yang musti dapa samua.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Sara saw Abraham's younger wife, Hager's child Ismael, keep bothering Isak. Seeing that, Sara spoke to her husband saying, &lt;&lt;Get rid of that slave from Masir, and her child! Cause I don't want that child of the slave to receive any belonging/inheritance. Only just my child Isak, is the one who must get it all.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ishmael is 14 or 15 when"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Ishmael is 14 or 15 when this happened, teen ager mtsacheq (piʿel partcpl): playing, fooling around, normal kind of thing (Alter). It doesn't say he was playing with Isaac. Laughing at Isaac? with him? laughing at Sarah? (Wenham). Mocking? (piʿel canʾt have that sense without a preposition) The word is used of sex play between Isaac and Rebecca in Genesis 26:8. But the negative readings are probably called on to justify Sarah's fury with Hagar, which isn't needed. More likely, seeing the two boys together, she started thinking about Abraham's inheritance (which she didnʾt control) and something snapped.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>garesh (piʿel impv): banish, divorce, expel, drive out ʾamah: female slave<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yiyrash: will take possession, be the heir (together with someone)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Dengar Sara pung omong bagitu, ju Abraham rasa tar enak, tagal Ismael tu, dia pung ana ju.<bt>Hearing what Sara had to say like that, Abraham didn't feel well, because Ismael was also his child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayeraʿ bəʿeyney (rʿʿ impf): it was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayeraʿ bəʿeyney (rʿʿ impf): it was displeasing to him, went wrong, got him all steamed up, ticked off. When God is raʿaʿ, he destroys cities; yet this is the only place it is intensified with mʾod. In the Code of Hammurabi and the Lipit Ishtar (Mesopotamian legal codes from before Abraham's time) if a man accepted a child, the child inherited. Another wife cannot kick the mother out. But if the father gives a slave mother her freedom, then her son loses the inheritance. The main wife's son takes precedence over an adopted son or the son of a concubine, even if the main wife's son is younger. ʿal-ʾodot: on account of<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ma Tuhan Allah omong deng Abraham bilang, &lt;&lt;Bram! Lu jang pikir itu bini muda deng dia pung ana. Iko Sara pung mau sa, tagal nanti lu dapa turunan yang Beta su janji tu, lewat Isak.<bt>But Lord God spoke to Abraham saying, &lt;&lt;Abe! You shouldn't worry about the younger wife and her child. Just follow Sara's desire, because you will have the descendants which I have promised, by-way-of Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-yeraʿ bʿenekha: donʾt let it be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-yeraʿ bʿenekha: donʾt let it be displeasing to you. This is the aftermath of the shock, hence "bodda" in 11 and "sore inside" naʿar: young man, youth (marriageable male while still single); a teen-ager's parents in those days would have been thinking about getting him married off fairly soon<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʾəmatekha: your slave woman byitskhaq: in connection with Isaac -- a direct clash with the Moslem Qurʿan, but highlighting the contrast between the two boys<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yiqareʾ (nif): be named</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ma Beta ju kasi berkat sang lu pung bini muda pung ana, tagal dia ju lu pung ana sandiri. Nanti dia pung turunan ju jadi satu bangsa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I will also give blessing to your younger wife's child, because he is also your own child. His descendants will also become a race/people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The reference to Ishmael is fronted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">The reference to Ishmael is fronted to highlight it. ʾəsimenu l- (sim impf): I will set them up as a people<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Dia pung beso papagi, ju Abraham bekin bakál ko kasi Hagar, deng gantong aer satu botol di dia pung bahu. Ais dia kasi lapás sang itu parampuan deng Ismael ko dong jalan suda. Ais ju dong jalan kuliling di tana kosong deka Beer Syeba.<bt>Early the following morning, Abraham made trailfood for Hagar, and suspended a bottle of water on her shoulder. Then he released the woman with her child Ismael for them to walk. Then they walked around the empty land near Beer Syeba.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chemat: goatskin stopped at both ends"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chemat: goatskin stopped at both ends with pitch, for water, wine, oil, etc. Maybe 3 gallons, which would weigh 30 pounds, which is not extravagant in a culture where most things are moved on somebody's back. sam ʿal-shikmah: put it on top of both shoulders (the water skin, not the boy!) People going away "show you their back (shekhem)". Noah's sons put a blanket "on their shoulders" to approach their drunk father.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vatetaʿ (tʿh): she wandered off, wandered around</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Itu waktu, Ismael pung umur su 14 taon lebe. Lia <span class="Italic">Carita Mula-mula</span> 16:16; 21:5, 8.<bt>At that time, Ismael's age was around 14 years or so. See Gen. 16:16; 21:5, 8.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00659c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Hagar deng Ismael<bt>Hagar and Ismael</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Waktu dong pung aer minum su abis, ju Hagar kasi tenga dia pung ana di satu pohon kici pung sombar.<bt>When their drinking water was gone, Hagar abandoned her child in the shade of a small tree.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikhlu (klh): finished, gone tashlekh: and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yikhlu (klh): finished, gone tashlekh: and she tossed him down (same word as used for throwing Joseph into the pit). Here, however, he stays and she leaves, so "left him there" or "made him stay there" makes more sense. Maybe for Joseph too.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʾakhad hasikhim: one of the bushes</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ju dia pikir dalam hati bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta sonde bisa tahan lai, lia ini ana pung mati.&gt;&gt; Ais dia ondor ko dudu kira-kira 50 meter dari itu ana. Ju dia manangis makarereu.<bt>And she though in her liver saying, &lt;&lt;I can't stand it anymore, seeing this child die.&gt;&gt; Then she retreated and sat around 50 metres from the child. And she wept in mourning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mineged: opposite lah: by herself|i(16) (16)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mineged: opposite lah: by herself<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>harkheq (rkhq hif): at a good distance away mətachəvey (Tchh piʿel partcpl pl construct, may be dual ʾtwo bowshots awayʾ): as a bow ranges -- about as far as an archer shoots<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>qeshet: bow bmot hayeled: look on the death of the child. She can see him from a hundred yards away, but perhaps she couldnʾt stand to hear him crying.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>vatisaʾ (nsʾ): lift, raise, show face, support, stand it; lift up her voice and wept; burst into tears</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Tuhan Allah ju dengar Ismael pung suara manangis, ais Dia pung ana bua dari sorga pange sang Hagar bilang, &lt;&lt;Hagar! Akurang ko lu susa bagini? Jang taku, te Tuhan su dengar itu ana pung manangis.<bt>Lord God also heard Ismael's crying, and His *angel/s (underlings from heaven) called to hagar saying, &lt;&lt;Hagar! Why are you in such difficulty? don't be afraid, cause the Lord has heard the child crying.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqraʾ: called out min-hashamayim: not God's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqraʾ: called out min-hashamayim: not God's dwelling, but the voice comes from above her or near her. Not like a loudspeaker in a helicopter, but somebody calling that you canʾt see. "Heavens" in Hebrew includes the air right around us, the air where the birds fly, the place where the clouds are, and the place of the stars, so it's much broader than English "sky" or "heavens".<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Sakarang lu bangun ko pi lia itu ana. Kasi kuat dia pung hati, te nanti Beta mau bekin dia pung turunan jadi satu bangsa yang hebat.&gt;&gt;<bt>Now get up and look-after the child. Encourage him (&lt;strengthen his liver), cause I will make his descendants become a noteworthy race/people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="səʾiy (nsʾ imperv fem): take, lift"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">səʾiy (nsʾ imperv fem): take, lift up, carry, convey hachəziqi et-yadekha bo (chzq hif): hold your hand in protection over him; encourage him, strengthen, hold him in your arms<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yeled / naʿar: check out the pattern of use</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ais ju Tuhan Allah bekin taráng dia pung mata, sampe dia dapa lia satu parigi di situ. Ju dia pi isi aer di itu botol, ais dia pi kasi minum dia pung ana.<bt>Then Lord God cleared up her eyes, to-point-that she could see a well there. So she went and filled water in the bottle, and gave it to the child to drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifqach: he opened tashq (shqh hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yifqach: he opened tashq (shqh hif): she cause him to drink<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Ju Ismael deng dia pung mama tenga di padang pasir Paran. Dia bésar datang, ju dia jadi jago bapana. Ais itu, dia pung mama kasi kawin dia deng nona Masir satu. Samua ni jadi, tagal Tuhan Allah ada sama-sama deng Ismael.<bt>Then Ismael and his mother lived in the desert (loan) of Paran. When he grew up, he was a champion bowman. After that, his mother married him to a young Masir woman. All this happened, because Lord God was together with Ismael.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roveh qashshat: bowman bowman, both hapaxes."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">roveh qashshat: bowman bowman, both hapaxes. May mean a superhunter, a hunter's hunter. End of P section.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham deng Abimelek badame di Beer Syeba<bt>Abraham and Abimelek make RECIP-peace at Beer Syeba</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Itu waktu, raja Abimelek deng dia pung panglima paráng, nama Fikol, datang katumu sang Abraham. Raja omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Abraham! Botong su tau bilang, Tuhan Allah ada sama-sama deng lu. Andia ko, lu bekin apa sa, samua jadi.<bt>At that time, raja Abimelek, and his war commander, named Fikol, came and met with Abraham. The raja spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham! We know that Lord God is together with you. That is why, whatever you do, everything happens/comes to be.</bt><v n="23" />Jadi sakarang beta minta lu angka sumpa di Tuhan Allah pung muka bilang, lu sonde akan putar-balek sang beta deng beta pung ana-cucu dong. Sama ke beta su kasi tunju hati bae deng lu, na, lu ju musti kasi tunju hati bae sang beta deng ini negrí.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) now I want you to raise an oath in front of Lord God, that you will not deceive me, and my children-grandchildren. In the same way that I have treated you well, na, you must also treat me well and this country.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tipu daya ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tipu daya =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshavʿah (shbʿ nif): swear an oath"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hishshavʿah (shbʿ nif): swear an oath hennah: here, now<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>ʾim tishqor li: if you deal falsely with me niyniy: my offspring<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>nekhed: my progeny cheSed: obligation to community, relatives, friends; unity, solidarity, loyalty, faithfulness<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>gartah bah: you have been living in it temporarily, not as a citizen</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ju Abraham manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu! Beta sumpa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham answered saying, &lt;&lt;Good! I swear.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ma ais itu, ju Abraham lapor sang raja bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja pung orang dong ada rampas ame beta pung parigi satu.&gt;&gt;<bt>But after that, Abraham reported to the raja saying, &lt;&lt;Father raja's people have robbed one of my wells.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hokhiach (ykch hif): set right, reprove,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hokhiach (ykch hif): set right, reprove, reproach someone for something, settle a quarrel, arbitrate ʿal-ʾodot: on account of<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>gazlu: they took away by force, tear away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Dengar bagitu, ju raja manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Waa! Beta baru dengar ini hal. Akurang ko bapa sonde lapor dari dolu? Beta sonde tau sapa yang bekin.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, the raja answered saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! I have just-now heard of this matter. Why haven't you reported this before? I don't know who did it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higadta (ngd hif): reported, spoke out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">higadta (ngd hif): reported, spoke out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27-28" />Ais itu, Abraham deng Abimelek ba'ika janji. Ju Abraham ame sapi deng domba ko kasi sang raja. Ais ju dia pili kasi kaluar tamba lai domba ténak tuju ekor.<bt>After that, Abraham and Abimelek bound a promise. And Abraham got cattle and sheep to give to the raja. After that, he selected out seven young-healthy sheep.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayikhrətu brit: cut a deal vayatstsav"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayikhrətu brit: cut a deal vayatstsav (ntsb hif): cause to stand, put to one side, set aside<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>kivsot: young ewe-lambs lvadhen: by themselves, isolated<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ju raja tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko lu bekin bagitu?&gt;&gt;<bt>And the raja asked him saying, &lt;&lt;Why are you doing that?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Tarús Abraham kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja tarima ini domba ténak tuju ekor ko jadi tanda bilang, bapa raja mangaku, beta yang gali ini parigi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham told him saying, &lt;&lt;Father raja accept these seven young-healthy sheep, as a sign that father raja acknowledges [check collocation] that I am the one who dug this well.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="was me an my guys dat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">was me an my guys dat wen dig dat puka, baʿavur: in order that<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>lʿedah: as a public witness chafartiy: I dug<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Tagal dong dua su angka sumpa di situ, ju dong kasi nama itu tampa, <span class="Italic">Beer Syeba.</span> Dia pung arti bilang, &lt;Parigi Sumpa&gt;.<bt>Because the two of them elevated and oath there, they named that place, Beer Syeba. It means, &lt;Oath Well&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shavaʿ: seven or oath - like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shavaʿ: seven or oath - like kaona nishbəʿu (shbʿ nif): they swore an oath<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="21:31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, Beer Syeba pung arti bisa macam-macam. Andia &lt;parigi dame&gt;, &lt;parigi nasib bae&gt;, &lt;parigi tuju&gt;, ko &lt;parigi sumpa&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language, Beer Syeba can have various meanings. Such as 'well of peace', 'well of good luck/descent', 'seven wells', or 'well of swearing_an_oath'.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Dong basumpa abis, ju raja Abimelek deng dia pung panglima pulang pi dong pung negrí Filistin.<bt>After they had finished swearing, then raja Abimelek and his war commander home to their Filistin country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikhrətu bəriyt: they cut the deal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yikhrətu bəriyt: they cut the deal</Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Ais itu, Abraham tanam satu pohon tamareska<bt>After that, Abraham planted a tamareska</bt><note reference="21:33" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Pohon <span class="Italic">tamareska</span> sonde ada di Timor. Itu pohon idop di tana karíng, ma dia pung daon garui tarús. Dia pung akar tikam maso pi di tana sampe dalam. Kambing dong makan dia pung daon.<bt>There are no <span class="Italic">tamareska</span> trees in Timor. That tree lived in dry land, but its leaves are evergreen. Its root pierces deeply into the ground. Goats eat its leave.</bt></note>di Beer Syeba. Mulai dari itu waktu, itu pohon kasi inga sang Abraham, ko di situ dia sémba sang TUHAN yang Idop Sampe Salamanya.<bt>tree at Beer Syeba. Beginning from that time, that tree reminded Abraham that there is where he had worshipped the LORD who Lives Until Forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="garui = green, fertile, plush (Belanda)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">garui = green, fertile, plush (Belanda)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiTTaʿ (nTʿ): planted ʾeshel: tamarisk (Tamarix"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiTTaʿ (nTʿ): planted ʾeshel: tamarisk (Tamarix aphylla, gallica, syriaca, and others). A small (up to 30 feet), fast-growing evergreen tree with durable wood, to be found abundantly in deserts, dunes and salt marshes. T. aphylla is leafless and has green branches and a wide crown. It soaks up lots of water, and excretes salt through its leaves. It has small white flowers, and its fruit is a capsule with feathery seeds. Planted from cuttings for its shade and soft branches that sheep can eat. 12 species in Israel. Looks like the cedar, which is not native there. There is also a wild Nile tamarisk (T. nilotica) which grows in nearly every deep wadi of the desert. NEB has "planted a strip of ground". Could be a kind of ironwood.<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Ais ju Abraham tenga manumpang sampe lama di itu orang Filistin dong pung negrí.<bt>Then Abraham stayed as an immigrant for a long time in the country of the Filistin people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəlishtiym: Philistines. They came later from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pəlishtiym: Philistines. They came later from the north into the coastal parts of Canaan, probably between the time of Abraham and the time of David.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan suru Abraham bekin Isak jadi korban<bt>The Lord orders Abraham to make Isak a sacrifice</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 3:17, 17:5; Markus 1:11, 9:7; Lukas 3:22, 9:35; 2 Petrus 1:17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="22" />
      <v n="1" />Sonde lama lai, ju Tuhan uji sang Abraham, ko mau lia dia dengar sang Tuhan, ko sonde. Ais Tuhan pange sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Abraham!&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long after that, the Lord tested Abraham, to see if he listened/obeyed the Lord, or not. And the Lord called him saying, &lt;&lt;Abraham!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uji = test their mettle, positive,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">uji = test their mettle, positive, from God; coba = mau kasi jato, dari setan dong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ia, Tuhan.&gt;&gt;<bt>So he answered saying, &lt;&lt;Yes, Lord.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niSSah (piʿel): put somebody to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">niSSah (piʿel): put somebody to the test positively, expecting them to come out okay; there is also a sense of training somebody by letting them experience something. The Hebrew doesn't actually say what the test was until v 12 ykhidkha: your only son<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ais Tuhan Allah suru sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Dengar bae-bae! Ame lu pung ana satu biji yang lu paling sayang. Bawa sang dia pi tana Moria, ko lu bekin sang dia jadi korban bakar kasi Beta. Sampe di sana, baru Beta kasi tunju sang lu dia pung tampa di satu gunung.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Lord God ordered him saying, &lt;&lt;Listen well! Get your only child (&lt;one seed), whom you most love. Take him to the land of Moria, to make him a burned sacrifice to Me. Arriving there, only-then will I point out to you the place on a mountain.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾet-yəchidkha: your only one haʿəlehu (ʿlh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾet-yəchidkha: your only one haʿəlehu (ʿlh hif): go up, take him up<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʾel-ʾerets hammoriyyah: to the land of Moriah. It is not clear that this was near Jerusalem, though Jerusalem was later associated with Mt. Moriah. It sounds like this Moriah was a large area away from any town, because Jerusalem was an inhabited city at that time and the king was Abraham's friend, so sacrificing Isaac a few hundred yards from Melkizedek's home doesn't add up. Besides, you can see the temple area of Jerusalem from just 9 miles north of Hebron, whereas Abraham went north for three days before he spotted it, and it was still a long hike from there. Some suggest Mt. Gerizim farther north, which matches the Samaritansʾ tradition, and is about the right distance. lʿolah (inf?): to go up<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʾakhad heharim: this is one of several higher places along a long ridge. Nobody knows fo sure which it is, but some have identified it as Mount Zion or the hill the Jewish temple was on, or even as the hill later known as Golgotha, all of which are in the up country and not a lot higher than the land around them (Golgotha is just 14 feet high) ʿolah: sacrifice that is burned up completely<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Dia pung beso papagi, ju Abraham potong kayu api. Ais dia ika-ika itu kayu dong, ju mua di atas binatang keledai. Tarús dia deng Isak, deng dia pung hamba dua orang, barangkat pi di tampa yang Tuhan su kasi tau sang dia.<bt>Early the next morning, Abraham cut firewood. Then he tied up the wood, and cargoed it on a keledai (donkey) animal. Then he and Isak, and two of his servant/slaves, left for the place that the Lord had told him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachvosh: wrapped a saddle around, saddled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yachvosh: wrapped a saddle around, saddled a donkey yəvaqqaʿ (bqʿ piʿel): chop wood, split wood<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʿətsey ʾolah (pl): pieces of wood to burn up the sacrifice</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dong jalan-jalan, ju dia pung lusa, Abraham dapa lia itu tampa dari jao.<bt>They kept walking, and the day after the next day (its lusa), Abraham saw the place from afar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishshaʾ ʾet ʿeynayw: he raised his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishshaʾ ʾet ʿeynayw: he raised his eyes, looked up merachoq: from a distance<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ais dia kasi tau sang itu dua hamba bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong dua tenga tahan di sini deng ini keledai, é! Beta deng be pung ana mau pi atas sana, ko mau sémba sang Tuhan. Abis, baru botong kambali datang sini lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he told the two servants saying, &lt;&lt;The two of you stay here temporarily with these donkeys, é! I and my child are going up there, to worship the Lord. After that, we-exc will return here again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shvu-lakhem poh: stay here. Why lakhem?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shvu-lakhem poh: stay here. Why lakhem? nishtachəweh: we will bow down deeply in worship<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Tarús Abraham ame itu kayu api buat bakar korban, ko kasi nae di Isak pung bahu. Deng dia sandiri bawa piso deng kayu yang ada api. Waktu dong dua ada bajalan sama-sama,<bt>Then Abraham took the firewood for the burned sacrifice, and put in up on Isak's shoulder. And he himself took a knife and wood that had fire. When the two of them were walking along together,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="api bara = arang manyala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">api bara = arang manyala</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayasem (sym): he put ʾesh: fire"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayasem (sym): he put ʾesh: fire maybe as coals inside a pot<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>maʾəkhelet: knife probably in a sheath yachdaw: together<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />ju Isak pange sang dia pung bapa bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Isak called to his father saying, &lt;&lt;Father!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais Abraham manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kanapa, Isak?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Abraham answered saying, &lt;&lt;What's the matter (&lt;why), Isak?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinnenniy: here I am. Response to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hinnenniy: here I am. Response to somebody who starts a conversation.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tarús Isak tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa. Kotong mau bakar korban. Di sini su ada dia pung kayu, deng dia pung api. Ma domba ana yang kotong pake jadi korban ada di mana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Isak asked saying, &lt;&lt;Father. We-inc are going to burn a sacrifice. Here there is already wood for it, and fire for it. But where is the lamb which we will use as the sacrifice?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayoʾmer: spoke, broke the silence seh:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayoʾmer: spoke, broke the silence seh: young sheep or goat<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais Abraham manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana, é! Nanti Tuhan Allah sandiri yang kasi Dia pung domba ana ko pake jadi korban.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Abraham answered saying, &lt;&lt;Child, é! Later Lord God himself is the one who will give His lamb to be the sacrifice.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirʾeh-lo: will select the sheep, see"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yirʾeh-lo: will select the sheep, see to it, choose, "has his eye on it" [JEG] In spite of the popularity of the "Jehovah-Jireh, my provida" song, rʾh means "see" most of the time, and sometimes has the sense "he is aware of the situation (and by implication, he will take care of it, without my being able to predict how)." It's like in English, where an "overseer" isn't suppose to just gaze, but to make things happen. The English would be better if it rendered "provide it [the sheep youʾre asking about]" rather than just "provide."<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00663c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Abraham siap dia pung ana Isak jadi korban<bt>Abraham is ready to sacrifice his son Isak</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dong dua jalan nae tarús.<bt>So the two of them kept on climbing.</bt><v n="9" />Waktu dong sampe di tampa yang Tuhan su kasi tau tu, ju Abraham susun batu ko bekin meja tampa bakar korban. Ais dia ator kayu api di atas meja batu. Ju dia ika dia pung ana, ko kasi tidor malenggang di atas kayu bakar.<bt>When they arrived at the place which the Lord had described, Abraham arranged stones to make a table for burning sacrifices. Then he arranged the firewood on top of the stone table. And he tied his child, and laid him face-up on the firewood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malenggang preferred \va malengga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">malenggang preferred \va malengga</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiven: built yaʿrokh: lay the pieces"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiven: built yaʿrokh: lay the pieces of split wood in rows or layers, all set up to burn; laid the wood for burning<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>yaʿqod: tie up a sacrificial victim vayasem: put; Isaac is probably a teenager by this time, but he doesn't fight his way out of it<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Tarús dia ame piso ko mau bunu dia pung ana.<bt>Then he took the knife to kill his child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayishlach et yado vayiqach et hamaʾəkhelet:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayishlach et yado vayiqach et hamaʾəkhelet: stretch out his hand and took the knife, reach for lishchoT: in order to slaughter<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ma takuju sa, TUHAN pung ana bua batarea dari langit bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bram! Tunggu dolo!&gt;&gt;<bt>But suddenly, the LORD's underling shouted from heaven/sky saying, &lt;&lt;We! Abe! Wait a second!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ada apa, Tuhan?&gt;&gt;<bt>And he answered saying, &lt;&lt;what is it, Lord?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="min-hashamayim: from the (1) starry heavens?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">min-hashamayim: from the (1) starry heavens? (2) lower heavens where the birds fly? (3) invisibly, from the surrounding atmosphere? Probably was 3, an unseen voice. For Hebrew you could say that "heaven" or "the sky" starts where my body ends. ʾavraham 2 times: To get somebody's attention when they are about to do something dangerous or stupid, or when they are absorbed in something else, &lt;&lt;Hui!&gt;&gt; with the person's name once (no repetition) is normal. You hear mothers yelling at their kids in the supermarket when the kids are about to get into something, to stop them. A lifeguard on the beach uses &lt;&lt;Hui!&gt;&gt; to direct a surfer in the ocean away from imminent danger. I guess in Hebrew they repeated the name to get this effect; in Pidgin they donʾt.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Tarús itu suara bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu jang bunu itu ana! Jang bekin apa-apa sang dia! Sakarang Beta su tau bilang, lu batúl-batúl iko Tuhan pung mau, tagal lu su siap kasi sang Tuhan lu pung ana satu biji tu, ko jadi korban.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the voice said, &lt;&lt;Don't kill that child! Don't do anything to him! Now I know that you really follow God's desires, because you were ready to give the Lord your only child, to be a sacrifice.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-tishlakh yadkha: donʾt stretch out your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-tishlakh yadkha: donʾt stretch out your hand toward the boy = donʾt lay a finger on the boy, donʾt harm him mʾummah: anything at all, any harm<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yreʾ: you are afraid of God, respect God (a noun) loʾ chasakhta ... mimeni: you did not hold back something under your control ... from me<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yəchiydkha: your only one</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Bk00008c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ais itu, Abraham dapa lia satu domba laki yang dia pung tandok taga'e di pohon kici pung cabang dong. Ais Abraham pi ame memang itu domba, ko dia bakar jadi korban kasi sang Tuhan Allah, ganti dia pung ana.<bt>After that, Abraham saw a male sheep whose horns were caught/hooked in the branches of a small tree. So Abraham went and fetched that sheep, to burn it as a sacrifice to Lord God, in exchange for his child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʾ ʾet-ʿeynayw: he raised his eyes,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yissaʾ ʾet-ʿeynayw: he raised his eyes, looked ʾayil: ram, adult male sheep<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>neʾəchaz (ʾchz nif): seized, caught Svakh: thicket<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>bqarnaw: by his two horns tachat: instead of. Needs the idea of substituting one for the other. The same idea comes up in the New Testament about Christ and us. [OK; "take place fo" implies substitution.]<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Jadi Abraham kasi nama itu tampa, &lt;Tuhan nanti sadia kasi apa yang parlú.&gt;<bt>So Abraham named that place, &lt;the Lord is prepared to give.&gt;</bt><note reference="22:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani bilang <span class="Italic">Yahova Yire</span>, yang dia pung arti &lt;Tuhan nanti sadia kasi apa yang parlú.&gt;<bt>The Ibrani language says <span class="Italic">Yahova Yire</span>, which means &lt;the Lord is prepared to give what is needed.&gt;</bt></note>Andia ko sampe sakarang ju orang omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Di atas TUHAN pung gunung tu, nanti Dia sadia kasi apa yang parlú.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why until now also people say, &lt;&lt;On top of that mountain of the LORD, He is prepared do give what is needed.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirʾeh (qal): from v 8, sees,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yirʾeh (qal): from v 8, sees, knows what we need, keeps his eye on us. (Most Pidgin speakers understand about glottal stops, which are part of Hawaiian, Samoan, Tahitian, and many of the Philippine languages, and is in some Pidgin words derived from those languages.) yeʾamer (nif): is said, is called<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yeraʾeh (nif): is seen? Should echo Verse 8. [JEG] "Provide" is an inference from "see," which is what the text says. In naming places, Hebrew speakers seem to presume that they need say only enough to identify the situation that calls for the name, rather than tell the whole story. Jacob's "Bet-ʾel" and Abraham's "Beʿer-Sheva" are cryptic. You canʾt spin "House of God" into Jacob's story, and "Seven Wells" doesn't necessarily imply a dispute over water rights, unless you already know the details yourself.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais ju Tuhan pung ana bua batarea ulang lai dari langit bilang,<bt>Then the Lord's underling shouted once again from the sky saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malʾakh: messenger (like Malachi ʾmy messengerʾ),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">malʾakh: messenger (like Malachi ʾmy messengerʾ), but handled like Verse 11, where it is clearly Yahweh talking.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />&lt;&lt;TUHAN sandiri bilang, &lt;Beta sumpa pake Beta pung nama sandiri, bagini: lu su siap kasi sang Beta lu pung ana satu biji ko jadi korban. Andia ko<bt>&lt;&lt;The LORD himself says, &lt;I swear-oath with My own name, like this: You were prepared to give me your one and only child, to be a sacrifice. That is why</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bi: on myself, swearing by myself."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bi: on myself, swearing by myself. Explanation has to be imported from Hebrews to make any sense at all in Pidgin. nishbaəʿti ki (nifʿal): swear that (content)<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>nəʾum: introduces a prophetic utterance giving God's decision in a matter yaʿan ʾəsher: because<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>loʾ chasakhta: and you did not hold back, withhold</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Beta nanti kasi berkat bam-banya sang lu deng lu pung turunan. Nanti dong tamba banya sampe sonde ada orang yang bisa itong ame sang dong, sama ke bintang di langit deng pasir di pante. Lu pung ana-cucu dong nanti kasi kala dong pung musu-musu.<bt>I will give many blessings to you and your descendants. They will increase greatly to-point-that there is no one who can count them, just like the stars in the sky, and sand on the beach. Your children-grandchildren (=descendants2) will defeat their various enemies.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ki-varekh ʾəvarekhkha vharvah ʾarbeh: infinitive absolutes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ki-varekh ʾəvarekhkha vharvah ʾarbeh: infinitive absolutes for emphasis varekh (brk piʿel inf abs): in blessing (intensive)<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>harbah (rbh hif inf abs): in making many kachol: like the sand, mud<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʿal-sfat: on the edge, the shore yirash: and it will take over, dispossess, inherit<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>shaʿar: city gate, center of power in city, the city itself ʾoyvaw: his enemy<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Dari lu pung turunan, nanti samua suku-bangsa di dunya dapa berkat, tagal lu su iko Beta pung parenta.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>From your descendants, all races/peoples in the world will get blessing, because you have followed My command.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitbarkhu: and they will wish a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hitbarkhu: and they will wish a blessing on themselves, call themselves happy ʿeqev ʾəsher: outcome, because<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ais itu, Abraham deng Isak turun kambali pi dong pung dua hamba, ko dong pulang sama-sama pi <span class="Italic">Beer Syeba</span>. Abraham dong tenga di sana.<bt>After that, Abraham and Isak descended again to his two servants, to they could go home together to Beer Syeba. And Abraham (collective) lived there. [EXEG: Isak from context, see NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***Isak added from Amarasi check Oct."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">***Isak added from Amarasi check Oct. 2005</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaqumu: they stood up yakhdaw: together|i(19)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaqumu: they stood up yakhdaw: together<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nahor pung turunan<bt>Nahor's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Satu kali, Abraham dapa dengar bilang, dia pung adi Nahor pung bini Milka su barana ame ana-ana.<bt>One time, Abraham heard that his younger-sibling's Nahor's wife Milka had had children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yuggad (ngd hofʿal): it was reported"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yuggad (ngd hofʿal): it was reported to him</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ana sulung, nama Us. Dia pung adi, nama Bus. Ais itu, Kemuel (yang jadi Aram pung bapa).<bt>The oldest child, was named Us. His younger-sibling, was named Bus. After that, was Kemuel (who was the father of Aram).</bt><v n="22" />Ais ada Kesed, Haso, Pildas, Yidlaf, deng Betuel.<bt>Then there were Kesed, Haso, Pildas, Yidlaf, and Betuel.</bt><v n="23" />Betuel tu, Ribka pung bapa.<bt>Betuel, was Ribka's father.</bt><v n="24" />Ma Nahor ju dapa tamba ana-ana dari dia pung bini piara, nama Reuma. Dia barana sang Teba, Gaham, Tahas, deng Maaka.<bt>But Nahor also had additional children from his mistress/concubine (&lt;pet wife/kept wife), named Reuma. She gave birth to Teba, Gaham, Tahas, and Maaka.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="piylagsho: his concubine (Some Asians know"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">piylagsho: his concubine (Some Asians know about concubines and understand "concubine wife", but not all speakers do. CHECK PARALLELS. End of S section.<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sara mati, deng Abraham kubur sang dia<bt>Sara dies, and Abraham buries her</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="23" />
      <v n="1-2" />Sara mati waktu dia pung umur su 127 taon. Waktu dia pung mati tu, Abraham dong ada tenga di kampong Kiryat-Arba (andia Hebron), di tana Kana'an. Abraham manangis makarereu deng mete dia pung bini yang su mati.<bt>Sara died when she was already 127 years old. When she died, Abraham (collective) were living in the village of Kiryat-Arba (that is Hebron), in the land of Kanaan. Abraham cried-with-grief and stayed-awake-mourning his wife who had died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəney chayyey Sarah: the years of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shəney chayyey Sarah: the years of the life of Sarah chevrown: Hebron<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>liSpod: to sound a lament, beat his breast as a sign of mourning livkotah (bkh inf): to weep for her<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais Abraham pi katumu sang orang Het dong. Ju dia omong bilang,<bt>Then Abraham went and met with the people of Het. And he spoke saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meto (mwt partcpl): his dying (why"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">meto (mwt partcpl): his dying (why masculine?) "town gate" isn't mentioned in Hebrew until after the deal is made, but it may need to be mentioned here to set the scene<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />&lt;&lt;Beta ni cuma manumpang di bosong pung teng-tenga. Beta sonde ada pung tana ko kubur beta pung bini. Jadi kalo bosong mau, na, kasi beta béli ame bosong pung tana sapo'ong, ko biar beta kubur sang dia di situ.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;I am just a visitor here among you. I have no land to bury my wife. So (consequently) if you-pl are willing, na, let me buy a piece of your land, so I can bury her there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi = let, allow to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi = let, allow to</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ger: a man who, either alone"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ger: a man who, either alone or with his family, leaves his village and tribe for one of several reasons, and seeks shelter and sojourn elsewhere, where his right to own land, to marry, and to participate in the administration of justice, worship, and war is curtailed toshav: means about the same as ger, but may imply that the person is more isolated from the local people, a real outsider<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>tənu (ntn imperv): give; but in the situation, it is a polite way of waying "sell". This is a very formal bargaining situation, kind of like dealing with the owners of a cemetery here. achuzzat-kever: property for a gravesite; possession<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>milfanay: out of my sight meti: my dead one (singular)<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>Hebron is on a limestone-chalk ridge, so there are probably lots of caves around</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ju dong manyao bilang,<bt>And they answered saying,</bt><v n="6" />&lt;&lt;Bagini, bapa! Bagini lama, botong su pandang sang bapa, sama ke orang tua satu yang botong hormat batúl. Jadi bapa pili sa, tana mana yang paling bae, yang cocok deng bapa pung mau. Botong tarima bae sa, sonde ada yang tolak.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;It's like this, father! For so long, we-exc have considered father, just like an elder whom we truly admire/respect. So (consequently) father just choose, whatever land is best, that good-fits father's purpose. We'll just accept that, and there is nobody who would reject/refuse.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəmaʿenu: lissen to our suggestion -"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shəmaʿenu: lissen to our suggestion - downplayed SK nsiʾ elohim: a person God has given high rank to, used for a chief or a minor king<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>bətokhenu: among us mivchar: choice<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>qvareynu: our burial sites qvor (imperv): bury<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>yikhleh (klʾ): restrain, keep back miqqvor (inf): from burying<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Tarús Abraham badiri, ais tondo ko kasi hormat sang tuan tana, orang Het dong.<bt>Right away Abraham stood, then bowed-head to show respect for the masters of the land, the Het people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishtachu (chvh hishtafal): bowed down deeply,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishtachu (chvh hishtafal): bowed down deeply, did obeisance</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ais dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bosong tarima beta pung omong tadi, na, beta minta tolong bosong ko omong deng bapatua Sohar pung ana laki-laki, Efron.<bt>And he said, &lt;&lt;If you agree with what I said just now, na, I aks your help to speak with old-man Sohar's son, Efron.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾim-yesh ʾet nafshəkhem: if it is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾim-yesh ʾet nafshəkhem: if it is on your souls, if you are in favor of this figʿu-li: put pressure on someone for me, urge someone to do something for me<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Minta, kalo bisa na, dia jual kasi beta dia pung goa, nama Makpela, yang ada di dia pung kabón pung pinggir. Dia minta harga barapa sa, beta bayar. Beta mau bayar putus dia pung harga di bosong samua pung muka, ko biar itu tana jadi beta pung hak milik. Beta mau bekin sang dia jadi botong pung tampa kubur.&gt;&gt;<bt>Ask, if possible na, for him to sell me his cave, named Makpela, which is at the edge of his garden/field. Whatever price he asks, I'll pay it. I want to pay-in-full his price in front of you all, so that land can be mine by right of ownership. I want to make it be our-exc burying place.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məʿarat: cave qaseh: the end, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">məʿarat: cave qaseh: the end, the border, far end. Efron has a field in the Makpelah area, on the east side of Hebron, and the cave is located at the far end of the field from Hebron<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>maleʾ: full; full price, what it is worth yittənennah liy: for him to give it (fem, the cave) to me<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Itu waktu, Efron sandiri ada iko dudu deng orang Het dong. Jadi dia ju dengar Abraham pung omong tu. Ais dia badiri ko manyao sang Abraham di muka orang tua-tua dong samua bilang,<bt>At that time, Efron himself was sitting there among the Het people, so he had also heard what Abraham had said. Then he stood to respond to Abraham in front of all the elders saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoshev: sitting among"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yoshev: sitting among</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />&lt;&lt;Jang bagitu, bapa! Bagini sa. Beta kasi sa itu kabón deng dia pung goa Makpela sang bapa. Bapa kubur sa bapa pung bini di situ. Beta sarakan itu tana sang bapa di muka beta pung orang dong. Biar ko dong samua jadi saksi!&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;It shouldn't be that way, father! This is the way. I'll just give that field, and its cave Makpela to father. Father just go ahead and bury your wife there. I turn over that land to father in front of my people. Let all of them be witnesses!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="extremely polite, Near Eastern courtesy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">extremely polite, Near Eastern courtesy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ais Abraham tondo lai di muka orang Het dong.<bt>Then Abraham bowed-head again in front of the Het people.</bt><v n="13" />Ju dia omong deng Efron bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagitu ju bae, ma bosong samua dengar sang beta dolo. Beta mau béli putus itu tana, ko biar beta kubur beta pung orang dong di situ.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke to Efron saying, &lt;&lt;That's also good, but all of you listen to me first. I want to buy outright that land, so I can bury my people there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beli putus = buy off (pay"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">beli putus = buy off (pay in full)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akh: assurance or emphasis, surely, indeed,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">akh: assurance or emphasis, surely, indeed, only do this lu: oh that I might, let me do this<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>shəmaʿeni: lissen to what I have to say</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14-15" />Ais ju Efron manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Itu tana pung harga cuma ampa ratus doi perak sa. Buat apa kotong dua batawar pi-datang deng doi sadiki ana tu? Bapa pi ko kubur bapa pung bini di situ suda.&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Efron responded saying, &lt;&lt;That land is only worth 400 silver money! For what purpose are the two of us-inc haggling back-and-forth about such a small amount of money? Father just go on and bury your wife there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾarbaʿ meʾot sheqel-kesef: 400 silver shekels"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾarbaʿ meʾot sheqel-kesef: 400 silver shekels is way overpriced; Efron is screwing Abraham and Abraham and everybody else know it, but because of the death nobody says anything. Maybe he was a used car salesman. There werenʾt many (if any; coins may have come from Anatolia around the 5th or 6th centuries BC) coins in use in Abraham's day; silver and gold were handled by weight, as in the gold rush days in the U.S. and Australia. The weighing unit was called the "shekel", around 12 grams or just under a half ounce by our weights. That would come to around $1,000 if we were to buy that much silver today, but its buying power was a lot more then beni ubenkha mah-hiʾ: between me and you, what's 400 shekels worth of silver? The implication is "no big deal, donʾt mention it"<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Abraham satuju deng itu tana pung harga, iko Efron pung omong. Jadi di muka samua orang Het yang jadi saksi di situ, dia itong doi perak ampa ratus biji, ais bayar kasi sang Efron.<bt>Abraham agreed to the price of that land, following what Efron had said. So (consequently) in front of all the Het people who were witnesses there, he counted out 400 pieces of silver money, and paid it to Efron.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishmaʿ: he heard, in this case"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishmaʿ: he heard, in this case he agreed to the deal. yishqol: weighed out the silver<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʿover: crossing over, passing; at the current rate for silver lasocher: for the merchant, buying-agent; Abraham weighed out silver at the going price of silver, equivalent to the standard shekel weight, which was around 1/2 ounce or 12 grams. He probably had a respected merchant bring his personal weight and use that for the weighing in front of everybody<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-19" />Jadi deng bagitu Abraham dapa Efron pung tana, jadi dia pung milik. Andia itu tana yang ada di Makpela, deka deng Mamre (andia Hebron). Dia béli putus itu tana deng dia pung kabón, dia pung goa, deng dia pung pohon-pohon samua. Samua tua-tua orang Het jadi saksi bilang itu tana deng dia pung isi samua, Abraham pung hak milik.<bt>So (consequently) in that way, Abraham obtained Efron's land, to be his possession. That is, the land that is at Makpela, near Mamre (that is Hebron). He paid-in-full for the land, its field/s, its cave, and all of its trees. All the elders of Het were witnesses that the land and everything in it was Abraham's right of possession.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** VS 17-19 merged to reduce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** VS 17-19 merged to reduce heavy redundancy in place names, at Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais ju Abraham pi kubur sang Sara di dalam itu goa, di tana Kana'an.<bt>After that, Abraham went and buried Sara in that cave, in the land of Kana'an.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaqam (qwm): it came to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaqam (qwm): it came to be lifne: before, facing; spatial, no motion<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>bkhol-gvulo: in all its boundary (gbl establish a boundary around an area, share a boundary with) saviv (as adverb): in a circuit; all around<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>lmiqnah: as an acquisition by purchase, made over to Abraham by purchase. The collective memory of the witnesses was the deed to the land, since there was no way of writing it down.</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Deng bagitu, itu kabón deng dia pung goa yang dolu orang Het dong pung tana, sakarang su jadi Abraham pung tana milik, ko dia pake jadi kerkof.<bt>In that way, the field, and its cave that had previously been the land of the Het people, now became Abraham's owned land, so he could use it as a graveyard (Dutch loan).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laʾachuzzat-qever: as the property for a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">laʾachuzzat-qever: as the property for a grave-site End of S section.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dong cari kasi Isak bini<bt>Looking for a wife for Isak</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="24" />
      <v n="1" />Abraham pung umur panjang sampe dia su talalu tua. Deng TUHAN jaga bae-bae sang dia, ais kasi dia idop deng dame-sajahtra.<bt>Abraham lived long until he was very old. And the LORD watched over him well, and allowed him to live in peace-prosperity (fixed compound).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="berakh: had bestowed power for success,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">berakh: had bestowed power for success, prosperity, fertility bakol: in all different ways. enumerate?<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2-3" />Abraham ada pung orang parcaya satu, yang urus dia pung harta samua. Satu kali, Abraham pange sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Dengar bae-bae! Beta minta lu sumpa mati,<bt>Abraham had a trusted person, who managed all his belongings. One time, Abraham summoned him saying, &lt;&lt;Listen well! I request you to swear-death-oath [=serious consequences or death if oath broken],</bt><note reference="24:2-3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Taro lu pung tangan di beta pung lelak.&gt;&gt; Dia pung arti, sumpa mati.<bt>The Ibrani language says &lt;&lt;Put your hand in my crotch.&gt;&gt; It means, a swear-death-oath.</bt></note>pake TUHAN pung nama. Andia Tuhan Allah yang bekin ame langit deng bumi. Bilang, lu sonde bole ame nona dari ini orang Kana'an dong, ko kasi kawin deng beta pung ana Isak.<bt>using the LORD's name. That is, Lord God who made heaven and earth. That, you may not take a young-woman from these Kanaan people, to marry my son Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lelak = between thighs, pohon paha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lelak = between thighs, pohon paha</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zqan: old; oldest in years? longest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">zqan: old; oldest in years? longest association with Abraham? moshel (partcpl): the one who was in charge<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>tachat yərekhi: under my thigh: the fleshy portion of the upper thigh, area of sexual organs, around to the hip-socket and butt. Hand placed there in making oaths during the period of the patriarchs and probably earlier. The idea is that one is swearing an oath by his posterity, or saying that if he doesn't do what he promises, may his own posterity be cut off. ʾashbiyʿəkha (shbʿ hif): I will make you swear<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bayahweh: swear by Yahweh, ask Yahweh to make sure you do everything you are about to promise, or else exchange w/consultant: [MC] When do you leave this descriptive name in small letters and when do you put it in caps? [JEG] YHWH ʾəlohey hasshamayim vəʾəlohey haʾarets ʾYahweh, god of the heavens and god of the earthʾ doesn't occur anywhere else. If we put the verb "stay" in it, then it's clearly a description of which god he means, not a trade marked name.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ma lu musti pi di beta pung negrí asal, di beta pung kelu dong. Lu cari ame satu nona di situ ko kotong kasi kawin deng beta pung ana.&gt;&gt;<bt>But you must go the my country/land/village of origin, to my relations. You will look there, for a young-woman for us-inc to marry to my son.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾel ʾartsi vʾel-moladti: hendiadys, to my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾel ʾartsi vʾel-moladti: hendiadys, to my land and my origin (moladti is not "my family", it's "my birthplace")</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ais itu hamba tanya sang Abraham bilang. &lt;&lt;Bae, bapa! Ma karmana kalo itu nona sonde mau iko datang sini? Kalo bagitu, na, beta musti bawa bapa pung ana ko pi kawin di sana, ko karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the slave/servant asked Abraham saying, &lt;&lt;Fine, father! But what if that young-woman doesn't want to come here? If that's the case, na, should I take father's son there to marry, or what?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾulai: expression of hope, entreaty, fear;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾulai: expression of hope, entreaty, fear; perhaps toʾveh (ʾbh): is willing<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>hehashev ʾashiv (shwv hif inf abs): take somebody back, bring somebody back yatsaʾta: you came away from<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Abraham manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu inga bae-bae! Biar karmana ju, lu sonde bole bawa beta pung ana pi sana!<bt>Abraham answered saying, &lt;&lt;You pay attention! No matter what, you may not take my son there!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshamer ləkha (nif impv): be on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hishshamer ləkha (nif impv): be on your guard, be careful</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Inga te TUHAN yang pegang kuasa di langit, su bawa kaluar sang beta dari beta pung negrí asal, ais antar sang beta sampe di ini tana. Dia ju su ika janji deng beta bilang, &lt;Nanti Beta kasi ini tana samua sang lu pung turunan.&gt; Jadi lu jang kawatir! Lu pi sa. Te nanti Tuhan suru Dia pung ana bua dari sorga datang buka jalan kasi sang lu, ko lu bisa katumu itu nona yang nanti jadi beta pung ana pung bini.<bt>Remember that the LORD who holds power/authority in heaven has brought me out from my country of origin, and escorted me all the way to this land. And He has bound a promise with me saying, &lt;I will give all this land to your descendants.&gt; So (consequently) don't worry! Just go. Cause the Lord will order his *angel (underling from heaven) to open the way for you, so you can meet the young-woman who will become my son's wife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾerets moladti: compresses Verse 4, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾerets moladti: compresses Verse 4, the land of my birth</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ma kalo itu nona sonde mau iko sang lu datang sini, na, lu bebas dari ini sumpa. Biar karmana ju, lu jang bawa beta pung ana pi sana.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if that young-woman doesn't want to follow you here, na, you are released from this oath. No matter what, you are not to take my son there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqita (nqh nif) you are exempt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">niqita (nqh nif) you are exempt from, free from the obligation of the oath raq: only<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais, itu hamba angka sumpa sang Abraham bilang, nanti dia bekin iko Abraham pung mau samua.<bt>So then, the servant lifted an oath (=swore) to Abraham, that he would do everything that Abraham wanted.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kil = crotch (of pants), celana"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kil = crotch (of pants), celana pung lelak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Tarús itu hamba pili ame onta sapulu ekor. Ais dia mua macam-macam barang yang bagus di itu onta dong. Ju dia barangkat pi Nahor pung kota di Mesopotamia.<bt>Right away the servant chose 10 camels. Then he loaded various sorts of good things onto those camels. And he left to go to Nahor's city in Mesopotamia. [NOTE to daughter translations: Consider whether servant plus underlings introduced here; required for vs. 25 &amp; 32]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="migmale ʾadonaw: from his master's camel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">migmale ʾadonaw: from his master's camel herd khol-Tuv: all sorts of the best things of his master, the choice stuff. Does the bride price need to be spelled out here, or only in v 53?<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>bəyado: in his hand, under his control</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, itu tampa pung nama <span class="Italic">Aram-Naharaim</span>. Sakarang itu tampa ada di Siria pung bagian utara.<bt>In the Ibrani language, the place is called <span class="Italic">Aram-Naharaim</span>. These days, the place is in the north part of the country of Siria.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ahirnya, itu hamba sampe di itu kota. Ais dia deng dia pung onta dong barenti cape di pinggir kota, deka satu parigi. Itu waktu su sore, pas deng ana-ana parampuan dong ada pi timba aer di itu parigi.<bt>Finally/eventually, the servant arrived in that city. Then he rested his camels at the edge of the city, near a well. The time was in the late afternoon, just when there were girls going to fetch water at that well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="timba = asuk (Buru), fetch from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">timba = asuk (Buru), fetch from well</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="After some days he finally arrived"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">After some days he finally arrived at his destination. It's over 300 miles with a lot of rough country, so even riding camels it could have taken 10 days to 2 weeks each way yavrekh (brk hif): caused to kneel down<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>bʾer: deep dug hole with water. At this one they let clay jars holding 5 or 10 gallons down into the hole with a rope, let them fill, and pulled them back up, or else went down steps inside and climbed back up ʿet: time<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tseʾt (ytsʾ inf): to go out shoʾəvot (partcpl): the women going to draw water<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ais, itu hamba sambayang bilang, &lt;&lt;TUHAN, beta pung bos Abraham pung Allah. Tolong buka jalan ko biar beta pung jalan ni dapa hasil yang bae. Kasi tunju Tuhan pung hati bae sang beta pung bos, deng inga dia pung janji kasi sang beta. Jadi biar ko beta dapa katumu Isak pung calon bini.<bt>Then, the servant prayed saying, &lt;&lt;LORD, my boss Abraham's Allah. Help open the way, so that this trip of mine can have good results. Show the (your) Lord's goodness/kindness/grace to my boss, and remember the his promise to me [EXEG: from TH &amp; CEV/TEV; TWOT Heb. /hesed/ is "loyalty...fidelity to covenantal obligations real or implied...freely given...kindness...on the basis of a relationship...lovingkindness"; Speiser "true loyalty"; referring to Abraham's promise that God would look after the servant in vs.7 here. (/hesed/ in v12, 27, (42 success), 49, (56 success)]. So (consequently) let me meet Isak's wife candidate.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** adjusted at Dhao check, Sept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** adjusted at Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nahum Sarna points out that this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Nahum Sarna points out that this is the first time somebody calls out to Yahwe. No priest, no offering, no special posture. Just hinneh "well, here I am" haqreh-naʾ (qrh hif): let something happen, set things up; make them go well for me<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>lfanay (pl): before me, ahead of me ʿaseh-chesed: act in loyalty to the community<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Tuhan, beta ada badiri di pinggir parigi ni. Deng nona-nona dari kota ada datang timba aer di sini.<bt>Lord, I am standing at the edge of this well. And young-women from the city are coming to fetch water here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): while I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): while I am standing here, make something happen. Gunkel -- complete trust in God plus worldly wisdom. ʿal-ʿen hamayim: here it's a spring, but later it's a dug well; probably a spring made into a well by digging a hole that would hold the water coming out of the spring to make it easier to get it by letting a clay pot down on a rope or going down steps<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>bnot ʾanshe haʿir: young women old enough to get married; 12 to 15 years mostly, and responsible to their fathers yotsʾot (qal partcpl): are coming out<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Jadi beta minta bagini: kalo beta omong deng satu nona bilang, &lt;Nona, é. Tolong kasi turun lu pung pareuk aer ko kasi beta minum sadiki dolo.&gt; Kalo dia manyao bilang, &lt;Bapa minum sa. Deng nanti beta kasi minum bapa pung onta dong ju.&gt; Naa, itu jadi tanda bilang, itu nona yang Tuhan su pili jadi Isak pung bini! Deng tanda yang bagitu, beta bisa tau bilang, Tuhan su kasi tunju Tuhan pung bae sang beta pung bos, Abraham.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) I request like this: If I speak to a young-woman saying, &lt;Young-woman, é! Please let down your clay-pot of water so I can drink a little now.&gt; If she responds saying, &lt;Father just go ahead and drink! And I'll also give a drink to your camels.&gt; Naa, [+shift] that will be a sign that this is the young-woman whom the Lord has chosen to become Isak's wife! With a sign like that, I will know that, the Lord has revealed the Lord's goodness to my boss, Abraham.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəʿar (qri hanʿarah): the girl (usually"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nəʿar (qri hanʿarah): the girl (usually masculine, read as feminine) hati-naʾ (nth hif): cause to incline, tip the water jar a bit so water will pour out<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>kadekh: your large pottery jar for water -- tall clay pot that held 3 to 5 gallons or even more ʾeshteh: and I will drink. Imperative + wa + imperfect = let down your jar so I may drink<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʾashqeh (shqh hif): I will give a drink to your camels too. Ten camels who have just crossed the desert can drink up a huge amount of water! John has a figure of 25 gallons per camel. hokhachta (ykch hif): you give judgment, determine, assign<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʿositi chesed: you have acted in solidarity, faithfulness, loyalty, with someone. Gordon Clark, collocations of chesed with ʾemet.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham pung hamba katumu nona Ribka<bt>Abraham's servant meets the young-woman Ribka</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15-16" />Dia balóm abis sambayang, te satu nona datang. Dia pung nama Ribka. Dia tu, Abraham pung adi Nahor deng dia pung bini Milka pung cucu. Ribka pung bapa, nama Betuel. Ribka tu, talalu manis deng masi parawan. Dia turun pi dalam itu parigi, ju isi dia pung pareuk aer, ais nae kambali.<bt>Before finishing praying, a young-woman came. Her name was Ribka. She was Abraham's younger-brother Nahor and his wife Milka's grandchild. Ribka's father, was named Betuel. Ribka was very pretty, and was still a virgin. She went down into the well, and filled her clay-pot with water, then climbed back up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kad: baked clay pot that holds"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kad: baked clay pot that holds 5 or 10 gallons, used all over that part of the world for water Terem: before<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>killah (klh piʿel): he finished hinneh: here she comes<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yulldah (yld qal pass): was born to Betuʿel shikhmah (shkhem): her shoulders. Usually refers to both shoulders, including the neck and the upper part of the back<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>Is the genealogy clear? Abraham and Nahor were brothers. Nahor married Milkah. They had a boy Betuʿel. Betuʿel was Rebecca's father. So Isaac and Rebecca were first cousins once removed in English terms, because Betuʿel and Isaac were first cousins. tovah marʾeh: beautiful to look at<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>bətulah: a girl old enough for sex, but either still a virgin or a young widow still of marriagable age, so still her father's responsibility tered (yrd): she went down<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>haʿaynah: the spring. Where the water came out, people had dug a hole big enough for the water to collect in, with a path or steps down from ground level. She would have climbed down inside, filled up the clay pot from the small pool at the bottom, and then climbed out carrying the clay pot full of water</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00668c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Waktu Ribka sampe di atas, ju Abraham pung hamba lari pi sang dia. Ais dia minta bilang, &lt;&lt;Nona. Tolong kasi beta minum sadiki dolo.&gt;&gt;<bt>As soon as Ribka arrived at the top, Abraham's servant ran to her. And he asked saying, &lt;&lt;Young-woman. Please give me a bit to drink now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayarats: he ran (might mean he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayarats: he ran (might mean he hurried) liqraʾtah (qrʾ II): to meet her, toward her, to come to her<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>hagmiʾini (gmn hif impv): let me sip; not the same words he used in his prayer. Could be he's really excited by how quickly God answers his prayer. gamaʾa is a swallow at most. mʿat: a little bit<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ais, itu nona manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Minum sa, om!&gt;&gt; Tarús dia kasi turun capát-capát dia pung pareuk aer, ko kasi minum itu hamba.<bt>Then, the young-woman responded saying, &lt;&lt;Just drink, uncle!&gt;&gt; Right away she put down her water pot, to let the servant drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təmaher: she hurried tored (yrd hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">təmaher: she hurried tored (yrd hif): she took down<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>tashqehu (shqh hif): let him drink</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Minum abis ju, itu nona bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar ko beta timba aer kasi minum om pung onta dong, sampe dong puas.&gt;&gt;<bt>After drinking, the young-woman said, &lt;&lt;Let me fetch water for uncles' camels, so they can drink until satisfied.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tkhal (klh piʿel): she finished ləhashqoto"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tkhal (klh piʿel): she finished ləhashqoto (shqh hif inf): letting him drink<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ʾeshʾav: I will draw water ʿad: until<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>killu (klh piʿel): they are finished</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Tarús dia pi po'a aer pung sisa di binatang dong pung tampa minum. Ais dia lari turun-nae timba aer dari itu parigi, ko kasi minum itu onta dong samua, sampe dong puas.<bt>Right away she poured the rest of the water into the animals' drinking place. Then she ran descend-ascend fetching water from that well, to give drink to all those camels, until they were satisfied.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tmaher: she hurried, did something quickly."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tmaher: she hurried, did something quickly. Verb where English would use an adverb. təʿar (ʿrh piʿel): she poured out<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>shoqet: watering trough tishʾav: she drew water<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Camels just in off the desert can drink a huge amount of water! 25 gallons</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Abraham pung hamba badiri diam-diam, ko pasang mata lia itu nona pung karjá. Dia pikir-pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini nona yang Tuhan pili, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>Abraham's servant stood there quietly, carefully observing (&lt;attach eyes watching) the young-woman's work. He kept thinking, &lt;&lt;Is this the young-woman that the Lord has chosen, or [what]?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karja pancuri tulang = rajin di"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">karja pancuri tulang = rajin di muka, malas di balakang ; ceke munta dara = makan rakus, ma karja pancuri tulang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishtaʾeh (shʾh hitp ptcpl cs): was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mishtaʾeh (shʾh hitp ptcpl cs): was standing there gazing at her. Have to make sure nothing in the interaction implies that the luna was interested in exploiting her sexually, or that he was quiet because he was angry -- nothing negative. He was watching quietly to see if she was the right one. "with bated breath" machərish (chrsh hif ptcpl): keep still; silently, not saying anything<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ladaʿat (ydʿ inf): to know hahitsliach darkho (tslch hif): interrogative heth, whether [God would] bring his trip to a successful conclusion, make it succeed<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʾim-loʾ: or not.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Itu onta dong samua minum sampe puas. Ju itu hamba ame cincin idong mas, deng satu pasang galáng mas ko taro di itu nona pung tangan dua-dua.<bt>Those camels all drank to-point-that satisfied. Then the servant took a gold nose ring, and a pair of gold bracelets to put on both of the young-woman's hands/arms.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nezem: nose ring beqaʿ: half-shekel, 1/4"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nezem: nose ring beqaʿ: half-shekel, 1/4 ounce of gold, now worth about $88, probably more at that time<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mishqalo: its weight tzmidim: woman's bracelets<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yadeah (dual): her two hands, arms, wrists ʿasarah zahav: ten shekels of gold, 5 ounces, now worth about $1,765, probably more at that time<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mishqalam: their weight (2.5 ounces each)</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;cincin idong mas pung barát satenga <span class="Italic">syekel </span>(andia 6 gram)&gt;. Ais, itu dua galáng mas pung barát &lt;10 <span class="Italic">syekel </span>(sama deng 114 gram)&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language says &lt;a gold nose-ring weighing a half syekel (that is 6 grams)&gt;. And, the two gold bracelets weighed &lt;10 syekel (same as 114 grams)&gt;.</bt></note><v n="23" />Ais, itu hamba tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Nona pung bapa, nama sapa? Kalo bisa, na, beta manumpang tidor di nona pung bapa pung ruma.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, the servant asked saying, &lt;&lt;What is your (&lt;young-woman's) father's name? If possible, na, I'd like to spend-night sleeping in young-woman's father's house.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bat-miy: daughter of who? hagidi naʾ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bat-miy: daughter of who? hagidi naʾ li (ngd hif impv): put me into the picture, clue me in<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>hayesh: is there? with interrogative h- lalin (lyn inf): to spend the night. Variant spelling to dissimilate from "lanu"<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ju itu nona manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta pung bapa, nama Betuel. Beta pung ba'i, Nahor. Deng beta pung nene, Milka.<bt>Then the young-woman answered saying, &lt;&lt;My father, is named Betuel. My grandfather, Nahor. And my grandmother, Milka.</bt><v n="25" />Di botong pung ruma ada tampa tidor cukup kasi om dong. Deng ada rumput banya kasi om pung binatang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>In our-exc house there are enough sleeping palces (=beds) for uncle (collective). And there is plenty of grass for uncle's animals.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Nobody here knows much about camels. “Grass for the animals” conflates “straw and fodder (provender)”, and leaves open the possibility of either hand feeding (bringing the food to the animals) or grazing (they do both in NTT). Attempts to make two categories of camel food make for 1) heavy information load, and 2) overtranslation of non-existing categories. Specific-generic. “Enough sleeping places for uncle (collective)” can include the camels. Concept of providing bedding for animals to sleep on bring the camels under the blankets with the people.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="She informs him that they have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">She informs him that they have plenty, but she isn't the one who can invite him in. teven: chopped stalks of wheat for the animals to eat; straw<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>miSpoʾ: fodder for donkeys lalun: regular form, not dissimilated as in verse 23. Rashi reads "lalin" as "one night's lodging" and "lalun" as "many nights."<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ais, itu hamba tondo ko sémba sang TUHAN.<bt>So then the servant bowed-head to worship the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqod (qdd): bowed down, kneeled down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqqod (qdd): bowed down, kneeled down (always followed by hishtachva). yishtachu (chvh hishtafal): bow down deeply, do obeisance<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ju dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Puji Tuhan! Tuhan su buka jalan kasi sang beta, sampe beta su dapa katumu langsung deng bos Abraham pung kelu di sini. Deng bagitu, Tuhan su kasi tunju Tuhan pung hati bae kasi sang beta pung bos Abraham, deng su bekin jadi dia pung janji sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Praise the Lord! The Lord has opened the way for me, to-point-that I could meet directly with boss Abraham's family here. In this way, the Lord shown His goodness/grace/kindness to my master Abraham, and done (=fulfilled) according to his promise to me.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: from TH &amp; CEV/TEV; TWOT Heb. /chesed/ is "fidelity to covenantal obligations real or implied"; referring to vs.7 here? Parallels vs.12; see discussion there.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** adjusted from Dhao check, Sept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** adjusted from Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loʾ-ʿazav: he does not abandon, forsake,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">loʾ-ʿazav: he does not abandon, forsake, leave, give up, be deficient in chasdo: obligation to him; loyalty to him<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʾamito: truth with him, faithfulness nachani (nchh): he leads me<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʾache: kinsmen, plural</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ais, itu nona lari pulang capát-capát, ko carita kasi isi ruma dong samua, apa yang su jadi.<bt>Then, the young-woman ran home quickly, to tell everybody in the house, what had happened.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tarats (rwts imperf): run tagged (ngd"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tarats (rwts imperf): run tagged (ngd hif): announce<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʾimah: mother; why the mother's family, when the servant had inquired about the father's family?</Message></Annotation><v n="29-30" />Ribka pung kaka laki-laki, nama Laban. Waktu dia lia itu barang mas, deng dengar Ribka pung carita, tarús Laban lari kaluar capát-capát, ko pi katumu deng itu hamba yang masi badiri deng dia pung onta dong deka itu parigi.<bt>Ribka's older brother, was named Laban. When he saw the gold things, and heard Ribka's story, Laban straight away ran out quickly, to go meet with the servant who was still standing with his camels near that well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kirʾot ... kshamʿo: Infinitive construct. The"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kirʾot ... kshamʿo: Infinitive construct. The seeing and hearing took place at the same time. Rashi "He cast his eye on the Mammon."</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ais Laban omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Om! TUHAN su antar sang om deng salamat sampe sini. Jadi jang badiri di luar sini! Mari pi di botong pung ruma. Botong su sadia kamar. Makanan buat om pung onta dong ju malimpa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Laban spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Uncle! The LORD has escorted uncle safely to here. So (consequently) don't stand outside here! Let's go to our-exc house. We have already prepared room/s. Food for uncle's camels, is also plenteous.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: “A place for the camels” is there by implication. Anyone who can provide rooms for a group of unannounced guests, and food for a caravan of camels is not going to have a problem with space for the camels. “Food and place” for the camels was felt to be redundant and heavy, since it was implied. Implicit.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʾanokhi: since I have ... piniti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʾanokhi: since I have ... piniti (pnh piʿel): clear up, fix up<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham pung hamba maso minta sang Ribka<bt>Abraham's servant enter requesting Ribka [=a step in wedding negotiations]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ais ju Abraham pung hamba iko sang Laban, ko maso pi di Betuel pung ruma. Tarús Laban dong bantu kasi turun muatan dari onta dong. Ais dong kasi onta dong makan rumput. Dong ju bawa aer ko itu hamba deng dia pung orang dong cuci kaki.<bt>So Abraham's servant went with Laban to go into Betuel's house. Then Laban's (collective) helped take down the cargo from the camels. When [that was] done, they gave the camels grass to eat. They also brought water for the servant and his people to wash their feet. [EXEG: The Heb text in 32 actually only says here “straw and fodder (provender)” (see NRSV), which are the same terms in vs. 25 for the food side of things, whereas bedding is a different clause in 25. So in vs. 32 NLT and TH are trying to make a distinction between straw (for bedding) and fodder (for food) which actually has no support from the text or context. Too microscopic.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yfatach (ptch piʿel): unsaddled the camls"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yfatach (ptch piʿel): unsaddled the camls for the evening, opened, loosened lirchots: to wash oneself<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Waktu dong ator makan di meja, ju itu hamba bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong ada mau makan, ma beta minta parmisi ko mau kasi tau satu maksud dolo.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they had set food on the table, the servant said, &lt;&lt;We're about to eat, but I ask permission to explain a purpose first.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Laban manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Om, omong sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Laban answered saying, &lt;&lt;Uncle, just speak.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiysam (qəriʾ for vayosam sym hof):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiysam (qəriʾ for vayosam sym hof): was put, laid; kətiv yisem. The "u" vowel is written so that none of the consonant letters need be changed.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Tarús itu hamba bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, bosong pung ba'i Abraham pung hamba.<bt>So then the servant said, &lt;&lt;I here, am your-pl grandfather Abraham's servant.</bt><v n="35" />TUHAN su kasi berkat bam-banya sang beta pung bos, sampe dia jadi talalu kaya. Tuhan su kasi sang dia mas-perak, hamba laki-laki deng parampuan, deng binatang bam-banya, andia: sapi, onta, keledai, deng kambing-domba.<bt>The Lord has given many blessings to my boss, to-point-that he has become exceedingly wealthy/rich. The Lord has given him gold-silver, male and female servant/slaves, and many animals, such as: cattle, camels, donkeys, and goat-sheep.</bt><v n="36" />Waktu beta pung bos laki-bini su tua, ju mama Sara barana kasi bos Abraham satu ana laki-laki. Dia yang nanti tarima bos Abraham pung pusaka samua.<bt>When my boss husband-wife were already old, mama Sara had a baby son for Abraham. He is the one who will receive all of boss Abraham's belongings/inheritance.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Does &quot;fo my boss&quot; make sense?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Does "fo my boss" make sense? Or no need? vayitten-lo: "give him" in the sense of "set up for him to inherit"<span class="Italic">(36)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Jadi bos Abraham suru beta sumpa bilang, &lt;Lu sonde bole ame nona Kana'an, ko kasi kawin deng beta pung ana Isak.<bt>So boss Abraham ordered me to swear-oath saying, &lt;You-sg may not take a young-woman of Kanaan, to give in marriage with my son Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashbiʿeni (hif): he caused me to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yashbiʿeni (hif): he caused me to promise</Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Ma lu musti ame nona dari beta pung kelu dong sandiri, jadi dia pung bini.&gt;<bt>But you must take a young-woman from my own family/kin, to be his wife.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾim-loʾ: surely, but rather mishpachtiy: my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾim-loʾ: surely, but rather mishpachtiy: my clan, my relatives<span class="Italic">(38)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ais beta tanya sang bos bilang, &lt;Karmana kalo itu nona sonde mau iko sang beta?&gt;<bt>So then I asked [my] boss saying, &lt;What if that young-woman doesn't want to follow/accompany me?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾulay: expression of hope, entreaty, fear; perhaps</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ju dia manyao bilang, &lt;TUHAN yang beta salalu iko Dia pung mau, nanti suru Dia pung ana bua dari sorga datang buka jalan kasi sang lu, biar lu bisa dapa satu nona dari beta pung kelu sandiri, ko jadi beta pung ana pung bini.<bt>So he answered saying, &lt;The LORD who I always follow His will, will order His *angel (underling from heaven) to come [and] open the way for you, to allow you to be able to get a young-woman from my own family/kin, to become my son's wife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitəhallakhti (hlk hitp): walk, my life"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hitəhallakhti (hlk hitp): walk, my life style, I conduct myself in his sight hitsəliach (hif): make something succeed, bring it to a successful conclusion<span class="Italic">(40)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Ma kalo beta pung kelu dong tolak ko sonde mau lapás itu nona datang sini, na, lu bebas dari itu sumpa.&gt;<bt>But if my family (collective) reject/refuse and don't want to release the young-woman to come here, na, you are free from that oath.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾaz: then tinnaqeh (nqh nif): you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾaz: then tinnaqeh (nqh nif): you will be free from your oath, off the hook<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>meʾalati: from my curse, the charge I have laid on you naqi: clear of the responsibility, free from guilt<span class="Italic">(41)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Jadi waktu tadi sampe di parigi, beta sambayang dalam hati bilang, &lt;TUHAN, beta pung bos Abraham pung Allah. Tolong buka jalan, ko biar beta pung jalan ni dapa hasil yang bae. Biar beta katumu Isak pung calon bini.<bt>So (consequently) when earlier arriving at the well, I prayed in my liver saying, &lt;LORD, the Allah of my boss Abraham. Please open the way, so that this journey of mine, gets a good result. Permit me to meet Isak's candidate for wife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾim-yeshkha-naʾ matsliach: if there is a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾim-yeshkha-naʾ matsliach: if there is a successfull outcome you will bring about matsliach (tslch hif partcpl): causing my way to prosper<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>ʿaleyah (ʿlh? ʿal-h): the purpose for which (fem) I am making this trip</Message></Annotation><v n="43" />Tuhan, beta ada badiri di pinggir parigi ni. Deng nona-nona dari kota ada datang timba aer di sini. Jadi beta minta bagini: kalo beta omong deng satu nona bilang, &lt;&lt;Nona, é! Tolong kasi turun lu pung pareuk aer ko kasi beta minum sadiki dolo.&gt;&gt;<bt>Lord, I am standing here at the edge of this well. And the young-women from the city are coming fetching water here. So (consequently) I ask like this: If I speak to one young-woman saying, &lt;&lt;Young-woman, é! Please lower your water jar to give me a little to drink now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): I am"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nitstsav (ntsb nif partcpl): I am standing haʿalmah: young girl of marriageable age, young woman up to when she has her first child (bətulah can be old enough to have been widowed; ʿalmah emphasizes young age)<span class="Italic">(43) (43) </span>lishʾov: to draw water hashqini: give me a drink<span class="Italic">(43) (43) </span>məʿaT: a little bit qaddekha: your water jar<span class="Italic">(43)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Kalo dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa minum sa! Deng nanti beta kasi minum bapa pung onta dong ju.&gt;&gt; Naa, itu jadi tanda bilang, itu nona yang Tuhan su pili jadi beta pung tuan muda pung bini!&gt;<bt>If she answers saying, &lt;&lt;Father just drink! And later I will give drinks to your camels also.&gt;&gt; Naa, [+shift] that will be a sign that, this is the young-woman whom the Lord has already chosen to be my young master's wife!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hokhiach (ykhh hif): determine, assign"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hokhiach (ykhh hif): determine, assign</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Beta balóm sambayang abis, te nona Ribka su datang bawa dia pung pareuk aer, ko timba aer di parigi. Waktu dia nae pi atas, ju beta minta bilang, &lt;Nona, kasi beta minum sadiki dolo.&gt;<bt>I had not-yet finished praying, and young-woman Ribka had come bringing her water jar, to fetch water at the well. As soon as she had climbed up, I asked saying, &lt;Young-woman, give me a bit to drink now.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəkhalleh (klh piʿel): I finished kadah:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾəkhalleh (klh piʿel): I finished kadah: large water pot<span class="Italic">(45) (45) </span>shikhmah: her shoulder tered (yrd): she went down<span class="Italic">(45)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="46" />Ju dia kasi turun dia pung pareuk aer capát-capát, ko bilang, &lt;Om minum sa! Deng nanti beta kasi minum om pung onta dong ju.&gt; Ais beta minum, deng beta pung onta dong ju minum.<bt>And she lowered her water jar quickly, and said, &lt;Uncle just drink! And then I will give drinks to your camels also.&gt; So I drank, and my camels also drank.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meʿaleyha: from on her shoulder tored"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">meʿaleyha: from on her shoulder tored (yrd hif): causes the thing to come down, lowers it<span class="Italic">(46) (46) </span>ʾesht (shth): I drank</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Ju beta tanya bilang, &lt;Nona pung bapa, nama sapa?&gt;<bt>Then I asked saying, &lt;What is young-woman's father's name?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais dia manyao bilang, &lt;Beta pung bapa, nama Betuel. Beta pung ba'i, Nahor. Deng beta pung nene, Milka.&gt; Ais ju beta kasi pake cincin di dia pung idong, deng taro satu pasang galáng mas di dia pung tangan.<bt>And she answered saying, &lt;My father's name is Betuel. My grandfather is Nahor. And my grandmother is Milka.&gt; So then I gave her a ring to wear in her nose, and put a pair of gold bracelets on her hand/arms.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeshʾal: I asked for, demanded"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾeshʾal: I asked for, demanded</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Tarús beta tondo ko sémba sang Tuhan bilang, &lt;Puji Tuhan! Tuhan su buka jalan kasi sang beta, sampe beta su dapa katumu langsung deng bos Abraham pung kelu di sini. Deng beta su dapa katumu langsung deng tuan muda Isak pung calon bini.&gt;<bt>Then I bowed-head to worship the Lord saying, &lt;Praise the Lord! The Lord has opened the way for me, to-point-that I have been able to meet directly with boss Abraham's family/kin here. And I have met directly with young master Isak's candidate for wife.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeqqod (qdd): I went down on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾeqqod (qdd): I went down on my knees Wenham: Genesis 11 says that Milcah is Haran's daughter. That means Rebecca is related to both of Abraham's brothers.<span class="Italic">(48) (48) </span>hinchani (hif nchh): led me, brought me bderekh ʾəmet: by the right road (but drk is not construct here). This (or the direct road) is the most common translation.<span class="Italic">(48) (48) </span>ʾəmet laqichat: to take continuing fidelity [?]</Message></Annotation><v n="49" />Jadi sakarang, kalo bapa dong mau kasi tunju sayang sang beta pung bos Abraham, na, kasi tau sang beta tarús taráng. Deng kalo sonde ju, na, kasi tau tarús taráng sa. Ko biar beta tau beta musti bekin apa.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) now, if you all (&lt;father (collective)) want to show your affection for my boss Abraham, na, tell me frankly/clearly. And if not, na, tell me frankly/clearly. So I can know what I must do.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeshkhem: there is with you all"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeshkhem: there is with you all ʿosim chesed (ʿsh ptc pl): act in loyalty. This may explain why the servant talks about linking up with his master's family, while Abraham himself did not say that.<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>ʾəmet: reliability, security, meeting obligation, lasting kindness, fidelity Imperative + imperfect: do it ... so I may ...<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>ʾefneh ʿal-yamin ʾo ʿal smoʾl: and I will turn to the right or the left; yes, or no and Iʾll explore other options; look for somebody else</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ribka pung kelu dong tarima pinangan<bt>Ribka's family accept the marriage proposal (lit. offer of betelnut)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Itu hamba omong abis, ju Laban deng Betuel manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo TUHAN su ator ame bagitu, na, botong mau bilang apa lai.<bt>[When] the servant finished speaking, Laban and Betuel answered saying, &lt;&lt;If the LORD has already arrange [things] like that, na, what else is there for us-exc to say.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʿan: answer, singular with plural animate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaʿan: answer, singular with plural animate NP OK yatsaʾ: came out<span class="Italic">(50) (50) </span>nowkhal (ykl): we are not able ; dabber (piʿel): to speak<span class="Italic">(50) (50) </span>raʿ ʾo tov: bad or good = there's nothing we can say one way or the other</Message></Annotation><v n="51" />Nona Ribka ada di sini. Ame sang dia ko bawa pi sana suda. Biar dia jadi ba'i Abraham pung ana mantu, iko apa yang TUHAN su ator.&gt;&gt;<bt>Young-woman Ribka is here. Get her and take her there. Allow her to become grandfather Abraham's daughter-in-law, according to what the LORD has already arranged.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hineh rivkah: here is Rebecca tahi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hineh rivkah: here is Rebecca tahi ʾishah (hyh imperf): she will become the wife<span class="Italic">(51) (51) </span>diber yhwh: God hadnʾt said anything to the servant, but he was involved in the matter.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Dengar bagitu, ju Abraham pung hamba tondo sampe di tana ko minta tarima kasi sang TUHAN.<bt>Hearing that, Abraham's servant bowed-head to the ground to give thanks to the LORD.</bt><v n="53" />Tarús dia angka kasi kaluar barang-barang mas-perak, deng pakean bagus-bagus ko kasi sang Ribka. Dia ju kasi sang Ribka pung kaka deng mama, hadia yang mahal-mahal.<bt>Then2 he lifted bringing out gold-silver things, and really nice clothes to give to Ribka. He also gave Ribka's older-sibling and mother, gifts that were very expensive.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayotseʾ (ytsʾ hif): he took out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayotseʾ (ytsʾ hif): he took out migdanot (meged): rich gifts, excellent things<span class="Italic">(53)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="54" />Ais itu, ju Abraham pung hamba, deng dia pung orang dong, dudu makan pesta. Ais dong tidor di situ. Dia pung beso pagi, dong bangun, ju itu hamba kasi tau sang tuan ruma bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta minta isin, ko kalo bisa, na, botong mau pulang sakarang pi beta pung bos.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Abraham's servant, and his people, sat down and ate in celebration/festively. Then they slept there. The next morning, they got up, and the servant told the master of the house saying, &lt;&lt;I ask permission, so that if possible, we would like to go back home now to my boss.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaliynu (lyn): they stayed overnight shalchuni"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaliynu (lyn): they stayed overnight shalchuni (imperv): sent me back<span class="Italic">(54)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Ma Ribka pung kaka deng dia pung mama bilang, &lt;&lt;Ko mau buru-buru barangkat bekin apa? Biar ko Ribka tenga deng botong barang sapulu hari bagitu dolo. Abis, na, bawa sang dia pi suda.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Ribka's older-sibling and her mother said, &lt;&lt;What are you in such a hurry to leave for? Allow Ribka to stay with us-exc for around ten more days or so first. After that, na, take her and go.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teshev (yshb): stay yamim ʾo ʿasor:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">teshev (yshb): stay yamim ʾo ʿasor: a few days or a block of ten days, up to a ten-day period, or possibly ten months; a few days or ten; a year or 10 months<span class="Italic">(55)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="56" />Ma itu hamba manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Aduu! Jang tahan sang beta! Te TUHAN su tolong sang beta, sampe beta su katumu sang tuan muda pung bini. Jadi mama dong lapás sang botong, ko botong pulang pi lapor sang bos dolo.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the servant responded saying, &lt;&lt;Aduu! Don't restrain me! Cause the LORD has assisted me, to-point-that I have met my young master's wife. So (consequently) mama (coll) release us, so that we can go-home and report to boss.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-taʾcharu ʾoti: donʾt delay me hitsliach"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-taʾcharu ʾoti: donʾt delay me hitsliach (tslch hif): cause to succeed<span class="Italic">(56)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Tarús dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Mari ko kotong tanya langsung sang Ribka sa. Dia pung mau karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they responded saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! Let's-inc just ask Ribka directly. What does she want?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqraʾ: we will call nishʾəlah (cohortative):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">niqraʾ: we will call nishʾəlah (cohortative): we will request it<span class="Italic">(57) (57) </span>et piah (peh): from her own mouth</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="58" />Ju dong pange sang dia ko tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Ribka! Sakarang tarsará lu sa. Lu mau iko memang deng ini orang, ko karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>And they summoned her to ask saying, &lt;&lt;Ribka! Now it's just up to you. Do you want to go right-away with this person, or how is it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais, itu nona manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta mau iko.&gt;&gt;<bt>So then the young-woman answered saying, &lt;&lt;I want to.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hətelkhiy: will you go?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hətelkhiy: will you go?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lari baroit--Isak deng Ribka kawin<bt>Leaving home [wedding phase (lit. running the bride) = female leaving her home to move to bridegroom's home]--Isak and Ribka marry</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lari baroit = antar mempelai perempuan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lari baroit = antar mempelai perempuan pi di dia pung laki pung ruma ; bawa lari = elope</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59-60" />Ais dong lapás sang Ribka, deng dia pung hamba parampuan yang urus sang dia dari kici, ko pi deng Abraham pung hamba dong. Ju dong omong kasi berkat sang Ribka bilang, &lt;&lt;Rika! Botong harap Tuhan kasi lu barana bam-banya, ko lu pung turunan nanti jadi baribu-ribu. Deng botong ju harap lu pung turunan dong kasi kala musu-musu dong!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they released Ribka, and her female servant/slave who had managed her from when she was small, to go with Abraham's servant (collective). And they spoke giving blessing to Ribka saying, &lt;&lt;Becka! We hope the Lord will give you many children, so your descendants will later become thousands. And we also hope your descendants will make their enemies lose!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾach: sister, kinswoman meniqtah (ynq ʾnurseʾ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾach: sister, kinswoman meniqtah (ynq ʾnurseʾ hif ptcpl): This woman was probably a slave who had taken over nursing Rebecca when she was a baby, and had worked for her ever since then. Named Deborah.<span class="Italic">(59) (59) </span>ʾat həyiy (hyh imperv): be! lʾalfe rvavah: one thousand times ten thousand (=10,000,000), more people than anybody can count<span class="Italic">(59) (59) </span>yiyrash ... et shaʿar: may you take possession of the gates, inherit, displace from land shaʿar: gate<span class="Italic">(59) (59) </span>sonʾaw: your [zarʿekha] enemy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Lb00040c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="61" />Ais itu, Ribka deng dia pung hamba parampuan dong manyimpan dong pung barang-barang, ju dong nae onta, ko barangkat memang iko Abraham pung hamba dong.<bt>After that, Ribka and her female servants packed their belongings, and they mounted the camels, to leave straight away, accompanying Abraham's servants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taqam ... tirkavnah: she got up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">taqam ... tirkavnah: she got up ... they rode telakhnah: they travelled<span class="Italic">(61) (61) </span>yiqqah ... et rivqah: he took Rebecca. It shouldnʾt imply that he left the other women behind. yelakh: he went<span class="Italic">(61)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="62" />Isak ada tenga di tana Negeb. Itu waktu, dia baru pulang dari parigi di Beer Lahai Roi.<bt>Isak was living in the land of Negeb. At that time, he had just come-home from the well at Beer Lahai Roi.</bt><v n="63" />Satu sore, dia kaluar dari tenda ko jalan-jalan cari angin. Dia angka muka, ju dia dapa lia onta dong datang.<bt>One afternoon, he came-out of [his] tent to stroll in relaxation (&lt;look for wind). He lifted his face, and he saw camels coming.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cari angin ; makan angin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">cari angin ; makan angin</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lasuach (swch inf): unknown word, dictionary"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lasuach (swch inf): unknown word, dictionary gives no meaning for it; unexplained, translations are only guesswork, hapax. REB "hoping to meet them", NLT "meditating", CEV "suddenly" basadeh: in the field, in the countryside<span class="Italic">(63) (63) </span>lifnot (pnh ʾturn, pass onʾ inf) ʿarev: as evening was coming on yissaʾ ʿeynayw: he lifted up his eyes, he took a look<span class="Italic">(63)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="64" />Waktu Ribka dapa lia sang Isak, ju dia turun capát-capát dari dia pung onta.<bt>When Ribka saw Isak, she got-down quickly from her camel.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tereʾ (rʾh): She didnʾt know yet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tereʾ (rʾh): She didnʾt know yet that it was Isaac, she just saw a man tifol (nfl): she got down quickly (could mean "tumbled" or "fell off", but probably doesn't here)<span class="Italic">(64)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="65" />Ais dia tanya sang Abraham pung hamba bilang, &lt;&lt;Om! Itu pak di sana yang ada jalan datang sini tu, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>And she asked Abraham's servant saying, &lt;&lt;Uncle! That mister who is walking over here there, who is it?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Itu hamba manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Dia tu, beta pung tuan muda.&gt;&gt; Ju Ribka ame dia pung salendang ko tutu dia pung muka.<bt>The servant answered saying, &lt;&lt;That is my young master.&gt;&gt; So Ribka took her scarf and covered her face.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hallazeh: this liqraʾtenu: toward us, coming"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hallazeh: this liqraʾtenu: toward us, coming up to meet us<span class="Italic">(65) (65) </span>tsaʿif: shawl, wrapper; possibly for general modesty, to show she was a modest person and not forcing herself on anybody. But a veil over the face was part of the marriage ceremony too, so this may have been her way of letting everybody know that she was ready to marry Isaac even if she had never seen him before in her life vatitkaS (kSh hitp): covered herself<span class="Italic">(65)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="66" />Ais, itu hamba lapor samua sang Isak.<bt>Then the servant reported everything to Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəSafer (piʿel): tell all the details"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yəSafer (piʿel): tell all the details</Message></Annotation><v n="67" />Tarús Isak bawa maso Ribka pi dalam dia pung mama pung tenda, ju dong dua kawin. Isak sayang mau mati sang Ribka, andia ko dia sonde susa lai deng dia pung mama pung mati.<bt>So then Isak took Ribka into his mother's tent, and the two of them married. Isak loved Ribka dearly, and so he was not in difficulty anymore with his mother's death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəviʾeah: he caused her to go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yəviʾeah: he caused her to go inside yeʾəhaveha: he loved her<span class="Italic">(67) (67) </span>yinnachem (nchm nif): he was comforted, found consolation End of P section.<span class="Italic">(67)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham kawin lai<bt>Abraham marries again</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="25" />
      <v n="1" />Abraham kawin lai deng satu parampuan, nama Ketura.<bt>Abraham married again with a woman, named Ketura.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayosef (hif): do something again. Some"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayosef (hif): do something again. Some commentators take this to have happened while Abraham was married to Sarah, when Esau and Jacob are around 15, partly by taking the references to concubines in verse 6 as including Keturah, since her children received no inheritance (the Code of Hammurabi stipulates that acknowledged children have the right to inherit), and partly because when the servant tells Laban that "my master has given everything to Isaac," it implies that Abraham is already dead and never met Rebecca. Neither point is without problems.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ketura barana kasi sang dia ana-ana, andia: Simran, Yoksan, Medan, Midian, Isbak, deng Sua.<bt>Ketura had children for him, named: Simran, Yoksan, Medan, Midian, Isbak, and Sua.</bt><v n="3" />Yoksan pung ana, Seba deng Dedan. Dedan pung turunan, andia orang Asyur, orang Letus, deng orang Leum.<bt>Yoksan's children, were Seba and Dedan. Dedan's descendants, were the people of Asyur, the people of Letus, and the people of Leum.</bt><v n="4" />Midian pung ana dong, andia: Efa, Efer, Henok, Abida deng Eldaa. Dong samua tu, Ketura pung turunan.<bt>Midian's had children, they are: Efa, Efer, Henok, Abida and Eldaa. All of them were descendants of Ketura.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The Hebrew doesn't mention Abraham. It"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">The Hebrew doesn't mention Abraham. It could be that Moses is playing up the Keturah line as something distinct from the Isaac and Ishmael lines, or that he is playing down Abraham because Keturah's children have no inheritance rights from him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-6" />Waktu Abraham masi idop, dia su bagi kasi Hagar deng Ketura pung ana-ana dong, satu-satu deng dia pung harta. Ais dia suru sang dong, ko pi tenga di tana Kana'an pung sablá matahari nae, ko biar dong jao dari dia pung ana Isak. Ma dia pung harta pusaka samua, dia sarakan kasi sang Isak.<bt>When Abraham was still alive, he had already divided up for Hagar and Ketura's children, each one with his things. Then he ordered them to go live in the eastern side of the land of Kanaan, so they would be far from his son Isak. But all of his inheritance/belongings, he turned over to Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hapilagshim: concubines. They had no dowry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hapilagshim: concubines. They had no dowry or marriage contract, and their children had no rights to inherit. It may cover Hagar and Keturah, or possibly others. The Midianites, including Mosesʾ father-in-law, traced their lineage to Keturah. matanot: gifts as settlements, one time only, possibly seed money for a new start<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>vayshalchem (piʿel): send away bʿodenu: while he was still living<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abraham mati<bt>Abraham dies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7-8" />Abraham mati waktu dia pung umur su 175 taon.<bt>Abraham died when he was already 175 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʾeleh: these (used in a summary)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʾeleh: these (used in a summary) yame shne-chaye Avraham: days of the years of the life of Abraham, his lifetime, period during which he functioned. This 4-term construct is rare, and is used here only, of Abraham. Ishmael in verse 12 gets only shne-chaye Avraham, as do others.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayigwa vayamat: breathed his last and died bsevah: in gray-headedness (he had lived a good life for a long time)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vsaveaʿ: sated, satisfied, had plenty of what he wanted vayeʾasef ʾel-ʿamav: gathered together with his family; die. SS prefers the "ancesta" spelling for this and other -Vr words. One of the earliest mentions of the afterlife and conscious immortality. Sarna points out that this phrase occurs only in the Torah; "sleep with one's fathers" is in the later books. Used only for very prominent people. Does not mean "buried with forefathers," but "went to join their illustrious ranks"; it's used of people like Jacob who werenʾt actually buried until quite a while after this is said of them.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9-10" />Ais dia pung ana Isak deng Ismael kubur sang dia di goa Makpela yang deka deng Mamre. Dolu Abraham béli itu kabón dari orang Het, andia Sohar pung ana Efron. Dolu dong ju su kubur sang Sara di itu goa.<bt>Then his children Isak and Ismael buried him in the cave of Makpela, which is near Mamre. Formerly Abraham had bought that field/garden from the Het people, that is [from] Sohar's son Efron. Formerly they had also buried Sara in that cave.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqbəru: they buried. ʿal-pne: physically nearby,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqbəru: they buried. ʿal-pne: physically nearby, as in Verse 18.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>qubbar (puʿal): was buried</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Abraham mati abis, ju Tuhan Allah kasi berkat sang Isak, sampe dia idop deng dame-sajahtra. Itu waktu, Isak tenga deka parigi, nama Beer Lahai Roi.<bt>After Abraham died, Lord God gave blessings to Isak, to-point-that he lived in peace-and-prosperity (idiom). At that time, Isak lived near a well named Beer Lahai Roi.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəʾer lachay roʾi: Da Puka Wea"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bəʾer lachay roʾi: Da Puka Wea Da God Dass Alive Wen See Me End of S section.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ismael pung turunan<bt>Ismael's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ini Ismael pung carita. Dia tu, Abraham deng dia pung bini muda Hagar pung ana. Hagar tu, Sara pung hamba dari Masir.<bt>This is Ismael's story. He was the son of Abraham and his younger-wife Hagar. Hagar, was Sara's servant/slave from Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tolədot: life and times of somebody,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tolədot: life and times of somebody, sometimes translated as "generations" or "genealogy," but it usually includes more than that. The Joseph story is part of the life and times of Jacob, the last big section of Genesis, which also includes the story of Judah, the other prominent son of Jacob. This section here is not very big, but it wraps up what Genesis has to say about Ishmaʿel</Message></Annotation><v n="13-16" />Ismael pung ana ada 12 laki-laki. Ini dong pung nama ba'iko-ba'iko dari yang sulung sampe deng yang bungsu, andia: Nebayot, Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam, Misma, Duma, Masa, Hadad, Tema, Yetur, Nafis, deng Kedma. Itu ana-ana dong, jadi nene-moyang dari dua blas suku-bangsa, satu-satu deng dia pung negrí sandiri. Dong kasi nama itu negrí, satu-satu iko dong pung moyang pung nama.<bt>Ismael had 12 sons. These are their names in succession (&lt;RECIP-follow reduplicated) from the eldest until the youngest, that is: Nebayot, Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam, Misma, Duma, Masa, Hadad, Tema, Yetur, Nafis, and Kedma. Those sons, became the ancestors of 12 races/peoples, each one with his own country/political land. They named those countries, each one following the name of their ancestor.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lətowlədotam: in their birth order chatsrehem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lətowlədotam: in their birth order chatsrehem: by their settlements (without walls) -- may be a way of reminding the Jews that these people never built real cities<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>Tirotam: and by their tent camps (with stone walls) -- also to emphasize that they never amounted to much nəsiʾim: chiefs or minor kings<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>lʾumotam: their nations, tribes</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ismael mati waktu dia pung umur su 137 taon.<bt>Ismael died while he was already 137 years old.</bt><v n="18" />Ma dia pung turunan dong, satu bamusu deng satu. Ais dong tenga tasiram mulai dari Hawila sampe Syur, yang babatas deng negrí Masir, tarús sampe di Asyur.<bt>But those descendants of his, they warred/made enemies with each other. so they lived scattered out beginning from Hawila until Syur, which borders with the country of Masir [Egypt], continuing on to Asyur.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***cross ref added from Amarasi check"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">***cross ref added from Amarasi check Oct 2005</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yigwaʿ: he died vayishknu: and they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yigwaʿ: he died vayishknu: and they settled, temporarily or long term<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>boʾakhah (bwʾ inf): your going, as you go ʾshurah: related to ʾashur, Keturah's grandson? The Assyrian people?<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ʿal-pney: opposite but in sight. REB and CEV take it to mean "in front, as you look in the canonical direction for giving directions," which computes as "to the east of" nafal: falling; opposite (or perhaps it implies conflict; scholars are not sure). Attacking? Something necessarily negative? Can also mean "settle" as in Judges 7:12.<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation><note reference="25:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Carita Mula-mula 16:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau deng Yakob<bt>Esau and Yakob</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ini Abraham pung ana Isak pung carita.<bt>This is Abraham's son Isak's story.</bt><v n="20" />Waktu Isak kawin deng Ribka, Isak pung umur 40 taon. Ribka pung bapa, Betuel. Deng dia pung kaka laki-laki, Laban. Dong tu, orang Aram dari Padan Aram.<bt>When Isak married Ribka, Isak was 40 years old. Ribka's father was Betuel. And her older brother, Laban. They were Aram people, from Padan Aram.</bt><note reference="25:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Padan Aram tu, andia Mesopotamia, di Siria pung sablá utara sana.<bt>That Padan Aram, is Mesopotamia at the north side of Siria.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ribka sonde dapa ana. Andia ko Isak sambayang sang TUHAN ko minta Dia buka Ribka pung tampa ana. TUHAN dengar dia pung sambayang, ju Ribka dudu parú.<bt>Ribka didn't have children. So Isak prayed to the LORD to ask the He open Ribka's womb (&lt;child place). The LORD heard his prayer, and Ribka got pregnant.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʿtar: he pled, entreated, prayed lnokhach:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʿtar: he pled, entreated, prayed lnokhach: directly in front of, [pray] for<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʿəqarah: barren yeʿater (nif): was moved by the entreaty<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>tahar (hrh): she became pregnant</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Padahal dia ada dudu parú sang dua ana. Ma itu ana dong maen bakosi tarús dalam dong pung mama pung parú. Ju Ribka batanya dalam hati bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko ini ana dua bagini, ni?&gt;&gt; Ais dia tanya sang TUHAN.<bt>Contrary-to-expectation, she was pregnant with two children. But those children kept wrestling inside their mother's abdomen. So Ribka asked in her liver saying, &lt;&lt;Why are these two children like this?&gt;&gt; So she asked the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayitrotsatsu (hitpolel): push each other around"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayitrotsatsu (hitpolel): push each other around (like sumo wrestlers?) bqirbah: in the inside of her body<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>ʾim-ken: if that's how it is lmah: why? painful pregnancy? threatened miscarriage? Or maybe (Calvin) it's the significance of the activity: If they are fighting now, is this a sign or prodigy of something worse? Syriac has "chayi" -- "If this is the way it is, why am I living?"<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>telekh lidrosh: go [where?] and turn in a petition to somebody</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ju TUHAN manyao bilang,<bt>And the LORD answered saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Dalam lu pung parú, ada dua bangsa yang nanti bamusu tarús.<bt>&lt;&lt;In your abdomen, there are two races/peoples who will war each other/be enemies with each other continually.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nanti yang bungsu lebe kuat dari yang sulung.<bt>The youngest will be stronger that the oldest.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Deng yang kaka karjá kasi dia pung adi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the older-sibling will work for his younger-sibling.&gt;&gt;biTnekha (beTen): your womb</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lʾumim (lʾom): ethnic community, people (archaic)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lʾumim (lʾom): ethnic community, people (archaic) mimeʿayika (meʿeh): from your belly, from inside you<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>yipparedu (nif): be apart, be cut off; separate themselves, be divided lʾom: people, ethnic community (old word)<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>yeʿəmats (imperf): will be strong, be stronger than (min) rav: the great one. Both terms in this context are referring to the family lines, not the two babies themselves. Alter: the subject is ambiguous, SVO or OVS (no object marker), like the Delphic oracle's speech; note the archaic wording.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>tsaʿir: the younger one</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Waktu dia pung hari su sampe, ju Ribka barana ame dua ana laki-laki bagambar.<bt>When her day had arrived, Ribka gave birth to two twin boys (&lt;RECIP-picture).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tomim (toʾm pl): twins"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tomim (toʾm pl): twins</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ana yang kaka pung warna mera, deng dia pung badan samua babulu. Andia ko dong kasi nama sang dia, <span class="Italic">Esau</span> (yang dia pung bunyi amper sama deng kata laen yang ada pung arti &lt;babulu&gt;).<bt>The elder-sibling was red in colour, and his whole body had body-hair. That is why they named him <span class="Italic">Esau</span> (which is similar to another word meaning &lt;hairy/furry&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾadmoni: reddish (red-brown like dried blood)."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾadmoni: reddish (red-brown like dried blood). This is a reddish skin color, not hair color. In medieval times it was thought that there was something sinister about redheads, so Judas was portrayed with red hair. But then, David had red hair: 1Sam 16:12; 17:42. kʾaderet seʿar: like a fur or hair garment, mantle of hair<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>seʿar: hair of head, pubic hair, hair made into a garment like a camel hair coat or a goat hair tent yiqrəʾu: they [probably the parents] called him; compare v.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Abis, baru dia pung adi kaluar. Ma dia ada pegang dia pung kaka pung tumit. Andia ko dong kasi nama sang dia, <span class="Italic">Yakob</span> (yang dia pung bunyi amper sama deng kata laen, yang ada pung arti &lt;tumit&gt;). Waktu barana sang dong dua, Isak pung umur su 60 taon.<bt>Finished, only-then did his younger-sibling come out. But he was holding his older-sibling's heel. That is why they named him <span class="Italic">Yakob</span> (which is similar to another word which means &lt;heel&gt;). When he gave-birth to the two of them, Isak was 60 years old.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾochezet (pt): hanging on to, grasping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾochezet (pt): hanging on to, grasping baʿəqev: by the heel (unless it's a euphemeism for genitals as in Jeremiah 13:22)<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>yiqrʾu ... vayiqraʾ: they called him Esau ... &lt;one person?&gt; called him Jacob. Some texts regularize both to plural, others both to singular. The singular one can be taken as impersonal. No children for 20 years, almost as long as Abraham had to wait (25 years).<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob tipu ame Esau pung hak sulung<bt>Yakob deceives taking Esau's eldest rights</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Waktu itu dua ana dong bésar datang, Esau jadi jago buru binatang. Dia suka tenga di utan. Ma Yakob tu pandiam, deng suka tenga di ruma sa.<bt>When those two children grew up, Esau became a champion animal hunter. He liked to live bush. But Yakob was a silent-type, and liked to just stay at the house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Jump in time from birth to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Jump in time from birth to at least adolescence, maybe even later. tsayid: game, hunting. Hunters are considered virile in our society, but at that time the contrast may have been between a stupid bumpkin that didnʾt have the sense to live a stable life and a smart pastoralist, who knew where his next meal was coming from because he controlled the animals.<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>sadeh: more likely conveys an undomesticated, untrammeled life rather than a rugged outdoorsman. tam: complete, orderly; peaceful, quiet; didnʾt make a lot of trouble. May imply that he had everything all together, self contained. The word is used of Noah to say that he was morally perfect. Here it might mean that Jacob was an ideal man of his time, which Esau wasnʾt. Probably doesn't mean that Esau was a real he-man and Jacob was a momma's boy. Karl Marx noted the frequency with which hunters and gatherers make the transition to a pastoral economy (there's evidence in East Africa that pastoral groups also transition back to hunting when ecological conditions shift JG); he overgeneralized it by elevating it to a principle, but it seems quite likely that at the time, Jacob seemed like the wave of the future (and Moses was part of that future, which Esau's descendants were not).<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>yoshev: living</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Isak suka makan daging binatang utan. Andia ko dia lebe sayang sang Esau. Ma Ribka lebe sayang sang Yakob.<bt>Isak liked to eat the meat of wild animals. That is why he loved Esau more. But Ribka loved Yakob more.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bfiw (peh): in his mouth From"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bfiw (peh): in his mouth From this point on, the second half of Genesis revolves around a long string of deceptions.<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00674c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Esau minta sop dari Yakob<bt>Esau requests soup from Yakob</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Satu kali, waktu Yakob ada masa sop kacang, Esau baru pulang dari baburu binatang. Dia cape deng lapar satenga mati.<bt>One time, when yakob was cooking bean soup, Esau had just returned from hunting animals. He was tired and extremely hungry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sop = soup"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sop = soup</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yazed: boiled, cooked nazid: a boiled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yazed: boiled, cooked nazid: a boiled dish (lentils, probably with spices). Commentators suggest Esau may have thought it was a meat stew or a blood broth because it was red.<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʿayef: exhausted, pooped; here it probably means famished.</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ju dia kasi tau sang Yakob bilang, &lt;&lt;Adi, é! Kasi lu pung sop mera di pareu sadiki dolo, ko beta isi beta pung parú! Te beta lapar mau mati.&gt;&gt; (Andia ko dong pange sang dia, <span class="Italic">Edom,</span> yang dia pung bunyi amper sama deng kata laen, yang ada pung arti &lt;mera&gt;.)<bt>So he said to Yakob saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sibling, é! Give some of your red soup there in that pot now, to fill my stomach! Cause I am really hungry.&gt;&gt; (That is why they refer to him as <span class="Italic">Edom</span>, which is simliar to another word meaning &lt;red-brown&gt;.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="halʿiyteni (hif): let me gulp down."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">halʿiyteni (hif): let me gulp down. A coarse word, "devour." In Rabbinical times it was used for feeding animals, but in older Hebrew it didnʾt necessarily have that meaning.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ais Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bae, kaka. Ma ofer kasi beta kaka pung hak sulung dolo!&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob answered saying, &lt;&lt;Good, older-sibling. But turn-over to me your elder rights first!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mikhrah (mkr imperv): sell The Jewish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mikhrah (mkr imperv): sell The Jewish commentators see this as cleverness or gamesmanship, an astute move on Jacob's part. The birthright had to do with things the father had control over, like possessions. The blessing, which is what Esau really got furious about missing, had to do with things the father had no control over, so it was more like a prophecy or the expression of a wish.<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="25:31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Iko dong pung adat, ana laki-laki sulung ganti dia pung bapa, deng dapa harta pusaka lebe banya dari dia pung adi dong.<bt>Following their adat/customs, the oldest male-child replaces his father, and gets more things/belongings than his younger-siblings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ju Esau manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Parsetan deng itu hak sulung! Lu soa sa. Beta su lapar mau mati ni. Lu sendo capát itu sop, ko bawa datang suda, te beta su mau makan.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Esau answered saying, &lt;&lt;To-hell-with those elder rights! You just take it. I am starving here. Quickly spoon out that soup and bring it here, cause I want to eat it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sendo = spoon it (vt) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sendo = spoon it (vt) ; parsetan! = fareek! , to hell with</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ma Yakob omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Bu tunggu dolo! Bu sumpa dolo bilang, bu su ofer kasi beta itu hak.&gt;&gt; Ju Esau angka sumpa bagitu.<bt>But Yakob spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;Older-sib wait a second! Older-sib swear-oath first that you have turned-over to me those rights.&gt;&gt; So Esau lifted up an oath like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshavʿah (shbʿ nif imperv): swear vayimkhor:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hishshavʿah (shbʿ nif imperv): swear vayimkhor: he sold<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Ais Yakob sendo kasi sang dia itu sop kacang, deng roti. Esau makan-minum abis, ju dia bangun jalan.<bt>So Yakob spooned out for him that bean soup, and bread. After Esau had finished eating-drinking, he got up and left.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Deng bagitu, Esau kasi parsén buang dia pung hak sulung.<bt>In that way, Esau gave away his elder rights.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿədashim: lentils, Lens lens The verb"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿədashim: lentils, Lens lens The verb sequence describes Esau's flippant attitude: "and in so doing, he trashed the birthright."<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>yivez (bzh impf): he despised, treated with contempt, thought lightly of End of S section.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Isak putar-balek raja Abimelek<bt>Isak deceives raja Abimelek</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="26" />
      <v n="1" />Satu kali, ada musim lapar yang hebat di itu negrí, sama ke musim lapar waktu Abraham masi idop. Jadi Isak pi minta isin sang Abimelek, orang Filistin pung raja, ko dia bisa tenga di Gerar.<bt>One time, there was an exceptional famine (&lt;hunger season) in that country, similar to the famine when Abraham still lived. So Isak went to ask permission from Abimelek, the raja of the Filistin people, so he could stay in Gerar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʿav: famine milvad (bad): besides|i(1) (1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raʿav: famine milvad (bad): besides<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʾavimelekh: "My Father Is King" sounds like a title like Pharaoh that is passed on from one generation to another, or a dynasty name like Kamehameha I, II, III, IV. Treated usually as a person's name. pəlishtiym: Philistines. Their archaeological sites show up in 1190 B.C., after the Exodus; but Abimelek may have been the leader of an early band that came from Caphtor (Crete Island and the adjacent coastlands of south Asia Minor, site of the Minoan civilization around 2000 B.C.) There were probably a few bands of Philistines in south Palestine during the time of Abraham and Isaac. They brought iron to Palestine; before that bronze was the metal used, and the Israelites got into using iron only later because they did not have access to its or know how to work it.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Dia bekin bagitu, tagal TUHAN su kasi tunju diri sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu jang pi Masir. Nanti Beta kasi tunju tampa laen sang lu.<bt>He did that, because the LORD had revealed Himself to him saying, &lt;&lt;You don't go to Masir. I will reveal to you another place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayeraʾ (rʾh nif): appear to someone,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayeraʾ (rʾh nif): appear to someone, make an appearance al-tered: donʾt go down (Egypt is always "down" from Canaan)<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>shkhon (imperv): stay</Message></Annotation><v n="3-4" />Kalo lu tenga manumpang di itu tampa, nanti Beta sama-sama deng lu, deng kasi lu berkat macam-macam. Nanti Beta bekin lu pung turunan dong batamba banya, sama ke bintang di langit. Deng Beta kasi lu deng lu pung turunan ini da'era deng dia pung negrí samua. Dari lu pung turunan, nanti samua suku-bangsa di dunya dapa berkat. Deng bagitu, Beta bekin jadi Beta pung janji sang lu pung bapa Abraham.<bt>If/when you stay temporarily in that place, I will be together with you, and give you various sorts of blessings. I will make your descendants increase in number, like the stars in the sky. And I will give you and your descendants this region and all its towns. From your descendants, all races/peoples in the world will get blessing. In that way, I will fulfill My promise with your father Abraham.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gur: stay as a stranger ʾasher:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gur: stay as a stranger ʾasher: which; probably not "the land I am telling you about", since he was already there<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>haʾəratsot: the lands. God's promise to Abraham was about haʾarets, singular. Isaac is already in a non-Canaanite area, and his wife is from another. haʾel: these<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>həqimotiy (qwm hif): I will raise up shvuʿah: oath<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>nishbaʿtiy (nif): I swore an oath hitbarakhu vzarʿakha (hitp): bless oneself, call oneself happy; wish a blessing to oneself; consider oneself to have been made capable of realizing one's potential, because of your descendants<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="26:3-4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Utusan dong pung Carita 3:25; Galatia 3:8</note><v n="5" />Beta bekin ini samua, tagal lu pung bapa su iko Beta pung mau, Beta pung parenta, deng Beta pung atoran.&gt;&gt;<bt>I do all this, because your father has followed My will, My commands, and My regulations.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿeqev ʾasher: the result of which"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿeqev ʾasher: the result of which is; because mishmarti: the obligation I laid on him<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>mitswoti: my commands chuqotai (chqh ptcpl): my statutes<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>torotai: my instructions. The variety of nouns may be like Deuteronomy; they are probably synonyms.</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Jadi Isak tenga tahan di Gerar.<bt>So Isak lived awhile in Gerar.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ribka tu, talalu manis. Jadi waktu orang-orang di situ lia sang dia, dong batanya so'al dia. Ma Isak manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ribka tu, beta pung adi.&gt;&gt; Dia taku kalo dia mangaku bilang dia pung bini, nanti itu orang dong bunu sang dia ko dong ame bawa Ribka.<bt>Ribka was very pretty (=sweet). So (consequently) when the people there saw her, they asked about her. But Isak responded saying, &lt;&lt;Ribka is my younger sister.&gt;&gt; He was afraid that if he acknowledged that she was his wife, those people would kill him so they could take away Ribka.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This section about Abimelek may be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">This section about Abimelek may be displaced from a time before the boys were born; there are no kids hanging around Rebecca. On the other hand, if it is in place chronologically, the boys are grown, and Rebecca is fortyish, but still beautiful. As with Abraham, the men lie to protect themselves, they place their wives in an awkward and dangerous position, and they get called on the carpet anyway.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yishʾəlu: they asked, demanded ʾanshey hamaqom: the people of the place<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yareʾ: he was afraid pen-yaharguni: lest they kill me<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Isak su tenga lama-lama di sana, ju satu kali raja maloi dari jandela, te dia dapa lia Isak deng Ribka ada bapaló-baciom.<bt>Isak had stayed there a long time, and once the raja peeped from [his] window, and [+contrary-to-expect] he saw Isak and Ribka were RECIP-hugging-kissing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barogo = putting hand into clothes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">barogo = putting hand into clothes (RECIP)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾarkhu-lo: days became long, they were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾarkhu-lo: days became long, they were there a long time Avi-Melek (dagesh): probably not the same person that Abraham tried to con, but his son. But the son probably knew the story, since it could have affected his mother.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vayashqef (hif): was looking down (from the point of view of somebody down below) bəʿad: through<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>mtsacheq (piʿel partcpl): laughing, playing; also a pun on name of Isaac, playing around, fondling</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ju dia suru orang dong pange ame Isak, ko dia togor bilang, &lt;&lt;Isak! Beta su tau parsís, itu parampuan tu, memang lu pung bini! Ma akurang ko lu bilang, dia tu, lu pung adi?&gt;&gt;<bt>So he ordered people to summon Isak, and he reprimanded saying, &lt;&lt;Isak! I know for sure, that woman there, is really your wife! But why did you say that she was your younger sister?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Isak manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini, bapa! Beta taku kalo beta bilang dia tu, beta pung bini, jang-jang nanti orang dong bunu mati sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>And so Isak answered saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, father! I was afraid that if I said she was my wife, people would probably kill me (&lt;may it not be that).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾakh: restrictive adverb (Waltke &amp; OʾConnor),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾakh: restrictive adverb (Waltke &amp; OʾConnor), "often essentially negators of continuity between clauses ... ʾI thought / It seemed to be otherwise but now I realize / it is obvious that...ʾ" Or "Now look! ..." ʾeykh: how? what?<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>ʿaleyah: because of her</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais raja manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo ada orang di sini yang tidor deng lu pung bini, pasti lu kasi sala sang botong! Akurang ko lu bekin bagitu sang botong?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the raja responded saying, &lt;&lt;If there was someone here who had slept with your wife, surely you would have accused us-exc! Why have you done that to us-exc?&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: The KM can be back translated as “accuse” or “given wrong” or “cause to be wrong”. TH notes “‘Guilt’ translates a noun meaning ‘offense’, ‘fault’, ‘sin’.” In shame-oriented societies like in eastern Indonesia, the closest to “cause to be guilty” is what the KM has.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mʿaT: almost, nearly; someone might easily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mʿaT: almost, nearly; someone might easily have taken her shakav: sleep, have intercourse<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>heveʾta (bwʾ hif): you would have caused guilt to come upon us ʾasham: guilt, consequences of doing something wrong. Used in Isaiah 53:10, guilt offering.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ais itu, ju Abimelek kasi inga karás sang dia pung rakyat bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong samua inga bae-bae! Bosong sapa yang barani ganggu ini orang, ko dia pung bini, nanti beta hukum mati sang dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, then Abimelek strongly reminded/warned his people/citizens saying, &lt;&lt;You all remember well! Whoever among you-pl dares to bother this person, or his wife, I will [+certain] punish him with death.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yətsaw (tswh piʿel): he ordered hanogeaʿ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yətsaw (tswh piʿel): he ordered hanogeaʿ: anyone touching<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mot yumat (hof): is to suffer death, be punished by death</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dong bakanjar so'al parigi<bt>They argue over wells</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="VS 12-16 moved here as intro"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">VS 12-16 moved here as intro to this section, *** Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Itu waktu, ju Isak batanam di itu negrí. Tarús dia dapa kambali dia pung hasil 100 kali, tagal TUHAN kasi berkat sang dia.<bt>At that time, Isak was planting/farming in that country. Subsequently he got returns of 100 times, because the LORD gave blessings to him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yizraʿ: he planted seeds yimtsaʾ: he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yizraʿ: he planted seeds yimtsaʾ: he found, achieved<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>meʾah shʿarim: 100 measures of grain, 100 fold increase (10,000%) shaʿar: measure<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>vayvarkhehu (piʿel): bestowed the power for success, prosperity, fertility on him (goes back to Gen 1)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Dia pung kaya batamba tarús, sampe dia jadi kaya talalu.<bt>His wealth kept increasing, to-point-that he became extremely wealthy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayelekh halokh: continuation and progress ʿad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayelekh halokh: continuation and progress ʿad: always, continuing into the future, continually<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Dia pung sapi deng kambing-domba dong tamba banya. Dia pung ana bua dong ju banya. Sampe orang Filistin iri sang dia.<bt>His cattle and goat-sheep increased in number. He also had many underlings. To-point-that the Filistin people were envious/jealous of him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqneh: landed property, livestock that one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miqneh: landed property, livestock that one owns ʿəvudah: collective, slaves and servants. String of nouns, sounds like the string of verbs at the end of Chapter 25.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vayqanʾu: they were envious, jealous, furious</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Dolu Isak pung bapa Abraham dong su gali banya parigi. Ma sakarang orang Filistin dong pi tutu ame itu parigi samua deng tana.<bt>Formerly Isak's father Abraham (collective) had dug many wells. But now the Filistin people went and closed up all those wells with dirt.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chafru: dug Sitmum (piʿel): they plugged"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chafru: dug Sitmum (piʿel): they plugged up<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yəmalʾum: they filled them up ʿafar: loose dirt<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais raja Abimelek omong deng Isak bilang, &lt;&lt;Isak! Lebe bae, lu barangkat kasi tenga ini negrí suda. Te lu pung kuasa su lebe dari botong.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then raja Abimelek spoke with Isak saying, &lt;&lt;Isak! It would be best if you go ahead and leave behind this country. Cause your power/authority is already more than ours-exc.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿatsamta: you are mighty, vast, numerous"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿatsamta: you are mighty, vast, numerous</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00220c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais itu, Isak ondor dari situ, ko pi tenga kambali di lemba Gerar.<bt>So then, Isak retreated from there, to go live again in the valley of Gerar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichan (chnh): camped for the night,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yichan (chnh): camped for the night, encamp for longer bnachal-grar: at the Wadi Gerar, intermittent stream<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ju dia gali ulang lai itu parigi-parigi, yang dong su tutu ame. Deng dia kasi nama itu parigi dong, iko nama-nama yang dia pung bapa su kasi nama sang dong.<bt>And he redug those various wells again, which they had closed. And he named those wells, according to the names which his father had named them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Some suggest that this verse belongs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Some suggest that this verse belongs after 15 (REB, but not NRSV) yashav: go back, do something again<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yachpor: he dug, had dug yəsatmum (stm piʿel): they plugged up the water springs<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>acharey mot avraham: after the death of Abraham - this overloads Pidgin syntax, and is implicit because of all that has been said</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Waktu Isak pung hamba dong gali parigi di lemba Gerar, ju dong gali kaná mata aer ko maspurak kaluar.<bt>Isak's servants dug a well in the valley of Gerar, and they dug connecting with a spring which artesianed out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="banachal: down in the wadi itself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">banachal: down in the wadi itself chayyim: running water coming out of that well, including in the dry season<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ma gambala Gerar dong bakanjar deng Isak pung gambala dong, tagal itu aer. Dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini botong pung aer!&gt;&gt; Andia ko Isak kasi nama itu parigi, <span class="Italic">Esek</span>, yang dia pung arti &lt;bakanjar&gt;.<bt>But the herders of Gerar argued [can include fighting] with Isak's herders, because of that water/spring. They said, &lt;&lt;This is our-exc water/spring!&gt;&gt; That is why Isak named that well, <span class="Italic">Esek</span>, which means &lt;argue/dispute&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarivu (ryv): dispute, quarrel in public"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yarivu (ryv): dispute, quarrel in public with complaints and reproaches, conduct a legal case, lawsuit hitʿassqu (ʿsq hitp): strive; they quarreled with him<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais itu, Isak pung orang dong gali satu parigi lai. Ma dong ju batangkár lai, tagal itu parigi. Andia ko Isak kasi nama itu parigi, <span class="Italic">Sitna,</span> yang dia pung arti &lt;baku malawan&gt;.<bt>After that, Isak's people dug another well. But they argued2 again, because of that well. That is why Isak named that well, <span class="Italic">Sitna,</span> which means &lt;oppose each other&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾacheret: another yarivu: dispute, as in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾacheret: another yarivu: dispute, as in 20<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>siTnah (sTn): accusation</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais itu, dia kasi tenga itu tampa, ju dia gali satu parigi laen lai. Ini kali dong sonde bakanjar. Andia ko Isak kasi nama itu parigi, <span class="Italic">Rehobot,</span> yang dia pung arti &lt;tampa luas&gt;. Deng dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang Tuhan su kasi kotong tenga di tana luas. Ais di sini, baru kotong bisa batamba banya.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, he left that place, and he dug a different well altogether. This time, they didn't argue. That is why Isak named that well, <span class="Italic">Rehobot,</span> which means &lt;wide/sufficient place/space&gt;. And he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Now the Lord has allowed us to live in a wide land. So here, can we only now be able to increase in number.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʿteq (ʿtq hif): move on, leave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaʿteq (ʿtq hif): move on, leave ravu (ryb): didnʾt dispute, contend<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>rchovot: open squares, plazas, from rchv open wide, broaden, extent, make room, provide wide room for, roominess hirchiv (hif): he provided wide room for us<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>parinu (prh): we are fruitful</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Dari situ, ju Isak dong barangkat lai ko mau pi tenga di Beer Syeba.<bt>From there, Isak (collective) departed again wanting to go live at Beer Syeba.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʿal (ʿlh): go up country, away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaʿal (ʿlh): go up country, away from Egypt, toward Jerusalem</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Itu malam, ju TUHAN kasi tunju diri sang dia, deng omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Isak! Beta ni, lu pung bapa Abraham pung Tuhan Allah. Jadi lu jang taku, te Beta jaga sang lu. Nanti Beta kasi berkat sang lu. Deng lu pung turunan nanti batamba banya. Beta bekin bagini, tagal Beta pung janji sang lu pung bapa.&gt;&gt;<bt>That night, the LORD revealed Himself to him, and spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Isak! I here, am the Lord God of your father Abraham. So (consequently) you don't be afraid, cuz (elaboration) I am guarding/watching/protecting you. I will give blessing to you. And your descendants will increase greatly in number. I do this, because of My promise to your father.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeraʾ (rʾh nif): he appeared, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeraʾ (rʾh nif): he appeared, he let himself be seen ʾal-tiyraʾ: do not be afraid<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>berakhtikha (piʿel): I will bless you hirbeytiy (hif): I will make them be numerous<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>baʿəvur: in order that (+ imperfect), in order to, on account of, for the price of; because of Abraham</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais Isak susun batu ko kasi bangun meja korban di situ. Ju dia minta tarima kasi sang TUHAN di itu tampa. Dia tenga di situ, deng dia pung orang dong mulai gali parigi lai.<bt>So Isak set up rocks to erect a sacrifice table there. And he gave thanks to the LORD in that place. He lived there, and his people began to dig wells again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The patriarchs seemed to set up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">The patriarchs seemed to set up an altar whenever God spoke to them, which was rarely. It not only let them reciprocate by making a sacrifice; it was a memorial to a life-changing experience. vayeT-sham (nTh): he set up his tent there, stretched it out<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>vayikhru (krh): they dug - different word than before</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja Abimelek deng Isak badame<bt>Raja Abimelek and Isak RECIP-peace</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Itu waktu, raja Abimelek datang dari Gerar. Dia sama-sama deng dia pung tamán Ahusat, deng dia pung panglima paráng, Fikol, datang katumu sang Isak.<bt>At that time, raja Abimelek came from Gerar. He together with his friend Ahusat, and his war commander, Fikol, came to meet with Isak.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tamáng &gt; tamán = ng form"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tamáng &gt; tamán = ng form seen as Ambon influence</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mereaʿ: intimate, close friend"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mereaʿ: intimate, close friend</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ju Isak tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja! Dolu bosong su usir kasi kaluar sang botong. Jadi sakarang bosong mau datang bekin apa lai?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Isak asked saying, &lt;&lt;Father raja! Formerly you-pl kicked us out. So now what else have you come to do?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maduaʿ: why? baʾatem: have you come?|i(27)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">maduaʿ: why? baʾatem: have you come?<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>sneʾtem ʾoti: you hate me. This sounds like an inhospitable statement. God had told Isaac not to be afraid and repeated his promise, so Isaac, instead of being a wuss, stood up to Abimelek.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ais dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Sakarang botong tau bilang, Tuhan jaga sang lu. Andia ko botong pikir-pikir, lebe bae kotong dua bekin janji bagini: lu sumpa bilang,<bt>So they answered saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! Noe we know that the Lord watches/guards you. Because of that, we have been thinking, it would be best if the two of us-inc make a promise like this: You-sg should swear-oath saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʾo raʾiynu (inf abs): we see,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raʾo raʾiynu (inf abs): we see, we get the picture ʾalah: an obligation by oath which puts a curse on the transgressor<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>beynoteynu: between us beyniynu uveynekha: between you and us<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>nikhrətah brit (krt): let's make an agreement, cut a deal</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />bosong sonde akan bekin jahat sang botong, sama ke botong ju sonde bekin jahat sang bosong. Memang botong pung hati bae deng bosong. Andia ko tempo hari, bosong kaluar deng dame dari botong pung tana. Botong su tau batúl, TUHAN yang kasi berkat sang bosong.&gt;&gt;<bt>you-pl will not do evil to us-exc, just like we-exc also will not do evil to you-pl. Our-exc liver is truly good with you-pl. That is why at that time you-pl left in peace from our-exc land. We-exc already know the truth, the LORD is the one who has given blessing to you-pl.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəjgʿanukha: harm, hurt, touch bshalom: in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nəjgʿanukha: harm, hurt, touch bshalom: in good condition, in peace, unhurt. "let you go way" same word as "throw me outa yoa land" in verse 27.<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʿattah: as of now, from this time forward? baruch yʾ: blessed of the Lord (passive partcpl). "see" from v. 28<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ais Isak bekin pesta kasi sang dong, ju samua makan-minum rame-rame.<bt>So Isak made a celebration for them, and everyone ate-drank festively together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishteh: feast with wine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mishteh: feast with wine</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ais dia pung beso papagi, ju dong ba'angka sumpa. Tarús Isak kasi lapás sang dong, ko dong pi deng dame.<bt>And then early the next morning, they RECIP-lifted oaths. Then Isak released them, and the went in peace.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkiymu: they got up early yishshavʿu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yashkiymu: they got up early yishshavʿu: they swore oaths each to the other<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>bshalom: cessation of hostilities? good feeling?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Itu hari, Isak pung orang karjá dong datang lapor so'al parigi yang dong gali bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! Botong su dapa aer.&gt;&gt;<bt>That day, Isak's workers came and reported about the well which they were digging saying, &lt;&lt;Father! We've found water.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayagidu lo: they reported to him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayagidu lo: they reported to him ʿal-ʾodot: on account of<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Ais Isak kasi nama itu parigi, <span class="Italic">Syeba,</span> yang dia pung arti &lt;sumpa&gt;. Jadi dong kasi nama itu kota <span class="Italic">Beer Syeba, </span>sampe sakarang.<bt>So Isak named that well, <span class="Italic">Syeba,</span> which means &lt;swear-oath&gt;. So (consequently) they named that city <span class="Italic">Beer Syeba, </span>until now.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿal-ken: as a result End of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿal-ken: as a result End of S section<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="26:33" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Syeba</span> pung arti bisa &lt;sumpa&gt;, ko &lt;tuju&gt;, ko &lt;nasib bae&gt;. Dalam bahasa Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Beer</span> pung arti bilang &lt;parigi&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language, 'Syeba' means 'oath', or 'seven', or 'good luck/fate'. In the Ibrani language, <span class="Italic">Beer</span> means &lt;well&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau kawin deng dua parampuan dari suku laen<bt>Esau marries two women from other tribes/clans</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Waktu Esau umur 40 taon, ju dia kawin deng dua nona dari suku Het. Yang satu, Beeri pung ana, nama Yudit. Deng yang satu lai, Elon pung ana, nama Basmat.<bt>When Esau was 40 years old, he married two young-women from the tribe of Het. The one was Beeri's child, named Yudit. And the other one, was Elon's child, named Basmat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Esau's action sounds like he is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Esau's action sounds like he is flouting convention and opting to not let a marriage develop the way his father set up for his brother. Isaac is 100 years old at this point. beʾeri: ʾmy wellʾ - perhaps everybody had wells on the brain.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Itu dua parampuan tu, bekin Isak deng Ribka pung hati susa.<bt>Those two women, made Isak and Ribka's livers difficult.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tihyeyna: they were morat ruach (mrr"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tihyeyna: they were morat ruach (mrr ʾbitterʾ? mrh ʾprovocationʾ?): bitterness of spirit, affliction<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ribka tipu Isak ko kasi berkat sang Yakob<bt>Ribka deceives Isak to give Yakob a blessing</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** changed at Dhao check, Sept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** changed at Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="27" />
      <v n="1" />Waktu Isak su tua, dia pung mata su talalu kabur, ju dia pange dia pung ana sulung yang dia paling sayang bilang, &lt;&lt;Sau! Lu mari sini dolo!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Isak was old, his eyes were very cloudy, and he summoned his oldest child, whom he loved most saying, &lt;&lt;Sau! Come here now!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Esau manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana, papa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Esau responded saying, &lt;&lt;What is there, father?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiqraʾ: not clear whether Esau was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiqraʾ: not clear whether Esau was staying at some distance away, or close by. tikhhena (khh): became expressionless, colorless, clouded [cataracts?]<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>hineni: Here "behold" wonʾt work at all. A response to a greeting from a blind man would be &lt;&lt;Dass me.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Isak kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Beta ni, su tua. Beta sonde tau kapan beta mati.<bt>Isak told him saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! I am already old. I don't know when I will die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Isaac may have been discouraged because"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Isaac may have been discouraged because of his encroaching blindness, or just felt like he was going to die. He actually lived for years after this event.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Jadi pi ame lu pung sanjata dong, ko pi buru kasi beta binatang utan satu dolo.<bt>So (consequently) go fetch your weapons, and go hunt me a wild animal.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saʾ-na (nsʾ): take up keleykha: your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">saʾ-na (nsʾ): take up keleykha: your implements<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>telyəkha: your hanger (tlh), quiver for arrows. SK quiver = someting shake qashtekha: your bow<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>tseʾ (ytsʾ): go tsuwdah (tswd imperv): hunt<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>tsedah, ktiv tsayid: provisions for a journey, ktiv game</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ais lu masa ena-ena iko beta pung suka, ko bawa datang kasi beta. Nanti makan abis, baru beta kasi berkat memang sang lu. Kalo su kasi berkat abis sang lu, biar beta mati, ju bae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then cook it deliciously according to the way I like, and bring it to me here. Then later after eating, only-then will I give blessing directly to you. When I have finished giving you blessing, allow me to die, is also good (= it's OK if I die).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matʿammiym: tidbits ʾahavtiy: I love|i(4) (4)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">matʿammiym: tidbits ʾahavtiy: I love<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>baʿəvur: on account of tvarekhkha nafshi (piʿel imperf): so my soul may bless you<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ais ju Esau kaluar ko pi buru binatang. Ma Ribka ju dapa dengar Isak pung omong tu.<bt>So then Esau went out to go hunt animals. But Ribka had also heard what Isak had said then.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shomaʿat: concurrent participle, simultaneous actions bəno:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shomaʿat: concurrent participle, simultaneous actions bəno: Esau is called "Isaac's boy" and "Jacob's brother". Jacob is "Rebecca's boy". Rebecca isn't "Isaac's wife". Maybe Rebecca is the most dysfunctional of the lot.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ais Ribka pi kasi tau sang Yakob bilang, &lt;&lt;We, Ako! Lu dengar bae-bae! Tadi beta baru dapa dengar bapa ada omong deng Esau bagini:<bt>So Ribka went ad told Yakob saying, &lt;&lt;We, Jake! Listen well! I just now heard father speaking with Esau like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mdabber (piʿel partcpl): saying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mdabber (piʿel partcpl): saying</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />&lt;Lu pi buru satu binatang utan, ko masa ena-ena kasi sang beta. Kalo beta su makan abis, nanti beta kasi berkat sang lu di TUHAN pung muka.&gt;<bt>&lt;Go hunt a wild animal, to cook it deliciously for me. When I have finished eating, then I will give blessing to you, in the LORD's face (=in front of the LORD).&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vrakhah: I will give you my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vrakhah: I will give you my formal blessing -- irrevocable, with Yahweh as witness lifne (like bterem): future, impending death<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Jadi lu dengar bae-bae! Iko batúl-batúl deng beta pung parenta ni.<bt>So (consequently) listen carefully! Follow carefully these commands of mine.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mtsawwah: I am ordering you to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mtsawwah: I am ordering you to do</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Sakarang lu pi di kotong pung tampa kambing-domba, ko pili ame dua kambing ténak yang gumu-gumuk. Ais potong ko ame dia pung daging, deng bawa kasi beta. Nanti beta masa, iko lu pung pung bapa pung suka.<bt>Now you go to our-inc place of goats-sheep, and select out two fat young goats. Then cut/butcher them to take their meat, and bring it to me. I will cook it, according to how your father likes it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gdayey ʿizzim: baby goats"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gdayey ʿizzim: baby goats</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Kalo be su masa abis, na, lu bawa pi kasi lu pung bapa ko dia makan. Ais nanti dia kasi berkat sang lu dolo, baru dia mati. Deng bagitu, lu yang dapa itu berkat. Bukan lu pung kaka.&gt;&gt;<bt>When I have finished cooking it, na, you take it to give to your father so he can eat it. In that way, you are the one who gets that blessing. Not your older sibling.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʿəvur: on account of yvarekhəkha: so"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">baʿəvur: on account of yvarekhəkha: so he will bless you. This is a single, irrevocable act.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ma Yakob omong deng dia pung mama bilang, &lt;&lt;Mama! Dia pung masala, bagini. Bu Sau pung badan babulu, ma beta pung badan licin!<bt>But Yakob spoke with his mother saying, &lt;&lt;Mama! The problem is like this. Older-brother Sau has a furry body, but my body is smooth!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: look! emphasizes the following word,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hen: look! emphasizes the following word, phrase, or clause. Used in agreeing Gen 30:34 saʾir: hairy, shaggy<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>chalaq: smooth, smooth-skinned</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Jang-jang nanti bapa raba kaná beta pung badan, dia tau memang beta tipu sang dia. Ju dia kutuk sang beta!&gt;&gt;<bt>There's a good chance father will grope connecting with my body, and he will know immediately that I am deceiving him. Then he'll curse me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾuwlay: perhaps ymusheni (mshsh): he will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾuwlay: perhaps ymusheni (mshsh): he will touch me, feel me<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>mətaʿteaʿ (tʿʿ pilpel): one who acts up (in this case, profaning something solemn) heveʾtiy (bwʾ hif): I will bring on myself<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>qalalah: a curse, both in action and in formula</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Dia pung mama manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ako, é! Lu jang kawatir. Sarakan sa, nanti mama yang ator! Kalo lu pung bapa kutuk sang lu, biar mama yang pikol sa! Sakarang lu pi ame itu kambing suda.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then his mother responded saying, &lt;&lt;Jake, é! Don't you worry. Just turn it over, so mama is the one who organises it! If your father curses you, just let mama be the one to shoulder-carry it! Now you go get that goat now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾakh: assurance, restriction ʾjust do as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾakh: assurance, restriction ʾjust do as I sayʾ</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais itu, Yakob pi pili ame itu kambing dong, ju dia potong ko bawa kasi dia pung mama. Tarús Ribka bamasa iko Isak pung suka.<bt>After that, Yakob went and selected the goats, and he butchered, to bring to his mother. Straightaway Ribka cooked (it) according to how Isak liked.</bt><v n="15" />Ais Ribka pi ame Esau pung pakean yang bagus, ko kasi Yakob pake.<bt>Then Ribka went and got Esau's nice clothes, to give Yakob to wear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bigdey (beged): clothes of chəmudot: desirable,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bigdey (beged): clothes of chəmudot: desirable, precious, delightful<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>talbesh (lbsh hif): she clothed qaTan: small, younger (by minutes, but that didnʾt matter)<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Dia ju bungkus Yakob pung tangan deng dia pung leher, pake itu kambing pung bulu.<bt>She also wrapped Yakob's hands/arms and his neck, using the fur of the goat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barbák = long and full beard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">barbák = long and full beard (like santa Claus, Alan Rogers)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿorot: hides hilbishah (lbsh hif): she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿorot: hides hilbishah (lbsh hif): she put something on somebody, dressed him. Goat hair and hide are not very thick, and feel like human hair much more than sheep's wool does.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>yadayw: hand and arm, hand and wrist, hand alone. Probably the first. chelqat tsawaʾraw: the hairless, smooth portions of the neck<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tsawwaʾrayw: the back of his neck</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Tarús dia kasi sang Yakob itu makanan enak, deng roti yang dia su bekin.<bt>Then she gave Yakob the delicious food, and bread which she had made.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00679c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Isak omong kasi berkat sang Yakob<bt>Isak speaks giving blessing to Yakob</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ais Yakob pi antar itu makanan kasi dia pung bapa. Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! Beta su datang ni.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob went to take that food to his father. He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Father! I've come now.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Isak manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Heh? Ko, lu ni sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Isak responded saying, &lt;&lt;He? What? Who are you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Tarús Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, bapa pung ana sulung, Esau! Beta su bekin iko apa yang bapa suru tadi tu. Bangun ko makan suda. Beta su masa itu daging yang beta su tangkap ame di utan. Makan, ko abis bapa kasi berkat sang beta suda!&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Yakob reponded saying, &lt;&lt;I am your oldest child, Esau! I have already done what father ordered me to do earlier [today]. Get up so you can eat. I've cooked the meat which I have successully caught in the bush. Eat, so afterwards father will give blessing to me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shvah (imperv): sit up baʿəvuwr: on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shvah (imperv): sit up baʿəvuwr: on account<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nafshekha: you (indirect reference to him as a person). Might mean "with all your heart"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ais Isak omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu ni hebat, ó! Ko lu bisa dapa binatang capát bagitu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Isak spoke saying, &lt;&lt;You are very impressive, ó! How [in the world] could you get an animal so quickly!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta dapa ni, tagal TUHAN yang bapa sémba tu, ada tolong sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob responded saying, &lt;&lt;I got this, because the LORD whom father worships, was helping me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miharta (mhr): you did it quicker"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miharta (mhr): you did it quicker than expected hiqrah (hif): make something happen, let something happen, ordain, direct, with lifnay for ʾmeʾ<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Tarús Isak pange sang Yakob bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu datang deka-deka, ko beta raba coba sang lu! Lu ni batúl Esau, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Isak summoned Yakob [closer] saying, &lt;&lt;Come here close, so I can feel-test you! Are you really Esau, or [what]?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gshah-naʾ (ngsh imperv): approach ʾəmushkha (mshsh):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gshah-naʾ (ngsh imperv): approach ʾəmushkha (mshsh): I will feel you<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais Yakob pi deka-deka dia pung bapa, ju bapatua mulai raba sang dia. Tarús dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini suara ni, sama ke Yakob pung suara! Ma ini tangan ni, Esau pung tangan.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob went close to his father, and the old-man began to feel him. Then he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;This voice here, is like Yakob's voice! But this hand/arm, is Esau's hand.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="farkót = pilek, cold (Bel. ferkout)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">farkót = pilek, cold (Bel. ferkout)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ymushshehu (mshsh qal): he felt him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ymushshehu (mshsh qal): he felt him</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ma Isak sonde kanál sang Yakob, tagal dia pung tangan babulu sama ke Esau. Ma waktu dia mau kasi berkat sang Yakob,<bt>But Isak didn't recognise Yakob, because his hand/arm was hairy/furry the same as Esau's. But when he was about to give blessing to Yakob,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hikhiro (nkr hif): recognize should this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hikhiro (nkr hif): recognize should this come later?<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>səʿirot: hairy</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />dia tanya ulang lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu ni, batúl-batúl Esau, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>he asked once again saying, &lt;&lt;You here, really are Esau, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tarús Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Batúl papa!&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yakob answered saying, &lt;&lt;Really father!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais ju Isak omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu sorong datang itu daging, ko beta mau makan. Abis, baru beta kasi berkat sang lu.&gt;&gt; Tarús Yakob sorong kasi itu daging sang dia, deng kasi aer anggor ko dia minum.<bt>So then, Isak spoke saying, &lt;&lt;You bring that meat over here, so I can eat it. Afterwards, I will give blessing to you.&gt;&gt; So Yakob scooted the meat over to him, and gave him grape juice/wine to drink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hagisha li (ngsh hif): bring it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hagisha li (ngsh hif): bring it close to me tvarekhkha (piʿel): for it (me?) to bless you. Why the feminine singular subject?<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Ais itu, dia pung bapa omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana, é! Mari deka-deka sini, ko ciom sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, his father spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Child, é! Come real close here, to kiss me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gshah-naʾ (ngsh): come close shqah-li (nshq):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gshah-naʾ (ngsh): come close shqah-li (nshq): kiss me (appropriate for a son to his father)<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Waktu Yakob pi deka-deka ko ciom sang dia, ju Isak dapa ciom Esau pung pakean pung baboo. Ais dia omong kasi berkat sang Yakob bilang,<bt>When Yakob went close to kiss (ciom) him, then Isak smelled (ciom) Esau's clothes odour. So he spoke giving blessing to Yakob saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Beta pung ana pung baboo, sama ke padang rumput yang TUHAN su kasi berkat.<bt>&lt;&lt;My child's odour, is like a grass field which the LORD has blessed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayarach reach (rwch hif): smell the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayarach reach (rwch hif): smell the smell, odor of his clothes rʾeh: look!<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>berəkho: he blessed it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="28" />Biar Tuhan Allah kasi turun embun dari langit,<bt>May Lord God bring down dew from the sky,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko bekin lu pung kabón dong jadi subur!<bt>to make your fields/gardens become fertile!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Biar Dia kasi lu padi limpa-limpa,<bt>May He give you an abundance of rice/grain,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">deng bua anggor ponu-ponu.<bt>and grape fruits that are really full.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tal: dew, light rain shmanne haʾarets:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Tal: dew, light rain shmanne haʾarets: fat (=fertile) fields<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>rov: abundance dagan: cereal grain, not just wheat<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>tirosh: old word for wine; ritual and poetic</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="29" />Bangsa-bangsa dong jadi lu pung hamba,<bt>Races/peoples will be/become your servants/slaves,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng suku-suku dong, tondo kasi hormat sang lu.<bt>And tribes/clans, will bow-head giving respect to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Biar lu parenta sang lu pung sodara dong samua,<bt>May you govern all your siblings,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng dong tikam lutut di lu pung muka.<bt>and they bow in front of you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sapa yang kutuk sang lu, dong ju dapa kutuk.<bt>Whoever curses you, they will also be cursed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng sapa yang kasi berkat sang lu, dong ju dapa berkat.&gt;&gt;<bt>And whoever gives blessing to you, they will also get blessing.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʿavduwkha: they will work for you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaʿavduwkha: they will work for you həweh (hwh imperv): become<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>gvir: lord, master acheykha: he only had one brother<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>yishtachəwwu: they will bow down ʾorərekha ʾarur (ʾrr partcpl pl): the ones who curse you will be cursed<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>mvarkhekha barukh: the ones who bless you will be blessed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau pulang, deng minta Isak kasi berkat sang dia ju<bt>Esau returns home, and asks Isak to give him a blessing as well</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Waktu Isak kasi berkat abis, ju Yakob baru kaluar kasi tenga dia pung bapa, dia pung kaka Esau pulang bawa binatang yang dia dapa tangkap.<bt>As soon as Isak had finished giving the blessing, and Yakob had just gone out leaving his father, then his older-sibling Esau returned home bringing the animal that he had caught.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khilah (piʿel): as Isaac finished vayhi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">khilah (piʿel): as Isaac finished vayhi ʾak yatsoʾ yatsaʾ (inf abs + perf): and what do you know? Just as Jacob was on his way out<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>vesaw ʾachiw baʾ: his brother Esau of all people came in</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ju dia pi bamasa, ais dia bawa kasi dia pung bapa. Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa! Bangun ko makan suda. Beta su masa itu daging yang beta tangkap. Abis makan, na, papa kasi berkat sang beta suda.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he went and cooked it, and he brought it to his father. He spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Get up and eat. I've cooked the meat that I caught. After you eat, na, father should give [the] blessing to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam: where does it fit? yaqum"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gam: where does it fit? yaqum (3sg imperf): sit up, get up, get ready to eat; deferential<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>yoʾkhal (3sg imperf): eat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ju Isak bingung, deng tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Heh! Ko lu ni, sapa lai?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Isak was surprised, and asked saying, &lt;&lt;He! So who are you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais Esau manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, Sau! Papa pung ana sulung.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Esau answered saying, &lt;&lt;I am Sau! Your oldest child.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Does this assume that Isaac is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Does this assume that Isaac is getting senile, or that he is getting mixed signals from voice versus other senses?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ju Isak mulai gamatar. Ais bapatua tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bagitu, tadi tu, sapa yang bawa kasi beta itu daging, ko beta su makan? Ais ju beta su kasi berkat sang dia. Deng sonde bisa cabu lai itu berkat.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Isak began to shake/tremble. Then the old-man asked saying, &lt;&lt;If that is the case, just now, who was it who brought me that meat for me to eat? And then I have already given blessing to him. And I cannot revoke/repeal/unplug that blessing.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yechərad: tremble, shudder; shake violently chəradah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yechərad: tremble, shudder; shake violently chəradah gdolah ʿad-mʾod: with great fear<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>mi-ʾefoʾ: who then?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Dengar dia pung bapa omong bagitu, ju Esau saki hati deng manangis makarereu, deng omong karás-karás bilang, &lt;&lt;Aduuu! Papa, é! Kasi berkat sang beta ju, papa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing his father speak like that, Esau was sick livered (=sad/angry/upset), and wailed, and spoke loudly/sharply saying, &lt;&lt;Aduuu! Father, é! Give me a blessing too, father!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayitsʿaq tsəʿaqah: he raised a wailing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayitsʿaq tsəʿaqah: he raised a wailing cry, a loud and bitter cry. Probably not a pun against tsachaq. marah ʿad-mʾod: totally bitter feeling, gloomy heart, provoked, embittered, furious<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ma Isak bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pung adi su datang tipu ame sang beta, deng curi bawa lu pung berkat.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Isak said, &lt;&lt;Your younger-sibling has come and successfully deceived me, and stolen away your blessing.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***connector changed to But, Amarasi check"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">***connector changed to But, Amarasi check Oct 2005</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bmirmah: in deceit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bmirmah: in deceit</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Tarús Esau omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Dia su tipu sang beta dua kali. Dolu dia tipu ame beta pung hak sulung. Sakarang dia tipu ame lai beta pung berkat. Pantas dia pung nama, &lt;Yakob&gt;. Ma papa masi ada pung berkat laen lai kasi beta, ko?&gt;&gt; (Nama Yakob pung arti &lt;pegang di tumit&gt;. Ma dia pung arti laen &lt;tukang tipu&gt;.)<bt>Then Esau spoke syaing, &lt;&lt;He has deceived me two times. At first he successfully deceived taking away my elder rights. Now he has successfully deceived taking away my blessing. It is appropriate that his name is, &lt;Yakob&gt;. But father still has another blessing for me, right?&gt;&gt; (The name Yakob, its meaning is &lt;he holds/grabs the heel&gt;. But it has another meaning &lt;trickster, deceiver&gt;.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** FTN contents moved into end"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** FTN contents moved into end of verse, Dhao check, Sept 2004</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʿəqveni: he cheated me. paʿəmayim (dual):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaʿəqveni: he cheated me. paʿəmayim (dual): both times<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>ʾatsalta (ʾtsl): you have laid by</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ais ju Isak manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su angka sang dia jadi lu pung bos. Deng dia pung sodara samua su jadi dia pung hamba. Beta su kasi sang dia padi limpa-limpa, deng anggor ponu-ponu. Jadi ana, é! Sakarang masi ada berkat apa lai, yang beta bisa kasi sang lu?&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Isak answered saying, &lt;&lt;I have already elevated him to be your boss. And all his siblings, have [elevated to] become his servants/slaves. I have given him rice/grain in abundance/excess, and grapes that are very full. So (consequently) child é! Now what other blessing is there, that I can give to you?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lakh (fem): for you [?] smakhtiw:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lakh (fem): for you [?] smakhtiw: I propped him up, supported him with things<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>ʾefowʾ mah: what then?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Dengar bagitu, ju Esau maen noki tarús sang dia pung bapa bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa pung berkat cuma satu sa, ko? Pasti bapa masi bisa cari kasi beta berkat laen. Biar berkat kici sa ju bae!&gt;&gt; Ju dia mulai manangis lai.<bt>Having heard that, Esau kept coaxing (idiom) his father saying, &lt;&lt;Does father only have just one blessing? Surely father can still find a different blessing for me. Even just a small blessing would be good!&gt;&gt; And he even began to cry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maen noki = kokoe, bujuk, minta"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">maen noki = kokoe, bujuk, minta dgn sangat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʾ (nsʾ): he lifted up his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yissaʾ (nsʾ): he lifted up his voice</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ais itu, ju Isak manyao bale sang dia bilang,<bt>After that, Isak responded back to him saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lu pung idop nanti jao dari kabón yang subur,<bt>&lt;&lt;Your life will be far from fields that are fertile,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te sonde ada embun yang turun dari langit ko bekin basa lu pung tana.<bt>cause there is no dew to come down from the sky to make wet your land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="min: in contrast to verse 28,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">min: in contrast to verse 28, which is partitive, this sounds like the directional use. shmanney (shaman): the fat<span class="Italic">(39) (39) </span>mowshavekha: your dwelling place Some Jewish commentators see this blessing as equivalent, though complementary. Protestant commentators tend to see it as negative.<span class="Italic">(39)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="40" />Lu pung kalewang yang nanti kasi lu idop.<bt>Your fighting-sword will give you life/be your means of living.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ma biar karmana ju, lu jadi hamba sang lu pung adi.<bt>But no matter what/nevertheless, you will be/become a servant to your younger-brother.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Cuma kalo lu bisa malawan sang dia, nanti baru lu bisa talapás dari dia pung tangan.&gt;&gt;<bt>Only if you are able to oppose him, only-then will you be free from his hand.&gt;&gt; [Recheck for Hebraism.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʿəvod: you will work tariyd (ryd?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">taʿəvod: you will work tariyd (ryd? rwd? hif): make you roam around? uncertain; grow restive REB<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>faraqta: you will pull away, tear away ʿullo: his yoke<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>tsawaʾrekha: your neck; get him off your back This verse is the official Masoretic halfway point.<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>[MC] The little Tyndale commentaries (IVP) by Kidner on this section is a gem! (vv. 1-40). He points out that Jacob depends on all his senses (smell, taste, etc) rather than the Lord.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ribka suru Yakob lari<bt>Ribka orders Yakob to flee</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Esau binci mau mati sang Yakob, tagal dia pung adi su rampas ame dia pung berkat. Ma dia pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde lama lai, te bapa mati. Jadi tunggu sa. Nanti mete-mete abis, beta bunu sang dia!&gt;&gt;<bt>Esau hated [+to extreme] Yakob, because his younger-sibling had robbed his blessing. But he thought saying, &lt;&lt;It won't be much longer, and father will be dead. So (consequently) just wait. Later, when the mourning is over, I will kill him!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yistom (qal): harbor a grudge against"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yistom (qal): harbor a grudge against Jacob, animosity toward him, hated him to the core of his soul. berkho (piʿel): he blessed him<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>yiqrəvo: the time is coming near ʾevel: time of mourning<span class="Italic">(41)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42-43" />Waktu Ribka dapa dengar Esau pung rancana, ju dia pange sang Yakob, deng bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu dengar bae-bae! Lu pung kaka ada niat mau balas dia pung saki hati, ko mau bunu sang lu. Jadi lu lari capát-capát pi di lu pung to'o Laban di Haran.<bt>When Ribka heard about Esau's plan, she summoned Yakob, and said, &lt;&lt;Listen well! Your older-sibling intends to avenge his anger, and is going to kill you. So (consequently) flee quickly to your mother's-brother (to'o) Laban in Haran.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yugad (ngd hof): it was reported."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yugad (ngd hof): it was reported. Why "ʾet" with hofal? Waltke &amp; OʾConnor 28.3, "The Hophal forms of roots that are transitive in Qal are passive causatives." e.g., somebody caused [ʾet] Rebecca to be informed ... mitnachem (hitp): is scheming revenge against you; literally, is comforting himself concerning you [things will be okay once I kill Jacob].<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>shmaʿ bqoli: lissen to my voice = obey me bərach-lakh: flee<span class="Italic">(42)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Pi tenga sadiki lama di sana, sampe lu pung kaka su sonde mara lai sang lu.<bt>Go live there awhile, until your older-sibling is no longer angry at you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿad-ʾasher tashuv chamat: until his anger"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿad-ʾasher tashuv chamat: until his anger returns, turns away ʿad chmat: during the anger of<span class="Italic">(44)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="45" />Kalo dia su lupa buang apa yang lu su bekin sang dia, nanti beta suru orang pange pulang sang lu. Te beta sonde mau beta pung ana dua-dua ilang dalam satu hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he has fully forgotten what you have done to him, then I will order someone to call you home. Cause I don't want to lose both my children on the same day.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shakhach ʾet ʾasher ʿasita lo: forget"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shakhach ʾet ʾasher ʿasita lo: forget what you did to him ʾeshkal: I would be bereaved of children<span class="Italic">(45)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Ais Ribka omong deng Isak bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su doak deng Esau pung bini orang Het dong! Kalo Yakob ju kawin deng nona Het, na, lebe bae beta mati sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Ribka spoke with Isak saying, &lt;&lt;I am already fed up (&lt;belching, vomiting) with these wives of Esau from the Het people! If Yakob also marries a young-woman from Het, it would be better if I just die.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doak = 1) burp, belch 2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">doak = 1) burp, belch 2) bosan, muak, revolt, sonde suka lia lai</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qatsti (qwts): I am disgusted mifney:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qatsti (qwts): I am disgusted mifney: because of<span class="Italic">(46) (46) </span>kaʾeleh: like these, like Esau's wives (indirect); a backhanded slap, reassuring Isaac that giving Jacob the blessing was a good idea. loqeach (participle): on the verge of marrying<span class="Italic">(46)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="28" />
      <v n="1" />Ais Isak pange sang Yakob, ju dia kasi berkat deng nasiat bilang, &lt;&lt;Dengar bae-bae! Lu jang kawin deng nona Kana'an.<bt>Then Isak summoned Yakob, and geve him blessing with advice saying, &lt;&lt;Listen well! You must not marry a young-woman of Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaytsawehu (tswh piʿel): he ordered him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaytsawehu (tswh piʿel): he ordered him, commanded. There is no reprimand for Jacob's having deceived Isaac.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ma lu pi di Padan Aram, di ba'i Betuel pung ruma. Lu pi kawin deng to'o Laban pung ana parampuan satu.<bt>But you must go to Padan Aram, to grandfather Betuel's house. Go marry one of mother's-brother Laban's daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qum lekh: get up and go,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qum lekh: get up and go, donʾt waste any time Paddenah Aram: directive is after the first noun. bayit is a locative noun.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>Betuʿel: defined in terms of Rebecca's kin, not Isaacʾs, though it's the same people involved. That establishes Jacob's connection with the Haran branch of the family.</Message></Annotation><note reference="28:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Padan Aram tu, andia Mesopotamia, di negara Siria pung sablá utara, deka-deka deng Irak. Haran tu, kota di Padan Aram.<bt>That Padan Aram, is Mesopotamia, in the north part of the country of Siria, very close to Iraq. That Haran, is a city in Padan Aram.</bt></note><v n="3" />Biar Tuhan Allah yang Paling Kuasa kasi berkat sang lu, ko lu pung ana-cucu batamba banya, deng lu pung turunan jadi banya bangsa yang hebat.<bt>May Lord God who is Most Powerful give you blessing, to your children-grandchildren increase in number, and your descendants become many impressive races/peoples.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾel shaday: Almighty God vyafrkha (frh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾel shaday: Almighty God vyafrkha (frh hif impf): and make you fruitful<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>liqhal ʿamim: become a convocation (community) of peoples</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Biar Tuhan pung janji sang Abraham jato pi di lu, deng lu pung turunan. Biar lu soa ini tana yang Tuhan Allah su janji kasi sang Abraham.&gt;&gt;<bt>May the Lord's promise to Abraham fall to you, and your descendants. May you possess/take possession of this land which Lord God has promised to give to Abraham.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="birkat: blessing in operation lrishtəkha (yrsh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">birkat: blessing in operation lrishtəkha (yrsh inf): to take possession of land. God gave it to Abraham. It's your possession (now, or with Laban?). Maybe Jacob had ancestral rights in Haran, so he was not "gur" there.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>mgureykha (magur, gwr): your place of residence as an alien</Message></Annotation><note reference="28:3-4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Utusan dong pung Carita 3:25; Galatia 3:8</note><v n="5" />Omong abis bagitu, ju Isak lapás sang Yakob pi Padan Aram, di dia pung to'o Laban deng ba'i Betuel pung ruma.<bt>After speaking that way, Isak released Yakob to go to Padan Aram, to his mother's-brother Laban and grandfather Betuel's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayishlach: he sent him somewhere, let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayishlach: he sent him somewhere, let him go yelekh: If we say before verse 10 that he actually went, it clashes with Pidgin rhetoric. We have to preserve the time iconicity, otherwise it communicates that Jacob made two trips. [MC] Oh, that all translators knew things like this about their languages!<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>(In Hebrew text): Jacob and Esau, in order of preeminence, not order of birth</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau kawin deng Ismael pung ana parampuan<bt>Esau marries Ismael's daughter</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Interlude, similar to the Judah and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Interlude, similar to the Judah and Tamar incident in Chapter 28. Joseph and Judah are the people in focus in the outcome of the whole Jacob story. Deceptions look like part of a cycle: Jacob and Esau, Shekem men, Judah and Tamar, ...<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Esau dapa dengar bilang, Isak su kasi berkat sang Yakob, deng larang sang dia ko jang kawin deng nona Kana'an. Dia ju dapa dengar bilang, dia pung bapa su suru dia pung adi ko pi kawin deng to'o pung ana nona satu di Padan Aram.<bt>Esau heard that Isak had given blessing to Yakob, and forbidden him from marrying a young-woman of Kanaan. He had also heard that his father had ordered his younger brother to go marry a mother's-brother's daughter in Padan Aram.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayarʾ: realized (not just visual). This"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayarʾ: realized (not just visual). This starts the wrapup of the Jacob-Esau story. bvarakho: in blessing him<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vaytsaw (tswh): he ordered him</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais Yakob dengar dia pung bapa deng mama pung parenta, ju dia barangkat pi Padan Aram.<bt>And Yakob listened to /obeyed his father and mother's command, so he left for Padan Aram.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shalach ... yelech: is this an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shalach ... yelech: is this an overlay structure?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Esau ju tau bilang, dia pung bapa sonde suka sang dia pung bini, orang Kana'an dong.<bt>Esau also knew that his father didn't like his wives, the Kanaan people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarʾ: saw, realized, perceived, it dawned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yarʾ: saw, realized, perceived, it dawned on him raʿot: disagreeable, contemptible, displeasing, objectionable<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Jadi dia pi sang bapa bésar Ismael, ais dia kawin lai deng Ismael pung ana, nama Mahalat. Mahalat tu, Nebayot pung adi parampuan.<bt>So (consequently) he went to his big father [=F's older brother] Ismael, and he married again [=in addition] with Ismael's daughter, named Mahalat. That Mahalat, was Nebayot's younger sister.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿesau: Esau goes to his father's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿesau: Esau goes to his father's half brother, just as Jacob goes to his mother's brother, mirror image. Maybe he still doesn't get it about what his father really wants, and thinks he will make his father happy by marrying a relative instead of somebody from a nearby family. He is close to his father, so he probably isn't doing this to bug him. But he might be. ʿal-nashaw lo: in addition to the wives he had - unusual construction.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob mimpi di Betel<bt>Yakob dreams at Betel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais Yakob jalan kasi tenga Beer Syeba, ko mau pi Haran.<bt>Then Yakob left behind Beer Syeba, on his way to Haran.</bt><v n="11" />Waktu matahari tanggalám, dia sampe di satu tampa, ju dia tidor di situ. Waktu dia mau tidor, dia ame satu batu ko bekin jadi bantal.<bt>Whe the sun was going down, he arrived at a place, and he slept there. When he was about to go to sleep, he got a stone to be his pillow.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meʾavney: from the stones of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">meʾavney: from the stones of the place. It could read "some of the stones," like a a ring of stones like a wall around his head for protection. But in the morning it's clearly a single stone being used as a head-rest (some would say a pillow). yifgaʿ: he reached a place, ran into someone, met someone<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>yalen (lyn): stay overnight, spend the night yasem (sim): put something somewhere<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mraʾashotav: what is at the head, as a head-rest for him yishkav: he laid down.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00683c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Itu malam dia mimpi. Dia dapa lia satu tangga badiri di tana deng dia pung ujung sampe di langit. Ais Tuhan Allah pung ana bua dari sorga dong turun-nae itu tangga.<bt>That night he dreamed, he could see a ladder/stair standing on the ground with its tip reaching the sky. And Lord God's *angels were descending-ascending that ladder.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sullam: ascending series of stones, steps"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Sullam: ascending series of stones, steps going up, staircase (more probable than a ladder). Hapax. Two "hineh", with the subject and with the participle. mutstsav (ntsv hof pt): that were set up, standing<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>magiaʿ (ngʿ hif pt): touching, reaching all the way to. Message: access to God is there, but limited. Jewish commentators say the ascending angels were Palestine angels, finished with their shift because he was about to leave that territory; the descending angels were a new squad taking over for the trip to Padan-Aram.</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Dalam itu mimpi, Yakob dapa lia TUHAN badiri di dia pung sablá, ais omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni TUHAN, lu pung ba'i Abraham deng bapa Isak pung Tuhan Allah. Nanti Beta kasi ini tana sang lu deng lu pung turunan.<bt>In that dream, Yakob could see the LORD standing at its/his side, speaking saying, &lt;&lt;I am the LORD, your grandfather Abraham and father Isak's Lord God. I will give this land here to you and your descendants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitstsav (pt): standing somewhere, have taken"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nitstsav (pt): standing somewhere, have taken a stand, stationed himself there ʿalaw: higher than him, in front of him (standing while Jacob is sleeping). It could mean ʾat the top of the stepsʾ, but probably means God was standing by the place where Jacob was sleeping.<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʿaleyah: on it (the ground)</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Nanti lu pung turunan dong pung banya sama ke abu. Deng nanti dong tasiram pi mana-mana di samua tampa. Dari lu pung turunan, nanti samua suku-bangsa di dunya dapa berkat.<bt>Later your descendants' numbers will be many like dust. And they will be scattered everywhere in all places. From your descendants, all races/peoples in the world will get blessing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaʿafar haʾarets: like the dry, fine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kaʿafar haʾarets: like the dry, fine particles of dirt on the ground (but in Pidgin this implies something negative, so have to shift to "sand", which is clean and positive) faratsta (frts burst out, make a breach): you will spread out, break over in numbers<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yamah: where the sea is, to the west qedmah: in front, in the east<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>tsafonah: north nibrakhu (nif): they will wish for themselves blessing like you have, will be blessed in relationship to you (Genesis 12)<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>mishpachot: extended families, clans (with felt blood relationship), ethnic groups</Message></Annotation><note reference="28:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Utusan dong pung Carita 3:25; Galatia 3:8</note><v n="15" />Inga bae-bae! Lu pi mana sa, Beta sama-sama deng jaga sang lu. Nanti Beta bawa sang lu pulang kambali di ini negrí. Beta sonde kasi biar sang lu sandiri. Deng nanti Beta bekin jadi samua janji yang Beta kasi sang lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember well! Wherever you go, I am together with and watching over you. I will bring you back home to this country. I will not allow you to be alone/by yourself. And I will fulfill all My promises that I have given to you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shmartikha: I will guard you, take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shmartikha: I will guard you, take care of you hashivotikha (shwv hif): bring you back, lead you back where you started from<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>loʾ ʾaʿezavkha: I will not abandon you ʿad ʾasher ʾim: until<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Waktu Yakob bangun tidor, ju dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta baru tau bilang, TUHAN ju ada di sini!&gt;&gt;<bt>As soon as Yakob woke up from sleeping, he said, &lt;&lt;I am just now aware that the LORD is also here!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqats (qal): wake up mishnato (shenah):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqats (qal): wake up mishnato (shenah): from his sleep<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʾakhen: truly, exclamation</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Dia taku, ju dia pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Ini tampa bekin beta pung bulu badan badiri. Pasti Tuhan Allah pung ruma ada di sini! Mangkali ini dia pung pintu pi sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he was afraid, and he thought saying, &lt;&lt;We! This place makes my body-hair stand. Surely Lord God's house is here! And this is the doorway to *heaven.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="fear here is reverence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">fear here is reverence</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiraʾ: he was afraid mah-noraʾ (yrʾ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiraʾ: he was afraid mah-noraʾ (yrʾ nif partcpl): to be feared, fearful<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʾeyn zeh ki ʾim: this is none other than shaʿar: gate<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="28:12-17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:51</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00685c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yakob sémba sang Tuhan di Betel<bt>Yakob worship's the Lord at Betel</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dia pung papagi, Yakob bangun, tarús dia ame batu yang dia pake jadi bantal tu, ko kasi badiri jadi tanda. Ais dia po'a minya di atas itu batu, ko sémba sang Tuhan.<bt>Early in the morning, Yakob got up, and right away he took the rock that he had used as a pillow, and he erected it as a sign. And he poured oil on that rock, to/and worship the Lord.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tugu (BI) = batu peringatan,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tugu (BI) = batu peringatan,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashkem: get up early mraʾashtav: as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yashkem: get up early mraʾashtav: as a place for his head<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>matstsəvah: standing stone, a memorial standing alone, an unhewn, upright stone for cult or burial or memorial purposes. This was forbidden later; but in its archaic significance it was like one of the altars that Abraham and Isaac built to commemorate dealings with God. yitsoq: he poured oil<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Dia kasi nama itu tampa, <span class="Italic">Betel,</span> yang dia pung arti &lt;Tuhan pung ruma&gt;. (Dolu itu tampa, nama <span class="Italic">Lus).</span><bt>He named that place, <span class="Italic">Betel,</span> which means &lt;the Lord's house&gt;. (Formerly that place was named Lus).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾulam: only lariʾshonah|i(19) |r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾulam: only lariʾshonah<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ais itu, ju Yakob angka sumpa bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo Tuhan Allah sama-sama deng beta, ais jaga sang beta di beta pung jalan ni, deng kasi beta makan deng pakean,<bt>After that, Yakob lifted an oath saying, &lt;&lt;If Lord God is together and watches over me on this journey of mine, and gives me food and clothing,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiddar neder (ndr imperf): he made"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiddar neder (ndr imperf): he made a vow (a promise to do something special). This is the key turning point in Jacob's life, dealing directly with God instead of just hearing about him.</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />sampe beta pulang deng salamat, nanti TUHAN jadi beta pung Allah.<bt>until I return home in safety, then the LORD will be my Allah.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vshalom: in good condition. This is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vshalom: in good condition. This is not negative; God has already promised to be with Jacob. in Hebrew: He is talking to God. He switches from 3rd person to 2nd within his speech (v. 22 "you"). (Note in eastern Indonesian lgs, 3rd person is often used for direct address.)<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Batu yang beta kasi badiri ni, jadi tampa sémba sang Tuhan Allah. Deng samua yang Tuhan kasi sang beta, nanti beta kasi kambali satu bagian dari sapulu.&gt;&gt;<bt>This rock that I have erected here, will be a place to worship Lord God. And everything which the Lord gives to me, I will give back one part from ten.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿasser ʾaʿassərenu lakh: I will give"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿasser ʾaʿassərenu lakh: I will give ten per cent to you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob sampe di to'o Laban pung ruma<bt>Yakob arrives at mother's-brother Laban's house</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="29" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, ju Yakob jalan tarús pi matahari nae.<bt>After that, Yakob went on going to the east.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayissaʾ raglaw (nsʾ): he lifted up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayissaʾ raglaw (nsʾ): he lifted up his feet = left there (hapax) bəne qedem: Easterners (they were actually more to the north and east, but that's how people saw their geography, and their political and religious connections were to the southeast of them, because it was a different culture there)<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Satu hari, dia dapa lia satu parigi deka satu kampong. Deka-deka situ, ada kambing-domba tiga kumpul, yang ada tunggu-tunggu ko dapa minum di situ. Ma ada satu batu bésar tutu itu parigi.<bt>One day, he saw a well near a village. Very near there, were three groupings/herds of goats-sheep, which here waiting to get a drink there. But there was a large stone covering/closing that well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lu'u = 1) baring, 2) mengeram,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lu'u = 1) baring, 2) mengeram, Fig = lu'u nona = hang out with a girl</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hine: shows things from Jacob's perspective,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hine: shows things from Jacob's perspective, not the narratorʾs basadeh: in an uncultivated area.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ʿedray: a flock or herd belonging to one individual rovtsim: lying down with chest on the ground<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yashqu (shqh hif): watered haʾeven: the stone -- why the article? gadolah is predicate; protecting a well with a stone was standard practice, so the stone is given; only the size is unusual.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dia pung biasa, kalo kambing-domba dong samua su bakumpul, baru gambala kasi ondor itu batu ko timba aer kasi minum binatang dong. Minum abis, dong tutu kambali itu parigi lai.<bt>The custom, was when all the goats-sheep had gathered, only-then would the herders move-back that stone to fetch water for those animals to drink. After drinking they would re-cover that well again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neʾesfu-shamah (nif): they gathered there. Waltke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">neʾesfu-shamah (nif): they gathered there. Waltke says the imperfect shows this to be a consequence of Verse 2. The other verbs are perfects. But it could also be a generic imperfect: it was their custom that the sheep gathered there gallu: they rolled the stone off the mouth of the well. The way they managed the flocks was not common practice, as Jacob pointed out. Possibly a local compromise designed to keep the first group there from hogging all the water.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>hishqu (shqh hif): they caused to drink limqomah: into its place<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Tarús Yakob pi tanya itu gambala dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bosong dari mana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob went and asked those herders saying, &lt;&lt;Hei! Where are you-pl from?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong ni, dari kampong Haran sini.&gt;&gt;<bt>They answered saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc are from the village of Haran here.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;Brothers&quot; shows he is being friendly,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">"Brothers" shows he is being friendly, though he doesn't know them and he doesn't have any clout with anybody. Joseph's brothers were taking care of their sheep at least 60 miles away from their home, so this might have been quite a ways out of Haran. But it canʾt have been very far, because both Rachel and Laban ran between there and home. So maybe it's over a rise from which the town is not yet visible, though it's actually close by.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>meʾayin: from where?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ais Yakob tanya lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong kanál beta pung to'o Laban, ko? Dia tu, Nahor pung ana.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob asked again saying, &lt;&lt;You know my mother's-brother Laban, right? He is Nahor's child/offspring.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong kanál.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they answered saying, &lt;&lt;We know him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ben: naming the most famous one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ben: naming the most famous one in the lineage, not the immediate father (Betuʿel). This has implications for lots of genealogies, especially in Genesis. yadaʿnu: Wenham interprets this as a surly reply, not very helpful; but given the nature of other reported conversations in Hebrew it sounds like normal question and response. Besides, in Verse 6 they have a helpful comeback, even though they donʾt know who Jacob is and they could have an interest in protecting Rachel.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju Yakob tanya tarús lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Dia ada bae-bae, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob kept questioning saying, &lt;&lt;He is well, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapatua ada bae-bae sa. Coba lia. Itu dia pung ana parampuan, nama Rahel, ada foo bawa dia pung kambing-domba dong ko datang minum di sini. Lu tunggu sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>They answered saying, &lt;&lt;The old-man is doing fine. Take a look. That's his daughter, named Rahel, herding his/her goats-sheep this way to come drink here. You just wait here.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="almost like &quot;as a matter of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">almost like "as a matter of fact, now that you mention Laban, there's his daughter!" The "try look" sounds like they want to be helpful, even though they still donʾt know who Jacob is.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais Yakob omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang matahari masi tinggi. Jadi lebe bae binatang mana yang su bakumpul di sini, na, bosong kasi minum suda. Ais bosong foo bawa pi padang, ko dong makan rumput lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yakob spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;Now the sun is still high. So it would be better if those animals that are already gathered here, na, you-pl go ahead and give them drink. After that, you can herd them to the grass-field, so they can eat grass again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: demonstrative conjunction. Jacob is probably"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hen: demonstrative conjunction. Jacob is probably talking to hired men or teenagers put in charge of the sheep. He is more curt with them than they are with him. There is no social equal for him to talk to. It also shows he is a take-charge guy who knows what he's about, which may have also attracted Laban's attention as a prospective son-in-law with guts. ʿod: still<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʿet heʿasef (nif inf): time to be gathered, gather hamiqneh: the livestock<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lkhu rʿu (hlk rʿh): let them go graze</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ma dong protes bilang, &lt;&lt;Awe', sonde bisa bagitu! Botong musti tunggu gambala dong samua bawa dong pung binatang ko bakumpul di sini dolo, baru botong kasi ondor itu batu, ko kasi minum binatang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>But they protested saying, &lt;&lt;We, [you/we] can't do it like that! We must wait for all the herders to bring their anomals to gather here first. Only-then will we move-back that stone, to give the animals [their] drink.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nowkhal: we canʾt ʿad ʾasher: until|i(8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nowkhal: we canʾt ʿad ʾasher: until<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yeʾasfu: they come together, are together gallu: 3rd person. Could be that the people who are talking are the ones that actually move the sheep by the watering troughs, after a designated group of them roll the stone off the mouth of the well.<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Yakob masi ba'omong deng itu orang dong, te Rahel sampe deng dia pung bapa pung kambing-domba dong. Dia yang biasa foo itu binatang.<bt>Yakob was still speaking with those people, when Rahel arrived with her father's goats-sheep. She was the one who normally herded those animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿodenu: while they were still talking;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿodenu: while they were still talking; their continuation At this point Jacob knows he has found the family. The emphasis is on still on kinship, not yet on Rachel herself.<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00687c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yakob buka parigi pung tutu kasi sang Rahel<bt>Yakob opens the well's cover for Rahel</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Waktu Yakob lia Rahel deng dia pung kambing-domba dong, ju dia pi kasi ondor itu parigi pung tutu. Ais dia kasi minum dia pung to'o pung binatang dong.<bt>When Yakob saw Rahel, and her goats-sheep, he went and moved-back the well's cover. And he gave drink to his mother's-brother's animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayigash (ngsh): step up, go forward."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayigash (ngsh): step up, go forward. Jacob may be showing off how strong he is. He's definitely a mover and shaker, and has already taken charge of the situation. yagel: he rolled the stone off the top of the well<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ais ju dia pi paló-ciom sang Rahel, deng manangis.<bt>And he also went hug-kissing Rahel, and cried.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayishaq (nshq qal): kiss, likely on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayishaq (nshq qal): kiss, likely on both cheeks. Since Rachel still doesn't know who he is, he is flouting convention. vayisaʾ ʾet-qolo: he lifted up his voice; loudly. Why is he crying? "Long lost cousin, wen dey firs meet, dey do." SK<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ais dia carita sang Rahel bilang, &lt;&lt;Adi! Beta ni, lu pung bapa pung adi Ribka pung ana.&gt;&gt; Ju Rahel lari pulang, ko pi kasi tau dia pung bapa.<bt>Then he narrated to Rahel saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sister! I am your father's younger sister Ribka's child.&gt;&gt; Then2 Rahel ran home, to go tell her father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaged (ngd hif): informed, announced, put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaged (ngd hif): informed, announced, put something up conspicuously in front of somebody. Jacob identifies himself as a kinsman, and probably gives some details, but he also probably doesn't tell the whole story of the intrigues and strife that made him come. achi: not "brothers" in the narrow sense, but "kinsmen".<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>tarats: she ran</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Waktu Laban dengar Rahel pung carita so'al Yakob, dia pung adi Ribka pung ana, ju dia lari pi sambut sang dia. Waktu katumu, ju Laban paló-ciom sang dia, ais dia bawa sang Yakob pi dia pung ruma. Ais Yakob carita samua sang Laban.<bt>As soon as Laban heard Rahel's story about Yakob, his younger-sister Ribka's child, he ran to greet him. When they met, Laban hug-kissed him, and then he brought Yakob to the house. Then Yakob narrated everything to Laban.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kishmoaʿ (abs): when he heard. Why"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kishmoaʿ (abs): when he heard. Why absolute? liqraʾto (qrʾ inf): happening to someone, come to someone, toward someone<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yəchabbeq: He embraced him ynashsheq (piʿel): kiss fervently? (Jacob kisses Rachel with Qal. Laban kisses Jacob with Piʿel.)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ysafer: relate, tell. Again, he probably doesn't say that he's on the run, or that he is looking for a wife. But he has to tell enough inside information to prove his identity as a member of the family. Laban had been a player in Rebecca's going away, but Jacob didnʾt show up with ten camels loaded with gold. The Return Of Martin Gere is a novel taken from a medieval French court report of an impostor who showed up and claimed Martin Gere's wife after Gere had gone to war. The impostor knows a lot of Gere family secrets (possibly told to him by the wife, or by Martin), and is accepted. Then the real Martin shows up. There is the same theme in The Sign Of The Fingerpost, a recent novel.</Message></Annotation><v n="14a" />Ju Laban omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Memang batúl! Kotong dua bakelu!&gt;&gt;<bt>And Laban spoke saying, &lt;&lt;It's really true! The two of us-inc are RECIP-family!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿatsmi uvsari: my bone and my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿatsmi uvsari: my bone and my flesh = total being, everything about you is just like me. Laban is convinced that Jacob is the real thing; the family secrets check out.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob kawin deng Lea deng Rahel<bt>Yakob marries Lea and Rahel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14b" />Waktu Yakob su tenga deng dong sampe satu bulan,<bt>When Yakob had lived with them for a month,</bt><v n="15" />Laban omong deng dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini, Ako! Beta sonde mau lu karjá farei kasi beta tagal kotong dua bakelu. Lu minta gaji barapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Laban spoke with him saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, Jake! I don't want you to work for free for me, because the two of us-inc are RECIP-family. How much wages do you ask for?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chinnam (adv): without compensation, for free"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chinnam (adv): without compensation, for free hagidah (ngd impv): put forward an opinion, report, announce, tell<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>maskurtekha: your wages</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Naa, Laban tu, ada pung ana parampuan dua orang. Yang kaka, nama Lea. Yang adi, nama Rahel.<bt>Naa, [+shift] Laban had two daughters. The older-sibling was named Lea. The younger-sibling, was named Rahel.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rashi points out that in normal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Rashi points out that in normal interfamily relationships, Leah would have been matched with Esau and Rachel with Jacob. Leah may have heard enough about Esau to be glad to settle for the younger son. She falls in love with him, probably after the marriage.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Lea pung mata sayu.<bt>Lea was droopy-eyed.</bt><note reference="29:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani di sini sonde jalás.<bt>The Hebrew here is unclear.</bt></note>Ma Rahel pung muka talalu manis, deng dia pung badan bagus.<bt>But Rahel had a pretty face/appearance, and a good/healthy/attractive body.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mata sayu = droopy-eyed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">mata sayu = droopy-eyed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rakhot: frail, weak; tender, sensitive, delicate,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">rakhot: frail, weak; tender, sensitive, delicate, soft (Wenham). The word is usually used positively: tender, vulnerable. It sounds like Leah was fairly ordinary looking except for her eyes, which were exceptionally soft and dreamy. Rachel, on the other hand, was a knockout, like Miss Mesopotamia. yfat-toʾar: beautiful figure, shape<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Yakob cinta sang Rahel. Jadi dia manyao sang Laban bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta karjá kasi to'o tuju taon, asal to'o kasi kawin beta deng Rahel.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yakob loved Rahel. So he answered Laban saying, &lt;&lt;I will work for mother's-brother [MB] for seven years, as long as MB lets me marry Rahel.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʾehav: he fell in love"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʾehav: he fell in love</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ais Laban manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Satuju! Lebe bae beta kasi kawin Rahel deng lu, andia beta pung kelu sandiri! Dia sonde usa kawin deng orang laen. Jadi lu tenga di sini sa, ko karjá kasi beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Laban responded saying, &lt;&lt;Agreed! Rather than my giving Rahel to marry someone else/an "other" person (=outside our people), it would be better with you, my own family! So (consequently) you just stay here, and work for me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="titi (ntn): infinitive absolute"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">titi (ntn): infinitive absolute</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ais Yakob karjá tuju taon, ko bisa dapa sang Rahel. Ma dia cinta mau mati sang Rahel. Jadi tuju taon tu, dia rasa sama ke cuma barapa hari sa.<bt>So Yakob worked seven years, so he could get Rahel. But he loved [+extreme] Rahel. So (consequently) those seven years, he felt just like they were only several days.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Lewat itu tuju taon, ju Yakob kasi inga sang Laban bilang, &lt;&lt;To'o! Beta su karjá kasi to'o tuju taon ni, jadi sakarang kasi kawin sang beta deng Rahel su.&gt;&gt;<bt>After seven years, Yakob reminded Laban saying, &lt;&lt;MB! I have worked for MB these seven years, so now let me marry Rahel now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="havah (impv): give, come on! Strange"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">havah (impv): give, come on! Strange form, possibly from yhb. vʾavoʾah (bwʾ impf): I will go in to her (referring to beginning a sexual relation). Take her as my wife. It has sexual overtones, and is kind of coarse, in contrast with "lwn" used for Ruth and Boaz.<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>The time discontinuity seems to be between 20 and 21. This break follows Tanakh, not the Christian versions.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ju Laban bekin pesta kawin, deng undang samua orang di itu negrí.<bt>Then2 Laban made a wedding celebration, and invited all the people in that country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʾsof: gather. This is not a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʾsof: gather. This is not a typical Hebrew wedding, where the groom goes to the bride's house or a third party's house to bring her back to his house. Jacob doesn't have a house; he's living with Laban just as Rachel is. ʾanoshey hamaqom: men of the place<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mishteh: drinking-bout, banquet with wine</Message></Annotation><v n="23-27" />Itu malam, Laban sonde kasi Rahel, ma dia kasi Lea maso pi Yakob pung tenda. Jadi Yakob tidor deng dia. Dia pung beso, baru Yakob dapa tau, kalo dia kawin deng Lea. Tarús Yakob pi protes sang Laban bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko to'o pakane'o sang beta? Beta su karjá banting tulang tuju taon, ko dapa sang Rahel! Ma akurang ko to'o ganti deng Lea?&gt;&gt;<bt>That night, Laban didn't give Rahel, but he caused Lea to enter into Yakob's tent. So (consequently) Yakob slept with her. The next day, only-then did Yakob find out that he had married/intercoursed Lea. Straightaway Yakob went to protest to Laban saying, &lt;&lt;Why did MB twist/deceive me? I have worked to the bone for seven years, to get Rahel! But why did MB exchange her with Lea?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Consider putting 1st sent in quote"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Consider putting 1st sent in quote at the end, as in Amarasi.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Leah's eyes might have given her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Leah's eyes might have given her away, even with a veil. Maybe Rachel attended the wedding, and Leah didnʾt show up till they were alone in the dark. Another elaborate deception behind the scenes; both Rachel and Leah must have been in on the switch (Rashi). Mishteh in v. 22 implies that Jacob had been drinking, so maybe he wasnʾt noticing details by that time. hineh: The situation has already been explained to the reader. Hineh gives Jacob's personal reaction to it. Prototype case of the word. "Hineh hiʾ leʾah" is unusual, a unique construction. "Hineh leʾah hiʾ" would be expected. In a Midrash, Jacob has pulled a deception on his father involving touch; Laban deceives Jacob in a way that involves touch too (but Jacob may not have noticed the parallel). Leah has to act the part of Rachel all night. She loves him and knows that he doesn't love her. From there on out, Jacob plays favorites inside the family just as Isaac did.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>rimitani (rmh piʿel): deceive me, leave me dangling</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais Laban manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu jang mara bagitu! Iko botong pung adat di sini, adi sonde bole kawin lebe dolo dari kaka. Jadi lebe bae bagini sa! Lu tunggu sampe ini pesta kawin tuju hari abis dolo. Baru lu dapa sang Rahel, asal lu karjá kasi beta tuju taon lai.&gt;&gt; Ais Laban kasi dia pung hamba parampuan, nama Silpa ko jadi Lea pung hamba.<bt>The Laban answered saying, &lt;&lt;You shouldn't be angry like that! Following our <span class="Bold">adat</span> here, younger-siblings may not marry before older-siblings. So (consequently) it would be best like this! You wait until this seven day wedding festival is over first. Only-then will you get Rahel, as long as you will work for me seven more years.&gt;&gt; Then Laban gave his female servant, named Silpa to be Lea's servant/slave.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiten: he gave - is this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiten: he gave - is this like a wedding present on that occasion (the narrative [consecutive] tense sounds like it), or had it happened before the wedding night? Probably put here to delay the punch line, (as both Labov and I have noticed is a characteristic of well told stories), because elsewhere in describing weddings only major gifts are mentioned on the bride's side of the family. shifchato: her maidservant, slave. lshifchato would be more usual.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>habəkhirah: older sister. Usually used only of males, but this is the feminine form. Jacob may have know the custom but assumed that they would make an exception for him. When they didnʾt, he didnʾt have a leg to stand on, but had to accept Laban's deal. tsʿirah: younger<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>Rebecca going off immediately may have bothered Laban. He takes elaborate steps to keep Rachel and Jacob around for a long time malleʾ (piʿel imperv): fill out this week<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>shvuaʿ zoʾt: the bridal week of this woman. zoʾt and hiʾ are never mixed in Hebrew. zoʾt is used here for both women. ʿod: still, besides, another seven years<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>nitnah: we will give her? I will give her? "we let you marry" is a variant taken from Samaritan, LXX, and other versions. Book of Jubilees: "he served seven years more for Rachel, because Leah had been given to him gratis."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Yakob satuju. Andia ko, waktu itu pesta tuju hari abis, ju Laban kasi kawin Rahel deng Yakob.<bt>Yakob agreed. That is why as soon as that seven day festival was over, Laban gave Rahel to marry Yakob.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ymaleʾ (piʿel): he fulfilled the time."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ymaleʾ (piʿel): he fulfilled the time. Jon Rawlings: "Outside of Eden there are no unmixed blessings."</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ais Laban kasi dia pung hamba parampuan satu lai, nama Bilha, ko jadi Rahel pung hamba.<bt>And Laban gave another of his female servants, named Bilha, to be Rahel's servant.</bt><v n="30" />Ais ju Yakob tidor deng Rahel. Dia lebe cinta sang Rahel dari Lea. Ju dia karjá tamba lai tuju taon kasi dia pung bapa mantu.<bt>So then Yakob slept with Rahel. He loved Rahel more than Lea. And he worked another seven years for his father-in-law.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob pung ana-ana dong<bt>Yakob's children</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ma TUHAN tau Yakob lebe cinta sang Rahel dari Lea. Ais Dia kasi loos ko Lea barana. Ma Rahel sonde dapa ana.<bt>But the LORD knew Yakob loved Rahel more than Lea. So He allowed (&lt;gave permission) for Lea to give birth. But Rahel didn't get children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This part is not chronologically later"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">This part is not chronologically later than Verse 30. It's the same time span, but focuses on a different set of circumstances. snuʾah (snʾ pt): hate; unable or unwilling to put up with somebody, slighted wife<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>vayiftach et-rachmah: God opened her womb ʿaqarah: barren, without offspring<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Ais Lea dudu parú, ju dia dapa satu ana laki-laki. Dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Ruben</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;lia, ada ana&gt;),<bt>So Lea became pregnant, and she had a son. She namme that child, <span class="Italic">Ruben</span> (which means &lt;look, there is a child&gt;),</bt><note reference="29:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Ruben</span> pung arti &lt;lia, ada ana&gt;. Deng dia pung bunyi amper sama deng satu kata yang pung arti &lt;dia su lia beta pung susa&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language, <span class="Italic">Ruben</span> means 'look, there is a child'. And it sounds almost like a word which means 'he has seen my difficulty'.</bt></note>tagal dia bilang, &lt;&lt;TUHAN memang su lia beta pung susa. Andia ko sakarang, beta pung laki ju mau lia sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>because she said, &lt;&lt;The LORD has really seen my difficulty. That is why now, my husband will want to pay attention to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tahar (hrh): get pregnant bʿanyi (ʿani):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tahar (hrh): get pregnant bʿanyi (ʿani): in my affliction, overwhelmed by want, unfortunate, misery. This is strong language, and having a character voice an inner state is rare for Hebrew narrative. Why the b-? look upon?<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>Naming the baby in hope that her husband will love her is poignant.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ais itu, Lea dudu parú lai, ju dia dapa satu ana laki-laki. Dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Simeon</span> (yang dia pung arti kira-kira &lt;orang su dengar&gt;), tagal dia bilang, &lt;&lt;TUHAN su dengar bilang, beta pung laki sonde toe sang beta. Andia ko Dia kasi tamba satu ana lai sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Lea became pregnant again, and she got a son. She named that child, <span class="Italic">Simeon</span> (which means &lt;someone has heard&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;The LORD has heard that my husband doesn't care about me. That is why He has added another child to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="snuʾah: hate, disdain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">snuʾah: hate, disdain</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ais itu, Lea dudu parú lai, ju dia dapa satu ana laki-laki lai. Dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Lewi,</span><bt>After that, Lea became pregnant again, and she had another son. She named that child, <span class="Italic">Lewi,</span></bt><note reference="29:34" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;Lewi&gt; pung arti kira-kira &lt;ta'ika&gt;, ko &lt;paló deka-deka&gt;.<bt>'Lewi' means something like 'bound to', or &lt;hug closely&gt;.</bt></note>tagal dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Deng ini ana, be pung parkara su abis. Pasti beta pung laki nanti ta'ika deng beta, tagal beta su barana kasi dia tiga ana laki-laki.&gt;&gt;<bt>because she said, &lt;&lt;With this child, my dispute is settled. Surely my husband will be bound to me, because I have given birth to three sons for him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hapaʿam: just this once, this time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hapaʿam: just this once, this time yillaweh (lwh nif): he will join himself. The priestly and kingly lines came about by Laban's deception. Leah was Jesusʾ great-to-the-nth-power grandma.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ais itu, Lea dudu parú lai, ju dia dapa satu ana laki-laki. Dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Yahuda</span> (yang dia pung arti kira-kira &lt;puji&gt;), tagal dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini kali, beta mau puji TUHAN!&gt;&gt; Ais itu, Lea sonde barana lai.<bt>After that, Lea became pregnant again, and she had a son. She named that child, <span class="Italic">Yahuda</span> (which means something like &lt;praise&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;This time, I'm going to praise the LORD!&gt;&gt; After that, Lea didn't give birth again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾodeh (ydh hif imperf): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾodeh (ydh hif imperf): I will praise taʿmod miledet: she stopped having children (stand still, go on hold)<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="30" />
      <v n="1" />Ma Rahel balóm dapa ana. Andia ko dia camburu sang dia pung kaka. Ju dia omong deng dia pung laki bilang, &lt;&lt;Bu! Kasi beta ana dolo! Kalo sonde, na, lebe bae beta mati sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Rahel had not yet had children. That is why she was jealous of her older-sibling. So she spoke with her husband saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Give me a child [+insist]! If not, it would be better if I just die.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="camburu = jealous, saki hati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">camburu = jealous, saki hati</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təqaneʾ: she was envious of her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">təqaneʾ: she was envious of her sister. Waltke-OʾConnor from Muraoka, qinneʾ ʾet ʾbe jealous of somebody, resent humiliation brought about by somebodyʾ, bə ʾenvy somebody's successʾ, lə ʾbe zealous for somebody or some causeʾ. This one is envy at Leah's success. havah: give, like Jacob to Laban, a demand, with desperate urgency; a request with an edge to it.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>bahim: sons? children? UBS suggests children. metah (mwt partcpl fem): I will die [of shame at being childless]; be mortified. These two verses are the only dialogue between Jacob and Rachel that is recorded. The rabbis considered this the opening ploy in Rachel's plan to have her children with Bilhah as surrogate mother. The Book of Jubilees says that when Leah has a child, she gives it to a nurse. Then she gets pregnant again, which gives her greater prestige in one-upmanship within the family.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ju Yakob masparak sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu kira beta ni Tuhan, ko bisa kasi lu ana!?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yakob spoke-angrily to her saying, &lt;&lt;Do you think that I am the Lord, to be able to give you children!?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayichar-ʾaf: it was kindled; his nose"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayichar-ʾaf: it was kindled; his nose became hot = he broke out angrily against. WO impersonal of emotion hatachat: underneath, instead of<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>manaʿ: restrains, withholds something from someone, deny something to someone. Jacob's view is that it is God who decides how everything is going to come out. This may echo in Verse 8 with the name Naftali pri-beten: fruit of the womb, offspring<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais Rahel omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Lebe bae bapa ame beta pung hamba Bilha. Pi tidor deng dia, ko dia barana kasi beta ana.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Rahel spoke saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! It would be best if father takes my servant Bilha. Go sleep with her, so she can give birth to a child for me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾamati: my slave girl ʿal-birkhay: bear"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾamati: my slave girl ʿal-birkhay: bear them on my knees, onto my lap (= I will be their recognized mother). Rare for a woman to say this; bearing a child "on someone's knees" is usually what a man does in contracting a surrogate mother to bear a child for his legal wife.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʾibbaneh (bnh nif): I will be built = I will get a child, start a family line of my own gam: also (the same as Leah is doing)<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>They do all the machinations and magic, but there is no indication that it is makes any difference. It is God who makes things come out his way no matter what they do.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ais dia kasi Bilha di dia pung laki. Ju Yakob tidor deng dia.<bt>So then, she gave Bilha to her husband. And Yakob slept with her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lʾishshah: wife, concubine; the same word"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lʾishshah: wife, concubine; the same word covers both. But Bilhah was a slave, and she had no way of ever getting recognized as Jacob's official wife.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ais Bilha dudu parú, ju dia barana ame satu ana laki-laki.<bt>And Bilha became pregnant, and she gave birth to a son.</bt><v n="6" />Ju Rahel omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su dengar beta pung sambayang. Andia ko Dia su kasi sang beta satu ana laki-laki. Allah su putus beta pung parkara deng adil.&gt;&gt; Ju dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Dan</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;putus parkara&gt;).<bt>Then Rahel spoke saying, &lt;&lt;God has heard my prayer. That is why He has given me a son. Allah has settled my dispute justly/fairly.&gt;&gt; So she named that child, <span class="Italic">Dan</span> (which means &lt;settle a dispute/judge a court-case&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dananni (dyn perf): bring justice, redress"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">dananni (dyn perf): bring justice, redress a wrong for someone, execute justice. Rachel is being vindicated for giving Bilhah to Jacob: Bilhah has a child, so it must have been God's will.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais itu, Bilha dudu parú lai, ju dia dapa satu ana laki-laki.<bt>After that, Bilha became pregnant again, and she had a son.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sheni: a second time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">sheni: a second time</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ais Rahel omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su basaing deng beta pung kaka, ais beta yang manáng.&gt;&gt; Andia ko dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Naftali</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;basaing&gt;, ko &lt;baterek&gt;).<bt>Then Rahel spoke saying, &lt;&lt;I have competed with my older-sibling, and I am the one who won.&gt;&gt; That is why she named that child, <span class="Italic">Naftali</span> (which means &lt;compete&gt;, or &lt;struggle&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baterek = saling menekan (dgn kata-kata),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">baterek = saling menekan (dgn kata-kata), basaing, compete</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naftuley ʾəlohiym: I have struggled mightily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">naftuley ʾəlohiym: I have struggled mightily (one use of "of God"). Calvin: mighty wrestlings? the struggles of God? I have devised a fine trick against my sister? the twists and turns of God's ways? Sarna: wrestling for God, for God's attention? Aalders: wrestling before God, referring to extraordinary circumstances? ʾəlohiym: God, but probably an intensifier here. Possibly a vocative.<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>niftalti ʿim (nif partcpl perf): twist, struggle, wrestle, be tortuous, subtle yacolti: I can; I win<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Waktu Lea rasa dia sonde dapa ana lai, tarús dia kasi dia pung hamba Silpa sang dia pung laki, ko kawin deng dia.<bt>When Lea felt/knew she wouldn't have any more children, she gave her servant Silpa to her husband, to marry/intercourse with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarʾ (rʾh): put two and two"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yarʾ (rʾh): put two and two together, perceive</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ais ju Silpa barana ame satu ana laki-laki.<bt>So then Silpa had a son.</bt><v n="11" />Ju Lea omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta pung nasib, su bae.&gt;&gt; Deng dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Gad</span> (yang pung arti &lt;nasib bae&gt;).<bt>And Lea spoke saying, &lt;&lt;My fate is now good.&gt;&gt; And she named the child, <span class="Italic">Gad</span> (which means &lt;good luck/fortune&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bagad: in luck, good luck, good"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bagad: in luck, good luck, good fortune; ktiv baʾ gad "good fortune has come". Calvin didnʾt like the idea of luck here.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Tarús Silpa barana ame satu ana laki-laki lai.<bt>Then2 Silpa had another son.</bt><v n="13" />Ais ju Lea omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Wei! Sakarang, baru beta sanáng! Lia te nanti samua parampuan ba'omong bilang, beta su talalu ontong.&gt;&gt; Andia ko dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Aser</span> (yang pung arti &lt;sanáng&gt;).<bt>Then Lea spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Wei! [+attention] Now, I can be happy! Look, cause now all women will RECIP-speak saying I am very fortunate.&gt;&gt; That is why she named the child, <span class="Italic">Aser</span> (which means &lt;happy&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾosher: good fortune, happiness baʾashri: ktiv"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾosher: good fortune, happiness baʾashri: ktiv baʾ ʾashri "my good fortune has come"<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʾishshəruni (ʾshr piʿel): they will consider me happy banot: the other women will be happy with me, consider me happy<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Satu kali, pas musim koru padi, Ruben pi utan, ju dapa katumu satu tanaman obat yang bisa bekin orang dapa ana. Tarús dia bawa kasi dia pung mama Lea. Lia bagitu, ju Rahel minta sang Lea bilang, &lt;&lt;Kaka, é! Kasi beta obat sadiki yang Ruben bawa tu.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, during the picking grain season, Ruben went into the bush, and he found a medicinal plant which can cause people to have children. The he brought it and gave it to his mother Lea. Seeing that, Rahel requested Lea saying, &lt;&lt;Older-sibling, é! Give me a bit of that medicine which Ruben brought.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: It is quite clear that Rachel &amp; Leah believed this plant to be potent. The KM is not nearly as strong as the English BT, only opening up the possibility. Ask anyone in NTT about traditional meds that can cause (make it possible) for women to become pregnant, and they will give you lists of varying lengths of leaves, roots, outer bark, inner bark, mixes, spells, etc. that can do this. Whether they actually have power to have the desired effect is irrelevant-they are in that category. Note TH, which says “In translation of this term it may be necessary to substitute a local plant that is believed to have the same powers as the mandrake. If no such plant is known, it may be possible to use a descriptive expression such as “plant that women eat to help them become pregnant” or “plant that helps women to have children.” Two examples from translations in the Pacific area are “a flowering plant that women eat to help them get children, and which is used as a love magic” and “some bush medicine that was growing there, a good medicine to help women to have babies.”” If the team would prefer a disclaimer saying “and he found a medicinal plant which (people thought) can cause people to have children” That weaker rendering is also acceptable.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qtsir: grain harvest (April to June)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qtsir: grain harvest (April to June) chiTTiym: wheat<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>dudaʾim: mandrakes, Atropa mandragora or A.M. officinarum, a traditional aphrodisiac (but Zohary points out that Mandragora did not grow in the region where Jacob was at the time, and the Testaments of Issachar use the word for apples; otherwise Zohary identifies it as Mandragora autumnalis). In Greek they were called "love apples". The roots sometimes look like a human body, and the idea was that they could make a barren woman conceive a child. Though somewhat poisonous, causing vomiting and diarrhea and some narcosis, they were regarded as aphrodisiac and also a fertility inducer. naʾ: polite request, hedge with min "some of them"<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ma Lea manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Weh! Lu ni, su talalu! Lu su rampas ame beta pung laki. Sakarang lu mau rampas ame itu obat dari beta pung ana lai? Lu ni, sonde tau malu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Lea responded saying, &lt;&lt;We! You are too much! You have already robbed my husband. Now you want to rob the medicine from my child as well? You have no shame!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Rahel omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini, kaka. Kalo beta dapa itu obat, na, ini malam, lu bole tidor deng Yakob.&gt;&gt; Ju Lea satuju.<bt>But Rahel spoke saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, older-sibling. If I get that medicine, na, tonight, you may sleep with Yakob.&gt;&gt; So Lea agreed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hamʿaT: is it a small matter?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hamʿaT: is it a small matter? qachtekh (lqch inf): for you to take. Leah's up tight response sounds like an overreaction to Rachel's request.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>laqachat (lqch inf): to take lakhen: if that's how it is<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yishkav: he will have sex with you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Dia pung sore, Yakob pulang dari kabón. Ju Lea pi katumu deng dia, ais omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Ako! Lu musti tidor deng beta ini malam! Te beta su bayar memang sang lu deng beta pung ana pung obat.&gt;&gt; Ais, itu malam ju Yakob tidor deng Lea.<bt>That afternoon, Yakob came home from the field/garden. And so Lea went and met with him, and spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Jake! You must sleep with me tonight! Cause I have paid for you with my child's medicine.&gt;&gt; So then that night Yakob slept with Lea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sakhor sakhortikha (inf abs): I have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">sakhor sakhortikha (inf abs): I have hired you. The report of the whole situation seems very compressed; a lot more must have been going on. Josephus: Jacob makes love to Leah to please Rachel.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais Tuhan Allah dengar Lea pung sambayang. Andia ko dia dudu parú, ju dia barana ame ana laki-laki kalima.<bt>And Lord God heard Lea's prayer. That is why she became pregnant, and she gave birth to her fifth son.</bt><v n="18" />Ais Lea kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Isaskar</span> (yang pung arti &lt;bayar cape&gt;), tagal dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su bayar beta pung cape, te beta su kasi Silpa kawin deng beta pung laki.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Lea named that child, <span class="Italic">Isaskar</span> (which means &lt;reward for labour&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;Lord God has paid my effort/tiredness / rewarded my labour, cause I gave Silpa to marry my husband.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skhari: wages ʾasher: because (rare usage)|i(18)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">skhari: wages ʾasher: because (rare usage)<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ʾissachar: ktiv - kreʾ never marked in Issachar's name.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ais itu, Lea dudu parú lai, ju dia barana ame ana laki-laki ka'anam.<bt>After that, Lea became pregnant again, and she gave birth to her sixth son.</bt><v n="20" />Dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su kasi beta hadia yang bagus. Jadi sakarang beta pung laki musti kasi hormat sang beta, tagal beta su barana ame kasi sang dia anam ana laki-laki.&gt;&gt; Andia ko dia kasi nama itu ana <span class="Italic">Sebulon</span> (yang pung arti &lt;kasi hormat&gt;).<bt>She spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Lord God has given me a good/nice gift. So (consequently) now my husband must give me honour/respect, because I have given birth to six sons for him.&gt;&gt; That is why she named that child <span class="Italic">Sebulon</span> (which means &lt;give honour&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zvadani ... zeved: he makes a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">zvadani ... zeved: he makes a gift to me, he endows me with a dowry hapaʿam: at last, this once<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>yizbəleni: he will tolerate me, exalt me, he will make me his preferred wife</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais itu, Lea barana ame satu ana parampuan, ju dia kasi nama, <span class="Italic">Dina.</span><bt>After that, Lea gave birth to a daughter, and she named her, <span class="Italic">Dina.</span></bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dinah: like Dan? Commentary doesn't say."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">dinah: like Dan? Commentary doesn't say. Dinah doesn't get much mention, but the strange thing is that she is mentioned in this list at all. But it's probably because she does come up later, getting involved with the prince of Shekem.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais Tuhan Allah inga sang Rahel, ju Dia dengar dia pung sambayang. Andia ko Dia buka dia pung tampa ana.<bt>Then Lord God remembered/paid attention to Rahel, and He heard her prayer. That is why He opened her womb (&lt;child place).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yizkor: remembered, was mindful of yiftach"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yizkor: remembered, was mindful of yiftach ʾet-rachmah: he opened her womb. Goes back to Verses 1 and 2 and Jacob's principle, that fertility comes from Yahweh.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ais itu, Rahel dudu parú, ju dia barana ame ana laki-laki satu. Dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su angka buang beta pung malu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Rahel became pregnant, and she gave birth to a son. She said, &lt;&lt;Lord God has thrown away my shame.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vtahar: got pregnant ʾaSaf: gather, take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vtahar: got pregnant ʾaSaf: gather, take in, take away. Gathered up my disgrace and dumped it.<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>cherpati: my disgrace, reproach</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ju dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Yusuf</span> (yang pung arti kira-kira &lt;biar dia kasi tamba&gt;), tagal dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta minta ko Tuhan Allah kasi tamba sang beta satu ana laki-laki lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>And she named that child, <span class="Italic">Yusuf</span> (which means something like &lt;it would be good if he adds another&gt;), because she said, &lt;&lt;I am asking Lord God to give me another son.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yosef (ysf qal participle, Holladay): add."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yosef (ysf qal participle, Holladay): add. May he have it in the works. Not a jussive? And not past. yosef (ysf hif imperf, Paratext): add, continue increase. God has chosen to open my womb, so may he do it again! ʾsf "take away", ysf "add", but not necessarily a pun, because they may be there for different reasons.<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>ʾacher: another</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob cari akal ko tamba dia pung kambing-domba<bt>Yakob looks for a scheme to increase his goats-sheep</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Waktu Rahel su barana sang Yusuf, Yakob omong deng Laban bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! Kalo bisa, na, beta mau pulang pi beta pung negrí dolo.<bt>When Rahel had given birth to Yusuf, Yakob spoke to Laban saying, &lt;&lt;Father! If possible, na, I want to go home to my own country now.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaʾsher: when, coterminous; Book of Jubilees"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kaʾsher: when, coterminous; Book of Jubilees says all the births fit into the second 7 year period of Jacob working for Laban shalcheni: send me off<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʾelkhah (cohortative): I will go</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Biar beta pulang deng bawa beta pung bini deng ana-ana dong. Bapa su tau, beta su karjá banting tulang kasi bapa, jadi beta su bayar putus sang dong. Tagal itu, sakarang dong tu beta pung hak.&gt;&gt;<bt>Allow me to go home and take my wives and children. Father knows, I have worked myself to the bone for father, so I have fully paid for them. Because of that, they are now my right.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tənah (ntn imperv): give me yəladay:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tənah (ntn imperv): give me yəladay: my children. Are they really his legal children? Several are from concubines and would not normally be recognized for inheritance, like Ishmael.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>ʾelekhah (hlk imperf cohortative, same meaning as 25): I will go</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ais dia pung bapa mantu manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana, é! Lu dengar dolo. Beta su ramal abis, ju dapa tau bilang, Tuhan su kasi berkat sang beta, tagal lu.<bt>So [his] father-in-law responded saying, &lt;&lt;Child, é! Listen to me first. I have divined/fortune-told/performed an unnatural something to find-out something, and have found out that the Lord had given blessing to me, because of you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="buka kutika = divination (one kind,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">buka kutika = divination (one kind, fairly general) (kuno, not known by several UNS), pake cara galáp; jai langkung (Java); orang pintar; ramal ame ~ ramal abis</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsaʾti: I chanced upon, I found,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">matsaʾti: I chanced upon, I found, I found out. Laban is over a barrel. chen: favor, approval, affection, find pleasure or satisfaction. Laban is talking like an inferior to a superior.<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>nichashti (nchsh piʿel): seek and give an omen, practice divination, I learned through divination. But Wenham reads "I have grown rich." (Waldman and Finkelstein cite Akkadian nakhashu "become full or wealthy". Sarna follows the traditional "learned by divination" reading, as opposed to "learned by experience"; but the Akkadian hypothesis fits the situation better. "observing signs" is not necessarily religious.) biglalekha (gll II): on account of you<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Naa, sakarang lu mau minta barapa sa, beta bayar! Asal lu tenga di sini, deng karjá tarús kasi beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>Naa, [=shift] now whatever amount you want to ask, I will pay it! As long as you stay here and continue working for me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naqvah (nqv imperv): stipulate, specify skharkha:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">naqvah (nqv imperv): stipulate, specify skharkha: your wages. For future work?<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ais Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa su lia sandiri, beta pung karjá karás. Andia ko bapa pung binatang dong tamba banya tarús.<bt>So Yakob answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father has seen himself, how hard I work. That is why father's animals continue to increase so greatly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqnəkha: the livestock you own"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miqnəkha: the livestock you own</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Waktu beta balóm datang tu, bapa pung harta sonde bagitu banya. Ma sakarang, bapa su kaya. Tuhan su kasi berkat sang bapa, tagal beta pung karjá. Sakarang su sampe dia pung waktu, ko beta mau karjá lai kasi beta pung bini-ana dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>Before for I had arrived, father's possessions were not that many. But now, father is already rich. The Lord has given blessing to father, because of my work. Now it is time, for me to work for my wife-child (collective).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məʿaT: little, small vayifrots: spread out,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">məʿaT: little, small vayifrots: spread out, break out, increase<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>larov: in abundance ləragley: to my feet, everywhere I went<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>matay: how long? when? "my own house" is mainly Rachel.<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>A master shepherd would get about 20% of the value of the flocks he managed. Jacob's offer, which does not stipulate a percentage, gives Laban an apparent advantage.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ais ju Laban tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Jadi beta musti bayar karmana sang lu?&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Laban asked saying, &lt;&lt;So what do I need to pay you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tarús Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa sonde usa kasi beta apa-apa. Nanti beta piara tarús bapa pung binatang dong, asal beta bisa bekin satu hal.<bt>And Yakob answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father doesn't need to give me anything. I will continue to raise father's animals, as long as I can do one thing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məʾuwmah: something ʾashuvah: I will go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">məʾuwmah: something ʾashuvah: I will go back (continue)<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʾerʿeh: I will manage your flocks ʾeshmor: I will care for<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Kasi isin sang beta, ko ini hari ju beta pi di bapa pung binatang dong, ko pili ame kambing-domba. Yang sonde batitik, deng yang sonde ada baláng dong, biar itu bapa pung. Ma yang batitik, deng yang ada baláng dong, biar beta yang dapa. Deng beta ju ame samua domba yang itam. Biar samua tu, bayar beta pung cape.<bt>Give permission to me, so that today I can go to father's animals to select-out goats-sheep. The ones who are not spotted/speckled, and those that do not have splotches, let those be father's. But the ones who are spotted, and the ones that have splotches, allow me to get those. And I will also take all the sheep that are black. Permit all of those, to pay/compensate/reward for my labour/tiredness.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="batitik = spotted, speckled (UNS) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">batitik = spotted, speckled (UNS) ; baláng = splotched (UNS), striped (zebra)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeʿevor (ʿvr): I will pass from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾeʿevor (ʿvr): I will pass from one side to the other haSer (swr hif inf): to remove, clear away, cull<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>seh: young sheep, young goat naqod: speckled, spotted; anything but solid color<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>Taluʾ: spotted; anything but solid color chum: an undefined color between white and black; anything but white sheep<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>bakhsavim: among the young rams</Message></Annotation><note reference="30:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dolu orang pikir domba warna puti tu, yang bae. Dong tu, banya. Deng domba yang warna itam tu, sonde bae. Ma domba itam cuma sadiki sa. Kambing deng domba yang batitik, deng yang baláng dong, cuma sadiki sa.<bt>In the olden days, people thought that white sheep, were the good ones. And there were many of them. And black/dark sheep, were not good. But there were not very many black sheep. Goats and sheep that were spotted, and those that had splotches, were only a few.</bt></note><v n="33" />Di balakang hari, nanti bapa bisa tau beta ni jujur, ko sonde. Kapan sa, bapa bisa datang pareksa beta pung binatang dong. Kalo dapa lia ada kambing yang sonde batitik, ko sonde ada baláng, ko domba yang puti, na, bapa tau memang bilang, beta yang pancuri bapa pung binatang.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later on, father can know if I am honest, or not. Whenever [you like], father can come examine my animals. If [you] see there is a goat which is not spotted, or there is no splotch, or a white sheep, na, father will know immediately that I am the one who has stolen father's animals.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʿantah-bi tsidqati: you will be in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʿantah-bi tsidqati: you will be in a position to testify to my blameless behavior machar: tomorrow, in the future; sounds almost poetic here<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>ʿal-shkhari lpanekha: to look at my wages, inspect my flocks that I got from you ganuv: stolen<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>ʾiti: with me (implying that it has also been stolen)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00009c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ais ju Laban satuju bilang, &lt;&lt;Bae! Bagitu sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Laban agreed saying, &lt;&lt;Good! Let's do that.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lu: O that ...!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lu: O that ...!</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Ma itu hari ju Laban kasi pisa samua binatang batitik, yang ada baláng, deng domba yang itam. Ais dia suru dia pung ana-ana dong ko urus itu binatang dong.<bt>But that same day Laban separated out all the spotted animals, the ones that had splotches, and the black sheep. Then he ordered his children to organise those animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="banoda"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">banoda</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yasar (swr): he removed, diverted. Did"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yasar (swr): he removed, diverted. Did he do this to help Jacob (as UBS suggests; doing what Jacob wanted (verse 33), but hurrying up the process by putting his whole crew on it), or to cheat him? The nonwhite sheep are actually Jacob's property, but Laban reasons that they wonʾt breed as fast if they are segregated from the main flock. exchange w/consultant: [MC] I vote "to cheat". ; [JEG] I vote "to cheat" in spite of Verse 33. Laban was trying to get all the breeding stock out of Jacob's reach. Recessive genes werenʾt discovered until Mendel. But the verse doesn't actually commit itself one way or the other.<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>tyashiym (masc): male goats ʿəqudiym (masc): striped? with twisted tails?<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>Təluʾim (masc): spotted nəquddot (fem): speckled nannies<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>Təluʾot (fem): spotted</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />Tarús dong bawa itu binatang dong pi satu tampa yang dia pung jao tiga hari jalan kaki dari Yakob. Ais Yakob masi piara bapa mantu pung kambing-domba yang sisa dong.<bt>Then2 they took those animals to a place whose distance was three days' walk from Yakob. So then Yakob continued to raise his father-in-law's remaining goats-sheep.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanotarot (ytr nif): the remaining sheep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hanotarot (ytr nif): the remaining sheep</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ais itu, Yakob potong ame cabang dari tiga macam pohon, ko dia kupas bekin strep-strep.<bt>After that, Yakob cut off branches from three types of tress, to peel them into stripes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="takis = ranting, smaller than cabang,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">takis = ranting, smaller than cabang, ranting; loreng-loreng = camoflauge patterns</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maqqal: rod (singular, but collective), plural"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">maqqal: rod (singular, but collective), plural at end of verse. livneh: styrax officinalis, storax, like a white poplar, a small tree 9 to 18 feet tall<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>lach: a rod that is still moist with sap luz: almond tree<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>ʿermon: plane tree, Platanus orientalis, large leaves, grows near water, good shade. The bark peels off in sheets vayfatstsel (piʿel): peel a strip, strip off somethng from them<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>pətslot: strips of bark lavan: white. May be a pun on Laban's name. Jacob tries imitative magic, but God gives good breeding anyway.<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>machsof (chsf partcpl): peeling the bark, laying bare the wood maqlot: sticks, shoots<span class="Italic">(37)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Dia taro itu kayu bastrep dong di itu binatang pung tampa minum. Binatang dong suka bakawin di itu tampa minum.<bt>He placed the striped sticks at those animals' drinking place. Those animals liked to marry/intercourse (mate) at that drinking place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatstsog (hif pf): he set them,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yatstsog (hif pf): he set them, placed them pitstsel (piʿel): he had peeled<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>barahaTim: at the watering troughs, the water receptacles (generic against shoqet, specific kind) shiqətot (shoqet): watering troughs for cattle<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>tavoʾna: where they came (fem) lnokhach: directly in front<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>yechmanah: they were in heat bvoʾan (bwʾ inf): as they (fem) came to drink<span class="Italic">(38)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="39" />Jadi waktu binatang bakawin di muka itu kayu bastrep dong, nanti dong pung ana dong kaluar datang, dong pung bulu ju batitik deng ada baláng.<bt>So (consequently) when those animals mated in front of those striped sticks, their children would later come out/be born with their fur spotted and splotched.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿaqudim: with twisted tail"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿaqudim: with twisted tail</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ais waktu Laban pung binatang dong mau bakawin, Yakob kasi mangada sang dong pi di binatang yang batitik deng babaláng. Ais dong pung ana dong ju batitik deng babaláng. Deng bagitu, ju dia pung binatang sandiri batamba banya. Ais dia kasi pisa sang dong dari Laban pung binatang.<bt>Then when Laban's animals were about to mate, Yakob made them face the animals that were spotted and splotched. So their children were also spotted and splotched. In that way, his own animals increased greatly in number. Then he separated them from Laban's animals. [EXEG: NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kəshaviym (masc): lambs hifrid (prd hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kəshaviym (masc): lambs hifrid (prd hif): he separated them out<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>ʿaqod: twisted tail, streaked chuwm: dark colored sheep<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>vayashet-lo (shyt): put, set, lay, order, appoint. White sheep facing black goats? ʿadarim: flocks of an individual<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>lbado: be alone</Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Waktu binatang yang kuat dong bakawin, Yakob taro itu kayu bastrep-strep di dong pung muka, di dong pung tampa minum.<bt>When the strong animals were mating, Yakob place the striped sticks in front of them, at their drinking place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bkol-yachem (ychm piʿel inf): every time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bkol-yachem (ychm piʿel inf): every time they were in heat hamqushsharot (qshr puʿal partcpl): the sturdy ones<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>among the rods, by the rods</Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Ma kalo dia lia binatang mamalek yang bakawin, na, dia sonde taro itu kayu dong. Jadi Laban dapa samua binatang yang mamalek. Ma Yakob dapa samua binatang yang kuat-kuat.<bt>But when he saw the weak/withered/scrawny animals mating, na, he didn't place those sticks. So Laban got all the scrawny animals. But Yakob got all the very strong animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʿaTif (ʿtf hif): the weak ones"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haʿaTif (ʿtf hif): the weak ones</Message></Annotation><v n="43" />Deng bagitu, Yakob jadi kaya mau mati. Dia pung kambing, domba, onta, keledai, deng hamba-hamba dong talalu banya.<bt>In that way, Yakob became extremely wealthy. His goats, sheep, camels, donkeys, and servants were very many.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifrots: busting at the seams shfachot:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yifrots: busting at the seams shfachot: female slaves<span class="Italic">(43) (43) </span>ʿvadim: workers</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob lari kasi tenga Laban<bt>Yakob runs away from Laban</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="31" />
      <v n="1" />Satu kali, Yakob dapa dengar Laban pung ana dong ba'omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Yakob su kaya mau mati, tagal dia su garu bekin karíng kotong pung bapa pung harta dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Yakob heard Laban's children speaking saying, &lt;&lt;Yakob is extremely wealthy, because he has scratched dry our father's belongings.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="garu = scratch, rake (= rampok"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">garu = scratch, rake (= rampok bekin abis)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kavod: weight, property"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kavod: weight, property</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Yakob ju lia dia pung bapa mantu Laban pung muka su karíng-karíng, deng sonde bae-bae deng dia sama ke dolu lai.<bt>Yakob also saw that his father-in-law Laban's face was unfriendly (&lt;dry-dry), and he was no longer nice as he had been before.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="muka su karing-karing = cold toward,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">muka su karing-karing = cold toward, unresponsive, not friendly, ignore</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəney lavan: Laban's face, Laban's attitude"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pəney lavan: Laban's face, Laban's attitude ʾeynennu: nothing to him; things with Laban were not like before; change in the relationship, gone sour.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>kitmol shilshom: like yesterday and the day before; formerly</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais itu, TUHAN omong deng Yakob bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang dia pung waktu su sampe. Jadi lu musti kambali pi di lu pung mama-bapa dong. Beta nanti sama-sama deng lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the LORD spoke with Yakob saying, &lt;&lt;Now the time has arrived. So you must return to your father-mother (collective). I will be together with you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moladtekha: your country of origin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">moladtekha: your country of origin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00692c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Yakob katumu deng dia pung bini dua<bt>Yakob meets with his two wives</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ais itu, Yakob suru pi pange sang Rahel deng Lea, ko datang katumu deng dia di tampa binatang di padang.<bt>After that, Yakob ordered Rahel and Lea to be summoned, to meet with him where the animals were in the open-field.</bt><v n="5" />Ais dia kasi tau sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Balakang hari ni, beta lia bosong pung bapa pung muka su karíng-karíng sa deng beta. Dia ju su sonde bae-bae deng beta lai sama ke dolu. Ma Tuhan Allah yang beta pung bapa sémba tu, ada sama-sama deng beta.<bt>Then he told them saying, &lt;&lt;Recently, I've seen your father's face is just dry-dry/unfriendly with me. And he is no longer nice to me as before. But Lord God who my father worships, is together with me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʾeh (rʾh partcpl): I see, notice,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">roʾeh (rʾh partcpl): I see, notice, am seeing tmol: yesterday. Same as in Verse 2.<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>shishom: 3 days ago, day before yesterday</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Bosong dua tau, bagini lama ni, beta su karjá banting tulang satenga mati kasi bosong pung bapa!<bt>The two of you know, as long as I've been here, I've worked to the bone for your father!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾatenah (2pl fem): you all (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾatenah (2pl fem): you all (not dual) bkol kochi (koach): in all my strength, to the best of my ability<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Biar bagitu, ma dia ju tipu barmaen sang beta ulang kali. Dia ganti beta pung sewa sampe sapulu kali. Biar bagitu, ma Tuhan Allah jaga mati sang beta.<bt>Even though it was like that, nevertheless he still deceived/conned me repeatedly. He changed my rent/wages ten times. Even though he did that, nevertheless Lord God has faithfully watched/guarded me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="culas = hati bengko"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">culas = hati bengko</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hetel (tll hif): cheat, deceive hechlif"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hetel (tll hif): cheat, deceive hechlif (chlf hif one thing follow another): replace one thing with another, changes wages<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>maskurti (maskhoret): wages ʿaseret: ten<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>monim: times ntano: allowed him (ntn)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lharaʿ (rʿʿ ʿim hif): harm someone</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Waktu bosong pung bapa omong bilang, &lt;Itu binatang batitik dong, jadi lu pung sewa,&gt; ju itu binatang dong barana ana batitik samua. Laen kali, dia omong lai bilang, &lt;Sakarang binatang yang ada baláng dong, jadi lu pung sewa,&gt; ju itu binatang dong barana ana baláng samua.<bt>When your father spoke saying, &lt;Those spotted animals, will be your wages,&gt; then all those animals had spotted children. Another time, he spoke differently saying, &lt;Now the animals that have splotches, will be your wages,&gt; then all those animals had splotched children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾim-koh: whenever nqudim (nqd): spotted, speckled|i(8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾim-koh: whenever nqudim (nqd): spotted, speckled<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>ʿəqudim: with twisted tails</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Tuhan Allah bekin bagitu, ko biar Dia ame bosong pung bapa pung binatang, ko kasi sang beta.<bt>Lord God did like that, so that He took your father's animals to give to me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayatstsel (ntsl hif): snatch away, take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayatstsel (ntsl hif): snatch away, take away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Satu kali, waktu binatang dong pung musim bakawin, beta lia dalam mimpi bilang, samua binatang laki yang ada bakawin tu, ada yang baloreng, batitik, deng ada yang baláng.<bt>One time, when the animals had their mating season, I saw in a dream, that all the male animals that were mating, had camoflauge-pattern, spots, and splotches.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baloreng = camoflauge pattern, multiple colours"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">baloreng = camoflauge pattern, multiple colours</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿet: time yachem (piʿel inf): in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿet: time yachem (piʿel inf): in heat<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʿessaʾ (nsʾ): lift up (eyes), look ʿatudim: male goats, rams<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>haʿolim (ʿlh): that were breeding brudim: speckled, dappled<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ais Tuhan pung ana bua dari sorga pange sang beta dalam mimpi bilang, &lt;We! Yakob!&gt;<bt>Then the Lord's *angel called me in the dream saying, &lt;We, Yakob!&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais beta manyao bilang, &lt;Ada apa, Tuhan?&gt;<bt>So I responded saying, &lt;What is it, Lord.?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Regular interchange forms."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Regular interchange forms.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ju dia kasi tau bilang, &lt;Lia dolo! Samua binatang laki yang bakawin dong, cuma ada yang baloreng, batitik, deng baláng. Beta yang ator itu samua, tagal Beta su lia apa yang Laban su bekin ame sang lu.<bt>And he told saying, &lt;Look here! All the male animals that are mating, there are only camoflauge-pattern, spots, and splotches. I am the one who has arranged all that. Because I have seen what Laban has done to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Could refer to dreams, though Sarna"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Could refer to dreams, though Sarna thinks not. saʾ (nsʾ imperv): lift up, look<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>rəʾeh (imperv): see</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Beta ni, Tuhan Allah yang kasi tunju diri sang lu di Betel. Di sana lu kasi badiri batu, ais po'a minya di atas ko sémba sang Beta. Ais lu ika janji deng Beta di situ. Sakarang lu musti jalan kasi tenga ini negrí, ko pulang pi lu pung mama-bapa dong pung negrí sana.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>I am the Lord God who revealed Himself to you at Betel. There you erected a stone, and poured oil on top, to worship Me. Then you bound a promise with Me there. Now you must go leaving behind this country, to return-home to your father-mother (collective)'s country there.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mashachta: you poured oil on the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mashachta: you poured oil on the surface of something matstsevah: standing-stone, usually an unhewn, upright stone for cult, burial-marking, or memorial purposes. Forbidden from Deuteronomy on, but used earlier by Jacob and Moses; also of stones erected to Baal and Egyptian obelisks.<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>nadarta li sham neder (ndr): vowed to me there to do a special deed moladtekha: your relations, descent<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais Rahel deng Lea manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu! Botong iko sa! Te botong su sonde ada pung pusaka apa-apa lai dari bapa Laban.<bt>Then Rahel and Lea responded saying, &lt;&lt;Fine! We'll go along with it! Cause we no longer have any belongings/inheritance from father Laban.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʿod: no more, nothing else. Would"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haʿod: no more, nothing else. Would this be because the property would go to Laban's sons? Or because he was managing it poorly? cheleq: share of property<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>nachəlah: inalienable hereditary possession</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Bagini lama, bapatua su anggap sang botong sama ke orang luar sa. Dia su jual buang sang botong. Ais dia makan buang botong pung belis.<bt>For a long time, the old-man has considered us just like foreigners. He has sold us off. And then he has fully consumed our bridewealth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haloʾ: doesn't he ... arenʾt we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haloʾ: doesn't he ... arenʾt we ... nakhriyyot (nakhri): foreigners, aliens. That's sort of what Jacob was, and it sounds like Laban was treating them that way.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>nechshavnu lo (chshv nif): we are considered by him as mkharanu: he sells us. This term was used for bride price (dowry) at that time, but the women hadnʾt benefitted from it.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>yoʾkhal gam-ʾakhol: and he has moreover eaten up kaspenu: the money he paid for us? our money?<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Samua harta yang Tuhan Allah ame dari bapa Laban tu, sakarang su jadi botong deng botong pung ana-ana dong pung pusaka. Jadi kalo Tuhan su bilang karmana, na, iko sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>All the belongings1 that Lord God has taken from father Laban, now has become ours, and our children's belongings2/inheritance. So (consequently) whatever the Lord has said, na, just go along with it!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿosher: riches hitstsil (ntsl hif): rescue,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿosher: riches hitstsil (ntsl hif): rescue, pull out<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-18" />Ais itu, Yakob mulai manyimpan dia pung barang-barang dong. Ju dia kasi nae dia pung bini-ana dong samua di atas onta, deng foo bawa dia pung binatang dong samua, deng barang-barang yang dia dapa di Padan Aram, ko dong pulang pi tana Kana'an.<bt>After that, Yakob began to pack his belongings. Then he put up all of his wives-children on camels, and herded along all his animals, and the things which he had obtained in Padan Aram, to return-home to the land of Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʾ: put them up yinhag: drive,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yissaʾ: put them up yinhag: drive, lead<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>rəkhusho: he had gathered qinyano: his possession<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Itu waktu, Laban ada pi gunting dia pung domba dong pung bulu. Ju Rahel curi bawa dia pung bapa pung patong songgo dong.<bt>At that time, Laban had gone scissoring his sheep's fur. And Rahel stole away his father's *worship statues.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ligzoz: to shear sheep tignov: she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ligzoz: to shear sheep tignov: she stole<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>tərafim: idols, figurines or household gods, maybe like Kwanyin or Buddha statues. Probably made of baked clay, very likely images of Ashtarot, the goddess of sex and childbearing. Rachel may have taken them because she wanted to have another baby</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Yakob dong barangkat diam-diam sa, deng sonde kasi tau dia pung bapa mantu.<bt>Yakob (collective) just left quietly, and didn't tell his father-in-law.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayignov et-lev laban: he stole Laban's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayignov et-lev laban: he stole Laban's heart = he deceived Laban ʿal-bli: because, without<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>higid lo (ngd hif): (without) informing him boreach (partcpl): fleeing<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Dia angka bawa dia pung harta dong samua, ais dong jalan buru-buru lewat kali Efrat, ju dong mangada pi gunung Gilead.<bt>He took along all his possessions, and they went quickly by way of/across the Efrat river, and they faced toward the Gilead mountain.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayasem et-panaw har hagilʿad (sim): set"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayasem et-panaw har hagilʿad (sim): set his face to the mountains of Gilead; headed for the high country in Gilead. The desert country was fairly level and high to the east of the Jordan Riva, but near the Jordan it went up even higher, with a sharp dropoff and small canyons cutting through it down to the Jordan River about 4,000 feet below. The rest of the chapter takes place not far from Jabbok Stream, which goes from the plateau down to the Jordan and has a wide enough valley that people can follow it between the plateau and the river.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Laban pi buru sang Yakob<bt>Laban chases after Yakob</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Lewat tiga hari, ju Laban dapa kabar bilang, Yakob dong su bangun lari.<bt>After three days, Laban received news that, Yakob (collective) had fled.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yuggad (ngd hofʿal): he was informed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yuggad (ngd hofʿal): he was informed</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ais Laban kumpul dia pung orang dong, ko pi buru sang dia pung ana mantu. Dong buru sampe tuju hari, baru dapa sang dong di gunung-gunung Gilead.<bt>So Laban gathered his people, to chase after his son-in-law. They chased for seven days, only-then encountered them in the mountains of Gilead.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirdof: he pursued vayadəbeq ʾoto (dbq"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yirdof: he pursued vayadəbeq ʾoto (dbq hif): they caught up to him (after sticking with his trail)<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Dia pung malam, ju Tuhan kasi tunju diri sang Laban dalam mimpi. Dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Laban! Nanti, kalo lu omong deng Yakob, lu jaga bae-bae lu pung mulu.&gt;&gt;<bt>That night, the Lord revealed Himself to Laban in a dream. He said, &lt;&lt;Laban! Later on, when you speak with Yakob, guard your mouth/watch what you say.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshamer (nif imperv): take heed to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hishshamer (nif imperv): take heed to yourself</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Itu malam, Yakob su pasang tenda di gunung Gilead. Ais Laban dong ju pasang dong pung tenda sonde jao dari situ.<bt>That night, Yakob had fastened his tent in/at/on the Gilead mountain. Then Laban (collective) also fastened their tents not far from there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashsheg (nshg hif): he overtook taqaʿ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yashsheg (nshg hif): he overtook taqaʿ: strike, thrust; set up tents<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ais itu, Laban datang katumu deng Yakob. Ju dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Heh, Yakob! Akurang ko lu bawa lari beta pung ana parampuan dong diam-diam bagini? Sama ke bawa orang yang lu tawan ame dalam paráng.<bt>After that, Laban came and met with Yakob. And he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;He! Yakob! Why did you run off quietly with my daughters like this? It's like taking people you have captured/taken prisoner/hostage in a war.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yoʾmer: he said (but in v."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yoʾmer: he said (but in v. 26 they are in separate camps) tignov: you stole my heart = you deceived me, as in v. 20. "bulai" involves an untruth, but not a deceptive action.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>vatnaheg (piʿel): carry off, lead away, drive off shvuyot (shvh pt): ones who have by made captive<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>charev: sword</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Masa' lu lari diam-diam, sonde pake togor sang beta lai! Kalo lu kasi tau sang beta bae-bae, tantu beta bekin pesta rame-rame, ko antar sang bosong pake musik,<bt>(Modal of speaker attitude) I can't believe you ran off quietly, and didn't even take-leave of me! If you had told me nicely/politely, I would certainly have made a festive party, and escorted you-pl with music,</bt><note reference="31:27" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;manyanyi deng pake tambur kici deng alat musik yang pake sanár&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language says &lt;sing with small drums and musical instruments that use strings&gt;.</bt></note>baru lapás sang bosong ko barangkat.<bt>and-then release you to leave.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ben = band ; drom ben"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ben = band ; drom ben = marching band ; musik ben = band in a room, but anachronistic for Bible times, to some implies drum set, electric guitars and electric keyboard</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nachəbeʾta (chbʾ nif): you hid yourself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nachəbeʾta (chbʾ nif): you hid yourself livroach (inf): to flee<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>tignov: you stole ʾəshallechəkha (piʿel): I would have let you go<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>simchah: joy shiriym: songs<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>bətof: tambourine kinnor: harp, guitar?<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Lu pung sala satu lai, andia lu sonde kasi beta sampat ko ciom beta pung ana-cucu dong, baru lapás sang dong. Lu pung cara ni, talalu bodo!<bt>And you-sg have done an additional wrong, that is, you did not give me opportunity to kiss me children-grandchildren, before releasing them. Your way of handling this, is too stupid/ignorant of proper norms!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nəTashtani (nTsh): you didnʾt leave me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nəTashtani (nTsh): you didnʾt leave me lənashsheq (piʿel inf): to kiss<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>hiSkalta (skl hif): you behaved foolishly ʿəso (ʿsh inf): its doing<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Deng gampang beta bisa bekin calaka sang lu! Ma tadi malam, Tuhan Allah, yang lu pung bapa sémba tu, togor sang beta bilang, kalo beta omong deng lu, beta musti jaga bae-bae beta pung mulu.<bt>It would have been easy for me to do something disastrous to you! But last night, Lord God, whom your father worshipped, warned me that if/when I speak with you, I must watch my mouth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʾel: in the power of my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ləʾel: in the power of my hand ʾemesh: last night<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>hishshamer (shmr nif imperv): take care!</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Memang beta mangarti bilang, lu barangkat tagal lu su rindu mau pulang. Ma akurang ko lu masi curi bawa beta pung patong songgo dong?&gt;&gt;<bt>I really understand that you are leaving, because you are yearning to go home. But why did you also steal my worship statues?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="halokh (inf abs): go on, walk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">halokh (inf abs): go on, walk nikhSof nikhsaftah (ksf nif): you are deeply longing for<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00689c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Laban deng Yakob<bt>Laban and Yakob</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ais ju Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;To'o jang mara sang beta! Beta jalan diam-diam tu, tagal beta taku, jang sampe to'o tahan ame ini ana dong, na, karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Yakob responded saying, &lt;&lt;Uncle (MB) shouldn't be angry with me! I left quietly, because I was afraid that perhaps MB might restrain/detain these children, or something?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pen-tigzol: lest you take away by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pen-tigzol: lest you take away by force</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Ma Yakob sonde tau bilang, dia pung bini Rahel yang curi ame itu patong dong. Jadi dia bilang, &lt;&lt;To'o! So'al patong tu, cari sa! Kalo dapa di sapa, na, hukum bekin mati sang dia. Galeda samua sa! Kalo dapa to'o pung barang pusaka laen, na, ame pulang. Biar ini orang dong samua jadi saksi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob didn't know that his wife Rahel was the one who had stolen those statues. So (consequently) he said, &lt;&lt;MB! About those statues, just look for them! If you find them in whoever's [possession], na, punish him/her to death. Scrounge/search [like customs official] through everything! If you find any other of MB's possession, take them back. Let all these people here be witnesses.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="galeda = pareksa, bongkar cari, like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">galeda = pareksa, bongkar cari, like a customs search</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="in front of haker-ləkha (nkhr hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">in front of haker-ləkha (nkhr hif): investigate, recognize; look it over as if you had never seen it before and recognize<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ais Laban pi galeda dong satu-satu pung tenda. Mula-mula Yakob pung tenda. Ais dia pi di Lea pung tenda. Tarús itu hamba parampuan dua pung tenda dong. Ma dia sonde katumu itu patong dong. Ahirnya, dia maso pi Rahel pung tenda.<bt>So Laban went and scrounge-searched in each of their tents. He began with Yakob's tent. Then he went to Lea's tent. After that the two female servants' tents. But he didn't find those statues. Finally, he went into Rahel's tent.</bt><v n="34" />Ma Rahel su sambunyi itu patong dong di kolong onta pung sadel. Ais dia dudu di atas itu sadel. Laban galeda alus-alus di Rahel pung tenda, ma sonde katumu.<bt>But Rahel had hidden those statues underneath the camel's saddle. Then she sat on top of that saddle. Laban scrounge-searched carefully in Rahel's tent, but he didn't find [them].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sadel, sela = saddle (sela not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sadel, sela = saddle (sela not known by younger generation), pelana (BI)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kar: saddle yəmashshesh: feel, grope; he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kar: saddle yəmashshesh: feel, grope; he rummaged through, opening everything up and looking inside<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ju Rahel omong deng dia pung bapa bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa jang mara. Beta sonde bisa badiri, te beta ada datang bulan.&gt;&gt; Tarús Laban cari-cari lai, ma dia sonde dapa itu patong dong.<bt>Then Rahel spoke to her father saying, &lt;&lt;I'm sorry, father [&lt;don't be angry]. I can't stand up, cause I'm having my period (Idiom &lt;coming month).&gt;&gt; So then Laban continued searching, but he didn't find those statues.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-yichar (chrh): donʾt get angry derek"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-yichar (chrh): donʾt get angry derek nashim: the way of women; menstrual period<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ychafes: he looked for it thoroughly</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ais Yakob pung dara nae, ju dia masparak sang Laban bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su bekin jahat apa sang to'o? Sampe to'o buru sang beta, tingka ke beta orang jahat!<bt>Then Yakob became angry (&lt;his blood rose), and he spoke-angrily to Laban saying, &lt;&lt;What evil have I done to MB? To-point-that MB has hunted me, as if I am an evil person/criminal!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar (chrh): became angry vayarev (riv):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yichar (chrh): became angry vayarev (riv): start a quarrel in public, attack verbally<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>mah-pishʿi: what is my rebellion against community solidarity? dalaqta: hotly pursue<span class="Italic">(36)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="37" />To'o su galeda abis beta pung barang-barang samua. Ais to'o dapa apa? Coba taro di muka sini ko kotong samua lia! Biar ini orang dong putus bilang, itu barang, sapa pung.<bt>MB has thoroughly scrounged-searched all my belongings. So what did MB find? Please place it here in front of us for all of us to see! Let these people decide who owns those things.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishshashta (piʿel): feel, grope yowkhiychu (ykch):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mishshashta (piʿel): feel, grope yowkhiychu (ykch): let them decide<span class="Italic">(37)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Su 20 taon beta bakuli sang to'o. Waktu beta jaga to'o pung binatang dong, sonde ada satu yang miskram. Satu ekor ju, beta sonde makan!<bt>For 20 years, I have hard-laboured for MB. When I watched MB's animals, there was not one that miscarried. Not even one tail did I eat!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miskram = miscarriage, gugur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">miskram = miscarriage, gugur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rcheleykha: your ewes (sheep) vʿizeykha: and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">rcheleykha: your ewes (sheep) vʿizeykha: and nanny goats<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>loʾ shikelu (piʿel): they never had a miscarriage ʾeyley (ʾayil): rams<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>ʾakhalti: I did not eat. SK "He's mad!"</Message></Annotation><v n="39" />Kalo ada binatang jahat yang bekin mati to'o pung binatang satu, beta sonde lapor sang to'o, ma beta ganti. Deng kalo orang pancuri to'o pung binatang, to'o suru beta ganti, biar bukan beta pung sala.<bt>If there was an vicious animal that killed one of MB's animals, I didn't report it to MB, but I replaced it. And if someone stole MB's animals, MB ordered me to replace it, even though it was not my fault.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tərefah: carcass torn by wild animals"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tərefah: carcass torn by wild animals heveʾtiy (hif): I did not bring<span class="Italic">(39) (39) </span>ʾachaTTenah (chTʾ piʿel): I made amends for it, I compensated for it tbaqshenah: you looked for [compensation], asked for<span class="Italic">(39) (39) </span>gənuvti (pass partcpl): I had it stolen</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />Siang-siang, matahari panggang sang beta. Malam-malam, beta gamatar dingin. Beta mete sampe sonde bisa tidor, tagal jaga to'o pung binatang.<bt>Day after day, the sun roasted me. Night after night, I shook with cold. I stayed awake, to-point-that I not couldn't sleep, because I was guarding MB's animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="some UNS's at check prefer bapak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">some UNS's at check prefer bapak to to'o in this passage ; kuti kalereng = shoot marbles ; kaneker = kelereng</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəchalaniy: it devoured me, ate me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾəchalaniy: it devoured me, ate me choreb: dryness, heat<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>qerach: frost tidad (ndd imperf fem): it fled, it wandered<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>shənatiy: my sleep</Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Memang 20 taon tu, batúl! Beta karjá 14 taon, ko dapa to'o pung ana parampuan dong. Ais itu, beta karjá tamba lai 6 taon, ko bisa dapa beta pung binatang. Karjá kuli bagitu lama, ma to'o maen ganti beta pung sewa sampe sapulu kali.<bt>That's really how it was for 20 years! I worked 14 years, to get MB's daughters. After that, I worked another 6 years, so I could get my animals. Worked hard-labour for so long, but MB kept changing my wages/rent as many as ten times.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bishtey: for your two daughters tachəlef"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bishtey: for your two daughters tachəlef (hif): you changed, replaced. Laban was breaking Hammurabi's Code right and left, and also later Jewish code, by not paying up promptly and fairly. SK "He telling um eryting dat go wrong now."<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>maskurtiy: my wages ʿeseret monim: ten times = over and over<span class="Italic">(41)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Ontong ada Tuhan Allah, yang ba'i Abraham deng bapa Isak sémba. Kalo Dia sonde jaga sang beta, pasti to'o su suru usir pulang sang beta deng tangan kosong. Ma Tuhan Allah sonde tutu mata deng beta pung susa, deng Dia lia beta pung karjá samua. Andia ko tadi malam, Dia datang togor sang to'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>Fortunately there was Lord God, whom grandfather Abraham and father Isak worship. If He had not watched over me, certainly MB would have evicted me sending me home with empty hands. But Lord God didn't close [His] eyes on my difficulty, and He saw all my work. That is why last night, He came and rebuked MB.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NOTE: “Fear of Isaac” is understranslated"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">NOTE: “Fear of Isaac” is understranslated here. Marge C says HCE “He da One dat make Isaac scared an shaky cuz he so awesome.” “is the best translation of "the terror of Isaac" I've seen.”</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luley: if he had not ..."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">luley: if he had not ... [contrary to fact], you would have ... pachad: trembling, terror; the God who makes Isaac feel terrified<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>reyqam: empty-handed ʿanyi: me overwhelmed by want, poor, wretched, in a situation of affliction<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>ygiyaʿ (ygʿ): exertion, gone to a lot of trouble, hard work kafay (kaf): my hollow, outspread hand, palm<span class="Italic">(42) (42) </span>yokhach (ykch hif): he gave judgment ʾamesh: yesterday evening<span class="Italic">(42)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob deng Laban ba'ika janji<bt>Yakob and Laban bind a promise</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Dengar abis Yakob pung omong bagitu, ju Laban manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini! Itu parampuan dua tu, beta pung ana. Ana-ana yang dong barana ame tu, beta pung cucu samua. Ini binatang samua ni, beta pung. Samua yang lu lia di sini ni, memang beta pung. Ma beta mau bekin apa? Beta sonde bisa tahan sang dong.<bt>After hearing Yakob speak like that, Laban responded saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! Those two women are my children. Those children which they gave birth to, are all my grandchildren. All these animals here, are mine. Everything which you see here now, is really mine. But what should/can I do? I cannot detain them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʾeh (partcpl): everything you are looking"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">roʾeh (partcpl): everything you are looking at ʾo: particle of choice. SK "I thought he wen give um."<span class="Italic">(43)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Jadi lebe bae, kotong dua ba'ika janji. Deng kotong musti idop iko itu janji.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be best, if the two of us-inc RECIP-bind a promise. And we must live according to that promise.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləkhah (hlk imperv): go nikrətah (krt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ləkhah (hlk imperv): go nikrətah (krt cohortative): let's cut a deal<span class="Italic">(44) (44) </span>ʿed: witness. The contents of the deal were not on paper, but they would be in the minds of everyone; common in preliterate societies like this one.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ais itu, Yakob ame satu batu bésar, ko kasi badiri di situ jadi tanda.<bt>After that, Yakob took a large stone, to erect there, as a sign.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tugu = monument, (tanda easier to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tugu = monument, (tanda easier to translate and favoured by UNS's)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yrimeah (rwm hif): caused it to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yrimeah (rwm hif): caused it to be put up, set it up</Message></Annotation><v n="46" />Ais Yakob suru dia pung orang dong, ko pi kumpul batu ko timbun. Ju dong samua dudu makan deka itu batu dong.<bt>And Yakob ordered his people to gather rocks, to pile them up. Then they all sat ad ate near those stones.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="timbun = pile, heap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">timbun = pile, heap</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="liqTu (lqT imperv): gather up gal:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">liqTu (lqT imperv): gather up gal: heap of stones<span class="Italic">(46)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="47" />Ais Laban kasi nama itu batu batimbun, <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span>. Ma Yakob kasi nama, <span class="Italic">Galeed</span>.<bt>Then Laban named that pile of rocks, <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span>. But Yakob named it <span class="Italic">Galeed</span>.</bt><note reference="31:47" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Aram, <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span> pung arti &lt;batu saksi&gt;. Dalam bahasa Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Galeed</span> pung arti &lt;batu saksi&gt; ju.<bt>In the Aram language <span class="Italic">Yegar Sahaduta</span> means 'witness monument/rock'. In the Ibrani language <span class="Italic">Galeed</span> means 'witness monument/rock'.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ais Laban bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini batu batimbun ni, jadi saksi kasi kotong dua.&gt;&gt; Andia ko itu tampa nama, Galeed.<bt>Then Laban said, &lt;&lt;This pile of ricks here, is a witness to/between the two of us-inc.&gt;&gt; That is why that place is named, Galeed.</bt><v n="49" />Laban ju kasi nama itu tampa, <span class="Italic">Mispa</span> (yang pung bunyi amper sama ke kata laen, yang pung arti &lt;tampa jaga yang tinggi&gt;), tagal dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Nanti TUHAN sandiri yang jaga kotong dua, ko biar kotong bajao ju, kotong jang langgar ini janji.<bt>Laban also named that place, <span class="Italic">Mispa</span> (which is similar to another word meaning &lt;high place for guarding&gt;), because he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;The LORD himself is the one who watches/guard the two of us-inc, so that even if/when/though we are far from each other, we don't violate this promise.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mitspah: observation point, place from which"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mitspah: observation point, place from which you can see people coming a long way off, watch tower yitsef (tsph): may he guard, keep an eye on<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>niSSater (Str nif): we are hidden from each other, we are out of each other's sight reʿahu: his counterpart<span class="Italic">(49)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="50" />Kalo lu bekin jahat sang beta pung ana dong ni, ko, kawin deng parampuan laen dong, tantu beta sonde tau. Ma inga! Tuhan Allah yang jadi saksi sang lu deng beta.<bt>If you-sg do evil to these children of mine here, or marry other women, I would certainly not know [it]. But remember! Lord God is the one who is a witness between you and me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təʿaneh (ʿnH II piʿel): you humiliate,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">təʿaneh (ʿnH II piʿel): you humiliate, oppress</Message></Annotation><v n="51-52" />Coba lia ini batu yang badiri, deng batu batimbun. Inga, te ini batu dong, ju jadi batas. Lu sonde bole lewat ini batu dong ko bekin jahat sang beta. Deng beta ju sonde bole lewat ini batu dong ko bekin jahat sang lu.<bt>Please look at this stone which is standing, and the pile of rocks. Remember, these stones, are also a boundary. You may not pass these stones to do evil to me. And I also may not pass these stones to do evil to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***&quot;also&quot; added to boundary, Amarasi check"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">***"also" added to boundary, Amarasi check Oct 2005</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gal: cairn matstsevah: stone set up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gal: cairn matstsevah: stone set up as a reminder<span class="Italic">(51) (51) </span>ʿedah: witness, another form (fem)</Message></Annotation><v n="53" />Kotong ika ini janji ni, pake kotong pung nene-moyang pung Tuhan Allah. Andia lu pung ba'i Abraham, deng beta pung ba'i Nahor pung Allah. Nanti Dia sandiri yang jadi hakim ko putus kotong pung parkara.&gt;&gt;<bt>We-inc bind this promise now, using our-inc ancestors' Lord God. That is, your grandfather Abraham, and my grandfather Nahor's Allah. Later He himself is the one who is the judge to decide our matter/dispute/litigation.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar abis bagitu, ju Yakob angka sumpa mati, pake nama dari Tuhan Allah yang dia pung bapa Isak sémba.<bt>After hearing that, Yakob lifted up an oath of death, using the name of Lord God whom his father Isak worshipped.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NOTE: Terror (cf v.42)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">NOTE: Terror (cf v.42)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishftu: settle the dispute (plural) vayishavaʿ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishftu: settle the dispute (plural) vayishavaʿ: swore an oath<span class="Italic">(53) (53) </span>bfachad: by the Terror (v. 42)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Ais itu, Yakob horo binatang, ju dia bawa jadi korban kasi Tuhan di atas itu gunung. Tarús dia pange orang dong samua ko makan rame-rame, deng dong mete sampe pagi di situ.<bt>After that, Yakob cut an animal, and he took it as a sacrifice to the Lord on top of that mountain. Then he summoned everyone to eat festively together, and they stayed awake until morning there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaliynu (lwn, lyn): they spent the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaliynu (lwn, lyn): they spent the night</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Dia pung beso papagi, ju Laban pi paló-ciom dia pung ana-cucu dong samua. Ais dia omong kasi berkat sang dong, ju dia pulang pi dia pung negrí.<bt>Early the next morning, Laban went hugging-kissing all his children-grandchildren. And he spoke giving blessing to them, and he returned-home to his country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaynasheq (piʿel): kissed fervently. This was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaynasheq (piʿel): kissed fervently. This was probably the last time he ever saw any of them.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob taku bakatumu deng dia pung kaka Esau<bt>Yakob is afraid to RECIP-meet with his older-sibling Esau</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="32" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, Yakob dong jalan tarús. Ju Tuhan pung ana bua dong dari sorga datang katumu deng dia.<bt>After that, Yakob (collective) continued going. And the Lord's *angels came and met with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifgʿu-bo: they encountered him, fell in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yifgʿu-bo: they encountered him, fell in with him. Pidgin "meet" is more intentional, so "see" may convey the chanceness of the meeting better.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Waktu lia sang dong, ju dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Mangkali di sini Tuhan pung tantara dong pung tampa barenti!&gt;&gt; Andia ko dia kasi nama itu tampa, <span class="Italic">Mahanaim</span> (yang pung arti &lt;dua tampa barenti&gt;).<bt>Upon seeing them, he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;This [+modal of certainty] is the Lord's army's stopping/resting place!&gt;&gt; That is why he named that place, <span class="Italic">Mahanaim</span> (which means &lt;two stopping/resting places&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʾam (rʾh): he sees them machəney:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raʾam (rʾh): he sees them machəney: a nomadsʾ camp? an army of spirits? if ʾelohim is plural. Can also be a military camp. Pidgin "camp" denotes a fixed camp for plantation workers, like Japanee Camp, so it has to go to "camping out" for temporary stays. The idea is that he is aware of the army of angels as God's protection for him. It is also the place where he splits his entourage into people and animals, which may be the reason behind the dual number.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais itu, Yakob suru dia pung ana bua barapa orang jalan lebe dolo pi negrí Edom (andia, Seir), ko kasi tau dia pung kaka Esau bilang, dia ada mau datang.<bt>After that, Yakob ordered several of his underlings, to travel ahead to the country of Edom (that is, Seir), to tell his older-sibling Esau that he was coming.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləfanayw: go ahead of him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ləfanayw: go ahead of him</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Yakob kasi tau dia pung ana bua dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong pi kasi tau beta pung kaka Esau bagini: &lt;Bos Esau! Bos pung hamba, adi Yakob, kirim salam hormat bam-banya sang bos. Dari beta barangkat dolu sampe sakarang, bos pung hamba ada tenga di to'o Laban pung ruma.<bt>Yakob told his underlings saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl go tell my older-sibling Esau like this: &lt;Boss Esau! Boss's servant/slave, younger-sibling Yakob, sends many respectful greetings to boss. Since I left formerly until now, boss's servant has lived in MB Laban's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿavdəkha: your servant, in the sense"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿavdəkha: your servant, in the sense of giving Esau a higher status ʾechar: I stayed on<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Sakarang bos pung hamba su ada pung sapi, keledai, kambing-domba, hamba laki-laki deng hamba parampuan. Beta kirim ini orang dong lebe dolo, ko kasi kabar sang bos, so'al beta pung datang. Beta harap, bos suka tarima sang botong deng tangan tabuka.&gt;&gt;&gt; Ju itu orang dong pi.<bt>Now boss's servant here, already has cattle, donkeys, goats-sheep, and male and female servants. I send these people on ahead, to give news to boss of my ciming. I hope that boss will receive us open arms.&gt;&gt;&gt; So then those people went.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hati luas = receptive, agreeable, favourable"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">hati luas = receptive, agreeable, favourable ; nere-nere datang = strolling along leisurely</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="showr: head of cattle haggiyd (ngd"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">showr: head of cattle haggiyd (ngd hif inf): to announce<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Waktu dong datang kambali sang Yakob, dong lapor bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong su pi katumu deng bapa pung kaka Esau. Sakarang dia ada jalan datang deng 400 laki-laki, ko mau katumu deng bapa.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they came back to Yakob, they reported saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc have gone and met with father's older-sibling Esau. Now he is coming this way with 400 men, to meet with father.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="liqraʾtəkha: on his way to meet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">liqraʾtəkha: on his way to meet you, coming against you (used mainly of soldiers going into battle). "Meet" in Pidgin doesn't leave open the possibility that Esau is hostile, which is Jacob's expectation in the next verse. "Coming by you" may leave open the question of what his attitude is going to be.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Dengar bagitu, ju Yakob pung hati duk-dak, deng dia taku mau mati. Ais dia bagi dia pung orang deng binatang dong samua, jadi dua rombongan.<bt>Hearing that, Yakob's liver/heart pounded, and he was extremely afraid. So then he divided all his people and various kinds of animals, into two travelling-groups.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetser (tsrr intrans): he became anxious,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yetser (tsrr intrans): he became anxious, hard pressed, in distress yachats (htsh): he divided (transitive)<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lishney machənot: divided them into two camps, groups</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Dia pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo Esau datang, ko saráng ame rombongan partama, na, rombongan kadua bisa lari cari salamat.&gt;&gt;<bt>He thought saying, &lt;&lt;If Esau comes, and attacks the first travelling-group, na, the second travelling-group can run for safety.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hikkahu (nkh hif): strike, hit nishʾar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hikkahu (nkh hif): strike, hit nishʾar (nif partcpl): left, remaining<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>lifleyTah: for escape</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais itu, Yakob sambayang bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah, é! Tuhan yang beta pung ba'i Abraham deng beta pung bapa Isak sémba. Dengar sang beta dolo! Tempo hari, Tuhan yang suru beta ko pulang datang di beta pung kelu dong, di ini negrí. Tuhan yang janji bilang, nanti Tuhan ator bekin beres samua.<bt>After that, Yakob prayed saying, &lt;&lt;Lord God, é! The Lord whom my grandfather Abraham and my father Isak worship. Listen to me now! That day, the Lord was the one who ordered me to return home to my family/kin, in this country. The Lord was the one who promised, that later the Lord would arrange everything making them right.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&quot;ancesta&quot; is used for people farther"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">"ancesta" is used for people farther away than "granfadda" ʾeytivah (ytv hif): I will make things go well with you<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Beta sonde pantas tarima Tuhan pung sayang, deng Tuhan pung satia. Dolu waktu beta langgar kali Yarden, beta cuma bawa tongkat sa. Ma sakarang beta pulang datang bawa dua rombongan manusia deng binatang.<bt>I am not worthy to receive the Lord's love/affection, and the Lord's faithfulness. Formerly when I crossed/transgressed this Yarden river, I only brought a walking-stick. But now I am returning-home bringing two travelling-groups of humans and animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qaTonti: I am too trifling, small,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qaTonti: I am too trifling, small, unworthy mikol hachasadim: all your faithfulness to our relationship<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>umikol-haʾemet: all the reliability, fidelity, permanence, faithfulness, truth bmaqli: in/with my walking stick<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʿavarti: I crossed the boundary (the river)</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Beta taku, jang-jangan kaka Esau datang saráng bekin mati sang botong samua. Jadi beta minta ko Tuhan kasi salamat sang beta deng beta pung bini-ana dong samua dari kaka Esau.<bt>I am afraid, that probably older-sibling Esau is coming to attack and kill all of us-exc. So (consequently) I ask the Lord save/give safety to me, and all my wives-children, from odler-sibling Esau.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hatstsiyleni (ntsl hif): rescue me, get"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hatstsiyleni (ntsl hif): rescue me, get me out of trouble yareʾ (yrʾ partcpl): I am afraid<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʾem: mother</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Tuhan yang janji bilang, Tuhan kasi berkat bam-banya sang beta, deng bekin beta pung turunan batamba banya, sama ke pasir di pante yang orang sonde bisa itong ame.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Lord was the one who promised that the Lord would give many blessings to me, and make my descendants increase greatly [in number], like the sand on the beach, which people are unable to count.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heyTev ʾeyTiyv (yTb hif inf abs):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">heyTev ʾeyTiyv (yTb hif inf abs): I will certainly do good chol: sand<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yiSSafer (nif): cannot be counted</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ais Yakob tidor di itu tampa. Dia pung beso, ju dia pili ame binatang ko mau kasi parsén sang dia pung kaka.<bt>Then Yakob slep in that place. The next day, he prepared animals to give as gifts to his older-sibling.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʾ (bwʾ partcpl): the stuff coming"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">baʾ (bwʾ partcpl): the stuff coming along with him minchah: as a gift to show homage or allegiance and respect<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Dia pili ame 200 kambing mai, 20 kambing laki, 200 domba mai, 20 domba laki,<bt>He selected out 200 female goats, 20 male goats, 200 female sheep, 20 male sheep,</bt><v n="15" />30 onta mai deng dong pung ana yang masi susu, 40 sapi mai, 10 sapi laki, 20 keledai mai, deng 10 keledai laki.<bt>30 female camels with their children that were still nursing, 40 female cows, 10 male cows, 20 female donkeys, and 10 male donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meyniyqot (ynq hif partcpl fem): nursing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">meyniyqot (ynq hif partcpl fem): nursing their young ʾətonot: female donkeys<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ais dia bagi itu binatang dong, satu-satu macam deng dia pung rombongan. Tarús dia kasi satu-satu rombongan deng dia pung gambala. Dia kasi tau sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong jalan lebe dolo. Nanti beta iko dari balakang. Ma bosong musti jaga ko rombongan yang satu sadiki jao dari rombongan yang laen.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he divided those animals each type into its travelling-group. Then2 he gave each travelling-group its own herder. He told them saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl travel on ahead. I will follow from behind. But you must take-care so that each travelling-group is a lttle far from the other travelling-groups.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿeder ʿeder: divided up into smaller"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿeder ʿeder: divided up into smaller individual flocks or herds lbado: alone, separately from the rest<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʿivru lfani: let them go ahead of me rewach: a space between flocks<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais Yakob parenta gambala dari rombongan partama bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo beta pung kaka Esau katumu deng lu, deng dia tanya bilang, &lt;Lu mau pi mana? Lu ni, sapa pung hamba? Ini binatang dong, sapa pung?&gt;<bt>Then Yakob commanded the herder/s from the first travelling-group saying, &lt;&lt;If/When my older-sibling Esau meet you, and he asks saying, &lt;Where are you going? You are whose servant? These animals are whose?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifgashkha: he will meet you, fall"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yifgashkha: he will meet you, fall in with you ʾanah: where?<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Naa, bosong musti manyao bilang, &lt;Ini binatang dong, bos pung hamba Yakob pung. Dia kirim kasi sang dia pung kaka, bos Esau. Ma dia sandiri ada iko dari balakang.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Naa, [+shift] you-pl must answer saying, &lt;These animals belong to boss's servant Yakob. He sends them to his older-sibling, boss Esau. But he himself is following from behind.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəluwchah (qal passive partcpl): the gift"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shəluwchah (qal passive partcpl): the gift is being sent vhineh gam-huʾ: and behold, he too<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19-20" />Dia ju kasi parenta bagitu sang samua gambala dari rombongan laen dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo su katumu deng kaka Esau, bosong kasi parsén itu binatang dong. Tarús bosong kasi tau bilang, beta ada iko dari balakang.&gt;&gt; Yakob pikir, kalo dia kasi itu binatang dong samua sang Esau, nanti Esau pung hati jadi noe deng dia.<bt>He also commanded like that to all the herders from the other travelling-groups saying, &lt;&lt;If/when you have met older-brother Esau, you-pl give those animals as gifts, and then tell him that I am following from behind.&gt;&gt; Yakob thought, if he gave all those animals to Esau, then Esau liver would soften toward him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hati noe = tender, gentle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">hati noe = tender, gentle</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾakhappərah panaw (kpr piʿel): I will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾakhappərah panaw (kpr piʿel): I will cover his face (with a gift); I will appease him by giving him a gift ʾulay: maybe<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>yissaʾ fanay (nsʾ): he will lift my head (legal expression); pardon me</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Jadi dia kirim itu binatang dong lebe dolo. Ma itu malam, dia masi tenga di situ.<bt>So he sent those animals ahead. But that night, he still stayed there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob bagulat deng Tuhan<bt>Yakob wrestles/struggles/grapples with the Lord</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bagulat = wrestle,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bagulat = wrestle,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Itu malam, ju Yakob bangun, ais dia ator ko dia pung bini dua-dua, dia pung bini piara dua-dua, deng dia pung ana 11 orang, ko dong langgar pi kali Yabok pung sablá.<bt>That night, Yakob got up, and he arranged for both his wives, and both his kept-wives/concubines/mistresses, and his 11 children, to cross/transgress to the river Yabok's other side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʿavar: a place where you can"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">maʿavar: a place where you can go across a river or a canyon</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Waktu dong samua su sampe di sablá, ju dia kirim dia pung pusaka samua pi sana.<bt>When they all arrived on the other side, he sent all his belongings over there.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00686c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ma Yakob tenga sandiri di situ. Ais ju ada satu laki-laki datang, ko bagulat deng dia sampe amper siang.<bt>But Yakob remained alone there. And then, a man came, to wrestle with him until almost light.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwater (ytr nif): was left over,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiwwater (ytr nif): was left over, he stayed over yeʾaveq (nif): was wrestling with him. Like Hawaiian haəkoəkoə or even lua (hand-to-hand fighting, including bonebreaking)<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>ʿad ʿəlot hashachar: till the going up of the reddish light before dawn</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Waktu itu laki-laki rasa dia su mau kala, ju dia hantam Yakob pung pinggul, sampe dia pung tulang bonggol talapás dari dia pung tampa dudu.<bt>When that man felt that he was about to lose, he struck/attacked Yakob's hipbone, to-point-that his femur bone was released from its sitting place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pinggul = hipbone ; tulang bonggol"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pinggul = hipbone ; tulang bonggol = femur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiggaʿ (ngʿ): he touched him, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiggaʿ (ngʿ): he touched him, he hurt him bkhaf: on the hollow, the socket<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>yrekho: his hip socket teqaʿ (yqʿ): Jacob's joint dislocated, got sprained<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>bheʾavqo (ʾbq inf): in the course of his wrestling</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Tarús itu laki-laki bilang, &lt;&lt;Lapás sang beta, te lai sadiki matahari su mau nae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 that man said, &lt;&lt;Let me go, cause the sun will soon rise.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shachar: dawn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shachar: dawn</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu omong kasi berkat sang beta dolo, baru beta lapás sang lu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob responded saying, &lt;&lt;You speak giving blessing to me first, only-then will I release you!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ju itu laki-laki tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pung nama, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that man asked saying, &lt;&lt;What is your name?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Yakob.&gt;&gt;<bt>He answered saying, &lt;&lt;Yakob.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ais, itu laki-laki omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pung nama, bukan Yakob lai. Ma mulai sakarang, orang pange sang lu <span class="Italic">Isra'el,</span> tagal lu su bajuang lawan manusia deng Tuhan Allah, sampe lu manáng.&gt;&gt; (Nama Isra'el pung arti &lt;yang bagulat deng Allah&gt;.)<bt>Then, that man spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Your name is no longer Yakob. But beginning now, people will call you <span class="Italic">Israel</span> because you have struggled opposing humans and Lord God, to-point-that you have won.&gt;&gt; (The name Isra'el means &lt;he wrestles with Allah&gt;.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʾamer (nif): be called sarita (srh):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʾamer (nif): be called sarita (srh): you contend, strive, struggle<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>yisraʿel: God strives, strive with God</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Tarús Yakob tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pung nama, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob asked saying, &lt;&lt;What is your name?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma itu laki-laki bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu mau tanya beta pung nama bekin apa?&gt;&gt; Ais ju dia omong kasi berkat sang Yakob di situ.<bt>But that man said, &lt;&lt;You want to ask my name for what?&gt;&gt; Then he spoke giving blessing to Yakob there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hagidah-naʾ (ngd hif): inform, announce, put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hagidah-naʾ (ngd hif): inform, announce, put forward</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ais Yakob omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su dapa lia Tuhan Allah muka deng muka, ma beta masi idop.&gt;&gt; Andia ko dia kasi nama itu tampa, <span class="Italic">Peni'el</span>, yang dia pung arti &lt;Tuhan pung muka&gt;.<bt>Then Yakob spoke saying, &lt;&lt;I have seen/been able to see Lord God face to face, but I still live.&gt;&gt; Because of that he named that place, <span class="Italic">Peni'el</span>, which means &lt;the Lord's face&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tinnatsel (nif fem): I escaped, I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tinnatsel (nif fem): I escaped, I was rescued; my life was saved</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Matahari su nae waktu Yakob jalan kasi tenga itu tampa. Ma dia jalan doka-doka, tagal dia pung pinggul tasala.<bt>The sun arose, when Yakob was leaving that place. But he walked limping, because his hipbone was not-right.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pincang-pincang = doka-doka = limp"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pincang-pincang = doka-doka = limp</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsoleaʿ: limp, stumble along"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsoleaʿ: limp, stumble along</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Andia ko sampe sakarang, orang Isra'el dong sonde makan daging dari binatang pung pinggul, tagal Tuhan puku bekin tasala dong pung ba'i Yakob pung tulang pinggul.<bt>That is why to this time, the people of Israel do not eat the meat of an animal's hipbone, because the Lord hit making not-right their grandfather/ancestor Yakob's hipbone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gid: sinew nasheh: major nerve of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gid: sinew nasheh: major nerve of the hip region, nervus ischiadicus (nshh forget? forgotten?)? sciatic vein? (a mistake in the Paratext lexicon).<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] nerve? ; [JEG] The nasheh, or sciatic nerve, in humans passes to the rear of the hip joint. There are muscles with their tendons that run posterior to it, distal to it, and anterior to it. Glossing gid as ‘sinew’ doesn't help, because it means (Concise OED) ‘tendon or ligament’. The ileofemoral ligament that wraps the hip joint is the largest ligament in the human body. The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the human body, 2 cm in diameter near the hip. People who butcher animals as regularly as these folks did would be familiar with both, even though they might not go into details on the attachments of the musculature. So ‘the [big] ligament near the [big] nerve’ is probably what they mean. Has anybody asked a rabbi what part the Jews stay away from? UBS: Part of the expression refers to the sinew (or tendon). These are tough white bands of connective tissue that attach the muscle, in this instance, to the hip joint. Translations vary considerably in the way they express this. neb has “sinew of the nerve that runs in the hollow of the thigh,” reb “sinew that is on the hollow of the thigh,” spcl “the tendon that is in the hip joint,” frcl “the thigh muscle that is in the hip joint.” The ball is normally held in the socket by very powerful ligaments that form a complete sleeve around the joint (the joint capsule). Gray's Anatomy: The Sciatic (n. ischiadicus; great sciatic nerve) (Fig. 832) supplies nearly the whole of the skin of the leg, the muscles of the back of the thigh, and those of the leg and foot. It is the largest nerve in the body, measuring 2 cm. in breadth, and is the continuation of the flattened band of the sacral plexus. It passes out of the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen, below the Piriformis muscle. It descends between the greater trochanter of the femur and the tuberosity of the ischium, and along the back of the thigh to about its lower third, where it divides into two large branches, the tibial and common peroneal nerves. This division may take place at any point between the sacral plexus and the lower third of the thigh. When it occurs at the plexus, the common peroneal nerve usually pierces the Piriformis. In the upper part of its course the nerve rests upon the posterior surface of the ischium, the nerve to the Quadratus femoris, the Obturator internus and Gemelli, and the Quadratus femoris; it is accompanied by the posterior femoral cutaneous nerve and the inferior gluteal artery, and is covered by the Glutus maximus. Lower down, it lies upon the Adductor magnus, and is crossed obliquely by the long head of the Biceps femoris. The nerve gives off articular and muscular branches. The articular branches (rami articulares) arise from the upper part of the nerve and supply the hip-joint, perforating the posterior part of its capsule; they are sometimes derived from the sacral plexus.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob bakatumu deng dia pung kaka Esau<bt>Yakob RECIP-meets with his older-sibling Esau</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="33" />
      <v n="1" />Itu hari, ju Yakob dapa lia Esau datang deng dia pung rombongan 400 orang. Ais dia babagi dia pung ana dong kasi pi dong pung mama satu-satu.<bt>That day, Yakob saw Esau coming with his travelling-group of 400 people. So he divided his children to go with each of their mothers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachats: he divided into two or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yachats: he divided into two or more parts</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Dia ator ko itu dua bini piara deng dong pung ana dong jalan di muka. Ais Lea deng dia pung ana dong, baru Rahel deng dia pung ana Yusuf paling balakang.<bt>He arranged for his two kept wives and their children to go in front. The Lea and her children, only-then Rahel and her child Yusuf in the back.</bt><v n="3" />Ma Yakob jalan paling muka dari dong samua. Waktu su mau deka deng dia pung kaka, dia tikam lutut deng tondo sampe di tana, tuju kali.<bt>But Yakob went in front of them all. When already very close to his older-sibling, he kneeled and bowed-head to the ground, seven times.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəʿamiym: times ʿad-gishto (ngsh inf): until"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pəʿamiym: times ʿad-gishto (ngsh inf): until he approached<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ma waktu Esau dapa lia dia pung adi, ju dia lari pi katumu sang Yakob, ais paló-ciom sang dia. Ju dong dua bamanangis.<bt>But when Esau saw his younger-sibling, he ran to me Yakob, and hugged-kissed him. And the two of them cried-together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəchabqehu (piʿel): he embraced him yippol"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yəchabqehu (piʿel): he embraced him yippol ʿal-tsawwaʾro: he fell on his neck; flung himself on his neck, embraced him affectionately<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yishshaqehu (nshq): he kissed him</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Waktu Esau dapa lia itu parampuan deng ana-ana dong, ju dia tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Ko ini orang dong samua ni, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Esau saw those women and children, he asked saying, &lt;&lt;Whose are all these people?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Dong tu, orang-orang yang Tuhan Allah su kasi sang beta, kaka pung hamba.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yakob answered saying, &lt;&lt;They are the people whom Lord God has given me, older-sibling's servant.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chanan: acted graciously"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chanan: acted graciously</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ais itu, ju dia pung bini piara dong, deng dong pung ana-ana, datang soya sang Esau.<bt>And then, his kept wives, and their children, came and bowed-in-homage to Esau.</bt><v n="7" />Tarús Lea deng dia pung ana dong, datang soya sang Esau. Paling balakang, Yusuf deng dia pung mama Rahel datang soya sang Esau.<bt>Then2 Lea and her children came and bowed-in-homage to Esau. Most to the rear, Yusuf and his mother Rahel came and bowed-in-homage to Esau.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais ju Esau tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Itu rombongan binatang yang lu kirim tadi tu, dia pung maksud apa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Esau asked saying, &lt;&lt;That travelling-group of animals which you sent earlier, what's its purpose/meaning?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini, kaka! Beta parsén samua kasi sang kaka, ko biar kaka tarima sang beta deng hati luas.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yakob answered saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, older-sibling! I present/give all of it to older-sibling, so that older-sibling receives me favourably/receptively.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miy ləkha: what to you? are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miy ləkha: what to you? are they yours? pagashtiy: I ran into them, I met them along the way (not on purpose)<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>limtsoʾ-chen: to find favor, to make a good impression</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ma Esau balas bilang, &lt;&lt;Adi Yakob! Beta pung harta ju banya. Jadi lu sonde usa kasi apa-apa sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Esau responded saying, &lt;&lt;Younger-sibling Yakob! I also have many possessions. So you don't need to give me anything.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is Middle Eastern politeness. Esau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">This is Middle Eastern politeness. Esau isn't refusing the gift; heʾll take it eventually.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kaka jang bagitu! Kaka musti tarima, ko jadi tanda bilang, kaka tarima sang beta deng tangan tabuka. Te waktu beta lia kaka pung senyum tadi, tingka ke beta lia Tuhan Allah pung senyum.<bt>Then Yakob responded saying, &lt;&lt;Older-sibling shouldn't [think] like that! Older-sibling must accept [them], as a sign that older-sibling receives me wholeheartedly (Idiom &lt;with open hands). Cause, when I saw older-sibling's smile just now, it was like I saw Lord God's smile.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="deng tangan tabuka = dgn segenap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">deng tangan tabuka = dgn segenap hati</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tirtseniy (rtsh): you are pleased with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tirtseniy (rtsh): you are pleased with me</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Jadi beta minta deng hormat, ko biar kaka tarima beta pung hadia yang sonde ada pung arti ni. Te Tuhan Allah su talalu bae sang beta, andia ko Dia su kasi samua yang beta parlú.&gt;&gt; Yakob kokoe tarús sang dia, sampe mau tar mau, Esau tarima itu hadia dong.<bt>So (consequently) I ask respectfully, for older-sibling to receive this gift of mine which has no significance. Cause Lord God has been too good to me, and that is why He has given everything that I need.&gt;&gt; Yakob kept coazing him, to-point-that there was no other option, Esau accepted those gifts.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="birkhatiy: my blessing, my gift huvaʾt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">birkhatiy: my blessing, my gift huvaʾt (bwʾ hof): is brought<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>channaniy: he has acted graciously with me yiftsar bo: he entreated him<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>yiqqach (lqch qal): he took it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ais itu, Esau omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bagitu, na, bosong siap ko kotong jalan su! Nanti beta antar sang bosong.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Esau spoke saying, &lt;&lt;If that is the case, na, get yourselves ready, so we-inc can leave now! I will escort you-pl.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niSʿah (nSh): let's depart, be on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">niSʿah (nSh): let's depart, be on our way nelekhah: let's go<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>lənegdekha: in front of you, lead the way</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ma Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde usa, kaka! Kaka lia sandiri. Ana-ana dong masi kici-kici, deng sonde bisa jalan capát. Binatang yang baru barana dong, ju banya. Kalo kotong paksa sang dong jalan capát, dalam satu hari sa, nanti ini binatang dong bisa mati samua.<bt>But Yakob responded saying, &lt;&lt;That's not necessary, older sibling! Older-sibling can see for himself. The children are still small, and cannot walk quickly. And the animals which have just given birth, are also many. If we-inc force them to walk/travel quickly, in just one day, all these animals could die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yodeaʿ (ydʿ partcpl): you are the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yodeaʿ (ydʿ partcpl): you are the one who knows rakiym: tender (little children), not robust<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʿalowt (ʿwl partcpl): are nursing dafquwm (dpq): they drive them too hard<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Jadi lebe bae, kaka dong jalan lebe dolo sa. Nanti botong samua jalan palán-palán dari balakang. Nanti beta datang lia sang kaka di Seir.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be better if older-sibling just goes on ahead. Then we-exc all will travel slowly behind. I will later come and see older-sibling in Seir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾetnahəlah: I will proceed. ləʾiTTiy: in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾetnahəlah: I will proceed. ləʾiTTiy: in my gentleness<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>məlaʾkhah: the work, the pace at which</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais itu, Esau omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bagitu, na, beta kasi tenga beta pung ana bua saparu deng lu, ko dong tunju jalan kasi bosong.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Esau spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;If that is the case, I will leave behind some/half of my underlings with you, so they can show you the way.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Yakob bilang, &lt;&lt;Kaka sonde usa repot-repot! Yang pantíng, beta su tau kaka su tarima bae sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob said, &lt;&lt;Older-sibling doesn't need to trouble himself! What is important, is I know older-sibling has received/accepted me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾatstsiygah (ytsg hif): let me place"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾatstsiygah (ytsg hif): let me place some of my people. Jacob is actually refusing what Esau wants, but he is being very polite about it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Dengar bagitu, ju Esau jalan kasi tenga sang dong, ko pulang pi Seir.<bt>Hearing that, Esau went leaving them behind, to return-home to Seir.</bt><v n="17" />Ma dari situ, Yakob pi Sukot. Di situ, dia bangun ruma deng bekin kandang kasi dia pung binatang dong samua. Andia ko itu tampa, dong kasi nama <span class="Italic">Sukot</span> (yang pung arti &lt;ruma tahan&gt;).<bt>But from there, Yakob went to Sukot. There, he built a house, and made corrals for all his animals. That is why that place is named <span class="Italic">Sukot</span> (which means &lt;temporary house/s&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ahirnya, Yakob dong sampe deng salamat dari Padan Aram pi kampong Sikem di negrí Kana'an. Ais dong pasang tenda ko tenga deka-deka di itu kampong.<bt>Finally, Yakob (collective) arrived safely from Padan Aram at the village of Sikem in the country of Kanaan. And they fastened tents to stay near that village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichan (chnh): set up a temporary"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yichan (chnh): set up a temporary residence, probably tents.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Itu tana yang Yakob pasang tenda tu, dia béli putus dari Hemor, Sikem pung bapa. Dia bayar deng 100 doi perak.<bt>That land in which Yakob fastened his tent, he bought-in-full from Hemor, Sikem's father. He paid with 100 silver moneys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqen (qnh): he bought chelqat: field"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqen (qnh): he bought chelqat: field (not the usual word); plot of land<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>naTah: he spread out his tent. Probably he camped there for a while, then bought the field he was in. As a nomad, he probably would not have invested money in land unless he was sure he wanted to stay there. qəshiyTah: an old weight, here referring to an amount of money<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Di situ, dia susun batu ko bekin meja korban. Ais dia kasi nama itu tampa <span class="Italic">El-Elohe-Isra'el</span> yang dia pung arti &lt;Allah tu, Isra'el pung Allah&gt;.<bt>There, he layered-piled rocks to make a sacrifice table. And he named that place <span class="Italic">El-Elohe-Israel</span> which means &lt;Allah, is Israel's Allah&gt;.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatstsev (ntsb hif): he set up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yatstsev (ntsb hif): he set up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sikem parkosa sang Yakob pung ana parampuan Dina<bt>Sikem rapes Yakob's daughter Dina</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="34" />
      <v n="1" />Satu kali, Yakob deng Lea pung ana parampuan, Dina, pi bakunjung sang nona-nona dari itu negrí.<bt>One time, Yakob and Lea's daughter, Dina, went to visit the young-women of that country/village/political unit.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lirʾot: to go see"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lirʾot: to go see</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Itu negrí pung raja, nama Hemor, dari suku Hewi. Dia pung ana laki-laki, nama Sikem. Satu kali, Sikem dapa lia sang Dina, ju bawa lari sang dia, ais parkosa sang dia.<bt>That country's raja, was named Hemor, from the tribe of Hewi. His son was named Sikem. One time, Siken saw Dina, and ran off with her, and raped her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parkosa = maen paksa ; gigi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">parkosa = maen paksa ; gigi asam = suka sakali</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nasiʾ haʾarets: the chief, minor king,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nasiʾ haʾarets: the chief, minor king, of that land (like some of the aliʾi before Kamehameha who ruled over a fairly small place) yishkav ʾotah: he slept with her<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yəʿaneah: he humiliated her, raped her</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Sikem jato hati sang Dina deng cinta mau mati sang dia. Jadi Sikem omong manis-manis deng Dina, ko biar Dina ju balas dia pung cinta.<bt>Sikem fell in love with Dina (lit: fell liver to), and loved her excessively. So (consequently) Sikem spoke sweetly with Dina, so that Dina might respond to his love.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatidbaq nafsho b-: his soul clung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vatidbaq nafsho b-: his soul clung to her; he became attached to her hanaʿara: the young marriageable girl<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vaydaber ʿal-lev hanaʿara: he tried to persuade the girl graciously</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ais Sikem kasi tau dia pung bapa bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! Tolong pi maso minta sang Dina, ko beta bisa kawin deng dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Sikem told his father saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Please go enter request Dina, so I can marry her.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Yakob dapa dengar ada orang su parkosa dia pung ana parampuan, ma dia diam-diam sa, deng sonde bekin apa-apa. Te itu waktu, dia pung ana laki-laki dong ada jaga binatang di padang. Jadi dia tunggu sampe dong pulang samua.<bt>Yakob heard that someone had raped his daughter, but he was just quiet about it, adn didn't do anything. Cause at that time, his sons were watching animals in the fields. So (consequently) he waited for all of them to return-home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="timeʾ (piʿel): dishonor, ravish, profane, defile,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">timeʾ (piʿel): dishonor, ravish, profane, defile, make unclean hechərish (hif): he kept still, was silent, didnʾt raise an objection<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Itu waktu, Sikem pung bapa Hemor datang sang Yakob ko mau maso minta sang Dina.<bt>At that time, Sikem's father Hemor, came to Yakob, to betelnut Dina (=as elder request her for wife for child).</bt><v n="7" />Pas dong dua ada ba'omong, Yakob pung ana-ana dong pulang dari padang. Waktu dong dengar bilang, Sikem su parkosa dong pung adi parampuan, ju dong saki hati, deng mara mau mati. Ais dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Hal macam bagitu, sonde pantas ada di Isra'el. Jadi kotong sonde bole tarima orang bekin jahat macam bagitu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Just when the two of them were RECIP-speaking, Yakob's children returned-home from the fields. When they heard that Sikem had raped their younger-sister, they were angry/upset, and extremely angry. So they said, &lt;&lt;A matter of that type is not appropriate to occur in Israel. So (consequently) we-inc must not accept someone doing evil of that sort.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitʿatstsəvu (hitp): they were outraged, felt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yitʿatstsəvu (hitp): they were outraged, felt grieved yichar: he became angry<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>nvalah ʿasah: an intolerable outrage had occurred, a grave sin, sacrilege, offense lishkav<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yeʿaseh (nif): such as is simply not done</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ju Hemor kokoe sang Yakob dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Sodara Yakob! Beta pung ana Sikem su jato cinta batúl-batúl sang sodara pung ana parampuan. Jadi beta minta ko kasi isin beta pung ana kawin deng dia.<bt>And Hemor was coaxing Yakob (coll) saying, &lt;&lt;Brother Yakob! My child Sikem has truly fallen in love with brother's daughter. So (consequently) I ask the you give permission for my child to marry her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chashqah: his soul experiences affection, love,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chashqah: his soul experiences affection, love, desire vitchem: your daughter; daughter and sister<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>tənu: please give</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Kalo bisa, na, kotong pung ana-ana dong ba'ame. Bosong pung ana laki-laki kawin deng botong pung ana parampuan. Deng botong pung ana laki-laki kawin deng bosong pung ana parampuan.<bt>If possible, na, we-inc children should RECIP-take (=marry each other). Your-pl sons should marry our daughters. And our sons, should marry your daughters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ba'ame = saling mengambil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ba'ame = saling mengambil</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hitchatnu (hitp): let's enter into relationships"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hitchatnu (hitp): let's enter into relationships by marriage</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Biar bosong tenga bacampor deng botong di sini. Bosong bebas pili mau tenga di mana sa. Ais badagang, deng dapa harta di sini.&gt;&gt;<bt>And you should live mixed with us here. You-pl are free to choose wherever you want to stay. And RECIP-commerce, and gain belongings here.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shvu (yshb): settle Səcharuah (imperv): travel|i(10)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shvu (yshb): settle Səcharuah (imperv): travel<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>heʾachəzu (inf impv): be settled in the land</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11-12" />Ais itu, Sikem omong deng Dina pung bapa, deng dia pung kaka dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong mau minta apa sa, beta iko. Bosong mau minta dia pung doi tutu malu, deng dia pung belis barapa sa, beta bayar. Asal bosong kasi isin ko beta kawin deng bosong pung adi parampuan.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Sikem spoke with Dina's father, and her older-siblings saying, &lt;&lt;Whatever you want to ask, I will go along with it. If you ask for the money covering shame (=fine for rape or premarital sex), and whatever amount for the bridewealth, I will pay. As long as you give permission for me to marry your younger sister.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doi tutu malu = denda perkosaan,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">doi tutu malu = denda perkosaan, denda premarital sex</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾemtsaʾ-chen baʿenekhem: If I have found"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾemtsaʾ-chen baʿenekhem: If I have found favor in your sight harbu (rbh hif imperv): make it great<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mohar: bride price matan: gift<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ma Yakob pung ana-ana dong su tau bilang, Sikem su parkosa dong pung adi Dina. Jadi dong manyao putar-balek sang Sikem deng dia pung bapa Hemor.<bt>But Yakob's children already knew that Sikem had raped their younger sister Dina. So (consequently) they responded deceptively to Sikem and his father Hemor.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="consider /putar-balek/ &gt; /jabák ko hiki/"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">consider /putar-balek/ &gt; /jabák ko hiki/</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="go make dea sista Dinah come"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">go make dea sista Dinah come pilau [kine]. mirmah: deceit, fraud<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʾasher: usually a relative clause introducer, but here it gives the cause Timmeʾ (piʿel): he caused to become ceremonially unclean<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ais dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong sonde bisa kasi kawin botong pung adi deng orang yang sonde sunat! Itu bekin malu sang botong!<bt>And they reponded saying, &lt;&lt;We cannot allow our younger sister to marry someone who hasn't been circumcised! That is shameful to us!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nuwkhal (ykl qal): we cannot ʿarlah:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nuwkhal (ykl qal): we cannot ʿarlah: foreskin<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>cherpah: disgrace</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ma dia pung jalan kaluar, bagini: bosong laki-laki samua, kici-bésar, musti sunat sama ke botong.<bt>But there is a way out, like this: All of you-pl males, small-large, must be circumcised like we are.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾakh: only neʾot (ʾwt nif): agree,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾakh: only neʾot (ʾwt nif): agree, consent<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>himmol (mwl nif inf): become circumcised zakhar: male<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Kalo bosong bekin bagitu, baru botong bisa ba'ame. Deng botong ju bisa tenga sama-sama deng bosong di sini, ko kotong bisa jadi satu bangsa.<bt>If you do that, only-then will we be able to RECIP-take (=marry each other). And we-exc can then also live together with you-pl here, to we could/can become one race/people.</bt><v n="17" />Ma kalo bosong sonde iko botong pung mau, deng sonde mau sunat, nanti botong ame pulang botong pung adi, ais botong bangun jalan dari sini.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if you do not follow our desire, and don't want to get circumcised, then we will take home our younger-sibling, and we will leave this place.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hemor deng Sikem tarima bae dong pung omong.<bt>Hemor and Sikem agreed with what they said.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiyTvu (yTb): it was okay with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiyTvu (yTb): it was okay with them</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ma Sikem su sonde sabar lai, tagal dia su cinta mati sang Dina. Naa, samua orang di itu negrí hormat sang Sikem.<bt>But Sikem could not be patient anymore, because he was desparately in love with Dina. Naa, [+shift] everyone in that country respected/honoured Sikem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cuz he tink Jacob daughta real"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">cuz he tink Jacob daughta real nice peopo get mo plenny respeck fo him den fo da odda Hamor ohana guys.<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ʾechar (piʿel): didnʾt stay, retard, wait around chafets: took pleasure in<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nikhbad (nif partcpl): was the most honored one</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Jadi Hemor deng Sikem pi di tampa urus parkara di kampong pung pintu maso, ais dong barunding deng samua orang di itu negrí. Dong omong bilang,<bt>So Hemor and Sikem went to the place of settling disputes at the village's gate, and they discussed with all the people of that country. They spoke saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʿar: gate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shaʿar: gate</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />&lt;&lt;Sodara dong samua! Ini orang Isra'el dong suka idop dame deng kotong. Jadi biar ko dong tenga sama-sama deng kotong di ini negrí. Ini negrí cukup luas buat kotong samua. Kotong bisa ba'ame deng dong pung ana nona. Dong ju bisa bakawin deng kotong pung ana nona dong.<bt>&lt;&lt;All you brothers! These people of Israel like to live in peace with us-inc. So let's let them live together with us in this country. This country is wide enough for all of us. We can RECIP-take their young-women. They also can marry our young-women.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shlemim: peaceable, in a relation of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shlemim: peaceable, in a relation of peace yischaru: wander, pass through the land<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>rachavat-yadayim: is broad on every side [dual]</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Dong cuma minta satu hal kici sa, dari kotong. Andia, kotong laki-laki samua musti sunat sama ke dong.<bt>They only ask just one small matter from us. That is, all of us males must be circumcised just like them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʾotu (ʾwt nif): they will consent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʾotu (ʾwt nif): they will consent nimmoliym (mwl nif partcpl): who are circumcised<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Kalo kotong su idop bagabung, nanti dong pung binatang deng harta samua ju jadi kotong pung pusaka, aa? Jadi lebe bae kotong tarima dong pung mau. Mari ko kotong samua sunat sama-sama! Satuju, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>If/when we are living conjoined, then their animals and all their belongings will also become our inheritance/belongings, right? So (consequently) it would be good if we accept their desire/request. Come, let's all get circumcised together! Agreed, right?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qinyanam: their possession neʾotah (ʾwt nif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qinyanam: their possession neʾotah (ʾwt nif): let's consent<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ais samua orang yang bakumpul di situ, satuju deng Hemor deng Sikem pung omong. Ju samua laki-laki di itu negrí dong sunat rame-rame.<bt>So all the people who were gathered there agreed with what Hemor and Sikem had to say. So all the males in that country got circumcised festively-together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotsʾey (ytsʾ partcpl pl): all the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yotsʾey (ytsʾ partcpl pl): all the ones going out the city gate. This is a military term for all the able-bodied men. yimmolu (mwl nif): got circumcised. Circumcision was done by somebody else, not by the person being circumcised<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Dia pung hari katiga, waktu samua yang kaná sunat dong pung luka masi saki, ju Dina pung kaka, Simeon deng Lewi, hela ame dong pung kalewang, ais dong maso diam-diam pi dalam kampong. Ju dong bunu itu laki-laki dong samua.<bt>On the third day, when all who had gotten circumcised's wounds were still sore, then Dina's older-siblings, Simeon and Lewi, drew their fighting-swords, and went quietly into the village. And they kille all those males.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="***city changed to village, Amarasi check"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">***city changed to village, Amarasi check Oct. 2005</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bihyotam (hyh inf): of their being,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bihyotam (hyh inf): of their being, when they were koʾavim: in pain from wound fever<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>beTach: securely, in security, unawares, without warning</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Hemor deng Sikem ju kaná bunu. Tarús dong ame bawa sang Dina kaluar dari Sikem pung ruma, ko dong pulang.<bt>Hemor and Sikem were also killed. Then they took Dina out of Sikem's house, and they went home.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ais itu, Yakob pung ana laen dong maso pi dalam itu negrí, ko dong rampok itu negrí pung isi. Dong mara, tagal orang su parkosa dong pung adi parampuan di situ.<bt>After that, Yakob's other children went into the city/country, and they robbed everything in that country. They were angry, because a person had raped their younger-sister there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəlaliym: the slain, the pierced yavozzu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chəlaliym: the slain, the pierced yavozzu (bzz): they plundered<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>Timmʾu: render unclean, defile, rape</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Dong rampas orang pung barang samua dari dalam ruma, deng dong foo bawa orang pung binatang samua dari padang.<bt>They robbed/looted all of people's things from inside the houses, and they herded away all of the people's animals from the fields.</bt><v n="29" />Dong ame bawa samua parampuan, deng ana-ana, deng rampas itu negrí pung barang mahal dong samua.<bt>They took away all the women, and children, and robbed all of that country/political unit's expensive things.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kol-cheylam: all their wealth tappam: those"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kol-cheylam: all their wealth tappam: those of a wandering tribe who are hardly fit to march, the weak ones, including children and elderly<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>shavu (shbh): they took them captive</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Waktu Yakob dapa tau itu hal, dia omong deng Simeon deng Lewi bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong su bekin karjá bodo apa ni? Bekin susa sang beta sa! Nanti orang Kana'an, orang Peris, deng samua orang di ini da'era, binci mati sang kotong. Dong pung orang banya. Ma kotong pung orang cuma sadiki sa. Kalo dong sarbú datang, na, kotong ancor memang, suda ma.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yakob found out about that matter, he spoke with Simeon and Lewi saying, &lt;&lt;What is this stupid work that you have done? Just causing difficulty for me! Later those people of Kanaan, the people of Peris, and all the people in this region, will hate us to an extreme. They have many people. But we have only a few people. If they come attacking, na, we will be destroyed immediately.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿakhartem: you have made me taboo,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿakhartem: you have made me taboo, cut me off from social life lhavʾisheni (bʾsh hif): you have made me become odious, stinking<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>mətey: men miSpar: count, number<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>neʾesfu ʿalay (ʾsf nif): be gathered, unite against me, conspire against me hikuni (nkh hif): strike me, hit me in battle, strike me down<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>nishmadti (shmd nif): I will be destroyed, exterminated</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ma dong manyao deng mara bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! Bapa kira botong mau kasi biar dong bekin botong pung adi jadi parampuan nakal, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>But they responded angrily saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Father thinks that we should just let it be what they have done to make our younger-sibling into a whore/prostitute!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parampuan jalang/ lonte/ palacor / nakal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">parampuan jalang/ lonte/ palacor / nakal</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zonah: prostitute, common whore End of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">zonah: prostitute, common whore End of P section.<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob dong lari pi Betel<bt>Yakob (collective) flees to Betel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="35" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, ju Tuhan Allah omong deng Yakob bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, Allah yang su kasi tunju diri sang lu, waktu lu lari dari lu pung kaka Esau. Sakarang lu pinda suda pi Betel. Sampe di situ, lu kasi bangun meja korban kasi Beta. Ais lu tenga di situ suda.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Lord God spoke with Yakob saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am Allah who has revealed Myself to you, when you ran from your older-sibling Esau. Now you must move to Betel. When you arrive there, you must build a sacrifice table to Me. Then you will live there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shev (yshb imperv): live hannirʾeh (rʾh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shev (yshb imperv): live hannirʾeh (rʾh partcpl): who allowed himself to be seen<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>barchəkha (inf): on your fleeing</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Ais itu, Yakob omong deng dia pung isi ruma dong samua bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang kotong samua mau barangkat pi Betel. Dolu waktu beta dalam susa, Tuhan Allah tolong sang beta di situ. Beta mau kasi badiri meja korban di situ. Jadi sakarang bosong angka buang bosong pung patong songgo samua. Bekin barisi bosong pung diri, deng ganti pakean, te kotong mau sémba sang Tuhan.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yakob spoke with all his family/household saying, &lt;&lt;Now we are going to leave for Betel. Formerly when I was in difficulty, Lord God helped me there. I want to erect a sacrifice table there. So (consequently) now you-pl need to throw away all your worship statues. Make yourselves clean/pure/holy, and change your clothes, cause we are going to worship the Lord.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haSiru (Swr hif): they are to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haSiru (Swr hif): they are to get rid of nekhar: foreign land<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>btukhkhem (twkh): in your midst hiTTaharu (hitp): purify yourselves cultically, get into the proper condition for worshipping God [Catholics today have special rituals to prepare themselves for Holy Communion - many religions do something like that]<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>hachalifu (hif): change your clothes simloteykhem: your clothes<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>haʿoneh (partcpl): the one who answered me, gave me a favorable hearing tsaratiy (tsarah): my distress<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Tarús dong sarakan dong pung patong songgo deng dong pung anteng-anteng<bt>Then they turned-over all their worship statues and their earrings.</bt><note reference="35:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tempo dolu, di dong pung anteng-anteng saparu ada gambar dong pung sosonggo.<bt>Long ago, on the earrings there were pictures of their objects-of-traditional-worship.</bt></note>samua. Ais Yakob kubur itu barang dong samua di bawa pohon bésar satu deka kampong Sikem.<bt>Then Yakob buried all those things under a large tree near the village of Sikem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="byadam: in their hands, in their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">byadam: in their hands, in their possession (not necessarily "in their house") nzamim: earrings<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>bʾaznehem: in their ears vayitmon: he hid<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʾelah: mighty tree, often with cultic significance</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Waktu Yakob pung rombongan dong barangkat dari Sikem, Tuhan Allah kirim rasa taku kasi orang-orang di negrí kuliling dong, sampe dong sonde barani bekin jahat sang Yakob dong.<bt>When Yakob's travelling-group left Sikem, Lord God sent a feeling of fear to the various people in the surrounding countries/villages, to-point-that they didn't have the courage to do anything bad to Yakob (collective).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSSaʿu (nSʿ): pull up tent stakes,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiSSaʿu (nSʿ): pull up tent stakes, break camp, start out, march on chitat ʾelohim: terror of God<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>Savivotehem: located around them loʾ radfu ʾacharey: and they did not pursue after, set off after someone to catch up with him with hostile intent<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju Yakob deng dia pung rombongan samua, sampe deng salamat di Betel (yang dolu, nama <span class="Italic">Lus),</span> di tana Kana'an.<bt>So Yakob and all of his travelling-group, arrived in safety at Betel (Which formerly was named <span class="Italic">Lus</span>), in the land of Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiwʾ (3sg fem pron agreeing with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hiwʾ (3sg fem pron agreeing with ʾarets): which was? in the same land, Canaan?</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Di situ Yakob kasi bangun meja korban dari batu. Ais dia kasi nama itu tampa, <span class="Italic">El Betel,</span> (yang pung arti &lt;Betel pung Allah&gt;), tagal dolu Tuhan Allah kasi tunju Dia pung diri sang Yakob di situ, waktu dia lari dari dia pung kaka.<bt>There, Yakob built a sacrifice table from stone. Then he named that place, <span class="Italic">El Betel,</span> (which means &lt;Betel's Allah&gt;), because formerly Lord God had revealed Himself to Yakob there, when he ran from his older-sibling.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niglu (glh nif): uncovered himself, let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">niglu (glh nif): uncovered himself, let himself be seen</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Deka deng kampong Betel, ada satu pohon bésar yang orang kasi nama <span class="Italic">Alon Bakut</span>. Dia pung arti &lt;pohon makarereu&gt;. Dia dapa itu nama, tagal waktu Ribka pung mama koko, nama Debora, mati, dong kubur sang dia di bawa itu pohon.<bt>Near the village of Betel, there is a large tree which people named <span class="Italic">Alon Bakut,</span> which means &lt;tree of mourning&gt;. It got that name, because when Ribka's nanny, named Debora, died, they buried her underneath that tree.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mama koko = nanny ; makarareu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">mama koko = nanny ; makarareu (preferred) ~ makareu ~ makarareuk ~ makarereu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meyneqet (ynq hif ptcpl): the one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">meyneqet (ynq hif ptcpl): the one who had nursed Rebecca when Rebecca was a baby (rich mothers hired somebody else to do the nursing) tiqqaver (piʿel): she was buried<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Waktu Yakob su kambali dari Padan Aram, Tuhan Allah kasi tunju diri lai, deng kasi berkat sang dia.<bt>When Yakob had returned from Padan Aram, Lord God revealed Himself again, and gave blessing to him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boʾow (inf): at his coming yvarekh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">boʾow (inf): at his coming yvarekh (piʿel): bestow power for success, prosperity, fertility<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Tuhan omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Mulai sakarang, lu pung nama, bukan Yakob lai. Ma Beta kasi lu nama baru, andia, <span class="Italic">Isra'el.</span><bt>The Lord spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Beginning now, your name is no longer Yakob. But I give you a new name, that is, Israel.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqareʾ (nif): will not be called"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqqareʾ (nif): will not be called</Message></Annotation><note reference="35:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Isra'el pung arti &lt;dia bagulat deng Tuhan&gt;.<bt>Israel means 'he struggles/wrestled with the Lord'.</bt></note><v n="11" />Beta ni, Tuhan Allah yang Paling Kuasa. Jadi lu barana-cucu bam-banya suda! Nanti bangsa-bangsa dong kaluar datang dari lu pung turunan. Deng lu nanti barana ame raja-raja dong.<bt>I am Lord God who is Most Powerful/Authority. So (consequently) [I want you to] have lots of children, and grandchildren! Later various races/peoples will come out from your descendants. And you will give birth to various rajas.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shadday: another name of the deity,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shadday: another name of the deity, English translations use "God Almighty." pəreh (imperv): be fruitful<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>rəveh (rbh imperv): become many [repetition of same idea doesn't sound good here SK] qəhal goyim: assembly of peoples<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>mechalatseykha (chalatsayim): from your loins (rib to hip), from your body = by natural descent yeteseʾu: they will come out<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Negrí yang Beta su kasi sang lu pung ba'i Abraham deng bapa Isak tu, sakarang Beta kasi sang lu deng lu pung turunan dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>The country which I have given to your grandfather Abraham and father Isak, now I give to you, and your descendants.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="natatiy: gave (but they didnʾt take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">natatiy: gave (but they didnʾt take possession)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\Hk00221c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-14" />Tuhan Allah omong abis bagitu, ju Yakob kasi badiri satu tiang batu di situ, ko biar jadi tanda yang kasi inga Tuhan pung janji. Tarús dia po'a aer anggor deng minya di atas itu batu, ko sémba sang Tuhan.<bt>When Lord God finished speaking, Yakob erected a stone pillar there, to be a sign remembering the Lord's promise. Then he poured grape juice/wine, and oil on top of that stone, to worship the Lord.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lingga (BI) = tiang batu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lingga (BI) = tiang batu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaʿal (ʿlh): he went up yatstsev"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaʿal (ʿlh): he went up yatstsev (ntsb hif): he set up<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>matstsevah: standing stone, an unhewn, upright stone for cult (here), burial-marking (Rachel, v. 20), or memorial purposes (deal with Laban) yaSSekh (nSk hif): pour a drink offering, libation<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>neSekh: drink offering, libation yitsoq (ytsq): pour (in general)<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Itu tampa, dia kasi nama <span class="Italic">Betel.</span><bt>That place, he named &lt;Betel&gt;.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob pung bini Rahel mati barana<bt>Yakob's wife Rahel dies in childbirth</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais itu, Yakob dong jalan kasi tenga Betel. Waktu dong masi sadiki jao dari Efrata (andia Betlehem), Rahel pung waktu barana su sampe. Ma dia barana susa.<bt>After that, Yakob (collective) left Betel. When they were still a little far from Efrata (that is Betlehem), Rahel's time to give birth arrived. But she gave birth with difficulty.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSʿu (nSʿ): they departed ʿowd: still|i(16)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiSʿu (nSʿ): they departed ʿowd: still<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>kivrat-haʾaretz: a certain distance on the ground teled: she gave birth [where does the information that she was pregnant go?]<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>təqash (qshh piʿel): have hard labor, severe pains in childbirth</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Waktu dia masi muku satenga mati, ju dukun barana kasi tau sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Mama Rahel! Bekin kuat hati, te mama dapa ana laki-laki lai!&gt;&gt;<bt>When she was still having hard contractions, the midwife told her saying, &lt;&lt;Mother Rahel! encourage yourself, cause mother has gotten another son!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ari-ari = placenta; muku = labour"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ari-ari = placenta; muku = labour contractions ; satenga ~ stenga ; dukun barana = bidan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haqshotah (qshh hif inf): in her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haqshotah (qshh hif inf): in her difficult labor məyalledet: midwife<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Waktu Rahel su mau putus napas, ju dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Ben-Oni,</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;ana dari beta pung sangsara&gt;). Ais itu, dia mati. Ma Yakob kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Benyamin,</span> (yang dia pung arti &lt;ana tangan kanan&gt;).<bt>When Rahel was about to take her last breath, she name that child, Ben-Oni, (which means &lt;child of difficulty2&gt;). After that, she died. But Yakob name that child, Benyamin, (which means &lt;right hand child/dependable child/right-handed child&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="btseʾt nefshah (ytsʾ inf): as her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">btseʾt nefshah (ytsʾ inf): as her soul was coming out, as her life was ebbing away ben-ʾoni: child of mourning, lamentation for the dead; Son of My Grief<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>binyamin: child of the right side, place of honor for someone particularly valued, oath, south side (on the right when facing east); Son of Good Luck, Son of the South (where they were headed)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ais ju dong kubur sang Rahel di pinggir jalan yang mau pi Efrata, (yang sakarang, dia pung nama Betlehem).<bt>Then they buried Rahel at the edge of the road going to Efrata, (which now is named Betlehem).</bt><v n="20" />Ju Yakob kasi badiri satu batu kubur di situ. Sampe ini hari ju, Rahel pung batu kubur tu, masi ada.<bt>And Yakob erected a grave stone there. to this day, Rahel's grave stone is still there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="batu nisan (BI) = batu kubur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">batu nisan (BI) = batu kubur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mattsevah: memorial pillar ʿal- is usually"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mattsevah: memorial pillar ʿal- is usually looking down on, or looking across at. English renderings of "tomb" are strange for cave burial, and unlikely for a dug gruva; Rachel's Tomb of today is a later structure as far as I can find out.<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] was this a cave or was she buried underground? ; [JEG] No clues. Rachel's Tomb is still there. IV: Jacob's continuing love for her is evidenced by the memorial pillar (maccEb) he set up over her grave, and its location was still known in Saul's day, when it was described as being on the border of Benjamin at celcah (*Zelzah, 1 Sa. 10:2). The site is unknown today, though Je. 31:15 (cf. Mt. 2:18) suggests it may have been near Ramah, c. 8 km N of Jerusalem. However, Rachel's memory was also preserved at Bethlehem in the time of Ruth (Ru. 4:11), probably because it was near Rachel's burial place.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob pung ana-ana dong<bt>Yakob's children</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais itu, ju Yakob<bt>After that, Yakob</bt><note reference="35:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tulisan bahasa Ibrani di ini ayat tulis bilang, &lt;Isra'el&gt;. Isra'el deng Yakob tu, dua nama kasi satu orang.<bt>Ibrani language writings say ‘Isra'el’ here. Israel and Yakob, are two names for the same person.</bt></note>bapinda-pinda tarús. Satu kali, dia pasang tenda di manara Eder pung sablá.<bt>kept moving continually. One time, he fastened his tent on the other side of the Eder tower.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiSSaʿ (nSʿ): pull up stakes, move"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiSSaʿ (nSʿ): pull up stakes, move vayeT ʾhlh (nTh, qetiv ʾahaloh): pitch his tent<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>mehalʾah: beyond</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Waktu dong ada di situ, Ruben tidor deng dia pung bapa pung bini piara, Bilha. Yakob dapa tau itu hal.<bt>When they were there, Ruben slept with his father's kept wife, Bilha. Yakob found out about that matter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section, in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">End of P section, in the middle of the verse. bishkon (shkn ptcpl): during the time he was living there<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yakob pung ana laki-laki ada dua blas orang.<bt>Yakob's sons were 12 people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="23" />Lea pung ana-ana, andia: Ruben (Yakob pung ana sulung), Simeon, Lewi, Yahuda, Isaskar, deng Sebulon.<bt>Lea's children were: Ruben (Yakob's oldest child), Simeon, Lewi, Yahuda, Isaskar, and Sebulon.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24" />Rahel pung ana-ana, andia: Yusuf deng Benyamin.<bt>Rahel's children were: Yusuf and Benyamin.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25" />Rahel pung hamba Bilha pung ana-ana, andia: Dan deng Naftali.<bt>Rahel's servant Bilha's children were: Dan and Naftali.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="26" />Ais Lea pung hamba Silpa pung ana-ana, andia: Gad deng Aser.<bt>And Lea's servant Silpa's children were: Gad and Aser.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Barana ame itu ana-ana dong di Padan Aram.<bt>Those children were born in Padan Aram.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob pung bapa Isak mati<bt>Yakob's father Isak dies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ais itu, Yakob pi lia dia pung bapa Isak di Mamre deka kampong Kiryat-Arba (andia sakarang, nama Hebron). Dolu dia pung ba'i Abraham ju tenga di situ.<bt>After that, Yakob went to see his father Isak at Mamre near the village of Kiryat-Arba (which is now, named Hebron). Formerly his grandfather Abraham had also lived there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gar (gwr): he lived as an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gar (gwr): he lived as an alien</Message></Annotation><v n="28-29" />Isak idop sampe dia pung umur 180 taon, baru dia mati. Tarús dia pung ana Esau deng Yakob kubur sang dia.<bt>Isak lived until he was 180 years old, and then he died. And his children Esau and Yakob buried him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yigwaʿ: breathed his last, expired yeʾaSef"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yigwaʿ: breathed his last, expired yeʾaSef (nif impf): was united with his people, his family = die<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>səvaʿ: sated, satisfied End of P section.<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>exchange w/consultant: [MC] cave or underground? [JEG] Probably cave, since he was living close to it and the family already owned it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Esau pung turunan dong<bt>Esau's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="36" />
      <v n="1" />Ini Esau pung turunan dong. Dia pung nama laen, ju Edom.<bt>These are Esau's descendants. His other name was Edom.</bt><v n="2" />Esau kawin deng dua nona Kana'an. Yang satu, orang Het, andia Elon pung ana parampuan, nama Ada. Yang kadua, orang Hewi, nama Oholibama. Dia pung bapa, nama Anah, deng dia pung ba'i, nama Sibeon.<bt>Esau married two young-women of Kanaan. The one was a person of Het, that is Elon's daughter, named Ada. The second, was a person of Hewi, named Oholibama. Her father was named Anah, and her grandfather, was named Sibeon.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bat: The Samaritan Torah has &quot;Anah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bat: The Samaritan Torah has "Anah was Zibeon da Hor guy boy", which agrees better with verses 20 and 21</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Esau ju kawin deng Ismael pung ana parampuan, nama Basmat. Basmat pung kaka laki-laki, nama Nebayot.<bt>Esau also married Ismael's daughter, named Basmat. Basmat's older brother was named Nebayot.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Esau pung bini tua, Ada, barana sang Elifas. Basmat barana sang Rehuel.<bt>Esau's first wife (&lt;old wife), Ada, gave birth to Elifas. Basmat gave birth to Rehuel.</bt><v n="5" />Ais Oholibama barana sang Yeus, Yalam deng Kora. Barana sang Esau pung ana dong samua di negrí Kana'an.<bt>And Oholibama gave birth to Yeus, Yalam and Kora. All of the children of Esau were born in the country of Kanaan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Satu kali, Esau pinda pi satu negrí laen, jao dari Yakob. Dia bawa dia pung bini-ana, orang karjá, binatang, deng dia pung harta dong samua.<bt>One time, Esau moved to a different country, far from Yakob. He took all his wives-children, his workers, his various animals, and his belongings.</bt><v n="7" />Esau bapisa deng Yakob, tagal dong pung binatang deng harta dong talalu banya. Jadi dong idop basesak di itu negrí.<bt>Esau separated from Yakob, because their animals and belongings were too many. So they were living crowded in that country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yachdaw: together, in the same place"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yachdaw: together, in the same place laseʾt: carry, support<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ju Esau (andia Edom), pi tenga di da'era bagunung di Seir.<bt>And Esau (that is Edom), went and lived in the mountainous region of Seir.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ini Esau pung turunan, yang dong bilang &lt;orang Edom&gt;. Dong tenga di da'era bagunung di Seir.<bt>These are Esau's descendants who they call &lt;Edom people&gt;. They live(d) in the mountainous region of Seir.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="10-13" />Esau pung bini Ada, barana satu ana laki-laki, nama Elifas. Elifas pung ana laki-laki ada lima orang. Andia, Teman, Omar, Sefo, Gatam deng Kenas. Elifas pung bini piara, nama Timna. Dia barana satu ana laki-laki, nama Amalek.<bt>Esau's wife Ada, gave birth to a son named Elifas. Elifas had five sons. They were, Teman, Omar, Sefo, Gatam and Kenas. Elifas' kept wife/mistress was named Timna. She gave birth to a son named Amalek.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">Esau pung bini Basmat, barana satu ana laki-laki, nama Rehuel. Rehuel dapa ana laki-laki ampa. Andia Nahat, Sera, Syama, deng Misa.<bt>Esau's wife Basmat, gave birth to a son, named Rehuel. Rehuel had four sons. They were, Nahat, Sera, Syama, and Misa.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="14" />Esau pung bini Oholibama, andia Anah pung ana, yang Sibeon pung cucu tu, barana ana laki-laki tiga. Andia Yeus, Yalam, deng Kora.<bt>Esau's wife Oholibama, that is Anah's child, who is Sibeon's grandchild, gave birth to three sons. They were, Yeus, Yalam, and Kora.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bat: daughter? Anah is the daughter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bat: daughter? Anah is the daughter of Zibeon in the Hebrew and his son in the Samaritan Torah and in verses 20 and 21</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="15-16" />Esau pung ana-cucu dong tapica-pica jadi banya suku. Satu-satu deng dong pung kapala suku. Esau pung ana sulung Elifas pung ana dong, jadi kapala suku Teman, kapala suku Omar, kapala suku Sefo, kapala suku Kenas, kapala suku Kora, kapala suku Gatam, deng kapala suku Amalek. Dong samua tu, Esau deng dia pung bini Ada pung turunan.<bt>Esau's children-grandchildren were broken up into many tribes/clans. Each had their own clan head. Esau's oldest child Elifas' children became the clan heads of the tribe of Teman, the clan head of Omar, the clan head of Sefo, the clan head of Kenas, the clan head of Kora, the clan head of Gatam, and the clan head of Amalek. All of them, are Esau and his wife Ada's descendants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾalufim: tribal chiefs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾalufim: tribal chiefs</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="17" />Esau pung ana Rehuel pung ana dong, jadi kapala suku Nahat, kapala suku Sera, kapala suku Syama, deng kapala suku Misa. Dong samua tu, Esau deng dia pung bini Basmat pung turunan.<bt>Esau's child Rehuel, children became the clan head of nahat, the clan head of Sera, the clan head of Syama, and the clan head of Misa. All of them, were Esau and his wife Basmat's descendants.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="18" />Esau deng dia pung bini Oholibama pung ana dong, jadi kapala suku Yeus, kapala suku Yalam, deng kapala suku Kora.<bt>Esau and his wife Oholibama's children became the clan head of Yeus, the clan head of Yalam, and the clan head of Kora.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Itu suku dong samua, Esau pung turunan.<bt>All those clans/tribes, were Esau's descendants.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Seir pung turunan<bt>Seir's descendants</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Di itu tampa, ju ada orang Hori satu, nama Seir. Dia pung ana-ana dong tapica-pica jadi banya suku. Satu-satu deng dong pung kapala suku. Ais dia pung ana jadi kapala suku Lotan, kapala suku Sobal, kapala suku Sibeon, kapala suku Anah, kapala suku Dison, kapala suku Eser, deng kapala suku Disan.<bt>In that place, there was also a Hori person, named Seir. His children were broken up into many tribes/clans. Each of them had their own clan head. So his children became the clan head of Lotan, the clan head of Sobal, the clan head of Sibeon, the clan head of Anah, the clan head of Dison, the clan head of Eser, and the clan head of Disan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="22" />Lotan pung ana, andia Hori deng Heman. (Lotan pung sodara parampuan, Timna).<bt>Lotan's children were, Hori, and Heman. (Lotan's sister was Timna).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="23" />Sobal pung ana-ana, andia Alwan, Manahat, Ebal, Sefo, deng Onam.<bt>Sobal's children were, Alwan, Manahat, Ebal, Sefo, and Onam.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="24" />Sibeon pung ana-ana, andia Aya deng Anah. Anah tu, yang dapa katumu mata aer panas di padang pasir, waktu dia gambala dia pung bapa pung keledai dong.<bt>Sibeon's children were, Aya, and Anah. Anah was the one who found [the] hot springs in the desert, when he was herding his father's donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yemim: hot springs (Vulgate)? mules? vipers?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yemim: hot springs (Vulgate)? mules? vipers?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="25-26" />Anah pung ana parampuan, andia Oholibama. Deng ana laki-laki, andia Dison. Dison pung ana-ana, andia Hemdan, Esban, Yitran, deng Keran.<bt>Anah's daughter was Oholibama. And [his] son, was Dison. Dison's children were, Hemdan, Esban, Yitran, and Keran.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="27" />Eser pung ana-ana, andia Bilhan, Sa'awan, deng Akan.<bt>Eser's children were, Bilhan, Saawan, and Akan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="28" />Disan pung ana-ana, andia Us deng Aran.<bt>Disan's children were, Us, and Aran.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="29-30" />Jadi kapala-kapala suku orang Hori dong, andia Lotan, Sobal, Sibeon, Anah, Dison, Eser, deng Disan. Dong samua tenga di negrí Seir.<bt>So (consequently) the clan heads of the Hori people were, Lotan, Sobal, Sibeon, Anah, Dison, Eser, and Disan. They all lived in the country of Seir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Edom pung raja-raja<bt>Edom's rajas</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Waktu negrí Isra'el balóm ada raja, di tana Edom su ada pung raja. Dong pung nama ba'iko-ba'iko, andia:<bt>When the country of Israel did not yet have rajas, the land of Edom already had their rajas. Their names in order are:</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="32" />Dong angka Beor pung ana, nama Bela, jadi raja di kota Dinhaba.<bt>They appointed/elevated Beor's child, named Bela, to be raja in the city of Dinhaba.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="33" />Waktu Bela mati, Yobab nae jadi raja, ganti sang dia. Dia pung bapa, nama Sera dari kampong Bosra.<bt>When Bela died, Yobab ascended to become raja, replacing him. His father was named Sera from the village of Bosra.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="34" />Waktu Yobab mati, Husam nae jadi raja, ganti sang dia. Husam tu, dari orang Teman dong pung negrí.<bt>When Yobab died, Husam ascended becoming raja, replacing him. That Husam was from the Teman people's country.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="35" />Waktu Husam mati, Hadad nae jadi raja, ganti sang dia. Dia pung bapa, nama Bedad dari kampong Awit. (Dia tu, yang kasi kala orang Midian waktu dong baparáng di Moab.)<bt>When Husam died, Hadad ascended becoming raja, replacing him. His father was named Bedad from the village of Awit. (He was the one who defeated the Midian people when they RECIP-warred in Moab.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="36" />Waktu Hadad mati, Samla nae jadi raja, ganti sang dia. Samla tu, dari kampong Masreka.<bt>When Hadad died, Samla ascended becoming raja, replacing him. That Samla was from the village of Masreka.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="37" />Waktu Samla mati, Saul nae jadi raja, ganti sang dia. Saul tu, dari kampong Rehobot di pinggir kali.<bt>When Samla died, Saul ascended becoming raja, replacing him. That Saul was from the village of Rehobot at the edge of the river. [EXEG: NRSV and CEV say this is the Euphrates. But TN discusses this and dismisses it becuase the Euphrates is too far from Edom.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="38" />Waktu Saul mati, Ba'al-Hanan nae jadi raja, ganti sang dia. Dia pung bapa, nama Akbor.<bt>When Saul died, Baal Hanan ascended becoming raja, replacing him. His father was named Akbor.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph Continuation" usfm="m">
      <v n="39" />Waktu Ba'al-Hanan mati, Hadar nae jadi raja, ganti sang dia. Hadar tu, dari kampong Pau. Dia pung bini, nama Mehetabel. Mehetabel pung bapa, nama Matret. Deng dia pung ba'i, Mesahab.<bt>When Baal Hanan died, Hadar ascended becoming raja, replacing him. That Hadar was from the village of Pau. His wife was named Mehetabel. Mehetabel's father was named Matret. And her grandfather, Mesahab.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40-43" />Jadi kapala-kapala suku yang turun dari Esau dong, andia: Timna, Alwa, Yetet, Oholibama, Ela, Pinon, Kenas, Teman, Mibsar, Magdiel, deng Iram. Dong satu-satu kasi nama dong pung negrí iko dong pung nama sandiri-sandiri.<bt>So (consequently) the clan heads who descended from Esau (collective) were: Timna, Alwa, Yetet, Oholibama, Ela, Pinon, Kenas, Teman, Mibsar, Magdiel, and Iram. Each of them named their country following their own names.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishpchotam: groups in which there is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mishpchotam: groups in which there is a felt blood relationship, subdivision of a tribe, ethnic group</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Jadi itu samua, carita so'al Esau pung turunan, andia orang Edom dong.<bt>So (consequently) all of that is the story/account of Esau's descendants, the people of Edom.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moshbotam (moshbah): seat, area of residence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">moshbotam (moshbah): seat, area of residence ʾachuzatam: their property<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob kambali pi tana Kana'an<bt>Yakob returns to Kanaan land</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="37" />
      <v n="1-2a" />Ini Yakob dong pung carita. Tempo hari, Yakob pi tenga ulang lai di tana Kana'an. Itu dia pung papa Isak pung tampa tenga dari dolu.<bt>This (is) Yakob 3p[=and those associated with him]'s story. At that time, Yakob went to live again in Kanaan land. That was his papa Isak's living place from before.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mgurey: stopover place, place where a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mgurey: stopover place, place where a resident alien lives, home JR: statement with different elaborations -- [overlay?] Lots of participles, piʿels.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf deng dia pung kaka dong<bt>Yusuf and his elder siblings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2b" />Itu waktu, Yakob pung ana satu dari dia pung bini Rahel, nama Yusuf. Waktu dia pung umur tuju blas taon, dia deng dia pung kaka dong biasa pi jaga dong pung kambing-domba sama-sama. Dia pung kaka dong, ana dari Yakob pung bini, Bilha deng Silpa. Ma Yusuf ni, tukang bawa mulu kasi dia pung papa, so'al dia pung kaka dong.<bt>At that time, Yakob had one child from his wife Rahel, his name was Yusuf. When he was 17 years old, he and his elder siblings habitually went to care-for their goats-sheep together. His older siblings, (were) children from Yakob's wifes, Bilha and Silpa. But this Yusuf, (he was) a habitual tattle-tale [tukang bawa mulut] to his father, about his elder siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dayang (archaic) = concubine; tukang bawa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">dayang (archaic) = concubine; tukang bawa mulut = tukang lapor; tuang bajudas = cari muka</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nshey: wives, in this case slave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nshey: wives, in this case slave women who were Jacob's concubines wayyabeʾ (buʾ hif): bring in news<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>dibbatam (dibbah): rumor, calumny; bad reports. In event tense, may refer to just one occasion. Wenham and others: dibbah is always negative, for untruths and fabrications. Joseph told lies about his brothers, not exemplary behavior. ʾet: preposition "with", not accusative<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>ba-: locative with semantic object naʿar: young man, but also attendant, in this case like an apprentice<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00697c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf dapa baju bagus<bt>They give a beautiful shirt/clothes to Yusuf</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Waktu barana sang Yusuf, Yakob su tua. Andia ko dia sayang sang Yusuf lebe dari dia pung ana-ana laen dong. Satu kali, Yakob bekin satu baju panjang yang talalu bagus<bt>When giving birth to Yusuf, Yakob was already old. This is why he loved Yusuf more than is other children. One time, Yakob made a very nice long shirt</bt><note reference="37:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab Bahasa Ibrani pung kata, bisa dia pung arti &lt;juba deng warna bagus macam-macam,&gt; ko, &lt;baju panjang bagus&gt;, andia baju panjang deng tangan panjang.<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab words, it's meaning can be 'robe with all sorts of good colors' or ' a nice long shirt,' that is a long shirt with long sleeves.</bt></note>kasi sang Yusuf.<bt>for Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ktonet: long shirt, maybe reaching clear"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ktonet: long shirt, maybe reaching clear down to the ankles. Sounds like an outer garment, not the inner tunic. passim: different kinds of cloth in a patchwork of different colors. The "different colors" appears to come from the oral tradition, which the Septuagint and Vulgate follow. An Egyptian fresco from iii-iv BCE shows Canaanite noblemen in outer robes with longitudinal stripes. Could also be embroidery or applique. In 1 Samuel, used of robes for virgin princesses.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Waktu dia pung kaka dong lia papa lebe sayang sang Yusuf, dong binci mati sang dia, sampe dong sonde mau ba'omong bae-bae deng dia lai.<bt>When his elder siblings saw that their papa loved Yusuf more, they hated him very much, to the point that they did not want to talk properly/civily to him anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="camburu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">camburu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lshalom: peaceably, civilly. They just couldnʾt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lshalom: peaceably, civilly. They just couldnʾt say anything to him; dey futless.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-7" />Satu malam, ju Yusuf mimpi. Ais dia kasi tau itu mimpi sang dia pung kaka dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bosong dengar dolo! Beta mimpi bilang, kotong samua ada ika kotong pung padi-gandum dalam kabón. Ju beta pung padi badiri lurus. Ma bosong pung padi dong badiri kuliling, ko soya beta pung.&gt;&gt; Dengar bagitu, ju dia pung kaka dong tamba jengkel lai sang dia.<bt>And then one night, Yusuf dreamed. Then he told that dream to his elder siblings sayings, "We! You-pl listen! I dreamed that we all were tying our wheat-padi in the garden. And my padi stood up straight. But your-pl padi-s stood around, in order to bow.down to mine.&gt;&gt; And hearing that, his elder siblings were even more upset/angry at him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jengkel = je'e ika bulir ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">jengkel = je'e ika bulir = satu tangan; = padi pung kelu, macam-macam padi; beta pung OK; soya = tunduk, sembah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="JR: This is the first dream"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">JR: This is the first dream in the Bible with obviously symbolic content. Earlier ones were dreams of specific encounters; but this one needed interpreting to be intelligible at all. The wheat was tied into sheaves, not bundles like laundry or hay.<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>hineh: shows it from Joseph's perspective. It sounds naive or clueless, but is it?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais ju dong togor sang Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Woi! Lu kira lu su mau jadi bos ko parenta sang botong, ko?&gt;&gt; Te dong su talalu jengkel sang dia, tagal dia kasi tau itu mimpi.<bt>Thus they scolded Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Woi! [+challenge] You think that you are going to become boss to order us around, [+tag question]?&gt;&gt; And they were exceedingly upset with him, because he told that dream.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dvaraw: the dream and the words."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">dvaraw: the dream and the words. Could be hendiadys, "the report of the dream". But could be the dream, coming on top of the talebearing.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00702c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf carita dia pung mimpi<bt>Yusuf tells his dream</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais itu, Yusuf mimpi ulang lai. Ju dia kasi tau dia pung kaka dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Beta mimpi lai. Beta lia matahari, bulan, deng sablás bintang. Samua soya bae-bae sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yusuf dreamed agained. And he told his elder siblings saying, &lt;&lt;We! I dreamed again. I saw the sun, moon and 11 stars. All were bowing in-good-fashion to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bae-bae = teratur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bae-bae = teratur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishtakhavim: bowing down deeply, doing homage,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mishtakhavim: bowing down deeply, doing homage, prostrating themselves to him personally, not to a symbolic sheaf. JR: sun, moon, and stars become an icon of Israel, used in Revelation.<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Waktu Yusuf su carita abis itu mimpi sang dia pung papa deng dia pung kaka dong, dia pung papa togor karás sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Mimpi ke apa tu! Lu pikir beta, lu pung mama, deng lu pung kaka-adi dong datang ko kotong ciom lu pung kaki? Lu pung mau lai!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yusuf had finished telling that dream to his papa and his elder siblings, his papa scolded him severely saying, &lt;&lt;What kind of dream is that! Do you think I, and your mama, and your elder-younger siblings are going to come in order that we kiss your feet? Don't you wish!(=cynical: impossible!)"</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lu pung mau/ena lai = tidak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Lu pung mau/ena lai = tidak mungkin! you wish = in your dreams! (cynical); mimpi kaya apa itu = older generation</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hvoʾ naboʾ: a rebuke; are we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hvoʾ naboʾ: a rebuke; are we really going to come and bow down? Unthinkable! wayyigʿar-bo: he rebuked him, reproached him<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>JR: lots of accusative absolutes</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Jadi Yusuf pung kaka dong camburu mati sang dia. Ma dia pung papa sonde abis pikir itu mimpi.<bt>Thus Yusuf 's elder siblings were very jealous of him. But his papa didn't stop thinking about that dream.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="camburu = iri hati; jealous, jengkel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">camburu = iri hati; jealous, jengkel</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="wayqanʾu-bo: their envy became aroused, they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">wayqanʾu-bo: their envy became aroused, they got very steamed up because they were jealous. Joseph's actions and words were really revolting to his brothers.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dong jual sang Yusuf pi Masir ko jadi budak di sana<bt>They sell Yususf to Masir to become a slave there</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ais satu waktu, Yusuf pung kaka dong bawa dong pung papa pung kambing-domba sampe deka deng kampong Sikem.<bt>Then one time, Yusuf's elder siblings brought their papa's goat-sheep to (a place) near Sikem village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Shekem is about 40 miles north"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Shekem is about 40 miles north of Jerusalem. Jacob's main center of operations was near Hebron, 20 miles south of Jerusalem, but the country was dry and the sheep had to be taken where the grass was. Shekem was the nearest town to where they were -- they werenʾt inside the town. (It was the place Simeon and Levi had wasted not too many years before, so maybe it was unpopulated at this time, or else they still terrorized the community.)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Sonde lama, ju dia pung papa bilang, &lt;&lt;Usu, é! Lu pung kaka dong ada jaga kambing-domba deka-deka di Sikem. Jadi siap-siap ko lu pi lia sang dong dolo.&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long after, their papa said, &lt;&lt;Usu, é (Yusuf nickname)! Your elder siblings are watching the goat-sheep around near Sikem. So you get ready in order for you to go see/take.care.of them (mild imperative).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bae, papa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf answered saying, &lt;&lt;Ok, papa.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinneni: look! me! = at your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hinneni: look! me! = at your orders</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ju dia pung papa bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pi dolo ko lia lu pung kaka dong, deng beta pung kambing-domba dong. Dong ada karmana, na, lu kambali ko lapor sang beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then his papa said, &lt;&lt;You go (imp), to see you elder siblings and my goat-sheep. However they happen to be, you return to report to me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lapor = more wajib than just"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lapor = more wajib than just kasi tau</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais ju Yusuf jalan kasi tenga tana Hebron pung padang, ko pi tarús sampe di Sikem.<bt>And so, Yusuf journeyed leaving behind Hebron land's fields, to go all.the.way to Sikem</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lagóng = ravine ; padang, lemba"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lagóng = ravine ; padang, lemba</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shalom: peace, see if they are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shalom: peace, see if they are doing all right vahashiveni (shwv caus): bring back<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>wayyaboʾ: went off towards Shekem A two or three day hike<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Sampe deng sampe ju, dia cari kuliling sang dong di itu padang. Ais ju dia katumu satu orang yang tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu ada cari apa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving there then, he hunted go.all around their fields there. And then, he met a person who asked him saying, &lt;&lt;What are you looking for?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʿeh: wandering around (Joseph) JR: Jewish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">toʿeh: wandering around (Joseph) JR: Jewish tradition has it that the guy was the angel Gabriel.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Om. Beta ada cari beta pung kaka dong. Dong ada foo kambing-domba cari rumput deka-deka di sini. Om ada lia sang dong, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yusuf replied saying, &lt;&lt;Mother's.brother. I'm hunting for my elder siblings. They are shepherding goat-sheep hunting for grass somewhere near here. Has mother's.brother seen them, [+tag question]?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dong ada foo (Rote) = gambala,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">dong ada foo (Rote) = gambala, giring; last sentence is natural to provoke right response; parigi tua = used to have</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00703c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf pung kaka dong lia dia pung datang<bt>Older siblings see Yusuf's coming</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais, itu orang kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Dong sonde ada di sini lai. Ma dong bilang dong mau pi deka-deka di kampong Dotan.&gt;&gt;<bt>Next, that person told saying, &lt;&lt;They are not here anymore. But they said they wanted to go somewhere near Dotan village.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais ju Yusuf pi iko dia pung kaka dong, sampe dapa lia sang dong di Dotan.<bt>And then, Yusuf went following his elder siblings, until he could see them in Dotan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naSʿu (nSʿ): they pulled out, departed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">naSʿu (nSʿ): they pulled out, departed Another 15 miles north, another half day's hard hiking<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ma waktu Yusuf masi jao, te dong su dapa lia sang dia. Ju dong ba'akór ko mau bunu sang dia.<bt>But when Yusuf was still far.away, [contrary to expectation] they had already seen him. And they were in.one.accord to kill him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baakór = in accord, barunding (neutral),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">baakór = in accord, barunding (neutral), basakongkol</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="merachoq: from a distance vterem: before|i(18)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">merachoq: from a distance vterem: before<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yiqrav: he approached yitnaklu (hitp): they acted cunningly; laying a trap that will result in his death. Rashi, "filled with craftiness and deceit"<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>lahmito (mwt hif inf): to see him dead, do him in. This is the first chance they have had to kill him in a long time - remote place, father not around, outnumbered. He is coming not to help with the sheep, but to check on the brothers. He's an outsider in age relative to his brothers, not close to any of them: dynamics of large families.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ais dong kasi tau satu deng satu bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong lia dolo. Bos tukang mimpi su datang!<bt>Thus they told each other saying, &lt;&lt;Y'all look (mild imp). The dream boss has come!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is the details of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">This is the details of the plan summarized in 18. ʾish: nobody singled out; each of them was thinking the same thoughts and telling them to somebody else<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>baʿal hachlomot: the Lord of Dreams; sarcastic, the Dreamer, Master Dreamer. baʿal "expert" (Moses tells God he's not an expert talker "baʿal dvarim") hallazeh: this, explained as ha + zeh<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>baʾ (partcpl): background participle</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Mari suda ko kotong bunu sang dia. Abis, na, kotong lempar buang sang dia pi dalam parigi mati satu. Nanti kotong kasi tau sang papa bilang binatang utan dong su makan buang sang dia! Baru kotong lia dia pung mimpi dong jadi karmana!&gt;&gt;<bt>Come on and let's kill him. After, na, we'll throw disposing him in one of the dead wells there. Later we'll tell our papa saying jungle animals have eaten him! Then we'll see what happens with those dreams of his!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parigi mati = dry well, or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">parigi mati = dry well, or parigi tua = unused well (kotor, busuk, setan); makan buang = kodo, telan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lkhu (hlk imperv): let's go somewhere"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lkhu (hlk imperv): let's go somewhere nashlikhehu: let's throw something down. fling, not a proper burial<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>borah: location, cistern, artificial excavation in rocky soil, usually ten to thirty feet deep, for collecting and storing winter rain. Plastered inside with lime, therefore smooth. Opening smaller than the bottom. Hard to get out of. Also used for storing grain chayah: wild animal<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>raʿah: evil. Used for dangerous animals - lion, bear, ... ʾəkhalat-hu: ate him<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>vnirʾeh (rʾh): become visible mah-yyihyu: what they will become. The rabbis saw this as a test of Joseph's prophetic spirit: is our word going to be fulfilled, or his?<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Dengar abis, ju dia pung kaka Ruben cari jalan ko mau kasi salamat sang Yusuf. Ju dia togor sang dia pung adi dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Kotong jang bunu sang dia!<bt>Hearing that then, his elder sibling Ruben sought a way to save Yusuf. And he scolded his younger siblings saying, &lt;&lt;We! Let's not kill him, ok!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi salamat = kasi lolos, kasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi salamat = kasi lolos, kasi lapás; parigi pung bibir</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaatstsilehu (ntsl hif): he rescued him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaatstsilehu (ntsl hif): he rescued him, snatched him away. Josephus thinks Reuben is off scouting for new pasture land, so he is away a lot, and this is the first he has heard of the plot yad: hand, power, in their power<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nakkennu nafesh (nkh hif): we strike him and he dies, we beat him to death</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Lebe bae kotong buang sang dia pi dalam ini parigi mati sa. Di sini tampa sunyi, jadi sonde ada orang yang tau. Asal jang bekin badara sang dia.&gt;&gt; Dia omong bagitu, tagal dia mau kasi lapás sang Yusuf, ko suru dia pulang.<bt>It's better that we just dispose of him in this dead well. This here (is) a lonely place, so no one will know. As.long.as we don't make him bleed.&gt;&gt; He talked like that, because he wanted to let Yusuf go free, to order him to go home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal tishpku-dam: donʾt shed blood, making"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal tishpku-dam: donʾt shed blood, making blood spill out. Reuben, as eldest but out of favor with his father, needs to secure his own birthright against Jacob taking it over. midbar: in the uncultivated place<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>yad ʾal-tishlkhu-bo: donʾt lay a hand on him lemaʿan hatsil ʾoto: in order to save him<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00705c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none:horizontalPosition:center">Dong tola maso Yusuf pi dalam parigi<bt>They shove Yusuf into a well</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ais waktu Yusuf sampe di dong, dia pung kaka dong pegang ame sang dia, ju dong ru'i buang dia pung baju yang bagus tu.<bt>Then when Yusuf arrived at them, his elder siblings took hold of him, and they ripped.off disposed off that good shirt of his.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ru'i =strip off, raba kasar, lebe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ru'i =strip off, raba kasar, lebe kasar dari hela buang; ru'i rambut (parampuan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yafshiTu (hif): they stripped him. et"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yafshiTu (hif): they stripped him. et ... et ... et ... things that are relevant later kutanto (ktonet): his tunic, inner garment. Like a long t-shirt, but hand woven and in this case, quite fancy<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ais itu, dong hela raroso sang dia, ju dong tola maso pi dalam parigi mati.<bt>After that, they dragged him on the ground, and they pushed entering (him) into that dead well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hela roroso = seret, drag on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">hela roroso = seret, drag on ground, di tana</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="req: empty, idle; [JEG] &quot;Req&quot; implies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">req: empty, idle; [JEG] "Req" implies that it wasnʾt in use for anything else, not that it was dry; so the extra statement is added, probably because such cisterns are used for water storage during dry times.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais ju dong kambali ko pi makan. Dong masi makan, ju takuju dong dapa lia satu rombongan datang. Itu rombongan pung onta dong ada mua bawa barang dagang, sama ke dara kayu wangi, bumbu-bumbu, deng obat macam-macam. Tau-tau te itu rombongan orang Ismael yang datang dari kampong Gilead mau pi jao sakali di negrí Masir.<bt>And then they returned to go eat. They were still eating, and suddenly, they could see a group coming. That group's camels were carrying merchant's stuff, like sap of sweet.smelling wood, spices, and different k.o. medicine. Unexpectedly, that group (was) Ismael people who came from Gilead village wanting to go very far to negri Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tenga = aspectual middle; getah wangi,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tenga = aspectual middle; getah wangi, dupa, kemenyan (not known),</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yisʾu (nsʾ): they raised their eyes,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yisʾu (nsʾ): they raised their eyes, they looked ʾorchat (ʾorchah): caravan<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>nkhoʾt: ladanum; aromatic gum exuded from the leaves of the cistus-rose (Cistus salvifolius, native to Palestine). Zohary identifies it as tragacanth gum, from Astragalus or from A. gummifer on Mt. Hermon. tsri: Jericho balm, a desert plant possibly identified with Balm of Gilead, lot, Commiphora opobalsamum, which is not native to Palestine but comes from Arabia. Commentators suggest it was Balanites aegyptiaca, which is found all over Egypt and Palestine; but both this passage and Gen 43:11 refer to tsri as something that grew in Palestine but not in Egypt. UBS following Moldenke suggests Pistacia lentiscus, the mastic tree, 1 to 3 m. tall, evergreen leaves, with a gummy sap. Zohary doesn't list it.<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>lot: myrrh or stacte (type of resin; FF 147-149,178). "Mor," Greek smyrna? Myrrh is Commiphora myrrha (Cistus salvifolia), a dark red gum with strong aroma and a bitter taste. Arabia, Abyssinia, Somalia coast, but not Palestine or Gilead. More likely "lot" is ladanum and "nkhot" is tragacanth. Zohary identifies it as ladanum, Cistus incanus, widespread in Gilead and elsewhere. lhorid (yrd hif inf): take it down to Egypt<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ais itu, Yahuda kasi tau dia pung kaka-adi dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Lebe bae bagini sa. Kotong jang bunu sang dia. Dia pung ontong apa? Biar karmana ju, kotong sonde bisa sambunyi dia pung dara.<bt>After that, Yahuda told his elder.younger siblings saying, &lt;&lt;We! The best (thing to do) is just like this. Let's not murder him. What would the benefit be? No matter how, we will not be able to hide his blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This story tracks Joseph, whose sons"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">This story tracks Joseph, whose sons Ephraim and Manasseh carry the most weight among the northern tribes later; but Judah plays an important role, because it is in this story that he takes over the leadership, and his descendants become the important ones in the south. Reuben appears to leave again.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>betsaʿ: cut, profit kiSinu (kSh piʿel): we cover up<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ada lebe bae kotong pi jual sang dia di itu orang Ismael dong. Biar kotong bekin karmana sang dia, ju dia masi kotong pung adi barana. Tagal itu, kotong jang bekin saki sang dia, é!&gt;&gt; Ju dong samua ba'akór deng dia pung omong.<bt>It's better that we go sell him to those Ismael people. No mattter what we do with him, he's still our younger sibling by birth. Because of that, let's not hurt him, ok! " And they all agreed with that talk of his.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vyadenu ʾal-thi-bo (hyh): our hand will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vyadenu ʾal-thi-bo (hyh): our hand will not be on him</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00709c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none:horizontalPosition:center;verticalPosition:top">Dong ba'akór ko mau jual sang Yusuf pi orang dagang dong<bt>They agree to sell Yusuf to the merchants</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ais pas deng itu orang dagang dong<bt>After that, just when those merchants were passing then, Yusuf's elder siblings pulled him up from that well.</bt><note reference="37:28a" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Banya tulisan bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;orang dari tana Midian&gt;. Ada barapa orang pintar bilang itu orang Midian deng orang Ismael tu, dua nama, ma satu bangsa. Dong tu jadi dari Ismael pung turunan, deng dong tenga di tana Midian. (Lia <span class="Italic">Tukang Putus Parkara dong</span> 8:22-24). Ada lai orang pintar saparu yang bilang orang Midian deng orang Ismael tu, dua bangsa, ma dong sama-sama orang dagang.<bt>Many Ibrani writings say 'people from Midian land'. Some knowledgable people think that the people of Midian and the people of Ismael, (are) two names, but one ethnic group. They are Ismael's descendants, and they live in the land of Midian (see Judges 8:22-24). There are others who say the people of Midian and the people of Ismael, they are from two ethnic groups, but both are merchants.</bt></note>lewat, ju Yusuf pung kaka dong hela nae sang dia dari itu parigi. Ju dong jual sang dia pi di itu orang Ismael dong deng harga dua pulu doi perak.<bt>And they sold him to those Ismael people, with the price 20 silver moneys</bt><note reference="37:28b" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Orang yang pintar dong kasi tau bilang, itu waktu, dong biasa jual-beli budak yang masi muda deng harga 20 doi perak.<bt>Knowledgeable people tell saying, at that time, they usually sold-buy slaves who were still young, with the price of 20 silver moneys.</bt></note>Ais itu, ju dong bawa sang Yusuf pi Masir.<bt>. After that then, they brought Yusuf to Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʿavru: they passed sochrim (partcpl): who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaʿavru: they passed sochrim (partcpl): who were traveling<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>yimshkhu: they drew him out, pulled him up and out. The brothers, not the Midianites. hem: Midian people and Ishmael people are two ways of talking about the same people -- Ishmael names the family, Midian names the place they were from. (Here it's Medan, from another son of Abraham besides Midian and Ishmael.) The way they are introduced makes it unlikely that there were two different groups of people moving through the area, the ones that bought Joseph, and another bunch that showed up out of nowhere and swiped Joseph out from under his brothersʾ noses to sell to the other group. Besides, later on Joseph says to his brothers, "You sold me into Egypt."<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>vayaviʾu (hif): took him away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Waktu dong jual sang Yusuf tu, Ruben sonde tau. Andia ko waktu dia bale pi itu parigi, dia takuju mati, tagal Yusuf su sonde ada lai. Ais dia robe-robe dia pung pakean di badan, tagal dia pung hati talalu susa.<bt>When they sold Yusuf then, Ruben did not know. So when he returned to that well, then he was very startled, because Yusuf was not there. Then he tore (repeatedly) his clothes on his body, because his liver was very distressed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Reuben may have come back after"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Reuben may have come back after his brothers left, or he may have waited for them to leave yiqraʿ: he tore<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>bgadaw: his clothes</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ju dia bale pi dia pung adi dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Aduu! Itu ana sonde ada lai di situ! Sakarang beta musti bekin apa lai?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he returned to his younger siblings saying, &lt;&lt;Adu! That child is no longer there! Now what am I going to do?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾanah ʾni-ba (ʾan) (boʾ participle): where?;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾanah ʾni-ba (ʾan) (boʾ participle): where?; ʾliterally "where shall I go?" meaning "where can I turn fo help? what can I do? there is no hope left for me"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ais dong horo kambing satu ekor, ju dong ame Yusuf pung baju bagus tu, ko calóp pi dalam itu dara.<bt>Then they sliced.the.neck of a goat, and they brought that good shirt of Yusufs, to dip it into that blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="horo = sembelih, slice neck to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">horo = sembelih, slice neck to bleed-kill (includes collecting the blood), horo viola; dong tada (collect in receptacle)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishchtu: they slaughtered sʿir: hairy one,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishchtu: they slaughtered sʿir: hairy one, he-goat<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʿizim: the goats (one of their own goats, not a wild goat like the ones that are all over the hills around here) yitblu: dip<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Ais dong bawa ame itu baju badara kasi dong pung papa, ko kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa! Botong dapa pili ini baju. Papa lia coba. Jang-jang ini adi Usu pung baju.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they took that bloody shirt there, brought gave it to their papa, and.so told saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! We unintentionally found this shirt. Papa please look at it. Hopefully it's not younger sibling Usu's shirt.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dapa pili = angka, temukan, kebetulan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">dapa pili = angka, temukan, kebetulan katumu accidently find (seperti dapa katumu doi di jalan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəshallchu (shlch piʿel): they sent, they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yəshallchu (shlch piʿel): they sent, they had the shirt brought to Jacob, probably by a servant yaviyʾu (bwʾ hif): they caused it to arrive<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>hakker-naʾ (nkr hif imperv, causative): investigate, recognize, know what it is. Recognize, please. (Same word used in Chapter 38, ties the two together.) ʾShirtʾ is not in the construct; there is a hiatus between it and binkha. binkha hiʾ, ʾim loʾ: is this your boyʾs, or not?<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Lia ame itu baju, ju Yakob langsung kanál. Tarús dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Aduuu! Ini memang beta pung ana pung baju. Tar tau binatang utan su rabe sang dia di mana. Awee! Beta pung ana su mati!&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing that shirt then, Yakob knew right away. Straight away he answered saying, &lt;&lt;Aduuu! This truly is my child's shirt. Who knows where what jungle animal has torn him apart. Adu! My child is dead!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rabe = tear apart, cakar, scrape,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">rabe = tear apart, cakar, scrape, gouge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yakirah (nkr hif imperf): he recognized"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yakirah (nkr hif imperf): he recognized it chayah raʿah: an evil beast, dangerous animals recognized as a class<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>tarof toraf: torn in pieces, the way a wild animal eats his prey</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ais itu, Yakob robe-robe dia pung baju, ju dia pake karong goni, tagal dia susa mau mati.<bt>After that, Yakob repeatedly.tore his clothes, and he work a gunny sack, because he was very distressed</bt><note reference="37:34" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Yakob robe-robe dia pung baju, ju dia ganti deng sarong dari karong goni, sama ke orang Yahudi dong biasa pake waktu dong pung orang mati.<bt>Yakub tore his clothes, and he changed to wear a sarong from a gunny sack, like the Yahudi people normally wore when their people died.</bt></note>Ju dia manangis makarereu sang dia pung ana sonde pake barenti.<bt>. And he cried in great sobs continually for his child for a long time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karong goni = gunny sack (rough)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">karong goni = gunny sack (rough)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="simlotaw: his clothing yasem: he put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">simlotaw: his clothing yasem: he put on<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>saq: poor quality material of goat hair covering the bare loins during mourning matnaw: the strong musculature which unites the upper and lower part of the body, lumbar region, hips, small of the back, loins<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>yitʾabel (hitp): he mourned yamim ravim: many days; Rashi says it is 22 years.<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Dia pung ana laki-laki deng ana parampuan samua datang kokoe sang dia, ma dong sonde ontong. Dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde! Beta bisa susa sampe mati, te beta sonde bisa lupa ini ana satu ni.&gt;&gt; Ju Yakob pung hati susa tarús, tagal dia inga dia pung ana Yusuf yang su mati tu.<bt>His male children and his female children all came to comfort him, but to no avail. He said, &lt;&lt;No! I can be distressed until death, because I cannot forget this child. " And Yakob's liver was continually distressed, because he remembered that child Yusuf of his who had died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kokoe = buju, persuade, comfort"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kokoe = buju, persuade, comfort</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaqumu (qwm): they arose, stood up."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaqumu (qwm): they arose, stood up. Were there other daughters besides Dinah? Probably, as women donʾt get mentioned much unless they do something that calls attention. Might include daughters-in-law too. lnakhmo (piʿel caus): to comfort him about the death, express condolences, reassure<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ymaʾen: he refused lhitnachem (nkm hitp): to be comforted<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ʾered (yrd imperf): I will go down ʾavel (adj): in mourning<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>sheʾolah: location, the world of dead people. Not Hell, which is a place of punishment yevk (bkh): he wept for his son, he bewailed him<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00713c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf jadi budak di Masir<bt>Yusuf becomes a slave in Masir</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Waktu Yakob masi susa bagitu, te itu orang dagang dong<bt>When Yakob was still distressed like that, [background info] those merchant people</bt><note reference="37:36" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab Bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang itu orang dagang dong &lt;orang Midian&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab says those merchants were 'people of Midian'.</bt></note>su sampe di Masir. Ais dong pi jual sang Yusuf kasi satu orang bésar, nama Potifar. Dia ni, raja Masir pung komandán jaga.<bt>had already arrived in Masir. Then they sold Yusuf to a big (important) person. His name was Potifar. He, (was) the comander of raja Masir's guard.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mədanim: Medan, textual variant Midian. Gen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mədanim: Medan, textual variant Midian. Gen 25:2 they were both Keturah's sons. Judges 8:22,24 Midian = Ishmael. makhru: they sold<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>sris: court-official, eunuch sar: king's representative, chief, leader of group<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>hattabachim: bodyguards; executioners, slaughterers CHECK (he ran a prison, according to 40)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yahuda deng dia pung ana mantu Tamar<bt>Yahuda and his child-in-law Tamar</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="38" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, Yahuda jalan kasi tenga dia pung kaka-adi dong, ko pi tenga deng dia pung tamán Hira di kampong Adulam.<bt>After that, Yahuda journey leaving behind his elder-younger siblings to go live with his friend Hira in Adulam village.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayered: go down; go from the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayered: go down; go from the Judea ridge toward Egypt, to the southwest. Judah may have been around 20; Joseph was 17. vayit (nth imperf): spread out = put up his tents. The brothers split up, and Judah distances himself not only by going elsewhere, but by throwing in his lot with a Canaanite. Rashi thinks Judah became Hirah's business partner.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>Judah is the second emerging leader of the Israel nation. He persuaded his brothers to sell Joseph, not kill him. Rashi defends Judah by saying that if he had told his brothers to return Joseph to their father, they would have done it; but that also implies Judah may have remorse for not having done it. Check on tabachim in 37:36 executioners or bodyguards? Potifar ran his own prison.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Di situ ada bapa satu, orang Kana'an, nama Sua. Yahuda basuka deng Sua pung ana nona satu, ju dong dua kawin. Ais itu, dia barana barapa ana laki-laki ba'iko-ba'iko.<bt>There there was a man (father), a Kanaan person, his name Sua. Yahuda liked one of Sua's young girl children, and they two married. After that, he gave birth to several male children in a row.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barana iko-iko ; karutuk = si"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">barana iko-iko ; karutuk = si kici</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="knaʿni: Rashi follows the Talmud in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">knaʿni: Rashi follows the Talmud in reading "Canaanite" as "merchant", but with no basis. He may be worried about too many women from outside the family marrying in. Shuaʿ: add "w" to distinguish it from a common Pidgin word. LXX calls her Batshua as in Verse 12.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>vayaboʾ ʾeleah: he went to her, had intercourse with her. Standard phrase for the consummation phase of a marriage, implied in Pidgin "marry".</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ana nomer satu, dong kasi nama Er.<bt>Child number one, they named Er.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant yiqraʾ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vatahar (hrh): she became pregnant yiqraʾ: masculine, but in the sequence "pregnant ... bore ..." it could be taken as feminine. Yet the first boy seems to normally have his name given by the father, even when the rest are named by the mother.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Tarús nomer dua, dong kasi nama Onan.<bt>Then number two, they named Onan.</bt><v n="5" />Ais nomer tiga, nama Sela. Waktu barana sang Sela, ju dong su pinda pi kampong laen, nama Kesib.<bt>Next number three, named Sela. When giving birth to Sela, they had already moved to another village, named Kesib.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatosef (ysf hif): did it again."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vatosef (ysf hif): did it again. Sounds like they came in rapid succession, so Shelah wasnʾt necessarily much younger than Onan. kziv: possibly ʾDeceptionʾ. Jeremiah uses it in that way.<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>blidtah (yld inf): at his birth Martin Ebegg and others at Notre Dame have brought out a new translation that leans more heavily on the Dead Sea Scrolls and the Septuagint than just on the Masoretic text. (Jon Rawlings studied with John Strudnell.)<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Waktu ana nomer satu, Er, su bésar datang, Yahuda pi maso minta kasi dia satu nona, nama Tamar. Ais ju dong dua kawin.<bt>When child number one, Er, was grown, Yahuda went enter-asking a young girl for him [to marry], named Tamar. Then they two married.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The Rabbis thought Tamar must be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">The Rabbis thought Tamar must be Aramean, in order to defend Judah's reputation. Between Verses 5 and 6, Er grows up. Maybe he's 18 by now. This could have been even before Joseph was sold, though the chronology may fit if Er was born soon after.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ma Er talalu jahat. Tagal itu, Tuhan hukum kasi mati sang dia. Andia ko Er mati sonde kasi tenga ana.<bt>But Er was exceedingly evil. Because of that, God punished killed him. That is the reason why Er died without leaving a child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʿ: ugly, disagreeable, unwholesome, bad, morally"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raʿ: ugly, disagreeable, unwholesome, bad, morally depraved, objectionable. Stative, not a discrete bad action. vaymitehu: he killed him; Er died, when the Lord took his life; allowed his death, took his life, put him to death -- almost like a judicial execution.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais itu, Yahuda suru dia pung ana nomer dua bilang, &lt;&lt;Onan! Lu pung kaka su mati, ma sonde ada ana. Jadi sakarang, iko orang tua dong pung biasa, lu musti ganti lu pung kaka ko kawin dia pung bini, ko biar lu kasi turunan sang lu pung kaka.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yahuda ordered his second child saying, &lt;&lt;Onan! Your elder sibling is dead, but there is no child. So (consequently) now, following the elder's custom, you must replace your elder sibling and.so marry his wife. In.order.that it will happen that you give a descendant to your elder sibling.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vyabem ʾotah (bwʾ piʿel imperv): consummate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vyabem ʾotah (bwʾ piʿel imperv): consummate the marriage of a brother-in-law, in which the obligation is fulfilled of marrying one's brother's widow to produce offspring. Dt 15:5 says that the first son born to the uncle will carry the dead man's name, and the uncle's other sons will carry their uncle's name. Onan didnʾt take it that way; he thought he was cut out of starting his own lineage. haqem (qwm hif imperv): raise up a family<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Onan su tau itu adat. Ma dia sonde mau kasi turunan sang dia pung kaka Er. Jadi tiap kali, kalo dia tidor deng Tamar, dia buang kaluar dia pung bibit, ko biar Tamar sonde usa barana.<bt>Onan already knew that adat. But he didn't want to give a descendant to his elder.sibling Er. So when ever, when he slept with Tamar, he disposed outside his seed, so that it.would.happen that Tamar won't give birth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bibit; air mani"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bibit; air mani</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayedaʿ (ydʿ imperf): he realized zeraʿ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayedaʿ (ydʿ imperf): he realized zeraʿ: offspring, collective, not singular. Keep the line going. There may be something about the inheritance involved too.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>hayah: introduces a temporal clauses. This is called a frequentative perfect, and matches baʾ; but it's about the only example there is. vshichet (piʿel): wipe out, spoil, ruin, misuse; he would purposely ejaculate on the ground rather than risk making Tamar pregnant with a child who was not his. She was probably about Onan's age, 16 or 17.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>lbilti: so that ... not</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Onan pung cara bagitu, bekin Tuhan mara mau mati. Andia ko Tuhan ju hukum kasi mati sang dia.<bt>Onan's way like that, made God very angry. That is the reason why God also punished killing him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiraʿ (rʿʿ impf): he was displeasing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiraʿ (rʿʿ impf): he was displeasing to God, stative.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Waktu Yahuda lia dia pung ana dua-dua yang kawin deng Tamar su mati, ju dia jadi taku. Dia pikir, jang sampe dia pung ana bungsu Sela kawin deng Tamar lai, nanti dia ju mati. Andia ko dia pi kasi tau dia pung ana mantu Tamar bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana, é. Lebe bae lu pulang pi lu pung orang tua sa. Nanti beta pung ana Sela su bésar dolo, baru lu kambali ko kawin deng dia.&gt;&gt; Ais ju Tamar pulang.<bt>When Yahuda saw that both his two children who married Tamar were dead, then he became afraid. He thought, his youngest son Sela shouldn't marry Tamar anymore, lest later he also die. That is the reason why he went telling his child-in-law Tamar saying, &lt;&lt;Child. It's better if you just return to your parents. Later [when] my son Sela is grown, only then [should] you return to marry him.&gt;&gt; And so Tamar returned.home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalato (kalah): woman who is first"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kalato (kalah): woman who is first under control of her father, then of her husband (and her father in law as the husband's representative); young daughter-in-law. Hittite and Middle Assyrian law (Tiglath-Pileser, reflecting customs that could already have been in force in Abraham's time) specify that if there is no other brother to marry the widow and perpetuate the dead man's line, the dead man's father is to do it, and if he dies, his brothers. Even if Tamar is living at her father's place, she is still under Judah. ʾalmanah: as a widow<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʿad-yigdol (imperf): until he grows up. Sounds like Shelah was 15 or 16, so waiting to become of marriagable age was on the order of maybe a year, not a decade. He might have been Tamar's age. pen: prevention of a theoretically possible event<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>vatelekh (hlk imperf): she went</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Lewat barapa lama, ju Yahuda pung bini mati. Jadi dia susa sampe waktu duka abis.<bt>After awhile, Yahuda's wife died. Thus he grieved until the grieving time was over.</bt><note reference="38:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Iko dong pung adat, kalo orang pung bini mati, dong sonde pi mana-mana, deng dong pake pakean susa. Sampe barapa bulan, baru abis.<bt>Following their adat, when a wife died, they didn't go anywhere, and they wore grieving clothes. Until several months, then it was finished/done.</bt></note>Ais dia pange dia pung tamán Hira, ko dong dua pi kampong Timna. Di situ orang dong ada rame-rame cukur domba pung bulu ko jual.<bt>then he called his friend Hira, for them two to go to Timna village. There people were busy shaving sheeps hair, in order to sell it. [EXEG: Heb. “his sheepshearers”: Here's the problem: As IVP commentary (for Gen 31:19) and others point out for the Middle East then (as for Australia and NZ these days), because the activity of sheepshearing is so labour intensive and its equipment so specialised, common practice is to bring the sheep to a central location, rather than take the shearers to the individual sheep owners (unless they are really large scale). It's a big festival, sort of like a county fair. (See also Note on Hebrew word in vs. 13 below.) While this was common knowledge to the original audience, it gets lost if one translates this literally. So a previous consultant pressured us to bring out this aspect, which we have with /rame-rame/ in v.12 and /iko pesta cukur…/ in vs. 13. But in the process we lost the point that he wasn't just going for the fun of it, but to “supervise the shearing of his sheep” when it was his turn (NLT). For discourse reasons (broader first then more specific) I'd like to leave vs.12 as is, but change vs.13 to get Judah's possession in.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lapas itam = period of grieving/mourning"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lapas itam = period of grieving/mourning (not known by UNSs!)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Batshua: might have been her name"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Batshua: might have been her name vayirbu (rbh): became many<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>vayinachem (nchm): observe the rites of mourning, was comforted gozzi: shearing<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>reʿehu: his friend</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ju orang kasi tau sang Tamar bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pung papa mantu ada pi Timna ko urus orang ko cukur dia pung domba dong pung bulu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then people told Tamar saying, &lt;&lt;Your father-in-law is on his way to Timna to oversee people shaving his sheep's hair.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) to bring in “his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) to bring in “his sheep”</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&lt;&lt;Lu pung papa mantu ada pi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">&lt;&lt;Lu pung papa mantu ada pi Timna iko pesta cukur domba pung bulu.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayugad (ngd pass): it was announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayugad (ngd pass): it was announced to Tamar hineh: in a quotation, it's a here and now event, not something presented from the speaker's specific point of view within a narrative.<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>lagor (grr inf): shear wool. The Sheep Shearing Festival was a big deal, with lots of wine and festivities. In 1 Samuel 25, David in the Negev hears about Nabal shearing sheep in Carmel, so he sends and hits him up for a reward for having protected his flocks -- which he had done. Abigail takes a large quantity of food that was prepared for the doings and transports it to David. In 2 Samuel 13, Absalom uses the sheep shearing as a pretext for getting one of his brothers drunk, then having him assassinated.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Itu waktu, Yahuda pung ana bungsu Sela su bésar. Ma Tamar su tau bilang, dia pung papa mantu sonde mau kasi dia kawin deng Sela. Tarús Tamar cari akal ko tuntut dia pung hak. Ju dia buka kasi tenga dia pung pakean janda, ais ganti pake pakean bagus. Dia pake salendang ko tutu dia pung kapala deng dia pung muka. Ais dia pi dudu di kampong Enaim pung pintu maso, pas di jalan pi Timna.<bt>At that time, Yahuda's youngest child Sela was already grown. But Tamar already knew that her father-in-law didn't want to give her to marry with Sela. So.that's why Tamar got an idea to get her right. And she took.off leaving behind her widow clothes, then changed to wear good clothes. She wore a scarf to cover her head and her face. Then she went to sit at Enaim's village entrance, exactly on the road to Timna.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lantas = so that's why"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lantas = so that's why</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatasar (swr hif impf): take off"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vatasar (swr hif impf): take off clothes beged: garments of a particular kind<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʾalmnutah: widowhood meʿaleyah: from her<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vatkhas (ksh piʿel): covered, concealed. Reflexive use of piʿel "to disguise herself" is rare; hitpaʿel is more likely. batsaʿif: in a wrapper, shawl<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>titʿalaf (ʿlf hitp): wrapped herself up, veiled herself bpetach: at the entrance<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>ʿenaim: Enaim, two eyes, two wells; fork in the road? open place, crossroads? village name, Two Waterholes? petach ʿenaim, the opening of the eyes? the entrance to Enaim? ʿal-derek timnatah: overlooking the road to Timnath. Timnath may be a play on "conceal."<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>loʾ-nitnah lo lʾishah (nif): the she was not given to Shelah as his wife. Up to this point Tamar is acted upon; from here she acts on her own.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Waktu Yahuda lewat itu pintu maso kampong, dia dapa lia satu parampuan. Dia kira itu parampuan nakal, tagal Tamar bagaya deng pakean, ais tutu dia pung muka lai.<bt>When Yahuda crossed the village entrance, he saw a woman. He thought it was a bad woman (prostitute), because Tamar was over dressed with her clothes, and also covering her face. [EXEG: Assumed knowledge-you can tell a woman is probably a prostitute by some things she does with her clothing. In this part of the world that is not shared knowledge. Going literal doesn't bring out this important aspect. Something in Tamar's way of dressing made Judah think she was probably a prostitute, and saying “because she covered her face” actually leaves people scratching their heads. What's the connection?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lonte = pelacur ; *** Back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lonte = pelacur ; *** Back Trans fixed (2009)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayachshveah l-: he thought her to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayachshveah l-: he thought her to be a prostitute, considered. see ... conclude zonah: ordinary prostitute, not one associated with a Canaanite temple (v. 21)<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>khistah (ksh piʿel): she concealed, covered</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Yahuda sonde sangka bilang itu parampuan tu, dia pung ana mantu. Jadi dia pi deka-deka itu parampuan, ko tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Kalo beta deng lu, na, lu minta barapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yahuda didn't think that that woman, was his child-in-law. So he went up close to that woman to ask saying, &lt;&lt;We! [+attention] If I'm with you, na, how much do you you ask?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayet (nth): he turned aside from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayet (nth): he turned aside from his road havah-naʾ (hb, yhb impv): give; come on, now. Rashi takes this as an entreaty. But's it propositioning a prostitute: Hey, come on, let's have sex!<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Tamar manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu! Dari pak pung suka sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Tamar answered saying, &lt;&lt;Whatever! Just whatever you want.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neu = OK, terserah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">neu = OK, terserah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Yahuda tawar bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana kalo beta kasi lu kambing satu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yahuda bargained saying, &lt;&lt;How about if I give you a goat?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais Tamar balas bilang, &lt;&lt;Bae, pak. Asal pak kasi beta pegang barang jaminan dolo. Kapan-kapan, baru pak kirim itu kambing datang.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Tamar responded saying, &lt;&lt;Ok, Father. As.long.as you (Father) give me a promise thing to hold first. Until whenever Father sends that goat.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeshalach: I will send gdi ʿizim"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾeshalach: I will send gdi ʿizim (gadah): a kid from the flock (not definite; in verse 20 he's chosen the kid, and it's definite)<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>Alter, The Art of Biblical Narrative, 1981 ʾim-titen (ntn imperf): if you give<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʿeravon: a security, pledge (like leaving your driver's license at the library desk), something you get back when you finish the deal. Alter: like giving her all his major credit cards. ʿad-shalchekha (shlk inf): until you send it<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18-19" />Ju Yahuda tanya lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta kasi lu barang jaminan apa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yahuda asked again saying, &lt;&lt;What promise thing should I give you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tamar manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Pak kasi tenga cap yang ada tagantong, deng dia pung tali di pak pung leher. Deng kasi tenga itu tongkat ju.&gt;&gt; Dengar bagitu, ju Yahuda kasi itu barang dong sang dia.<bt>Tamar answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father leave behind that seal that is hanging, with its rope on Father's neck there. And leave behind that staff also.&gt;&gt; Hearing that then, Yahudi gave that stuff to her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="stempel (old) ~ cap (young)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">stempel (old) ~ cap (young)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chotamkha: your signet ring. Many commentators"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chotamkha: your signet ring. Many commentators take this to be a cylinder seal with a cord going through the axis; but that's more Mesopotamian, for clay tablets, and flat seals were more common in Palestine. ftilekha (patil): the cord you use to tie the ring around your neck, like a modern ID tag or a house key. Targums read it as ʾcloakʾ.<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>matkha (mateh): your walking stick vatahar lo: she became pregnant by him. Providential timing (36 hour period during the month)? or smart planning? Everything else is pretty well worked out in advance.<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais dong dua pi tidor sama-sama. Ais itu, Tamar pulang. Dia buka dia pung pakean bagus deng dia pung salendang, ko pake ulang dia pung pakean janda. Tau-tau te Tamar su dudu parú.<bt>Then they two went to sleep together. After that, Tamar went.home. She took off her good clothes and that scarf of hers, to wear again her widow clothes. It became apparent that Tamar was already pregnant.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsʿifah: the wrapper, veil tilbash: she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsʿifah: the wrapper, veil tilbash: she put on<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Sonde lama, ju Yahuda minta tolong sang dia pung tamán Hira bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu bawa ini kambing kasi itu parampuan nakal di Enaim sana, ko ame kambali beta pung barang yang dia ada pegang.&gt;&gt; Hira pi sampe di sana, dia batanya pi-datang, ma sonde dapa katumu itu parampuan.<bt>Not much longer, Yahuda asked his friend Hira saying, &lt;&lt;You this goat give to that naughty woman at Enaim over.there, in order to get back my things that she is holding.&gt;&gt; Hira went arriving there, he asked all around, but didn't meet that woman.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palacur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">palacur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reʿehu: his friend. Sounds like Judah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">reʿehu: his friend. Sounds like Judah is playing the big man at the shearing party, canʾt be bothered to go look up a prostitute himself.</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ju dia batanya orang-orang di situ bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bosong ada dapa lia itu palacor yang biasa dudu di pintu maso sini, ko? Dia ada di mana, é?&gt;&gt;<bt>So he asked people there saying, &lt;&lt;We! Have you-pl seen that prostitute who usually sits at the village entrance here, [+tag question]? Where is she?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Pak, di sini sonde ada parampuan nakal.&gt;&gt;<bt>But they answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father, here there is no naughty woman.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishʾal: ask maqomah: used more of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishʾal: ask maqomah: used more of towns than of the place along the road where Tamar was sitting. There probably werenʾt people hanging around out there.<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʾayeh: where? haqdeshah: consecrated woman, cult prostitute, shrine prostitute. May be Spec(zonah). One strong idea in the Canaanite religion was that having sex was a way of worshipping the Canaanite gods of fertility, and so there were both male and female prostitutes connected with the centers of worship. The fees paid to them may have supported the centers as well as the prostitutes themselves<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Jadi Hira kambali pi Yahuda. Dia kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta sonde katumu itu parampuan. Beta cari-cari, ma orang di sana kasi tau bilang, di itu tampa sonde ada parampuan nakal.&gt;&gt;<bt>Thus Hira returned to Yahuda. He told saying, &lt;&lt;I could not find that woman. I looked and looked, but people there told saying, at that place there was no naughty woman.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Yahuda manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar kasi tenga itu barang dong, ko dia soa sa! Asal orang jang bekin malu sang kotong! Te beta su mau bayar, ma kotong sonde dapa katumu sang dia na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yahuda answered saying, &lt;&lt;Just leave the stuff then, just let her own it! As.long.as people don't embarass us! Cuz I want to pay, but obviously we cant find her.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pen nihyeh labuz: lest we become"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pen nihyeh labuz: lest we become a laughingstock (many commentators, even Holladay's lexicon). But buz is normally contempt, derision, disgrace. That is more likely here too; Judah's personal prestige could take a nosedive if the word gets around that he welshed on paying a prostitute. So he's not going to push the point any further -- easier to get a new seal.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Lewat tiga bulan, ju orang pi kasi tau sang Yahuda bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pung ana mantu Tamar su bekin diri jadi parampuan nakal. Sakarang dia ada bunting.&gt;&gt;<bt>After three months, people went to tell Yahuda saying, &lt;&lt;That child-in-law of yours Tamar, has made herself a naughty/promiscuous woman. Now she's pregnant.&gt;&gt; [LEX: choice of ‘pregnant’ is course, often used for animals. Reflecting speaker attitude of contempt.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bunting collocates with animals, or course"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bunting collocates with animals, or course situation with humans</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar bagitu, ju Yahuda mara mau mati. Ais dia parenta itu orang bilang, &lt;&lt;Pi hela bawa itu parampuan datang, ko bakar idop-idop sang dia!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, Yahuda was incredibly angry. So he ordered that person saying, &lt;&lt;Go drag bring that woman here, to cook her alive!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chdashim: lunar cycles, months zantah: she"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chdashim: lunar cycles, months zantah: she played the prostitute. The only actual offense here is against Er; Tamar is thought to have had sex with a stranger, rather than with Shelah, who was supposed to perpetuate Er's line. For that matter, Judah is not taking very good care of his own lineage. That's why Tamar comes through as "more righteous".<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>kalatekha: your daughter-in-law hotsiʾuah (ytsʾ hif): produce her, make her come<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>tisaref (nif): she shall be burned up. Two words, short and brutal, no investigation whether the charge is true. Gets Judah off the hook. Stoning was the only option under the Law, but things were not as constrained four centuries earlier.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais dong pi hela bawa sang Tamar. Ma dia kasi kaluar itu cap deng itu tongkat. Ju dia suru dong pi kasi tau dia pung papa mantu bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa, tolong pareksa ini barang dong dolo. Ini cap deng tongkat pung tuan ni yang bekin beta dudu parú.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they went to drag bring Tamar. But she took out that seal, and that staff. And she told them to go tell her father-in-law saying, &lt;&lt;Papa, please inspect these things. The person who owns this seal and staff is the one who made me pregnant.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mutseʾt (hof particpl): as she was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mutseʾt (hof particpl): as she was being led out. Going public was her only protection; if she had taken it up with Jacob privately, he might have killed her quietly. Sounds like she had her contingencies pretty well figured out, since she let it go this far. Since she was under Judah's control, they would have waited for him to come before killing her. shalchah: she sent (word? writing?)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>chamiah: her father-in-law haker-naʾ (nkr hif): investigate as unknown, establish judicially (just as in Chapter 37; now the con that Judah started about Joseph comes back and bites Judah)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>lmi: who do they belong to? hachotemet: seal, chop, signet ring<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Lia itu barang dong, ju Yahuda kanál memang, te itu dia pung. Ais dia kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Memang! Itu parampuan sonde sala. Beta yang sala. Dia yang batúl. Iko adat, na, beta musti kasi kawin dia deng beta pung ana Sela. Ma beta yang sonde mau. Kasi lapás sang dia sa!&gt;&gt; Ais ju Yahuda sonde bakumpul lai deng Tamar.<bt>Seeing that stuff, then Yuhuda straight away knew, that that stuff was his. Then he told saying, &lt;&lt;Correct. That woman is not wrong. I am wrong. She is right. That is why I should have married her with my son Sela. But I'm the one who didn't want to. Let her go!&gt;&gt; After that, Yahuda did not join again with Tamar.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaker (nkr hif): recognized, acknowledged. He"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaker (nkr hif): recognized, acknowledged. He also has to think of the hereditary promises to his lineage. (promises to genes, JR) ki-ʿal-ken: a reason, long in existence, is finally recognized. At the crunch point, Judah digs down deep.<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Tamar pung waktu barana su sampe, ju dia barana ana bagambar.<bt>Tamar time to give birth arrived, and she give birth to twins.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana kambar = ana bagambar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ana kambar = ana bagambar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lidtah (yld inf): for her to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lidtah (yld inf): for her to give birth tʾomim = toʾmim: twins<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>bbitnahh: in her womb</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Waktu dia barana, ana satu kasi kaluar dia pung tangan. Ju ibu bidan ika banáng mera di itu tangan. Dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Ini yang nomer satu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When she gave birth, one child put out his hand. And the midwife tied a red string on that hand. She said, &lt;&lt;This is number one.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tiqach: she took it myaledet (yld"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tiqach: she took it myaledet (yld piʿel partcpl): the one helping her have the baby<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>vatiqshor: tied shani: crimson, scarlet; a vivid dye obtained from eggs of the shield-louse, collected on leaves of oak trees; crimson thread<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>yatsaʾ: came out riʾshonah: the first in a series<span class="Italic">(28)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ma itu ana hela kambali dia pung tangan. Ais dia pung kambár yang kaluar lebe dolo. Ibu bidan bilang sang itu ana, &lt;&lt;We! Lu ni memang kuat, ó! Andia ko lu baseti kaluar lebe dolo!&gt;&gt; Ais dong kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Peres </span>(dia pung arti bilang, &lt;baseti kaluar&gt;).<bt>But that child yanked back his hand. And his twin is the one who came out first. The midwife said of that child, &lt;&lt;We! You are really strong! That's why you fought to come out first!&gt;&gt; Then they named that child, Peres (its meaning 'fight to come out').</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meshiv (shwb hif partcpl): as he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">meshiv (shwb hif partcpl): as he was bringing his hand back in paratsta: you broke out<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Abis, baru dia pung adi yang ada ika banáng mera tu kaluar. Dong kasi nama sang dia, <span class="Italic">Sera </span>(dia pung arti bilang, &lt;mera manyala&gt;).<bt>After that, then his younger sibling who had that red string came out. They named him, Sera (its meaning, 'shiny red').</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mera nao = mera batul/manyala \lf"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">mera nao = mera batul/manyala \lf Max</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zarach: the shining forth of light,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">zarach: the shining forth of light, sunrise, blast of light</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf deng bos Potifar pung bini<bt>Yusuf, and bos Potifar's wife</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="39" />
      <v n="1-2" />Tempo hari, itu orang Ismael dong bawa sang Yusuf pi Masir. Di situ ada orang bésar satu, nama Potifar. Dia tu, kapala dari samua tantara yang bajaga di raja Masir pung ruma jabatan. Ais ju Potifar béli Yusuf dari itu orang dagang dong, ko jadi dia pung budak di dia pung ruma. Di situ, TUHAN tolong sang Yusuf, sampe dia pung karjá samua jadi deng bae.<bt>At that time, those Ismael people brought Yusuf to Masir. There there was a big person, named Potifar. He was head of all the soldiers who guarded the raja Masir's official house. And then, Potifar bought Yusuf from those merchants, in order to be his slave at his house. There, GOD helped Yusuf, to the point that all his work went well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tempo hari = resumptive for interrupted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tempo hari = resumptive for interrupted story; soldadu (going out of use, but in many vernaculars)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hurad (yrd hofʿal): be brought down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hurad (yrd hofʿal): be brought down SəriS: court official, eunuch (not in this case)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>sar: outside Israel, a representative of the king, official, ruler, leader of a group Tabbachim: bodyguards and executioners, slaughterers<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>howriduhuw: they brought him down matsliach (tslch partcpl): successful man<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dia pung bos lia Yusuf pung karjá bagitu bae, ju dia tau batúl TUHAN ada tolong sang Yusuf.<bt>His boss saw Yusuf's work so good like that, then he truly knew that GOD was helping Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yang = compltzer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">yang = compltzer</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Andia ko dia pung bos suka sang Yusuf, deng parcaya sang dia. Tarús dia angka sang Yusuf jadi mandor di dia pung ruma. Dia ju kasi Yusuf urus dia pung ruma deng dia pung pusaka dong samua.<bt>That is why his boss liked Yusuf, and believed in him. Continuing on, he raised Yusuf to be the supervisor in his house. He also gave Yusuf [responsibility] to arrange/manage his house and all his possessions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mandor = supervisor (coordinator, not necessarily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">mandor = supervisor (coordinator, not necessarily planning, etc); pusaka = harta-benda, tanah, milik; kapala urusan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yimtsaʾ: found, got chen: agreeableness, charm,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yimtsaʾ: found, got chen: agreeableness, charm, approval, satisfaction<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ysharet: became an attendant, serve yafqidehu (pqd hif): he appointed him<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Mulai dari Yusuf jadi mandor di situ, Tuhan ju kasi berkat sang dia pung bos, orang Masir tu. Dia pung isi ruma, dia pung pusaka, dia pung kabón, deng dia pung karjá samua jadi deng bae.<bt>Beginning from Yusuf becoming supervisor there, God also blessed his bos, that Masir person. The people and contents of his house, his possessions, his gardens, and all his work went well. [DISCOURSE: Good Hebrew discourse loves heavy repetition and redundancy. Local lgs like tail-head linkage in narrative (more in oral style and less in written style). But here the Heb. “From the time that he made him overseer in his house and over all that he had,” is setting up a reason, not an event sequence, so in our lgs making vs.5 literal on this point makes it very heavy information load and redundant with what is already in vs. 4. It was the team and UNS's that insisted it had to be streamlined for style reasons.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="isi ruma = can include people,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">isi ruma = can include people, but in the context of this list is more understood to be barang ; *** revised (2009)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tagal Yusuf tenga di situ, andia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Tagal Yusuf tenga di situ, andia ko Tuhan ju kasi berkat sang dia pung bos,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifqiyd (pqd hif): he appointed yvarekh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hifqiyd (pqd hif): he appointed yvarekh (brkh piel): bless = declare someone endowed power for success, prosperity, fertility<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>biglal: on account of sadeh: fields<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ais waktu Potifar lia Yusuf urus samua karjá deng bae, andia ko dia sonde pikir apa-apa lai, cuma tau makan sa.<bt>Then when Potifar saw Yusuf arrange all the work so well, that's why he didn't have to think/worry about anything anymore, he only just thought about eating.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ais = \va es"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ais = \va es</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʿazov: he let go məʾuwmah: something|i(6)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaʿazov: he let go məʾuwmah: something<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>loʾ-yadaʿ ʾitto: he did not keep account with him kiy ʾim-hallechem: not even the food<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Itu waktu, Yusuf talalu gaga.<bt>At that time, Yusuf was very handsome.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yafeh: good looking, beautiful toʾar: form,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yafeh: good looking, beautiful toʾar: form, shape (woman, cow, olive tree); for a man, appearance, dignity, impressive<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>marʾeh: nice to look at, appearance</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Dia balóm lama tenga di sana, ma Potifar pung bini su jato hati deng dia. Ju dia kokoe ko Yusuf tidor sama-sama deng dia.<bt>He lived there not very long yet, but Potifar's wife already fell in love with him. And she tried to persuade Yusuf to sleep together.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kokoe = invite/persuade to do s.t."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kokoe = invite/persuade to do s.t. ; kapingin = desire (strong, but tends toward things, wnats him for her slave), mangidam, (like a pregnant woman)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tishshaʾ (nsʾ): lift up her eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tishshaʾ (nsʾ): lift up her eyes at shikhvah: lie down with me, sleep with me<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ma Yusuf sonde mau. Ju dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Jang bagitu, mama! Te beta pung bos Potifar su kasi beta kuasa ko urus dia pung karjá samua.<bt>But Yusuf didn't want to. So he answered saying, &lt;&lt;Don't do like that, Mama! Cuz my boss Potifar has given me authority to arrange/take.care.of all his work.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ymaʾen: he refused hen: 3sg pronoun,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ymaʾen: he refused hen: 3sg pronoun, emphatic here<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Di ini ruma sonde ada orang laen yang pegang kuasa lebe dari beta. Te bos su kasi beta urus samua-samua. Cuma mama sa, yang beta sonde ada hak urus. Karmana ko beta bisa bekin jahat bagitu! Itu ju su malawan Tuhan Allah pung mau!&gt;&gt;<bt>In this house, there is no person who holds more authority than me. Cuz boss has given it to me to take care of everything. Just only not mama. How could I do something evil like that! That also opposes/goes against God's will!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeynenu: nobody loʾ-chasakh: and he does"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾeynenu: nobody loʾ-chasakh: and he does not hold back<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>ʾeykh: how? chaTaʾti leʾəlohiym: I do something morally wrong against God<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00716c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Potifar pung bini maen kokoe sang Yusuf<bt>Potifar's wife likes to flirt at Yusuf</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Biar bagitu, ma tiap hari itu bos pung bini maen kokoe tarús sa. Ma Yusuf sonde toe sang dia.<bt>Even though (he spoke) like that, nevertheless every day that boss' wife would kept trying to persuade/coax/cajole him. But Yusuf didn't pay attention to her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saban hari = stok lama; deng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">saban hari = stok lama; deng more reciprocal; sang more unidirectional</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾetslah: by her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾetslah: by her</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ais satu kali, ju Yusuf maso pi dalam ruma, ko mau lia dia pung karjá. Itu hari, sonde ada orang laen dalam ruma.<bt>And so one time, Yusuf entered the house, to see/take.care.of his work. That day, there were no other people in the house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** paragraph added, Dhao check Sept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** paragraph added, Dhao check Sept 2004</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mlaʾkhto: his business"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mlaʾkhto: his business</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ju dia pung bos pung bini datang ko pegang Yusuf pung baju, tarús hela ame sang dia, ju bilang, &lt;&lt;Mari suda! Sakarang tenga kotong dua sandiri sa. Mari su, kotong dua pi tidor.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then his boss' wife came to hold Yusuf's shirt, and then pull at him, and saying, &lt;&lt;Come on! Now it's only us two alone. Come on lets the two of us go sleep.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Yusuf sonde mau. Ais dia marontak, sampe dia pung baju talapás. Ju dia lari kaluar. Ma itu parampuan masi pegang tarús itu baju.<bt>But Yusuf didn't want. Then he struggled, to the point that his shirt was free. And he ran outside. But that woman was still holding his shirt.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marontak ; siri = menghelakan diri,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">marontak ; siri = menghelakan diri, avoid stone, spear;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="titpsehu: she took hold of (thing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">titpsehu: she took hold of (thing or person) bbigdo: by his clothes (any kind of clothes)<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>yanaS (nwS): he fled hachutsah: outside<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Waktu Potifar pung bini lia Yusuf su lari kaluar kasi tenga dia pung baju,<bt>When Potifar's wife saw that Yusuf had run outside leaving his shirt,</bt><v n="14-15" />ju dia pange orang karjá dong, ko kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bosong mari lia dolo! Tadi, itu laki-laki Ibrani tu maso beta pung kamar. Dia mau bekin jahat sang beta, ma beta batarea karás-karás. Ini, dia kasi tenga dia pung baju, ais dia lari kaluar. Beta pung laki ni, dia bawa ini orang biadab ko bekin malu-malu sang kotong sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>then she called the workers, to tell saying, &lt;&lt;We! You-pl look! Just now, that male Hebrew there, entered my room. He wanted to do evil with me, but I screamed loudly. This, he lefted behind his shirt, and he ran outside. This husband of mine, he has brought this uncouth person here just to make us ashamed!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="orang biadab = kurang ajar dong,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">orang biadab = kurang ajar dong, sas ka tewa adat; manangis cina = paid mourners; opseter = mandor</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsacheq (piʿel inf): to mock us"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsacheq (piʿel inf): to mock us həriymotiy (rwm hif): I raised my voice<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00720c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around:horizontalPosition:left">Potifar pung bini kasi tunju Yusuf pung baju<bt>Potifar's wife shows Yusuf's clothes</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ju Potifar pung bini pegang itu baju sampe dia pung laki pulang.<bt>And Potifar's wife held that shirt until her husband came home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tannach (nwch hif): she laid it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tannach (nwch hif): she laid it down</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Pas dia pung laki pulang, ju dia carita bilang, &lt;&lt;Bu, é! Itu orang Ibrani yang bu bawa di sini tu, tadi dia su maso di beta pung kamar, ko mau parkosa sang beta!<bt>Just when her husband came home, she told him saying, &lt;&lt;Elder brother [term of address of wife to husband]! That Ibrani person that Elder Brother brought here, earlier he entered my room, in order to rape me!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parkosa = nae (special sense, coarse)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">parkosa = nae (special sense, coarse)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ltsakheq: to play around, fondle, amuse"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ltsakheq: to play around, fondle, amuse himself, insult[?]</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ma beta batarea karás-karás ko pange orang dong. Ais dia lari fuik, kasi tenga dia pung baju ni.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I yelled loudly calling people. Then he ran wildly, leaving this shirt of his.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bangun odar = flee non-ordered; fuik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bangun odar = flee non-ordered; fuik = liar (Rote, Tetun), bangun lari sampe ilang; ro'o kaluar = shake</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kahəriymiy (rwm hif): in lifting up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kahəriymiy (rwm hif): in lifting up my voice</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Dengar dia pung bini carita bagitu, ju Potifar mara mau mati.<bt>Hearing his wife's story like that, then Potifar was extremely angry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maruak = marah, ngomel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">maruak = marah, ngomel</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yichar ʾappo: he got hot in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yichar ʾappo: he got hot in his anger</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Tarús dia suru orang dong pi tangkap sang Yusuf. Ju dong kasi maso sang dia pi dalam raja pung bui.<bt>Next he ordered people to go capture Yusuf. And they put him in the raja's jail.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sohar: prison (Pidgin usually says &quot;jail&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Sohar: prison (Pidgin usually says "jail" unless youʾre a prisoner. ʾSwry: the ones bound. qereʾ ʾəSiyrey: prisoners of<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>ʾəSuwriym: the ones bound</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ma TUHAN sonde lupa sang Yusuf. Andia ko, TUHAN tolong tarús sang dia, sampe itu bui pung bos ju talalu suka sang Yusuf.<bt>But GOD did not forget Yusuf. That.is.why, GOD continued helping him, until that jail's boss also liked Yusuf very much.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeT (nTh): extended (protection) khased: obligation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeT (nTh): extended (protection) khased: obligation to the community based on a close relationship, faithfulness, loyalty; leads to protection; or extraordinary kindness even when he didnʾt have to<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>chinno: his favor, his kindly attitude</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ais dia parcaya sang Yusuf. Andia ko dia kasi ofer Yusuf urus orang bui dong samua, deng urus samua karjá di situ.<bt>Then he trusted Yusuf. That's why, he delegated to Yusuf to take care of all the jail people, and take.care of all the work there.</bt><v n="23" />Jadi bos su sonde pusing urus apa-apa lai di itu bui. TUHAN tolong tarús sang Yusuf, andia ko samua karjá di itu bui jadi bae.<bt>Because of that, the boss didn't need to worry about anything in that jail anymore. GOD continued helping Yusuf, that's.why all the work in that jail went very well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ofer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ofer</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsliyach (tslch hif partcpl): the one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">matsliyach (tslch hif partcpl): the one causing him to prosper, making him a success End of S section.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf kasi tau dua orang bui pung mimpi pung arti<bt>Yusuf tells the meaning of two jail people's dreams</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="40" />
      <v n="1-3" />Dalam itu bui, ada dua orang yang parná jadi kapala urusan di raja Masir pung ruma jabatan. Yang satu urus raja pung minum. Yang satu lai urus raja pung roti. Dong dua ada bekin tasala sang raja. Andia ko raja mara, sampe dia kasi maso sang dong pi dalam bui. Jadi dong dua tenga satu tampa deng Yusuf.<bt>In that jail there were also two people who had once been head coordinators of the raja Masir's official house. The one, coordinated the raja's drink. The other one, coordinated the raja's bread. Both of them had done wrong to the raja. That's why the raja got angry, to the point that he entered them inside the jail. So they two were staying in one place with Yusuf. [EXEG: Here I think the NET Bible has overtranslated a simple Hebrew phrase, not looked at the higher level discourse, and in doing so skewed the focus and become misleading. TH characterises this as a vague timeframe “one day”, seeming to shift the story down the pike, but really introducing new participants into the discourse “The transition expression does not refer to a particular event in verses 20-23 but to that report in general…. we may translate, for example, “After some time,” “A while later,” “Time went on and then one day,” or “One day.”” Bridging vs.1-3 indicates we've reworked these to get the foreground-background discourse info right. I can see why you you might think the KM and Rikou have them already in prison with Joseph, but they are actually worded neutrally. (Barbara also doesn't see the current rendering as making any claims about order.) The end of 1-3 explains basically “That's the background of how they came to be in the same place together with Joseph.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Yang satu itu = baker (bakar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Yang satu itu = baker (bakar roti, kue, kokis); tunju muka = show your face, i.e. fulfill social obligation; sese maso = stuff in. *** Dhao check "who had once been" ; *** note added (2009)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chaTəʾu: miss, be at fault, offend"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chaTəʾu: miss, be at fault, offend in matters of morals, sin against somebody mashqeh: cupbearer<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>haʾofeh (partcpl): the one baking, the baker yiqtsof: he got angry<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>SariSayw: his court officials sar: head person<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>vayyitten (ntn impf): he put mishmar: guarding<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>Sohar: prison ʾaSuwr (ʾSr partcpl pass): was bound<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ais, itu kapala bui parenta sang Yusuf ko urus itu dua pagawe. Dong tenga di situ sampe satu-dua taon.<bt>Then, that jail head ordered Yusuf to take/care of those two servants. They stayed there a couple of years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sipir bui = warden (BI);"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sipir bui = warden (BI);</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yifqod: he commissioned, appointed, implies he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yifqod: he commissioned, appointed, implies he noticed Joseph and sought him out for this job yəsharet (piʿel): he was an attendant to them, served them<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Satu malam, itu dua pagawe mimpi. Satu-satu deng dia pung mimpi sandiri-sandiri. Deng itu mimpi dong pung arti ju laen-laen.<bt>One night, those two servants dreams. Each one with his own dream. And those dreams' meanings were also different.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyakhalmu khlom: they had dreams fitron:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyakhalmu khlom: they had dreams fitron: in the interpretation<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Dia pung beso, Yusuf datang, dapa lia dong dua muka susa.<bt>The next day, Yusuf came, saw their two faces in distress.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="muka murung (BI) = layu-layu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">muka murung (BI) = layu-layu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zoʿəfim: looked like a mess, wretched,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">zoʿəfim: looked like a mess, wretched, pitiful, ejected, embittered</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ju dia tanya sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko ini hari, bosong pung muka tar enak bagitu?&gt;&gt;<bt>And he asked them saying, &lt;&lt;Why today, are your-pl faces not looking good like that?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="wayyishʾal: he asked them madduaʿ: why?|i(7)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">wayyishʾal: he asked them madduaʿ: why?<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>pneykhem raʿim: bad faces, out of sorts, feeling lousy, discontented</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ju dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Tadi malam botong ada mimpi, ma botong sonde tau dia pung arti.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they answered saying, &lt;&lt;Last night we dreamed, but we don't know it's meaning.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: ALT: /ma sonde ada yang bisa kasi tau itu mimpi dong pung arti./]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais Yusuf omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde ada satu manusia yang tau mimpi pung arti, cuma Tuhan Allah sa. Coba bosong carita dolo. Nanti beta cari tau dia pung arti dong dari Tuhan.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf spoke saying, &lt;&lt;There is no human who knows the meaning of dreams, only just the Lord God. You go ahead and tell me. Later I will seek the meaning from God.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="foter: one who can tell what"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">foter: one who can tell what they mean</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais itu, orang yang urus raja pung minum, carita bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini. Dalam beta pung mimpi, beta dapa lia satu pohon anggor,<bt>After that, the person who takes.care/coordinates the raja's drink, storied saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. In my dream, I saw an anggor tree,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gefen: vine, creeping plant, grape vine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gefen: vine, creeping plant, grape vine</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />bacabang tiga. Itu pohon langsung badaon, babunga, deng babua barangke-rangke sampe masak.<bt>with three branches. The tree straight away had leaves, had flowers, and had clusters of fruit until they were ripe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rangke = cluster of fruit like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">rangke = cluster of fruit like pinang,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarigim: branches of the grape vine."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">sarigim: branches of the grape vine. SK has grown grapes, but they turned out kind of sour. There are vineyards on Maui, in Ulupalakua, and there used to be some on Oʿahu, where Vineyard Street now runs through downtown Honolulu. kforakhat: budding<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʿaltah nitstsah: its blossoms came up hivshilu (bshl hif): they ripened<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʾashkloteha: its clusters ʿanavim: grapes<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ais beta lia, beta ada pegang raja pung galás minum. Ju beta ame itu bua anggor ko parés pi dalam raja pung galás. Ais itu, beta sorong kasi sang raja ko minum.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I saw, I was holding the raja's drinking glass. And I took those grapes' fruit to squeeze into the raja's glass. After that, I passed it to give to the king to drink.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pares = squeeze"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pares = squeeze</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kowS: cup, wine cup ʾeqqakh (lqkh):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kowS: cup, wine cup ʾeqqakh (lqkh): I took, grabbed hold, acquired<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʾeschaT: I squeezed kaf: palm, outstretched hand, open hand<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Dengar bagitu, ju Yusuf kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa. Itu mimpi pung arti bagini: itu cabang tiga pung arti, andia tiga hari.<bt>Hearing that then, Yusuf told saying, &lt;&lt;Father. That dream's meaning is like this: those three branches there, the meaning three days.</bt><v n="13" />Dalam tiga hari ni, nanti raja kasi kaluar sang bapa dari bui. Ais dia angka kambali sang bapa, ko urus ulang dia pung minum sama ke dolu.<bt>In these next three days, later the raja will take father out of this jail. Then he will raise you again, to coordinate again his drink like before.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nanti is surer than mau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">nanti is surer than mau</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yissaʾ roʾshekha (nsʾ): lift your head,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yissaʾ roʾshekha (nsʾ): lift your head, raise high, pardon, accept kindly, be favorable to həshivkha (shwv hif): he will bring back, see that you get back, restore to office<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>kannekha: your place</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Kalo bapa pung nasib su bae bagitu, na, jang lupa sang beta, ó! Kalo bapa sayang sang beta, na, tolong kasi tau sang raja, ko dia ju kasi kaluar sang beta dari sini.<bt>If father's fate happens good like that, don't forget me, ok? If father loves me here, please tell the raja, so that he will also take me out of this place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dapa barkat bagitu ATAU idop babae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">dapa barkat bagitu ATAU idop babae di sana</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khased: obligation to the community, solidarity,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">khased: obligation to the community, solidarity, loyalty, faithfulness, kindness, grace hotseʾtani (ytsʾ hif): and you will cause me to go out<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ko kalo iko dia pung batúl, dong ame paksa sang beta dari orang Ibrani dong pung kampong. Di sini, beta sonde bekin jahat apa-apa. Ma tau-tau, te dong su kasi maso sang beta di bui, sama ke beta ni, orang jahat sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>In order to go according to what is true, they took me by force from Ibrani people's village. And here also, I have not done anything evil at all. But wouldn't you know it, cuz they have entered me in this jail here as if I here, were just an evil person.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gunnov gunnavti: I have been stolen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gunnov gunnavti: I have been stolen away məʾuwmah: something<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>samu (sym): they put me bor: cistern as in 37, dungeon<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Dengar ame itu mimpi pung arti yang bagus bagitu, ju itu orang yang urus roti carita sang Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Adi, é. Beta ju mimpi bagini: beta ada su'u bakul tiga susun.<bt>Hearing that dream's meaning that was so good like that, that person who coordinates the bread storied to Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Younger brother. I also dreamed like this: I was head-carrying baskets three layers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="su'u = head carry; sapai ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">su'u = head carry; sapai = isi jagung karanjang cocok untuk bawah kokis di atas kapala?<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Salley: baskets of choriy: cake, fancy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Salley: baskets of choriy: cake, fancy bread<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Di bakul paling atas, ada isi raja pung kue macam-macam. Ma burung dong datang ko toto bekin abis itu kue dong dari atas beta pung kapala.&gt;&gt;<bt>In the basket on top, were all sorts of the raja's cakes. But birds came to eat making all gone those cakes from on top my head.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿelyown: the top one, upper one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿelyown: the top one, upper one (also used of God, da one dat stay ova all da odda gods). Da Numba One God?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dengar bagitu, ju Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa pung mimpi pung arti bagini: itu bakul tiga pung arti, tiga hari ju.<bt>Hearing that then, Yusuf answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father's dream's meaning is like this: Those three baskets there, the meaning is also three days.</bt><v n="19" />Dalam tempo tiga hari ni, nanti raja suru orang datang potong buang bapa pung kapala. Ais dong gantong bapa pung badan di tiang. Ju burung dong datang toto bekin abis bapa pung daging.&gt;&gt;<bt>In three days from now, later the raja will order people to come cut dispose of father's head. Then they will hang father's body on a pole. And the birds will come eating making all gone father's flesh/meat.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="talah: he will hang ʿets: tree,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">talah: he will hang ʿets: tree, piece of wood, pole<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Lewat tiga hari, pas deng raja pung hari jadi, ju dia bekin pesta bésar kasi dia pung pagawe samua. Dia parenta ko dong pi kasi kaluar itu dua pagawe dari bui.<bt>After three days, exactly the raja's birthday, and he made a big feast for all his servants. He ordered that they go take out those two servants from jail.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pegawe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pegawe</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yom hulledet (yld qal pass inf):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yom hulledet (yld qal pass inf): birthday mishteh: drinking party, feast<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ais itu, dia angka kambali itu pagawe yang urus raja pung minum, pi dia pung pangkat yang dolu, ko dia urus ulang raja pung minum.<bt>After that, he appointed again that servant who coordinated the raja's drink, back to his former rank, to coordinate again the raja's drink.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ma itu pagawe yang urus raja pung roti tu, dong gantong bekin mati sang dia, parsís ke yang Yusuf su omong.<bt>But that servant who coordinated the raja's bread there, they hung killing him, exactly like Yusuf said.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="{hanged the baker}"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">{hanged the baker}</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ma itu pagawe yang urus minum tu, sonde inga lai sang Yusuf. Te dia su lupa buang sang Yusuf.<bt>But that servant who coordinated drinks there, didn't remember Yusuf anymore. He forgot disposing (completely) of him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf kasi tau raja Masir pung mimpi pung arti<bt>Yusuf tells the meaning of raja Masir's dream</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="41" />
      <v n="1" />Lewat dua taon, ju raja Masir dapa mimpi. Dia mimpi, dia ada badiri di kali Nil pung pinggir.<bt>After two years then, raja Masir got a dream. He dreamed, he was standing at the Nil river's edge.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqqets shnatayim yamim: after two years"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miqqets shnatayim yamim: after two years cholem: dreamed (as background to events)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʿomed: was standing (background) yʾor: large river, the Nile River<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Takuju, dia dapa lia tuju sapi gumu-gumuk. Dong pung kulit mangkilat. Dong kaluar dari itu kali, ko makan rumput di situ.<bt>Unexpectedly, he happened to see seven really fat cows. Their skin shone. They came out of that river to eat grass there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gumuk-gumuk = fat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">gumuk-gumuk = fat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿolot: they were coming up (background)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿolot: they were coming up (background) parot: cows<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>yəfot: beautiful, right marʾeh (rʾh): (beautiful) in appearance<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>briʾot basar: fat in flesh; well fed, fat looking cattle tirʿeynah (rʿh impf): grazing<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>baʾachu: in among the reed-land. Possibly an Egyptian word for papyrus or another plant that grows by the Nile, Butomus umbellatus (UBS 125-126), reed grass or reed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00022c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais ju ada tuju sapi laen lai kaluar dari itu kali. Dong pung badan kurus karempeng. Dong badiri deka-deka deng itu sapi gumuk dong.<bt>And then, there were seven other cows, came out of that river. Their bodies were extremely skinny (see bones). They stood close to those seven fat cows.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kurus karing ; kurus karempeng; karempeng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kurus karing ; kurus karempeng; karempeng = see bones</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾakherot: other raʿot marʾeh: ugly in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾakherot: other raʿot marʾeh: ugly in appearance, just the opposite of the others<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>daqqot basar: scanty of meat, skinny taʿmodnah: they were standing<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʾetsel: beside ʿal-sfat: on the bank of the river, edge<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ais, itu tuju sapi kurus dong kodo ame itu tuju sapi gumuk dong. Ju raja takuju bangun.<bt>Then, those seven thin cows swallowed up those seven fat cows. Then the raja woke up startled.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kodo = telan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kodo = telan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʾkhalnah: eat up, swallow down yiyqats:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">toʾkhalnah: eat up, swallow down yiyqats: wake up (intrans)<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Sonde lama lai, dia sonu ulang. Ju dia mimpi lai. Dia lia tuju buler padi yang ba'isi kaluar dari satu batang yang subur.<bt>Not long after that, he went to sleep again. And he dreamed again. He saw seven stalks of padi that had lots of grain come out of one stem/root that was fertile.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiyshan: he fell asleep shibbəlim: ears"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiyshan: he fell asleep shibbəlim: ears of wheat, the spiky clusters that grow on top of the grass-like wheat stalk. The Egyptian variety produced three to seven spikes of wheat. The ones in the dream were healthy and big, heavy enough with ripe grain to make the stalk bend some<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>ʿolot (participle): growing up, coming up qaneh: stalk, main support<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>briʾot: the ears of wheat were fat and healthy, just like the cattle</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ais dia dapa lia lai tuju buler padi yang kosong, su mamalek kaná angin panas.<bt>Then he could see again, seven stalks of padi that were empty, already withered, having been affected by hot wind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mamalek = layu;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">mamalek = layu;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="daqqot: meager, skinny, stalks where the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">daqqot: meager, skinny, stalks where the wheat berries had not developed or were too small and dry to bother with, no nutritional value shəduwfot: scorched by the east wind from the Sinai, too hot and dry to grow<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>qadim: east side, east wind tsomchot: sprouting<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ju samua buler padi yang kosong tu, kodo ame itu tuju buler padi yang ba'isi. Ais ju raja tabangun. Baru dia tau, dia su mimpi lai.<bt>And all those empty padi stalks swallowed up thos seven fruitful padi stalks. And then, the raja woke up. Only then he knew, he had dreamed again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tivlaʿnah: they gulped down, swallowed whole"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tivlaʿnah: they gulped down, swallowed whole (used of the whale swallowing Jonah) məleʾot: full -- all the nutrition they could possibly hold<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>yiqats: came to an end, ended the night = woke up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Dia pung pagi, ju raja rasa tar enak. Ju dia parenta orang dong pi pange ame samua dukun deng orang pintar di Masir. Ais dia carita dia pung mimpi sang dong, ma sonde ada yang bisa kasi tau itu mimpi pung arti.<bt>That morning then, the rasa did feel good (psycologically). So he order people to go call all the healers/seers (dukun) and wise people (orang pintar) in Masir. Then he told them his dream, but there was not anyone who could tell that dream's meaning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dukun = divination??, (UNS) pake ilmu;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">dukun = divination??, (UNS) pake ilmu; orang pintar = 1) wise, learned men, 2) seer</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tippaʿem rucho (nif): he was disturbed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tippaʿem rucho (nif): he was disturbed in his spirit, the natural spirit every person has that means he or she is alive vayishlakh: he sent a message<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>charTummey: soothsayer-priests of Egypt, they led the worship of the gods and they recognized signs of the future chakhameha: (the landʾs) wise men, skilled in wisdom<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yəSapper (piʿel): he recounted, told the story powter (partcpl): explainer of dreams<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00723c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Pagawe yang urus raja pung minum omong deng raja<bt>Official that handles the king's drink speaks to the king</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais, itu pagawe yang urus raja pung minum tu, baru dapa inga sang Yusuf. Ju dia pi kasi tau sang raja bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuan raja. Beta musti mangaku sala.<bt>Then that civil.servant who coordinated the raja drink there, only then remembered Yusuf. And he went to tell the raja saying, &lt;&lt;Mr. Raja. I must confess a wrong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chətaʾay: my fault mazkir (zkr hif"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chətaʾay: my fault mazkir (zkr hif participle): in mentioning, remembering<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Dolu, waktu bapa mara sang beta deng beta pung tamán, ko kasi maso di bui,<bt>Before, when you (father) was angry at me, and my friend, so put us in jail,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qatsaf: get angry with somebody ʾofiym:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qatsaf: get angry with somebody ʾofiym: bakers<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />satu malam ju botong dua mimpi. Satu-satu deng dia pung mimpi, deng dia pung arti laen-laen.<bt>one night then, we two dreamed. Each one with his dream, and different meanings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kfitron: in interpretation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kfitron: in interpretation</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Dalam itu bui ju ada satu orang Ibrani yang masi muda. Dia parná jadi raja pung komandán jaga pung budak. Botong carita botong pung mimpi sang dia. Ju dia kasi tau itu mimpi dong pung arti.<bt>In that jail there was also a Ibrani person who was still young. He had once been the king's commander of the guard's slave. We told our dreams to him. And he told those dreams' meaning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾish: each one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾish: each one</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Andia ko tuan raja angka ulang sang beta. Ma beta pung tamán kaná hukum mati. Jadi samua tu, parsís sama ke itu orang Ibrani pung omong!&gt;&gt;<bt>That's why mr. raja promoted me again. But that friend of mine, was given a death sentence. So all that, was exactly like that Ibrani person said!&gt;&gt; [EXEG (connector): This is the tension we all face in Back Translation. Most consultants want us to always gloss our connectors the same in all occurrences, but then in cases like this, the English gloss doesn't really fit the context. This particular connector can range from a strong causal relationship all the way to a weak “I see a connection between these two parts.” In this context I would see the Rikou /Huu ria na,/ could be / should be read in a weaker sort of “That's why (we weren't surprised when)…” “That's why (I'm bringing this up, because…)” This same type of connector occurs in the context of “X happened. That's why the prophet YY said…” Other candidates actually imply “so (consequently)” which is asserting a much stronger causal link. The problem with taking this to the UNS's is how it is put to them-they will tend to overanalyze it. If a strong reading is sought they can find it even though it's not required. But see if they can come up with a better option. Having no connector here wouldn't work.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="talah: he hanged"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">talah: he hanged</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Dengar bagitu, ju raja suru orang capát-capát pi ame Yusuf dari bui. Ais ju Yusuf pi barias barisi-barisi, deng ganti pakean, ko pi mangada sang raja.<bt>Hearing that then, that raja ordered people to quickly go get Yusuf from jail. And then Yusuf when to take.bath/shave, and change clothes, to go stand.before the raja. [NOTE to daughter translations: the fact that the Heb specifically says ‘shave’ is seen by some as evidence of this being a genuine historical document recorded by a culturally Hebrew person. They never shaved. Egyptians always did. It would be noticed by a Hebrew person that Joseph had to do so before he could go to Pharaoh. Make sure your equivalent of /barias barisi-barisi/ would include shaving.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barias = menghiasi diri, bersihkan, cuci"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">barias = menghiasi diri, bersihkan, cuci rambut (prepare body)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəriytsuhuw (rwts hif): they ran and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yəriytsuhuw (rwts hif): they ran and brought him ygallach: he shaved<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>yəchallef (piʿel): he changed simlotayw: mantle and under-wrapper<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Dia sampe, ju raja omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Nyong, é! Beta ada mimpi, ma sonde ada satu orang ju yang bisa kasi tau itu mimpi pung arti. Ma ada orang kasi tau sang beta bilang, lu bisa.&gt;&gt;<bt>He arrived, then the raja said saying, &lt;&lt;Young boy! I dreamed, but there is no one person who can tell me that dream's meaning. But a person told me that you can.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shamaʿti: I have heard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shamaʿti: I have heard</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ju Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuan raja. Beta ju sonde tau apa-apa. Cuma Tuhan Allah sa yang bisa kasi tau deng batúl itu mimpi pung arti. Tantu Dia mau kasi tau hal yang bae sang tuan raja.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf answered saying, &lt;&lt;Mr raja. I don't know anything. Only just the Lord God who can really tell that dream's meaning. He surely will make known something good to Mr. king.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bilʿaday: except for, with extension &quot;I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bilʿaday: except for, with extension "I am not involved" yaʿneh (ʿnh nif): be provided with an answer<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais ju raja carita bilang, &lt;&lt;Dalam beta pung mimpi tu, beta ada badiri di kali Nil pung pinggir.<bt>And then, the raja storied saying, &lt;&lt; In that dream of mine, I was standing on the Nil river's edge.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sfat: bank of river, lip, edge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">sfat: bank of river, lip, edge yʾor: major river, flowing all the time<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ju ada tuju sapi gumu-gumuk deng dong pung kulit mangkilat. Dong kaluar dari kali, tarús dong pi makan rumput di kali pung pinggir.<bt>And there were seven really fat cows with their skin shining. The came.out of that river, and.then they went to eat grass on that river's edge.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vifot toʾar: beautiful in form, nice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vifot toʾar: beautiful in form, nice appearance tirʿenah (rʿh): grazed, pastured<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ais ju ada tuju sapi laen lai yang datang. Ma itu sapi dong kurus karempeng. Di tana Masir ni, beta balóm parná lia sapi kurus macam bagitu!<bt>And then there were seven other cows who came. But those cows were skinny to the bone. In this land of Masir, I have never seen a cow as skinny as that!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dallot: scrawny, skinny raʿot toʾar: bad,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">dallot: scrawny, skinny raʿot toʾar: bad, ugly in appearance<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>raqqot basar: thin, lank in their meat roaʿ: bad quality (laughed)<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ma beta heran! Te takuju sa, itu tuju sapi yang kurus tu, kodo abis itu tuju sapi gumu-gumuk.<bt>But I was so amazed! Because totally unexpectedly, those seven cows that were thin, swallowed completely those seven really fat cows. [DISCOURSE -- High level context (speaker attitude): The tone for pharaoh's confusion and desperation is set in vs. 8, and made explicit in the language of vs. 19 and vs. 21 (which bring out the unique, unexpected, and counter-intuitive events-if one expected anything like cows eating cows it would be (20) the fat cows eat the skinny cows, or (21) after eating the skinny cows get fat and shiny, but they don't!).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Dong kodo abis, ma itu sapi dong kurus tarús. Ais ju beta takuju bangun.<bt>They finished swallowing, but those cows continued to be skinny. And then I woke up startled.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tavoʾnah: they entered ʾel-qirbenah: the inner"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tavoʾnah: they entered ʾel-qirbenah: the inner part of their body<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>nowdaʿ (ydʿ nif): become known marʾehen: their appearance<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>batəchillah: at the beginning</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais itu, beta sonu lai, ju beta mimpi ulang. Beta lia ada tuju buler padi yang ba'isi, kaluar dari satu batang yang subur.<bt>After that, I slept again, and I dreamed again. I saw there were seven stalks of padi that were full of grain, coming out of one stem/root that was fertile.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaʾereʾ (rʾh): I saw qaneh: one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaʾereʾ (rʾh): I saw qaneh: one stalk<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>mleʾot: full of grain</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ais beta dapa lia lai tuju buler padi yang kosong, su mamalek kaná angin panas.<bt>Then I was able to see again, seven stalks of padi that were empty, withered, affected by hot wind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsənumot: hard, barren daqqot: scanty, used"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsənumot: hard, barren daqqot: scanty, used of hairs an beards of grain<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>shədufot: scorched by the wind tsomkhot: in sprouting<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ju samua buler padi yang kosong tu, kodo ame itu tuju buler padi yang ba'isi. Ais itu beta tabangun. Ju beta carita itu mimpi di orang pintar dong. Ma sonde ada satu orang yang bisa kasi tau dia pung arti.&gt;&gt;<bt>And all those empty stalks, swallowed those seven padi stalks that were full of grain. After that I woke up. And, I told that dream to the wise people. But there was not one person who could tell its meaning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tivlaʿəna: they swallowed up charTummiym: soothsayer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tivlaʿəna: they swallowed up charTummiym: soothsayer priests (v. 8)<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>maggid li (ngd participle): putting forward an opinion, solution, explanation</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00727c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf kasi tau raja pung mimpi pung arti<bt>Yusuf explains the meaning of the raja's dream</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais Yusuf kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuan raja. Itu dua mimpi pung arti, cuma satu sa. Tuhan Allah su kasi tau memang sang tuan raja apa yang Dia mau bekin.<bt>Then Yusuf told saying, &lt;&lt;Mr. raja. Those two dream have just one meaning. The Lord God has foretold mr raja, what He wants to do.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higgid (ngd hif): announce, tell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">higgid (ngd hif): announce, tell</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Itu mimpi pung arti bagini: itu tuju sapi gumu-gumuk dong, deng tuju buler padi ba'isi tu, andia musim kinyang tuju taon. Dong pung arti satu sa.<bt>Those dreams' meaning is like this: those seven really fat cows, and those seven stalks of padi full of grain, those are seven years of plentiful/satisfied(enough to eat) seasons. Their meaning is just one.</bt><v n="27" />Ais, itu tuju sapi yang kurus karempeng, deng itu tuju buler padi yang kosong tu, andia musim lapar tuju taon.<bt>Then, those seven skinny to the bones cows, and those seven empty stalks of padi, those are seven years of hungry seasons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʿav: famine, hunger"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raʿav: famine, hunger</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Jadi Tuhan Allah su kasi tau memang apa yang Dia mau bekin. Itu sama ke beta su omong tadi.<bt>So (consequently) Lord God has foretold what He wants to do. That is like I said earlier.</bt><v n="29" />Nanti kotong dapa musim kinyang sampe tuju taon di samua tampa di negrí Masir.<bt>Later we will get plentiful seasons until seven years in all the places in this country of Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katong dapa 7 taon kinyang ATAU"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">katong dapa 7 taon kinyang ATAU 7 taon kinyang datang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="savaʿ: be satiated, have plenty to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">savaʿ: be satiated, have plenty to eat</Message></Annotation><v n="30-31" />Ais itu, baru kotong dapa musim lapar sampe tuju taon. Nanti itu musim lapar hebat mati pung! Sampe sonde ada makanan lai di ini negrí. Samua orang lapar mau mati, sampe dong sonde bisa inga lai itu musim kinyang.<bt>After that, then we will get hungry season until seven years. Later those hungry seasons will be very intense. To the point that there will be no more food in this country. All people will be extremely hungry, to the point that they can't remember anymore those plentiful seasons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nishkach (nif): be forgotten killah (klh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nishkach (nif): be forgotten killah (klh piʿel): complete, finish; prepare; come to an end, cease; consume, waste; destroy; make to pine away<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>yiwwadaʿ (ydʿ nif): be known savaʿ: plenty<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Naa! Tuan raja dapa mimpi sampe dua kali tu, dia pung arti bilang, Tuhan Allah su ator memang. Sonde lama lai, te apa yang Dia ator tu, su mulai jadi.<bt>So! Mr raja getting those dreams twice, it's meaning is, the Lord God has already arranged it. Not much longer, cuz that which He has arranged, it will begin to happen.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshanot (shnh nif inf): be repeated"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hishshanot (shnh nif inf): be repeated paʿmayim (dual): two times<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>nakhon (kon nif): stable, secure, decided, agreed upon, reliable məmaher (piʿel participle): is hurrying<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Tagal itu, beta usul bagini: lebe bae tuan raja cari satu orang yang pintar, yang bisa urus deng bae. Ais angka sang dia ko ator bae-bae ini negrí.<bt>Because of that, I suggest like this: it's best that mr raja seek a wise person, who can coordinate things well. Then promote him to make good arrangements for this country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʿattah: introducing a new thought or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʿattah: introducing a new thought or section, now yereʾ (rʾh jus): let him look for, pick<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>navon (byn nif): be perceptive chakham: skilled, experienced, wise man (41:8)<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>yəshitehu (shyt): set him, appoint him; implies giving him the authority to act</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Waktu musim kinyang tuju taon tu, lebe bae tuan raja ju angka orang laen lai, ko dong kumpul hasil lebe. Itu hasil, dong bagi lima ko simpan satu bagian.<bt>When those plentiful seasons seven years, it's best mr raja also promote other people, for them to gather in extra harvest. That harvest, they divide by five to save one part. [NOTE: the “extra harvest” refers to “more than normal harvest because they are years of (extra) plenty”. This has tested fairly consistently with UNSs. In the last clause of the BT “in order to” I assume is B trying to consistently reflect the gloss of a certain irrealis (purpose) complementizer. But a more dynamic gloss to capture the force of it in this context might be "to" “and then” or “and so”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəqidiym: officers yafqed: appoint|i(34) (34) |rchimmesh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pəqidiym: officers yafqed: appoint<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>chimmesh (piʿel): levy a 20% tax</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Dong musti iko tuan raja pung parenta, ko dong ame padi dari samua kampong di Masir. Ais dong musti simpan itu padi di lumbung-lumbung ko jaga bae-bae.<bt>They must follow mr raja's orders, for them to take padi from all the villages in Masir. Then they must store that padi in graineries to guard/take.care.of it well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lumbung = grain bin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lumbung = grain bin</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqbətsu: let them collect yitsbru-var: stack"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqbətsu: let them collect yitsbru-var: stack up<span class="Italic">(35) (35) </span>ʿariym: cities</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />Ko nanti itu tuju taon lapar sampe, na, kotong masi ada makanan. Deng ator bagitu, sonde ada orang yang mati lapar.&gt;&gt;<bt>In.order.that later when those seven hungry years arrive, obviously, we will still have food. By arranging things like that, there will be no one dying of hunger.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="fiqqadown: deposit tihyeyna (fem): they will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">fiqqadown: deposit tihyeyna (fem): they will be<span class="Italic">(36) (36) </span>loʾ-tikkaret (krt nif): so that it will not be destroyed, ruined, consumed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja angka Yusuf jadi dia pung tangan kanan di tana Masir<bt>The raja promotes Yusuf to become his right hand in Masir land</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Dengar Yusuf ba'omong bagitu, ju raja deng dia pung pagawe tinggi dong satuju deng Yusuf pung usul.<bt>Hearing Yusuf speak like that then, the raja and all his high.level civil.servants agreed with that suggestion of Yusuf's.</bt><v n="38" />Ais raja omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah pung Roh pung kuasa su ada memang di Yusuf. Andia ko sonde mungkin botong dapa orang laen lai, yang lebe dari dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>So the raja spoke saying, &lt;&lt;The Lord God's Spirt has truly given power to this Yusuf. That's why it would be impossible for us to get another person, who is more than him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanimsaʾ: meet by chance? find by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hanimsaʾ: meet by chance? find by searching?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ais raja omong deng Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su kasi tau ini hal dong samua sang lu. Sakarang baru botong tau bilang, lu ni pintar. Deng lu pung pintar lebe dari samua orang.<bt>Then the raja spoke with Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;The Lord God has told all this to you. Only now do we know that you are wise. And your good.ideas are more than everyone else.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akal = otak, clever ideas, useful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">akal = otak, clever ideas, useful ideas</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="howdiyaʿ (hif): made known"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">howdiyaʿ (hif): made known</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />Andia ko sakarang beta angka lu jadi beta pung tangan kanan, ko lu jadi bos di beta pung istana. Deng nanti beta pung rakyat samua iko lu pung parenta. Cuma beta sandiri sa, yang lebe dari lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's why now I promote you to be my right hand. So you will be boos in my palace, And all my people will follow your orders. But only just me myself, who will be more than you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tangan kanan = nomer 2, ma"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tangan kanan = nomer 2, ma sama ke raja; orang parcaya</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿal-beytiy: over my house yishshaq (nshq):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿal-beytiy: over my house yishshaq (nshq): put themselves in order, accomodate themselves<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>raq hakkisseʾ: only in regard to the throne am I greater than you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41-42" />Ais itu, ju raja cabu kasi kaluar dia pung cincin stempel, ko kasi maso di Yusuf pung jari. Ju dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Deng bagini, beta angka lu jadi beta pung tangan kanan di samua negrí Masir.&gt;&gt; Ais dia kasi pake Yusuf satu baju panjang yang alus, deng gantong rante mas di dia pung leher.<bt>After that then, the raja pulled taking off his stamp ring, to put it on Yusuf's finger. And he said saying, &lt;&lt;With this, I promote you to be my right hand in all this land of Masir.&gt;&gt; And he give to Yusuf a long robe that was finely[contructed] to wear, and [he] put a gold chain on his neck.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koru = slip off"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">koru = slip off</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaSar (nif): put away, take off"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaSar (nif): put away, take off Tabbaʿto: his seal-ring<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>yalbesh (hif): caused him to wear shesh: Egyptian linen cloth<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>ravid: necklace zahav: gold<span class="Italic">(41) (41) </span>tsawwaʾro: his neck</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Ais itu, dia kasi dia pung kareta kuda nomer dua ko Yusuf nae. Ada orang yang lari di muka kareta ko batarea ulang-ulang bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Buka jalan, ó! Kasi hormat!<bt>After that, he gave his number two horse cart for Yusuf to ride. There was a person who ran in front of that cart to yell repeatedly saying, &lt;&lt;We! Open the road! Give respect!</bt><note reference="41:43" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kata asli Ibrani bisa juga dia pung arti bilang &lt;soya&gt;, ko, &lt;tondo&gt;.<bt>The original Ibrani word can also mean ‘bow/worship’, or, 'bow-to-the-ground'.</bt></note>Ada orang bésar mau lewat!&gt;&gt; Deng bekin bagitu, raja su angka Yusuf jadi dia pung tangan kanan di tana Masir.<bt>A big person wants to pass by.&gt;&gt; And by doing like that, the raja promoted Yusuf to be his right hand in Masir land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ba'eki = pange, summon by shouting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ba'eki = pange, summon by shouting</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarkev (hif): cause him to ride"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yarkev (hif): cause him to ride mishneh: the second-best (chariot), rank next to the king<span class="Italic">(43) (43) </span>ʾavrek: make obeisance? bow down? Egyptian word? natown (inf): he gave<span class="Italic">(43)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Ais itu, raja omong deng Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini. Lu su tau memang beta ni, raja. Deng beta su kasi tau samua orang di Masir bilang, kalo lu sonde kasi loos, na, dong sonde bisa bekin apa-apa.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the raja spoke with Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. You truly know that I am raja. But I have told all the people in this Masir saying, if you don't give permission obviously, they can't do anything.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi luas = give permission, kasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi luas = give permission, kasi lós, mengizinkan, setuju</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vilʿadeykha: without you yariym (rwm hif):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vilʿadeykha: without you yariym (rwm hif): cause to move: SK "Simon says!"<span class="Italic">(44)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00731c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf deng dia pung bini<bt>Yusuf and his wife</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ais ju raja kasi nama sang Yusuf, <span class="Italic">Safnat Panea,</span> iko orang Masir pung nama. Dia ju kasi kawin Yusuf deng satu parampuan, nama Asnat. Yusuf pung bapa mantu, nama Potifera. Dia yang urus agama di kota On.<bt>And then the raja gave a name to Yusuf, Safnat Panea, following the Masir people's names. And he also married Yusuf with a female, named Asnat. Yusuf's father-in-law, named Potifera. He was the one who coordinated religion in On city.</bt><note reference="41:45" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kota On pung nama laen dalam bahasa Yunani bilang &lt;Heliopolis&gt;.<bt>The City of On's other name in the Greek language is 'Heliopolis'.</bt></note>Deng bagitu, Yusuf jadi orang bésar di tana Masir.<bt>With that, Yusuf became a big person in Masir land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetseʾ: came out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yetseʾ: came out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Waktu dong angka sang Yusuf tu, dia pung umur tiga pulu taon. Ais itu, dia pi lia kuliling samua tampa di tana Masir.<bt>When they promoted that Yusuf, [background info} his age was 30 years. After that, he went looking all around all the places in Masir land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿamdo (ʿmd inf): when he began"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿamdo (ʿmd inf): when he began to serve</Message></Annotation><v n="47" />Dalam waktu tuju taon musim kinyang tu, kabón dong pung hasil talalu banya.<bt>During those seven years of plentiful season, the garden's harvest was exceedingly very great.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="liqmatsiym: produced by fistfuls"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">liqmatsiym: produced by fistfuls</Message></Annotation><v n="48" />Ais Yusuf pi kumpul itu hasil lebe dong, ko dia simpan. Hasil padi dari tampa-tampa deka kota mana, na, dia simpan di itu kota pung lumbung.<bt>So Yusuf went gathering that extra harvest, in order for him to store it. The padi harvest from places near whatever city, it stored in graineries in that city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqbots: he collected, assembled towchah: its"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqbots: he collected, assembled towchah: its midst<span class="Italic">(48)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="49" />Sampe hasil padi yang dia kumpul tu, banya talalu, sama ke pasir di pante, sampe sonde ada orang yang bisa ukur lai.<bt>To the point that the padi harvest that he gathered, very great. Just like the sand on the ocean beach, to. the.point. that there was no person who could measure it anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitsbor: he heaped up bar: grain|i(49)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yitsbor: he heaped up bar: grain<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>chowl: sand harbeh (rbh hif): he made it great<span class="Italic">(49) (49) </span>chadal: he ceased from an activity miSpar: number, count<span class="Italic">(49)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Waktu musim lapar balóm sampe, Yusuf pung bini Asnat su barana dua ana laki-laki.<bt>When the hungry season had not yet arrived, [background info] Yusuf's wife Asnat had given birth to two male children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəTerem: before"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bəTerem: before</Message></Annotation><v n="51" />Ju Yusuf omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su bekin beta lupa beta pung sangsara waktu beta kaluar dari beta pung papa pung ruma.&gt;&gt; Andia ko dia kasi nama sang dia pung ana nomer satu, <span class="Italic">Manase</span> (yang dia pung bunyi amper sama deng kata laen, yang dia pung arti bilang &lt;lupa&gt;).<bt>And Yusuf spoke saying, &lt;&lt;The Lord God has made me forget my tribulation when I went.out of my papa's house.&gt;&gt; That's why he gave the name to his number one child <span class="Italic">Manase</span> (which is similar to another word meaning &lt;forget&gt;).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nashshaniy (nshh piʿel): he made me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nashshaniy (nshh piʿel): he made me forget ʿəmaliy: my heavy, wearisome labour; produce of labour; weariness, trouble, vexation; sin, wickedness<span class="Italic">(51)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Waktu dia dapa ana nomer dua, ju dia omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su dapa sangsara banya di ini tampa. Ma Tuhan Allah su kasi berkat deng beta dapa ana di sini.&gt;&gt; Ju dia kasi nama itu ana, <span class="Italic">Efraim.</span><bt>When he got child number two, he also spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;I have gotten much tribulation in this place. But the Lord God has given blessing, with me receiving this child.&gt;&gt; And he named that child, <span class="Italic">Efraim.</span> [NOTE: Q: Do you want these two verses to be consistent in handling names? A: We started out in early drafts of Genesis with all names in the text and all meanings in footnotes. But we proved quite consistently that even educated people don't read the footnotes, so the translation can't depend on it. And unread footnotes didn't make any sense to the reader of names earlier in Genesis like saying “she named him XX because YY”. One consultant wanted us to reverse it (vernacular meanings as names, and Hebrew names in ftn), but that won't work in a churched society where they are already familiar with the names and their stories (even the obscure ones). Another consultant pointed out that for the original audiences who knew Hebrew the “she named him XX because YY” formula made perfectly good sense because they knew what the word meant, or what words that sounded similar meant. So after several versions and several languages we finally started putting both the name and the meaning in the text (using the pattern in vs. 51). But there are several where there are multiple possibilities or more complex information, and we really can't put this in the text, so we put those in footnotes (as in vs. 52). If this were the only occurrence then I'd say let's be consistent here. But we're actually following a higher level pattern that we've established at the book level for this kind of thing. Thanks for double-checking.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tanaman garui = lush (plants) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tanaman garui = lush (plants) ; *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hifraniy (prh hif): he made me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hifraniy (prh hif): he made me fruitful ʿanyiy: my misery<span class="Italic">(52)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="41:52" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dalam bahasa Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Efraim</span> pung arti bisa ju &lt;dapa ana&gt;, ko, &lt;tana ba'isi&gt;, ko, &lt;tamba banya&gt;.<bt>In the Ibrani language, <span class="Italic">Efraim</span> can mean 'receive child' or 'fertile land' or 'increase more'.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="53" />Ais musim kinyang tuju taon tu abis.<bt>After that then, those seven years of plentiful season were over.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tikhleynah (fem): they finished"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tikhleynah (fem): they finished</Message></Annotation><v n="54" />Ju musim lapar tuju taon mulai datang, pas deng apa yang Yusuf su omong memang. Di tampa laen orang su lapar. Ma di samua tampa di Masir ada makanan, tagal su tasimpan memang di lumbung-lumbung dong.<bt>And the seven years of hungry season started coming, exactly like what Yusuf had said before. In other places, people were hungry. But in all the places in Masir there was food, because it had been stored beforehand in the various grainaries. [EXEG: last clause added (see NLT) to remove the ambiguity that allowed a reading that there was no famine in Egypt.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tichilleynah (chll hif): they began"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tichilleynah (chll hif): they began</Message></Annotation><v n="55" />Lama-lama ju orang Masir dong mulai lapar. Ais dong pi minta makanan di raja. Ju raja suru dong pi di Yusuf, ko iko Yusuf pung parenta.<bt>After a while then, the Masir people started being hungry. Then they went request food from the raja. And the raja told them to go to Yusuf, in order to follow Yusuf's orders.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitsʿaq: the people cried out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yitsʿaq: the people cried out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="56" />Ma itu musim lapar tamba hebat lai, sampe samua tampa di Masir ju kaná. Ju Yusuf mulai buka samua lumbung ko jual padi kasi orang Masir dong.<bt>But that hungry season increased even more in severity, to the point that all the places in Masir were affected. And Yusuf started opening all the graineries to sell padi to the Masir people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiftach: he opened yishbor: he sold"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiftach: he opened yishbor: he sold grain<span class="Italic">(56) (56) </span>yechəzaq: it was heavy</Message></Annotation><v n="57" />Ais itu, orang dari mana-mana datang béli makanan dari Yusuf di Masir, tagal itu musim lapar batúl-batúl ngarí.<bt>After that, all sorts of people from all over the place came buy food from Yusuf in Masir. Because that hungry season was truly-truly very horrific.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf pung kaka dong pi Masir ko béli makanan<bt>Yusuf's elder.siblings to Masir to buy food</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="42" />
      <v n="1" />Itu waktu, papa Yakob dengar orang bilang ada padi di Masir, ju dia ba'omong deng dia pung ana dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana dong, é! Akurang ko bosong dudu-dudu tanganga bodo bagitu sa!<bt>At that time, Papa Yakob heard people saying there was padi in Masir, and he spoke with his children saying, &lt;&lt;Children! Why are you just sitting around with your mouths open stupidly like that!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyarʾ: become aware (not just with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyarʾ: become aware (not just with eyes) shever (shvr): grain for sale (not that Egypt had a crop and Palestine didnʾt; neither had a crop)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>lammah titraʾu (rʾh hitp): looking at each other; donʾt just stand there, do something!</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Beta su dengar bilang, di Masir ada makanan. Lebe bae bosong pi béli di sana dolo, ko biar kotong jang mati lapar.&gt;&gt;<bt>I have heard that in Masir there is food. It best that you-pl go buy there first, so that we don't die of hunger.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rədu (yrd): go down (Egypt is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">rədu (yrd): go down (Egypt is always "down", and Jerusalem and the Judean highlands are always "up")</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais ju Yusuf pung kaka sapulu orang basiap-siap ko mau pi béli makanan di Masir.<bt>So then, those ten elder.siblings of Yusuf, got ready to go buy food in Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akhey-yosef: Joseph's half brothers"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">akhey-yosef: Joseph's half brothers</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ma Yakob sonde mau kasi loos Yusuf pung adi bungsu Benyamin ko pi sama-sama deng dong. Ko dia ada pikir, &lt;&lt;Jang sampe itu ana dapa calaka lai!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakokb didn't give permission for Yusuf's youngest younger sibling Benyamin to go together with them. Because he had thought, &lt;&lt;Lest that child also gets in an accident/disaster!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sama-sama ~ sam-sama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sama-sama ~ sam-sama</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akhi-yosef: Joseph's full brother pen: so"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">akhi-yosef: Joseph's full brother pen: so that not, lest, prevention of a theoretically possible event<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yiqraʾenu: (distaster) happens ʾason: mortal accident<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Tagal orang di mana-mana su dengar ada makanan di Masir, andia ko banya orang pi béli di sana. Itu musim lapar ju su sampe di tana Kana'an. Ais Yakob pung ana dong<bt>Because people from all over had heard that there was food in Masir, that's.why may people went to buy there. That hungry season also had arrived at Kanaan land. So Yakob's children</bt><note reference="42:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani pung tulisan bilang &lt;Isra'el pung ana dong&gt;. Ma Isra'el deng Yakob tu, satu orang pung nama.<bt>Ibrani language writings say 'Israel's children'. But Israel and that Yakob, one person's names.</bt></note>ju pi iko béli di sana.<bt>also went to buy there.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00730c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf pung kaka dong tikam lutut kasi hormat sang dia</fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Itu waktu, Yusuf su jadi raja pung tangan kanan di Masir. Kalo orang datang dari mana-mana ko mau béli padi, na, Yusuf yang jual kasi sang dong. Andia ko, waktu dia pung kaka dong sampe, dong pi tikam lutut kasi hormat sang dia sampe dong pung muka kaná tana.<bt>At that time, Yusuf had become the raja's right hand in Masir. If people came from whereever obviously in order to buy padi, Yusuf was the one who sold it to them. That's why, when his elder.siblings arrive, they went bow the knee give honor to him, to the point that their faces hit the ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaliyT: ruler, tyrant, the one with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shaliyT: ruler, tyrant, the one with the power hammashbir (shbr hif partcpl): the one who did the selling<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vayyishtakhvu (shkh hitp): bow down deeply, do homage, prostrated themselves ʾappayim (dual): their faces, their nostrils?<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7-8" />Waktu dia lia sang dong, ju dia kanál memang. Ma Yusuf bekin diri sama ke orang Masir, andia ko dong sonde kanál sang dia. Ais dia batanya deng kasar sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong ni, dari mana?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he saw them then, he truly knew them. But Yusuf made himself like a Masir person, that's.why they didn't know him. Then he asked them in a rough way saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl here, from where?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong ni dari Kana'an. Botong datang ko mau minta béli makan di pak wakil.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they answered saying, &lt;&lt;We here are from Kanaan. We come to request to buy food from Mr. Vice-(raja).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyakirem (nkr hif): he recognized them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyakirem (nkr hif): he recognized them vayyitnaker (also nkr hitp): he kept his identity from them<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>qashot (qasheh): hard, difficult, heavy, severe meʾayin: from where?<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayyakker (nkr hif narr): he recognized hikkiruhu (nkr hif): they did not recognize him<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais Yusuf inga dia pung mimpi dolu tu. Ju dia bekin taku sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta sonde parcaya! Pasti bosong samua ni mata-mata. Bosong datang ko mau cari tau tana Masir pung rahasia, ais bale ko saráng sang kotong, to!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf remember that earlier dream of his. And he made them afraid saying, &lt;&lt;I don't believe that! Of course you all here are spies. You've come to find out Masir land's secrets, then return in order to attack us, haven't you?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="serbu = attack (BI); saráng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">serbu = attack (BI); saráng</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məraglim (regel): roamers, spies ʿerwat: nakedness,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">məraglim (regel): roamers, spies ʿerwat: nakedness, undefended areas<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ma dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde, pak! Botong ni cuma pak pung orang suru-suru sa. Batúl-batúl botong datang cuma mau béli makan sa.<bt>But they answered saying, &lt;&lt;No, Father! We here are only just your (Father's) ordering-around people. Truly-Truly we have only just come to buy food.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿavadekha: and your slaves, servants"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿavadekha: and your slaves, servants</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Botong samua ni satu bapa barana. Botong bukan mata-mata, pak! Botong orang bae-bae.&gt;&gt;<bt>All of us here [have] one father. We are not spies, Father! We are good people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nakhnu: we kenim: honest people: SK"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nakhnu: we kenim: honest people: SK laugh.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ma Yusuf omong tamba karás lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Heh! Omong kosong! Jang putar-balek sang beta! Memang bosong ni batúl mata-mata, ma. Tantu bosong datang ko mau cari tau ini negrí pung rahasia dong!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yusus spoke even more harshly saying, &lt;&lt;He! Lies! Don't lie to me! Truly you here are really spies [+assertion]. Of course you've come to find out this country's secrets!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ais dong protes bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde, pak! Botong ni cuma bapa pung orang suru-suru sa! Botong datang dari tana Kana'an. Botong basodara dua blas orang. Botong samua satu papa. Botong pung adi bungsu ada tenga deng papa. Deng botong pung adi satu, su sonde ada lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they protested saying, &lt;&lt;No, Father! We here are only just father's ordering-around people! We come from Kanaan land. We are twelve siblings. We all have one father. Our youngest sibling is staying with papa. And our one sibling, don't exist anymore.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shneym ʿasar: twelve haqqaTon: the youngest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shneym ʿasar: twelve haqqaTon: the youngest (Benjamin would have been in his late twenties or early thirties, no longer a kid, but still the youngest in the family)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʾeynennu: he does not exist (in other words, he's dead)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00733c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Yusuf masparak sang dia pung kaka dong</fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais Yusuf bale manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde! Su batúl apa yang beta omong tadi tu! Bosong ni memang mata-mata.<bt>Then Yusuf answered saying, &lt;&lt;No! It's true what I said earlier. You here are actually spies.</bt><v n="15" />Naa! Bosong musti kasi bukti dolo, ko beta tau bosong pung omong tadi memang batúl, ko sonde. Beta sumpa! Kalo bosong pung adi bungsu tu sonde datang di sini, na, bosong sonde bisa jalan kasi tenga ini negrí!<bt>So now! You must first give some evidence, so that I can know if what you were saying earlier, is actually true or not. I swear! If that youngest sibling of yours doesn't come here [+assertion], you will not be able to leave this land! [EXEG: "as surely as Pharaoh lives." Naturalness to get similar understanding and impact and not skew the focus. We've done quite a bit of work on cursing, swearing, and oath-taking in the region. Going literal “as surely as Pharaoh lives” (evoking a semi-devine king) doesn't fit any local patterns. Appealing to God is taking it in a different (and higher) direction than the Hebrew. Evoking the ancestors is also taking it in a different direction and bringing in problematic baggage. “I swear” in English is certainly weak, but the lgs in the region it evokes “I am really serious about what we are talking about here, and something bad will happen to you if you cross me on this!”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tibbachenu (nif): you will be put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tibbachenu (nif): you will be put to the test chey: as surely as Pharaoh lives<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>tetsʾu (ntsʾ imperf pl): come out bəvoʾ (inf): in coming<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Jadi bosong pili satu orang ko pi ame itu adi bungsu datang di sini. Yang laen, beta tahan. Beta mau lia bosong omong batúl, ko sonde. Kalo sonde, bosong memang batúl mata-mata.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) you choose one person to go get that youngest sibling to come to here. The others, I'll detain. I want to see if you are really speaking true or not. If not, you are actually really spies.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heʾaSru (ʾSr nif imperv): you are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">heʾaSru (ʾSr nif imperv): you are to be kept yibbachənu (nif): your words will be tested<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ais Yusuf suru tahan sang dong di bui tiga hari.<bt>Then Yusuf ordered to detain them in jail three days.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyeʾəSof (ʾSp narr): he took away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyeʾəSof (ʾSp narr): he took away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00735c.tif" rtfFormat="width:9.0cm;textWrapping:none">Yusuf lempar buang dia pung kaka dong pi dalam bui</fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dia pung tiga hari, ju Yusuf pi omong deng dong di bui bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, satu orang yang taku sang Tuhan. Deng beta salalu iko Dia pung mau. Beta mau lapás sang bosong, ko biar bosong bisa idop. Ma ada satu sarat.<bt>After three days then, Yusuf went to speak with them in jail saying, &lt;&lt;I here, one person who fears the Lord. And I always follow His will. I want to let you go free, so that you can live. But there is one requirement.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿəsu (ʿsh imperv): do this wichyu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿəsu (ʿsh imperv): do this wichyu (hyh imperv): stay alive<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>yareʾ: fear, shudder at, be in awe of, hold in deference</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Kalo bosong omong jujur, na, bosong musti kasi tunju bukti sang beta. Dia pung jalan bagini: beta tahan satu orang dalam bui. Yang laen pulang ko bawa makanan kasi bosong pung kelu. Te dong ada tunggu bosong pulang bawa makanan.<bt>If you are really speaking the truth here, you must show me some evidence. This is how: I will detain one person in jail. The others return home to bring the food to your family. Cuz they are waiting for you to return bringing food.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hati lurus = honest, truthful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">hati lurus = honest, truthful</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʾaSer mishmarkhem: your detention place, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʾaSer mishmarkhem: your detention place, the prison where I would have kept you all<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>raʿəvon: hunger</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ais bosong bawa datang bosong pung adi tu, ko jadi bukti bilang bosong orang jujur. Ko biar beta jang kasi hukum mati sang bosong.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then you-pl bring here that youngest sibling of yours, to become evidence that you are truthful people. So that I don't give the death penalty to you.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar bagitu, ju dong satuju.<bt>Hearing that, then they agreed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʾamnu (ʾmn nif): your words will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʾamnu (ʾmn nif): your words will be confirmed</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ais dong satu ba'omong deng satu bilang, &lt;&lt;Naa! Sakarang kotong kaná balas dari kotong pung dosa tempo hari, yang kotong su bekin di kotong pung adi. Kotong su lia dia sangsara mati, sampe dia minta tolong, ma kotong sonde toe sang dia. Andia ko sakarang kotong sangsara bagini.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they spoke with one another saying, &lt;&lt;So! Now we are being revenged for our sin from before, which we did to that younger sibling of ours. We saw him in great distress, to.the.point that he was asking for help, but we didn't pay.attention to him. That's why now we are in tribulation like this.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sonde hosek = sonde nodek (Du"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sonde hosek = sonde nodek (Du - noodig) = sonde toe (Rote) = sonde ame pusing = sonde taru kira</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəval: introducing a statement that may"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾəval: introducing a statement that may not be pleasing to the hearer ʾəshemiym (pl): guilty<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>raʾiynu: we saw tsarat: distress<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>hitchanno (chnn hitp inf): his pleading for pity, praying for mercy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ju Ruben kasi inga sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We, adi-adi dong! Dolu beta su larang sang bosong, ko jang bekin apa-apa sang itu ana, to! Ma bosong sonde nodek beta pung omong. Andia ko, sakarang kotong pikol Yusuf pung dara suda, ma.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Ruben reminded them saying, &lt;&lt;We, younger siblings! Before I forbade you not to do anything with that child, right? But you didn't go.along.with that talk of mine. That's why, now we are shoulder-carrying Yusuf's blood, [+assertion].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-tekhetʾu: donʾt you sin against him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-tekhetʾu: donʾt you sin against him yeled: boy, young man; also used of a fetus<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>hinneh: focus on the current situation nidrash (nif): is being sought, is required<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Dong ba'omong bagitu, ma dong sonde tau bilang, Yusuf ju mangarti dong pung bahasa. Tagal waktu Yusuf ba'omong deng dong, dia pake bahasa Masir, ais jubir salin pi dalam bahasa Ibrani.<bt>They spoke like that, but they didn't know that Yusuf also understood their language. Because, when Yusuf spooke with them, he used Masir language, then a spokesperson poured it into Ibrani language.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meliyts (lyts hif partcpl): interpreter bayinotam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">meliyts (lyts hif partcpl): interpreter bayinotam: between them<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Dengar dong ba'omong bagitu, ju Yusuf bangun kasi tenga sang dong, ko dia pi manangis sandiri di tampa laen. Waktu dia su manangis abis, ju dia kambali pi dong. Ais dia suru orang ika ame sang Simeon di dia pung sodara dong pung muka.<bt>Hearing them talk like that then, Yusuf got up leaving them, in order for him to go cry alone in another place. When he had finished crying, he returned to them. Then he ordered a person to tie up Simeon in front of his sibling's faces.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiSSov (Sbb narr): he turned away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyiSSov (Sbb narr): he turned away vayyashav (shwb narr): he came back. Speiser thinks it is used adverbially, as ʿʿWhen he was able to face them again.ʾʾ<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>vayyeʾəSor (ʾSr narr): he tied him up, had him tied up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf pung kaka dong pulang pi Kana'an<bt>Yusuf's elder.siblings return to Kanaan</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais itu, Yusuf parenta dia pung orang dong, ko isi padi di dia pung kaka dong pung karong-karong. Deng kasi maso kambali satu-satu pung doi di dong pung mulu karong. Dia ju suru kasi sang dong bakál. Tarús, itu orang dong bekin iko Yusuf pung parenta.<bt>After that, Yusuf ordered his people, to fill padi in his elder.siblings sacks. And to put back each one's money in the mouth of their sacks. [[NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK if discourse structure requires adding: Then sew them shut. [NOTE: close gunny sack so won't see contents (gunny sacks = if not full, then tie; if full then sew; context implies full.]]] And he ordered to give them trail.food. Immediately, those people did according to Yusuf's order.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaytsaw (tswh piʿel narr): he ordered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaytsaw (tswh piʿel narr): he ordered klihem: their grain bags (kli = useful object, gear, vessel, receptacle)<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>bar: grain hashiv (shwv hif inf): give back<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʾel-saqqo: into his bag (poor quality material of goat hair) tsedah: provisions for a trip<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Ais itu, Yusuf pung kaka dong mua ame itu karong padi samua pi dong pung keledai. Ais ju dong bangun pulang.<bt>After that, Yusuf's elder.siblings put those padi sacks on their donkeys. Then they got up went home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyisʾu (nsʾ narr): they loaded chamoreyhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyisʾu (nsʾ narr): they loaded chamoreyhem: their donkeys<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Di tenga jalan dong barenti cape. Ju satu dari dong buka dia pung tali karong, ko mau kasi makan dia pung keledai. Ma dia lia dia pung doi ada di atas padi.<bt>In the middle of the road they stopped to rest. And, one of them opened his sack's string, to give food to his donkey. But he saw his money was on top of that padi.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiftach (ptch narr): he opened mispowʾ:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyiftach (ptch narr): he opened mispowʾ: fodder<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>malon: lodging, camping-ground for the night (modern "hotel") bpi: in the mouth of (the bag)<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʾamtachto: load, bag</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Dia takuju mau mati! Tarús dia batarea dia pung kaka dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Bosong mari lia ini dolo! Te kotong su paya ni, ma! Dong su kasi pulang beta pung doi di beta pung karong.&gt;&gt;<bt>He was exceedingly startled! Straight away he yelled to his elder.sibling saying, &lt;&lt;Awiii! You-pl come look here! Cuz we have really in difficulty here, [+assertion]. They they given back my money in my sack.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="should it be batarea dia pung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">should it be batarea dia pung sodara (rather than kaka)?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00737c.tif" rtfFormat="width:9.0cm;textWrapping:none">Yusuf pung kaka lia dia pung doi dalam karong</fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lia bagitu, ju dong ilang kira ko dong taku mau mati. Ais dong ba'omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan Allah su bekin apa sang kotong lai ni?&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing that, then they were unable to think straight because they were exceedingly afraid. Then they spoke to each other saying, &lt;&lt;The Lord God is doing what else with us?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ilang kira = unable to think,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ilang kira = unable to think, bingung; kotong su dapa kualat ini, ma = kutuk; kosi inja deng habok =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huwshav: returned, brought back vayyetseʾ libam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">huwshav: returned, brought back vayyetseʾ libam: their heart went away = their courage failed, their determination stopped<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>vayyecherdu (chrd narr): and each looked with trembling at his brothers</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ais dong jalan tarús. Sampe di Kana'an, ju dong carita sang dong pung papa samua yang su jadi.<bt>Then they continued travelling. Arriving in Kanaan then, they storied to their father, all that had happened(adversely) to them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyagidu (ngd narr): they reported haqorot"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyagidu (ngd narr): they reported haqorot otem (qrh partcpll plur fem): the things (neutral) that happened to them<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Dong kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa, é! Itu raja Masir pung tangan kanan tu, talalu sakali, é. Dia pung omong sa, kasar mau mati. Dia tudu sang botong bilang, botong pi mata-mata dia pung negrí.<bt>They told saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! That raja Masir's right hand there, he's just too much! Just his speech, is very rough. He accused us saying, we went to spy his country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="culas = hati bengko (dari judas);"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">culas = hati bengko (dari judas); tudu = accuse, kasi sala</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dibber (dbr piʿel): he spoke qashot"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">dibber (dbr piʿel): he spoke qashot (qasheh): hard, difficult, heavy, severe<span class="Italic">(30)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Ma botong manyao bilang, &lt;Sonde! Botong omong jujur sa. Botong ni bukan mata-mata.<bt>But we replied saying, 'No! We are only speaking truthfully. We here are not spies.</bt><v n="32" />Botong orang bae-bae. Botong samua basodara dua blas orang. Botong satu papa barana. Cuma satu su sonde ada lai, deng yang bungsu ada tenga deng papa di Kana'an.&gt;<bt>We are good people. We all are 12 siblings. We have one father. Only one is no longer (=dead or disappeared), and the youngest is staying with our papa in Kanaan.'</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ais, itu pak bilang, &lt;Beta mau coba, bosong ni jujur, ko sonde! Bosong satu musti tenga di sini. Yang laen pulang, bawa padi kasi bosong pung kelu, ko biar dong jang mati lapar.<bt>Then, that Father said, &lt;I want to test, you here are truthful or not! One of you must stay here. The others go home, bring padi for your family, so they don't die of hunger.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanikhu (nwkh hif imperv): leave behind"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hanikhu (nwkh hif imperv): leave behind raʿavon: hunger, famine<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>batechem: for your houses qakhu (lqkh): take away<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Bosong musti bawa datang bosong pung adi dolo. Deng bagitu, baru beta tau bosong ni bukan mata-mata, ma bosong memang orang jujur. Tarús beta bisa kasi lapás bosong pung sodara yang beta su tahan. Ais beta kasi loos, ko bosong bole pi mana sa, di ini negrí.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>You must bring come your youngest sibling. With that, only will I know that you here are not spies, but you are really truthful people. Then2 I can release that sibling of yours who I am detaining. And I will give permission, for you to be able to go wherever, in this country.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeten: I will give tiScharu: pass"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾeten: I will give tiScharu: pass through, wander around<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Carita abis, ju dong mulai bongkar dong pung isi karong dong. Takuju dong dapa lia satu-satu pung doi masi ada di dong pung karong. Lia bagitu, ju Yakob deng dia pung ana samua taku mau mati.<bt>Finish storying then, they began to unpack the contents of their sacks. Unexpectedly they saw each one's money, still was in their sack. Seeing that, then Yakob and all his children were exceedingly afraid.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məriqim (ryq partcpl): as they were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">məriqim (ryq partcpl): as they were emptying tsəror-kesfo: a bundle of his money<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ais itu, Yakob omong deng dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong ni su bekin ilang beta pung ana dong. Yusuf sonde ada lai. Ais Simeon ju bagitu. Sakarang ju bosong mau ame bawa Benyamin lai? Bosong ni batúl-batúl mau bekin sangsara sang beta sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yakob spoke with them saying, &lt;&lt;You here have made my children disappear. Yusuf is anymore. Then Simeon is also like that. Now you want to take Benyamin as well? You-pl here truly just want to cause distress to me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oti shikkaltem (piʿel): you have bereaved"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">oti shikkaltem (piʿel): you have bereaved me, deprived me of my children</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ju Ruben omong deng dia pung papa bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa, é! Sarakan Benyamin sang beta suda. Beta yang tanggong-jawab. Beta janji, nanti beta kasi pulang dia di papa. Ma kalo sonde, na, biar papa bunu beta pung ana laki-laki dua orang.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Ruben spoke with his papa saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! Surrender Benyamin to me. I will be responsible. I promise, later I will bring him home to papa. But if obviously not, then papa may kill those two male children of mine.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tamiyt (mwt hif): may you kill"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tamiyt (mwt hif): may you kill ʾəshiyvennu (shwb hif): I will bring him back<span class="Italic">(37)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ma Yakob omong bale bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde bisa! Bosong sonde bole bawa sang Benyamin. Te dia pung kaka Yusuf su mati. Sakarang tenga dia sandiri sa. Kalo dia ju calaka di tenga jalan, bosong bekin susa tamba di beta pung kapala sampe beta maso kubur.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yakob spoke back saying, &lt;&lt;No way! You can't take Benyamin. Cuz that elder.sibling Yusuf of his, is dead. Now there's only him left. If he also encounters.accident on the way, you will make more difficulty on my head to the point that I will enter the grave.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="susa is carried on the head;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">susa is carried on the head; pikol sengsara ; su'u ; muat ~ mua</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləvaddo: in his aloneness, he alone"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ləvaddo: in his aloneness, he alone nishʾar (shʾr nif): remains<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>qəraʾahu: befall, meet him ʾaSown: misfortune, mischief, accident<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>vəhoradtem (yrd hif narr): you will bring down seyvatiy: my grey hairs, my old age<span class="Italic">(38) (38) </span>yagown: grief shəʾowlah: to Sheol, the place of the dead<span class="Italic">(38)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="42:38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;sampe beta turun pi Sheol (andia: orang mati dong pung tampa)&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab says "to the point that I descend down to Sheol (that is the place of dead people)".</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf pung kaka dong kambali pi Masir, bawa dong pung adi Benyamin<bt>Yusuf's elder.siblings return to Masir, bringing their younger sibling Benyamin</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="43" />
      <v n="1" />Itu waktu, musim lapar di Kana'an tamba hebat lai.<bt>At that time, the hungry season in Kanaan was increasingly more severe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʿav: famine kaved: heavy, oppressive, grievous|i(1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raʿav: famine kaved: heavy, oppressive, grievous<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Yakob pung kelu dong su bekin abis itu makanan yang tempo hari dia pung ana dong bawa dari Masir. Ais dia kasi tau sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana dong, é! Lebe bae bosong kambali pi Masir, ko béli kasi kotong padi lai dolo.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yakob's family had finished that food which his children had brought from Masir before. Then he told them saying, &lt;&lt;Children! It's best if you return to Masir, to buy again padi for us.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="killu: they finished INFing shuvu: go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">killu: they finished INFing shuvu: go back<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>lanu: for us (the sons, Jacob too, and their families) məʿaT: a little<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ma Yahuda manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa! Tempo hari, itu raja Masir pung tangan kanan su kasi inga karás sang botong bilang, botong sonde bole kasi tunju muka sang dia, kalo botong sonde bawa papa pung ana bungsu Benyamin!<bt>But Yahuda answered saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! Before, that raja Masir's right hand reminded us really roughly saying, we cannnot show our faces to him, if we do not bring Benyamin that youngest child of papa's.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi tunju muka = pi mangada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi tunju muka = pi mangada</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haʿed heʿid: decisively, solemnly (as in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haʿed heʿid: decisively, solemnly (as in swearing a witness)</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Jadi papa musti kasi loos sang adi Benyamin, ko iko sang botong dolo. Baru botong mau pi béli makanan kasi papa.<bt>Thus papa has to give allowance for younger sibling Benyamin, to go with us (mild imperative). Only then can we buy food for papa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məshalleach (shlch piʿel partcpl): sending nerdah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">məshalleach (shlch piʿel partcpl): sending nerdah (yrd): we will go down<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>nishbərah: we buy grain</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ma kalo papa sonde kasi sang Benyamin pi, na, botong ju sonde akan pi. Te itu orang Masir su omong bagitu na!&gt;&gt;<bt>But if papa doesn't allow Benyamin to go obviously we also can't go. Cuz that Masir person has obviously spoken like that.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju Yakob togor sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko bosong su kasi tau itu orang bilang, bosong pung adi masi satu lai! Bosong cari-cari ko bekin susa sang beta sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob scolded him saying, &lt;&lt;Why did you tell that person, that you stil had one younger sibling! You-pl are just looking for a way, to cause distress to me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cari-cari = looking for a way"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">cari-cari = looking for a way to (?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həreʿotem (rʿʿ hif): you did evil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">həreʿotem (rʿʿ hif): you did evil haʿowd: that there is still one<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais dong kokoe bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa, é! Itu orang maen batanya tarús, ko mau cari tau kotong, deng kotong pung kelu samua na. Dia batanya bilang, &lt;Karmana? Bosong pung papa masi idop, ko? Bosong masi ada adi laki-laki laen lai, ko?&gt; Ais botong mau bilang apa lai! Tarpaksa botong omong jujur sa. Ko sapa pi tau bilang, dia mau suru botong bawa botong pung adi pi sana?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they comforted him saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! That person kept on asking and asking, to find out about us, and all of our family [it's obvious]. He asked saying, 'How is it? Is your father still living, [+tag question]? You still have another male younger sibling, don't you?' So what else could we say! We were forced to just be honest. Who could have known he would order us to bring our younger sibling there?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sapa pi tau = who could"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sapa pi tau = who could have known</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʾowl shaʾiyl moladtenu (moledet): our relations,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shaʾowl shaʾiyl moladtenu (moledet): our relations, descent, parentage<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>haʿod: still vanagged-lo (ngd hif): put something up conspicuously in front of someone, lay it all out, tell everything, speak out<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>həyadoaʿ nedaʿ (inf abs): did we have any idea? horidu (yrd hif): bring down (to Egypt), cause to go<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8-9" />Ju Yahuda omong tamba lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa! Kasi loos ini ana pi deng botong suda. Beta janji, kalo jadi apa-apa sang dia, na, biar beta yang tanggong ganti dia. Kalo beta sonde bawa pulang sang dia idop-idop kasi papa, na, biar papa mua itu sala sang beta sampe mati. Jadi papa kasi loos ini ana suda, te botong su mau jalan ni. Lebe bae botong pi capát-capát, ko jang ada yang mati lapar.<bt>And Yahuda spoke more again saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! Give permission for the child to go with us [imperative]. I promise, if anything happens to him [+obvious], let me be responsible to replace him. If I don't bring him home alive to papa [+obvious], let papa place that wrong on me until death. So papa give permission for that child [imperative], cuz we are ready to travel now. It's best if we go right away, so that there is none who die of hunger. [EXEG: What we have nicely reflects the NRSV, NET, Hamilton, and Hebrew lexicon (TWOT and BDB) and idioms. Note CEV and TH badly weakens the force of what Judah is saying (as does the suggestion “I will be responsible to take care of him.”) Heb. ʔeʕervenu: I will stand surety for him, guarantee, pledge myself; Hamilton (note) and “…Yahweh will require the blood of the wicked at the prophet’s hand (Ezek. 3:18, 20; 33:8). All use the phrase mîyað bãqaš to convey the sense of personal responsibility. Judah’s proposal differs from that of Reuben. The latter was willing to put the lives of two of his sons on the line (42:37). Judah is prepared to place his own life on the line.” This is far more serious than just “I will be responsible to take care of him”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="borokh/agunan beta pung = surety (Du"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">borokh/agunan beta pung = surety (Du - borog) ; CEV misses surety *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʿr: marriageable male while still single"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">naʿr: marriageable male while still single vnaqumah (qvm): stand up, get up; used to intensify an action, weʾll be on our way<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>Tappenu (Taf): our children ʾeʿervenu: I will stand surety for him, guarantee, pledge myself<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>tvaqshenu: you will seek, require it from me həviʾotiyw (bwʾ hif): cause him to come back<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vhitstsagtiyw: produce him, bring him forward vkhaTaʾti: be blameworthy, be guilty<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Coba kalo botong sonde tunggu bagini lama, na, tantu botong su pulang bale dua kali.&gt;&gt;<bt>If we hadn't waited this longer now, surely we could have already come home two time.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luwleʾ: if not hitmahmahnu (mhh hitpalpel):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">luwleʾ: if not hitmahmahnu (mhh hitpalpel): we lingered here and there, delayed<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ais ju dong pung papa bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bagitu, bosong bekin bagini sa. Pi ame kotong pung hasil tana yang paling bae. Andia: madu, bumbu-bumbu, dara kayu wangi, salap obat, kanari<bt>And then there papa said, &lt;&lt;If that's the case, you-pl do just like this. Go get some of our best harvest. That is: honey, spices, sap of sweet-smelling wood, medicine salve, kanari</bt><note reference="43:11" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab Bahasa Ibrani bilang <span class="Italic">&lt;shaqed&gt;.</span> Dia pung isi sama ke kanari.<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab says <span class="Italic">'shaqed.</span> It's contents are like kanari.</bt></note>deng kacang utan yang laen dong. Ais bawa kasi itu raja Masir pung tangan kanan, ko bilang ini kotong pung ole-ole.<bt>and other wild (jungle) nuts. Then bring them to the raja Masir's right hand, to say this is our travel-gift.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pohon pung dara = sap, getah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pohon pung dara = sap, getah ; *** (2009) kacang utan restored from earlier version</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾefoʾ: now, then mizimrat: strength, strong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾefoʾ: now, then mizimrat: strength, strong point; the best produce of the land<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>bikhleykhem: in your things, your baggage horiydu (yrd imperv): go down = go to Egypt<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>minkhah: gift, present tsəri: mastic, resin: (gummy sap) of Pistacia mutica (Zohary p. 31 P. lentiscus). In other passages Moldenke suggests that it is Balanites aegyptiaca, Jericho balsam, found in the Jordan and Dead Sea valleys<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>dəvash: honey nkoʾt: a resin (cistus-rose, rock-rose, Astragalus gummifer, A. tragacantha?)<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>loT: myrrh or stacte baTniym: pistachio nuts<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>shqediym: almonds</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Bosong ju bawa doi dua kali lipat, tagal bosong musti kasi pulang doi yang bosong dapa di bosong pung karong tempo hari tu. Mangkali itu orang dong yang bekin tasala.<bt>You also take two times the money, because you must return that money that you got in your sacks that earlier time. Probably some people who made a mistake.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi pulang doi = implies return"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi pulang doi = implies return to it's rightful place (removed accidentally) vs. kasi kambali doi (put back s.t. shouldn't have taken)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishneh: doubling muwshav (shwb hofʿal): that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mishneh: doubling muwshav (shwb hofʿal): that was returned to you<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʾamtəchoteykhem: your bags tashiyvu (shwb hif imperv): return something<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ʾuwlay: perhaps mishgeh: inadvertent mistake, oversight<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>huʾ: that (thing that happened)</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Bosong ju bawa bosong pung adi, ais capát bale pi sana, é!<bt>You also take your younger sibling, and go back there quickly, é! [EXEG: ‘be on your way again to the man’ If the intent was to return to Canaan the lexical choice in the KM should be /pulang/ ‘come home’ not /bale/ ‘return, go back’. So /bale/ is correct for KM.] [NOTE to daughter translations. CHECK that you don't use a ‘pulang’ term here. It would not be natural to say “go back to that man” in these lgs. ALT: /capát bale pi Masir/ or /capát bale pi itu orang di Masir/ would have the same impact.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Beta do'a-do'a ko Tuhan Allah yang Paling Kuasa, bekin raja Masir pung tangan kanan, ko dia rasa kasian sang bosong. Sampe dia mau kasi pulang Benyamin deng Simeon sang bosong, ko bosong samua pulang sama-sama. Ma kalo beta pung ana dong musti ilang, biar beta pikol itu susa tarús sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will hope/pray that the Lord God who Most Powerful, will make that right hand of the raja Masir, so he feels pity/love toward you. To the point that he will return Benyamin and Simeon to you, so you all return home together. But if my children have to disappear, allow me to just continually shoulder.carry that difficulty.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="do'a-do'a ko = hope, harapan dengan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">do'a-do'a ko = hope, harapan dengan permintaan, *** Deleted picture of young Benyamin, who was probably 40+ (see Gen 46:21)<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾel: very old Semitic term for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾel: very old Semitic term for deity, used in compounds rachəmiym: loving feeling, compassion, grant you mercy before him<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shakholtiy: I am bereaved of children</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais itu, dong pi kumpul ame itu ole-ole deng doi dong, ko bawa pi Masir. Dong ju bawa sang Benyamin. Sampe sana, ju dong pi mangada sang Yusuf.<bt>After that, they went to gather those travel gifts, and that money, to take to Masir. They also took Benyamin. Arriving there then, they went to face Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾanashim: men (poetic) vayaʿamdu: they stood|i(15)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾanashim: men (poetic) vayaʿamdu: they stood<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Waktu Yusuf lia Benyamin deng dia pung kaka dong, ju dia suru dia pung kapala urusan bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bawa ini orang dong pi beta pung ruma! Ais pi horo sapi satu ko bamasa ena-ena. Te nanti dong makan siang deng beta.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yusuf saw Benyamin and his elder.siblings, he told his head supervisor saying, &lt;&lt;We! Take these people to my house! Then go neck.cut one cow, to cook it deliciously. Cuz later they will eat mid.day with me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaur = KApala URusan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kaur = KApala URusan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="utəvoach tevach: prepare a slaughtering vəhakhen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">utəvoach tevach: prepare a slaughtering vəhakhen (kwn hif): prepare (meat)<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>tsahərayim: noon time</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ais, itu kapala urusan bekin iko Yusuf pung parenta. Ju dia antar bawa sang dong pi Yusuf pung ruma.<bt>Then, that head coordinator did according to Yusuf's command. And he brought them to Yusuf's house.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Waktu dong bajalan pi Yusuf pung ruma, dia pung kaka dong taku mau mati. Di tenga jalan dong ba'omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Weh! Akurang ko dia suru bawa sang kotong di sini? Jang-jangan dia mau bekin susa sang kotong, tagal itu doi yang dong su kasi kambali di kotong pung karong tempo hari tu. Dong sangaja antar kotong di sini, ko takuju sa, dong tangkap ame sang kotong ko bekin jadi dia pung budak. Abis, na, dong rampas ame kotong pung keledai samua.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they were going to Yusuf's house, his elder.siblings were exceedingly afraid. On the way they spoke [to each other] saying, &lt;&lt;Weh! Why did he say to bring us like this? Hopefully he doesn't want to cause difficulty to us, because of that money which they put back in our sacks that earlier time. They purposefully are bringing us here, in order that all.of.a.sudden, they will capture us, and make us his slaves. Then they will steal all our donkeys.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huwvʾu (bwʾ hofʿal, passive of causative):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">huwvʾu (bwʾ hofʿal, passive of causative): were brought təchillah: the first time<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>lhitgolel (gll hitpol roll): fall upon, attack ləhitnappel (npl hitpaʿel): attack<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Andia ko, waktu dong su deka-deka Yusuf pung ruma, ju dong omong deng itu kapala urusan bilang,<bt>That's why, when they were getting close to Yusuf house, then they spoke to that head coordinator saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiggəshu: they approached him petach: opening|i(19)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiggəshu: they approached him petach: opening<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />&lt;&lt;Pak! Botong minta ma'af, te tempo hari botong su parná datang béli makanan di sini.<bt>&lt;&lt;Father! We apologize, cuz earlier we once ame to buy food here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bi ʾadonai: to open a conversation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bi ʾadonai: to open a conversation with a superior, "excuse me, sir, but ..." = "may any bad consequences of what I say affect me" yarod yaradnu: we came (down) here to Egypt. Why the infinitive absolute? politeness, with biy?<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>təchillah: the first time, the beginning</Message></Annotation><v n="21-22" />Ais waktu botong pulang kampong, botong barenti di jalan ko mau tidor. Tarús botong buka karong ko mau kasi makan binatang dong. Tau-tau te botong dapa kambali satu-satu pung doi béli padi tu, dalam karong. Botong sonde tau sapa yang taro di situ! Ma sakarang botong su bawa pulang itu doi dong samua. Jadi pak jang mara, ó! Biar pak tau, sakarang botong ju ada bawa doi laen lai, ko mau béli makanan baru.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then when we return to our village, we stopped on the road to sleep. Then we opened a sack to give food to the animals. Who would know, (unexpectedly) cuz we each one got returned our money from buying that padi, inside the sack. We do not know who put it there! But now we have returned all that money. So Father, don't be angry [=we're sorry]. Just so Father knows, now we have also brought other money, to buy new food.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ais, itu kapala urusan manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong tanáng sa! Sonde usa taku! Mangkali bosong pung Tuhan yang kasi berkat sang bosong dalam itu karong dong. Tempo hari, beta su tarima bosong pung doi samua, ma. Bosong sonde ada utang lai!&gt;&gt; Ais ju dia lapás kasi kaluar sang Simeon pi dong.<bt>Then, that head coordinator replied saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl just be quiet/at.peace! There's no need to be afraid. Probably that God of yours, who gave the blessing to you in those sacks. Earlier, I had already received all of your money [+assertion]. You don't have any debt!&gt;&gt; Then he released exited Simeon to them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bmishqalo: as he had weighed it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bmishqalo: as he had weighed it out, by weight (= what he paid) shalom: being whole, intact, at ease, unaffected, in good shape<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>maTmon: hidden treasure shimʿown: Simeon<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>vayyowtseʾ (ytsʾ hif narr): he brought him out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Tarús dong samua maso pi dalam Yusuf pung ruma. Ais, itu kapala urusan kasi aer ko dong cuci kasi barisi dong pung kaki. Dia ju kasi makan dong pung keledai dong.<bt>Then they all entered inside Yusuf's house. Then, that head coordinator gave water for them to wash clean their feet. And he also gave food for their donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyirchətsuw (rkhts narr): they washed feet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyirchətsuw (rkhts narr): they washed feet miSpoʾ: fodder<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ais dia kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Nanti bosong makan siang sama-sama deng bos.&gt;&gt; Waktu dong masi tunggu-tunggu Yusuf pung datang, dong ator memang dong pung ole-ole.<bt>Then he told saying, &lt;&lt;Later you will eat mid.day together with boss.&gt;&gt; While they were still waiting for Yusuf to come, they went ahead and arranged their travel.gifts.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyakhiynuw (kwn hif): they made it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyakhiynuw (kwn hif): they made it ready</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Waktu Yusuf sampe, ju dong samua tikam lutut di dia pung muka. Ais dong sorong dong pung ole-ole dong kasi sang dia.<bt>When Yusuf arrived then, they all bowed at his face. Then they extended their travel.gifts, to him. [EXEG: order of bowing and giving. In my limited Hebrew, the conjunction used is normally glossed ‘and, also, even’. NRSV, NLT, CEV, NET all say ‘and’. LXX uses /kai/ ‘and’. So these events are not critically ordered, just juxtaposed. In local RL cultures bowing first shows proper respect. Doing something else first and then bowing evokes “How rude? Don't they know proper adat?” Or perhaps they forgot something that everyone should know. Since the Hebrew is not actually ordered, we have felt justified in reordering this so as to not skew the focus of non-critical events. Unfortunately the TB uses /lalu/ here, which orders the events. KM /ju/ would better mirror the neutral Heb, but since it is required in the previous clause, stylistically we cannot use it here. That's why we use the slightly less satisfactory /abis/ here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ais Yusuf tanya sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana? Bosong samua babae, ko? Karmana deng bosong pung papa yang su tua tu? Dia ju ada babae, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf asked them saying, &lt;&lt;How is it? Are you all well, [+tag question]? How is that papa of yours who is old? He's also well, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Pak pung hamba tua, yang botong pung papa barana ada babae sa.&gt;&gt; Ju dong tondo ko kasi hormat lai sang dia.<bt>They answered saying, &lt;&lt;Father's old servant, who is our birth father is well, Father.&gt;&gt; And they bowed to give honor again to him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jilat = scurry favour, brown-nose (Timor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">jilat = scurry favour, brown-nose (Timor tulu-fufu (kneel, cover mouth, stretch out back of neck))</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ais itu, Yusuf buang mata kuliling, sampe dia dapa lia dia pung adi Benyamin. Dong dua tu, satu bapa, satu mama. Ju dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Ooo! Andia ni, bosong pung adi bungsu yang bosong su carita tempo hari tu, ko?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yusuf look around, until he saw his younger sibling Benyamin. The two of them had the same father, same mother. And he said, &lt;&lt;Ooo! This here, your youngest sibling whom you told about before, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais dia omong deng Benyamin bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana, é! Beta do'a-do'a ko Tuhan Allah kasi berkat bam-banya sang lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke with Benyamin saying, &lt;&lt;Child! I pray/hope that the Lord God will give lots of blessing to you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tamba bam-banya sadiki dolo!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tamba bam-banya sadiki dolo!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yahənkha (chnn): may God be gracious"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yahənkha (chnn): may God be gracious to you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Lia sang Benyamin tu, Yusuf pung rindu su mau tapo'a kaluar. Te dia sayang mau mati dia pung adi na. Dia su sonde bisa tahan dia pung hati lai. Ju dia capát-capát kasi tenga sang dong, ko maso pi dia pung kamar. Ais dia manangis maskakeduk di situ.<bt>Seeing Benyamin there, Yusuf's longing was ready to pour out. Cuz he obviously loved that younger sibling of his very much. He could no longer control his liver anymore. So he quickly left them, to enter his room. Then he cried with.great.sobs there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymaher: he hurried nikhmaru (kmr hof):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaymaher: he hurried nikhmaru (kmr hof): was agitated, emotional (Pidgin "funny kine" refers more to unfamiliar or abnormal or undefined feelings than to humor.)<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>rachəmayw: his love, compassion livkot (bkh cry): to weep<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>chadrah (cheder): to a chamber</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Manangis abis, ju dia pi cuci muka. Dia bekin tanáng dia pung hati, ais dia kaluar pi katumu sang dong. Ju dia suru dia pung pambantu dong pi ator meja.<bt>Finishing crying then, he went to wash his face. He made his liver calm, then he went out to meet them. And he told his helpers/servants to arrange the table.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyirchats: he washed vayitʾappaq (hitpaʿel): pulled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyirchats: he washed vayitʾappaq (hitpaʿel): pulled himself together, restrained himself, collected himself<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>shimu: put the food where it belongs, bring on the food</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ais dong taro kasi Yusuf makan di meja sandiri. Dia pung kaka-adi dong makan di meja laen. Dia pung staf orang Masir dong, ju makan di dong pung meja sandiri, tagal orang Masir dong rasa noju dudu makan bacampor deng orang Ibrani.<bt>Then they put Yusuf's food on a table alone. His elder-younger sibling's food on another table. His Masir staff, also ate at their own table. Because Masir people feel grossed.out sitting eating mixed with Ibrani people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hina = rendahkan diri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">hina = rendahkan diri</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləvado: by himself, at a separate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ləvado: by himself, at a separate table loʾ yukhlun: they cannot<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>toʿevah: abhorrent, loathsome, detestable (cultic, then moral)</Message></Annotation><note reference="43:32" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Orang Masir noju sang orang Isra'el, tagal orang Isra'el, tukang jaga kambing-domba.<bt>The People of Masir were grossed-out with the Israel people, because the Israel people, were people who HAB watched goats-sheep.</bt></note><v n="33" />Itu kapala urusan su ator ko Yusuf pung kaka-adi dong dudu bamangada deng Yusuf. Dia ator sang dong satu-satu dudu iko dong pung umur, mulai dari yang paling kaka sampe yang paling adi. Waktu dong lia cara ator dudu bagitu, dong heran.<bt>That head coordinator had arranged so that Yusuf's elder.younger siblings sat facing Yusuf. He arranged them each one sitting following their age, starting from the most eldest to the most youngest. When they saw the sitting arrangement like that, they were amazed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəkhor: firstborn tsaʿir: youngest|i(33) (33) |rvayyitməhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bəkhor: firstborn tsaʿir: youngest<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>vayyitməhu (tmh): they look in astonishment, stunned, benumbed, transfixed with astonishment reʿehu: the one they had dealings with, their friend<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Ais Yusuf ator ko pambantu dong ame kasi dia pung kaka-adi dong makanan dari dia pung meja sandiri. Dong samua tarima sama banya. Ma dong taro kasi Benyamin pung, lebe banya lima kali dari dia pung kaka dong. Ais ju dong samua makan-minum sampe takinyang-kinyang.<bt>Then Yusuf arranged for the helpers to take his elder.younger sibling's food from his own table. They all received the same amount. But they put Benyamin's, five times more than his elder.siblings. Then they all ate-drank until full-full.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="masʾot: share vayishkru: got drunk|i(34) (34)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">masʾot: share vayishkru: got drunk<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>terev (rbh): it was more yadot: hands, five times<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>vayyishtuw: they drank vayyishkəruw: they got drunk with him<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf pung mok perak ilang<bt>Yusuf's silver mug is lost</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="44" />
      <v n="1" />Dong makan abis, ju Yusuf bakusu-kusu deng dia pung kapala urusan bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pi isi ini orang dong pung karong satu-satu deng padi sampe ponu. Ais lu taro ulang dong pung doi pi dalam satu-satu pung karong.<bt>They finished eating, then Yusuf whispered to his head coordinator saying, &lt;&lt;You go fill these people's sack each one with padi until its full. Then you put again their money inside each one's sack.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bakusu-kusu = bisik, whisper in ear"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bakusu-kusu = bisik, whisper in ear slowly and clearly</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This scene is the peak of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">This scene is the peak of the Joseph and Judah story. They were the ancestors of the two major forces in Hebrew society for the next 600 years. vaytsav (tswh piel impf): give order, command<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>malleʾ (piʿel imperv): fill ʾamtəchot: sacks, bags<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʾokhel: food yukhlun: they are able [to hold]<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>sʾit (nsʾ inf): to carry sim (imperv): put<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ais lu ame beta pung mok perak, ko taro pi di ana bungsu pung karong.&gt;&gt; Ju dia pi bekin iko Yusuf pung parenta.<bt>Then you take my silver mug to put it in the youngest child's sack.&gt;&gt; And he went to do according to that order of Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gviʿi gviaʿ: my drinking bowl tasim"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gviʿi gviaʿ: my drinking bowl tasim - imperfect after imperatives, but not initial. It's the cup that is fronted.<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>shivru (shever cs): his grain The rabbis assumed that the brothers already knew that their money had been returned, perhaps as compensation for all that Joseph has put them through. But if Joseph's manager was conducting a search of their bags, he would not have let them see the money that was there.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Dia pung beso papagi, ju Yusuf lapás sang dong ko pulang bawa makanan deng dong pung keledai.<bt>The next day early morning, Yusuf released them to go home taking food with their donkeys.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾur (ʾwr partcpl): as it was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾur (ʾwr partcpl): as it was becoming day; the morning became light, grew light vhaʾanoshim: v- may be consecutive to haboker ʾor; but it is on the noun. Maybe it has something to do with hemah?<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>shullchu (puʿal): were sent away [who sent them?], they were allowed to go hemmah: they<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>chəmoreyhem: their donkeys</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dong balóm jalan talalu jao dari kota, ju Yusuf kasi tau dia pung kapala urusan bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pi buru iko itu orang dong capát-capát. Kalo su katumu sang dong, lu bilang bagini: &lt;Akurang ko bosong pung hati culas deng bapatua? Ko bosong balas dia pung bae deng jahat bagini!<bt>They had not yet traveled very far out of the city, then Yusuf told his head coordinator saying, &lt;&lt;You go chase follow those people quickly. When you meet up with them, you say like this: 'Why are your livers swollen toward the big man? How is it that you return his good with evil like this!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="culas = hati bengko; buru ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">culas = hati bengko; buru = kejar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hem yatsʾu (pf): they went forth,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hem yatsʾu (pf): they went forth, went on their way et: they left that particular city; also Ecclesiastes 7:18 (usually takes min)<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>hirchiqu (hif): they went far rdof: set off after them to catch up to them, can be hostile<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>hissagtam (nsg hif): reach, overtake shillamtem (piʿel): you repay, balance things out<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>raʿah: evil tachat: instead of<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Karmana ko bosong sampe hati pancuri bawa bos pung mok perak? Bosong sonde tau, ko? Itu bukan bos pung mok minum sa! Dia ju pake itu mok ko cari tau orang pung nasib. Te itu mok ilmu na! Bosong pung bekin ni, memang su talalu jahat!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>How is it that you-pl got to the point that your liver stole took boss' silver mug? You don't know, right? That is not just boss' drinking mug. He also uses that mug to foretell people's fate. That's a divination mug [and you should know that]! What you've done here, is really exceedingly evil!'"</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishteh: (shth imperf): would drink. Also"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishteh: (shth imperf): would drink. Also Psa 105. nachesh (piel) ynachesh (piʿel imperf: can seek and give omens, practice divination, learn things through divination, find out unknown information<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>hreʿotem (rʿʿ hif): you do evil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00749c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Dong dapa itu mok perak di Benyamin pung karong<bt>They get/find the silver cup inside Benyamin's gunny-sack</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ais ju itu kapala urusan pi buru sang dong sampe dapa. Ju dia kasi tau sang dong, iko Yusuf pung omong tadi.<bt>And then, that head coordinator went to chase them until he got them. Then he told them, according to what Yusuf had said earlier.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayassigem (nsg): overtake, catch up with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayassigem (nsg): overtake, catch up with</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais dong protes bilang, &lt;&lt;Pak pung maksud karmana ni? Botong sumpa. Botong sonde mungkin bekin jahat bagitu!<bt>Then they protested saying, &lt;&lt;What are you meaning her, Father? We swear. It's impossible that we would have done evil like that!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chalilah: aversive, negative interjection: far be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chalilah: aversive, negative interjection: far be it from us meʿəsot (ʿsh inf cs): to do<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Pak sandiri su tau, to? Itu doi dong dalam botong pung karong tempo hari tu, botong su kasi kambali sang pak, to? Jadi, karmana ko botong bisa pancuri bos pung mas ko perak dari dia pung ruma! Sonde mungkin!<bt>Father (you) yourself already knows, right? Those moneys in our sack that earlier time, we have returned to Father, right? So (consequently), how could we still boss's gold or silver from his house! Impossible!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: here it is! ʾamtchotenu: our"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hen: here it is! ʾamtchotenu: our sacks<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>heshivonu (shwv hif): we brought it back ʾekh: how?<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>nignov: we steal ʾo: or<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Pak pareksa sa! Dapa itu barang di sapa pung karong, hukum mati sang dia suda! Deng biar botong yang laen ni, jadi pak pung budak sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Father just go ahead and inspect! Find that think in whoever's sack, give him the death penalty [imperative]! And even let the rest of us here, just become your slave.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kuli = kerja kasar di luar;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kuli = kerja kasar di luar; jongos di dalam ruma</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Joseph created a lot of possible"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Joseph created a lot of possible outcomes, any one of which would benefit him. He wanted Benjamin and he wanted his father; reconciling with his brothers may have been a lower priority. yimmatseʾ (mtsʾ nif impf): is found, is discovered<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>mit (mwt): he dies, let him die nihyeh: we will become<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais, itu kapala urusan bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde! Bagini sa. Kalo dapa itu mok di sapa, na, dia jadi beta pung kuli. Yang laen bole pulang.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, that head coordinator said, &lt;&lt;No! Just like this. If I find that mug in whoever, now he will become my kuli. The rest may return home.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam-ʿatah: The servant takes the brothersʾ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gam-ʿatah: The servant takes the brothersʾ rash statement as meant, not as uttered. He gives them the benefit of the doubt (we are honest men), so he softens his restatement of the consequences if the cup is found. ken-huʾ: thus it; if that's how it is<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ʾatem: you guys nəqiyim (naqi pl): innocent, exempt from blame, free<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ju dong kasi turun capát-capát itu karong dong. Tarús dong buka memang.<bt>Then they quickly took down their sacks. Straight away they went ahead and opened them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymahəru (piʿel cs): they hurried, acted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaymahəru (piʿel cs): they hurried, acted quickly vayoridu (yrd hif): they took down<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ais, itu kapala urusan pareksa alus-alus itu karong dong satu-satu, mulai dari yang paling kaka pung karong, sampe yang paling kici pung. Ju dia dapa lia itu mok perak di Benyamin pung karong.<bt>Then, that head coordinator carefully inspected each of those sacks, starting from the eldest's sack, until the smallest. And he found that silver mug in Benyamin's sack.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaychappes (chfs piʿel): look thoroughly for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaychappes (chfs piʿel): look thoroughly for something hechel (chll hif pf): begin<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>killah (klh piʿel pf): finish, end with yimmatseʾ: was found. It doesn't mention the money; with the manager conducting the search, he would not have let them see what he saw.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lia bagitu, ju Benyamin pung kaka dong pung hati ancor-ancor. Ais dong kasi nae kambali itu karong dong di atas keledai, ju dong bale pi kota.<bt>Seeing that then, Benyamin's elder.siblings livers were destroyed. Then they put back up those sacks on the donkeys, then they returned to the city. [EXEG: 1) Typical of symbolic action, “tearing clothes” carries different meaning in different cultures. The ref in 37:34 has a) action, plus b) meaning, plus c) explanatory footnote. That is an indication of how problematic it is. In this context Marge encouraged us to just go for the meaning so the action (normally indicating rage or being crazy) wouldn't skew the focus. 2) Referent tracking: ‘they’ doesn't work here, because grammatically it would track to the /kepala urusan/ and whoever his assumed /ana bua/ might be. The Heb ‘they’ is vague in this context-whether it includes Benjamin or not. Hamilton explicitly excludes Benjamin from this reaction of those responsible for Benjamin who have made promises to their father. CEV and TH use of ‘brothers’ also seems to exclude Benjamin. Trying to include Benjamin in the reaction would require heavy over-translation, and also miss the social impact of the panic of the brothers responsible for him.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqrʿu: tear, tear into pieces simlotam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiqrʿu: tear, tear into pieces simlotam: their mantles (heavy outside robes)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>vayaʿmoS: they loaded the animals khamoro: his male donkey<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>vayashuvu (shuv): they went back</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Waktu dong sampe di Yusuf pung ruma, dia masi ada di situ. Ju dong tikam lutut di dia pung muka.<bt>When they arrived at Yusuf's house, [background info] he was still there. And they bowed in front of his face.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾechaw: his brothers ʿodennu: still him|i(14)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾechaw: his brothers ʿodennu: still him<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>vayippəlu (npl): threw themselves down, get down quickly, fling themselves down. A unique way of putting it, not the ordinary ceremonial "bowing to the ground."</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ais Yusuf masparak sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Heh! Akurang ko bosong bekin beta bagini! Bosong sonde tau bilang, orang bésar ke beta ni, bisa pake ilmu ko cari tau orang pung rahasia?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yusuf spoke.angrily with them saying, &lt;&lt;He! Why did you do like that to me! Don't you know that a big person like me here, can use divination to know people's secrets?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʿaseh: deed nachesh (piʿel inf) ynachesh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">maʿaseh: deed nachesh (piʿel inf) ynachesh (piʿel imperf): he divines; he can certainly divine<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>ʾish asher kamoni: a man such as I</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais Yahuda manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Tuhan Allah su kasi talanjang botong pung sala dong. Ais botong mau bilang apa lai, pak? Botong mau bela diri karmana lai. Kalo pak mau tahan sang botong pung adi bungsu ni, na, lebe bae pak tahan botong samua. Ame botong samua jadi pak pung budak sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yahuda answered saying, &lt;&lt;Awi! The Lord God has made naked our sins. So what else can we say, Father! How else can we defend ourselves. If Father wants to detain our youngest sibling here [+assertion], it's best Father detail us all. Just take us all to be Father's slaves.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi talanjang sala = malu, caught"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi talanjang sala = malu, caught red-handed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nitsTadaq (tsdq hitp): prove ourselves to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nitsTadaq (tsdq hitp): prove ourselves to be innocent ʿavon: activity that is crooked or wrong, conscious, intentional offense, sin, guilt incurred by an offense, punishment. ʾet: the specific evil thing?<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>hinnennu (particle, 1pl suf): here we are gam: both ... and<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>nimtsaʾ (mtsʾ nif): was found, was caught bayado: in his hand, under his control<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ma Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde! Dapa itu mok di sapa, na, dia tu yang jadi beta pung kuli! Bosong yang laen dong, bebas. Pulang pi bosong pung papa suda!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yusuf replied saying, &lt;&lt;No! Find that mug in whoever, na, he is the one who will become my kuli! Your others, free. Return home to your papa [imperative]!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chalilah: far be it from me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chalilah: far be it from me lshalom: being whole, intact, in prosperity, peace, unaffected, whole, unmolested. Joseph is planning ahead move by move like a chess player.<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yahuda minta ko dia ganti sang Benyamin<bt>Yahuda requests to replace Benyamin</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ais itu, Yahuda pi deka-deka sang Yusuf, ju omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Pak wakil! Beta tau pak pung kuasa sama ke raja sandiri. Tagal itu, jang mara sang beta dolo. Te beta parmisi minta ba'omong sadiki deng pak.<bt>After that, Yahuda went close to Yusuf, and spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Father vice(raja)! I know Father's authority is like the raja himself. Because of that, don't be angry with me. Cuz I as permission to speak a bit with Father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiggash (ngsh): step up, come near,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiggash (ngsh): step up, come near, approach. This passage is important enough that Jewish tradition gives the section the title Vayiggash. Here Judah assumes the guilt for Joseph's disappearance and takes the responsibility. In the entire chapter, everything Judah says and everything Joseph says have to go through interpreters, and Joseph has to pretend he doesn't understand Judah. bi ʾadoni ydaber-naʾ: with your permission, on me, my lord, let there come whatever unwelcome or hurtful thing our conversation might bring<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>naʾ: please, urgency bʾazney ʾadoni: in the ear of my lord<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>vʾal-yichar ʾapkha (chrh impf): donʾt burn, donʾt become angry, break out ki khamokha: since you are like Pharaoh. Identical in some regard; you can be as deadly or as forgiving as Pharaoh. Josh 14:11, 1Sm 30:24; Ez 18:4; Dn 11:29; Jdg 8:18; Is 24:2 not exactly being said that the first thing is like the second, nor that the second is like the first, but that the first is like the second AND the second is like the first. Gn 18:25, Lv 7:7, Lv 24.16, Gn 44:18, Hg 2:3, Ec 9:2<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Kamaren pak su tanya sang botong bilang, &lt;Bosong pung papa deng adi yang satu masi ada, ko?&gt;<bt>Yesterday Father asked us saying, &lt;Your papa and your one younger sibling, still living, right?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaʾal: asked ʿvadaw (sg): your slave|i(19)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shaʾal: asked ʿvadaw (sg): your slave<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00744c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Yahuda pi deka-deka sang Yusuf<bt>Yahuda approaches Yusuf</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ais botong manyao bilang, &lt;Botong pung papa su tua. Deng ada ju botong pung adi bungsu satu. Waktu barana sang dia, papa su tua. Itu adi bungsu pung kaka barana ada satu, ma dia su mati. Dong dua pung mama su mati ju. Jadi sakarang, tenga adi bungsu sandiri sa. Andia ko, botong pung papa sayang mau mati sang dia.&gt;<bt>Then we answered saying, 'Our papa is old. And also there is our one youngest sibling. When giving birth to him, papa was old. That youngest sibling had one birth elder.sibling, but he's dead. Them two's mama is dead. So (consequently) now, there only just the youngest younger sibling alone. That's why, our papa loves him exceedingly.' [EXEG: “their mother is dead”. Context plus discourse (foreground-background). In vs.19-34 Yahuda is trying to build a sob story about how detaining Benjamin would effect Jacob. Hamilton points out “In the second subsection (vv. 24-29) Judah again places special emphasis on their father’s inability to survive without Benjamin,…” But the way these lgs want background info before event line info this info goes in vs. 20. Implicit to explicit to carry speaker attitude and urgency the way RL would tell the story.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="punya can be used propositionally dia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">punya can be used propositionally dia punya kaka barana satu; jadi used propositionally ; *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Why does Moses go into such"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Why does Moses go into such detail in this scene? Longacre may have an answer. David Klines, who has written the definitive lexicon in 9 volumes, addresses it in _The Theme of the Pentateuch_. This section develops Judah's character. When the brothers sold Joseph, probably none of them had children of their own. Since then, Judah has gone through the loss of two sons and Tamar's decisive acton to perpetuate his line. At the same time, he has seen his father mourning Joseph for years; and now that he has lost his, he knows from experience how his action has torn up his father. He is determined that no traumatic agony like that will happen again with Benjamin. So the question of Benjamin's actual guilt or innocence never comes up. zaqen: old<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>zqunim: time and circumstance of the aged, in his old age qatan: small, young<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>met: he died. Rashi comments that Joseph doesn't ask about the dead brother. He's not playing games; he wants to know about his father. vayyiwater (ytr nif): is left over, remains over<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>lvadow: alone, in solitude ʾahevo: loves him<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais pak suru botong bawa datang botong pung adi tu, ko pak bisa lia sang dia.<bt>Then Father told us to bring here that younger sibling of ours, so that Father could see him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="horiduhu (yrd hif imperv): bring down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">horiduhu (yrd hif imperv): bring down (to Egypt) vʾasimah (sym): so I can put my eyes on him. v- gives the consequence here; little logical apparatus, but a lot of causal ties. Sarna "So I can pay special attention to him"; but bringing Benjamin there in the first place was the proof Joseph needed that they were genuine, or as he put it to them, "not spies."<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʿeyni: my eyes</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ju botong manyao bilang, itu ana sonde bisa kasi tenga dia pung papa. Kalo dia kasi tenga, na, botong pung papa su mati, andia tu.<bt>And we replied saying that child cannot leave his papa. If he leaves [it's obvious], our papa would die, that how it is.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="su...andia tu and that's the way"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">su...andia tu and that's the way it is, there's no two ways about it. Speaker attitude expressing emphatic certainty; not how Ena/Yanto would say it, but they understand it and accept it ~ andia bagitu suda!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanaʿar: the young man, marriageable male"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hanaʿar: the young man, marriageable male while still single laʿazov, ʿazav: leave behind, abandon. hypothetical situation + result given again without "if."<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Tarús pak manyao bilang, &lt;Kalo bosong sonde bawa sang bosong pung adi tu, na, bosong sonde bisa lia beta pung muka lai.&gt;<bt>Next Pak replied saying, 'If you don't bring that younger sibling of yours, na, you may not look at my face again.'</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yered: come down to Egypt tosifun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yered: come down to Egypt tosifun (ysf hif): add, increase, go on, do something again. Joseph knows how long the famine is going to last, and this is probably the early part of it. So he knows the brothers will have to come again for more grain.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ais ju botong pulang. Sampe di papa, ju botong kasi tau pak pung omong samua tu.<bt>And then we returned home. Arriving at Papa, then we told all that Father (you) had said.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿalinu (ʿlh): go up, go to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿalinu (ʿlh): go up, go to Palestine vanaged-lo (ngd): reported to him<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Lama-lama ju botong pung makanan su abis. Ais papa suru botong datang ulang di Masir ko béli makanan lai.<bt>After a while then, our food ran out. Then papa told us to come again to Masir to buy more food.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shivru (imper): buy grain mʿat: little"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shivru (imper): buy grain mʿat: little bit<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Ma botong balas bilang, &lt;Papa, é! Botong sonde bisa pi sana lai. Te raja pung tangan kanan su bilang, kalo botong sonde bawa botong pung adi bungsu, na, botong sonde bisa lia dia pung muka. Jadi botong pung adi bungsu musti iko dolo, baru botong jalan.&gt;<bt>But we replied saying, 'Papa! We can't go there again! Cuz that raja's right hand, has said, if we don't bring this youngest sibling here, we many not see his face. So our youngest sibling must go, only then can we travel.'</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nukhal (ykl): we can only go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nukhal (ykl): we can only go there. Hypothetical at this point. yaradnu: we go down to Egypt<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>ʾenenu (3sg suf): he is not there. Judah is appealing to Joseph as a man, on humanitarian grounds.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ais itu, botong pung papa omong lai bilang, &lt;Bosong su tau, to? Beta pung bini Rahel pung ana cuma dua sa.<bt>After that, our papa spoke again saying, &lt;You-pl know, right? That wife Rahel of mine, had only just two children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾishti: Only Rachel counts. Judah by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾishti: Only Rachel counts. Judah by now is mature and has had children of his own. He can accept the fact that Rachel is the favorite wife, not his mother Leah. Parallel to Esau coming to terms with what Jacob had done to him.</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Ana yang partama su sonde ada lai. Pasti binatang utan su kodo ame sang dia. Andia ko sampe sakarang, beta sonde dapa lia sang dia lai.<bt>The first child is no longer. Surely a jungle animal has swallowed taking him. That's why until now, I have not seen him again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetseʾ: he has gone out haʾechad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yetseʾ: he has gone out haʾechad: one of them<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʾakh: surely, assurance or emphasis. Also restrictive and contrastive. It narrows down the options: the only thing left for me to conclude is that the lions got him. tarof toraf (trf pual): torn in pieces by wild animals<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>rʾitiw: I will not see him. Jewish commentators regard Jacob as still holding out a hope that Joseph is alive -- the evidence is that he's dead, but maybe Iʾll see him now. ʿad: during, continuing; unto<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>hennah: 3fem pl. Owens treats -h as locative. Up to now?</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Kalo bosong ame ini ana bungsu dari beta lai, tarús dia kaná calaka, na, bosong bekin tamba susa beta yang su tua ni, ko beta mati memang.&gt;<bt>If you take this youngest child from me again, then he gets affected by some disaster, na, you will make me who is already old even more distress, so that I will die.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ulqachtem: you are taking hold of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ulqachtem: you are taking hold of him, seizing. The u- has conditional force. meʿim: away from [with] my presence<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>qarahu (qrh): befalls him ʾason: mortal accident<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>horadtem (yrd hif): you will bring down seyvati: my gray-headedness<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>braʿah: in evil, harm. In 47:8 when Jacob meets Pharaoh he says his years are "few and raʿah," so it must have been a major part of his mindset that life is crummy.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30-31" />Bagini, pak wakil. Kalo beta kambali pi papa, deng sonde bawa ini adi bungsu, pasti botong pung papa su mati, andia tu. Ko dia pung jiwa ta'ika deng ini ana na. Dia su talalu tua, sampe kalo botong bekin tamba susa sang dia, pasti dia mati.<bt>That's why, Mr. vice. If I return to papa, without bring this youngest sibling, surely our papa will die, that's why. Because his soul is obviously tied up with child. And he is too old, to the point that if make any more difficulty for him, surely he will die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʿatah: and now ʾenenu: he is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʿatah: and now ʾenenu: he is not there; Samaritan Pentateuch and translations have ʾitanu (wit us)<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>qshurah (qshr partcpl fem): tied up together, bound together met: he will die. Some translators read "and the boy dies"; but Jacob is both topic and subject of the whole sequence.<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>byagon: torment, trouble</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Tamba lai, beta su bajanji deng papa bilang, beta yang jamin ini ana. Beta bajanji sang papa, kalo beta sonde bawa bale ini ana pi dia, na biar beta tanggong itu sala sampe mati.<bt>And also, I have promised papa saying, I am the one who promises that child. I promised papa, if I don't bring back that child to him, well hold me responsible for that wrong until death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jamin = tanggung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">jamin = tanggung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿarav: stand surety for him, pledge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿarav: stand surety for him, pledge myself, mortgage my life (like cosigning a note) ʾviʾenu (bwʾ hif): I bring him. v- is hypothetical<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>chataʾti: I have been guilty</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Jadi beta minta bagini, pak: biar beta sa yang tenga di sini ganti dia, jadi pak pung budak. Biar dia pulang deng dia pung kaka dong.<bt>So I request like this, Father: Allow me to stay here to replace him, so that it's just me who becomes's Father's kuli. Allow him to return home with his elder siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeshev-naʾ: may your servant stay. The"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeshev-naʾ: may your servant stay. The series of jussives is very deferential. But the proposal is bizarre in terms of known Near Eastern laws. tachat: instead of. The first place the idea of substitution comes up = hyper<span class="Italic">(33) (33) </span>yaʿal: go up to Palestine</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Kalo ini ana sonde iko, na, beta ju sonde bisa pulang. Beta sonde bisa tahan lia papa pung sangsara sampe mati.&gt;&gt;<bt>If that child doesn't follow well [+assertion], I also can't go home. I can't stand to see papa distressed until death.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾekh: how? yimtsaʾ: will find, will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾekh: how? yimtsaʾ: will find, will happen to<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf kasi kanál dia pung diri, deng minta dia pung papa dong pinda pi Masir<bt>Yusuf introduces himself, and requests his papa them to move to Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="45" />
      <v n="1" />Dengar bagitu, ju Yusuf pung hati noe sampe sonde bisa tahan lai di dia pung pagawe dong pung muka. Andia ko dia suru dong kaluar, ko dia bisa tenga sandiri deng dia pung kaka-adi dong. Deng bagitu, dia bisa mangaku dia pung diri tu, sapa.<bt>Hearing that then, Yusuf liver was melting to the point.that he could endure anymore in front of his civil.servants. That's why he ordered them to go out, so that he could be alone with his elder-younger siblings. Like that, he could confess who he was.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lhitʾappeq (hif): pull himself together, collect"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lhitʾappeq (hif): pull himself together, collect himself, restrain himself. With "But," this gives the idea he canʾt control himself. hanitstsavim (nif partcpl): the ones standing, stationed; not milling around like a cocktail party<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʿalaw, maʿalay: does this mean Joseph was seated and they were standing? or were they facing him? Or were they his bosses? hotsiyʾu (ytsʾ hif): let everybody go out!<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>ʿamad: to stand; to stand (before), i.e. serve, minister to; to be set over; to confide in; to stand by hitwaddaʿ (ydʿ hitp): when he made himself known. Use of "wen" here is interesting<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ais, itu pagawe dong samua kaluar, ju Yusuf manangis makarereu karás-karás, sampe orang Masir dong di luar itu kamar dapa dengar. Deng orang-orang di raja pung ruma ju dapa dengar.<bt>Then, those civil.servants all went.out, and Yusuf cried loudly in great sobs. Until the Masir people outside that room could hear. And the people in the raja's house also could hear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="makarereu = not holding back; maskakeduk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">makarereu = not holding back; maskakeduk = holding back a little</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bivakhi: in weeping. Joseph canʾt do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bivakhi: in weeping. Joseph canʾt do anything but bawl and let it all come out. min: because of his expression? in front of him?<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais Yusuf kasi tau tarús taráng sang dia pung sodara dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Kaka-adi dong, é! Beta ni Yusuf, bosong pung sodara! Papa memang masi idop, to?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf told openly to his siblings saying, &lt;&lt;We! Elder-younger siblings! I here am Yusuf, your sibling! Papa really is still living, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar bagitu, ju dia pung kaka-adi dong taku mau mati, sampe dong sonde bisa omong apa-apa lai.<bt>Hearing that, immediately his elder-younger siblings were exceedingly afraid, to the point that they could not say anything more.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hedek = pull back, put distance"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">hedek = pull back, put distance between</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nivhlu (bhl nif): were terrified, out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nivhlu (bhl nif): were terrified, out of their senses</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ais ju Yusuf gape sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Mari bosong datang deka-deka di sini dolo.&gt;&gt;<bt>And then Yusuf hand-motioned them [to come] saying, &lt;&lt;We! Come over here close [mild imperative].&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dong pi deka deng Yusuf. Tarús dia omong ulang bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni Yusuf, yang tempo hari bosong jual buang pi Masir.<bt>And they went close to Yusuf. Then he spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;I here am Yusuf, the one who before you sold disposing of to Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gshu-naʾ (ngsh): approach, come near, step"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gshu-naʾ (ngsh): approach, come near, step up naʾ: entreaty? permission? A great man doesn't use naʾ; it's for a subordinate speaking to his superior. So suddenly the relationship is different.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>mkhartem: you sold. The repetition of "I am Joseph" does not indicate a second source; Joseph has to penetrate their state of shock, and they canʾt believe what is happening. mitsraymah: into [slavery in] Egypt (locative)<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Bosong memang su jual buang sang beta. Ma bosong jang taku, deng jang bakanjar kasi sala satu deng satu lai. Padahal, Tuhan Allah sandiri yang bawa beta datang di sini lebe dolo dari bosong. Ko deng bagitu, Dia pake sang beta ko kasi salamat banya orang, ko dong jang mati lapar.<bt>You actually sold disposing of me. But you don't be afraid, and don't go blaming each other anymore. Actually, it was the Lord God himself who brought me to here ahead of you. So.that with that, He use me to save many people. So.that they don't die of hunger. [EXEG: “angry with yourselves” (lit. do not become hot in your eyes; do not blaze up in your eyes). Note the English “angry with yourselves” is ambiguous between reflexive (internal and individual) versus reciprocal (external and social “with each other”). MC explicitly pushed us toward the latter interpretation, as it reflects a recurring higher-level theme/pattern of behaviour exibited throughout the Joseph story, from ch.37 right up to chapter 50 after Jacob dies. Since “don't be afraid/distressed/worried” already carries the internal sense, we take the second as deliberately dealing with the relational issue, which Joseph knows is a perenniel problem with his brothers.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jang bakanjar kasi sala satu deng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">jang bakanjar kasi sala satu deng satu = jang batola-bahela = don't go around accusing each other ; *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-teʿatsvu: do not be distressed, worried,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-teʿatsvu: do not be distressed, worried, grieve vʾal-yikhar (khrh): do not become hot, angry<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>bʿehekhem: in your own eyes, angry with yourselves? hinah: to here<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>lmikhyah: for preservation of life, means of living; to result in life. It's rare in the Hebrew Bible to have anybody reflecting on the past and the reasons why something happened. This is not an interpretation of Joseph's earlier dreams; it's a fulfillment.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Sakarang musim lapar baru jalan dua taon. Masi ada sisa lima taon lai. Itu waktu, orang sonde akan bale tana, sonde batanam, deng sonde dapa hasil apa-apa.<bt>Now the hungry season has only been going two years now. There are still five more years. That time, people will not turn soil (prepare the soil), will not plant, and will not get any harvest whatsoever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ki: used frequently. He's making sense"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ki: used frequently. He's making sense out of a lot of things all at once. All of a sudden seeing God's purpose blows Joseph away - an integrative experience. shnatayim (dual): two years<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>haraʿav: the famine. He doesn't ask how they are, or anything about his father. He gets right down to the main business, preserving life. bqerev: in the middle of<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʿod: still khariysh: time of plowing<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>qatstsiyr: grain harvesting activity (April to June)</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Deng ini cara yang kotong sonde mangarti ni, Tuhan Allah bawa beta lebe dolo dari bosong. Ko biar ada dari bosong, deng bosong pung ana-upu dong, yang salamat.<bt>In this way that we did not understand here, the Lord God brought me ahead of you. In.order.that there are some of you (PL), and your children-grandchildren, who will be saved.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lasum (sym inf): to set up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lasum (sym inf): to set up, put in place shəʾerit: a means of survival? remainder, remnant, what is left, remnant of a people who have been destroyed, make sure there are survivors<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ʾarets: land of Egypt? land of Canaan? the world? lhachəyot (chyh hif): to keep you alive<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>lifleytah: for escape, deliverance</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Jadi yang batúl, bukan bosong pung bekin sampe beta ada di sini, ma ini Tuhan Allah pung karjá. Dia yang bekin sang beta jadi raja pung tangan kanan di Masir. Ju beta jadi kapala urusan di raja pung ruma jabatan. Sonde ada orang laen yang lebe bésar dari beta.<bt>So what is true, it was not your doing so that I'm here, but the Lord God's doing. He is the one who made me become the raja's right hand in Masir. And I became the head coordinator in the raja's house. There is no person who is more important (bigger) than me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kariang = (Oe Sao) karja"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kariang = (Oe Sao) karja</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʿatah: logical? I canʾt read it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʿatah: logical? I canʾt read it temporally. It's like Verse 5: now then (before a negative). Almost like "furthermore" henah: here<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vaysimeni: put me in the position of (is va- consecutive, or a follow-on with additional information about ki haʾlohim?) beto: his house -- his government? his extended family?<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>moshel (mshl 2 partcpl): as ruler</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Naa, sakarang bosong pulang capát suda, ko kasi tau beta pung omong sang papa, bilang bagini: &lt;Papa pung ana Yusuf tu, masi idop! Dia su jadi orang bésar di negrí Masir. Dia ju minta papa pi Masir capát-capát.<bt>Naa, [+shift] now you return home quickly [imperative], to tell my speech to papa saying like this: 'That child of papa's Yusuf, still lives! He has become an important person in Masir country. He also requests that papa go to Masir quickly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maharu: hurry, do something quickly. Joseph"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">maharu: hurry, do something quickly. Joseph is normally in command mode. He's the guy that makes things happen. koh: thus<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>samaniy: he has put me in a position rdah (yrd): go down (to Egypt)<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>ʾal-taʿmod: donʾt stand around. Joseph in charge again.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Nanti papa bole tenga di da'era Gosen deka deng dia. Itu tampa bae deng luas. Jadi papa bisa piara papa pung kambing-domba deng sapi dong samua. Ais dia ju minta ko papa datang deng ana-upu, isi ruma, deng dong pung pusaka samua ko tenga tarús di sana.<bt>Later papa can stay in the area Gosen close to him. That place is good and wide. So papa can care.for all papa's sheep, goats, cows. And then he also requests that papa come with children-grandchildren, and household items, and all their wealth to live continually there. [EXEG: “place is good and wide” High-level: Why is Joseph telling Jacob this? He wants to overcome any reluctance Jacob has for moving to Egypt in this time of crisis. Assumed knowledge make explicit: raising sheep, goats, and cows takes a lot of land. Because the land is good and plenty, Jacob will not have any problems with his herds, so not to worry-come on down! This background cultural knowledge is needed, to indicate why Yusuf was not allowing his family to be near him (cultural assumption: if he really loved them, his family should be near him). Without this info made explicit, it is likely to be wrongly interpreted, as if Yusuf was expelling his family to Siberia. Making this explicit reinforces Joseph's purpose and attitude.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qarov: near tsoʾnka: your small livestock"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qarov: near tsoʾnka: your small livestock (sheep and goats)<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ubqarka: and your cattle herd (one cow is shor)</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Kalo papa di Gosen, na, dia bisa jaga papa di sana. Te musim lapar masi lima taon lai. Jadi dia nanti ator ko papa, kelu dong, deng papa pung binatang samua sonde kurang satu apa ju.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Now if papa is in Gosen, he can look.after papa there. Cus the hungry season is still five more years. Thus he can later arrange for papa and the family, all papa's animal won't lack anything either.'"</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** picture deleted, Dhao check Sept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** picture deleted, Dhao check Sept 2004</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vkhilkalti (kwl pilpel): I will be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vkhilkalti (kwl pilpel): I will be commandeering food, I will provide food raʿav: famine<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>pen-tiwwaresh (yrsh nif): become poor [from having to buy food at exorbitant prices]</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Yusuf kasi tau abis, ju dia omong lai bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang bosong su lia sandiri, to? Ais lu ju, Benyamin. Beta ni, memang Yusuf.<bt>Yusuf finished telling, then he spoke again saying, &lt;&lt;Now you-pl have seen for yourselves, right? And you, Benyamin. I here, am really Yusuf.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʾowt (pl particpl): seeing (force?) While"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">roʾowt (pl particpl): seeing (force?) While I am speaking to you. ki-fi (peh ʾmouthʾ): according to? It is my mouth that is speaking to you.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>hamdabber (dbr piel pt): the thing I am saying, the one who is speaking</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Jadi kasi tau sang kotong pung papa bilang, beta pung kuasa di Masir ni talalu bésar. Deng carita ju sang papa samua-samua yang bosong su lia. Ais itu, bosong bawa datang papa capát-capát di sini suda!&gt;&gt;<bt>So tell our papa saying, my authority here in Masir is very big. And also story with papa about everything that you have seen. After that then, you quickly bring come papa here [+imperative]!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vhigadtem (ngd hif): report, announce something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vhigadtem (ngd hif): report, announce something kvodi: my weight, weightiness, impressive appearance, respect<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>mihartem (piʿel): hurry horadtem (yrd hif): you bring him to Egypt<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais dia paló dia pung adi Benyamin, ko dong dua manangis.<bt>Then he embraced his younger sibling Benyamin, and.so they two cried.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayipol ʿal-tsawwəʾərey (nfl): he fell on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayipol ʿal-tsawwəʾərey (nfl): he fell on Benjamin's neck, used to describe an emotional greeting yevk (bkh imperf): cry<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>bakhah: why does the aspect change?</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Dia ju paló ame dia pung kaka dong, ko dia ciom satu-satu. Ais itu, baru dong mulai ba'omong deng dia.<bt>He also embraced his elder.siblings, and.so he kissed each one. After that, only then did they begin to talk with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nashsheq (nshq piʿel): kiss vayevk ʿaleyhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">nashsheq (nshq piʿel): kiss vayevk ʿaleyhem: and he cried over them<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>khen: thus. Understated. dibbəru (piʿel): they talked. In Hebrew the focus changes ʾhe wept over them ... the brothers talked with himʾ but in Pidgin it seems more coherent to keep the focus on Joseph.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja Masir tarima Yusuf pung kaka-adi dong<bt>The Masir Raja receives Yusuf's elder-younger siblings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais itu, waktu raja deng dia pung pagawe dong dengar Yusuf pung kaka-adi dong ada datang, ju dong samua sanáng.<bt>After that, when the raja and his civil.servants heard Yusuf's elder-younger siblings had come, then they were all happy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haqol: sound, voice, this word yitav:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">haqol: sound, voice, this word yitav: it went over well in the estimation of Pharaoh<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ais ju raja ba'omong deng Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Yusuf, é! Kasi tau lu pung kaka-adi dong, ko dong mua ame padi di dong pung keledai, ko bawa pulang pi Kana'an.<bt>And then the raja spoke with Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Yusuf! Tell your elder-younger siblings, so that they take padi on their donkeys, to take it home to Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taʿanu: load your animals bʿirkhem: beasts"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">taʿanu: load your animals bʿirkhem: beasts (grazers)<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>laxu-boʾu: go and arrive there</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ais suru dong bawa datang lu pung papa deng kelu samua, ko dong pinda di sini suda. Nanti beta kasi dong tana yang paling bae di Masir, ko dong bisa idop di situ, deng dong makan dari itu tana pung hasil.<bt>Then tell them to bring come your papa and all family, so that they move here [imperative]. Later I will give them land which is the best in Masir, for them to be able to live there, and they can eat that land's harvest.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʾetnah: and I will give ʾikhlu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʾetnah: and I will give ʾikhlu: they will eat<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>chelev: fat, best part, select</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ju kasi tau sang dong, ko dong bawa memang barapa kareta dari sini, ko nanti dong mua ame ana-ana kici deng lu pung papa.<bt>And tell them, so they go ahead and bring several carts from here, so that later they transport the small children and your papa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsuwweytah (tswh pual): are ordered, receive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsuwweytah (tswh pual): are ordered, receive command. Variant reading LXX and Vg: tsaweh ʾotam ʾyou command themʾ ʿgalowt: wagons (not chariots), carts<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>lətapkhem: for the ones who are hardly fit to march: women, children, the elderly linsheykhem (ʾishah, pl cs nʾshey): for your wives<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>unəsaʾtem: and carry them</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Jang pikir itu pusaka yang dong sonde bisa angka bawa, te samua yang paling bae di Masir, nanti dong soa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't worry about that wealth that they can't lift.up to take, cuz all that is the best in this Masir, later they will own.'"</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soa = dong pung milik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">soa = dong pung milik</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vʿeynkhem: your eyes ʾal-takhos ʿal (khws):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vʿeynkhem: your eyes ʾal-takhos ʿal (khws): do not let your eyes begrudge your household furnishings, do not be troubled about them<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Dengar bagitu, ju Yusuf kasi dong barapa kareta deng bakál di jalan, iko raja pung parenta. Deng dia pung kaka-adi dong<bt>Hearing that, then Yusuf gave them several carts and travel food for the road, according to the raja's order. And his elder-younger siblings</bt><note reference="45:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tulisan Ibrani asli tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Isra'el pung ana dong iko raja pung parenta.&gt;&gt; Isra'el tu, Yakob pung nama laen.<bt>Original writing says, &lt;&lt;Israel's children followed the raja's command.&gt;&gt; That Israel, is Yakob's other name.</bt></note>ju manyimpan ko pulang iko raja pung parenta.<bt>also got ready to return home following the raja's command.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsedah, tsidah: provisions"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tsedah, tsidah: provisions</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Yusuf ju kasi sang dong satu-satu pakean baru satu pasang. Ma dia kasi Benyamin doi perak tiga ratus, deng pakean baru lima pasang.<bt>Yusuf also gave them each one, a pair of new clothes. But he gave Benyamin 300 silver coins, and five pairs of new clothes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lukhulam: to all of them. Still,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lukhulam: to all of them. Still, Joseph loves Benjamin and his father more than the other brothers, if he could be said to love them at all. khalifot (khlf piel): substitute clothing, special gala changes of clothes<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>smalot: mantles or wrappers (both garment and under-blanket)</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Dia ju kirim kasi dia pung papa barang-barang yang paling bae dari Masir, ko mua di atas sapulu keledai laki. Dia kasi tamba lai, padi, roti, deng makanan macam-macam, di atas sapulu keledai mai, ko jadi bakál buat dong bale datang pi Masir.<bt>He also sent to his papa stuff that was the best from Masir, to transport on top of ten male donkeys. He gave even more, padi, bread, and various k.o. food, on top of ten female donkeys, to be their travel food for them to come back to Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kzot: according to the following (equivalent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kzot: according to the following (equivalent to a colon) ʿsarah: ten<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>khamorim: male donkeys nosʾim: carrying<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>mitov: some of the wealth ʾatonot: female donkeys<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>bar: cleaned, threshed grain mazon: food<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ais itu, dia kasi pulang sang dong, deng kasi inga bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong jang bakanjar di jalan, é!&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, he made them go home, and reminded saying, &lt;&lt;You dong fight on the way, ok!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pesan = word with schwa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pesan = word with schwa</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-tirgəzu (rgz): quake, be perturbed; donʾt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-tirgəzu (rgz): quake, be perturbed; donʾt be emotionally upset (agitation, fear), fly into a passion (rage). Sarna, do not engage in mutual recrimination. Other rabbis take it as "donʾt be afraid of robbers."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob dengar kalo Yusuf masi idop<bt>Yakob hears Yusuf is still alive</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais ju dong jalan pulang pi dong pung papa di Kana'an.<bt>And then they travel returning home to their papa in Kanaan.</bt><v n="26" />Sampe di sana, ju dong kasi tau dong pung papa bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa, é! Papa pung ana Yusuf masi idop. Dia su jadi orang bésar ko parenta di Masir!&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving there then, they told their papa saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! Papa's child Yusuf is still alive. He has become an important person and.so gives orders in Masir!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** dropped picture; Benjamin too young"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** dropped picture; Benjamin too young</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu Yakob dengar, ju dia tanganga bodo, deng dia sonde parcaya dong pung omong.<bt>When Yakob heard that, his mouth hung open stupidly (=speechless), and he did not trust that speaking of theirs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tanganga bodo = speechless, shocked, bingung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">tanganga bodo = speechless, shocked, bingung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayaggidu (ngd): report moshel (partcpl): the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayaggidu (ngd): report moshel (partcpl): the ruler<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>vayyafag (fwg impf): feeble, numb, cold. Rashi, Jacob was unable to believe them heʾəmin (ʾmn hif): believe, convinces. In general, Jacob did not put trust in what they said. Rashi, ceased to believe<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ma waktu dong su kasi tau abis Yusuf pung omong, deng dia dapa lia kareta yang Yusuf kirim ko mau mua bawa sang dia pi Masir, baru dia mulai parcaya.<bt>But when they finished telling Yusuf's talk, and he saw the cart which Yusuf sent to transport bring him to Masir, only then did he start believing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laseʾt (nsʾ inf cs): to carry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">laseʾt (nsʾ inf cs): to carry vatkhi ruwakh: and his spirit came alive<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Tarús dia omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Awii! Beta pung ana masi idop, ó! Bagitu baru beta sanáng! Beta musti pi lia sang dia dolo, baru beta bisa mati deng tanáng.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Awii! [+amazed] My child is still alive! In that way only now I can be happy! I must go see him now, only then can I die in peace.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rav: that's plenty. Enough! I have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">rav: that's plenty. Enough! I have enough information, Iʾm convinced by the evidence! Jewish commentators consider "rav" to take in more than the whole. ʾelkhah (hlk): I will travel<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>bterem: before</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob deng dia pung kelu dong siap-siap ko mau pi Masir<bt>Yakob and his family get ready to go to Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="46" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, Yakob<bt>After that, Yakob</bt><note reference="46:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Isra'el manyimpan ais barangkat&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab says, &lt;&lt;Israel got ready and left".</bt></note>manyimpan dia pung barang-barang dong, ju dong barangkat kasi tenga Kana'an. Sampe di kampong Barseba, ju dia horo binatang ko bekin korban kasi Tuhan Allah, yang dia pung papa Isak sémba dari dolu.<bt>got ready his stuff, and they left leaving behind Kanaan. Arriving at Barseba village, then he neck.cut an animal to make a sacrifice, for the Lord God that one who from before his papa Isak worshipped.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mafafa'u = menyimpan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">mafafa'u = menyimpan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiSSaʿ (nSʿ qal): pull up stakes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiSSaʿ (nSʿ qal): pull up stakes and go, set out o a trip vkol-ʾasher-lo: and everything he had -- people, animals, belongings<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>bʾerah (bʾer): watering place, well of underground water vyizbach zbachim: he slaughtered large and small cattle (cows, goats, and sheep) as communion sacrifices (not sin offerings, but communion between the one sacrificing and the deity to whom the sacrifice is offered, who is himself a partner in the act). See ʿola 2Kings 10:24, minkha 1 Samuel 2:19, shlamim 1 Kings 8:63, also 2 Kings 10:19 for other kinds<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00760c.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Dong barangkat kasi tenga tana Kana'an<bt>They leave, leaving behind the land of Kana'an</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ais satu malam ju dia mimpi. Dalam mimpi, dia dengar Tuhan Allah pange sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Yakob! Lu bangun dolo ko dengar!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then one night he dreamed. In that dream, he heard the Lord God call him saying, &lt;&lt;We! [+get attention] Yakob! You get up and listen [mild imperative]!&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: many lgs do NOT repeat a name as a vocative. Check, and don't force it.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dia manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kanapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>And he replied saying, &lt;&lt;What's the matter?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bmarʾot: vision, apparition (not a dream)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bmarʾot: vision, apparition (not a dream) yaʿqov yaʿqov: would God have said it twice if he had been talking Pidgin? or only in Hebrew?<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais Tuhan bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni Tuhan Allah yang lu pung papa su sémba dari dolu. Lu jang taku pi Masir. Te Beta nanti bekin lu pung turunan jadi bangsa yang bésar di sana.<bt>Then the Lord said, &lt;&lt;I here am the Lord God whom your papa worshipped from before. You don't need to be afraid to go to Mesir. Cuz I later will make your descendants become a big nation there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾal-tiraʾ: do not be afraid merdah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾal-tiraʾ: do not be afraid merdah (yrd inf cs) = min rədah: to go down, source of fear<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>gadol: great (wealthy, important) ʾsimxa (sym): I will place you as a great nation, establish you, set you up as<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Beta nanti pi Masir sama-sama deng lu. Deng nanti Beta ju bawa pulang lu pung turunan kambali pi tana Kana'an. Nanti, waktu lu mati, lu pung ana Yusuf dapa lu pung napas.&gt;&gt;<bt>I later will go to Masir together with you. And later I will also bring home your descendants returning to Kanaan. Later, when you die, your child Yusuf will get your breath (=be there when you die).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Yusuf's ones will be the ones"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Yusuf's ones will be the ones who will shut your eyelids, wrap you == do s.t. immediately after death.; Yusuf dapa lu pung napas = present at death (UNS)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾaʿalkha (ʿlh hif): I will bring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾaʿalkha (ʿlh hif): I will bring you back up [to Canaan] gam-ʿaloh (inf): why gam? why the infinitive absolute, hifʿil + qal? Waltke &amp; OʾConnor "I will surely bring you up again"<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yashit (shyt): put. BT: a pretty nice genuine idiom "will be at your side when you die." SS: For Buddhists, close da eyes mean pau, da spirit gone</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ais itu, Yakob deng dia pung ana dong<bt>After that, Yakob and his children</bt><note reference="46:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Isra'el pung ana dong ame bawa sang dong pung papa Yakob.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab says, &lt;&lt;Israel's sons took their father Yakob'.</bt></note>kasi tenga kampong Barseba. Ju dong kasi nae sang dia deng dong pung bini-ana, di atas kareta yang raja Masir su kirim datang.<bt>left behind Barseba village. And they put him, and their wives-children, on the carts which the Masir raja had sent.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** deleted last sentence from earlier"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** deleted last sentence from earlier draft.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tappam (taf): their children laseʾt (nsʾ):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tappam (taf): their children laseʾt (nsʾ): to lift someone up, carry, support, transport<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6-7" />Tarús dong ame bawa dong pung pusaka deng dong pung binatang samua yang su jadi dong pung milik di tana Kana'an. Ais Yakob deng dia pung ana laki-laki, dia pung ana parampuan, deng dia pung cucu-cece dong samua, jalan pi Masir.<bt>Then they took all their wealth, and all the animals that had become their possessions in Kanaan land. Then Yakob and his male children, and his female child, and grandchildren-great.grandchildren all, traveled to Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqneyhem: their possessions, especially cattle rəkusham:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miqneyhem: their possessions, especially cattle rəkusham: property, goods gained by work, not by purchase [CHECK]<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>rakshu: they had acquired zarʿow: his seed, his descendants, offspring<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>heviʾ (bwʾ hif): bring (main verb) End of S section<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob pung kelu yang iko pi Masir<bt>Yakob's family who goes to Masir</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Yakob pung kelu yang iko pinda pi Masir, andia:<bt>Yakob's family who went moving to Masir, [list]:</bt><note reference="46:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani ada tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Isra'el pung kelu&gt;&gt;.<bt>Ibrani language Alkitab says 'Israel's family'.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ruben, ana partama.<bt>Ruben, the first child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bkor: firstborn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bkor: firstborn</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Dia pung ana-ana dong, andia: Henok, Palu, Hesron, deng Karmi.<bt>His children, [list]: Henok, Palu, Hesron, and Karmi.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Simeon deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Yemuel, Yamin, Ohad, Yakin, deng Sohar. Deng Saul, andia dia pung ana dari bini orang Kana'an.<bt>Simeon, and his children. [List]: Yemuel, Yamin, Ohad, Yakin, and Sohar. And Saul, that is his child from a wife a Kanaan person.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Lewi deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Gerson, Kehat, deng Merari.<bt>Lewi, and his children. [List:] Gerson, Kehat, and Merari.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Yahuda deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Sela, Peres deng Sera. Yahuda pung ana laen, Er deng Onan, su mati di Kana'an. Dia ju bawa Peres pung ana-ana, andia: Hesron deng Hamul.<bt>Yahuda, and his children. [List:] Sela, Peres and Sera. Yahuda's other children, Er and Onan, had died in Kanaan. He also brought Peres's children, [list]: Hesron and Hamul.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Isaskar deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Tola, Pua, Ayub, deng Simron.<bt>Isaskar, and his children. [List]: Tola, Pua, Ayub, and Simron.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Sebulon deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Sered, Elon, deng Yahleel.<bt>Sebulon, and his children. [List]: Sered, Elon, and Yahlel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Dong samua tu, Yakob deng dia pung bini Lea pung ana barana waktu dong tenga di Mesopotamia. Ada lai dong pung ana parampuan, nama Dina. Jadi Yakob deng Lea pung turunan samua ada tiga pulu tiga orang.<bt>All of those, were Yakob and his wife Lea's birth children, when they lived in Mesopotamia. There was also their daughter named Dina. So all of Yakob and Lea's descendants were 33 people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Tarús, ada dia pung ana-ana dari bini laen. Andia, Gad, deng dia pung ana-ana: Sifion, Hagi, Suni, Esbon, Eri, Arodi, deng Areli.<bt>Then, there were his children from other wives. [List], Gad, with his children: Sifion, Hagi, Suni, Esbon, Eri, Arodi, and Areli. [NOTE to daughter translations: If your grammar requires it, mark “other wives” as plural.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />Aser deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Yimna, Yiswa, Yiswi, Beria, deng dong pung sodara parampuan, nama Sera.<bt>Aser, and his children. [List]: Yimna, Yiswa, Yiswi, Beria, and their sister, named Sera.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ada ju Beria pung ana-ana: Heber deng Malkiel.<bt>There was also Beria's children: Heber and Malkiel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dong samua tu, ada anam blas orang. Andia Yakob deng dia pung bini Silpa pung ana-upu. Silpa tu, andia babu yang Laban kasi sang dia pung ana parampuan Lea, Yakob pung bini tua.<bt>All of those, were 16 people. That's Yakob and his wife Silpa's children-grandchildren. That Silpa, that's the maid that Laban gave to his daughter Lea, that oldest [by marriage order] wife of Yakob.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="babu = pembantu perempuan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">babu = pembantu perempuan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />Tarús, ada lai Yakob pung bini laen, nama Rahel. Dia barana dua ana. Andia Yusuf deng Benyamin.<bt>Then, there was also, Yakob's other wife, named Rahel. She gave birth to two children. [List], Yusuf and Benyamin.</bt><v n="20" />Itu waktu, Yusuf su kawin deng Asnat di Masir. Dia pung papa mantu tu, kapala agama di kota On. Dia pung nama Potifera. Ais Yusuf deng Asnat pung ana-ana, andia, Efraim deng Manase.<bt>At that time, Yusuf was married to Asnat in Masir. That father-in-law of his, was the head of religion in the city On. His name Potifera. Then Yusuf and Asnat's children, [list], Efraim and Manase.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiwwaled (nif): were born"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yiwwaled (nif): were born</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="21" />Benyamin ju iko pi Masir deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Bela, Beker, Asibel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi, Ros, Mupim, Hupim, deng Ared.<bt>Benyamin also went to Masir with his children. [List]: Bela, Beker, Asibel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi, Ros, Mupim, Hupim, and Ared.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais Yakob deng dia pung bini Rahel pung turunan tu, ada ampa blas orang.<bt>So the descendants of Yakob and his wife Rahel's, were 14 people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yulad (qal pass): were born"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yulad (qal pass): were born</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="23" />Ais itu, masi ada Yakob pung bini satu lai, nama Bilha. Dong pung ana, andia Dan deng Naftali.<bt>After that, there was still one more wife of Yakob, named Bilha. Their children, [list] Dan and Naftali.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dan pung ana, nama Husim.<bt>Dan's child, named Husim.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** made separate paragraph"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** made separate paragraph</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Naftali deng dia pung ana-ana. Andia: Yasel, Guni, Yeser deng Silem.<bt>Naftali, with his children. [List]: Yasel, Guni, Yeser and Silem.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Yakob deng dia pung bini Bilha pung turunan tu, ada tuju orang. Bilha tu, andia Rahel pung babu yang dia dapa dari dia pung papa Laban.<bt>Those descendants of Yakob and his wife Bilha, were 7 people. That Bilha, she was Rahel's maid whom she got from her papa Laban.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ko here = yang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ko here = yang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Jadi Yakob pung turunan samua yang pi Masir ada anam pulu anam orang. Balóm maso dia pung ana mantu dong.<bt>So (consequently) all of Yakob's descendants who went to Masir were 66 people. Not yet including his children-in-law.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="balom maso ~ sonde itong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">balom maso ~ sonde itong</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotsʾey: who set out yəreko: back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yotsʾey: who set out yəreko: back of his (Jacobʾs) upper thigh, another way of talking about the genitals and procreation<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>milləvad: alone, not counting</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Tamba deng Yusuf pung ana yang lahir di Masir, dua orang. Jadi Yakob deng dia pung kelu yang tenga di Masir, samua ada tuju pulu orang.<bt>Adding Yusuf's children who were born in Masir, 2 people. Thus Yakob and his family that lived in Masir, in all were 70 people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="alternate: Tamba Yusuf deng dia pung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">alternate: Tamba Yusuf deng dia pung ana-ana yang lahir.... (to get 3 more people + Yakob = 70)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="habaʾah: in this case, who ended"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">habaʾah: in this case, who ended up in Egypt (two grandkids already there) End of P section.<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob katumu lai deng dia pung ana Yusuf<bt>Yakob meets again with his child Yusuf</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Waktu dong su amper deka Masir, Yakob suru dia pung ana Yahuda jalan lebe dolo, ko pi pange sang Yusuf datang katumu deng dia pung papa di Gosen. Waktu dong su sampe di Gosen,<bt>When they were almost near Masir, Yakob ordered his child Yahuda to travel on ahead, to go call Yusuf, come meet his papa in Gosen. When they arrived in Gosen,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samech - major section, P readings"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">samech - major section, P readings for the year, thru 48; 49:1-26 is another, then 49:27-c50 lfanayw: ahead of him (twice<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>horot (yrh hif inf): direct, teach. No direct object, problematic.</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />ju Yusuf nae pi dia pung kareta, ko pi katumu deng dia pung papa di situ. Waktu dong bakatumu, ju Yusuf paló dia pung papa, ju manangis lama sakali.<bt>then Yusuf got on his cart, to go meet his papa there. When they meet each other then, Yusuf embraced his papa, and cried a long time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʾəSor: tie the chariot to the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yeʾəSor: tie the chariot to the horses, harness the chariot; bind himself with a vow? prohibit? merkavto: his chariot, a two-wheeled vehicle pulled by horses. There were war chariots, state chariots used for parades, and traveling chariots<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>liqraʾt: to confront, but in a good sense, more like "meet" vayeraʾ (nif): be seen, appear<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>vayyippol (npl qal): he fell ʿal-tsawwaʾraw: on his neck, embraced him - emotional scene. Rashi, Jacob did not reciprocate the same way. But it's told from Joseph's point of view, so the brothersʾ reaction might be taken for granted, and Jacob's likewise. Parallel to Joseph meeting his brothers.<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>yevk: cried ʿod: for a time<span class="Italic">(29)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00753c.tif" rtfFormat="width:8.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:bottom">Yusuf bakatumu deng dia pung papa Yakob</fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ais Yakob omong deng Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana Yusuf, é! Sakarang beta sandiri su lia sang lu. Deng beta su tau lu masi idop. Andia, biar beta mati sakarang ju bae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob spoke with Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Child Yusuf! Now I have seen you myself. And I know that you are still alive. That's why, even if I die now it's ok.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hati luas ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">hati luas =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾamutah (mwt): let me die; I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾamutah (mwt): let me die; I am willing to die, -h cohortative hapaʿam: once, at last, now<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>ʾachrey: afterwards rʾoti (rʾh inf cs): for me to see<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>ʿodkha: you still (not "again")</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ais ju Yusuf kasi tau sang dia pung kaka-adi dong samua bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta musti pi kasi tau sang raja bilang, beta pung kelu dong su datang dari Kana'an.<bt>And then Yusuf told all his elder-younger siblings saying, &lt;&lt;I must go tell the raja, that my family has come from Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾeʿleh: let me go up (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾeʿleh: let me go up (not to Canaan, but to Pharaoh mauka Goshen? Or going to the top) cohortative in group setting, open to group veto - in grammars, Jouen, Gesenius. Segol he, no qamets. vʾaggidah (ngd hif imperf): and I will report, inform (cohortative)<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʾomrah: I propose to say (cohortative)</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Ju nanti beta kasi tau bilang, bosong ni, orang yang piara domba deng sapi. Andia ko bosong ju ada bawa bosong pung binatang deng pusaka dong dari Kana'an.<bt>And later I will tell saying that you-pl here, people who take care of sheep and cows. That's why you have brought you animals and your wealth from Kanaan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roʿe (rʿh partcpl cs): into caring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">roʿe (rʿh partcpl cs): into caring for tsoʾn: small cattle (sheep and goats) - Egyptians donʾt like sheep or nomads, but Joseph shrewdly buffers the meeting, doesn't say they are traders<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>ʾanshe miqneh: cattle breeders; people who own their own cattle (miqneh ʾproperty, livestockʾ). Not coming as freeloaders or refugees or boat people. vəqaram: their herds, cattle (FF 62)<span class="Italic">(32)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Kalo nanti raja pange bosong, ais dia tanya bosong biasa karjá apa,<bt>If later the raja calls you, and he asks what your usual work is,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vhayah ki-: v- it will happen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vhayah ki-: v- it will happen that (=and then)? when he summons you, he will say ... [?] yiqraʾ: he will summon<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="34" />na, bosong manyao suda sang dia bilang, bosong samua ni, tukang piara binatang dari kici-kici, sama ke bosong pung nene-moyang dong. Deng bagitu, nanti dia suru bosong tenga di da'era Gosen.&gt;&gt; Yusuf kasi tau bagitu, tagal orang Masir dong rasa noju kalo dong tenga bakumpul deng gambala dong.<bt>well you answer [imp.] him saying, we all here, animal carers from youth, like our ancestors. With that, later he will order you to stay in the Gosen area.&gt;&gt; Yusuf told like that, because the Masir people feel grossed.out, if they live mixed with [animal] herders.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="minʿurenu (nʿurim): from our youth baʿavur:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">minʿurenu (nʿurim): from our youth baʿavur: in order that<span class="Italic">(34) (34) </span>teshvu (yshv): you may live toʿavat: they loathe, abhor, treat as an abomination, with horror, detestable 43:22. Ramses III had 3,000 people taking care of cattle. 1 Kg 4, daily provisions 10 fattened cows, 10 range ...<span class="Italic">(34)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja kasi tana sang Yusuf pung kelu<bt>The raja gives land to Yusuf's family</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="47" />
      <v n="1-2" />Ais ju Yusuf deng dia pung sodara lima orang pi mangada sang raja. Yusuf kasi kanál bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuan raja! Beta pung papa deng beta pung kaka-adi dong su datang dari Kana'an. Dong datang deng dong pung kambing-domba, dong pung sapi deng dong pung barang-barang samua. Sakarang dong samua su ada di da'era Gosen.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that Yusuf and five of his siblings went to face the raja. Yusuf introduced [them] saying, &lt;&lt;Mr Raja! My papa and my elder-younger siblings have arrived from Kanaan. They have come with their goats-sheep, and their cows and all their stuff. Now they all are in the Gosen area.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaged (ngd hif): announced hinnam: focus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaged (ngd hif): announced hinnam: focus marker: calls attention to next sentence or next word or the preceding word. As a discourse marker: response after being summoned: Here am I! or introduces unexpected event, or introduces a challenge. As a conjunction: introduces observation, or introduces a condition or assumption; here they are! Fait accompli with Joseph's relatives, wisely planned and scripted.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>miqtseh: from the end, border; to the last man vayyatstsigem (ytsg hif imperf): he set them; brought them forward, produced them -- an official introduction<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00755c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf omong deng raja Masir<bt>Yusuf speaks with the raja Masir</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais raja tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong pung karjá apa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the raja asked saying, &lt;&lt;Your work is what?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dong manyao sang raja bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong ni gambala, sama ke botong pung nene-moyang.<bt>And they answered the raja saying, &lt;&lt;We here are herders like our ancestors.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʿəseykhem: what's your line of work,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">maʿəseykhem: what's your line of work, occupation? roʿeh tsoʾn: taking care of small animals (specifically sheep and goats). How did they keep from offending the Pharaoh?<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>gam ... gam: as we do, so our ancestors did</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Sakarang ni, di tana Kana'an ada musim karíng yang hebat sakali sampe sonde ada makanan deng rumput lai. Andia ko botong datang di ini negrí ko tenga tahan. Botong ju ada bawa botong pung binatang dong. Naa, sakarang botong minta isin sang papa raja, ko botong tenga di da'era Gosen, ko piara botong pung binatang dong di situ.&gt;&gt;<bt>Right now, in Kanaan land there is a hungry season that is very intense to the point that there is no food and grass anymore. That's why we came to this land to stay awhile. We have also brought our animals. Naa, [+shift] now we ask permission from papa raja so that we can stay in the Gosen area to take care of our animals there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ko tenga tahan = sementara, temporarily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ko tenga tahan = sementara, temporarily</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lagur (inf): dwell as an alien."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lagur (inf): dwell as an alien. Not necessarily temporary; we want to immigrate without native born status. mirʿeh: pasturage<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>khaved: heavy, difficult raʿav: famine<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yeshvu-naʾ: please let them settle down, sit down. Requesting permission to settle</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ais ju raja kasi tau dia pung mau sang Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Sakarang lu pung papa deng kaka-adi dong su ada di sini.<bt>And then the raja told his will/wishes to Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Now your papa and elder-younger siblings are here.</bt><v n="6" />Jadi dong bole bekin ini negrí sama ke dong pung negrí sandiri. Yang beta tau, da'era Gosen tu, da'era yang paling bae di ini negrí. Jadi lebe bae dong tenga di situ sa. Deng kalo dari dong ada yang tau urus binatang deng bae, biar ko dong ju urus beta pung di situ.&gt;&gt;<bt>So they may make this country as if it was their own country. From what I know, that Gosen area, is the best are in the country. So it's best if they just stay there. And if there are some among them who know how to take care of animals well, then they can also take care of mine there.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiʾ: = ʾerets meTav: best|i(6) (6)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hiʾ: = ʾerets meTav: best<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>hoshev (yshb hif): to cause to sit, dwell, to be inhabited; settle them chayil: capacity, power, qualified<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>vsamtam (sim): put them in a position, appoint sare: officers in charge of, princes, chiefs<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>miqneh: possession (cattle; fields)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais ju Yusuf kasi kanál dia pung papa sang raja. Ju Yakob sambayang minta ko Tuhan Allah kasi berkat sang itu raja.<bt>After that, Yusuf introduced his papa to the raja. And Yakob prayed asking the Lord God to give blessing to that raja.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyaveʾ (bwʾ hif): he brought yaʿəmidehu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyaveʾ (bwʾ hif): he brought yaʿəmidehu (ʿmd hif): to stand; to stand (before), i.e. serve, minister to; to be set over; to confide in; to stand by, defend; to stand firm, remain, endure; to resist; to persist, persevere; to stand still, stop; to stand up, arise; to be constituted, set, appointed; introduced him<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vayvarekh: formal greeting, asking after well-being, wish long life, O king, live forever</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ju raja tanya sang Yakob bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa su umur barapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>And the raja asked Yakob saying, &lt;&lt;Father is how old?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is a polite question"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">This is a polite question</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co00757c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Yusuf deng Yakob omong deng raja Masir<bt>Yusuf and Yakob speak with the raja Masir</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Yakob manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su idop saratus tiga pulu taon, ma beta sonde tatáp di satu tampa. Beta pung nene-moyang dong ju bagitu. Kalo banding deng dong, na, beta pung umur memang lebe pende, ma ponu deng sangsara.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yakob answered saying, &lt;&lt;I have lived 130 years, but I have not been continuously in one place. [EXEG: following CEV, TH; Heb. /magur/ BDB "be a stranger, pilgrimage, sojourn"] My ancestors also were like that. If you compare with them, well my age is actually shorter. But full of tribulation.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sonde tetap = pindah-pindah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sonde tetap = pindah-pindah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mguwray: my stay, my residence, my"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">mguwray: my stay, my residence, my stays in various places, not as a citizen mʾat: hundred<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>mʿaT: few, little raʿim: bad quality, ugly, disagreeable, no value, adverse<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>hissigu (sgh hif): make great; reach the same number, attain to ʾavotim: Abraham and Isaac<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ais Yakob minta parmisi sang raja. Ma dia balóm jalan, dia minta Tuhan kasi berkat lai sang raja.<bt>Then Yakob asked to take.leave of the raja. But before he left, he asked the Lord again to give blessing to the raja.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayetseʾ: he went out (formal leave-taking)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayetseʾ: he went out (formal leave-taking)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ais Yusuf iko raja pung omong, tarús dia tunju tampa kasi sang dong di da'era Gosen. Itu tampa talalu bagus. (Nanti dong kasi nama itu tampa &lt;Rameses&gt;.) Ais ju Yusuf pung papa deng dia pung kaka-adi dong tenga tarús di situ.<bt>Then Yusuf followed the raja's speech, next he showed/choose the place for them in the Gosen area. That place was exceedingly good. (Later they named that place 'Rameses'.) And then Yusuf papa and his elder-younger sibling lived continuous there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** parentheses added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** parentheses added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayoshev (yshv hif): settle, let them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayoshev (yshv hif): settle, let them live somewhere ʾachuzzah: landed property, long term<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>tsiwwah (tswh): order, direct, command</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ais Yusuf ju sadia makanan ko kasi dia pung papa, dia pung kaka-adi dong, deng dong pung bini-ana dong samua, dari yang paling bésar sampe yang paling kici.<bt>And Yusuf also prepared/arranged food for his papa, his elder-younger siblings, and all their wives-children, from the biggest to the smallest (age-wise).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaykhalkel (polpel) ... lechem: he provided"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaykhalkel (polpel) ... lechem: he provided food (over and over) lfi: for the mouth of, their need<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>Taf: lexicon says "drops" [?], but could be those who are not strong enough to march: women, children, and the elderly</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Musim lapar di tana Masir<bt>Hungry season in Masir land</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Itu waktu, musim lapar talalu hebat, sampe di mana-mana su sonde ada makanan lai. Dari Masir sampe Kana'an orang dong samua su soák. Dong sonde bisa bekin apa-apa lai, tagal dong su lapar mau mati.<bt>At that time, the hungry season was exceedingly very intense, to the point that everywhere there was no food left. From Masir to Kanaan all the people were weak (from lack of food). They could do anything anymore, because they were exceedingly hungry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="some say mamalek only collocates with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">some say mamalek only collocates with plants; suák = like weak battery run out of juice</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʿav: famine telah (lhh): the land"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raʿav: famine telah (lhh): the land was languishing, in bad shape<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>mippəne: as a result of</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ais orang datang dari samua tampa di Masir deng samua tampa di Kana'an, ko béli makanan di Yusuf. Ju dia kumpul itu doi samua, ko pi simpan di raja pung ruma.<bt>Then people came from all the places in Masir and all the places in Kanaan, to buy food at Yusuf. And he collected all that money, to store in the raja's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayəlaqqeT (piʿel): Joseph gathered in all"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayəlaqqeT (piʿel): Joseph gathered in all the money -- Joseph wen collect all da money from da peopo? o all da money end up with Joseph? Scraped up. Gleaning, not much left, dredging up nimtsaʾ (nif): that was to be found<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shever: grain hem: them<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shovrim: people buying grain, act of buying yaveʾ (hif): brought<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Itu waktu, orang Masir deng orang Kana'an dong pung doi su abis. Andia ko dong sonde bisa béli makanan lai. Ais ju dong datang mangada sang Yusuf, ko minta bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa wakil, é! Kasi botong makan dolo, ko botong jang mati lapar. Te botong pung doi su abis na.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, the Masir people and the Kanaan people's money was all gone. That's why they couldn't buy food anymore. So they come in.front.of Yusuf, to request saying, &lt;&lt;Mr. vice! Give us food, so that we don't die of hunger. Cuz [background] our money is all gone [and you should know it].&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayitom (tmm): The money ran out,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayitom (tmm): The money ran out, got used up, spent, gone vayaboʾu: they came, not all at once, but probably family by family, or delegations<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>havah (yhv imperv): give namut: we die<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>negdekha: in front of you ʾafeS: ceased = yitom?<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo memang bosong pung doi sonde ada lai, na, bekin bagini: kasi sa bosong pung binatang, ko beta tukar deng makanan.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf replied saying, &lt;&lt;If your money is actually all gone, na, do like this: give your animals, so that I exchange them for food.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="havu (yhv imperv): give (mortage?) miqnekhem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">havu (yhv imperv): give (mortage?) miqnekhem: your possessions (property, fields). Livestock in general, not individual cows.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ʾetnah lakhem (ntn imperf): I will give to you (elliptical object). ʾafeS: come to an end<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ais ju dong kasi dong pung binatang sang Yusuf, ko tukar deng makanan. Andia dong pung kuda, dong pung domba, dong pung kambing, dong pung sapi deng dong pung keledai, tagal itu taon Yusuf su janji bagitu.<bt>And so they gave their animals to Yusuf, to exchange for food. That.is their horses, their sheep, their goats, their cows and their donkeys. Because that year Yusuf had promised like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaviʾu (bwʾ hif): brought basusim: in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaviʾu (bwʾ hif): brought basusim: in exchange for horses, 1st time mentioned<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>vaynahlem (nhl piel): guide, help along, saw them through, supply them with</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Bale taon, dong datang lai di Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa wakil, é! Botong omong jujur sa. Botong pung doi deng botong pung binatang, papa su tukar ame samua. Sakarang sonde ada apa-apa lai. Tenga botong pung diri deng botong pung tana sa.<bt>The next year, they came again to Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Mr vice! We'll just speak honestly. Our money and our animals, papa(you) have exchanged them all. Now there's nothing left. There only left ourselves and our land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bale taon = the next year,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bale taon = the next year, taon brikut (UNS)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="titom (tmm): be completed, consumed yavoʾu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">titom (tmm): be completed, consumed yavoʾu: they came<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>shenit: second nkhached: keep hidden, cover up<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ʾim-tam (tmm): if it is used up miqneh habhemah: cattle, animals<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>nishʾar (nif): remain, left bilti: except, only<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>gəwiyyatenu: our bodies ʾadmatenu: our earth; dust; land, region, country; ground, land, field; our land<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>Does "sell our bodies" imply slavery, or does it sound like prostitution?</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Jang kasi biar botong mati. Kalo botong mati, na, sapa yang urus itu tana dong? Lebe bae, papa wakil ame botong jadi papa pung budak. Deng papa ju ame botong pung tana, ko jadi papa pung. Tarús papa kasi bibit ko botong tanam kasi papa. Ais botong pung cape, deng botong pung tana tu, papa ganti deng makanan sa. Asal botong jang mati!&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't allow us to die. If we die [+obvious], who will take.care of the land? It's best, papa vice takes us to become papa's slaves. And papa also take our land, to become papa's. And then papa give seed so that we can plant for papa. Then our tiredness(effort), and that land of our, papa just exchange for food. As.long.as we don't die!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: “land dying/becoming desolate.” It is handled by “who will manage the land?” In this semi-arid climate with the poorest soils in Indo, neglecting the land makes it “desolate”. TH says, “but in what sense is the land said to die? The thought expressed here is that, if farmers do not have seed to sow, their lands are useless and become abandoned. … land is farm land that has gone to waste from neglect, that is, from not being cultivated and planted.” So it's covered, not ommitted.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="namut: we die qneh (qnh): acquire,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">namut: we die qneh (qnh): acquire, buy<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>nihyeh: we will be ʿvadim (ʿeved): slaves<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ten-zeraʿ: give seed; the Nile is still running niHyeh: we will live<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>tesham (shmm): become desolate; to be laid waste, to be withheld</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Tagal musim lapar tamba hebat, andia ko samua orang Masir jual buang dong pung tana. Ju Yusuf béli ame samua tana di Masir ko jadi raja pung pusaka.<bt>Because that hungry season increased in intensity, that's.why all the Masir people sold disposing of their land. And Yusuf bought taking all the land in Masir to become the raja's wealth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jual buang &lt;-&gt; beli ame"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">jual buang &lt;-&gt; beli ame</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayiqen (qnh): acquire, buy, get maxru:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayiqen (qnh): acquire, buy, get maxru: they sold<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>ʾish: each one, one by one. This happened farm by farm, not all at once sadehu: their fields<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>Hazaq: the famine lay heavy on them; to be heavy = severe, difficult (of events) thi (fem): it became<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Deng bagitu, andia samua rakyat Masir jadi raja pung budak.<bt>With that, that's.why all the people of Masir became the raja's slaves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿam: a people, viewed as an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿam: a people, viewed as an ethnic unit with internal solidarity, but may also be used for part of an ethnic group or the people associated with a leader heʿvir (ʿvr hif): made them pass through an area, sent them to the other side, turned his eyes to the other side, cause someone to cross over. Probably Joseph did it. OR made them slaves Samar, LXX heʿvid<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>leʿarim (ʿir): to the cities (also means populations of cities) needed so that they could move massive quantities of food miqtseh ... vʿad qatsehu: from a border ... as far as their border<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>gvol-mitsraim: from the border that is the boundary of Egypt, same word for the country and the people, always sounds like a plural, with mitsri as a rare gentilic noun or adjective Maybe "make um move house from one side Egypt to da odda side"?<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="47:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ada tulisan bahasa Ibrani saparu yang tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Yusuf kasi pinda orang samua pi dalam kota dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>There are Ibrani language writing which also say, 'Yusuf moved everyone inside the cities'.</bt></note><v n="22" />Ma Yusuf sonde béli kapala agama dong pung tana, tagal raja kasi sang dong makanan tarús. Andia ko dong sonde parlú jual dong pung tana.<bt>But Yusuf did not buy the head of religion's land, because the raja continued to give food to them. That's why they didn't need to sell their land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kapala agama = bos agama, imam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kapala agama = bos agama, imam dong</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raq: only choq (chqq), chuqqam: something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">raq: only choq (chqq), chuqqam: something prescribed; portion, limit of life, task, something due to the priests (their income)<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Itu waktu, ju Yusuf omong deng rakyat dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Naa! Sakarang bosong su jadi raja pung budak. Bosong pung tana samua, ju beta su béli kasi raja. Jadi bosong ame ini bibit dong, ko pi tanam di itu tana dong suda.<bt>At that time also, Yusuf spoke with the people saying, &lt;&lt;So! Now you have become the raja's kuli. All your land also, I have bought for the raja. So you take these seeds, to plant in those lands [imperative].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hen: 3 pl fem pronoun. Text?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hen: 3 pl fem pronoun. Text? heʾ-lakhem: lo, behold, to you<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>zeraʿ: seed zraʿtem: plant them<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ais nanti waktu koru, na, bosong bagi lima. Satu bagian bawa kasi raja. Sisa ampa bagian, bosong pake bekin bibit, deng saparu bosong makan deng bosong pung kelu dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>And then later when it's harvest time, you divide by five. One part bring to the raja. The remaining four parts, you use to make seed, and a part you and your family eat.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koru = panen (padi)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">koru = panen (padi)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təvuʾot: whenever there are harvests (produce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">təvuʾot: whenever there are harvests (produce or yield of the land) ntatem: you will give them<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>chəmiyshiyt: one fifth, 20% ʾarbaykhʿ: four<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>hayadot (yad): hands, places; parts? laʾsher: for whatever<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>bateykhem: your homes ləTapxem (Taf):for your children<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ais ju dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Pak su kasi salamat sang botong, tagal itu botong minta tarima kasi. Botong mau jadi tuan raja pung budak sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>And then they replied saying, &lt;&lt;Father has saved us, because of that we say thank-you. We just want to become mr. raja's kuli.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pulang memang = (sonde tidor), langsung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pulang memang = (sonde tidor), langsung pulang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hechəyitanu (chyh hif): you caused us"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hechəyitanu (chyh hif): you caused us to live, kept us alive, preserved us nimtsaʾ-chen bʿeyney (impf): we will find favor in your eyes, may we ...h<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ais Yusuf bekin itu atoran jadi adat di negrí Masir. Andia dari samua padi yang rakyat dong su koru, dong bagi lima. Satu bagian dong kasi sang raja. Ampa bagian dong pake sandiri. Cuma kapala agama dong pung tana, raja sonde béli. Itu adat, dong masi pake tarús.<bt>Then Yusuf made that rule become custom in Masir country. That's why all the padi that the people harvested, they divided in five. One part they gave to the raja. Four parts they used themselves. Only the heads of religion's land, the raja did not buy. That custom, they still use it continuously.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yasem (sym): put, established ʾotah (fem):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yasem (sym): put, established ʾotah (fem): it<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>ləchoq: as a share, allotment (food, territory, work) ʾadmat: land<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>lachomesh: fifth part raq: only<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>lvadam: only for them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf bajanji ko kubur Yakob di dong pung nene-moyang pung tampa kubur<bt>Yusuf promises, he will bury Yakob in their ancestors grave place</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Mulai itu waktu, ju orang Isra'el dong tenga tarús di Masir di da'era Gosen. Dong jadi orang kaya, deng dong pung turunan ju tamba banya.<bt>From then on, the Israel people lived continuously in Masir, in the Gosen area. They became rich people, and their descendants also increased.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishev: sat down, settled vayeʾachazu (ʾchz"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishev: sat down, settled vayeʾachazu (ʾchz nif): they lay hold of, grasped; they were seized?<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>vayifru (prh): they were fruitful, multiplied vayirbu (rbh): they became numerous<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Di Masir Yakob masi idop lai tuju blas taon, sampe dia pung umur samua jadi saratus ampa pulu tuju taon.<bt>In Masir, Yakob still lived 17 years more, until his age was 147 years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yHi (Hyh): lived, was alive shvaʿ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yHi (Hyh): lived, was alive shvaʿ ʿesreh: 17<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>shne Hayaw: the years of his life shevaʿ: 7<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>ʾarbaʿim umʾat: 140</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ais waktu dia pung hari mati su deka-deka, ju dia pange sang Yusuf ko kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana Usu, é! Beta rasa-rasa sonde lama lai, te Tuhan Allah su pange pulang sang beta. Jadi beta minta, kalo lu sayang sang beta, lu sumpa ko lu jang kubur beta di tana Masir.<bt>Then when his dying day was near, then he called Yusuf to tell him saying, &lt;&lt;Child Usus! I feel that not much longer, cuz the Lord God has called me home. So I request, if you love me, you swear to not bury me in this Masir land here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="UNS comment (Sabu) &quot;This is where"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">UNS comment (Sabu) "This is where te SHOULD be!"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqrvu: they drew near, came near"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyiqrvu: they drew near, came near (the days for Israel to die) vayyiqraʾ: he summoned, called<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>ʾim-naʾ matsaʾti chen bʿeyneyka: Please, if I have found favor in your eyes. In terms of Joseph's position and power? He's asking for a lot of effort. sim-naʾ: I would like you to put<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>yrekhi: fleshy portion of my upper thigh, the back part (where the angel touched Jacob Gn 32:32), area of sexual organs where the hand was placed when making a solemn oath, also in 46:26 chesed: obligation to the community, solidarity, loyalty of a son to a dying father<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>veʾmet: reliability, security, permanence, lasting kindness (khesed veʾmet), fidelity, faithfully, truly ʾal-naʾ: donʾt<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>tiqbreni: you bury me</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Lu musti bawa pulang beta pung mayat, pi kotong pung nene-moyang dong pung tampa kubur, ko kubur beta di situ. Itu papa pung mau.&gt;&gt;<bt>You must take return.home my corpse, to the place of our ancestor's grave place. So.that you bury me there. That's papa(my) will.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bae, papa! Kalo papa su mau bagitu, na, beta iko sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yusuf answered saying, &lt;&lt;Ok, papa! If papa wants like that, I'll just do it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vshakhavti: I will lie down, sleep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vshakhavti: I will lie down, sleep (means he's going to die) unsaʾtani: you will carry me up (Egypt to Canaan is always "up")<span class="Italic">(30) (30) </span>biqvuratam: in their burial place, grave, tomb</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Tarús Yakob omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Naa, kalo bagitu, sakarang lu angka sumpa dolo, ko bilang lu iko papa pung mau.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yakob spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Naa, [+shift] if that's the case, now you swear [mild imp.], to say that you will follow papa's will.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais ju Yusuf sumpa iko Yakob pung omong. Tarús Yakob tikam lutut di atas koi, ko sambayang minta tarima kasi sang Tuhan Allah.<bt>And then Yusuf swore following that speaking of Yakob's. Then Yakob knelt on the bed, to pray saying thank-you to the Lord God. [EXEG: bowing vs. kneeling. Lex choice. KM has /tikam lutut/ ‘kneel, bow down’, which can also be associated with prayers of supplication or thanksgiving, or /soya/ ‘bow one's head in honour, obeiscance’ (but not prayer). So for KM this is the correct one to get him close to prostrating himself (see TH). For daughter lgs, check it out with the UNS's and the team. “Head of bed” is explicit to implicit ’UNS's and team (for KM) said nobody would think of doing it with any other orientation on the bed.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishavʿah (shb nif imperv): yishtaHu (Hyh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hishavʿah (shb nif imperv): yishtaHu (Hyh hitp): he bowed his head (to Joseph)? To God? Rashi, upon the head of the bed, the divine presence above the head of the sick man? Standard ritual for oath.<span class="Italic">(31) (31) </span>ʿal-rosh: over the head (does this refer to the bed? Rashi takes it to be that.) ha miTah: the couch; ha maTih ʾstaffʾ? LXX.<span class="Italic">(31)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob minta berkat kasi sang Yusuf pung ana, Efraim deng Manase<bt>Yakob requests blessing on Yusuf's children, Efraim and Manase</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="48" />
      <v n="1" />Sonde lama lai, ju orang datang kasi tau sang Yusuf bilang dia pung papa su saki barát. Jadi dia bawa ame dia pung ana dua, andia Manase deng Efraim, ko pi lia sang dong pung ba'i Yakob.<bt>Not much longer then, people came to tell Yusuf that his papa was very sick. So he brought his two children, that is Manase and Efraim, to go go see their grandfather Yakob.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinneh: just choleh: weak, tired, ill|i(1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hinneh: just choleh: weak, tired, ill<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Waktu Yakob dengar Yusuf dong su datang, ju dia paksa diri ko dudu di koi.<bt>When Yakob heard Yusuf-p had come, then he forced himself to sit(up) on the bed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vatyagged (ngd hif imperf): [somebody] announced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vatyagged (ngd hif imperf): [somebody] announced to Jacob vayyitchazeq (chzq hitp): took courage, showed himself courageous, took strength; Jacob sat up in bed, but it took almost all his strength CEV. Showing respect to Joseph. Also used of Joseph pulling himself back together after crying.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ju dia kasi tau sang Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana Usu, é! Tempo hari Tuhan Allah yang Paling Kuasa su kasi tunju diri sang beta di kampong Lus di tana Kana'an. Di situ, Dia janji sang beta.<bt>And he told to Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Child Usu! Long ago, the Lord God who has that very intense power, showed Himself to me in the village of Lus in the land of Kanaan. There He promised me. [EXEG: “blessing” Earlier version with “give blessing to me”, which the UNS's said means he gave “wealth, land, protection” (and perhaps a Kijang or two). This is a problem in most of our lgs. Since the content of vs. 4 brings out that God is promising good things for Jacob and his descendants, the quote margin in vs.3 goes to “promise” so as to not carry wrong meaning. If God gave blessing at Lus, there would need to be evidence (give blessing = to have children, good gardens, success etc). None of that happened at Lus. Culturally, God promised to give blessing.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi berkat = wealth, land, protection"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi berkat = wealth, land, protection ; *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shadday: traditionally: Almighty One; better: All-sufficient"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shadday: traditionally: Almighty One; better: All-sufficient One (= the One every good and perfect gift comes from). The rabbinic analysis of this word is that it is a compound word composed of the relative she, "who" and the word day, "enough: she-day," the one who is (self-)sufficient" (Babylonian Talmud, Hagigah 12a)... Another possibility, and this is the most widely accepted today, is that shadday is to be connected with the Akkadian word, s]adu "mountain." Thus El Shaddai would translate into English something like "God/EI of the mountain," i.e. God's abode. nirʾah-ʾelay (nif): be seen, appear<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>vayvarekh ʾoti (brk piʿel): bestow power for success, prosperity, fertility, declare that someone has been given power for success, prosperity, fertility (like the Army slogan "Be all you can be"</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dia omong bilang, &lt;Nanti Beta kasi lu pung ana-upu tamba banya, ko lu pung turunan jadi bangsa yang bésar. Nanti Beta ju kasi ini negrí pi sang lu pung turunan dong, ko jadi dong pung pusaka sampe kiamat.&gt;<bt>He said saying, &lt;Later I will give you increasing amounts of children grandchildren, so that your descendants become a very big nation. Later I will also give this country to your descendands, to become their wealth forever.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinəni: here I am, I am"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hinəni: here I am, I am now making you fruitful. mafrkha (prk hif ptcpl): making you fruitful (lots of descendants)<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>vhirbitikha: (rbh hif): I have made you have many children, have made you great untatikha liqhal ʿamim (ntn): I have given you an assembly of nations; God promised not just to give Israel a lot of descendants, but that a whole company of different nations would descend from him.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʾachuzat: property</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Naa, sakarang lu pung ana Efraim deng Manase pung hak bagini: beta datang di Masir, te dong dua su ada. Biar bagitu, ju sakarang, beta su anggap dong dua ke beta pung ana sandiri, sama ke Ruben deng Simeon.<bt>Naa [+shift] now, those children Efraim and Manase of yours, their rights are like this: I came to Masir, cuz they two existed/were here. So because of that, now, I am assuming them two like my own children, like Ruben and Simeon.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hanoladim (yld nif partcpl): who were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hanoladim (yld nif partcpl): who were born ʿad-boʾi (bwʾ inf cs): before my coming<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>li-hem: they will be mine (= adoption)</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ma nanti kalo lu dapa ana lai, na, itu lu pung ana sa. Beta sonde anggap dong, beta pung ana. Jadi biar nanti dong tarima dong pung pusaka dari dong pung kaka Efraim deng Manase sa.<bt>But later, if you get other children, well those will just be your children. I will not assume them, to be my children. So (consequently) just let them later receive their inheritance from their elder siblings Efraim and Manase.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moladtkha (moledet): offspring, family holadta (yld"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">moladtkha (moledet): offspring, family holadta (yld hif): that you may father<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʿal shem ʾəchehem: more than the name of their brothers - domination? bnachlatam: taking possession, occupation of; possession, domain; inheritance; lot (assigned by God); as far as their property rights are concerned? Rashi thinks so.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Beta bekin bagitu, ko inga lu pung mama Rahel. Waktu kotong kambali dari Mesopotamia pi Kana'an, lu pung mama mati barana di tenga jalan deka deng kampong Efrata di tana Kana'an. Itu waktu beta pung hati susa mau mati! Ju beta kubur sang dia di pinggir jalan yang mau pi kampong Efrata.&gt;&gt; (Itu kampong sakarang, dong kasi nama <span class="Italic">Betlehem</span>.)<bt>I'm doing like that, because of remembering your mama Rahel. When we(ex) returned from Mesopotamia to Kanaan, [background info] your mama died giving birth in the middle of the journey near the village Efrata in Kanaan land. At that time, my liver was incredibly distressed! And I buried her on the side of the road that goes to that village Efrata.&gt;&gt; (That village now, they name it ‘Betlehem’.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="metah ʿali: she died on me;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">metah ʿali: she died on me; and it affected me deeply bʿod kivrat-ʾerets: a stretch of land; a little distance. About The amount of land you can cover in two hours.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Yakob<bt>Yakob</bt><note reference="48:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Isra'el&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab says 'Israel'.</bt></note>omong abis, ju dia angka muka, ais dia lia Yusuf pung ana-ana di situ. Ju dia tanya sang Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Ini sapa pung ana-ana dong ni?&gt;&gt;<bt>finished speaking then, he lifted his face, and he saw Yusuf's children there. Then he asked Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;We! These children here whose are they?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qachem (lqch imperv): bring them kavdu:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">qachem (lqch imperv): bring them kavdu: were heavy, dull; it means he could barely see anything<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vayyaggesh (ngsh hif): he brought them close vayyishshaq (nshq): he kissed them<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>vayəchabbeq (piʿel): embraced them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Tarús Yusuf manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Dong ni, ana-ana yang Tuhan Allah kasi sang beta di Masir.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf replied saying, &lt;&lt;These ones here, the children which the Lord God has given me in Masir here.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais ju Yakob omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bagitu, na, lu bawa dong deka-deka sang beta, ko beta sambayang minta Tuhan Allah kasi berkat sang dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>And then Yakob spoke saying, &lt;&lt;If that the case now, you bring them close to me, so that I can pray asking the Lord God to give them blessing.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="10" />Yakob su tua, deng dia pung mata su kabur. Andia ko dia sonde bisa lia babae lai. Tarús Yusuf bawa dia pung ana dua pi deka-deka sang Yakob, ko dia paló-ciom sang dong.<bt>Yakob was old, and his eyes were already cloudy. That's why he could not see well anymore. Then Yusuf brought those children of his, close to Yakob, for him to embrace kiss them.</bt><v n="11" />Ais ju dia omong deng Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini lama beta pikir sa, beta sonde mungkin katumu deng lu lai. Ma sakarang Tuhan Allah su bekin lebe lai, sampe beta ju masi bisa lia lu pung ana dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>And then he spoke with Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;This long, I just thought, it was impossible for me to meet you again. But now the Lord God has done even more, to the point that I also can still see your children.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rʾoh (rʾh inf cs): to see"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">rʾoh (rʾh inf cs): to see loʾ pillalti (piʿel): I had formed an expectation that I would not see you again, I presumed<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>herʾah (hif): God has made/let me see your offspring gam: even?<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ais ju Yusuf kasi ondor dia pung ana dong dari Yakob,<bt>And then Yusuf reversed his children from Yakob</bt><note reference="48:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Yusuf kasi ondor dia pung ana dong dari Yakob pung teng-tenga lutut.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab says “Yusuf reversed his children from between Yakob's knees.”</bt></note>ju dia tikam lutut deng muka sampe di tana, di dia pung papa pung muka.<bt>, and he knelt with face to the ground, in front of his papa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangku"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">pangku</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotseʾ (ytsʾ hif): he caused them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yotseʾ (ytsʾ hif): he caused them to go meʿim? seated on the bed next to Judah? Theyʾre young men.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>birkayw: his knee(s); out from between his knees? (Rashi, but improbable) by his knees? yishtaHu (Hyh hitp): he prostrated himself<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>lʾappaw: at his face</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ais ju Yusuf bangun. Tarús dia ame dia pung ana dong ko kasi badiri deka-deka deng dia pung papa. Dia taro ana nomer satu, Manase, di Yakob pung sablá kanan; deng ana nomer dua, Efraim, di Yakob pung sablá kiri.<bt>Then Yusuf got up. Next he took his children to have them stand near his papa. He put child number one, Manase, on Yakob's right side; and child number two, Efraim, on Yakob's left side. [NOTE on order: older before younger; right before left. Both are significant cultural issues. The result is the same, even though the presentation differs. it this way, helps bring out the point of the story.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yamino: his right hand mismoʾel: on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yamino: his right hand mismoʾel: on the left<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>yagesh (ngsh hif): he made them approach close</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ma waktu Yakob mau taro tangan ko minta berkat kasi sang dong dua, dia kasi pinda dia pung tangan kanan ko taro pi atas adi pung kapala, deng dia taro tangan kiri pi atas kaka pung kapala.<bt>But when Yakob went to put his hands to ask for bless for the two of them, he moved his right hand to put it on top of younger sibling Efraim's head, and he put his left hand on elder.sibling Manase's head.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishlach: stretch out, send yashet (shyt):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yishlach: stretch out, send yashet (shyt): he set, put<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>tsaʿir: the younger one sikel: he laid his hands crosswise<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>habxor: the firstborn</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Tarús dia sambayang minta Tuhan Allah kasi berkat sang Yusuf bilang,<bt>Then he prayed requesting the Lord God to give bless to Yusuf saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lu pung ba'i Isak pung bapa Abraham,<bt>Your grandfather Isak's father Abraham,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng lu pung ba'i Isak sandiri,<bt>and your grandfather Isak himself,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dong dua iko tarús sang Tuhan Allah pung mau.<bt>the two of them continually followed the Lord God's will.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tuhan Allah ju su piara sang beta dari muda sampe sakarang.<bt>And the Lord God took care of me from youth until now.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hithalləkhu (hlk hitp): they walked ʾvotay:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hithalləkhu (hlk hitp): they walked ʾvotay: my fathers, ancestors<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>haroʿeh: who shepherded meʿodi: from before continually<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="16" />Dia su kasi lolos sang beta dari samua macam calaka.<bt>He has also made me escape from all kinds of disaster. [EXEG: contentious ideas about ‘angel’ vs. ‘God’ here handled by going deliberately vague in the text above ‘He’, and explaining the issue in the footnote (to those who might be interested--the TB says Malaikat [capitalized]).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added, ftn and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added, ftn and btft revised slightly to clarify.</Message></Annotation><note reference="48:16" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta minta ko Tuhan pung ana bua dari sorga kasi lapás sang beta dari samua macam calaka.&gt;&gt; Ma ada ju orang yang pintar bilang ini Tuhan tunju Dia pung diri waktu Dia pake Dia pung ana bua dari sorga ko kasi lapás sang Yakob dari macam-macam calaka. Lia ju <span class="Italic">Carita Mula-mula</span> 16:7; 21:17; 22:11,15.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes saying "I request because *God's assistant from heaven (angel) frees me from all kinds of disaster.&gt;&gt; But there are some knowledgable people say that this is God referring to Himself when He used his angels to free Yakob from all kinds of disaster. See <span class="Italic">Genesis</span> 16:7; 21:17; 22:11,15.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Jadi beta ju minta ko Dia kasi berkat sang ini ana dong deng dong pung turunan.<bt>So I also request that He gives blessing to these children and their descendants.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng kalo dong sambayang sang Tuhan Allah,<bt>And if they worship the Lord God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dong sonde lupa ba'i Abraham, ba'i Isak, deng beta pung nama.<bt>they won't forget grandfather/forefather Abraham, grandfather Isak, and my name.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) deleted /subu/ ‘mention’ to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) deleted /subu/ ‘mention’ to broaden it like Heb.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Biar ko dong pung turunan batamba banya,<bt>May their descendants increase alot,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) ko biar -- biar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) ko biar -- biar ko</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ko biar dong pung turunan tamba"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Ko biar dong pung turunan tamba banya,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko jadi bangsa yang bésar di ini dunya.&gt;&gt;<bt>to become a big/important nation on this earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi lolos = kasi salamat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi lolos = kasi salamat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malʾakh: the angel goʾel (partcpl): the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">malʾakh: the angel goʾel (partcpl): the one delivering; first mention of redemption?<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>raʿ: evil yəvarekh: may he bless<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>yiqqareʾ (nif): my name will be called vyidgu (dgh): may they multiply - related to "fish", multiply like fish<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>larov: into a multitude bqerev: interior, in the midst of, here in the world<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ma waktu Yusuf lia dia pung papa ada taro dia pung tangan kanan di adi Efraim pung kapala, ju dia pegang ame dia pung papa pung tangan, ko kasi pinda di kaka Manase pung kapala.<bt>But when Yusuf saw that his papa put his right hand on Efraim's head, then he grapped that hand of his papa, to move it to elder.sibling Manase's head.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayeraʿ (rʿʿ): he was sad, displeased,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayeraʿ (rʿʿ): he was sad, displeased, discontented, something wrong (raʿ here for a mistake, not absolute evil) vayitmokh: he took hold of his father's hand<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>lhaSiyr (Swr inf): to change it, to put it where it belonged</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Dia kasi tau dia pung papa bilang, &lt;&lt;Papa, é! Jang bekin bagitu. Te dia tu, adi. Dia bukan ana nomer satu. Papa musti taro papa pung tangan kanan di atas kaka pung kapala. Ko itu kaka pung hak na!&gt;&gt;<bt>He told his papa saying, &lt;&lt;Papa! Don't do like that. Cuz that one, younger sibling Efraim. He is not child number one. Papa must put your right hand on elder.sibling Manase's head. Because that is child number one's right.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ma dia pung papa Yakob sonde mau. Ju dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana, é! Beta memang tau. Te nanti Manase jadi hebat, deng dia pung turunan tamba banya sampe jadi bangsa yang bésar. Ma dia pung adi Efraim tu, nanti lebe hebat dari dia. Deng dia pung turunan dong, nanti talalu banya sampe dong jadi banya bangsa yang hebat.&gt;&gt;<bt>But his papa Yakob didn't want to. And he said, &lt;&lt;Child! I actually know. Cuz later Manase will become great, and his descendants will increase until becoming a big nation. But that younger sibling Efraim of his, later he will be even greater than him. And those descendants of his, later will be exceedingly many until they become many nations that are great.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="take the exegesis that 'great' ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">take the exegesis that 'great' = in number/hebat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymaʾen: he refused vʾulam: on the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaymaʾen: he refused vʾulam: on the other hand<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>haqaton: the young(er) one mloʾ: full number, abundance, extent<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ais ju dia kasi tau sang itu ana dua bilang, &lt;&lt;Nanti kalo orang Isra'el minta Tuhan Allah kasi berkat sang orang, dong ju subu bosong dua pung nama. Nanti dong minta bilang, &lt;Moga-moga Tuhan Allah kasi berkat sang lu, sama ke Dia kasi berkat sang Efraim deng Manase.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>And then he told those two children saying, &lt;&lt;Later if the Israel people request the Lord God to bless someone, they will say your two names. Later they will request saying, 'May.it.be that the Lord God blesses you, like He blessed Efraim and Manase.'"</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Deng bagitu, Yakob ju subu Efraim pung nama lebe dolo dari dia pung kaka Manase pung nama.<bt>And like that, Yakob said younger sibling Efraim's name before elder.sibling Manase's name.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ysimkha: may he put you lifney:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ysimkha: may he put you lifney: ahead of<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ais ju Yakob kasi tau sang Yusuf bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana, é! Sonde lama lai, te beta su mati. Ma nanti Tuhan Allah tolong sang bosong, ais Dia bawa bale sang bosong pi di bosong pung nene-moyang dong pung negrí.<bt>And then Yakob told Yusuf saying, &lt;&lt;Child! Not much longer, cuz I will die. But later the Lord God will help you-pl, and He will bring you back to your ancestors' country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heshiv (shwb hif): he will take"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">heshiv (shwb hif): he will take you back</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ma sakarang, beta kasi sang lu lebe dari beta kasi sang lu pung kaka-adi dong. Te beta kasi tamba sang lu gunung di tana Kana'an yang dolu beta ame dari orang Amori, waktu beta baparáng deng dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>But now I give to you more than I give to your elder-younger siblings. Cuz I give extra to you a mountain in Kanaan land which before I got from the Amori people, when I warred with them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shkhem: mountain-ridge (shoulder) End of P"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shkhem: mountain-ridge (shoulder) End of P section.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob omong dia pung ana satu-satu pung sifat deng berkat<bt>Yakob talks about his children each one's character and blessing</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="49" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, Yakob suru pange dia pung ana dong samua. Dong datang abis, ais dia kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Ana dong, é! Mari ko bosong bakumpul deka-deka deng beta di sini dolo. Beta mau kasi tau sang bosong, satu-satu pung jalan idop di balakang hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yakob ordered to summon all his children. He told saying, &lt;&lt;Children! Come and you-pl gather close with me here [mild imp.]. I want to tell you, each one's life's path in the future (lit. behind today).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heʿasfa (nif impv): be gathered, come"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">heʿasfa (nif impv): be gathered, come together ʾagidah (ngd): put forward, announce, explain<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>yiqraʾ: will happen, befall you bʾacharit hayamim: outcome, end of the days<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ais Yakob mulai kasi tau memang dia pung ana-ana dong bilang,<bt>Then Yakob begain to foretell his children saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Bagini! Yakob pung ana dong! Mari bosong badiri kuliling sang beta.<bt>"It's.like this! Yakob's children! Come, you-pl stand around me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dengar bosong pung papa Isra'el mau omong.<bt>Hear your the speaking of this papa Israel of yours.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiqqavtsu (nif impv): assemble"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hiqqavtsu (nif impv): assemble</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />
      <span class="Italic">Ruben!</span> Lu ni, beta pung ana paling tua! Lu ni, beta pung tongkat, deng beta pung tangan kanan. Orang paling hormat sang lu.<bt>Ruben! You here, my oldest child. You here, my staff, and my right hand. People respect/honour you most. [EXEG: ‘outstanding in power’ In last half of verse Heb. /sʔet/ ‘nobility, dignity, rank’; / ʕaz/ ‘power, strength’. Most agree that this is not talking about Reuben's physical strength, which would be in focus if we went literal here. With help from two consultants, we've gone to the metaphors of ‘staff’ and ‘right hand’. The first evokes rank/authority, and the second evokes influence/authority. So it's all there.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beta pung tongkat sang lu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">beta pung tongkat sang lu = tempat bersandar,; koi &lt; Dutch ; *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kochi: my strength ʾoni: my generative"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kochi: my strength ʾoni: my generative power, ability to make a woman pregnant<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>yeter: over and above, remaining, have precedence sʾet: nobility, dignity<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ʿaz: power, strength</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ma lu pung hati gampang tagoyang, sonde tau lu pung mau yang mana, sama ke arus laut yang takuju pi sini-pi sana. Takuju sa, lu su pi tidor deng beta pung bini Bilha, ko bekin kamomos lu pung papa pung koi. Andia ko lu pung pangkat kaka jato memang!<bt>But your liver is easily shaken, doesn't know your will is what, just like currents in the sea that suddenly go here or go there. Unexpectedly, you slept with my wife Bilha, and.so defiled your papa's bed. That's why your rank of elder.sibling has actually fallen! [EXEG: Heb. unstable, undisciplined, reckless, fickle. TH says unstable translates a word whose meaning is uncertain. Driver thinks the basic idea is probably “to be uncontained,” Worked with several consultants on this. NRSV. Careful, NET Bible ‘destructive’ is off on its own without much support.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uncontrollable / unpredictable as water ***reintroduce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">uncontrollable / unpredictable as water ***reintroduce figure of metaphor (unstable as water, currents of the sea)<span class="Italic">(4) </span>*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pachaz: undisciplined, reckless: koniaku is kind"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">pachaz: undisciplined, reckless: koniaku is kind of like jello or tofu that isn't stiff, wishy-washy; but only Japanese recognize it. ʾal-towtar (ytr hif): do not excel<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ʾaz (not ʿaz): then? emphasis? chillalta: you profaned<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>yətsuwʿi: my couch End of P section.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />
      <span class="Italic">Simeon</span> deng <span class="Italic">Lewi!</span> Bosong dua satu merek! Bosong dua talalu gampang maen angka kalewang, ko bekin orang dong sangsara.<bt>Simeon and Lewi! You two one brand! You two are very easy to habitually pick up a sword, to make people in distress.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="merek = brand (can be applied"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">merek = brand (can be applied to people) ; satu hoang (a cut of daging se'i)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CONSIDER GOING TO 3P TO SIGNAL"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">CONSIDER GOING TO 3P TO SIGNAL FATHER'S CONTINUING ANGER / DISAPPOINTMENT</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kli chamas: an instrument of violence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">kli chamas: an instrument of violence mkeroteyhem: their weapons; text not clear<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Bosong pung sanáng, andia potong bekin putus sapi pung urat kaki, sampe dong taputar satenga mati di tampa sa. Deng bosong pung jahat lai, andia bosong makan gigi, baru bosong bunu orang. Andia ko beta sonde mau toe bosong pung omong. Beta ju sonde mau iko campor deng bosong pung parkara.<bt>Your happiness, it's cutting cow's foot tendons, to the point that they just turn.around and around half dead in one place. And your other evil, it's you get very angry (lit: eat your teeth), then you murder people. That's why I don't want to pay attention to your talk. I also don't want to get involved with your debates/affairs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="makan gigi(1) = mara memang; makan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">makan gigi(1) = mara memang; makan gigi(2) = cubit anak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sodam: their circle of confidants qəhalam:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Sodam: their circle of confidants qəhalam: their assembly<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʾal-techad: donʾt join kvodi: my good reputation, my honor<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʾappam: their anger birtsonam: their liking to do arbitrarily whatever they like<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>ʿiqqəru (piʿel): hamstring, cripple</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Jadi sakarang beta kutuk bosong pung asaráng tu, ko su talalu na! Deng bosong pung mara yang sonde ada pung rasa kasian sadiki ju. Nanti bosong musti tanggong sandiri bosong pung jahat. Nanti Tuhan kasi talempar kiri-kanan bosong pung turunan dong. Ais dong tenga tasiram di mana-mana di tana Isra'el.<bt>So (consequently) now I curse your roughness of yours, because it is excessive [+obvious]! And also your anger which has not even any feeling of pity/love. Later you must bear responsiblity yourselves for that evilness of yours. Later the Lord will throw left-right your descendants. And they will stay spread all over the place in Israel land.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="asaráng (MK) = kasar, kejam; tampias"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">asaráng (MK) = kasar, kejam; tampias = spread (water splashing)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾarur: cursed ʿevratam: their arrogance|i(7) (7)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾarur: cursed ʿevratam: their arrogance<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>qashatah: harsh, severe ʾechalləqem: I will set them aside, scatter them<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>vʾafitsem (fwts): disperse End of S section.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00047c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Singa laki deng singa mai<bt>Male and female lion</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />
      <span class="Italic">Yahuda!</span> Lu pung nama pung arti bilang &lt;puji&gt;. Lu pung kaka-adi dong nanti puji sang lu, deng tondo kasi hormat sang lu. Lu ju tendes ame lu pung musu dong, sampe dong sonde bisa angka kapala.<bt>Yahuda! Your name means 'praise'. Your elder-younger siblings praise you, and they offer respect to you. You also put pressure on your enemies, until they cannot left their head.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kandók = back of neck; ceke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kandók = back of neck; ceke = front of neck</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yodukha: they will praise you (pun)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yodukha: they will praise you (pun) ʾoref: hair area, from the top of the head to the back of the neck; the metaphor doesn't communicate in Pidgin, but the idea of being able to handle opposition directly does<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>yishtachuvu (shchh hitp): bow down</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Lu ni ke singa muda yang hebat, ko bisa cari makan sandiri. Lu ju sama ke singa laki yang hela badan ko mau pi tidor; sonde ada yang barani pi korek sang lu. Lu ju sama ke singa mai yang ada jaga dia pung ana; sonde ada orang yang barani pi ganggu. Bagitu ju deng lu, te orang eleng sang lu, deng sonde barani bekin macam-macam.<bt>You here are like a young lion who is great, and can go hunt for food himself. You are also like a male lion who throws his body to go sleep; there is no one who dares flick/bother you. You are also like a female lion who watch her children; there is no one who dares go bother. It's also like that with you. People are afraid of you, and they don't dare do anything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="singa tenak = muda (betina); hela"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">singa tenak = muda (betina); hela badan, ais tidor; korek = flick; eleng = segan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="guwr: young lion Teref: prey|i(9) (9)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">guwr: young lion Teref: prey<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>karaʿ: crouch like a lion, chest on ground ravats: he lies down (said of animals)<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>labiʾ: lioness (poetic word) yəqiymennuw (qwm hif): make him get up<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Nanti lu yang pegang parenta. Lu pung turunan dong ju pegang parenta ba'iko-ba'iko sampe nanti ada satu yang ada pung hak lebe dari samua, yang dudu pegang itu parenta. Ais bangsa-bangsa dong samua soya deng dengar sang Dia.<bt>Later you here, will hold authority. Your descendants will also hold authority one after another, until later there is one who has the most right to sit hold that authority. Then all nations will bow (give respect) and listen/obey Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaSuwr (Swr): turn aside shevet: rod,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yaSuwr (Swr): turn aside shevet: rod, staff. King Kalakaua had one.<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>məchoqeq: lawgiver (with implicit reference to "loins")? ruler's staff? Shiloh: could be the place name, which would mean "until he comes to Shiloh", or a Midrash interprets it as Shai Lo "tribute to him". Since nobody seems to know where Shiloh is, we follow the latter.<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>yiqchat: obedience of peoples to him</Message></Annotation><note reference="49:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 1:3</note><v n="11" />Nanti lu idop sanáng-sanáng. Lu mau apa sa, ada! Lu mau bekin apa sa, jadi! Ais lu pung binatang deng kabón pung hasil dong, tamba banya sampe tabuang-tabuang.<bt>Later you will live happily. Whatever you might want, it will be there! Whatever you might do, it will happen [successfully]. And your animals, and garden harvest, will increase to the point that you throw stuff away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾoSriy: binding, tying. The idea is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾoSriy: binding, tying. The idea is that he will be so rich that the loss of a grape vine here and there isn't going to put him out of business, and he's got so much wine that he might as well wash clothes in it. Same idea as lighting your cigar with a $100 bill. gefen: grape vine<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>ʿiroh: his male donkey bni ʾatono: his female donkey's child<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>kibes: clean clothes without soap by treading, kneading, or beating fuller's earth, stale urine, or ashes into them. There was no soap back then. dam-anavim: blood of grapes; squeezings from grapes<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>Suwtah: his garment</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Lu pung makan-minum dong ena-ena, sampe sonde tau abis-abis.<bt>Your food-drink, delicious, to the point that they never run out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chakhəliyliy: sparkling (dark, like sparkling dark"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chakhəliyliy: sparkling (dark, like sparkling dark eyes?) ləven: white<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>shinnayim: his two [sets of] teeth End of P section.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />
      <span class="Italic">Sebulon!</span> Lu pung tana pusaka paling luas, deng deka laut, sampe babatas deng kota Sidon. Kapal-kapal dong datang dari mana-mana ko buang jangkar deng aman di lu pung pante.<bt>Sebulon! Your inheritance land is the widest, and near the ocean, until the border with Sidon city. Ships come from all over to throw anchor in safety at your beach.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chof yamim: beach, shore yishkon: settle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chof yamim: beach, shore yishkon: settle down, inhabit<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>lchof: as a harbor? We have the Waiʿanae Boat Harbor here, a major center for sport and small scale fishing. The trawlers and large freighters and passenger ships go out of Honolulu Harbor, and the long liners and sport fisherman go out of Kewalo Basin. End of S section.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14-15" />
      <span class="Italic">Isaskar!</span> Lu ni, sama ke keledai kuat, ma lu pung kapala batu sonde bisa-bisa pung. Kalo lu su tidor di tenga jalan, na,<bt>Isaskar! You here, are like a strong donkey, but your stubborness is the greatest. If you sleep on the road,</bt><note reference="49:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani bisa pake dua arti: &lt;&lt;tidor di dua tampa pung teng-tenga,&gt;&gt; deng &lt;&lt;tidor di dua karong muatan pung teng-tenga&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language can have two meanings: 'sleep between two places' or 'sleep between two cargo sacks.'</bt></note>sapa yang masi bisa paksa kasi bangun sang lu, ko jalan tarús. Ma kalo lu su dapa lia kampong bagus di sablá sana, sonde suru ju, lu su pikol lu pung muatan ko jalan pi. Andia lu tu, bagitu suda!<bt>who can still force you to wake up, and keep traveling. If you have seen that good village on the other side, even without being ordered, you shoulder-carry your cargo in order to go. That's you that, just like that! [EXEG: Hamilton discusses credibly a number of problems with majority interpretation as "slaves", both internal to this passage, as well as external, and extrabiblical.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nt tidor = istilah untuk kuda;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">nt tidor = istilah untuk kuda; sonde bisa-bisa pung = sangat kapala batu, kapala batu pung ba'i, impossible to deal with</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">garem: bones sticking out? strong? castrated? rovets: lies down on his chest, possibly exhausted from work, or maybe just lazy as the next verse suggests.<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>beney hamishpatayim: between his two saddlebags mnuchah: resting-place<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>naʿemah: nice, pleasant, agreeable vayet (nth): bends down his shoulder<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>shikhmo: his shoulders, with both the neck and the back liSbol (Sbl inf): to carry a load<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>maS: lowest form of work, complete enslavement, cheap day labor End of S section.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />
      <span class="Italic">Dan!</span> Lu pung nama pung arti bilang &lt;hakim&gt;. Ais lu ni, deng lu pung turunan yang nanti putus lu pung suku pung parkara dong deng sonde barát sablá. Te lu pung suku tu, satu dari bangsa Isra'el dong.<bt>Dan! Your name means 'judge'. So you here, and your descendants, will be the ones to decide your tribe's litigations without being heavy on one side (=justly, fairly). Cuz (elaboration) your tribe is one of the nation/race/ethnic group of Isra'el.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lurus; sonde barát sablá = unbiased,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lurus; sonde barát sablá = unbiased, adil ; *** (2009) revised</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yadin (dyn): will judge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">yadin (dyn): will judge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ais lu ini, deng lu pung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Ais lu ini, deng lu pung turunan, yang nanti putus lu pung bangsa Isra'el dong pung parkara deng sonde barát sablá.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Lu ni ju lihai sama ke ular baracon yang ada tidor jaga di pinggir jalan. Kalo orang nae kuda lewat di situ, takuju sa, lu su gigi kuda pung balakang kaki, sampe dia pung orang jato talempar.<bt>You here also are cunning like a poisonous snake that lies on the side of the road. If a person on a horse goes by there, suddenly/unexpectedly, you bite the back of the horse's foot, until his person falls thrown off. [ALT: /lihai/, also /licik/]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="grounds of comparison = snake +"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">grounds of comparison = snake + Dan = trecherous kaki balakang; lihai = pintar cari salák *** (2009) fixed BT, added note</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shfifon: possibly the horned snake, Zamenis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shfifon: possibly the horned snake, Zamenis diadema. There are 23 species of snakes around the Palestine area (though this was in Egypt), and 20 of them are poisonous.&gt;&gt; ʾorach: way, path<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ʿiqqəvey: hooves of horses vayipol (nfl impf): fall down<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>rokhvo: his rider</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ee, TUHAN, é! Beta do'a-do'a ko Lu kasi salamat sang botong samua.<bt>Yes LORD! I hope and pray You will save all us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="do'a-do'a ko = harapan sungguh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">do'a-do'a ko = harapan sungguh</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lishuʿatkha (yshwʿ): for your help qiwwiti:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lishuʿatkha (yshwʿ): for your help qiwwiti: I am waiting for something tensely, eagerly -- not just twiddling my thumbs till something happens.<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19" />
      <span class="Italic">Gad!</span> Lu pung nama pung bunyi amper sama ke &lt;saráng&gt;. Nanti gerombolan parampok dong saráng sang lu, ma lu bale saráng kasi kala sang dong.<bt>Gad! You name's sound is almost like 'attack'. Later gangs of robbers will attack you, but you will counterattack defeating them. [NOTE to daughter translations: The “sounds like” is actually with reference to two similar Hebrew words, so this may be non-sensical in your language. If this is a problem, just use /lu pung nama amper sama ke.../]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gdud: raiding party, troop division, hosts"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gdud: raiding party, troop division, hosts (pun) ygudenu (gwd): attack (pun)<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>yagud: he will attack aqev: in the end<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="20" />
      <span class="Italic">Aser!</span> Nanti lu pung kabón pung hasil paling bae, sampe lu bisa bekin kue mewa-mewa yang enak, ko raja-raja dong datang béli di lu.<bt>Aser! Later your garden harvest will be very good, to.the.point.hat you can make really fancy delicious cakes, for rajas to come buy them from you. [EXEG: ‘delicacies’. The challenge is between too broad (food) and too specific (baked goods). The solution is provided by the context. As TH notes “dainties are luxury items, things people can afford only if they are rich enough. The sense of this line is that the food raised in Asher’s territory will find its way to the tables of kings because of its fine quality.” The category that best symbolizes that luxury in this region is “baked goods”. DON'T just say generic “delicious food”--add least add “expensive”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shmenah: with oil in it, rich"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shmenah: with oil in it, rich maʿadannim: delicacies<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00034c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Rusa<bt>Deer</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="21" />
      <span class="Italic">Naftali!</span> Lu ni, sama ke rusa mai yang liar, ais sonde ada orang bisa ator sang lu. Lu ju barana ame ana-ana yang manis-manis.<bt>Naftali! You here, are like a wild female deer, whom noone can (really) manage. You also gave birth to your children who are very good looking. [EXEG: wide-ranging possibilities with this verse. We go with animal (deer) rather than plant (terebinth). We go with ‘wild’ (TH, CEV, NET). Older version /lari fuik/ evoked irresponsibility rather than free spirit, while /talapás/ implies debatable ideas of a tamed deer set free, in which the scholars are not in agreement.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rusa yg terlapas = liar; bandingan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">rusa yg terlapas = liar; bandingan = lu akan idop bebas, sonde ada yang parenta sang lu ; *** (2009) deleted /lari/ and added note</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿayyalah: female fallow deer, Dama mesopotamica,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿayyalah: female fallow deer, Dama mesopotamica, extinct there since 1914, Fauna p. 20 shluchah (pass): is let get away<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>hannoten (ntn partcpl): giving, producing ʿemer: branched antlers? fawns? words?<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>ʿimrey-shafer: antlers End of S section.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="22" />
      <span class="Italic">Yusuf!</span> Lu sama ke pohon malata yang idop deka mata aer. Lu pung cabang dong malata nae pi tembok tinggi-tinggi.<bt>Yusuf! You are like a climbing tree/vine that lives near a spring. Your branches climb/spread up a tall wall. [NOTE to daughter translations: consider: Its branches will climb over a tall (stone)wall, like your descendants spread out to other places.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malata = menjalar ke sirih (UNS);"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">malata = menjalar ke sirih (UNS); cabang = takis pakai tafsiran TB di sini, bukan BIS; malata = creep, but doesnt' have connotations that marayap has of gradually taking over s.o. else's things, position, rights; ma'orok = steal, snitch, sneakily; pi pacaran galap-galap; bamengge = crawl, curl around s.t.; batambi = dating nona,<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="porat (partcpl fem): fruitful tsaʿədah: mount"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">porat (partcpl fem): fruitful tsaʿədah: mount up (like branches growing up and over a wall)<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>shuwr: wall</Message></Annotation><note reference="49:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani dalam ini ayat sonde jalás. Ada orang yang pintar bilang dia pung arti &lt;pohon malata&gt;, ada yang bilang &lt;keledai&gt;.<bt>The Ibrani language Alkitab in this verse is not clear. There are knowledgeable people who say it's meaning is climbing tree/vine, there are those who say 'donkey'.</bt></note><v n="23" />Ada ju orang yang lempar dong pung saki hati sang lu, sama ke musu yang pana sang lu.<bt>There are also people who throw their injured liver at you, like an enemy who shoots you with an arrow. [EXEG: Hamilton and others raise the question, If this is to be taken literally, there is no record of this kind of attack on Joseph recorded and similarly if one takes the critical line that this was written later and refers to Joseph's tribe (?), it is equally problematic. So Hamilton and others interpret enemies here as Joseph's brothers, and the whole thing as figurative. The Hebrew word ‘made his life bitter, provoked him’ also leans it toward figurative problems with relationships. The linguistic pattern in this region is “people attack you (grounds of comparison), like a person shoots arrows (figure), not the other way around. And since vs. 23 is overtly a simile throwing it into figurative interpretation, that figurative interpretation carries over to vs. 24. The Rotenese are the kings of figurative usage, and once they get the figurative signal they carry it through.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasi tersurat bahwa dia pung musu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">kasi tersurat bahwa dia pung musu itu = dia pung kaka adi dong; pana = arrow *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaymarəruwhuw (mrr piʿel): they made his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaymarəruwhuw (mrr piʿel): they made his life bitter, provoked him varov: and it was abundant<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>vayisTəmuhuw: they bore a grudge baʿaley chittsim: masters of arrows = archers<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Ma Tuhan Allah yang beta sémba tu, tolong sang lu. Andia ko Dia bekin kuat lu pung tangan, sampe lu bisa pana balas sang dong, biar dari jao-jao. Lu bisa manáng sang dong, tagal Tuhan yang tolong sang lu, memang Dia pung kuasa hebat batúl! Andia ko beta basandar di Dia. Te Dia yang jaga sang beta.<bt>But the Lord God whom I worship, helped/helps you. That's why he made your arm strong, to the point that you can shoot them with an arrow in return, even from far. You can win over them, because the it's the Lord who has helped you, really He whose power is truly awesone! That's why I lean.against Him. Cuz He is the one who watches/guards me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teshev: sat, stayed ʾeytan: firm|i(24) (24)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">teshev: sat, stayed ʾeytan: firm<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>vayyafozzu (pzz): was nimble, agile zəroʿey: the force of<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>zroʿey yadaw: the power of his hand ʾavir: strong, powerful<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Dia ju nanti jaga sang lu. Deng Dia kasi berkat sang lu, berkat dari langit, berkat dari bumi, deng berkat barana ana bam-banya yang sehat-sehat.<bt>He also later will guard/watch you. And He will give blessing to you, blessing from the sky, blessing from the earth, and blessing of giving birth to many children who are really healthy. [EXEG: ‘deep’ Genre: poetry; grammar: Hebraism (sky above - deep below); note ‘breast &amp; womb’ also show pattern of part representing whole; rendering: local categories used extensively in local poetic parallelisms; support: NLT (worldwide protocols say that's enough reason) We've actually put a lot of work in on vs. 25-26 with a couple consultants.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vyaʿzrekha: he supports you ʾet shadday"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vyaʿzrekha: he supports you ʾet shadday (accusative + shadayim dual): two breasts = yoa wife wen she make milk fo yoa kids OR<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>ʾel shadday: Almighty God rovetset: crouching, lying<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>the breast and the womb; part for the whole</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Gunung dong sonde ilang buang. Deng beta pung berkat kasi sang lu ni, lebe banya dari gunung dong samua! Biar berkat samua ni, tapo'a pi sang lu, tagal lu yang paling lebe dari lu pung kaka-adi dong samua.<bt>The mountains never disappear. And this blessing I am giving to you here, it's more than all the mountains! [EXEG: eternal = explicit &gt; implicit; early draft tried /kekal/ (Indo, not KM), but collocational clash; /tua/ is tautology; other attempts skewed the focus; /yang dari dolu-dolu dong/ (implies some are newer)?] May it be that all these blessings, pour out on you, because you are the most more(superior) of all your elder-younger siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paling kantara = kelihatan, menonjol; paling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">paling kantara = kelihatan, menonjol; paling lebe *** element of "eternal" added back in with first sentence as background, Dhao check, Sept 2004<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Suggestion from Amarasi team: reconsider tapo'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">Suggestion from Amarasi team: reconsider tapo'a &gt; malele</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gavru: exceed, excel over taʾəwat: delightful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">gavru: exceed, excel over taʾəwat: delightful things<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>givʿot: hills qadqod: girigiri (the whorl of hair over the back of the skull); head, crown of head, top of head, hairy crown, scalp; from qdd ʾbowʾ, possibly the part of the head you see when somebody bows to you. Most translations say "brow," but it's not the forehead.<span class="Italic">(26) (26) </span>nəzir: one dedicated as a prince, singled out End of P section.<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\bk00045c.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Anjing utan di tana Isra'el</fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="27" />
      <span class="Italic">Benyamin!</span> Lu pung barani sama ke anjing utan lapar. Kalo papagi, dia su baburu ko tangkap ame dia pung makanan. Kalo malam, dia pi babagi yang sisa dong kasi dia pung ana-ana. Lu pung turunan ju hebat bagitu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Benyamin! Your boldness is like a hungry jungle(wild) dog. If/when early in the morning, he has already gone hunting to catch his food. If/when it's night, he goes to divide the left.over, to his children. Your descendants will also be great like that.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bandingan anjing utan deng Benyamin ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bandingan anjing utan deng Benyamin = fierce ; *** (2009) restructured slightly to mirror poetic parallelism</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zʾev: wolf, Canis lupus yitraf: he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">zʾev: wolf, Canis lupus yitraf: he tears in pieces<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>ʿad: prey ychalleq (piʿel): divide booty<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>shalal: prey, booty</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Bagitu suda, Yakob kasi tau memang dia pung ana-ana pung jalan idop di balakang hari, satu-satu deng dia pung turunan. Dong samua tu yang kasi turun dua blas suku Isra'el.<bt>Already like that, Yakob foretold his children's lives in the future, each one with his descendants. They all there are who descended the 12 clans of Israel. [EXEG: don't force the sense of ‘blessing’ in this verse. TH correctly points out that one sense of these Heb words is simply “parting words”. “the wording is repetitive and is literally “and he blessed them each one whom after his blessing he blessed them.” As noted at the beginning of the chapter, the term “blessing” is really inappropriate in English and many other languages for the content of much of what Jacob says to the sons. Here in verse 28 is the only occurrence of words for “blessing” in the Hebrew text of this subdivision. TEV, Speiser, and NJB (in part) show us one possible way to deal with the problem: to render the Hebrew terms as “give a parting message” or “say farewell,” as in 47.10, where the same verb is used. This is a particularly good recommendation for those languages in which “parting words” or “last words” in a deathbed context give the sense of speaking about the inheritance and the leadership of the clan. Speiser “as he bade them farewell, addressing to each an appropriate parting message”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yakob pung mati<bt>Yakob dies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29-30" />Ais ju Yakob minta dia pung ana dong janji bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde lama lai, te beta su mati. Kalo beta mati, bosong musti pi kubur sang beta di ba'i Abraham pung kubur. Itu kubur ada di goa, badeka deng kampong Makpela deng Mamre di tana Kana'an. Dolu ba'i Abraham béli ame itu goa deng dia pung kabón ko bekin dia pung tampa kubur. Dia béli kontan dari orang suku Het, nama Efron.<bt>After that Yakob asked his children to promise saying, &lt;&lt;Not much longer, cuz I will be dead. When I die, you must go bury me in grandfather Abraham's grave. That grave is in a cave, close to the village of Makpela and Mamre in Kanaan land. Before grandfather Abraham bought that cave and its field to make his grave place. He bought outright from people of clan/group Het, his name Efron.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beli kontan = sonde kredit (UNS)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">beli kontan = sonde kredit (UNS)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaytsaw (tswh): ordered neʾəSaf (nif): meet,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaytsaw (tswh): ordered neʾəSaf (nif): meet, gather, be gathered, be taken away<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>məʿarah: cave laʾəchuzzat: as a possession<span class="Italic">(29) (29) </span>qever: grave, sepulcher</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Di situ dong kubur kotong pung ba'i Abraham deng nene Sara, beta pung papa Isak, deng beta pung mama Ribka. Jadi bosong ju musti kubur sang beta di situ, di beta pung bini Lea pung sablá.<bt>There they also buried our grandfather Abraham and grandmother Sara, my papa Isak, and my mama Ribka. thus, you must bury me there, at my wife Lea's side. [EXEG: vs. 29-32 are Jacob's very detailed death-bed instructions about his burial. Context sets up 3 pairs of husband-wife. So “at my wife Lea's side” is RL naturalness from context, not addition.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nene Sara *** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">nene Sara *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shammah: to there"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">shammah: to there</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Naa, bosong jang lupa kubur sang beta di itu goa yang ba'i Abraham su béli ame tu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Naa, [+shift] you don't forget to bury me in that cave that grandfather Abraham bought.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miqneh hasadeh: the landed property"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">miqneh hasadeh: the landed property</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Yakob omong abis bagitu, ju dia tidor kambali di atas koi, ju dia mati.<bt>Yakob finished talking like that then, he laid down again on the bed, and he died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyeʾəSof: collect, take in, take away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayyeʾəSof: collect, take in, take away vayyeʾaSef (nif): meet, gather, be gathered, be taken away<span class="Italic">(33)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="50" />
      <v n="1" />Ais Yusuf paló ame dia pung papa, ju dia manangis makarereu. Tarús dia ciom dia pung papa ulang-ulang.<bt>Then Yusuf embraced his papa, and he cried with.loud.sobs. Next he kissed his papa over and over.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manangis berduka = ?; cium ulit-ulit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">manangis berduka = ?; cium ulit-ulit (hard on both cheeks)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayipol (nfl): let himself fall, throw"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayipol (nfl): let himself fall, throw himself down; a sign of grief, often seen on TV reports of Mid East funerals</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ais ju Yusuf parenta tukang urus mayat dong, ko taro ramuan, ko bekin awet Yakob pung mayat.<bt>After that then, Yusuf ordered the craftsmen who arrange corpses, to put perservates, to preserve Yakob's corpse.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ramuan = macam-macam obat; awet ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ramuan = macam-macam obat; awet = ko tahan lama, preserve; rampe is only to deal with smell of corpse, not to preserve</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lachənoT: to embalm, Egyptian style"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">lachənoT: to embalm, Egyptian style</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ais, itu tukang dong urus itu mayat sampe ampa pulu hari, iko dong pung biasa. Ju orang Masir dong samua iko manangis Yakob pung mati. Dong bekin bagitu sampe tuju pulu hari, sama ke dong pung orang bésar yang mati.<bt>Then, those craftsmen took.care.of that corpse for 40 days, following their custom. And the Masir people all followed crying (for) Yakob's death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="official grieving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">official grieving</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayimlʾu-lo: they filled up 40 days"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayimlʾu-lo: they filled up 40 days on him; it took them 40 days to do it vayivku (bkh): they cried = observed a mourning period<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Abis dia pung tuju pulu hari, ju Yusuf kasi tau dia pung pagawe bilang, &lt;&lt;Dengar! Beta minta ko bosong bawa beta pung omong ni, pi kasi tau sang raja bilang bagini:<bt>After 70 days then, Yusuf told his civil.servants saying, &lt;&lt;Listen! I ask that you take this talking of mine, go tell the raja saying like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾim-naʾ matsaʾti chen bʿeynekhem: if I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾim-naʾ matsaʾti chen bʿeynekhem: if I have found favor in your eyes bʾazney farʿoh: in Pharaoh's ear; privately, not as a formal request<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />&lt;Waktu beta pung papa su mau mati, dia ada minta beta janji ko pi kubur dia pung mayat di tana Kana'an. Jadi beta minta raja kasi isin ko beta pi kubur beta pung papa. Ais itu, baru beta bale datang di sini.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;When my papa was about to die, he asked me to promise to bury his corpse in Kanaan land. So (consequently) I request the raja to give permission for me to go bury my papa. After that, then I will return to here.&gt;&gt;&gt; [EXEG: ‘caused me to swear an oath’ is undertranslated (as in CEV) so as to not make heavy information load. ‘Ordered’ also doesn't fit here. In local RL languages and cultures ‘swearing an oath’ is more associated with affirming the truth of something. It is quite common here for children to be obligated to move the bones of a loved one at a later date, but this obligation is expressed as a ‘promise’, not ‘swearing an oath’. Context and collocation. See also next verse.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishbiyʿaniy (shbʿ hif): he caused me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">hishbiyʿaniy (shbʿ hif): he caused me to swear an oath qivriy: my tomb<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>kariti (krh): I have dug (maybe a shelf inside the Makpelah burial cave?)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Dengar bagitu, ju raja manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo lu su janji lu pung papa bagitu, na, pi ko kubur sang dia di sana suda.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that then, the raja answered saying, &lt;&lt;If you have promised your father like that then, go bury him there [imp.]"</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Tarús Yusuf pi kubur dia pung papa. Orang banya ju iko pi deng dia. Andia raja pung pagawe dong samua, deng orang bésar samua dari Masir.<bt>Then Yusuf went to bury his papa. Many people also went with him. That.is the all the raja's civil.servants, and the big(important) people from Masir.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ziqney: senior officials"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ziqney: senior officials</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Yusuf pung kaka-adi, deng dong pung orang karjá samua ju iko pi kubur sang Yakob. Yang tenga di Gosen, cuma dong pung bini deng ana kici dong, deng dong pung binatang.<bt>And Yusuf's elder-younger siblings, and all their workers went to bury Yakob. Those remaining in Gosen, only their wives and the little babies, and their animals.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bini-ana"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">bini-ana</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tappam: their people who were too"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">Tappam: their people who were too weak to walk - children and older people ʿazvuw: were left behind<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Tantara banya yang iko ju. Ada yang pake kareta, deng ada yang nae kuda. Tagal yang iko tu, banya sakali, andia ko rombongan yang iko bajalan antar mayat jadi talalu panjang.<bt>Many army [people] also went. There were those who used carts, and those who rode horses. Because those who went, very many, that's.why the group that went traveling to deliever that corpse was very long.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rekhev: contingent of chariots parashim: horsemen,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">rekhev: contingent of chariots parashim: horsemen, cavalrymen<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>machaneh: encampment, contingent</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais dong samua bajalan sampe langgar kali Yarden di satu tampa nama Atad. Orang biasa datang ko puku padi di situ. Ais di itu tampa, Yusuf dong manangis makarereu dia pung papa pung mati. Ju dong mete-mete lai tuju malam.<bt>Then they all travel until crossing Yarden river at a place called Atad. People usually come to thresh padi there. So at that place, Yusuf-them cried in great sobs about his father's death. And they held wakes again for 7 nights.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="puku padi = thresh by flailing,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">puku padi = thresh by flailing, (UNS) rontok (BI), kasi gugur dia pung isi dong</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goren: threshing floor, threshing camp ʾatad:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">goren: threshing floor, threshing camp ʾatad: boxthorn<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>vayyiSpəduw: they beat their breast, sounded a lament miSped<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>vayaʿas ʾevel: he made mourning rites</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Waktu orang Kana'an di situ lia dong susa bagitu, ju dong omong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bosong lia dolo. Orang Masir dong pung cara mete pung sedí ame lai! Dong manangis sampe bagitu macam tu.&gt;&gt; Andia ko dong kasi nama itu tampa <span class="Italic">Abel-Misraim.</span> Dia pung arti &lt;orang Masir pung duka&gt;.<bt>When the Kanaan people there saw their distress like that, they spoke saying, &lt;&lt;We! You-pl look at that. The Masir people's way of holding wakes is very sad! That's why they named that place Abel-Misraim. It's meaning, 'Masir people's grief.' [EXEG: ‘They’ in next to last sentence is delberately vague to mirror the Hebrew. It can map to either the Canaanites or the Egyptians (as can the Hebrew). Don't force a clear referent.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sedi ame = sedih sekali ***"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">sedi ame = sedih sekali *** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ais Yakob pung ana dong bekin iko sama ke dong pung janji.<bt>Then Yakob's children did according to that promise of theirs.</bt><v n="13" />Ju dong angka bawa Yakob pung mayat, ko pi kubur di goa deka kampong Makpela deng Mamre. Abraham su béli itu tampa dari orang suku Het, nama Efron, ko dia bekin jadi dong pung tampa kubur.<bt>And they lifted brought Yakob's corpse, to go the grave in the cave near the villages of Makpela and Mamre. Abraham had bought that place from a person of clan Het, named Efron, to make it be their burying place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bimʿarat: in a cave in a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">bimʿarat: in a cave in a field qanah: buy<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>ʾəchuzzat: possession</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf bekin tanáng dia pung kaka dong pung hati<bt>Yusuf makes calm his elder siblings' livers</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Yusuf kubur abis dia pung papa, ju dia deng dia pung kaka-adi dong bale pi Masir. Bagitu ju deng samua orang laen yang iko pi kubur deng dong.<bt>Yusuf finished burying his papa, then he and his elder-younger siblings returned to Masir. And so also all the other people who went to the grave with them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Waktu dong sampe di Masir, Yusuf pung kaka dong mulai taku. Tagal dong pung papa su sonde ada lai, ju dong ba'omong bilang, &lt;&lt;We! Bosong pikir dolo! Andekata Yusuf masi simpan hati sang kotong, ko dia balas kotong pung bekin jahat sang dia, na, karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they arrived in Masir, Yusuf's elder siblings started being afraid. Because their papa was no more, then they spoke saying, &lt;&lt;We! You-pl think about it! If for example Yusuf is still storing his liver toward us, in order to return our evil deed that we did to him, na, what about it?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luʾ: suppose yisTəmenuw: still bears a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">luʾ: suppose yisTəmenuw: still bears a grudge (but doesn't say anything)<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>hashev yashiv (shwv): pay back, take revenge gamalnu: we perpetrated, rendered<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Ais dong ba'akór ko dong kirim kabar kasi Yusuf bilang bagini: &lt;&lt;Pak wakil. Botong masi inga waktu kotong pung papa masi idop, dia ada suru sang botong<bt>Then they all agreed to send word to Yusuf saying like this: "Mr Vice. We still remember when our papa was alive, he told us</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaytsawwuw: they made an an appointment"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vaytsawwuw: they made an an appointment</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />ko kasi tau sang pak bilang, &lt;Usu musti lupa buang dia pung kaka dong pung sala. Tagal dolu dong su bekin jahat sang dia.&gt; Botong ju inga kotong pung papa ada sémba sang Tuhan Allah dari dolu. Botong ju jadi itu Tuhan pung hamba-hamba. Andia sakarang botong datang minta ampon, tagal botong samua su bekin sala sang pak.&gt;&gt;<bt>to tell Mr saying, 'Usu must forgive his elder sibling wrongs. Because before they did evil to him.' We also remember our papa worshipped the Lord God from before. We also have become that Lord's servants. That's why now we come to request forgiveness, because we all have done wrong to Mr.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: ‘the crime of the servants of the God of your father.’ too many genitives have to be unpacked into separate propositions. That means they also have to be linked back together coherently. “The God your father worshipped” (whom we also now serve, hint, hint) is the basis for why Joseph should forgive them. 16-17 is very manipulative language. As Barbara says, 'We also remember previously' is setting the timeframe for this. Versification follows KM, NRSV, NLT, NET, TB, etc. instructed us = he told us ; say to Joseph/you = say to papa/you.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="*** (2009) note added"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">*** (2009) note added</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar bagitu, ju Yusuf manangis.<bt>Hearing that, then Yusuf cried.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="could add reason: tagal dia pung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">could add reason: tagal dia pung kaka dong sonde parcaya sang dia na.; aer mata mura = cry easily</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾannaʾ: I pray! Please! saʾ (nsʾ):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾannaʾ: I pray! Please! saʾ (nsʾ): forgive<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>peshaʿ: revolt, rebellion chaTTaʾtam: sin against you<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ais ju dia pung kaka dong datang sandiri ko dong tikam lutut di dia pung muka, deng dong omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar pak bekin sang kotong jadi pak pung budak sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>And then his elder siblings came themselves to bow before his face, and they spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Mr go ahead and make us, just become Mr's slaves.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ma Yusuf kasi tau sang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kaka dong, é! Bosong sonde usa taku lai! Cuma Tuhan Allah sa yang ada pung hak ko kasi hukum orang. Ma beta ni, sonde.<bt>But Yusuf told them saying, &lt;&lt;Elder siblings! You don't need to be afraid any more! Only the Lord God who has the right to punish people. But me here, no.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta'usa = tak usah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ta'usa = tak usah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tachat: in the place of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">tachat: in the place of</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Dolu tu, bosong memang su basakongkol ko mau bekin jahat sang beta. Ma Tuhan Allah su roba bosong pung maksud jahat, ko Dia bekin jadi bae. Andia ko Dia angka beta jadi orang bésar, ko orang banya bisa dapa salamat.<bt>At that earlier time, you actually did be in one accord to do evil to me. But the Lord God has changed that evil intent of yours, for Him to make it become good. That's why he promoted me to become a big person, so that many people can be saved. [NOTE to daughter translations: God changes evil intentions/purposes into something good. Be careful to not miss it and introduce erroneous theology by saying “God replaced their evil hearts with good hearts.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oba = robah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">oba = robah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəshavtem: planned lmaʿan: in order to|i(20)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">chəshavtem: planned lmaʿan: in order to<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Jadi sakarang beta kasi tau sang bosong ko jang taku lai. Te beta janji nanti beta lia bosong deng bosong pung ana-ana samua.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) now I'm telling you to not be afraid anymore. Cuz I promise later I will look after you, and all your children.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lia or provide for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">lia or provide for</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Deng omong babae bagitu, ju Yusuf bekin tanáng dia pung kaka dong pung hati.<bt>By speaking well/nicely like that then, Yusus made calm his elder siblings' livers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʾəkhalkel (kwl pilpel): provide for vaynachem:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʾəkhalkel (kwl pilpel): provide for vaynachem: he reassured them<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>vaydiber ʿal-libam: he spoke to their hearts; he tried to persuade them graciously</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yusuf pung mati<bt>Yusuf's death</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ais itu, ju Yusuf tenga tarús di Masir deng dia pung kaka-adi dong samua. Dia idop sampe saratus sapulu taon.<bt>After that, then Yusuf lived on in Masir with all his elder-younger siblings. He lived until 110 years.</bt><v n="23" />Dia masi dapa lia Efraim pung ana-upu dong. Deng dia sandiri ju ada piara Manase pung cucu, andia Makir pung ana-ana.<bt>He still got to see Efraim's great-grandchildren. And he himself also took care of Manase's grandchildren, that's Makir's children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="piara kasi besar = raise children"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">piara kasi besar = raise children</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʿal-birkey Yosef: on Joseph's knees; as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">ʿal-birkey Yosef: on Joseph's knees; as if they were born to him (not just sitting on Grandpa's knee, but almost like a hanai relationship; also used of Zilpah bearing kids for Leah)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Yusuf kasi tau dia pung kaka dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kaka dong, é! Beta rasa-rasa, beta pung hari mati su deka-deka. Ma beta parcaya, Tuhan Allah pasti piara bosong. Dia yang nanti antar bosong kaluar dari ini negrí. Dia ju pimpin bosong bale pi negrí yang Dia su sumpa ko mau kasi sang ba'i Abraham, ba'i Isak deng papa Yakob.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yusuf told his elder siblings saying, &lt;&lt;Elder siblings! I'm feeling, my day of death is near. But I believe, the Lord God will surely take care of you. He's the one who later will take you out of this country. He also will lead you to return to the country which He has sworn promised to our grandfather/forefather Abraham, Gf Isak and papa Yakob.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paqod yifqod: he will take care"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">paqod yifqod: he will take care of (also verse 25) nishbaʿ (nif): he swore an oath<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Tarús Yusuf minta dia pung sodara dong angka sumpa bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong musti janji sang beta. Kalo sampe waktu Tuhan Allah bawa bale sang bosong pi itu negrí, na, bosong ju musti bawa beta pung mayat.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yusuf requested his siblings take.up a oath saying, &lt;&lt;You must promise me. If it is the time the Lord God takes returning you to that country, na, you must also bring my corpse.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ais ju Yusuf mati di Masir, waktu dia pung umur saratus sapulu taon. Tarús dong taro ramuan di dia pung mayat. Ju dong kasi maso pi dalam dia pung peti.<bt>And then Yusuf died in Masir with his age 110 years. Then they put perservatives on his corpse. And they put him in his coffin.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ramuan = obat macam-macam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z">ramuan = obat macam-macam</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayachanTu: they embalmed, mummified. Kind of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-01 23:41:35Z" status="Information">vayachanTu: they embalmed, mummified. Kind of like preparing a kaʿiwi. baʾaron: inside a box (in this case, a coffin or mummy case). The same word is used for the Ark of the Covenant.<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
  </book>
</bible>